<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 00:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8742 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-PEBBLEBEACH-HNS &LR;      02-07 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PEBBLEBEACH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ If it were anybody else, people would be
sticking a fork in him.
</P>
<P>
   For anybody else, there are too many strokes to make up and too
many people to leapfrog.
</P>
<P>
   But because it's Tiger Woods, and because the two players
leading the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am don't exactly have a
proven track record of fending off a superstar, nobody is jumping
the gun to announce the end of Woods' winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Those in front of him are practically breaking their necks
looking over their shoulders. And those closest to Woods say there
isn't a single reason why he can't extend his streak to six
consecutive victories today _ if his balky putter straightens up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't putted very well all week,'' Butch Harmon, Woods'
coach, said Sunday evening after an extended putting session on the
practice green. ``We worked on that a lot, and if he putts well in
the final round he probably will win the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being five behind the leader is a lot for some people. But not
for Tiger. He could have easily shot 63 (Sunday). That's how well
he's hitting the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's Harmon's job to be optimistic and to instill the
same sort of confidence in his star pupil.
</P>
<P>
   But you get the feeling that Woods is not going to let the
streak die without a huge fight.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he shaved three shots off the deficit he was facing at
the beginning of the day. Woods shot a decent round, 4-under-par 68
in the third round at Pebble Beach Golf Links, leaving him at
7-under 209.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd feel a lot better,'' said Matt Gogel, ``if he was about
2-under.''
</P>
<P>
   And Woods' chances of rallying might be slimmer if it were
somebody other than Gogel and Mark Brooks sharing the lead at
12-under 204. Gogel is a rookie who just graduated from the Nike
Tour (now the Buy.com Tour), and Brooks might as well be coming out
of retirement, for all we've heard from him since he won the '96
PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   These just aren't the sort of guys whom people envisioned ending
Woods' streak.
</P>
<P>
   Especially not Gogel, who had a 67 at Pebble Beach on Sunday.
Unheralded outside family circles until two weeks ago, Gogel
finished in a tie for seventh at the Bob Hope Classic and now is in
the driver's seat to gain his first PGA Tour victory.
</P>
<P>
   But he already has experience at final-day sloppiness. He was
one stroke off the lead going into the final round of the Hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got passed by,'' he said. ``It was like being at the Indy
500 watching cars go by.''
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't sound like the voice of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   As for Brooks, who shot 6-under 66 at Poppy Hills, he hasn't had
a top-three finish in four years.
</P>
<P>
   A shot behind the leaders is Vijay Singh, whose round of par-72
Sunday at Pebble Beach did nothing to strike fear into Woods or
anybody else. Notah Begay is at 10-under 206 after a 72, and nobody
else is closer than four shots.
</P>
<P>
   So can Woods catch all seven players ahead of him?
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends on the weather,'' Begay said. ``But if it's a
day like we had today, with not much wind, if he's within seven or
eight shots, Matt might be hearing footsteps.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, actually, is hoping for a nasty day, and he'll probably
get his wish. Rain was moving into the Monterey Peninsula area
Sunday night, and more rain and wind were forecast for today.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's ugly out there, then I'm in great shape,'' Woods said.
``But if it's calm, then it's going to be a tough task to make that
many birdies to catch them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if it's ugly and it's blowing hard, maybe even raining,
just make a few birdies here and there and it might be enough.''
</P>
<P>
   And a friendlier putter wouldn't hurt, either. The greens at
Pebble Beach have been softened by the rain and scraped up by 180
players walking around the same pin placements for three days.
</P>
<P>
   The bumpy greens are the same for everybody, however. Woods was
more concerned about fixing his putting stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of times I hit it high on the face or sometimes I hit
it thin,'' Woods said. ``That's not a good sign. That means you are
not hitting the putt solid.''
</P>
<P>
   Harmon said Woods' goal Sunday was to reach 10 under par, which
would have meant shooting a 65. Woods said he will pick a target
number before he starts today's round. What that number will be
depends on the weather.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, of the seven players ahead of Woods, only Singh
would seem to be a major threat to handle today's pressure,
particularly if Woods, who will tee off 30 minutes before the
leaders, posts a couple of early birdies to tighten things before
the others begin their rounds.
</P>
<P>
   And so, we wait to find out who will be the Fred Haas of 2000 or
if he even emerges today. Haas was the amateur who ended Byron
Nelson's streak of 11 consecutive wins in 1945, beating Nelson by
five shots in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
