<HEADER>
A8744 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     02-07 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LEGAL mayhem made the NFL what it is today, our premier spectator
sport, the 800-pound gorilla in the network boardrooms. For three
quarters of a century, from Johnny Blood to Chuck Bednarik to Dick
Butkus to Jack Tatum to any one of a number of contemporary
helmeted hooligans, violence has always been the engine driving the
game's popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Even the WWF's faux body-slammers and hatemongers want to get
into the act, offering up a new football league _ the XFL _ that
will exhibit a real ``attitude.'' Oh, goody, another giant step for
mankind.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, hardly a play passes on any given Sunday without
some sort of heinous, and felonious, assault upon another man's
person. We not only demand brutal behavior; we pay big, big money
for it. Yet, illogically, we also ask the participants to be
perfectly normal when they leave the office to return to home and
hearth.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, we accord them the status of role models, somebody for
little Billy to admire and, gulp, emulate.
</P>
<P>
   Still, given the non-genteel requirements of their jobs, what's
most surprising about the arrests of Rae Carruth and Ray Lewis is
that they were practically unprecedented. Statistics show that NFL
players are led off in handcuffs at a far lesser rate than American
males at large.
</P>
<P>
   First Carruth was charged with murder in the death last fall of
his pregnant girlfriend. Now Lewis, Baltimore's superstar-caliber
linebacker, joins him in jail after two men who had crossed Lewis'
path in Atlanta _ the night of the Super Bowl, no less _ wound up
stabbed to death.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rams linebacker Leonard Little played in the Super
Bowl only a season after he did time for manslaughter, having
killed a St. Louis woman while driving drunk. Ex-Ram Darryl Henley
did miss the game, however. He's in prison for drug dealing.
</P>
<P>
   All these gents hold, or held, a special place in our society,
with its badly skewed, ``hero''-worshipping value system. By virtue
of their high-profile occupations, we pay undue attention to what
they do and what they think. People in my business frantically
scribble down or electronically record their every utterance,
giving them platforms way out of kilter with what they contribute
to the greater good. Lewis, as the leader of the Ravens' defense,
is routinely allowed to hold court on all manner of subjects, one
of which produced the following observation: ``The devil's busy,
always after God's children. He's always trying to get you one way
or another.''
</P>
<P>
   The devil, it seems, has been particularly troublesome for Mr.
Lewis during his football career. Before the ill-fated soiree with
his shady entourage in Atlanta's swinging Buckhead district, he was
already scheduled to stand trial for attacking a woman in a
Baltimore bar in early December. He was twice accused of assault
while in college, and he has had his share of paternity problems as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens signed Lewis to a $26 million contract in late 1998
that made him the league's highest-paid linebacker. They showed him
the money even though they knew he was hanging with an unsavory
crowd, yet they have done next to nothing to protect him from his
own bad instincts.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials say they intended to speak to Ray after the Pro
Bowl. You wonder if they waited so as to not distract him from his
football duties, perhaps fearing that asking him to settle down off
the field might also stymie his valuable antisocial tendencies on
it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the children of Baltimore _ their parents, too _
begged for his autograph and wore his name and number on their own
jerseys. If Lewis beats the double-murder rap, they no doubt will
again, applauding his strength and courage for overcoming, ahem,
adversity.
</P>
<P>
   That's not going to change. We can't help ourselves. The
physically gifted in all cultures have always been accorded status
that's grossly out of sync with their tangible contributions to
humankind.
</P>
<P>
   While it's pointless to begrudge jocks in general their exalted
status and oft-obscene riches, it would be a more perfect world if
athletic prowess didn't unilaterally provide a license to behave
badly and profit accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   The bright, upstanding ones should be afforded the full
privileges of celebrity, including, of course, the capacity to
influence behavior in others. In turn, wouldn't it be nice if the
cretins _ Dennis Rodman and John Rocker's names come quickly to
mind here _ would simply disappear from our collective
consciousness, out of sight, out of mind, the moment they return to
the locker room?
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
