<SLUG> BC-BBO-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM MELVIN DEFTLY STEERS RANGERS CLEAR OF INSANITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The richer Juan Gonzalez gets, the smarter Doug Melvin looks.
</P>
<P>
   I telephoned Doug Melvin personally Sunday to tell him so. In
light of recent baseball insanities, Melvin, general manager of the
retooling Texas Rangers, is now a confirmed genius.
</P>
<P>
   My recommendation of Melvin for American League Nostradamus of
the Year comes in the wake of both Gonzalez's new contract offer
and the latest bad blood being dripped in the Ken Griffey Jr.
affair.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin deftly avoided both. But there, but for the grace of a
little fiscal planning, go the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Back in November, when two-time MVP Gonzalez was dealt to the
Detroit Tigers, local wise rumps _ well, me, for one _ criticized
Melvin for not getting enough. The proverbial ``cow for a bag of
beans'' argument.
</P>
<P>
   The other question was, why then? Why November? Shouldn't Melvin
have waited and shopped Gonzalez to a more eager bidder?
</P>
<P>
   Melvin's answer remains the same. ``My fear,'' he said, ``was
not so much what the player was asking. It was the stance of the
agent, if word were to get out that we were close to trading him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The player could have said, `If you trade me, it doesn't
matter because I'm not going to sign with the new team, anyway.'''
</P>
<P>
   Try closing that deal, in other words, for Justin Thompson, Gabe
Kapler and Francisco Cordero. It can't be done, as the Seattle
Mariners are systematically finding out.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey sat down with ``The Seattle Times''' Steve Kelley last
week at the Pebble Beach pro-am and revealed that since the trade
stories began, he has received a death threat from an allegedly
fed-up and demented Mariners fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like that is pretty much the last straw,'' Griffey
told Kelley. ``How can I possibly go back there and play now?''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners open spring training Feb. 17. It doesn't sound like
Junior plans to be there.
</P>
<P>
   As each day passes, the Mariners' trade leverage dwindles. There
are baseball people who chuckle that Seattle general manager Pat
Gillick was playing liar's poker from the beginning. Griffey gave
them a list of seven teams that he agreed to be traded to, and he
soon skinned the list down to one.
</P>
<P>
   That's not exactly leverage. Then, on Dec. 13, according to
Junior, Gillick called him at his Florida home at 11:40 p.m. and
asked Griffey if he would OK a pending trade with the New York
Mets. ``You've got 15 minutes,'' Griffey said Gillick told him.
</P>
<P>
   Junior, stunned at the deadline, said no. And here they sit,
with Cincinnati general manager Jim Bowden erasing names from the
potential trade pool weekly.
</P>
<P>
   The latest rumored offer has the Reds sending spare outfielder
Dmitri Young and pitchers Denny Neagle, Dennis Reyes and Scott
Williamson, and the Mariners dispatching Griffey and _ get this _
cash. They want Seattle to help pay Griffey's 2000 salary.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin himself remembers hanging up the phone in November, after
talking to Detroit's Randy Smith, and telling his people, ``I want
to do this deal today. Let's get Tom Hicks on the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   The other half of the clairvoyance, of course, is Melvin's
assessment of the kind of money that Gonzalez would be after. Faced
with the opening of a new stadium and seats to fill, Smith has
offered Juan a package worth $148 million over eight seasons. He
wants Gonzalez, in effect, to become the symbol of the new Detroit
Tigers _ big shoes for a man who prefers to walk softly.
</P>
<P>
   If memory serves, there was outrage when the Twins made Kirby
Puckett the game's first $3-million-a-year player. The same people
gasped when Roger Clemens became the first to make $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   But ever since the White Sox ignored the $9- and $10-million
plateaus and made Albert Belle baseball's first $11 millionaire,
there have been quantum leaps in salaries. Gonzalez is just the
most recent example.
</P>
<P>
   Juan hasn't signed the Tigers' deal, by the way. On the day last
week that he was supposed to be in Detroit, signing the $140
million contract, Gonzalez was photographed jogging on a Dominican
Republic beach.
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. Heaven can wait?
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of GMs seem to realize that a team can't
consistently field a winner if too much payroll is tied up in one
player. Consider last season _ of the 14 players whose annual
salary exceeded $8.5 million, nine of them didn't make the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   As each day passes, Griffey drifts further away from Seattle,
and Melvin's November big score seems a bit wiser.
</P>
<P>
   The bag of beans never looked better. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
