<SLUG> BC-HKN-ALL-STARS-GAMER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW WORLD ORDER TAKES CENTER STAGE AT ALL-STAR GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ A simple, albeit poignant, clip capped pregame
festivities at Sunday's 50th NHL All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   NHL legends Wayne Gretzky, Mario Lemieux and Gordie Howe were
seen walking along a snowy trail, talking hockey and reminiscing,
before arriving at a frozen pond. All of them toy with playing
until Anaheim's Paul Kariya, Philadelphia's Eric Lindros, Florida's
Pavel Bure and Pittsburgh's Jaromir Jagr skate over.
</P>
<P>
   Nah, Gretzky says, the game is now theirs.
</P>
<P>
   The first Gretzky-less All-Star Game in 18 years _ won 9-4 by
the World Team _ showed that the torch has indeed been passed to
guys like Bure. He turned in an MVP performance with his hat trick,
including two goals that his younger brother, Valeri, set up. Pavel
Bure also assisted on another goal.
</P>
<P>
   He said being involved in filming that clip with Gretzky a
couple days earlier had effected him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was part of the hockey history when you see
those legends like Wayne, Mario and Gordie,'' Bure said. ``Just
shooting this _ I don't think it was just a commercial. It was
something bigger. It was something, something that specific, a
little movie would probably make history. It is like changing
generations, and it meant a lot to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bure wasn't alone.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of guys on ice Sunday realized that the face of the game
is changing. A league once ruled by Gretzky and Lemieux suddenly
has Jagr and Bure along with names like Gomez and Turek and Kariya
dominating games. NHL hockey is definitely younger and more global.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a changing of the guard,'' Stars captain Mike
Modano said. ``You don't know how much more Ray Bourque is going to
play or (Mark) Messier or Steve Yzerman or guys like that who were
part of the Gretzky-Lemieux era. Those guys are going to be the
front-and-center guys now.''
</P>
<P>
   This new generation certainly commanded attention Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis' Pavol Demitra scored twice. Modano assisted on goals
by Phoenix's Jeremy Roenick and Chicago's Tony Amonte. Jagr had a
goal and an assist. Of course, Bure had an assist along with his
hat trick. He said some of those moves were picked up while playing
with his brother on a pond near their home in Russia not too unlike
the one in the Gretzky spot.
</P>
<P>
   For the first All-Star Game without him, Gretzky was everywhere.
The NHL retired his number around the league before the game. He
drew the largest ovation of the day as he walked out for the
presentation. But mostly, the game he helped build was moving on.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first heard that they were going to do it, I was almost
shivering,'' St. Louis Blues coach Joel Quenneville said. ``Then
when I saw it, I saw it prior to going out on the ice and `Wow.' It
was `Wow.' And when I saw it again on the big screen, I almost got
a tear going down my cheek. It was a special moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The clip didn't end with Gretzky's symbolic declaration.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Kariya, Lindros and Bure began skating away, Jagr called
them back to face Gretzky and Lemieux and Howe. They slowly began
tapping their sticks on the ice, the way hockey players honor other
hockey players.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Stars watching down on the ice starting tapping their
sticks, too.
</P>
<P>
   That, Bure says, was their way of saying thanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody did more things for hockey than Wayne,''
Bure said. ``He brought the hockey in the south of United States,
to Calgary, to everywhere, and he is still great. And so I think it
is going to be really hard to compare our generation to guys like
Wayne Gretzky.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't worry, they promise to try.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
