<SLUG> BC-BKC-TULSA-SUCCESS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT TULSA, SUCCESS REMAINS A CONSTANT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Growing up in Bakersfield, Calif., Brandon Kurtz had always
dreamed of playing basketball at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing up a high-scoring senior year at Newman Smith High
School in Carrollton, Greg Harrington was leaning toward SMU.
</P>
<P>
   Coming out of high school in Eufaula, Okla., Eric Coley was
getting a lot of advice about positioning himself in a high-profile
program at a major state university.
</P>
<P>
   All three are now starters at Tulsa, which _ as usual _ is
progressing toward a berth in the NCAA Tournament. Following a
sweep of TCU and SMU last week, the Golden Hurricane (22-2, 7-1) is
leading the Western Athletic Conference and figures to improve on
its No. 17 national ranking.
</P>
<P>
   And as usual, there is speculation about the coach. The names
and faces change every few years, but the basic profile remains
strikingly similar: a young, energetic talent, who is obviously
ready for a leap to college basketball's ``national'' level.
</P>
<P>
   The chronicles of the past are laced with the names of Nolan
Richardson, Tubby Smith, and Steve Robinson, all of whom moved on
to higher profile positions.
</P>
<P>
   The current resident, Bill Self, 37, regards the process with an
air of detached amusement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I know there's always some kind of speculation,'' he
said, laughing. ``But it's usually done by people who aren't really
involved in the process. Anyway, I am definitely not going to let
it become a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that in the past this has been a steppingstone type
job ... but that was before we built the new arena. It was also
before they made a hire where both the coach and his wife were born
and raised in Oklahoma.''
</P>
<P>
   True, the $28 million Donald W. Reynolds Center _ including a
state-of-the-art, 8,355-seat basketball arena _ represents a
dramatic departure from the school's frugal past. Sitting alongside
it, ancient Skelly Stadium, the football stadium, assumes a
skeletal aura.
</P>
<P>
   And Self, who grew up in Edmond, Okla., and played at Oklahoma
State, is definitely a native son. After a year as an assistant
under Larry Brown at Kansas, he spent seven seasons _ three under
Eddie Sutton _ at Oklahoma State before a four-year tenure as head
coach at Oral Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   When Robinson left for Florida State after the 1996-97 season,
Self _ who won 31 of his last 38 games at Oral Roberts _ moved
across town.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing a remarkable tradition, he has won 64 games in less
than three seasons in the time-honored Tulsa fashion _ with players
that others missed, such as Kurtz, Coley and Harrington. Beginning
with Richardson's first team (1980-81), which played in the
National Invitation Tournament, Tulsa has reached the postseason 14
times in 19 years, including 10 trips to the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   It has been accomplished over two decades at a small (4,300
enrollment) private school with a limited budget despite numerous
changes in administration, and with coaches continually leaving for
more prestigious, better-paying jobs _ Richardson to Arkansas,
Smith to Kentucky, Robinson to Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   The secret, Self says, is ``players.'' And obviously,
aggressive, hungry young coaches with the sense and ability to
recruit them.
</P>
<P>
   At Tulsa, the pattern was established with Richardson and has
been broken only once _ with the hiring of J.D. Barnett, an
established head coach who came in when Richardson went to Arkansas
after the 1984-85 season. It turned out to be the least successful
tenure of the past 20 years, although Barnett averaged nearly 18
victories per season.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the school has hired rising assistants or fledgling
head coaches who yearned to stack up victories as a way of
introducing themselves to Division I society. In the process, an
odd juggernaut _ without the usual trappings of stability at the
top _ was established.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched it all, because I was in highschool when it
started,'' Self said. ``When Nolan came in, Oklahoma was not yet a
basketball-crazed state. It was a football-crazed state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school tried to hire either Nolan or Billy Tubbs, who took
the Oklahoma job. They both took over programs that had had
sporadic success, and they began winning almost immediately. The
whole state went crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   While Tubbs built a powerhouse at OU, Richardson did the same at
Tulsa, which became a certain kind of destination for young coaches
on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get inside it, there's a lot there,'' Self said.
``Tulsa has always been a good job because there's a strong
recruiting base. There's a lot of talent in this state, and if you
work at it, you'll get your share.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great community, a city with a college-town atmosphere,
but with a technology base that presents at lot of opportunities.
You can get a terrific education _ and that's always been a major
selling point.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's also true that each school recruits a certain type of
player that fits its atmosphere. We've had highly recruited players
here, like Shea Seals (who wanted to stay in his hometown), but
more often, the program has been built with under-recruited
prospects who have developed into strong college players.''
</P>
<P>
   A typical example is last year's wheelhorse, Michael Ruffin, a
cerebral type who stayed four years, thoroughly enjoyed the
curriculum, married his sweetheart, nurtured an eclectic menagerie
of pets, including the only coatimundi in the WAC, and collected
enough rebounds and blocked shots to sign a contract with the
Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the last place I ever expected to wind up,'' said Kurtz,
who was overlooked by UCLA and wound up at a small private school
2,000 miles away because Self knew his junior-college coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he called me, I said, `I don't need a big man,''' Self
recalled, ``and he said, `You need this one.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Now an all-star candidate, the 6-foot-10 Kurtz says, ``I love it
here. There was a cultural difference at first, but I found
something. I'm very glad this happened, because it was the best
thing for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington wound up at Tulsa because SMU ran out of
scholarships. So he consoled himself by becoming the WAC Freshman
of the Year in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactlythe place I need to be,'' he said. ``It's
perfect _ it's not a big city and it's not a small town. Everything
you want is here, but you're not overwhelmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Coley came because he wanted to stay close to home _ and be part
of a tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was close, it was familiar, it was what I wanted,'' he
said. ``It was a blow when we missed the NCAA's a couple of years
ago, because it broke a streak. But we got back in it last year
(making the school's fifth NCAA Tournament appearance in six
years). Around here, that means a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Self's team will make it six of seven this year, after which he
mightbe gone. He has a multi-year contract, but so did the others
... and there are suitors out there offering bigger salaries,
national exposure, and membership in a conference with a lucrative
television contract, something the WAC lacks. If Georgia Tech
calls, does Self answer?
</P>
<P>
   If so, it could actually be a painful decision. As far back as
the memory stretches, the ``homecourt'' of the Golden Hurricane has
been the Tulsa Convention Center. Now there is an on-campus arena
that is packed for almost every game.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the previous residents would have been thrilled by the
facility. Probably only Self _ born in Okmulgee, raised in Edmond _
could describe it thusly:
</P>
<P>
   ``All those years, we never had a home ... now, we do.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
