<SLUG> BC-HKN-ALL-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODANO ENJOYS TIME ON IRONIC LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Stars captain Mike Modano said he's coming back from
the All-Star break feeling rejuvenated for the stretch run.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, Phoenix's Jeremy Roenick deserves a little
credit for that turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Playing on a line with Roenick and Chicago's Tony Amonte
reminded Modano just how much fun the game can be. Modano had two
assists, giving him six points in the past two All-Star Games. The
three had played together in the World Junior Championships in 1988
and again in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what? It was funny. I was standing with Teemu Selanne
in the third period, that was the line that we had back in the
World Junior Championship,'' Roenick said. ``Myself, Modano and
Tony playing guys like Fedorov, Bure and Mogilny, Teemu. He
remembered that, and we had a chuckle about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say that the group has had a few ``issues'' since.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick earned a five-game suspension earlier this season for
purposely slashing Amonte, a particularly strange incident in that
Amonte and Roenick were good friends in Chicago. Roenick, of
course, took a jaw-breaking hit from Stars captain Derian Hatcher
last season, an incident that many believed was retaliation for an
earlier hit on Modano.
</P>
<P>
   Hard feelings, though, have seemed to evaporated. At least
between Modano and Roenick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always gotten along,'' Modano said. ``You get him into
these situations and you get him alone, he's fun to be around and
fun to play with.'' HIT MAN
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Roenick, he was the only player on either team to
have any hits with three. One of them was on Toronto defenseman
Dimitri Yushkevich, drawing boos from the partisan crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Typically in All-Star Games, there isn't any hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The refs told me to leave everybody alone,'' a disappointed
Roenick said. ``Only three? I thought I had four or five hits.''
SO-SO FOR TUREK
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis Blues goalie Roman Turek had a pretty good All-Star
experience.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed only two goals in the period he played. The second,
however, was a little more annoying than the first considering it
was his turnover that started it. And even worse, it was his former
Stars teammate, Modano, who picked off the pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe, he knows me well,'' Turek said, laughing. GRETZKY
RETURNS
</P>
<P>
   Maple Leaf Gardens had a pretty big visitor Saturday: Wayne
Gretzky. He skated around and played hockey for a while, his first
skate since he retired last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``First time I have skated, played hockey, since April 18, and
it probably showed that,'' Gretzky said. ``I actually had a lot of
fun, and Maple Leaf Gardens, as everyone knows, is always one of
the great places to play in. I had a really good time playing.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
