<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCELZI IS TOP DOG IN TOP FUEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   POMONA - Gary Scelzi has enough experience to know that one race
does not make a championship.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop him from celebrating Sunday after defeating
reigning Top Fuel champion Tony Schumacher to win the 40th
Winternationals at the Fairplex.
</P>
<P>
   Scelzi, who won this event in 1997, was joined in the winner's
circle with Jerry Toliver in Funny Car, Jeg Coughlin in Pro Stock
and Bob Panella in Pro Stock Truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``To beat Tony Schumacher was extra special,'' said Scelzi after
beating his new rival in the final. ''He's the (Top Fuel) champion.
We're No. 2, but right now we're No. 1 in (championship points).
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't forget the rest of the season. This is one race, but
it's a great way to start.''
</P>
<P>
   And Scelzi achieved the right beginning with consistency. The
former two-time series champion had both the quickest and most
consistent car Sunday, making four passes in the 4.60-second range,
including a 4.605 at 317.12 in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get to the final and don't win it,'' said Scelzi, who
beat Tim Gibson, Cory McClenathan and Larry Dixon en route to the
final, ``it's like somebody putting a big chocolate cake in front
of you with a mountain of ice cream. You finally get to it, then
somebody takes it away.''
</P>
<P>
   Not on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Scelzi made sure by blistering the Pomona asphalt with a stout
4.613 at 317.79 mph, more than enough to beat Schumacher's losing
4.712 at 309.56.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Former Funny Car champion) Frank Hawley once told me that
every athlete that does well, practices,'' Scelzi said. ''You have
to. My guys went into training during (preseason testing). (Crew
chief Alan Johnson) was playing with different combinations and he
found out what worked. It carried right over to Pomona. My guys are
tired right now, but there's nothing like winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The final, I was probably a little more nervous. It was Tony
Schumacher. He's the champ, and I want to knock him off. I didn't
want to blow it because I knew we had a race car. And I knew they
would have to step up to beat us, and they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Consistency proved to be the difference for Toliver as well. The
former drag boat racer, in just his second full season, made three
consecutive passes of 4.95 or quicker before beating Tony Pedregon
on a hole shot in the Funny Car final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just in a zone,'' said Toliver, who has now won
back-to-back national events at Fairplex. ``Everything was great.
My lights were great, I was leaving hard and the car was was
working well.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did we run all day? (4.94s), .95s, .93s ... that's tight.
That just shows you the ability of (crew chief) Dale Armstrong.
He's phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   So was Toliver, who used a .09-second advantage off the starting
line to defeat Pedregon, who ran a quicker 4.929 but couldn't get
around Toliver before the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin, victorious in the previous two national events at the
Pomona facility, made it three in a row after running a smooth 6.89
at 199 mph, beating two-time defending class champion Warren
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Crew chief Dick Maskin) has a good handle on tuning here at
Pomona and I just like running here,'' Coughlin said. ``I wish we
could be here for the next 23 (national events).
</P>
<P>
   ``The highlight of today was that we were the quickest car every
round. To have last year's champion and runner-up in the final,
that's what it's all about. And fortunately, No. 2 beat No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Panella won in Pro Stock Truck, beating former sportsman
teammate Greg Stanfield following a 7.454 pass at 178.52 mph.
Stanfield, who held a slight starting-line advantage, ran a slower
7.568.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw him until the finish,'' said Panella, the 1999
class champion. ``Then I looked over and saw my win light come
on... what a feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will celebrate this, and just hope we can keep it going for
14 more races.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
