<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS COULD SEE JAZZ IN PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (set ital) Today's run-and-gun edition of The Sporting Muse:
(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   - The Lakers' rout of Utah last week sure looked great, but
wasn't it just a few weeks ago that Utah routed the Lakers in Salt
Lake? The Jazz are showing their age, and no longer can win at a
.700 rate. But pity the fool who thinks they couldn't beat the
Lakers in a playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   And as the playoff race is shaping up, the Lakers could wind up
meeting the Jazz in the first round. That could happen whether they
finish first in the Pacific Division or not, too. Through Saturday,
a mere four wins separate the five teams elbowing for position in
the Western Conference behind the Lakers, Spurs and Trail Blazers.
...
</P>
<P>
   - The Zen-ification of the Lakers may continue if Phil Jackson
gets his way. He hasn't hidden his attitude about the selfish Glenn
Rice, who may be traded, or his desire for the Bulls' Toni Kukoc, a
big man who can shoot. Kukoc's downside is his age, 31, and the
fact he's considered an old 31 because of bad habits (smoking) and
so many years playing physical international basketball. ...
</P>
<P>
   - The Lakers' chances of winning the Pacific and the No. 1 seed
in the playoffs may hinge on how well they play on the road. After
the all-star break, they play 20 of 34 on the road. ...
</P>
<P>
   - I think I've discovered the secret to keeping college
basketball juniors and sophomores in school: Give the Clippers the
rights to all underclassmen. ...
</P>
<P>
   -It's good to be Orange: Jim Boeheim's Syracuse team is still
unbeaten, and former Boeheim assistant Wayne Morgan is 16-3.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the 49ers dominated the crowd in Saturday's win at
Fullerton, raising the question of where they go on game nights at
the Pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   For those confident of the 49ers' earning a NCAA berth, the west
regionals will be held in Tucson and Salt Lake City. And while on
that subject, will the meddlesome NCAA please explain the
geographic dysfunction of this year's tourney sites? The NCAA South
regional finals are in Texas (Austin). The NCAA West regional
finals are in (set ital) Detroit (end). ...
</P>
<P>
   - The 1999-2000 season is shaping up as the most wide-open of
recent memory. Many of the perennial powers have modest-looking
teams this season, and conferences like the ACC, Big East and Big
Ten aren't as deep as usual.
</P>
<P>
   There's only two ACC teams in the Top 25, in fact, Duke and
Maryland. The SEC seems to have the most good teams, and it
wouldn't be a shock if both Pac-10 powers, Stanford and Arizona,
made it to the Final Four. ...
</P>
<P>
   - The way things are shaping up in town, the Clippers and UCLA
could get into a bidding war for coach Larry Brown, who seems
poised to leave the 76ers and never burns his bridges. This assumes
North Carolina, on the NCAA bubble, doesn't beat them to him. ...
</P>
<P>
   - The Kings chances of moving beyond their recent slump and
earning a playoff spot is good. Once they get past a six-game road
trip this month that includes stops in Detroit and the Buffalo
Haseks, they will be a staple of Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   They play 12 of 16 games in March and April there, and only two
are against teams in the upper strata of the league. The downside
is that they still are longshots to win enough games to earn home
ice for first round, meaning a first-round match against a St.
Louis, Detroit or Dallas. ...
</P>
<P>
   - My new favorite commercial is Bud Light's ..
</P>
<P>
   - I can't think of any athlete who has turned around his image
as dramatically as Andre Agassi. Once feckless and inconsistent,
he's become thoughtful and dedicated, never moreso than playing in
the Davis Cup a week after winning the Australian Open, and doing
so Sunday despite a severe illness.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of illness, that was some Dick Vermeil-like moment U.S.
coach John McEnroe had after the Davis Cup win over Zimbabwe. Tears
from John McEnroe? He's obviously getting in touch with an inner
child we've never met before. ...
</P>
<P>
   - Will someone please explain why our local baseball teams are
being operated by former executives of the Montreal Expos, a team
with one playoff season on its resume, and that in the 1981 strike
season?
</P>
<P>
   Here's Kevin Malone signing Geronimo Berroa. Here's Bill
Stoneman signing, uhh, nobody. Here's Southern California baseball
fans burning their season tickets. ...
</P>
<P>
   - Former Dodgers manager Tommy Lasorda reportedly in on a list
of managerial candidates for the U.S. Olympic baseball team, which
will be made up of young minor league stars not on major league
40-man rosters. ...
</P>
<P>
   - Not only is Heisman Trophy winner Ron Dayne not the first
running back listed in NFL mock drafts, but he's not even the first
player from Wisconsin. Tackle Chris McIntosh is getting more
attention. ...
</P>
<P>
   - There may be a shortage of good quarterbacks in the NFL, but
there's no shortage of available quarterbacks. Among the available
are Jeff Blake, Bubby Brister, Trent Dilfer, Jim Druckenmiller,
Jeff George, Erik Kramer, Rick Mirer, Scott Mitchell, Neal
O'Donnell and every quarterback in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The smart teams may be those that plan to keep two -- Buffalo
(Doug Flutie, Rob Johnson), Chicago (Cade McNown, Shane Matthews),
Detroit (Charlie Batch, Gus Frerotte), the New York Jets (Vinny
Testaverde, Richie Lucas) and the Rams (Kurt Warner, Trent Green).
...
</P>
<P>
   - Those close to Madame Ram, Georgia Frontiere, say her postgame
``This proves we were right to move to St. Louis'' chortle was
aimed at NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue, who extorted some of the
Rams' bounty in the move, and not anyone in Southern California.
Perhaps, but she had to know how it would sound. ...
</P>
<P>
   - Please pardon my tears, but I'm still choked up over the U.S.
not qualifying a boat for the America's Cup final. ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 0017EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
