<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8751 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-PISTONS-H     02-07 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-PISTONS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ With seven-tenths of a second left and the
Rockets a couple of free throws from finally being beaten, coach
Rudy Tomjanovich tried one more desperation move.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``One point two!'' he shouted to official Tim Donaghy, knowing
there was no way he could have gotten that extra half-second, and
knowing Donaghy knew just what he was up to.
</P>
<P>
   ``One point two!'' Tomjanovich said again, making sure Pistons
coach Alvin Gentry heard before smiling broadly to reveal the truth
behind his dastardly plan _ that he was going for the laugh.
</P>
<P>
   But as Detroit's Michael Curry sank two free throws with
seven-tenths of a second left Sunday night to finally put away a
109-105 Pistons win over the Rockets, the real shocker was that a
half-second could have mattered.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting horribly against the league's most porous defense most
of the night, the Rockets fell behind by as many as 16 points in
the fourth quarter and trailed by 11 with just 1:48 left.
</P>
<P>
   But with a mix of players who before might never have shared a
court outside Westside Tennis Club _ Bryce Drew, Cuttino Mobley,
Devin Gray, Kenny Thomas and Kelvin Cato _ the Rockets rallied
within two. They needed just one more defensive stop to have a
chance to steal a game in which they had been outplayed for 47
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very impressed with it,'' Tomjanovich said of the
comeback. ``We have plenty of excuses to give up. These guys
haven't given up all year. I mean, they (the Pistons) played great,
and we still hung in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at it, and you wonder, `How the hell did we do
that?'''
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons, having scored so easily the rest of the night,
seemed to slow down short of the tape to consider the same
question.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets were minus Steve Francis, out with a right knee
sprain, for the second consecutive game. By the time they reached
the midpoint of the final quarter, they had made just 29 of 70
shots. Grant Hill and Jerry Stackhouse, the NBA's most prolific
scoring duo, were lighting them up. The Rockets' frequent
equalizer, 3-point shooting, was horrible, the free-throw shooting
worse.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Pistons might have been ready to celebrate the
triumphant return of Hill _ who had missed five of the previous
seven games with a bruised hip _ the Rockets finally made their
move.
</P>
<P>
   With the clock under two minutes, Drew hit a tough fadeaway on
the baseline to cut the margin to nine. Christian Laettner threw
the ball away, and Drew passed to Thomas for a 3 that moved the
Rockets within six with 1:21 left.
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons isolated Hill outside, but Gray stripped him of the
ball. And if that didn't conflict enough with everything the NBA
will sell on All-Star Weekend, Drew found Hill defending him on a
switch and promptly beat him off the dribble to cut the deficit to
103-99 with 49.8 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went for the head fake,'' Drew said. ``He thought I was
going to shoot over him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill inbounded, but Thomas came up with the steal. And after
Drew missed a 3, got his own rebound and missed the follow, Thomas
grabbed the rebound, drew a foul and moved the Rockets within
103-101 with 40.4 seconds remaining. The Rockets had rallied with a
9-0 run in the span of 68 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows no matter how far you're down, you can definitely
come back and have a chance to win,'' Drew said after his second
consecutive 20-point game filling in for Francis. ``If we won, we
definitely would have snuck one out, because they were in control
of the game for the most part. But I guess it was encouraging to
get close at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Another bright spot for the Rockets was Cato, who scored 23
points and matched a career high with 12 rebounds. They could not,
however, get another stop down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Rockets got within two, the Pistons immediately went
back to Hill. He had scored 34 points in the first three quarters,
but with Gray renewing their Clemson-Duke matchups against one
another, Hill had missed his only two shots in the fourth quarter
and had two turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   With 24.9 seconds left, however, Gray left just enough room for
Hill to launch a jumper from 17 feet that swished. He gave the
Pistons a 105-101 lead with too little time remaining for the
Rockets to do anything but foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played him through college,'' Gray said. ``We went against
each other for years. He's much better than he was in college, and
he was a hell of a player in college. When it counted, I let down.
The jumper, I think I could have played better `D.' I gave him a
chance to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons went 1-4 in games Hill missed with his injury. The
jumper and a 36-point, seven-rebound performance sufficiently
marked his return to the court and to form.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still hurts some,'' Gentry said. ``But I just think that
when he gets on the court, the adrenaline just takes over and he
plays himself through that. The guy is a great player, and when you
put him back on our team, it makes us pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
