<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODRUFF SAVES US IN DAVIS CUP 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ Andre and the Other Guy, Chris Woodruff,
escaped from Africa by the skin of John McEnroe's teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Levering, president of the US Tennis Association, was
breathing for the first time in five hours, as though she'd been
rescued from King Kong by the Other Guy.
</P>
<P>
   And Zimbabwe, a poor yet friendly and hospitable country
containing but three serviceable tennis players (two of them the
Black magic brothers, Byron and Wayne), had to settle for giving
the rich United States a big-time fright in a Davis Cup clash that
left everybody in City Sports Centre limp from tension,
exhilaration, and hopes dashed or fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   When the Other Guy, Knoxville, Tenn., native Woodruff,
catapulted his 15th ace past Wayne Black, he became a new season's
American lifesaver.
</P>
<P>
   An unlooked-for hero from the lost-and-found, he had been lost
in the delirium of a Cup coming-out mess Friday. By Sunday, he
found himself under the prodding of the new US captain to beat the
gallant younger Black, 6-3, 6-7 (2-7), 6-2, 6-4, in a match that
flip-flopped several times.
</P>
<P>
   That concluded three jittery, suspenseful, high-decibel days of
bedlam, and a rare revival for McEnroe's invaders. Their 3-2
victory in the best-of-five series, one of the more memorable tight
squeezes in US Davis Cup annals, sends the Yanks into the
quarterfinals against the Czech Republic at Los Angeles in April.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a near and perhaps lucky thing, as the bargain
basement Blacks (getting $5,000 apiece from their tennis
federation) tweaked the $100,000 payday visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Agassi genuinely gutted it out _ vomiting on court in the
last minutes of his 6-2, 6-3, 7-6 (7-4) triumph over Byron Black.
</P>
<P>
   A triple-whammy of heat, humidity, and altitude (5,510 feet)
struck Agassi. Could he have gone on had he lost the third set?
Agassi says yes.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Black wondered, ``When I saw Andre puking in the
tiebreaker I wished I hadn't lost those two minibreaks,'' which
lifted Agassi to 6-3. ``He might have been finished.'' But Agassi
hung on for two more points.
</P>
<P>
   The day had begun with the United States behind, 2-1, a dire
hole from which only four previous American teams have climbed to
victory: 1902, 1934, 1961, 1981. Agassi's win left it in the hands
of the Other Guy as Levering continued to wring her hands in
anxiety. She had selected the volatile McEnroe as captain against
the advice of many. And she had convinced Agassi to return to the
team, ending his yearlong feud with the USTA.
</P>
<P>
   But now her designs on the 2000 Cup were up to the Other Guy:
this afterthought, the last one asked to the dance, the one who
stepped on his own feet when he got there, losing to Byron Black on
opening day in straight, bewildering sets.
</P>
<P>
   Woodruff was nobody's idea of second fiddler to No. 1 Agassi.
But Pete Sampras got hurt, Todd Martin was sick, and Jim Courier,
Michael Chang, and Vince Spadea looked shopworn. So the phone call
from a desperate McEnroe went out to No. 51 Woodruff. A
big-shouldered, 6-foot-2-inch down-home character who wrecked a
knee two years ago goofing around kicking field goals, he provided
the last kicks of the American weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the biggest honor of my life to be asked,'' said
Woodruff. He had just returned to Knoxville from losing to Sampras
at the Australian Open. After a day of his mom's cooking, he
boarded a plane, not quite sure where Zimbabwe is located.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so nervous Friday, and all the noise was not conducive
to tennis as I'd known it,'' he said. The drums, the precise
Zimbabwean cheering-and-dancing squad, the blizzard of flags
zombied him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``John (McEnroe) got me together. He told me to take Saturday
off, not hit a ball. By today I was calmed down. I knew what to
expect, and I wasn't too nervous. I was doing just fine _ and then
the altitude got me. My shots started flying again . . . I was out
of gas.''
</P>
<P>
   Crunching his groundies, picking on Wayne Black's second serve
to get to the net, and serving huge, Woodruff was up a set and 3-1.
The gritty, diminutive Black caught him, but at 4-5 faced a set
point. Woodruff could taste a two-set lead as he whacked a monster
forehand inside-out beyond Black. But it missed the sideline by a
fraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``About then I hit the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   In the tiebreaker, the Other Guy got ahead by a mini to 2-1,
double-faulted, and began to spray balls, losing six successive
points. Before he knew it, the pandemonium level induced by the
4,000 fans was ratcheted up in the cramped, steaming arena, and
Woodruff was down, 2-0. There, Black faltered to lose serve. On the
changeover, McEnroe yelled at Woodruff ``to suck it up _ but not in
words that kindly,'' the captain said. ``He had to give more,
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``John really got into my kitchen,'' said Woodruff, ``and it was
what I needed to persevere. I got my second wind.'' Then he banged
his way to win the set and take a winning lead, 2-0, in the fourth.
Fracturing Black's declining serve with a roaring backhand to 3-2
in the third, Woodruff finished that set by winning 14 of the last
15 points and had seized 22 of 25 by the time he arrived at 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   A remarkable runner and retriever, feeling somehow he could
still make it Zimbabwe's greatest sporting day, Wayne Black belied
his No. 130 ranking, battling for every point. But there wasn't
much left in a little guy who had qualified for the Australian, and
gone three rounds of singles, nearly beating Sampras, and six
rounds of doubles to the final. He was playing every day Down
Under, and every day here, and it wore him down so that he was
running on only the fumes of desire.
</P>
<P>
   Woodruff, hardly the picture of style, manhandles balls, labors
on his serving motion, runs with effort (but gets there), and
sometimes seems the 900-pound gorilla on Levering's back. His
volleying, often awkward, paid off, nonetheless, as he
resourcefully charged in behind returns of Black's waning second
serves.
</P>
<P>
   Black's last gasp was a break point at 3-2 in the fourth.
Woodruff changed rackets and cracked a service winner. He was
submerged by teammates after the last swing of the series, a
blinding ace. In tears, McEnroe hugged his lifeguard, screaming,
``This is what it's all about, Chris. Welcome to Davis Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, McEnroe said, ``This may be corny, but it gets to me that
seven years ago today Arthur Ashe died. Great man. He was my
captain the last time we came back from 1-2, against Mexico in '81,
and I won the fifth match over Raul Ramirez.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 33 times in a century of Davis Cup has an American been
thrust into the sudden-death fifth match. Woodruff joins those
who've come through, such Hall of Famers as McEnroe, Don Budge,
Chuck McKinley, Frank Shields, Courier, and Agassi. He has his
place, no longer the Other Guy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
