<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BLAZERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS SUCCUMB TO FINISHING FLOURISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They come at you in waves. We're not talking high tide
at Nauset Light Beach. We're talking `Endless Summer' here.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's game, Celtics assistant coach Jim O'Brien
said the first 10 players of the Portland Trail Blazers represented
the strongest team he'd seen in more than a decade. ``Their second
team could compete for the playoffs,'' he said. Their first team
ain't bad either.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers eventually wear out most everyone with their depth
and talent. Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, the Celtics became Victim No. 35 of this
outrageously gifted troupe, but not before making Portland go the
full 48.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics never led in the fourth quarter _ Portland is 31-2
when it leads after three _ but were still very much alive until a
Scottie Pippen trey with 82 seconds left. That made it 95-88 and
proved to be the fatal dagger, as Portland hung on for a 100-94
victory before the fifth sellout of the season at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the sixth in eight games for the Celtics, who
dropped to 21-26, tied with Orlando. Portland is an NBA-best 35-11,
which includes an impressive 19-8 on the road. (No team has played
more road games.) The Blazers are 14-4 against Eastern Conference
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Portland does present problems everywhere. This is a team that
brings Brian Grant off the bench, for goodness sakes. The only
figurehead on the roster is old friend Joe Kleine, who turned 38
last month and is along for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   True to form, Portland Sunday &UR;  &LR; night had six players in double
figures, led by Steve Smith with 23. Grant (22 minutes) and
Jermaine O'Neal (13 minutes) each had eight rebounds as Portland
had a 42-35 advantage on the boards, including an 11-5 margin in
the fourth (six of them off the offensive glass).
</P>
<P>
   And, like so many teams these days, they made the Celtics pay at
the line, outscoring Boston by 10 points there. Portland attempted
39 free throws to the Celtics' 27. The Celtics had two more field
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of those nights,'' shrugged Kenny Anderson, who had 11
points and 10 assists. ``You almost have to play a perfect game to
beat that team. We didn't. And we don't want no moral victories,
either. We've got to win these games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics can look back at this one and see many lost chances.
Paul Pierce had 16 points, but missed three big free throws in the
fourth. Antoine Walker had five shots blocked _ he must lead the
league in that category _ and was 5 of 16 from the field. Boston's
biggest offensive weapon was Vitaly Potapenko, who had 19 points in
24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Rick Pitino was upset about the pace of the game _ too
slow _ and the Celtics' rebounding _ too little. But what really
killed the Celtics was an inability in the first half to run away,
as Portland opened the second quarter by going scoreless for the
first 5:56 and basket-less for the first 6:48.
</P>
<P>
   All Boston could manage in that stretch was 8 unanswered points.
The Celtics missed 10 of 14 shots in that stretch and added a
couple of turnovers. You get a team like that in trouble, you
should pounce. The Celtics did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``They looked kind of tired in the beginning,'' Anderson said.
``We just didn't keep up the tempo in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Pierce, ``We've got to get that rebound and get out and
run.''
</P>
<P>
   So, instead of a decent lead at the break, all the Celtics had
was a 45-42 advantage. Not good enough. The third quarter featured
nine lead changes until a Pippen trey made it 71-70 heading into
the fourth. That turned out to be the last of the 17 lead changes
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the fourth, the Blazers got a big lift from O'Neal, who
had 9 points, 5 rebounds, and a blocked shot in 7 active
fourth-quarter minutes. ``I can score,'' said O'Neal, who had 13
points and 2 blocks in his 13 minutes. ``But I don't have to.''
Portland eventually built the lead to 8 (87-79) only to see the
Celtics get back to within 87-83. Pierce was then fouled with 4:55
left. He missed them both.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics never got closer than 4 the rest of the way. But it
was still a 4-point game when Damon Stoudamire rolled a pass from
under the basket right out to Pippen (19 points, 7 rebounds.) He
calmly swished a trey to blow the lead to 7 and the Celtics were
officially cooked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
