<SLUG> BC-GLF-NATIONAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SITUATION GIVES TIGER PAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
 PRO-AM-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ The story, so dominant in its focus early
in the week, was a virtual afterthought by midday, lost in the
glare of Hollywood stars and silenced by a parade of routine pars.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, continually frustrated by birdie putts that burned
the cup, shot a 4-under-par 68 Sunday in the third round of AT&AMP;T
Pebble Beach National Pro-Am, and while his attempt to win a sixth
straight PGA Tour event still has a pulse, it presents a challenge
that many consider too great even for his remarkable skills.
</P>
<P>
   Butch Harmon isn't one of them. ``If he putts well (Monday),''
said Woods's swing coach, ``he'll win this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods enters a rare Monday finish _ one necessitated by
Thursday's wash-out _ at 7-under 209, five shots behind a pair of
co-leaders who had to feel like they were intruders at an event
that is as much for Andy Garcia as it is for Sergio Garcia. Matt
Gogel, playing just his fourth tournament on the PGA Tour, shot 67
at the same course as Woods played, Pebble Beach, to finish 54
holes at 204, a figure that was matched by Mark Brooks (6-under 66
at Poppy Hills).
</P>
<P>
   Vijay Singh, the second-round leader, managed just an even-par
72 at the event's third course, Spyglass Hill, and is in third
place, one shot back. Notah Begay (72 at Spyglass) is fourth at
206, while Jimmy Green (68), Chris DiMarco (69), and the pride of
Trinity College in Hartford, Jay Williamson (69), shot themselves
into a share of fifth place at 208.
</P>
<P>
   The five-player group at 209 includes Woods and Jim Furyk, who
ripped off a 64 at Pebble on a day when the majestic layout was as
defenseless as it ever will be. Low wind, blue sky, warm
temperature. That he didn't take advantage of such pristine
conditions was frustrating, said Woods, who made five birdies but
hit it close enough all day to make twice that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that I have given myself a chance,'' said Woods, who
had been eight back through 36 holes in this high-profile pro-am
that does not match his golf-serious personality. Everyone may love
Raymond Romano, he of the TV series and 18-handicap, but try
playing in the group behind him for three days as you chase
history, something Woods had to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was . . . interesting,'' said Woods, though as he stood in
the fairway waiting to hit his second shot to the par 5 18th, Woods
probably had seen enough of Romano's hackings, not to mention Tommy
Smothers's comedy routine with the yo-yo. Alas, such activities
come with the territory here _ at least through three rounds.
</P>
<P>
   That changes Monday for those who made the cut, as the venue is
Pebble Beach for a serious round of golf. Woods's trademark red
shirt will be out. So, it is predicted, will the notorious Pebble
Beach weather, which does not bother Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's ugly out there,'' said Woods, ``then I'm in great
shape. But if it's calm, then it's going to be a tough task to make
that many birdies to catch them.''
</P>
<P>
   Calm was the order of business Sunday, but on a day when David
Duval inexplicably shot 75 and missed the cut and Woods struggled
to make birdies despite striping his irons, it was a PGA Tour
rookie (Gogel) and a PGA Tour veteran who hasn't been heard from
since winning the 1996 PGA (Brooks) who took advantage. Gogel,
playing Pebble's back first, bogeyed the difficult par-4 11th, then
ran off five birdies in his next nine holes to vault to the top of
the leaderboard.
</P>
<P>
   That he was doing it with virtually no one other than his caddie
and playing partners watching, even when he birdied the par-5 sixth
to get to 12-under, speaks as much for Gogel's unheralded status as
it does Woods's immense star power. ``I don't think anybody ever
knows when it's their turn or time to win,'' said Gogel, a six-time
winner on the Nike Tour.
</P>
<P>
   If it is yet again Woods's turn to win, something he has done in
every PGA Tour-sanctioned event in which he has played since
September, it will come via his patented charge in harmony with
others collapsing. No one would come out and say so, but the
leaderboard _ save for Singh and Begay _ is loaded with players who
would need road maps to a PGA Tour winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on the weather,'' said Woods, whose only miscue in
Round 3 came on the heels of a bizarre suspension in play. It was
bright and warm at Pebble, but as Woods stood on the eighth tee,
officials stopped play. Fog had enveloped Spyglass and ``we have to
play in the same conditions at the same time,'' explained PGA Tour
official Mark Russell.
</P>
<P>
   After a 30-minute wait, Woods immediately bogeyed the eighth
hole, though he had to breathe a sigh of relief. His second shot
over the famous cliff landed short of the green and was almost lost
in the hay. ``I could see the `R' in my name (on the ball). I
figured it could be my ball,'' said Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was, though he had to pull off a miraculous shot just
to get it to the green. He missed the par-save from 20 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been a lot worse,'' said Woods, for one slip and
he would have perhaps gone down a steep bank into the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   It also could have been better than his 68, though, as he
figures, but it was enough to get him into the picture. As if he is
ever out of it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
