<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8755 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SAIL-AMERICA'SCUP-BOS     02-07 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-AMERICA'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAYARD GRACIOUS AFTER LOSING 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ If Italy's Prada beats New Zealand to
win the America's Cup, there is no way to overemphasize the debt it
owes Paul Cayard, who brought its national Cup aspirations to a
fever pitch in 1992, then raised its game this year through the
fiercest battle in challenger history.
</P>
<P>
   Still, at a news conference in the raucous aftermath of Prada's
Louis Vuitton Cup win Saturday, Cayard, who became a hero in Italy
when he led Il Moro di Venezia into the Cup final in '92, would not
rise to the bait.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by an Italian journalist if the nine-race series had been
about ``the student passing the teacher,'' Cayard, who skippered
AmericaOne's 5-4 loss, said, ``I would never say Francesco (de
Angelis, Prada's skipper) was my student. We are very different
people. We complement each other because we are so different. I am
happy for him that he is doing so well and wish him the best in the
America's Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Cayard stepped off the Cup stage, leaving it without
an American racing for the first time in its 149-year history. And
the analysts, who up until now had resisted, were left with this
explanation: Prada's Luna Rossa was slightly faster, the team
slightly smoother sailing, than AmericaOne.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Cayard worlds different from ``Baroni'' (the Baron)
de Angelis, the campaigns were a study in contrasts. Cayard, in
fact, believes the ``Prada model'' is the way to go.
</P>
<P>
   With an early start, two fast boats, and enough time and money
to develop its sailing program to near perfection on the Auckland
waterfront, Prada is, said Cayard, a ``leave-no-stone-unturned''
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, when Prada was first in Auckland in January 1998,
Cayard was sailing in the Whitbread around-the-world race _ which,
incidentally, he won in his rookie year.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, said Cayard, when his Whitbread entry, E F Language,
made its Auckland layover in winter 1998, the Prada team already
was here practicing.
</P>
<P>
   Distracted by the complexity of his sailing syndicate _ ``too
many things on my plate'' as boss and skipper of the Whitbread and
America's Cup campaigns two years apart _ Cayard admitted, ``I am
not the sailor I was in '92 (Louis Vuitton win) or '95 (Cup
defending skipper). I haven't spent as much time as I could have on
the sailing side to prepare for this.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It is not an insignificant coincidence that the
amount of money and time spent on these campaigns (shows in the
result). Prada was the model campaign, but we did a damn good job
with the time and money we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cayard's AmericaOne campaign did push Prada almost to the
breaking point. The first two races resulted in a split. Still
unresolved was the speed of the boats. But the Prada style was
clear. When it gets out in front, there's almost no stopping the
red-trimmed silver bullet, as its speed and smooth sailing team
stretches out most leads.
</P>
<P>
   Races 3 and 4 _ both Prada wins _ made it look like a blowout.
But trailing, 3-1, Cayard showed the strength of his team, which
fought back with aggressive starts and match-racing moves. Once
behind in a race and the series, Prada seemed shaken, unable to
react spontaneously. In fact, tactician Torben Grael admitted, ``We
have a plan that we follow for the first leg. We always stick to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   A stunned Cayard said he never could sail confined to a
prearranged plan. Cayard and his tactician, John Kostecki, mixed up
the attack, and the results showed on the course.
</P>
<P>
   Three straight wins _ of 34, 9, and 66 seconds _ put AmericaOne
on a roll, and Cayard liked his chances, saying, ``Let's see how
those boys handle the pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   It was then that de Angelis, Grael, and the Prada team reached
down and found something new _ some street fighting moves similar
to AmericaOne's. Trailing, 4-3, in a must-win race, Prada came out
aggressively at the start and nearly tagged Cayard with a quick
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   A tactical mistake by AmericaOne and an aggressive move near the
end of the second leg sealed the race for Prada, as Cayard gybed
too close to leeward, drawing a penalty that took AmericaOne out of
the race.
</P>
<P>
   That set the scene for the excruciating finale. The race itself,
anticlimactic and rather unremarkable, showed more than any other
that the difference is boat speed. In 12-knot wind, Prada cruised
in the sunny turquoise wash of Hauraki Gulf to an easy but historic
49-second win.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, the what-if game will start among US camps:
</P>
<P>
   --What if New York Yacht Club's Young America had been launched
in Rhode Island early enough for the structural failures to be
detected and fixed at the Goetz yard a few miles away in Bristol?
</P>
<P>
   --What if the New York Yacht Club sailing team had included
Dennis Conner and Tom Whidden, which it had a chance to do two
years before the Cup?
</P>
<P>
   --What if Cayard had sailed for New York _ another onetime
possibility?
</P>
<P>
   ``We will miss having an American boat in the Cup,'' said New
York Yacht Club commodore Dooie Isdale, ``but watch out the next
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about matching the Prada model of a long campaign, Isdale
said a US challenger for the next Cup should start ``probably
today. I'm not being facetious. We are having many discussions
about all the possible scenarios. We'll be talking here with all of
us together.''
</P>
<P>
   Isdale agreed with Cayard that too many US challengers diluted
the resources. ``We have to talk about how to merge the clubs into
a mega-challenge,'' he said. ``We talked about it last time, but
there were too many egos. But we won't be ready to make any
announcement until after we know where the next Cup will be.''
</P>
<P>
   The best-of-nine final begins Feb. 19.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
