<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLAZERS-PIPPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIPPEN PIPES UP ON MANY TOPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ You figure someone selected as one of the NBA's 50
greatest players would be a cinch for the All-Star Game. If
Portland Trail Blazers forward Scottie Pippen sought to make a name
for himself after playing second fiddle to Michael Jordan for years
in Chicago, surely this isn't what he had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to be able to take the break, but of course there's
a sense of (disappointment) not being there,'' said Pippen, who
helped lead the Blazers to a 100-94 win over the Celtics
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be . . . something that messes with your ego,''
Pippen added, ``but I'm a veteran player. There are worse things
that can happen. Probably not the best thing, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to say that Pippen hasn't achieved some notice out of
Jordan's shadow. This season he is one of the leaders of a team
tied with the Los Angeles Lakers for the best record in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The only active player with six championship rings, Pippen
registered his 16,000th career point on Dec. 11 against the
Sacramento Kings and a month earlier grabbed his 6,000th rebound in
a win over the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Averaging 12.6 ppg (fourth on the team), 5.4 assists (second), 7
boards (second), and 1.54 steals (first), Pippen helped the Blazers
to a 13-3 mark in November (a franchise best) and an 11-3 record in
January, its best mark in that month since the 1989-90 team went
12-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to get tougher,'' said Pippen. ``We lose a bit
of our toughness sometimes and give up a lot of offensive rebounds.
We have a lot of areas where we need to step up offensively and we
could be more consistent defensively. And then, there are just a
few fundamental things where we could be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Pippen struggled in his first season away from the
Bulls. Traded to Houston in January of last year, he averaged 14.5
ppg (the lowest since his second season with the Bulls) and posted
a career low in field-goal percentage (43 percent).
</P>
<P>
   He was brought to Houston to help make them a title contender
again but had highly publicized feuds with Charles Barkley. The
Rockets were eliminated in the first round of the playoffs by the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a short season, and it was going to be a tough season
no matter how you look at it. My options were limited because of
the short period of time,'' said Pippen. ``But this is a great
situation for me. It gives me an opportunity to be a leader with
younger guys. I can give my court awareness in running the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Being the team leader is something he didn't have to worry about
when he played with Jordan. ``I feel like whatever this team does,
it's going to fall back on me, since I was brought in here to lead
this team to a championship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you have to understand I came in here not knowing many of
these guys, so I have to try to build relationships rather than
destroying them. I have to allow those relationships to develop
before I start making those leadership type of corrections.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen applauds Jordan's move to becoming part owner and general
manager of the Washington Wizards and wishes him the best but
added, ``I don't know . . . there's nothing he can do, really, from
his point of view to make the franchise turn around, but we just
have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the return of former Bulls teammate Dennis Rodman,
now with the Dallas Mavericks, Pippen said: ``I'm happy for him as
well. He's a great player, someone who knows his way around the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done some things that have sort of taken him away from
the game, and have put him in an at-risk situation where no one
wants to deal with him. But he's got a second chance and hopefully
he can take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The only Blazer to start all 47 games, Pippen tallied 19 points
on 7-for-13 shooting Sunday &UR;  &LR; night and added 7 boards and 3 assists
to offset 3 turnovers. He had two key treys at the end of both
quarters in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   His 24-foot baseline trey with 2.2 seconds left in the third
gave the Blazers a 71-70 lead they would not relinquish. His
24-foot trey with 1:22 left gave Portland a 95-88 lead, virtually
sealing it for the visitors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
