<SLUG> BC-HKN-ALLSTAR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE AN APPROACHABLE STAR 
</HEADLINE>
 GAME-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ No one has said for sure, least of all the man
himself. But there are many indications that Bruins captain Ray
Bourque will retire at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   If that holds true, Bourque's appearance at Sunday's 50th
All-Star Game at the Air Canada Centre will have been his last. In
the 9-4 victory by the World Team, which scored four unanswered
goals in the third, Bourque logged 15 minutes 17 seconds of ice
time, had 12 shifts, and finished a plus-2 for the North Americans.
</P>
<P>
   He and Vancouver center Mark Messier each picked up an assist,
giving them each an All-Star-record 13 for their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the enjoyment of the weekend for the 39-year-old Bourque
was mentoring young players, something he has done during his
veteran years in the NHL. Sunday, he took time to encourage
promising rookie forward Scott Gomez of the New Jersey Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talked to me before I went out there,'' said Gomez, 20.
``What he said really helped me out. He said, `Remember what got
you here and just go out there and have fun. If you don't forget
how you got here, you'll be in many more.' That was some good
advice.''
</P>
<P>
   And poignant considering this is likely Bourque's swan song.
Bourque, who also honored Gomez's request of a stick to take home
as a souvenir, said he never has taken these games for granted. He
remembers what it is like to be just starting out. He appreciated
it then, he said, and he appreciates it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started, I came to these games and there were guys like
Larry Robinson and Guy Lafleur that I grew up watching and kind of
were my idols,'' said Bourque. ``You just watch them and how they
go about their business. Any little thing that they tell you, it's
like, `Wow, he spoke to me.' It's pretty neat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been there, so I know when certain young guys come around
you just make sure you go say your two cents and make them feel
comfortable. You come to these games and it can be pretty
intimidating your first time. So you just make sure they feel
comfortable and they're having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque said the opening ceremonies were moving, particularly
when Wayne Gretzky was honored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up there at the beginning of the game, you look around and see
Gretzky come out and that whole thing, it was pretty neat,'' said
Bourque. ``You know you may not be here again. It's a pretty
special feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The game itself was an offensive spectacle as always. But not as
offensive as the North Americans and Bourque would've liked. When
Bourque talked about the team's problems in the goal department, he
could well have been talking about the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just couldn't put it in,'' said Bourque. ``Lack of scoring,
do you believe that? Guys couldn't finish. We were behind the whole
night. We got within one but couldn't score that next one. We came
out in the third and didn't do very much. We had a hard time
finishing out there. It's tough to say with all the scoring we have
in this room.''
</P>
<P>
   There was one penalty in the game and about as much physical
contact as you see in figure skating. Bourque said that's great for
the forwards but makes it hard on the defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough on everyone that plays somewhat of a physical game
or just plays hard,'' he said. ``Nobody is doing it, you just don't
want to be the jerk that goes out there and runs over somebody. You
just want to make sure you're in the right position . . .''
</P>
<P>
   And if this turns out to be his last, he said, he'll be glad he
was here no matter the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a special feeling,'' he said. ``You come in for an
All-Star Game not knowing if you're going to play in another one.
Obviously there are a few thoughts going through your mind. Before
the game, the introductions, that whole ceremony and when Wayne
came out. You just appreciate the moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
