<HEADER>
A8758 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-PROBOWL-HNS &LR;      02-07 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PROBOWL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
HONOLULU _ The next time someone tells you that no one cares about
the Pro Bowl, just tell them about Sunday's game at Aloha Stadium.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the 2000 Pro Bowl lacked the exciting finish of Super
Bowl XXXIV, 767 yards were generated and a record number of points
were scored in the NFC's 51-31 victory that left coach Tony Dungy
and quarterback Steve Beuerlein accusing AFC coach Tom Coughlin of
breaking the rules.
</P>
<P>
   There are specific rules against blitzing and double-covering
receivers in the Pro Bowl. Beuerlein said there was a message in
his 25-yard touchdown pass to Randy Moss with 1:05 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AFC was using questionable tactics the whole second
half,'' Beuerlein said. ``They were breaking a lot of rules. I
think it was a statement from our coaching staff to theirs, like,
`Look at the scoreboard, and here's another touchdown to think
about the next few months.'''
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin, the Jacksonville Jaguars coach who came one game short
of reaching the Super Bowl, denied violating any rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beuerlein's out of control in that respect,'' Coughlin said.
``We didn't coach anything other than what the rules are. Before
they speak about what we're doing, they probably ought to look at
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Dungy, who is mild-mannered but highly respected, echoed
Beuerlein's sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned about the safety of our players,'' Dungy said.
``We're supposed to have restrictions about what we can do
defensively, and we went over them. It was tough because we have a
set of rules for both teams, but one didn't always follow those
rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we had the wrong rule book.''
</P>
<P>
   The AFC was penalized one time for breaking a rule. That came
when Jacksonville outside linebacker Kevin Hardy sacked Beuerlein
and was penalized 15 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an understanding, but, obviously, they didn't,'' Dungy
said. ``Our quarterbacks took some unnecessary hits. I don't think
it's good when the game's set up for no blitzing and then they
blitz. Someone could have gotten hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's Pro Bowl also will be known as the one in which the
game's Most Valuable Player didn't appear in his team picture.
</P>
<P>
   Moss, who caught nine passes for 212 yards and a touchdown, was
voted MVP one day after he threw a fit and refused to appear in the
team picture. Saturday was photo day at the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I wasn't in the team picture, but I'm not going to tell
you why,'' Moss said.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Moss was angry when stadium security wouldn't let
some of his friends onto the field because they didn't have passes.
``This is a different setup with a different set of rules,'' Dungy
said. ``That wouldn't happen in regular season.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFC led from start to finish and scored a record number of
points. Dungy, who coaches the Tampa Bay Buccaneers, fired
offensive coordinator Mike Shula during the week. Quarterbacks
coach Clyde Christensen called plays for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   During the season, the Bucs finished 11-5 but scored more than
30 points only once. They had five games in which they failed to
score an offensive touchdown. Tampa Bay fullback Mike Alstott
scored three touchdowns Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know what to say, except that 51 points is a
lot,'' Dungy said. ``And it's always nice to see the defense score,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona cornerback Aeneas Williams returned an interception 62
yards for the NFC's first touchdown, and Tampa Bay outside
linebacker Derrick Brooks returned an interception 20 yards for a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The only NFC touchdown pass came when Beuerlein found Moss to
rub it in.
</P>
<P>
   AFC quarterbacks Peyton Manning, Mark Brunell and Rich Gannon
combined to throw five interceptions. The NFC suffered none.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules are set up a certain way, and we tried to take
advantage of them,'' Dungy said. ``Great players make coaching a
lot easier. Great players always want the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
