<SLUG> BC-SKATE-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD GUARD IS OVERCOME 
</HEADLINE>
 SPEEDSKATING-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ They had been champions so often that most folks
figured they had retired the trophies. Gunda Niemann-Stirnemann of
Germany had won five straight world all-around speedskating titles
and eight of the last nine. Rintje Ritsma of the Netherlands had
won three of the last five. Sunday, both of them were toppled by
teammates halfway along the road to Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old Niemann-Stirnemann, the most dominant women's
skater of the last decade, was beaten by 27-year-old Claudia
Pechstein, runner-up the last four years. And the 27-year-old
Ritsma was taken down by the 26-year-old Gianni Romme, who led a
Dutch sweep of the medals ahead of two-time champ Ids Postma and
Ritsma, winning by a whopping margin of more than two points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible,'' said Romme, who was making his all-around
debut after winning both the 5,000 and 10,000 at the Olympics.
``The Olympics is one thing. But the all-around championship is the
biggest thing in speedskating.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, as expected, were innocent bystanders in their
own oval. Derek Parra, KC Boutiette, and Jennifer Rodriguez all
missed the cut for the final race and finished out of the top 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can only skate as fast as we can skate,'' shrugged Parra,
who has been fighting a respiratory infection and was coughing up
blood before he took the ice. ``We tried our best.''
</P>
<P>
   No US skater has won a world all-around medal since Eric Flaim
and Dave Silk went 1-3 in 1988. The Dutch own the men's side of the
sport and the Germans the women's. The only questions here were
whether distance king Romme could sprint fast enough to prevail and
whether Pechstein could unseat Niemann-Stirnemann after chasing her
for a quadrennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second place is a good place, but the first place is better,''
declared Pechstein, whose name means ``unlucky stone'' in German.
``Maybe I thought I could beat Gunda, but I didn't believe it
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Niemann-Stirnemann, who has skated for two countries (East and
reunified Germany) under three names, has been an icon for years
and is arguably the best female skater of all time. Her resume is
unparalleled _ eight world titles, eight Olympic medals (three of
them gold) at four Games, 16 world records, eight world
single-distance crowns.
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of the world has been catching up. Anni Friesinger,
another teammate, had beaten Niemann-Stirnemann at last month's
European championships, which Niemann-Stirnemann had been using as
a tuneup for the world meet. ``The goal for Gunda was here,'' said
Pechstein. ``But that was my goal, too.''
</P>
<P>
   After Pechstein had beaten her nemesis in Saturday's 3,000 and
finished four places ahead in the 500, she knew she was sitting
solid. When Pechstein edged Niemann-Stirnemann again in Sunday's
1,500, she needed only to stay within lassoing range in the 5,000
to claim her crown. ``I know Gunda can beat me,'' Pechstein said.
``I have this in my head when I race. But she has to beat me by
five seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   For half the distance, Pechstein stayed alongside her. Then
Niemann-Stirnemann opened the throttle and widened the gap to a
second, then two, then three. ``As an athlete, you always think you
can get there,'' she said. ``You must always hope, because you can
never tell what will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Niemann-Stirnemann punished herself for the final two laps, legs
churning, face contorted, mouth agape. She finished in a humming
7:02.11, but Pechstein was only 3.76 seconds behind. ``I look at
the scoreboard for a time,'' said Pechstein. ``And when I see it is
not five seconds, now it is clear in my head that I am the
winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Romme didn't bother checking the math. After he'd skated a
respectable 500 (12th, but less than half a second behind Ritsma)
and blown away the field by 10 seconds in the 5,000, Romme only had
to keep from seizing up Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was only fourth in the 1,500, Romme still beat Ritsma
and all but dead-heated with Postma in his pair. All he needed do
in the 10,000 was put his arms behind his back and cruise _ and he
did. ``I thought, another 25 laps, this will be heavy,'' said
Romme, whose mother named him after Gianni Rivera, the old Italian
soccer player. ``But once I was racing, I wasn't tired. After half
the race, I knew I had it.''
</P>
<P>
   Back home, they stayed up until 1 in the morning to see what the
scoreboard said. The citizenry knew a Dutchman would win here. They
just wanted to see which name would go on the trophy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
