<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORDS TAKE TUMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
 BALANCE MEET-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Johnny Gray had no intention of losing. He never does.
Especially not this time, when his 4x800-meter relay team was going
up against a foursome that included a couple of milers and a
hurdles guy. When you've held the 800-meter American outdoor record
(1:42.60) for 15 years and you're coming off a couple of big
early-season indoor wins that included the Millrose Games and
you're gunning for a world record, you feel pretty confident you
can handle a couple of milers and a hurdles guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we kind of underestimated the other team,'' said a
subdued Gray after his cooldown.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently so. In the final event of Sunday's fifth annual New
Balance Invitational, in front of 2,250 fans at the Reggie Lewis
Track &AMP; Athletic Center, the Global Athletics &AMP; Marketing team of
Joey Woody (400-meter hurdler), Karl Paranya (miler), Rich Kenah
(the only pure 800-meter guy), and David Krummenacker (another
miler) gathered for the first _ and probably last _ time to set a
world record in 7 minutes 13.94 seconds, knocking almost four
seconds off the 7:17.8 set by a Soviet Union team back in 1971. The
second-place Reebok Enclave squad (7:14:78) and the Gray-anchored
Santa Monica Track Club (7:16.59) also broke the old mark, becoming
the second- and third-fastest teams in history.
</P>
<P>
   Also clicking Sunday was Regina Jacobs, who set an American
record at 1,000 meters when her 2:35.29 easily slipped under the
2:37.6 set by Mary Slaney 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's way up there,'' declared the 36-year-old Jacobs, asked
where the record stands on a list of career accomplishments that so
far includes two silver medals at 1,500 meters at the outdoor World
Championships and three Olympic appearances. ``I never would have
imagined I would be running like this at this age.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, Jacobs demolished the mile field at Millrose
when she triumphed in 4:24.04, less than four seconds off another
Slaney record. ``Running Millrose and really going for it there
took a lot out of me,'' said Jacobs. ``The last 100, I had to
really dig in.''
</P>
<P>
   What was billed as a chase for the record actually turned into
quite a race when Toni Hodgkinson stunningly took it out from the
gun, leaving both Jacobs and the rabbit behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never raced the 1,000 before, so I just raced the 800
pace,'' said the New Zealand 800-meter Olympian. ``I was thinking
when she goes how hard it was going to be to hang on to her.''
Seeing Jacobs go through 800 in 2:03, her husband and coach, Tom
Craig, began to fear his wife was racing Hodgkinson rather than
watching the clock, and so with 180 meters left he yelled for her
to go. Now. She listened, and so takes back to Oakland, Calif., the
US record and the new Chevy Blazer that comes with it.
</P>
<P>
   In the relay, the new world-record holders will split a $50,000
bonus, and Gray said it was the hurdler who did the most to earn
it. Running the first leg for the GAM team, Woody, who finished
second at the 400-meter hurdles in last summer's national
championships, barely trailed Lubert Lewis of the Syracuse Chargers
when he handed off to Paranya, putting him in good position to take
a lead that Kenah and Krummenaker _ running anchor basically by
default after the others turned it down _ never lost. ``I didn't
think (Woody) would have the heart and guts to run that leg, and
that did it for them,'' said Gray. ``I think he was the reason they
won. Our guys didn't run under control; they kind of panicked.''
</P>
<P>
   The GAM team, meanwhile, ran remarkably even splits of 1:49.34,
148.31, 1:48.48, and 1:47.81. ``On paper it looked like this was an
easy record, but there's a reason it was around since 1971,'' said
Kenah. ``We were lucky we all clicked on the same day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 0053EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
