<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-NORWAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US WOMEN GIVEN FRIENDLY BOOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ They are no longer invincible nor
unbeatable. And after a 3-2 loss to Norway Sunday, the image of the
US women's national team is bound to suffer, at least until it
meets the Norwegians in a rematch Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the rematch will be conducted behind closed gates at Florida
Atlantic University in Boca Raton. This defeat occurred before
12,031 spectators at Lockhart Stadium, plus a national television
audience.
</P>
<P>
   This was not a successful start to the April Heinrichs coaching
era, though Heinrichs emphasized the game as a stage to try out new
players rather than a must-win situation.
</P>
<P>
   Norway, though, played to win, and coach Per-Mathias Hogmo made
effective substitutions in the second half. The US team had taken a
2-1 lead as Kristine Lilly finished in a chaotic scramble near the
goal area in the 71st minute. But the US was becoming disorganized
and slightly wreckless, and the Norwegians capitalized, tying it on
a goal by Carla Overbeck 10 minutes later. Then, substitute Dagny
Mellgren launched a dramatic winner from 25 yards into the far
upper corner of the net over goalkeeper Saskia Webber a minute into
injury time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the players it's not where you start but where you
finish, whether it's this game or in life,'' Heinrichs said. ``We
lost but we learned. We played very dynamic, exciting, and it was
difficult to defend against our flank play. We got forward and sent
numbers forward. We were able to settle down the game with
possession. We were rusty, but we can take care of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the United States was capable of winning this match,
because of and despite the rawness of young players such as Nandi
Pryce, whose poor back pass led to Hege Riise's 19th-minute
penalty. But as Pryce, the 17-year-old sister of Denver Broncos'
Pro Bowler Trevor Pryce, improved and became more composed,
Heinrichs made so many changes that the United States began losing
its compactness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see willful players, how they would impact us for
winning,'' Heinrichs said. ``We don't want to give away a win. But
I wanted to see personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many ways to win, though, and the US failed to play
the possession game while holding the lead in the final minutes,
precisely when it was most judicious to do so. By then, the players
best suited to that tactic _ Julie Foudy, Mia Hamm, Shannon
MacMillan, and Tiffeny Milbrett _ had departed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always hate to lose, but it's the first game of the year
and we worked out some kinks,'' said MacMillan, whose dynamic play
on the right side led to Hamm's diving header in the 25th minute.
``Those young players are the future. We had a lot of different
looks and we have a lot of talent not even suiting up. You always
learn from losses more than wins. But this makes us mad and we will
be fired up Wednesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lilly: ``We never want to lose, but we played a good game
and we want to win the next game. Give us a break _ it's early, and
we lost two to China last year. We don't mind these losses. It's
better now than later.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the United States hardly seemed like a beaten squad
afterward. This was its first defeat since a 2-1 loss against China
April 25, and there will be four more games against Norway this
year in preparation for the Sydney Olympics in September. And for
players such as Pryce, this is their Dream Team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing is never fun, but we are excited to build on this,''
Pryce said. ``It's a whole new atmosphere. I watched them win the
World Cup and everyone that watched that got chills because they
did it and because of the way they did it. I never, in my wildest
dreams, thought I would be playing with these players. But they
were great to me _ they told me everything would be all right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
