<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS CATCH OFF-AGAIN SONICS IN OLD FORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Like an age-old soap opera with repeating story lines,
the Sonics reverted to a familiar plot.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the team's shooting suffered a horrific death. The
Sonics' energy level and rebounding were on life support. And they
left betrayed by an official, who eventually ejected coach Paul
Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   Another episode of As The Sonics Turn _ from a team with a
contending look to one that is a ratings nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal's rare dismissal was about the only twist Sunday on a
night the Sonics were predictably inconsistent throughout a 105-93
loss to the Phoenix Suns at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've shown how good we can be, but we're not doing it every
night,'' Westphal said. ``It comes down to effort. That shouldn't
be the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The on-again/off-again Sonics lost for the sixth time in the
past nine games. They have dropped every other game in the past
week, this time losing to a team they had dominated Friday at
KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton out-dueled Phoenix point guard Jason Kidd in that
game with 23 points, a career-high 13 rebounds and seven assists.
Payton's turnaround Sunday characterized how the Sonics' struggled
offensively this time.
</P>
<P>
   He had 13 points, seven rebounds, seven assists and five steals,
but Payton missed 14 of his 18 shots. Kidd stole the show with 22
points on 7-for-12 shooting, 12 assists and seven rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Payton wasn't the only Sonics starter whose shooting was shabby.
Excluding Ruben Patterson (2-for-3, 10 points), the starting five
combined to shoot just 12-for-44.
</P>
<P>
   Vin Baker followed his 22-point, nine-rebound game Friday with a
paltry eight points and four rebounds in 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the guys might be tired,'' Payton said. `` ... We've
got to ride this out. We've got to suck it up. A lot of guys are
hurt and playing with it. So these four days (off) coming up for
the All-Star (break) are going to be pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Sonics must get through two more road games _ Tuesday
at San Antonio and Wednesday at Dallas _ before the midseason break
in the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The stated goal is to go into the All-Star weekend on a positive
note. For that to happen, the Sonics must break this disturbing
cycle. They came out flat against the Suns. And despite staying
within 46-45 at halftime, the Sonics never found the enthusiasm to
remain close.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns opened the third quarter with an 11-2 run that
separated them from the Sonics for good.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-pointer from Kidd capped the offensive barrage, and Phoenix
outscored the Sonics 31-17 in the period. Kidd, held to eight
points on 3-for-14 shooting in the first half, ignited the Suns in
that decisive period.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Kidd drove past Payton and threw down a one-hand
dunk before Baker could rotate to the basket for a block. Moments
later, Kidd stole the ball from Payton at midcourt, dodged a pair
of Sonic defenders on the fastbreak, and scooped a layup that
basket put the Suns ahead 70-58.
</P>
<P>
   They led 77-62 heading into the fourth. The Sonics never got any
closer than 13 points, and they forged that 103-90 score with just
1:23 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played aggressively,'' Payton said of Kidd. ``He made
shots. Friday he couldn't make a shot and he did today. ... And we
didn't have a lot of intensity out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal perhaps exhibited more fire in 30 seconds than his
players did in all of that decisive third quarter. With the Sonics
trailing 87-70 and 7:49 left in the fourth period, Westphal got
into a confrontation with referee Jack Nies.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal was upset that Shammond Williams did not receive a foul
after having his jumper blocked from behind. Westphal drew his
first technical almost immediately after he petitioned Nies.
</P>
<P>
   A surprised Westphal kept arguing and Nies wasted little time
issuing a second technical foul and automatic ejection.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no point in talking about it,'' Westphal said
afterward. ``I can't win. The more I think about it, I really
didn't have very many nice comments about the game. ... We were
very flat, and that contributed to my mood.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's bench was its only reprieve. Williams, Rashard Lewis,
and Jelani McCoy played extended minutes. Each played a big role in
the reserves shooting 18-for-38 and outscoring Phoenix's bench
46-32. Even so, the starters had dug a hole too deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play well as a team,'' Patterson said. ``Some nights
we come out with a lot of effort and some nights we don't. I don't
know what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
