r s BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT     02-07 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER AWFUL NIGHT FOR CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _In an event that fetched memories of the ``down
with disco'' demolition, the scariest records in the NBA collided
Sunday at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Hellish records that can't be fully depreciated until they're
spun backward.
</P>
<P>
   And when the warping was finished, the Chicago Bulls had
improved to a still-NBA-worst 10-35 by whipping the Clippers
(11-35), 100-90, before 12,973.
</P>
<P>
   Interim head coach Jim Todd's honeymoon record is love-2. The
squad's broken record includes 18 losses in the last 20 dates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so bitter,'' Clipper rookie Lamar Odom said when
quadruple-teamed by reporters. ``I don't want to say anything. I'd
be a bad interview.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right.
</P>
<P>
   No problem; we still had Maurice Taylor, the team's go-to
interview and game-high scorer (23 points). Taylor was reading the
final stat sheet when the press arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same thing as everyone saw,'' Taylor said when asked what the
numbers suggested. ``An ass-kicking.''
</P>
<P>
   The proof: The beata-Bulls made 54 percent of their field-goal
attempts. After his team coughed up 10 turnovers in a
Clipper-dominated (29-13) first quarter, Toni Kukoc ripped the
Clips for 11 of his 20 points in the second quarter and helped
slice the deficit to 48-45 by intermission. Chicago pounded the
home team, 27-15, in the third and coasted in.
</P>
<P>
   Another disaster clue was the Clippers' 36-24 rebounding
disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   The ballpark remedy?
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a sense of urgency on the defensive end,'' Taylor
said. ``Actually, we need that sense or urgency for the game,
period. Not just one aspect of the game. But our main problem is
our defense ... we don't play any.''
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, the Clips gained valuable ground leading up
to the May 21 draft-lottery showdown with the Bulls and any other
slackers. It should be noted that Kukoc's return from injury has
helped produce a relatively amazing eight victories in 17 games.
Chicago is threatening to louse up its shot at the No. 1 selection.
</P>
<P>
   On the Clippers' ``it figures'' side, there is no monster player
primed for plucking with this year's first pick.
</P>
<P>
   Of sidebar interest was the first on-court meeting between last
year's first pick, Bulls rookie Elton Brand, and the player most
sharpies had expected to be that pick, Odom.
</P>
<P>
   Odom, who was the fourth pick, must have been sufficiently
stoked to prove the Bulls wrong, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah, not really,'' Odom said. ``They picked one of my best
friends, Elton Brand.''
</P>
<P>
   So there weren't any sour grapes and the matchup provided little
competitive juice. Brand, a power forward, had 21 points on 8-of-11
shooting and 8 rebounds. Odom, a small forward, had 4 points, 2
rebounds, 26 minutes and 4 participation-killing fouls.
</P>
<P>
   Also harpooning the Clipper cause was bad karma for Eric
Murdock, who turned his left ankle and left the game for good with
8:33 remaining in round one. Troy Hudson closed for Murdock,
supplying 19 points and 8 assists.
</P>
<P>
   The Clips were up, 8-5, when Murdock left, but did increase
their lead to 27-11 when Tyrone Nesby dropped a pair of free throws
with 47 seconds left in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Center Michael Olowokandi had 6 field-goal attempts and 10
points in the first quarter, but finished the game with 12 points
and 11 field-goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either they (Bulls) did a better job of defending him,'' Todd
said, ``or we did a bad job of getting the ball to him. It was
probably a little bit of both.''
</P>
<P>
   All Todd and the Clips need to do in preparation for Wednesday's
game at Portland is work on, well, everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing for us,'' Derek Anderson (12 points) said, ``is
to start a whole new training camp.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
