<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, Feb. 7.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VIOLENCE (Mitrovica, Yugoslavia) _ Gani Gjaka buried his
wife, Nerimane, on Sunday, laying her shrouded body in a muddy
field on the southern edge of this tense and bitterly divided town,
where Mrs. Gjaka was one of the eight Albanian victims of an
eruption of violence by local Serbs. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   PLUTONIUM-SECURITY (Undated) _ _In a major agreement aimed at
safeguarding nuclear fuel that could be used to make weapons,
Russia has promised to stop making plutonium out of fuel from its
civilian power reactors as part of a $100 million joint research
and aid package from the United States, Clinton administration and
Russian officials say. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA-POLITICS (Zagreb, Croatia) _ Croatia votes on Monday for
only its second president in a tightening race that hinges more on
personality than on policy. But after the death in December of the
autocratic Franjo Tudjman, who ruled Croatia from its independence
in 1991, voters still seem likely to go for the man who has
presented himself as least ambitious and power-hungry, the
avuncular Stipe Mesic, 65. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-LABOR (Washington) _ President Clinton plans to ask
Congress to more than double the nation's spending on reducing
child labor overseas, administration officials said Sunday. By
Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   KOHL-KICKBACKS (Berlin) _ Prosecutors estimate that more than
$70 million was illegally paid in kickbacks to middlemen on the
sales of tanks and a dilapidated oil refinery during the rule of
Helmut Kohl, the former chancellor whose once glowing reputation
has already been battered by revelations of secret party financing.
By Roger Cohen and John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-HOUSING (Ft. Meade, Md.) _ Last year Secretary of
Defense William Cohen trumpeted a hefty pay increase for the
military. This year he's highlighting more money for housing _ all
to stop the steady departure of service members from the military.
By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ Bill Bradley said flatly Sunday
that he must win primaries in several states on the next big day of
voting March 7. And to do so, he said, he must sell his agenda more
powerfully to hard-core Democrats who streamed to Vice President Al
Gore in the Iowa caucuses and New Hampshire primary. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZ-MCCAIN (Phoenix) _ There is a long history in presidential
campaigns of candidates winning their home state primaries by hefty
margins, often by more than 40 percentage points. So Sen. John
McCain of Arizona, suddenly on a roll elsewhere, should have little
to worry about when this state holds its Republican primary on
February 22, right? But the fact is, McCain is running a bit scared
at home. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   GRAHAM-PROFILE (Beaufort, S.C.) _ On the McCain bus with Rep.
Lindsay Graham, one of the few Republican leaders in South Carolina
who backs John McCain. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-MEDIA (Undated) _ The role of free media in the
campaign. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BUDGET _ President Clinton will propose a $1.84 trillion
federal budget for next year on Monday and will call for using much
of the projected budget surplus over the next decade to strengthen
and expand the Medicare system of health insurance for the elderly,
administration officials said Sunday. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC-BOOKS-MEDIA (New York) _ The demand for Arthur C.
Clarke's science fiction novel about a malevolent computer named
HAL has endured for three decades, but interest was rather tepid
for the author's six-page, double-spaced essay about ``TV's
Time-Travel Future.'' So last month the British author of ``2001 _
A Space Odyssey'' plunged into the infant market for electronic
books _ ignoring the risk to his prestige. By Doreen Carvajal
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE-MANNESMANN (Undated) _ Interviews with executives on
both sides in the Vodafone takeover of Mannesmann tell the story of
a struggle that reached a level of Machiavellian intrigue rivaling
anything served up by American corporate raiders in the 1980s. By
Edmund L. Andrews and Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-NEWYORK (New York) _ When the first people tried to
start Internet companies in New York in the mid-'90s, they had to
scrounge to raise money. To their chagrin, the big Silicon Valley
venture capital firms largely shunned New York as an Internet
backwater. But all that has changed. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DOUBLECLICK-CRITICISM (Undated) _ DoubleClick, a company that
tracks consumers as they make their way around the Web, has never
been popular with privacy advocates. In recent weeks, though, mere
tension has grown into all-out war with the announcement that the
company has begun adding information about consumers' offline
behavior to its vast database. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   GQ-TITILLATE-MEDIA (New York) _ Bowing to pressure placed on the
entire men's magazine field by the success of Maxim magazine, GQ
has with the past few issues appeared to ramp up the explicitness
of female sexuality on its pages. But the changes may backfire. By
Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-BRIEFS _ Edward Koch, the former mayor of New York, is
co-founder of TheLaw.Com, which is to appear on the Web on Monday.
And other news items from the computer world.
</P>
<P>
   PAMPERS-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The push by Procter &AMP; Gamble to
improve the creativity of its advertising accelerates Monday with a
campaign for one of its most important products: Pampers. By Stuart
Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   BRILLS-EDITOR-MEDIA (New York) _ His new job was only hours old,
but already the editor in chief of Brill's Content was promising
``evolution, not revolution'' at the magazine that offers a sober
leveling gaze at the media industry. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRUFFLER-BOOK-REVIEW _ Gustaf Sobin's ``The Fly-Truffler'' is
one of those rare, haunting novels that you consume in a single
sitting. By Christopher Lehmann-Haupt.
</P>
<P>
   TV-MARY-REVIEW _ Mary Richards and Rhoda Morganstern are back
together again, this time in a TV movie. By Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   OSCARS-PREDICT _ Last year at this time, a titanic struggle was
already under way between the forces of ``Saving Private Ryan'' and
the minions of ``Shakespeare in Love'' to win the Oscar for best
picture. This year, though, the awards race could go in any one of
a half-dozen directions. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   MONK-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ In the one-man show ``Monk,''
the challenge is how to animate, in language, a man whose eloquence
was both indisputable and wordless: Thelonious Monk, the brilliant,
troubled and enigmatic jazz pianist.  &QL; 
By Bruce Weber.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Undated) _ Bob Herbert examines the glass
ceiling in politics.
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Washington) _ William Safire offers George W.
Bush some advice for revitalizing his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKN-DRUG-TEST (Undated) _ ichard Dumas, who was suspended for
drug and alcohol abuse by the NBA twice in the early 1990s, once
said that if the league ever tested players for marijuana, ``there
wouldn't be no NBA.'' For the first time the league is now testing
for marijuana, and Dumas' calculations appear more than slightly
off. According to two people with knowledge of the results, 12 out
of 430 active players tested positive for marijuana during training
camp last fall. Exclusive. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-ARATON-COLUMN (Harare, Zimbabwe) _ Analysis of John McEnroe
as Davis Cup captain; Wayne Black rips into him. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   HKN-ALLSTAR-COLUMN (Toronto) _ On Hockey column about the NHL
All-Star Game. By Joe Lapointe.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-MIKE-SCHMITT (Miami) _ Mike Schmitt is trying to make the
senior golf tour. By Charlie Nobles.
</P>
