<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8800 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-ANDERSON-NET-LADN     02-07 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-NET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY CENTER TO GIVE GRADUATES TOOLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Anderson School, UCLA's graduate school of
business management, is stepping into the new Internet and
e-commerce world by establishing a center dedicated to the
technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   The University of California, Los Angeles, Center for Management
in the Information Economy will combine research and real-world
experience, making it one of only a handful of universities across
the nation with a business program focused on technology. School
officials are expected to announce the new program today.
</P>
<P>
   The center will not offer a separate degree but will be a
resource for the Anderson School's degree candidates, said Uday
Karmarkar, the center's director.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles' tech leaders said UCLA is filling a need for the
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world has changed, technologies are changing, and at the
heart of this is information technology,'' said Rohit Shukla, chief
executive officer of the Los Angeles Regional Technology Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Technology in general is much more important to management than
it was a decade ago, said Tim Walsh, vice president, international,
at Calabasas-based video game maker THQ Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology to me represents the ability to use more tools to
solve the problems you have,'' Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's an intranet that links your sales staff with the
home office or a new telecommunications network that works more
efficiently, managers in any industry must know how to apply
technology, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't have to be in a technical environment, you could
be selling cookies,'' he said. ``If someone that's aspiring to be
in management uses tools like that, it really gives you a leg up on
your competition, and I think it gives you a leg up as a manager.''
</P>
<P>
   All managers must understand how to use technology in
management, Shukla said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no longer relegated to MIS departments,'' he said. ``From
the perspective of the preparation of the student, it's extremely
important.''
</P>
<P>
   An additional benefit of having such a center is that it builds
a loyal base of alumni, Shukla said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Endowments are where it's at, and UCLA has been very behind
the curve on that,'' Shukla said.
</P>
<P>
   The Westwood school joins academic leaders such as the
University of California at Berkeley, Stanford University, Harvard
University and MIT in addressing the mushrooming technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   One of the center's goals is to give MBA students real-world
experience with technology. To that end, the center has programs to
place its students in start-up companies, helping them develop
workable business or marketing plans.
</P>
<P>
   Shukla said he hopes to see that type of commitment inside the
classroom as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely vital that their graduates have real-life
exposure to the trends that are pushing those companies along,''
Shukla said.
</P>
<P>
   It will be important for the Anderson School to attract
knowledgeable professionals into its classroom to explain the
industry's latest developments to the students, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changes almost every month, if not every quarter,'' Shukla
said. ``It's a dynamically changing environment. They have got to
be able to make sure that dynamism is represented in the
instructional setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the Anderson School's 360 MBA candidates, 120 have a special
interest in technology, Karmarkar said. The school's graduates
typically enter one of four fields: finance, marketing, consulting
or entrepreneurial ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect that Los Angeles is increasingly going to be a
competitor to Silicon Valley in terms of entrepreneurial
activity,'' he said. ``It's a surprising, almost inexplicable thing
that we don't have a Silicon Valley type of experience already.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
