<HEADLINE>
A NATIVE DAUGHTER SPEAKS SOFTLY, CAUGHT IN A CULTURAL LIMBO 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
(bl) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ So here I am in Darty, a huge discount appliance store,
trying to buy a dishwasher. So far, it's going really well. I am
just another customer _ more important, just another French
customer _ and the saleswoman is eager to make a sale.
</P>
<P>
   Then it happens. I am talking about installation and I need to
say that my clothes dryer is in the way. Only I stumble. I can't
remember the name for a dryer. Did I ever know it? We never had one
when I was growing up here as a child.
</P>
<P>
   In desperation, I try ``a machine that dries clothes.'' Nope,
that's not it. I see it on the woman's face. That look of
suspicion. It's all over. The fact that she got me to buy a more
expensive model makes no difference. I'm a foreigner. I'm not one
of them. Her tone changes. She is suddenly brusque. I place my
order and leave, defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, yes, I did get my dishwasher. But that's not the point. The
thing about the French is that you're either one of them or you're
not, and they don't like being fooled. And for me, who as a child
used to make merciless fun of the way my American father spoke
French, being taken as an insider is a point of pride. No matter
that I have not lived here in 35 years. Being found out as less
than French in these small daily encounters is humiliating.
</P>
<P>
   Within days of moving here last fall, helpful American
expatriates were giving us tips and offering us books on how to
survive in France. Some of the practical information was about
which bilingual schools were good. But much of the advice was about
psychological survival: How to understand the French and not have
your feelings hurt when they treat you rudely because you are a
foreigner. Which phrases you might use to get a smile when you are
trying to buy a croissant. Why you would be considered a lout if
you brought a bottle of wine to the dinner party that you were
unlikely to get invited to anyway because the French take such a
long time to make friends. Whom you should kiss on both cheeks and
at what times of the day.
</P>
<P>
   I found all this very amusing. My mother is French. French was
my first language. I have relatives in Nice. I do not find the
French so mysterious. But we moved back to America when I was 8
years old and there are lots of gaps in my knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I know I can't play on the grass in the Luxembourg Gardens
_ that hasn't changed. And I know you have to pay for both the
beach chair and the umbrella and maybe even the mattress by the
pool. But I stood dumbfounded the first time I went into a
supermarket and realized that I needed to pay a 10 franc deposit to
push a  &UR; chariot &LR;  up and down the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes I almost envy the American with a thick accent. It is
clear who he is. Instead, I lead an odd life of constantly being
discovered as a fake or treated like a moron. Perhaps this is worse
in Paris, where there is the usual big-city impatience. But you
find it all over. Who is this idiot who obviously speaks French but
has asked me for a booklet for her subway pass, when everyone knows
it's called a case? What is the matter with this middle-aged woman
that she would come into a curtain store to ask for curtain hooks,
when everyone knows they are sold at the Prisunic five-and-dime?
Isn't she far too old to be just discovering that fitted sheets for
twin beds come in three different sizes here?
</P>
<P>
   Some of the stuff written in those how-to-survive-France books
seems pretty ludicrous. If you believe it all, you would never want
to meet a French person, let alone gain acceptance. One guide says
the French never use bathrooms outside their homes and you
shouldn't ask to use their bathroom when you visit them.
</P>
<P>
   That's ridiculous. Who are all those people who are always in
the restaurant bathrooms when I want to use them? The French half
of me can't help but be partly offended. What would my aunt say to
such nonsense?
</P>
<P>
   Here is another one: the French don't waste smiles. Americans
walk down the street smiling, willy-nilly. But not the French. They
must have a reason, something must amuse them before they grin. I
test this one day. Smiles all over the place. Although there may be
some truth to it because I tried a smile on one of the guards in my
office building, and now he practically falls off his chair trying
to greet me every time I come in.
</P>
<P>
   But I have to agree that the French are not wild about
strangers. Some of the books point out that the French have been
invaded more times than anyone can count. Tourism is surely a form
of invasion, too. How many times have I sat with my relatives in
Nice watching some American tourist complaining that the French
version of a grilled cheese sandwich, a croque monsieur, isn't
toasted on the bottom. Or asking for cold milk with coffee,
something incomprehensible to the French.
</P>
<P>
   How we have laughed. Let them go back to their bologna
sandwiches, or better yet those chalky things they call
marshmallows, we have joked. Nowadays, however, I am often on the
other side.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's not the basic exchanges but the follow-up
questions that are my demise. I wanted my hair cut and highlighted,
for example, and called for an appointment. No problem, until the
receptionist asked me what kind of highlights. I caved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm American and I don't understand what you just said,'' I
said. The aggravation on the other side of the line was total.
``Never mind,'' she snapped. ``Just come in.''
</P>
<P>
   I know there is a whole part of France that I can not have just
yet because I don't know how things are done here. The butcher
shops, for instance. I don't even know what half the stuff hanging
from the ceiling is. I just know I'm headed for humiliation if I go
in there. So I don't, not yet. But I remember visiting my
grandmother when I was a teen-ager and how she would insist that I
go grocery shopping with her. Mr. Laiolo, the butcher, had known
the family for years. He would play his part. Oh, she is so big, he
would say. She is so beautiful. And my grandmother, who had been
widowed for years by then, would beam.
</P>
<P>
   It is nice when I am not discovered. When I'm taken for French,
I have all sorts of kindnesses to recount. The car rental agent who
gave me a big car at a discount and wished me ``bon courage''
because she knew I was going to a furniture discount store
notorious for crowds and long lines. The saleswoman who would not
sell me shoes with a slight flaw in them, even though I had not
noticed it. And the many waiters who have tried to deter me from
what they considered terrible choices.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the French even seem to sympathize with the burden of
dual nationality. After hearing me translate what my two daughters
wanted for lunch, one waiter smiled down at us and tsked over the
situation. ``Ah,'' he said. ``I see, a French mother with two
American children.''
</P>
<P>
   The children are catching on fast, though. The other day, they
insisted that I speak French to them as we walked down the street
so nobody would know they did not entirely belong here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 0938EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
