<SLUG> BC-WWF-FOOTBALL-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WWF IS READY TO RUMBLE WITH THE NFL 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
(bl) 
 By ALAN SCHWARZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a foreign object in the ring!
</P>
<P>
   Just days after its Super Bowl-winning coach (Dick Vermeil)
retired and its second player in two months (Ray Lewis) was
arrested on murder charges, the National Football League now has to
grapple with this: The renegade World Wrestling Federation is
starting its own football circuit next February.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the barbarous, spandexed, testosterone-pickled theater of
professional wrestling is invading the barbarous, spandexed,
testosterone-pickled theater of professional football. The WWF
gleefully unveiled its plans for the XFL _ the X stands for
``xciting,'' ``xplosive'' and ``xtreme,'' naturally _ at a New York
press conference with onlookers grudgingly nodding that this thing
could actually work.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the WWF knows more about lowest common denominators
than Euclid.
</P>
<P>
   Having built its billion-dollar programming and merchandising
empire on sating fans' basest desires with cartoonish villains and
blood-soaked steel-cage matches, the WWF hopes to apply similar
rawness to the XFL.
</P>
<P>
   Outcomes will not be scripted, but looser rules will allow a
return to the finest traditions of ``smash-mouth football,'' as the
pugnacious WWF mastermind Vince McMahon called it. Meanwhile,
microphones and cameras will pummel fans into sensorial ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   Fair catches will be discouraged so more runners get creamed on
punt returns. No in-the-grasp rule will protect ``lilly-white
quarterbacks,'' McMahon vowed. He didn't specify just what felony a
player will have to commit to get called for a personal foul,
merely saying, ``This will not be a league for pantywaists or
sissies.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameras inside helmets will let viewers experience huddles and
play-calling up close, and perhaps enjoy the vicarious pleasure of
being run over by a huge person wearing armor. Microphones will
deliver coaches' sideline diatribes live.
</P>
<P>
   At least one WWF fan is looking forward to the XFL: Bob
Kuberski, a 6-foot-4, 300-pound Philadelphian who happens to play
defensive tackle for the NFL's New England Patriots. ``I think it's
a good idea,'' Kuberski said. ``Go out there, cut it loose, see
what kind of interesting twists they can put on the game. It'll be
real physical.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions about whether the WWF can run a legitimate football
league only widened McMahon's Cheshire-cat grin. ``May I never be
thought of as legit,'' he sighed. ``Anything but that.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether hyped-up opponents will be encouraged to stage screaming
matches outside locker rooms remains to be seen. But asked later
whom he meant with his ``sissies'' remark, McMahon barked, ``I
think I'm looking at one now.''
</P>
<P>
   You go, Vince!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 0940EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0053 </DOCNO>
