<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-PRESS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIRED OF NEWS THAT ROCKS THE BOAT? VISIT JAPAN. 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
(bl) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ When Japan's largest newspaper recently refused
advertising from two of the country's most popular weekly
magazines, citing their sexually explicit content, it put Mizuho
Fukushima in a quandary.
</P>
<P>
   As a leading feminist here, she found the magazines' big
displays of women posing nude or engaging in sex acts deeply
troubling. But as a member of parliament, she found the coverage of
current events by these same weeklies indispensable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women should take the initiative in eliminating the nudity
from these magazines,'' Fukushima said. ``But I must buy them
because they always carry stories on subjects that I need to know
about, subjects that the newspapers don't cover.''
</P>
<P>
   Fukushima's statement was a stinging indictment of Japan's huge
daily press, and one shared by growing numbers of readers in this
country.
</P>
<P>
   Media critics here say that Japan, virtually alone among
advanced industrialized democracies, combines a lack of aggressive,
independent-spirited daily newspapers with a lack of commercially
successful weekly newsmagazines in the vein of Time, Newsweek, The
Economist or Der Spiegel.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's daily newspapers boast the highest circulation figures
in the world. In the 19th century they were an instrument of
nation-building and patriotism, and critics say they have evolved
in the postwar period into increasingly complacent entities that
routinely leave a large host of taboo subjects _ from the imperial
family to corruption in sumo _ untouched. Most other matters,
meanwhile, are reported in uncritical, gazette-like snippets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newspapers here don't write lies, but they avoid dealing with
uncomfortable truths,'' said Tatsuya Iwase, author of ``The Reason
Newspapers are not Interesting,'' a 1999 book. ``Japan has the
hardware of the Western press, but there is no software. The inside
is empty.''
</P>
<P>
   Iwase said Japanese newspapers have little more than a formulaic
recognition of the freedom of speech and ``disregard the readers'
right to know.'' The public, he said, would eagerly welcome a new
newspaper that carried feistier reporting and better analysis, but
the system, from the government to the advertising powers, would do
everything to prevent this.
</P>
<P>
   The textbook case illustrating the reluctance of Japan's
newspapers to dig up controversial or embarrassing stories dates to
the 1970s, when a reporter for Mainichi Shimbun produced a major
scoop about the United States' compensation to residents for
damages by the U.S. military in Okinawa. Rather than being
rewarded, the reporter was accused of having had an affair with a
source and was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's racy weeklies regularly plunge into this void with
gusto, revealing scandals in government and delving into many other
subjects that the dailies deem too controversial. Recently there
have been articles asserting that the government kept the victim of
a recent nuclear accident alive just long enough to get a new
nuclear safety bill passed. Other reports have detailed heavy,
behind-the-scenes pressures to produce an heir that were placed on
the crown prince's wife prior to her recent miscarriage, and
scandals within the finance ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We present articles that the newspapers should write, but
don't touch,'' said Tetsu Suzuki, editor in chief of Shukan Gendai,
which claims a weekly circulation of 930,000.
</P>
<P>
   But what news these magazines carry is buried among nude photos,
obscene comics, serialized fiction and titillating reports. For
many readers, the result is that no matter how serious an article
is _ and a good number are based on hard fact _ it is usually taken
with a large grain of salt.
</P>
<P>
   So the weeklies seem to serve more as pressure valves for
burdensome matters in a society that shuns open disputes and
confrontational debate, than they do as journalistic crusaders for
the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Hall, a historian and author of ``Cartels of the Mind,'' a
powerful recent critique of Japan's intellectual closed-mindedness,
likened the role to the Japanese salaryman's ritual of drinking
after work with superiors. Once drunk, all manner of truths may be
safely spoken _ and are sure to be forgotten, or at least played
down, the morning after.
</P>
<P>
   Even seen in this light, Japan's pulp weeklies are somewhat less
than meet the eye. ``The taboos for newspapers involve anything to
do with power: the government, the parliament, justice,'' said
Yasunari Okadome, publisher and editor of Uwasa no Shinso, a
crusading monthly that refuses major corporate advertising. ``These
matters go to the weeklies. But the weeklies cannot be totally free
either, because they are afraid of Dentsu, and of the tax
investigators.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a growing body of press criticism says Japan's
mainstream dailies suffer from their cosseted relationships with
the government and other powerful institutions, while the fat,
glossy-covered weeklies pull some of their punches out of fear of
Japan's huge and omnipresent advertising agency, Dentsu, an
integral part of a deeply conservative establishment.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Okadome and others say, Japanese journalism is
weakened by tax codes and other legal favors that inhibit
competition among newspapers and help keep them tame. But the most
important factor, many say, is the institution of the kisha clubs _
press clubs paid for by government agencies and private industries
for the mainstream reporters that cover them.
</P>
<P>
   These are typically the places of work of the reporters, who
often simply wait for news to be handed out to them and compare
notes before writing. Hall likened them to cartels: ``They keep out
the weeklies, they keep out the foreign press and they tamp down
embarrassing matters on behalf of their sources.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of Japanese newspapers admit that the kisha clubs pose
problems, but argue that critics who focus on them miss the point.
Culture, they say, more than anything else, divides Western
journalism from its Japanese counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   Japan lacks the adversarial, fiercely independent spirit that is
the ideal in Western journalism, according to Yoshibumi Wakamiya, a
deputy managing editor at the daily Asahi Shimbun, who declared
himself unsatisfied with his country's journalism but aware that
another country's style cannot be easily transplanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Japanese society, it is difficult to hold healthy
debates,'' he said. ``The person you are debating will feel their
personality is under attack, and will hold a grudge. That is
Japanese society, and we have to get information from our
politicians. If you ask sharp questions, you may end up being
isolated, even from other journalists.''
</P>
</TEXT>
