<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 09:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8903 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-CAMPAIGN-PRIMARIES-RE     02-07 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-PRIMARIES-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUDDENLY, IT'S A NATIONAL CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
(DUPLICATION NOTICE: Also sent with `p' code) 
(bl) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fresh from his victory rally in New Hampshire, Vice
President Al Gore boarded Air Force Two around midnight Tuesday and
headed for New York City, and on to Washington and Ohio, winding up
in Los Angeles for a town hall meeting that ended at 1:20 a.m.
Later that morning, Gore mingled with voters in Venice, Calif.,
flew to Olympia, Wash., for a labor event and returned home to
Washington around 4:30 a.m. on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   His challenger, former Sen. Bill Bradley, also departed New
Hampshire after midnight Tuesday for a similarly punishing schedule
that took him to New York, San Francisco and Hartford, Conn., over
the same period. It was so grueling and the plane to the West Coast
grew so chilly that the normally placid Bradley roamed the aisles
cursing about another cold dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The two Democrats may have been on adrenaline highs after the
New Hampshire primary, but their frantic _ and virtually sleepless
_ transcontinental hopscotch was driven by genuine political
imperatives: all the states they visited _ and 11 more _ have
Democratic contests March 7, a single day of voting so colossal
that candidates are calling it Titanic Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Never before have so many electoral powerhouses held so many
contests simultaneously. Rather than a traditional primary season,
voters are now faced with what is, in essence, a campaign that
resembles a general election. And as much as critics call it a rush
to judgment, Titanic Tuesday may turn out to be not so bad for
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   More voters may have more influence over who gets the Democratic
and Republican nominations than they have had in many years.
Roughly one third of the delegates to the parties' nominating
conventions will be picked, meaning that more than one third of
eligible voters will get to participate. And the compressed
calendar could resemble a European-style election: a compact but
intense primary season where many voters pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   That is especially true because, for now at least, there are
unexpectedly competitive one-on-one contests in both parties, with
Gore vying with Bradley, and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas with Sen.
John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates must project messages that appeal to a broad national
audience, losing the flexibility of tailoring appeals to regional
or ideological interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're dabbling in every region of the country,'' said Rhodes
Cook, a political analyst who has examined the 2000 calendar
closely. ``It's a national sampler, so candidates have to show
strength in every part of the country. It makes this year a fairer
test than in '92 or '96, when it was New Hampshire, Ohio, South
Carolina and then a block of states in the South.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, because the run up to March 7 will be the closest the
United States has come to a national primary, there will be less
incentive for candidates to try to pander to particular states or
regions. When the Democratic race turned south in 1992, for
example, Paul Tsongas ridiculed Bill Clinton as a ``pander bear''
for, among other things, his narrow appeals to the elderly in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   When candidates do appeal to narrow audiences, the new national
dynamic could beam that message much farther afield. When Bush
pounded a conservative message in a speech at Bob Jones University
in South Carolina last week, Bradley roundly criticized him for
appearing at the Southern Christian bastion, which lost its
tax-exempt status in the 1970s because it prohibited interracial
dating.
</P>
<P>
   While critics of the big primary day argue that each state on
that day will be competing for attention from the candidates _ and
smaller states like Maine, Maryland and Vermont might be neglected
_ it is also true that the sheer number of contests could stir up
even greater national interest and a bigger voter turnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a tremendous amount of attention and focus for a
short amount of time,'' said Carter Eskew, one of Gore's top
strategists, ``and that might draw people into the process. It's a
critical mass.''
</P>
<P>
   Gina Glantz, Bradley's campaign manager, said it was a struggle
trying to figure out where her candidate should spend his time.
After campaigning 49 days in New Hampshire, for instance, he now
has 30 more days to make his pitch in 16 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many places you'd like to go and there are a
limited number of days,'' Glantz said. ``But you look to do things
to spark a national interest.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-CAMPAIGN-PRIMARIES-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WASHINGTON: national interest.'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, the dynamics are not quite as oriented
to a national campaign because there is an important primary in
South Carolina on Feb. 19, and a pair of crucial contests three
days later in Michigan and Arizona. But Bush has, for months,
painstakingly assembled organizations in many states that vote
March 7. And McCain is hoping that the shower of national attention
he is enjoying from his landslide upset in New Hampshire will allow
him to overcome Bush's towering organizational advantages.
</P>
<P>
   For all the allure of more states participating, many prominent
Democrats and Republicans are horrified about the glut of
primaries. They argue that the sprawling nature of the contests
will put so much pressure on candidates to be in so many places at
once that their campaigns will amount to little more than 30-second
television commercials and cameo drop-ins at airport tarmacs.
</P>
<P>
   As Haley Barbour, the former chairman of the Republican Party,
put it, ``You've taken down your Christmas tree and people want you
to decide who they should vote for president. It's bad for
presidential candidates and campaigns. It's bad for the body
politic. I unsuccessfully tried to do something about it as
chairman.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the crush of early primaries was purely
accidental: several states moved up their contests in a play for
more influence. But this time, the public may be served. The voters
of Iowa and New Hampshire played their usual role of inspecting the
candidates up close, helping winnow the field and pressing upon the
candidates the need to be responsive and listen to voters. Now that
the candidates have been introduced to the public and bloodied a
bit it is time for a far broader electorate to have its say.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Pete Wilson of California, a Republican, does not
see the merits. ``It's the antithesis of what happens in New
Hampshire,'' Wilson said. ``It becomes this television
extravaganza. It is exhausting for the participants, the candidates
and the public, and can produce results that were not seen by the
framers of the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Wilson sees the barrage of talking heads on television
as negative, their messages may reach more voters. Even before they
left Manchester late Tuesday night, Gore and Bradley sat for round
after round of interviews with local television stations in states
that have contests on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, the campaigns are already plotting how best to
compete. The big question, obviously, is how they divide their
precious days _ a subject about which the campaigns are cagey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's somewhere between a closely guarded secret and a
no-brainer,'' Eskew said. ``Obviously, we're going to spend time in
New York, Ohio, California and Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, McCain's aides are trying to settle on an East
Coast-West Coast shuffle. ``There are ways to make the time zone
work for you,'' said Mike Murphy, a strategist for McCain. ``You
start on the East Coast. You move with the time zone to California,
then you red-eye back to the East Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   In this tarmac-to-tarmac campaign, there is one constituency, at
least, that can't grouse about being neglected: voters who cool
their heels in the frequent flyer lounges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 0946EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0063 </DOCNO>
