A8923 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN09-CO     02-07 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Too quick to judge Austria?
 &HT;    (For release Feb. 9, 2000.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Servicez
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are mixed signals on the swelling Austria crisis: Some
want to isolate that country as a result of its government
acceptance of members of the far-right Freedom Party; others wonder
if the crisis really is a crisis or something blown far out of
proportion.
</P>
<P>
   Only time can clear the air. The question: How much time will it
take?
</P>
<P>
   In this world of instant communication _ and demands for equally
sudden reaction _ Austria became a pariah, not within days but
within hours.
</P>
<P>
   Joerg Haider, the Freedom Party master, has said things in the
past that have come to haunt both him and the people he said them
about. He has alienated immigrants, Jews and many others by his
softness on some of Adolf Hitler's programs _ although he has not,
to my knowledge, uttered a public word in defense of the Holocaust
or any other crimes Hitler perpetrated on the remainder of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The platform of the Freedom Party is without complexity: It
wants a homogeneous society. This is not fully unlike the ambitions
of other Western European nations including France, Germany and the
United Kingdom, all three inundated with immigrants. What makes the
Freedom Party of Austria different is that it took the issue to the
voters, and rather than be ostracized for such provincial thought,
it won 27.3 percent of the Austrian vote last October. The People's
Party took 26.9 percent and the Social Democrats 33 percent; no
clear-cut consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, the word ``Nazi'' has been tossed about in relation
to Haider and his party, principally because Haider has expressed
respect for the Nazi SS hoodlums and for certain of Hitler's
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Haider has since apologized for those remarks, but so did
baseball's John Rocker for the verbal trash he unloaded on a
sportswriter last fall. It is obvious that if the hurt is deep
enough, no apology will do. Neither have been forgiven by those
they offended.
</P>
<P>
   As always, there are comparisons. And this is where Patrick
Buchanan comes in. Frankly, I think Haider's speeches were stolen
from Buchanan's manuscripts that included calls for bans on
immigration and cottony references to Hitler and German war
criminals who faced deportation from the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   And Buchanan is running for president of the United States!
</P>
<P>
   In the very unlikely occurrence that Buchanan would be elected
president, would the world's nations retreat from its friendship
with the U.S.? Withdraw ambassadors? Cut economic ties?
</P>
<P>
   Not likely. But that is what is happening with Austria. In an
emotional moment, I can warrant it. After all, Austrians threw
flowers in the path of Austrian-born Hitler when he marched in in
1939. This also is the country that elected Kurt Waldheim president
in 1986 after documents revealed that he was an officer in a German
army unit during World War II that killed thousands of Yugoslavians
and deported Greek Jews to concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is a history. So, you do have to be wary of
Austria and its attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   But should we already be close to a political and economic
rebuffing of Austria?
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom Party is attempting to distance itself from the
image of a Nazi-like party while not retreating on its immigration
platform. Haider, himself, will not be a part of the new
government. Should this placate the rest of us? Or is this the trap
that befell Neville Chamberlain, who is remembered as the British
prime minister who appeased Hitler, thus allowing the dictator to
become even more brazen?
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, a British foreign relations expert was quoted
as saying the breakneck world reaction to the Austrian situation is
being blown far out of proportion. Hopefully, this is so.
</P>
<P>
   You can live with a few far-right or far-left wingers in any
government (we have them) so long as the remainder steer a straight
and amenable course. I'd like to wait a while before judging
Austria's internal politics. The remainder of the world certainly
is strong enough to stop anything that goes beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
