<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A South without kudzu?
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As they say, be careful what you wish for. You might get kudzu.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeastern states did, starting in the 1930s. Looking for
a carefree ground cover to stop erosion, the region harkened to the
advice of the U.S. Soil Conservation Service and took up with an
obscure ornamental vine.
</P>
<P>
   The South has been trying to get away from it ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Kudzu was slipped into the country for the garden that Japan
contributed to the 1876 Centennial Exposition in Philadelphia and
didn't spread, socially, much beyond similar discreet uses for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   But then a well-meaning nation, appalled by the arid horror of
the Dust Bowl, unleashed kudzu on the South to prevent similar
devastation. The Civilian Conservation Corps planted it. Farmers
were paid $8 an acre to cover unused fields with it.
</P>
<P>
   Well-mannered in its native Asia, kudzu turned profligate in the
Southeastern climate, partying across the region with Dionysian
abandon, a herbal hedonist on an eternal toot. It spreads at a slow
walk. (Well, actually a foot a day, but that's in every direction.)
There are tales of grazing cows being overtaken and lost forever.
</P>
<P>
   Kudzu overwhelms trees, snakes up fence posts, races down
gullies. (Oddly, it seems to balk at billboards, which ought to
tell us something about billboards.) Guns can't kill it. Tanks
can't kill it. Strong herbicides can, but it takes at least four
years, sometimes as many as 10.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Tuskegee University have found that Angora goats
can eat kudzu to a standoff, but not everybody wants Angora goats.
In fact, almost nobody wants goats of any sort.
</P>
<P>
   So it must be good news in the Southeast that scientists have
found that a common fungus, Myrothecium verrucaria, can kill kudzu
dead within hours, and without harming other plants.
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes and no it's good news.
</P>
<P>
   Kudzu is a pest all right, and worse. It can waste whole forests
by blocking sunlight. When it goes dormant in the winter, it drapes
the countryside in an ugly grey pall.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also sort of like having a crazy uncle living in the
attic. You'd rather he'd go away, but at least he gives everybody
something to talk about and he does lend the place a certain
peculiar distinctiveness. And OK, he's crazy but, hey, he's OUR
crazy uncle.
</P>
<P>
   And in season, verdurous to excess, kudzu landscapes tease the
idle mind _ improvised topiary that arranges itself into fabulous
shapes, abstract or evocative: vast green undulations or, if you're
lucky, a castle right out of Sir Walter Scott, complete with a
mounted knight compounded of a couple of kudzu-invested shrubs and
a tilted lance made of an entwined guy wire. (Or maybe just a
chickie or a ducky. We all have our off days.)
</P>
<P>
   Now that we apparently can, do we really want to kill off the
kudzu? If it goes, it will take its menace with it, but also those
surprising roadside dinosaurs, pirate ships and dancing maidens.
And we'd be left alone with all those billboards.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
