<HEADER>
A8930 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN08-COX     02-07 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A slipperly ride was par for the course
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ The day of the first storm of winter
started out pleasantly enough, with a plate of heuvos rancheros,
beans and tortillas, washed down with a strong cup of coffee and a
tall glass of milk at a Mexican restaurant in downtown Buda, a
charming little town about 15 miles south of Austin. Outside, it
finally felt like a Texas winter _ 35 degrees and raining, wind
whipping a gray band of clouds from the west. My prediction: Winter
came in like a lamb and will go out like a lion this season. Blame
La Nina.
</P>
<P>
   I met my brother in Buda to discuss our aborted plan to play
golf at a new course a few miles away, where he had a free
membership taken in trade for designing some brochures. Looks like
golf is out, I said, and he nodded but I could tell he wasn't quite
ready to give up just yet. He was decked out in a waterproof
windsuit and kept telling me that the lessons he had taken were
making a difference. I was wearing blue jeans, a sweatshirt and a
windbreaker, none of which repelled water. He has been bitten with
the golf obsession, a phase I have passed through. Now I avoid
playing if the temperature is lower than my age or if it's raining.
I don't read golf magazines, never practice and am content to
remain at a comfortable level of mediocrity. Eventually, he will
get over the obsession, too.
</P>
<P>
   We dawdled in the cafe for an hour, reading the Austin paper and
talking politics. He kept going to the window and peeking outside.
Slacked off, he said, and it looks lighter in the west. Believe
it's blowing through. Want to take a ride out and look over the
course, meet the owners?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, why not, I said. Then I can get back on the road to East
Texas and beat the ice storm I was reasonably sure was coming out
of the plains of Oklahoma and north Texas, headed hard toward the
Pine Curtain.
</P>
<P>
   We drove out, met the owners and the club pro, who had plenty of
time to chat, since we were the only ones out there. One of the
owners said it was supposed to blow through any time now. After
about 30 minutes, I could tell my brother was holding fast to the
idea of hitting the rock, so I relented. The pro shook his head and
told us we could walk the course with pull carts; it was too wet
for a cart. Idiots, I could sense him thinking.
</P>
<P>
   It rained steadily but softly for the first four holes, the wind
hitting upward of 30 mph. Pretend you're in Scotland, my brother
said, playing St. Andrews. I was more interested in pretending I
was sitting in front of a fire in the clubhouse, sipping on a hot
toddy.
</P>
<P>
   On the fifth hole, the skies opened, the wind whipped up and we
were stuck probably a mile from the clubhouse in a deluge. In
seconds I was soaked to the bone. I couldn't feel my ears, hands or
feet. We hiked back. After a while, I began to believe we weren't
going to make it back, that this was how my life would end, frozen
to death on a golf course or drowned in a flash flood.
</P>
<P>
   We survived, of course, the pro shaking his head as we trudged
back and began shedding clothes. I luckily had a spare, dry set of
clothes, and a cup of coffee at my brother's home restored me
somewhat. Soon I was driving back east propelled by a tail wind
that whipped the back end of my rental pickup to and fro. Still,
the heater worked well, I drank coffee or cappuccino nonstop, and I
sang along with the country music stations from small town to town.
</P>
<P>
   Then I hit the ice just east of Crockett. Soon I was approaching
every bridge with my breath held and my knuckles white on the
steering wheel as the pickup skated across the pavement even at 40
mph.
</P>
<P>
   It was snowing in Alto. That's been a running joke in the
newsroom in the 10-plus years I've been back here. Every winter
storm that comes through, somebody calls and says it's snowing in
Alto. I'm a witness that, as this storm blew through, it truly was
snowing in Alto, so maybe we newsroom cynics have been, well, too
cynical.
</P>
<P>
   The worst moment came when three unloaded bobtail pulpwood
trucks tailgating each other roared past from the opposite
direction as I crossed an icy bridge. Three men bent on suicide or
getting home in time to watch ``Wheel of Fortune,'' I guess. I had
to stop and let my heartbeat slow down after that near-death
experience.
</P>
<P>
   The ice ended just outside of Nacogdoches. My feet were still
frozen, my hands were shaking from caffeine overload, and I was
seriously considering suing my brother for mental anguish, though
he doesn't have any money, and I'm afraid he'd try to stick me with
one of his dogs in the asset settlement _ the mean one who promptly
bit me on the foot (luckily it was shod) as soon as I walked in the
door.
</P>
<P>
   But that's another story.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mail: gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
