<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain's honesty tactic a novel concept that just might work
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ At his 100th or so town meeting in New Hampshire,
GOP presidential candidate John McCain said a woman stood up to
make a statement rather than ask a question.
</P>
<P>
   Her statement impressed McCain so much that he started including
it in all his public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't think it is any coincidence that so many independents
and mainline Republican men and women moved to support him after he
started using the woman's remarks in his speeches.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said the woman rose to tell him that what she wanted more
than anything was a politician who always told the truth.
</P>
<P>
   McCain accepted the woman's statement at face value. He figured
if she was fed up with politicians who duck, weave, spin, dodge and
flip flop, then so were other voters.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons behind his romping, stomping victory over
George W. Bush on Tuesday, McCain felt, was his statement to New
Hampshire voters that they could count on him to never lie to them.
</P>
<P>
   The size of McCain's victory over Bush was startling because
Bush worked hard and spent big in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Bush stuck to his themes of big tax cuts, compassionate
conservatism, education, home, family, morality and the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also didn't make any flubs in his debates. This was such an
important goal in New Hampshire that Bush went into hiding from the
national press to lessen his chances of making an embarrassing
blunder.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also emphasized the usual issues that he felt would appeal
to women voters.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the New Hampshire campaign, Bush brought in his
mother and father.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, Bush had all the Republican heavyweights and
party machinery in his oversized hip pocket that also contained
enough cash to pay for a first-class ticket to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing worked for Bush. McCain got the women's vote. McCain got
the Republican vote. McCain got the independent vote. McCain got it
all by an 18-point margin, 49 percent to 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The same issue that McCain believes helped him beat Bush may
have played an important role in the New Hampshire Democratic
primary race between presidential contenders Al Gore and Bill
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore administered such a whipping to the soft-spoken Bradley in
Iowa a few days earlier that the likelihood of Bradley continuing
after New Hampshire appeared slim.
</P>
<P>
   After his lopsided loss in Iowa, Bradley began to hit Gore's
honesty. He reminded voters that candidates who don't tell the
truth before the election are not likely to tell the truth after
the election.
</P>
<P>
   After Bradley began to question Gore's truthfulness, he gained
voter support and just barely lost the New Hampshire primary in a
nip-and-tuck race.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bradley left New Hampshire with reinvigorated
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   It would be great for American politics if the message coming
out of New Hampshire is that the voters are fed up with politicians
who spin, shade, split hairs, parse, mislead or outright lie.
</P>
<P>
   American democracy will receive a needed boost if voters begin
demanding the truth, the whole truth and nothing but the truth from
their politicians.
</P>
<P>
   It's past time for American voters to support politicians who
speak their minds and tell the truth. Voters should spurn
politicians who attempt to win support with public opinion polls,
focus groups and misleading marketing ploys. Politicians willing to
tell people whatever polls show they want to hear are false
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Americans should reject false leaders and demand politicians
with outspoken personal principles.
</P>
<P>
   With luck, the New Hampshire primaries will cause politicians at
all levels to compete with straight talk and unvarnished truth.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
