<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0208-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Full blown glass craze
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN CITY, Ore. _ I don't live here but I do come to visit
every so often just to see what these folks on the coast are up to.
It's always something. They're real different from us
Midwesterners.
</P>
<P>
   Back in northwest Ohio where I live in a tiny village called
Gibsonburg, my neighbors are mostly successful German farmers who
have worked long and hard to keep the land they inherited from
their fathers productive. They've never had much time for creative
stuff, except the time Orton Schmidt got snockered and painted the
wheels on his tractor sunny orange.
</P>
<P>
   The house I live in is on the corner behind a hedge, about a
block-and-a-half from the dime store. The funeral home is directly
across the street.
</P>
<P>
   We have five churches, a snow plow, and every third Saturday
night there's karaoke at Hoy's Bar. Watching Jon Younker change the
letters on the Lions Club sign from HAPPY MILLENNIUM to THINK
SPRING, is just about as exciting as it gets around here.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it strikes me as more than a little odd this morning
when I look out Gail's front window and spot a crowd of people down
there on the beach in a driving rain, jabbing sticks around in the
sand. I ask her what those fools might be doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking for millennium floats,'' my old friend
answers, sounding kind of like I should have been able to figure
that out on my own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' I remind her, ``remember where I live? It isn't often
we look out our windows and spot a herd of tourists with
flashlights strapped to their hats, wandering around the village in
a freezing drizzle poking holes in the dirt with sharp sticks.''
</P>
<P>
   Gail doesn't get it. She's been out here too long.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, I explain, back in Gibsonburg, the only beach most of
us see is in the National Geographics down at the library, and even
then we're kind of careful not to look too long at certain pages
just in case a neighbor might spot us eyeballing a half-naked
native and get the wrong idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``What,'' I insist, ``is a millennium float?'' Gail fills me in.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, folks living on the Pacific shores, particularly in
the northwest and Alaska, have been harvesting the colorful glass
floats that occasionally break loose from Japanese fishing boats
and float up on shore. They're not rare. Antique shops up and down
the coast sell them to visitors for about 20 bucks apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Then last summer a local entrepreneur with time on his hands
came up with the bright idea of millennium floats _ 2000
jewel-hued, blown-glass balls to be scattered along the 14-mile
stretch of Lincoln City beaches for tourists to
</P>
<P>
   discover in the sand and exclaim: OOH! LOOK-Y THERE MABEL! IT'S
A COLORFUL GLASS BALL IN THE SAND! I THINK I'VE DISCOVERED A
MILLENNIUM FLOAT.
</P>
<P>
   The idea caught on and the place is going nuts. Beaches are
being combed 24-hours a day for the freebies, and art galleries are
moving these balls in and out so fast the glass hardly has time to
cool. With price tags starting at $42 and ranging up to $200, the
blowers, who usually close up between December and March, are
working through the winter. Top production is about 36 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Gail works part-time in a gallery that, like all of the others
in town, can't keep up with the demand. One day she sold a dozen
balls in 17 minutes. In the past two months she's bought 27 of them
herself and has them hanging all over the house.
</P>
<P>
   But all is not wonderful in the land of west coast Oz. Obsession
has struck and Lincoln city is finding itself in the midst of a
full-blown, blown-glass crime wave. Folks are stealing each other's
floats. Just the other night three
</P>
<P>
   motels and a bed and bath shop were knocked over by ball thieves
who carried off their stashes.
</P>
<P>
   It's insanity out here folks. It'll be good to get home. I'm
leaving Thursday . . . or as soon as I can find a box to pack my
floats in.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
