<HEADER>
A8934 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LANE-COLUMN08-COX     02-07 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A decade of stock market foreboding
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA, Fla. _ This is an old joke. A really old joke. About a
300-year-old joke:
</P>
<P>
   Two Puritans meet on a bright and lovely New England spring day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lovely weather, Caleb,'' says one, by way of greeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aye,'' responds Caleb. ``And we'll pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   They pause for a moment to observe the beauty about them and
shudder inwardly.
</P>
<P>
   I think about this chestnut every time I read a news story about
the current economic expansion. Last week was a record-breaker. The
nation entered its longest period of uninterrupted economic growth
since, well, if not from the time Caleb joined the choir invisible,
then at least since the government has been keeping records.
</P>
<P>
   The length of the expansion is amazing. Many people in the work
force have never known a downturn in their working life. People my
age shudder at the vague memory of something called ``stagflation''
_ stagnant growth coupled with inflation _ but a serious downturn
is, for most of us, the stuff of history class.
</P>
<P>
   The image of stockbrokers flinging themselves from windows is no
more than a quaint cartoon conceit _ like single-palm desert
islands _ dating from a far-off era when stockbrokers worked in
buildings with windows that opened.
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean we all are happy and thank the stock-market gods
for being born at the right time?
</P>
<P>
   Not a bit. The 1990s stock-market rally barely began before its
death was predicted. The tax increase in the first years of the
Clinton administration was supposed to bring a loss of jobs and
recession. The increase in the minimum wage was supposed to lead to
loss of jobs and recession. The economic might of Japan was
supposed to lead to loss of jobs and recession. The economic
weakness of Japan was supposed to lead to loss of jobs and
recession. Each free-trade agreement was supposed to lead to
</P>
<P>
   loss of jobs and recession.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to the business shelf of any larger used-book store is a
doleful experience. You see titles like: ``The Stock Market Crashes
of 1998 and 1999: The Asian Crisis and Your Future'' (1998), ``The
Great Depression of 1990'' (1989), and ``America in Depression: The
Coming Economic Collapse'' (1993).
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to sense that many economic writers aren't merely
bears; they are scaredy cats.
</P>
<P>
   Never has a time of economic expansion and prosperity been so
little enjoyed. It is as though, like the Puritans in the old joke,
experts see brewing retribution every time a record shatters.
</P>
<P>
   I slept though much of my economics classes, but I don't recall
an economic counterpart to Newton's Third Law of Motion, that for
every action there is an opposite and equal reaction. Big highs
don't always mean big lows.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing close is a sensible, if unscientific, law of
Universal Karma and Economic Motion _ what goes up, must come down.
We are up now. We shall be down sometime.
</P>
<P>
   When? Tomorrow, say pop economists. The Y2K-fear books are
stacked on the remainder table to make room for new and scarier
titles. ``At the Crest of the Tidal Wave: A Forecast for the Great
Bear Market,'' ``Beat the Millennium Crash: Survive and Thrive in
the Coming Financial Cataclysm'' and ``The Return of Depression
Economics'' ...
</P>
<P>
   It's not as though there are no grounds to question the
permanance of the dot-com economy. But it seems that much of the
economic hand-wringing over the booming economy is not based on
charts and formulae. It comes from a sense that we just don't
deserve this. People are partying too hard and the next knock on
the door is bound to be the cops.
</P>
<P>
   There are critics out there who think the invisible hand of
economics is on the side of virtue and about to slap down a people
who are getting too arrogant, fat and silly. A beautiful economy
and, aye, we'll pay for it in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Yet sometimes the sun shines on people who don't deserve it. We
should be grateful for this and not freak out. As economist John
Maynard Keynes said: ``Long run is a misleading guide to current
affairs. In the long run, we are all dead.''
</P>
<P>
   It's too nice a day for long-run analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.) News-
Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
