<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nyko components put the dream in Dreamcast
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE:
</P>
<P>
   Nyko has just released its total Dreamcast control and memory
system, and we're happy to report, it's a dream (get it?). For the
Sega system, the company introduced Dreammaster, Thunder Pak and
Jumbo Memory Pak 2x ($25, $15 and $35; www.nyko.com). The
Dreammaster is really an advance on the Sega controller. It feels
better in the hand and looks great with its purple, translucent
shell. The Thunder Pak does exactly what the Sega unit does but at
$10 cheaper. The icing on the Nyko cake is the Jumbo Memory Pak 2x.
Much has been written about the Dreamcast memory unit's memory _
the Sega memory unit saves very little and isn't worth the price.
The Nyko unit has two times the memory and is priced right. The
Jumbo Memory Pax 2x stores 400 blocks and allows you to save your
position in more than one game, which is a huge advance.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP:
</P>
<P>
   Squaresoft's Final Fantasy series has pushed the envelope on
console systems with great storylines, fantastic animation and
great adventures. Unfortunately, the same can't be said for the PC
translation, especially their latest release, Final Fantasy VIII.
The game is an exact translation of last year's Playstation title,
which isn't all bad _ the game boasts some of the best
computer-generated animations in a game _ ever. It also has an epic
storyline that includes great battles and even greater romances,
and has a lengthy play life worthy of its five-CD package.
Unfortunately, the game does nothing to improve on the Playstation
version. You get menus that look like they belong on a console
system, graphics that actually look worse than on the Playstation
(even with a high-end video card), and controls that just aren't as
tight. And if you want flawless gameplay, you'd better have a fast
computer, or you'll be viewing the action in a quarter-screen,
low-resolution window just to keep the audio and video from
stuttering. Final Fantasy VIII isn't a nightmare, but like a lot of
console-to-PC ports, this one instead plays out like a mildly
diverting daydream.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
