<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Solving problems doesn't require knowing what's wrong
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ My best lessons are the most unpleasant ones. Last
weekend I learned a lot. My home computer _ which has been so
reliable that I seldom give it a thought _ had a nervous breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   Something wasn't wrong with it. Everything was wrong with it.
The cursor would freeze. It would lose track of modems and printers
and reinstall them every time I turned it on. Then I'd restart and
it would work for a while and stop again.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it just stopped working. It was an icy weekend and I
was stuck at home anyway, so I tried to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to follow the advice I give so often here. I played
detective and tried to remember the last big change I had made.
That's always a good place to start. I had recently added a better
video card, so I removed the new card and reinstalled the old one.
Things worked fine for a while and _ just when my arm was getting
sore from patting myself on the back _ the computer started showing
the same old symptoms again.
</P>
<P>
   So the first lesson is that when you have trouble, the chief
suspect should be the last device you put in or the last program
you installed.
</P>
<P>
   The second lesson is that the first lesson is sometimes wrong.
Life would be great _ for newspapermen, computer repair guys and
cops _ if the most logical suspect was always guilty.
</P>
<P>
   So, once again I dived into the computer. I removed and
reinserted every card. I remembered that when there is a big change
in temperature (and my house surely qualified since I just had a
three-day period without electricity because of an ice storm),
accessory cards such as those for video, modem, sound and the like
can expand and contract enough to unseat themselves a little from
the slot. That will cause an intermittent connection that can cause
a computer to act as odd as my Aunt Vera Mae.
</P>
<P>
   I tried that. Again, things seemed to work fine for a while and
then freeze up. (That's why it's important to wait a while between
changes when you are trying to fix a computer; some problems take a
while to pop up). Anyway, I put my detective hat back on and
remembered that there have been scattered trouble reports involving
the power-saving feature in Windows that powers down the monitor
and even the hard disk after a long period of inactivity. That's
it, I thought. So I went into the Control Panel, found the icon for
Power Management and told the computer never to shut off.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help. But at least I was getting a refresher course in
computer hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Next, I decided to check the Web to see if there were newer and
better drivers for my new video card. A driver is a tiny software
program that lets the device communicate with the computer and vice
versa. That's a good idea with any new device. Manufacturers _
especially with a device that is new to the market (and my video
card is) _ are constantly finding bugs in early versions of
software and fixing them. No help this time.
</P>
<P>
   Finally I threw up my hands and decided to use the equivalent of
the atomic bomb. I backed up the information on my computer and
reformatted the hard disk. And I reinstalled Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Things worked beautifully after that.
</P>
<P>
   So what was wrong with my computer?
</P>
<P>
   Danged if I know. I'll never know now. But that's fine. The
object of this exercise was to fix my computer. And I did.
</P>
<P>
   So, keep the final and best lesson in mind when you have
troubles at home. Ask any computer repair person and they'll tell
you that reinstalling Windows _ especially if you go to the trouble
(and it is trouble) of a clean installation with a reformatted hard
disk _ cures most problems. And keep your sights set low. Unless
you are a hobbyist, you don't have to be able to explain the
problem. It's quite enough to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
