<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smut in the office?
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ First John Rocker, now this.
</P>
<P>
   A study by NetPulse shows that Southerners are more likely than
people from any other region to download pornography at work while
on break.
</P>
<P>
   If the recent peek into the mind of the Atlanta Braves relief
pitcher didn't make Southerners look bad enough, this might.
</P>
<P>
   The Web study was paid for by the folks at Pogo.com, a Web site
devoted to online versions of offline games like backgammon, euchre
and poker.
</P>
<P>
   But a solid 2 percent of the polled _ roughly 20 people _ were
bold enough to download porn on the boss's bandwidth.
</P>
<P>
   Southerners were three times as likely to download porn as folks
from the East Coast, and apparently it would be twice as easy to
find a porn-looker at a workplace in the South than it would on the
West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The tendency to hunt for online pictures of naked people is
found most often in white-collar workers, defined as people earning
more than $75,000 a year, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   Unmarried employees were four times as likely as their
spoken-for co-workers to enjoy looking for X-rated material while
at work.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, male porn fans outnumbered females 20 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   NetPulse is a weekly survey that polls a panel of 1,000 people
who are weighted by age, gender and region to represent Internet
users.
</P>
<P>
   JOINING TV, NET
</P>
<P>
   You might have seen the ads during the Super Bowl in which ABC
was trying to steer viewers toward its ``enhanced TV'' function,
which blends television show with Web site. But is anyone really
sitting there, mouse in one hand, clicker in the other?
</P>
<P>
   According to Cyber Dialogue, some are.
</P>
<P>
   The Web research firm found that 10 million people visit Web
sites and watch TV at the same time. Of those, one of every four is
doing it during a sporting event. The next most commonly watched
and surfed events are situation comedies and news magazines, each
of which attracted 13 percent of those polled. General news, games
and product information sites also attracted visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people polled, 66 percent, were not taking full
advantage of enhanced television's features. About two-thirds of
the people polled were online and just had the television on in the
background, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   Cyber Dialogue's survey included interviews with 1,000 Internet
users and 1,000 nonusers. The survey has been conducted every three
months since 1994. Cyber Dialogue is an Internet customer
relationship management company that offers data and services that
help businesses target online consumers.
</P>
<P>
   HOT DOG SITE A REAL WIENER
</P>
<P>
   The hot dog is the cockroach of foods. Upton Sinclair couldn't
kill it early last century with his literary expose on the
meat-packing industry.
</P>
<P>
   Decades of jokes about what exactly goes in them has not
dampened people's taste buds.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, we ate 20 billion hot dogs, 7 billion between
Memorial Day and Labor Day. That's roughly 73 hot dogs for every
American. A new Web site is devoted to the study and appreciation
of our love of encased pork and beef byproducts.
</P>
<P>
   The site, www.hot-dog.org/, is sponsored by the National Hot Dog
and Sausage Council and the American Meat Institute. It is
apparently designed to counter negative perceptions about wieners.
The material sounds a little defensive. For example, the site
includes ``the real story'' of how hot dogs are made:
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of hot dogs and sausages consist of the same
high-quality meats that shoppers buy straight out of their grocer's
meat case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confused about what goes into processed meat products like
sausage and hot dogs? You are probably not alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``For literally centuries, hot dogs and sausages have suffered
from more than their fair share of misperceptions about their
content and manufacture.''
</P>
<P>
   The site includes recipes for such things as sausage pancake
puffs, sausage stir-fry and sausage pie.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
