<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sites detail how to survive Valentine's Day encounters
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's an art to Valentine's Day. The Web can help
but not in the way you might expect.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, you could go to Blue Mountain's e-card site at
www1.bluemountain.com
</P>
<P>
   /eng/valentine/index.html and select from what seems to be
hundreds of choices for the day. There are animated cards,
schmaltzy cards, friendship cards, funny cards, about any kind of
electronic greeting card you can imagine. But if you go to the next
site on our Valentine's Day tour you may decide to skip Blue
Mountain altogether.
</P>
<P>
   It's called How to Avoid a Valentine's Day Massacre and is
located at www.menshealth
</P>
<P>
   .com/noframes/features
</P>
<P>
   /everyman/sex/rm7.html. The idea behind this site is to give
solid advice on what to give _ and, more importantly, what not to
give _ your valentine to avoid a massacre.
</P>
<P>
   So, let's take a look. There's no advice about e-cards, but
here's the advice you'll find for printed Valentine's Day cards:
</P>
<P>
   The gift: A Hallmark card. What you see: A last-minute remedy
for almost forgetting the holiday. What she sees: Another guy.
Strategy: Don't bother.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a gift the site recommended, on the other hand.
</P>
<P>
   The gift: A professional massage. What you see: A way to pass
the back-rub buck. What she sees: A man who knows what a woman
wants. Strategy: Give it.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it. Some people just aren't good at romance. And
that's the notion behind the site called Love Poems at www
</P>
<P>
   .seductionpalace.com
</P>
<P>
   /library/poems/poems.html. Not only will you find poems here,
you'll also get computerized help in selecting just the right one
to fit your particular circumstances. For instance, you can click
on categories such as: for a secret love, to the love of your life,
a marriage proposal, to a lover you fear may be leaving you, or to
rekindle old passion. The site will then find just the right words
to fit the situation.
</P>
<P>
   There are links at the same site that will provide suggestions
for music, recipes and gifts.
</P>
<P>
   All this may leave you wondering about the holiday itself.
There's help on the Web for that, too. The Catholic Encylopedia at
www.newadvent.org
</P>
<P>
   /cathen/15254a.htm will give you information on the history of
the day and about the real St. Valentines.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Valentines. There were three of them, all of them
martyrs according to Catholic doctrine. One is described as a
priest at Rome, another as bishop of Interamna (modern Terni) and a
third Saint Valentine, a rather obscure saint who suffered in
Africa with a number of companions, according to the encylopedia
and of whom it says ``nothing further is known.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the niftiest Valentine's Day sites on the Web this year
was produced by Atlanta's CNN. It's called Welcome to the Love Zone
and can be found at www
</P>
<P>
   .cnn.com/EVENTS/valentine/.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, you'll be presented with a series of links that
offer choices depending on your mood or situation. For instance,
you can press the link called ``She Loves Me'' and you'll find
poetry as well as a collection of news stories that play off that
theme. Press the link called ``She Loves Me Not'' and you'll get
sympathy _ ``So you're left with a tattoo that says, `Rita Forever'
and a bag of hacked up bits that was your heart'' _ as well as
another collection of news stories that play off that sadder theme.
</P>
<P>
   There also is a list of Valentine's Day links as well as some
musical recommendations: ``Embraceable You,'' Billie Holiday;
``L-O-V-E,'' Nat King Cole; ``I Fall to Pieces,'' Patsy Cline;
``Let's Stay Together,'' Al Green; and ``Crazy Love,'' Van
Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
