<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8951 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE-SPEA     02-07 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE-SPEAKER08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sound of success: Speakers no longer have to be massive and
expensive to get the job done
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No matter how much you invest in receivers, DVD
machines or digital recordings, nothing enhances the sound better
than choice speakers.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when the speakers, collectively, amounted to
the lion's share of the cost of a good sound system. Today,
speakers that make a true difference are cheaper proportionally
than they were many years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, experts say they last longer, because they are
manufactured from materials like polypropylene rather than the
fiber likely to be found in vintage speakers.
</P>
<P>
   The really good news is that the efficiency of speakers _ their
ability to work well with less raw power from the amplifiers _ has
improved, making speakers today smaller.
</P>
<P>
   That means speakers are more easily movable and can be located
in spots unthinkable just several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers that perform like the familiar towers of blessed memory
now can be mounted on bookshelves, on pedestals, or even hung from
ceilings and walls, leaving more space for the growing number of
machines for sound and video.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, it means that speakers can be used in ensembles
or systems _ not just the familiar enthusiast's setup with two
mountainous $2,000 Klipsch speakers, weighing about 50 pounds
apiece, topped off with a cute little tweeter horn atop each.
</P>
<P>
   Now the new standard, for music and so-called home theater,
involves five or six speakers. Manufacturers as diverse as Boston
Acoustic, JBL, Klipsch and others are producing such ``matched''
sets of speakers for less than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The new arrangement usually features three speakers across the
front and two rear speakers, with a powered subwoofer tucked away
almost anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The subwoofer is run by its own electrical power source and is
not a ``slave'' like the other speakers, which draw their power
directly from the amplifier. Because low frequencies are not
directional, the subwoofer can be put in a corner. It has always
taken more electrical power to produce the ground-shaking bass
notes than others, and that's why a separate power supply is used.
And that's also why the remaining speakers, mostly not bearing so
much of the bass responsibility, can be smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the apportioning of the sound production among the
six speakers means that each can carry out specific assignments,
behaving more like a team or an audio chorus surrounding the
listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, where DVD is concerned, the system has to reproduce a
huge range of sounds ranging from crashes and crunches to whispers
and the tinkling of glasses. The speaking voices come from the very
important center channel speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, that speaker should have broad tonal range, but it
does not have great responsibility for bass.
</P>
<P>
   In one nice touch, a Bose center channel speaker, the VCS 10 for
$199 at Circuit City, looks terrific. It's has a long, low
silhouette that turns the head. It reminds us, especially the
old-timers, of the days when speakers were furniture, meant to
enhance the room. Now, function's mostly the thing.
</P>
<P>
   The two rear speakers and the front corner speakers should be
lively, eloquent in producing high notes and discerning in
separating the other sounds, giving what audio lovers call a
transparent sound.
</P>
<P>
   SPECIFICATIONS SIMILAR
</P>
<P>
   The odd thing about speakers is that they all tend to have
nearly the same numerical specifications, the numbers that show how
many cycles per second the speaker can reproduce. A zillion
kilohertz or cycles represent the high notes, and a kilohertz range
under 100, sometimes in the 25 to 30 range, represents the lows.
</P>
<P>
   But numbers aside, how do they sound?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is they sound different. Some speakers, like the old
reliable DCM TimeWindows and the newer JBL and Boston Acoustic
speakers, can produce a mellow sound that seems especially suited
to subtle music, like jazz and classical music, and crooning _
either in solos and in choruses.
</P>
<P>
   But the vibrant modern sounds, including movie soundtracks, come
across dramatically in speakers like the Klipsch set that I enjoyed
one day.
</P>
<P>
   The Klipsch Micro Quintet gets by with four speakers no larger
than alarm clocks, combined with a center channel speaker not much
larger, and a hefty subwoofer. But the little package fills a room
as home theater.
</P>
<P>
   There are other systems I like better for straight music, but
it's a matter of taste _ and you have to listen and compare.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that given the double mission of producing
home theater and the best in serious musical sounds, the priority
should be to plunk down the lion's share of investment across the
front with emphasis on the two front side speakers.
</P>
<P>
   When the theater is closed at the end of the day, and you want
to spend another mellow hour with Grieg, or Robert Shaw's
choristers or Sinatra or Miles Davis' ``Kinda Blue,'' the two
classically situated dual stereo speakers must keep the candle
glowing.
</P>
<P>
   That means speakers with good range and accurate but not
overbearing playback. What we used to call high fidelity.
</P>
<P>
   In this area, you get what you pay for, and few are better than
the Boston Acoustics floor standing towers with built-in powered
woofers, and similar machines by Mirage, JBL, Klipsch and others,
mostly in the range of $1,500 to $3,500 a pair.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
