<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time line a nice feature of Grolier's encyclopedia
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A year or so ago, after my annual examination of new
editions of the electronic encyclopedias, I got an e-mail from a
gentleman scolding me for failing to warn him that the encyclopedia
he was about to buy didn't even mention his favorite war.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot remember which war that was; suffice it to say it was a
very old one. This reader was very put out with my tendency to
compare such frippery things as flamenco and didgeridoo while
utterly ignoring military history.
</P>
<P>
   I don't remember which encyclopedia it was, either, although I
certainly would have whacked it a good one for failing to include
some mention of any European war. I don't blame the fellow for
being incensed about that.
</P>
<P>
   But it's no good expecting someone like me to go hunting for
obscure 13th century conflicts since I'm not interested in them,
know nothing about them and wouldn't even notice if one were
overlooked. Thus are the vagaries of critical reviews; the reviewer
who does not stick with what he knows, however peculiar and useless
that may be, is going to get into big trouble.
</P>
<P>
   So with that windy preamble, we take up the portentously named
Year 2000 Grolier Multimedia Encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   As with nearly all the electronic encyclopedias, it is aimed at
the younger students.
</P>
<P>
   Its most outstanding feature, I think, is a historic time line
that can be viewed in a couple of ways. The time line gives the
viewer a brief look at each century of the past millennium in terms
of major events, science and technology, religion and philosophy,
literature and art.
</P>
<P>
   The more common sort of time line, breaking history into smaller
increments, includes a host of concurrent lines _ for India, China,
Europe and Russia, and three others, usually devoted to the
Americas but sometimes broken into other categories such as science
and technology.
</P>
<P>
   Grolier's article on flamenco is very brief but surprisingly
accurate, in comparison to most. There is no audio example, and the
accompanying photo shows a couple dancing sevillanas, which is not
exactly flamenco. The article on bullfighting is also satisfactory,
and it gets three illustrations, two of them most unfortunate. The
color photo shows El Cordobes performing one of his uncommonly
awkward and ugly passes, and another shows Manolete placing
banderillas, which is essentially beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   As with all the other encyclopedias save Microsoft's, music is a
mixed bag. Why bother to adorn the article on Jimmy Rodgers with a
clip from ``Mule Skinner Blues'' if it's going to be performed on
the synthesizer? He's a singer, for goodness sake. Let's hear him
sing.
</P>
<P>
   Among classical selections, you never know what you're going to
hear. A good deal of the orchestral music is really played by an
orchestra, some of the recordings very recent and full-bodied,
others sounding as if they were taken off an old 78. Then you come
up against something like Bruch's G minor concerto rendered on the
synthesizer.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose all this musical ducking and dodging is an attempt to
save money by avoiding royalties, and of course MIDI files don't
take up as much room. With these encyclopedias, now all expanding
to two discs, going for cheap, I suppose it can't be helped.
</P>
<P>
   As for my old correspondent's interests, I cannot offer advice.
Under ``war'' in the list of articles, we have War, War and Peace,
War Crimes, War of 1812, War of the Worlds and War on Poverty.
However, one can summon a subdivision of either European History or
Military History. The latter, at least, seems pretty exhaustive,
right down to a paragraph on Hereward the Wake, an 11th century
Anglo-Saxon rebel who fought the Normans under William I and sacked
Peterborough Abbey.
</P>
<P>
   Grolier's is a perfectly serviceable encyclopedia for primary
and secondary school students. It has easily used online links to a
number of other research sources. Its suggested retail price is
$60.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
