<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _Q: My neighbor and I
<TEXT>
have a friendly wager; if he wins I mow his lawn, and if I win he
mows my lawn. The question: Since 1970, which team has had more
college football players drafted into the NFL, Ohio State or
Nebraska? P.S. I am from Nebraska ... Go Big Red!!! P.P.S. Where
does Texas rank?? _ Mark Brewster
<P>
   A: How about comparing Nebraska and the University of Texas?
Neither Ohio State nor the NFL could provide stats for the
Buckeyes. Since 1970, the University of Nebraska has had 206 NFL
drafts and Texas, 133. Looks like you may get a free mow.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My daughter had an attorney through Legal Aid represent her
in a divorce. Her husband got the house. He now tells her that she
and their small children must be out in two weeks. He told her that
if she doesn't leave on time, he will bring the sheriff to put them
all out. Who can we call to file a complaint against her attorney?
_ C.T.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Without knowing the language of the divorce decree it is
difficult to advise someone,'' says Karen Kretschman, an attorney
board-certified in family law, ``but I am not surprised by the
two-week time period.'' Did your daughter agree to these terms,
receive a divorce decreed by a judge or by default, and was there a
trial? In any case, the sheriff does not enforce divorce decrees.
He enforces eviction notices. Your ex-son-in-law may need one to
force your daughter out of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently saw a book on Martin Luther King Jr. that showed
pictures of the inside of his home. On one wall was a framed
photograph of Mahatma Gandhi. I would love your help in locating a
photograph of Gandhi suitable for framing. Peace.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rick Rodney
</P>
<P>
   A: The M.K. Gandhi Institute for Nonviolence, founded by
grandson, Arun Gandhi, sells Gandhi paraphernalia such as
photographs. Proceeds go to the Institute, which promotes the
principles of nonviolence. They have a variety of picture sizes.
Prices begin at $6. The contacts? The M.K. Gandhi Institute for
Nonviolence, Christian Brothers University, 650 East Parkway South,
Memphis, TN 38104, orwww.cbu.edu/Gandhi/ or (901) 452-2824.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Most weather forecasters on local television stations refer
to the average temperature as the ``normal'' temperature for a
date. Wouldn't it be more accurate to use the word ``average?''
``Normal'' insinuates the high and low temperatures are the same
from year to year, while we all know that the weather forecasters
are simply giving us an ``average'' of temperatures recorded
through the years. What do you think?
</P>
<P>
   _Tommy Ryan
</P>
<P>
   Q: The normal is an average, an average that is recomputed every
10 years. Mark Murray, a meteorologist, says, ``When we give the
normal high, low and rainfall, we're using a 30-year average for
the years 1961-1990. These normals are updated every 10 years.''
Next year, those averages will be updated to reflect 1971-2000.
Murray expects that since the 1990s have been such a warm decade
(1999 was the warmest ever for Austin), normal temperatures will
rise. ``Record'' highs, lows and rainfall are based on the entire
period of record (1942 for Bergstrom and 1897 for Camp Mabry).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Lately, I have not been able to find a product by Revlon
called Color-Lock, a tube eyeshadow base. I've been using it since
I was 16! It really keeps your eyeshadow on all day. See what you
can find out. _Leslye Allen
</P>
<P>
   A: Time for a change. Revlon has discontinued Color-Lock. The
eyeshadow gurus at Revlon recommend Ultima II Fade Not Crease Not,
which is available at JCPenney's. Q: My daughter got gum on a pair
of black stretchy pants. We did the ice thing and got most of it
out. The gum seems to be in the weave. What's the next step? I'm
afraid to use a hot iron on it because it looks to be part Lycra or
spandex. _Cindy Austria
</P>
<P>
   A: Oops. Use a piece of brown paper or plastic to remove the gum
once it has been softened with a hair dryer. Some readers have luck
blotting with a pre-wash before laundering. Here is a novel
approach from Jeff Bredenberg's ``Clean it Fast, Clean it Right'':
Heat the residue with a hair dryer and use a plastic sandwich bag
to blot up the gum. Use fresh areas of the bag. Repeat. Then use
some Ben-Gay rub to break the hold the gum has on the fabric. Blot
with plastic bag.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, before you use anything, test for colorfastness in an
unobtrusive area.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a 1953 bottle of Piper-Heidsieck champagne. It was
produced and bottled by Kunkelmann &AMP; Co. in France. Would
appreciate help with a value. _ Dave Stamy
</P>
<P>
   A: You are not going to like this answer: 1953 was a good, not
great year, for champagne. But this bottle is ``over the hill,''
according to Greg Steiner of Grape Vine Market. In the 1950s
Piper-Heidsieck bottled champagne to be consumed within 20 years.
Current production should be consumed within eight years. So what
has happened to your champagne? After many years, the acidity
breaks down, and the bubbles may even be gone. Interestingly, the
British have developed a taste for these ``less bright''
champagnes, but in the States this bottle is virtually valueless,
concludes Steiner.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My name is Lauren Lucas. I am in the fifth grade at Brushy
Creek Elementary School in Round Rock. As a school assignment, I
have to write a letter of persuasion. I want to write a letter to
Dominique Moceanu, and ask for her autograph. But first, my dad
told me to write this letter of persuasion to you, requesting Ms.
Moceanu's address. Can you please help me get Ms. Moceanu's
address? Thank you for your help. _ Lauren Lucas
</P>
<P>
   A: Pretty persuasive. Moceanu, the youngest member of the 1996
Gold Metal Olympic Gymnastic team, finished ninth in the all-around
competition. Write to her in care of USA Gymnastics, Pan American
Plaza, Suite 300, 201 S. Capitol Ave., Indianapolis, Ind. 46225, or
her home, 17911 Fall River Circle, Houston, TX 77090. Good luck
with your project. Q: I am in the process of buying a home, but do
not know whether to buy a one- or a two-story home. Which one is
likely to settle faster and start showing signs of cracks
throughout the house? Where can I obtain some information? _ O.G.
Herrera
</P>
<P>
   A: A good foundation is a good foundation, regardless of the
number of stories, says Tim Atkinson of Atkinson Engineering. When
you purchase a home, a licensed real estate inspector will check to
see if the foundation is adequate for the home and its location.
While looking at the home, consider how its foundation performs its
intended purpose (serviceability, in engineer-speak). Some cracking
is not objectionable. ``In general, if no foundation problems arise
in a home after five years, there probably won't be any,'' adds
Atkinson. For more tips, visit www.atkinsonusa.com. Contact Jane
Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968. Due to the number of
inquiries, not all questions can be answered.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
