<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For this reunion, Moore is less
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Some memories are best left alone. Nostalgia is
fine, but people should resist the urge to act on it every time the
mood strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Take Mary Richards. We remember her as the independent but
slightly insecure producer at WJM in Minneapolis. She could turn
the world on with her smile and often did. She could even toss her
hat into the air in the middle of traffic without getting squashed.
</P>
<P>
   Now here she is three decades later _ recently widowed, losing
her spunk, sparring with her college-age daughter and trying to
persuade twenty-something executives to hire a sixtysomething
woman. The only bright spot in her life comes when she bumps into
long-lost best friend Rhoda Morgenstern, who used to be the whiny
one but now is brimming with optimism. Thank God for small favors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary &AMP; Rhoda,'' which aired Monday, ABC's reunion movie based
on CBS's Emmy-laden series, was turned down by CBS. Network chief
Leslie Moonves commissioned the script but then backed off the
project, telling Moore he was afraid the update would ``cast a
shadow'' on the beloved original. Wise move, Les.
</P>
<P>
   So ABC snapped it up and even toyed with the notion of using the
movie as a pilot to launch a new series. Thankfully, that's not
much of a serious consideration _ unless the ratings shoot through
the roof. The movie would have to be a whole lot funnier to spawn a
sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that ``Mary &AMP; Rhoda'' is terrible. It's a
soul-searching look at the late midlife crises of two interesting
women. But it's not even remotely similar in tone to ``The Mary
Tyler Moore Show.'' In the classic sitcom, Mary was the anchor of a
sailboat full of zanies. We counted on guaranteed chuckles from
gruff news director Lou Grant, dimwit newsman Ted Baxter,
quick-witted writer Murray Slaughter and man-hungry feature
contributor Sue Ann Nivens. At home, Mary enjoyed frequent visits
from wisecracking neighbor Rhoda and high-strung landlady Phyllis.
</P>
<P>
   The famous ensemble is but a memory (and a fine one at that).
The reunion narrows its focus to the title women _ perhaps because
the others had the good sense to say no.
</P>
<P>
   When the story begins, Mary is returning home to New York after
spending a few months in Italy mourning the death of her
congressman husband. He left her penniless, so she decides to go
back to work. (Since the movie wound up on ABC, we learn that Mary
used to work for ABC News.) Her daughter Rose (Joie Lenz) is
threatening to drop out of college and become a stand-up comic.
</P>
<P>
   Hailing a taxi one day, Mary bumps into Rhoda, who has just
ditched her philandering French husband and decided to become a
professional photographer. Instead, she winds up fetching coffee
and bagels for a pushy fashion photographer. Her daughter Meredith
(Marisa Ryan) wants to drop out of pre-med and reconsider her life
goals. Rhoda is on a spiritual quest, which she describes to Mary
as ``somewhere between Jewish and Shaker _ so I can make my own
furniture and sell it retail.'' It's the only funny line in the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the plot concerns Mary's age discrimination at work
and her crusade to get a meaningful story about a teen-age murderer
on the air at a station that would rather show mayhem than meaning.
At every turn she comes up against her jerk-of-a-boss Jonah (Elon
Gold).
</P>
<P>
   The whole thing is dreary and a little sad _ not what fans of
the 1970-77 sitcom expect. In the old show, Mary was a constant
source of amusement and inspiration to the new breed of single,
working women in the '70s. Even in reruns, she can make us laugh.
Not long ago I saw the famous ``Chuckles the Clown's Funeral''
episode and marveled at how well it holds up. When Mary is seized
with the giggles, viewers can't help howling and snorting along
with her.
</P>
<P>
   Memories of favorite shows are sustained in reruns but shattered
in reunions. Nobody wants to see Archie Bunker in a wheelchair or
Jerry Seinfeld and pals on a Club Med singles cruise. It's not that
aging is a bad thing, but TV characters need to stay frozen in
time, the way they were when the shows went off the air. Digging
them up just seems macabre, sort of like grave robbing. Leave 'em
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
