<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain picks up steam
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Republican presidential candidate John McCain scored
an important victory last week. He won the New Hampshire primary
with about 49 percent of the vote. George W. Bush garnered about 31
percent. For McCain's win, he earns 17 of the 1,033 delegates that
a candidate needs to clinch his party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The largest benefit of the New Hampshire win for McCain is that
he has momentum leading into the South Carolina, Michigan and
Arizona primaries. When a candidate wins an important primary, it
helps convince people that he could go all the way to the White
House. People will donate more money and their time to a candidate
they have confidence in.
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina primary will be Feb. 19 and Michigan and
Arizona follow on Feb. 22. Be sure to keep track of who wins each
primary and how many delegates are awarded.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD WORRIED ABOUT AUSTRIA
</P>
<P>
   Many countries are upset about the new Austrian government that
was sworn in last week. The world leaders fear some of the new
cabinet members' beliefs are similar to those of the Nazi party.
The Nazi party was led by Adolph Hitler in Germany during the 1930s
and 1940s. The racist Nazi party supported the killing of 6 million
Jews during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Finland cut off ties with Austria, and Israel withdrew its
ambassador last week. About 5,000 Austrians demonstrated to protest
the new government.
</P>
<P>
   Austria is a small European country situated north of Italy and
east of Germany. (If you've seen ``The Sound of Music,'' you've
seen some of Austria.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMUNISTS PULL PLUG ON PORKY PIG AND GANG
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government said ``That's all, folks'' and blocked
the satellite feed of the Cartoon Network last week. The channel
was never available to Chinese citizens, but was broadcast to the
country's tourist hotels.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the move is unknown. But it is a reminder that
U.S. culture is still tightly controlled in China. Only about a
dozen Hollywood films are allowed each year in movie theaters
there.
</P>
<P>
   China's leadership has been trying to kick-start its own
animation industry by restricting Western cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   Disney characters, such as Mickey Mouse and Goofy, are still
commonly seen in China on videos and magazine stands. Chinese
youngsters often stick U.S. cartoon characters to their backpacks
and jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
