<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-HOMELESS0208-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    3 families struggle with homelessness
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In recent weeks, metro Atlanta kids got a taste of
hardship similar to what some poor people face. The ice storms left
many homes without heat and lights for days.
</P>
<P>
   But imagine living without heat and power _ in a car. That's
right: no home, no bathroom, no television. You wake up in a car,
and go to sleep in a car.
</P>
<P>
   That's what life was like for Heartents Maples and her four boys
in October. After moving to Atlanta from Chicago, the family became
so poor they had to live in their car for days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not fun,'' said her son Michael Neal, who is 8 years
old. ``It was cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael slept in the back seat. To pass the time, the kids would
sing along with the car radio. They played ``Rock, Paper,
Scissors.'' If they had to go to the bathroom, their mother would
take them to a restaurant to use the restroom. That's also where
she would wash them.
</P>
<P>
   Since they had no closet in the car, their clothes were kept in
plastic bags in the trunk. At night, their mother would park in a
motel parking lot, and they would sleep in the car. Four people
sleeping in a car was uncomfortable. Sometimes they slept sitting
up. Sometimes they had trouble sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   Other poor people also sleep in cars sometimes. LaShawn Coleman
and her three kids slept in a car for two weeks in December. They
had hardly any money for gas or food. Kendall Coleman, who is 7
years old, would do his homework in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes poor people in metro Atlanta have an apartment but
cannot afford to pay their power bills. So the heat and electricity
are turned off. When that happened to Edith Parks and her two kids
last winter, they had to live in a dark and cold apartment.
</P>
<P>
   They all stayed in one room and slept in the same bed. They
snuggled and used their body heat to keep each other warm. They lit
candles for light. Sometimes Marcus Hamilton, who is 7, and his
sister Catina Parks, who is 4, would cry and complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was too cold and too dark and too scary,'' Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   Now these three families live in places called shelters in
Atlanta. These shelters allow people who are poor to live there
temporarily for free. The families receive food, heat and beds. The
parents also receive help finding jobs so they can make money and
move into their own homes.
</P>
<P>
   HOW CAN KIDS HELP OTHERS?
</P>
<P>
   Several shelters and other services for the needy allow children
to help out. For example:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Children's Restoration Network _ This is an agency that
provides goods and services to more than 60 women's and children's
shelters in the metro area. Children age 12 and above can tutor
younger children in math and English. Children under 16 should be
accompanied by an adult. For more information, call 770-649-7117.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Atlanta Union Mission _ Children can help serve meals or
help other children with reading. In some cases, adult supervision
is required. Call 404-588-4000.
</P>
<P>
   _ Children can also help the poor by collecting food and
clothing at their schools and churches.
</P>
<P>
   Write to News for Kids at nfk(at)ajc.com, and tell us how you
are going to make a difference in the lives of less-fortunate
children. We'll publish how classes and individual kids are going
to help.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
