<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Tuesday, February 8, 2000 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ For the past half-century and
then some, Mary Caldwell has been Lufkin's very own Martha Stewart
of down-home cooking. Now her granddaughter wants to collect Mary's
recipes for a book. So she is: ``She is a storehouse of vast
information, and I don't want her to leave this earth without it
being recorded.'' (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ LINCOLN CITY, Ore. _ For decades, folks living
on the Pacific shores, particularly in the northwest and Alaska,
have been harvesting the colorful glass floats that occasionally
break loose from Japanese fishing boats and float up on shore.
They're not rare. Antique shops up and down the coast sell them to
visitors for about 20 bucks apiece. Then last summer a local
entrepreneur with time on his hands came up with the bright idea of
millennium floats _ 2000 jewel-hued, blown-glass balls to be
scattered along the 14-mile stretch of Lincoln City beaches for
tourists to discover in the sand and exclaim: OOH! LOOK-Y THERE
MABEL! IT'S A COLORFUL GLASS BALL IN THE SAND! I THINK I'VE
DISCOVERED A MILLENNIUM FLOAT.(Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ The day of the first storm
of winter started out pleasantly enough, with a plate of heuvos
rancheros, beans and tortillas, washed down with a strong cup of
coffee and a tall glass of milk at a Mexican restaurant in downtown
Buda, a charming little town about 15 miles south of Austin.
Outside, it finally felt like a Texas winter _ 35 degrees and
raining, wind whipping a gray band of clouds from the west. My
prediction: Winter came in like a lamb and will go out like a lion
this season. Blame La Nina. (Borders, Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ Think you just have to be
born between World War II and the 1960s to qualify as a baby
boomer? According to this e-mail I received, there's a qualifying
exam to take before you can become a full-fledged boomer. While not
as complicated as the Mensa test, it does touch on everything from
music and politics to sports and TV. And in keeping with the boomer
philosophy, there's no points off for wrong answers. (Murray,
Lufkin Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA, Fla. _ It's not as though there are no
grounds to question the permanance of the dot-com economy. But it
seems that much of the economic hand-wringing over the booming
economy is not based on charts and formulae. It comes from a sense
that we just don't deserve this. People are partying too hard and
the next knock on the door is bound to be the cops. (Lane, Daytona
Beach News-Journal) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ Americans should reject false leaders and
demand politicians with outspoken personal principles. With luck,
the New Hampshire primaries will cause politicians at all levels to
compete with straight talk and unvarnished truth. (Rowland Nethaway
is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
