<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9058 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-SCI-BREAKTHROUGHS-ART     02-07 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BREAKTHROUGHS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKTHROUGH BRIEFS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    THREE COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By THE EDITORS OF DISCOVER MAGAZINE  
 c.2000 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   &UR; SEASICK SEAS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is brewing beneath the waves. Biologists report that
marine diseases are on the rise, and the ocean's inhabitants _
fish, mammals, plants and invertebrates alike _ are suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows the exact cause of the ocean epidemics, but human
activity undoubtedly plays a role.
</P>
<P>
   Untreated sewage is thought to feed outbreaks of toxic algae,
such as the fish-killing Pfiesteria. Industrial runoff may be
responsible for the rash of tumors seen in fish around coastal
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Canine distemper virus from domesticated dogs apparently killed
a significant fraction of seal populations in Antarctica and
Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   Marine diseases are best documented among commercially important
species. Viruses from cultured shrimp in the Pacific severely
diminished wild stocks near Mexico, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fish populations are being seriously affected. The trends
are very striking,'' says aquatic ecologist JoAnn Burkholder of
North Carolina State University.
</P>
<P>
   By far the most dramatic crisis is the pandemic of coral
bleaching. According to marine ecologist James Porter of the
University of Georgia in Athens, 70 percent of the coral reefs in
the Indian Ocean have whitened and died in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Reefs are rich stores of biodiversity and sensitive measures of
environmental health. Elevated sea temperatures trigger the
bleaching, which makes Porter suspicious about the timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing like this has occurred within the last half-century,''
he says. ``The most viable hypothesis to explain coral bleaching is
global warming.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; BIG BIG FUN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you need to pack a large structure in a small box, talk to
designer Chuck Hoberman. His folding Hoberman Sphere toy, made of
linked plastic struts, expands from the size of a basketball to a
sphere big enough for a child to sit in.
</P>
<P>
   He's taken that idea a step further with the new Expandagon
Construction System, a set of articulated, snap-together building
components.
</P>
<P>
   Each colorful part is a marvel of mechanical engineering. Linked
together, they can form anything from octahedrons to rocket ships
that stretch to many times their original proportions.
</P>
<P>
   An accompanying guidebook explains the geometric principles
behind Hoberman's creations.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; THE VANISHING WATERS OF MARS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few years, astronomers have spotted signs of
ancient coastlines on Mars, the remnants of a vast, possibly
life-harboring ocean. But those Martian seashores now seem to be a
hopeful illusion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 and 1998, the Mars Global Surveyor snapped more than
1,000 pictures of the Red Planet. Geologist Ken Edgett and
geomorphologist Michael Malin of Malin Space Science Systems in San
Diego scrutinized 14 images containing purported shorelines.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists saw no wave-cut cliffs or sediment shaped by
waves. Instead, they found boundaries between lava flows and
highlands, or disconnected features that looked continuous in
earlier, poorer images.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the real Mars is still plenty interesting. Pictures
from the Global Surveyor show evidence of giant floods, including
boulders that ended up stacked on top of one another when the
waters receded.
</P>
<P>
   All being well, the Polar Lander that reached Mars last month
will dig for remnants of that water buried frozen in the soil,
monitor clouds, and send back sounds of the Martian winds. If the
past is any guide, Mars has more surprises in store.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; THE MANLY MAMMARY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fourth most popular kind of cosmetic surgery among men is _
surprise! _ breast reduction.
</P>
<P>
   According to statistics compiled by the American Society of
Plastic and Reconstructive Surgeons, 9,023 of these operations were
performed in 1998, more than double the figure for 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Solomon, a Philadelphia plastic surgeon whose clientele
includes many men, points to the growing number of bodybuilders
downing anabolic steroids to increase muscle bulk. The drugs can
trigger breast growth when the body converts them into estrogenlike
compounds.
</P>
<P>
   Reproductive endocrinologist Claude Hughes of Cedars-Sinai
Medical Center in Los Angeles says poor diet and lack of exercise
help send men to surgeons as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our population is more obese than it's ever been, and it's
reasonable to think that would increase demand for this
procedure,'' he observes.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a more sinister possibility. Many common pollutants,
including some PCBS, also mimic the effect of estrogen.
</P>
<P>
   Could these compounds cause men to develop breasts?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a plausible hypothesis,'' says Hughes, who studies
environmental estrogens.
</P>
<P>
   To test it, he suggests examining fat tissue removed during male
breast reduction and comparing its levels of estrogen-mimicking
contaminants to those of fat removed from men undergoing a neutral
operation, such as cardiac surgery.
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
