<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9095 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-FASHION-PROTEST-NYTSF     02-07 1335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-PROTEST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SAGA AT DIOR  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from Women's Wear
Daily, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By BRIDGET FOLEY  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   How far is too far?
</P>
<P>
   John Galliano is finding out. The furor over the couture
collection he showed recently for Christian Dior, inspired, he
said, by the ``wet world'' of tramps and hobos he discovered while
jogging around the Seine, just won't go away. In terms of
controversy, it's the biggest thing to hit fashion since Heroin
Chic.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jan. 23, two of The New York Times' most high-profile
columnists have addressed the issue _ Maureen Dowd, who compared
the collection to Rudolph Giuliani's street-sweep of the homeless,
and Cathy Horyn, in a piece on the power of spin.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy took yet another turn on Jan. 27, when riot
police were called in to fend off a small but vocal group of
homeless activists in front of the Dior headquarters and store on
the Avenue Montaigne.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in Le Figaro, Dior chairman Bernard Arnault went
on the record about the whole affair for the first time. He
defended the collection vigorously, calling it ``the strongest
presentation since John started at Dior.'
</P>
<P>
   Galliano, he said, ``had transcended his status as a couturier,
and had shown that he was a veritable artist. A gust of genius blew
through the room.''
</P>
<P>
   However, by the end of the day, Galliano himself seemed to
retreat from his defiant stance, when he said that his critics are
``bourgeois people, condescending and smug.'' At the time, Galliano
refused to apologize for anything about the collection, saying, ``I
really, really saw nothing wrong with it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 27, Dior issued a more conciliatory statement, in which
Galliano said, ``I never wanted to make a spectacle of misery, nor
did I intend to do a sociological collection that would be a
documentary of poverty in the street. In no way did I mean it to be
offensive to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   This collection is but the latest of many examples in which a
designer or the industry at large has been accused of tossing out
responsibility in pursuit of hype.
</P>
<P>
   Did Galliano go too far? Many would say no, since one of the
roles of fashion is to provoke and unsettle.
</P>
<P>
   As a young man coming to Paris with his first collection, Yohji
Yamamoto recalled, his point was ``to break the rules, to question
traditional beauty,'' and certainly, there has always been a
faction, usually those on the avant-garde edge, which has continued
to do that.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, with media such a focus and so all-pervasive, the
ante has been increased. And anyone who goes the shock route who
claims a lack of interest in potential publicity can be accused of
being either delusional or disingenuous.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, some high-profile brouhahas have broken
out on the fashion front. Everybody's all-time favorite, Heroin
Chic, wound up with President Clinton chastising the fashion
industry on the front page of The New York Times. Remember Calvin
Klein and kiddie porn? Now there's Benetton and its merry band of
murderers.
</P>
<P>
   Other designers have caused stirs with their runway themes _
Alexander's McQueen with his ``Highland Rape,'' for example, or
Jean Paul Gaultier and his Hasidic collection.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Rei Kawakubo's fall '95 men's collection for
Comme des Garcons, presented on the 50th anniversary of the
liberation of Auschwitz, for which she was accused _ but denied _
dressing gaunt-looking models to resemble concentration-camp
prisoners. And the list goes on.
</P>
<P>
   The king of controversy himself, Calvin, thinks that the market
should decide the boundaries of taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make a comparison between John Galliano and Rudolph Giulani
is just nonsense,'' Klein said, referring to Dowd's column. ``One
is a very creative, artistic fashion designer, and the other, a
public servant. Creative people find inspiration in everything
around them, and to have the courage to explore that and show it to
the world _ I applaud John. He's not making a political statement.
He's looking at an unfortunate situation in the world as an artist
and is inspired by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see nothing wrong with someone putting his work out there
for the world to see,'' Klein continued. ``People have the freedom
to express themselves. And this is a business that targets a
market. If John goes in a direction that no one understands, the
company might suffer the consequences in terms of business,
although I would add that all this coverage is probably creating
business for Dior.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, says Galliano's LVMH compatriot Marc Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand them,'' Jacobs said of the collection's
critics. ``I'm not one for the story-telling school of fashion.
Inspiration doesn't make a good piece of clothing. I didn't see the
show, but it sounds very `Let them eat cake' to me, and they cut
off (Marie Antoinette's) head over that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fashion isn't art. I'm pretty open-minded; I don't take
offense easily. But I think that, whenever you touch on someone's
misfortune or seem to be caricaturing their culture, you're likely
to be misconstrued. Gaultier made the Hasidic Jews furious. Comme
des Garcons made the concentration-camp survivors furious. Wasn't
it Chanel who made the Muslims furious over some sacred writing on
a dress?
</P>
<P>
   ``Inspiration is a personal thing; you can find it anywhere. The
danger is not in being inspired by a group of people, the danger is
in boasting about the inspiration, unless you're putting it to a
charitable pursuit. Once you start talking about it, it becomes
exploitation, and I don't think that's right. You don't go around
parading on other people's plight.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, underscoring the whole debate is that the venue was
couture, creating the juxtaposition of unimaginable wealth against
unimaginable poverty. That's a tough one to get past, no matter how
much respect one has for Galliano's brilliance. And there's no
question, ``let them eat cake'' is alive and well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt John was honoring the homeless,'' said Mouna Ayoub,
currently couture's most editorial client. Ayoub purchased five of
the collection's looks for her personal wardrobe, and bought one _
the ``burnt coat'' made to look, Galliano said, as if the wearer
had ``gotten too near a fire'' _ for her couture collection. She
will house it in a 12-room Paris apartment she has converted into a
veritable museum, just for her own collection of haute couture.
</P>
<P>
   ``By bringing the homeless on the podium, it's an homage. He
brought them on the podium, and we cannot forget them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayoub then turned to Galliano's critics. ``If they took one
close look at these dresses, everyone would understand. They didn't
see these dresses close up like I did. The workmanship is
fantastic. Chapeaux off to the seamstresses.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, not everyone would agree with Ayoub.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Cohen, president and ceo of the Partnership for the
Homeless in New York, believes that an olive branch can be wielded
more effectively than a sword.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to extend an invitation to John Galliano,'' he said.
``Let's use this as an opportunity to raise some funds, support our
programs, work with the Partnership, putting an end to all this
uproar. Use this as an opportunity to raise public awareness about
how homelessness devastates lives the lives of men, women and
children on the streets, especially now in this bitter cold. I'd
love to work with John Galliano and put together an event.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Bridget Foley is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 1311EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9096 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-FASHION-PROTEST-NYTSF     02-07 1335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-PROTEST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SAGA AT DIOR  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from Women's Wear
Daily, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
