<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9101 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-BUSH-`RETOOLED'-INDEP     02-07 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-`RETOOLED'-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SEEKS TO ERASE `LOSER' IMAGE OF NEW HAMPSHIRE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for Tuesday's primary, Delaware)   (This timely 750-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, DEL. _ A newly ``retooled'' George W. Bush _ the term was
used by his campaign _ flew into the small East Coast state of
Delaware Monday, intent on finishing off his pesky challenger,
Steve Forbes, and simultaneously banishing the memory of his
chastening defeat in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   With his presidential bid appearing suddenly vulnerable and less
than two weeks to go before the key primary in South Carolina, Bush
is having to treat Tuesday's Delaware primary as a serious test.
</P>
<P>
   Delaware may be small _ it has only 750,000 inhabitants and
elects only one member of the U.S. House of Representatives _ but
as the first state to ratify the Constitution, it enjoys a certain
cachet.
</P>
<P>
   It also has two highly experienced senators and wields
disproportionate legislative clout, thanks to its relative wealth
and its prowess in banking and pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   Its liberal tax laws have attracted many corporations to site
their headquarters here, among them some of Bush's most generous
donors.
</P>
<P>
   Which is one reason why he is campaigning here in person: among
supporters in the miniature state capital, Dover; among servicemen
at the nearby Air Force Base (one of the major shipping points for
aid to Kosovo last year); and among big corporate sponsors in the
state's business powerhouse, the city of Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason is the billionaire publisher, Steve Forbes, whose
own base lies just to the north, in the state of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, Forbes may not look the greatest threat to Bush's
presidential prospects. That honor currently goes to Senator John
McCain, who trounced him by 18 points in New Hampshire and has
drawn level in opinion polls in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking the big money of either a Bush or a Forbes, however,
McCain has picked his contests carefully, choosing to disregard
Delaware, as he did the Iowa caucuses two weeks ago. He is applying
all his effort to South Carolina, and the primary shortly
thereafter in the northerly state of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   In his newly aggressive campaign mode, Bush scorned his rival's
tactics. McCain's absence, though, leaves him in a straight fight
with Forbes _ who actually won the Delaware primary four years ago,
beating the party favorite, Robert Dole, into second place.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Dole had chosen, like McCain this year, not to campaign
in Delaware, but the notion persists that Delaware is Forbes's sort
of state, and he has campaigned here as though that were so.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, election day, he will have spent four full days
here, breaking only last Friday to speak at a state party gathering
in California.
</P>
<P>
   Often an awkward campaigner, Forbes has nonetheless gone from
town hall to town hall, spreading his message of tax reform and
presenting himself in the guise of ``independent outsider'' that
has proved so successful for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Just north of Dover, in the small town of Smyrna _ a town whose
commercial heart has been comprehensively killed by the nearby
shopping center _ Forbes found a typical standing-room-only crowd
of around 200 waiting for him in the fire station hall.
</P>
<P>
   They were small business people and pensioners mostly, none of
them wealthy, and not all of them loyal. The name John McCain was
on many lips, even though he had not deigned to campaign in their
state.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush appeared to be widely disliked, except by the dozen
or so young pickets who stood on the pavement outside with large
Bush placards.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has some good lines. He compares the length of the
Gettysburg Address, the Declaration of Independence and even the
Bible with the 7 million plus words of the U.S. tax code.
</P>
<P>
   He suggests that redundant taxmen could usefully be redeployed
shovelling away some of the snow piled up beside Delaware's roads.
</P>
<P>
   And to all those in Washington who say we cannot scrap the tax
code? ``Well, hello guys! Whose country is this?''
</P>
<P>
   In the televised Republican debates, it was clear that there is
little love lost between the stolid Forbes and the smooth George W.
And rumors abound that the Republican Party has urged Forbes to end
his bid so that Bush can take on McCain without lesser
distractions.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing Bush needs is another poor primary showing. But
Forbes has the money (his own) to fight on, and he might not be
averse to diluting Bush's effort.
</P>
<P>
   At least as of Monday, the Forbes camp was adamant: ``We are in
this to the end.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
