<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIVES-CANDIDATES-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WOMEN BEHIND THE CANDIDATES  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 700-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The tightening of the Republican race this week
following John McCain's spectacular victory in the New Hampshire
primary plunged into the spotlight two women who had hitherto done
their best to remain in the shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush, wife of George W. for the past 22 years, and Cindy
McCain, married to John for almost 20 years, were both at their
husband's side in the last days of campaigning and again at their
post-campaign speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bush, unaccustomed to hearing her husband concede defeat,
stood stoically beside him at the microphone, with their
17-year-old twins _ the very picture of blonde, cheerleading young
womanhood - behind.
</P>
<P>
   A teacher and librarian before she met and married George W.,
Mrs. Bush, 53, has done the traditional thing as first lady of
Texas, devoting herself to good works _ children's literacy above
all _ and what Americans call ``homemaking'' (being a housewife).
</P>
<P>
   Dressed most often in trousers and cardigan, she exudes an air
of capable common sense and wifely loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Present or absent, she always features at the start of her
husband's standard stump speech: Marrying Laura, he says, was the
best decision he ever made, then he habitually draws a laugh by
adding ``though it may not be the best decision she ever made.''
</P>
<P>
   He also claims that a pre-marriage pledge to her that she would
not have to make speeches is the ``only promise I have ever
broken.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Mrs. Bush has made relatively few solo appearances on
her husband's behalf and sometimes seems sullen when traipsing
after him in public.
</P>
<P>
   She gave a rare glimpse of relaxed domesticity last week when
she watched her husband reveal himself as a dab hand with a spatula
during a pancake-tossing contest.
</P>
<P>
   Absent or demurely submissive during campaigning, Mrs. Bush is
quite capable of speaking for herself. But when she does, she
wisely keeps to homely subjects, as she did in a pre-Christmas
television interview, where she appeared jointly with her
formidable mother-in-law, Barbara Bush, beside the family Christmas
tree.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking extempore, she comes across as surprisingly strident
and broadly Texan, suggesting another side to her that could be a
liability to her husband when the campaign trail goes fully
national.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Hensley, 45, became John McCain's second wife in 1980,
several years after he divorced his first wife _ a divorce for
which he takes abject responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   After appearing utterly terrified by the razzmatazz and the
crowds at the start of his presidential campaigning, she has
recently relaxed a little and frequently appears solo, deputizing
for her husband when Senate duties keep him from fulfilling
campaign engagements.
</P>
<P>
   In his 18 years as a congressman and senator, she has hardly
come to Washington at all, staying with their family in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Daughter of a wealthy Arizona family and _ like Laura Bush _ a
teacher by training, Mrs. McCain founded a children's medical
charity in 1988 that works in war zones and regularly travels with
its missions, most recently to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, she started a second children's charity that
works in Arizona and neighboring states. The McCains have four
children, and one adopted _ a child she brought back from one of
her charity trips to Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   She tells how, when she arrived at the airport, he was there to
meet her and asked where the child would stay. ``With us,'' she
replied, to which he responded: ``I thought so,'' _ just like that.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McCain, who is strikingly good-looking and always
impeccably dressed and coiffed in a suburban American way, brought
a skeleton out of her closet early by admitting last spring that
she had been addicted to painkillers, even to the point of stealing
the drugs from shipments intended for her charity.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, for his part, went on the record to regret that he
had been perhaps ``wrapped up too much in Washington and my
ambitions'' to notice her problem until a very late stage. The
sting thus drawn, reporters have left the subject alone. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 700-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 1312EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
