<P>
   STEAL OF THE MILLENNIUM? _ In its ``Persons of the Century''
edition, Time magazine made a big blunder, writes columnist TIm
Giago. ``Under the heading, `Steal of the Millennium,' Time
announced, ``On Aug. 10, 1626, the Canarsee Delaware Indians agreed
to sell the 22-square-mile Manhattes island at the mouth of the
Hudson River to Dutch settlers under Peter Minuit. The price: cloth
and trinkets. At the end of the 20th century, Manhattan was
estimated to be worth at least $143 billion.''' But Indian tribes
do not sell their land. ``Every tribe considers the Earth to be
their mother, and one does not sell their mother,'' Giago writes.
The truth: Settlers usually moved on to the Indian land, set up
housekeeping, and when the landlords protested, offered to pay a
price to continue living on the land. In this commentary, Giago
debunks this longstanding myth about the sale of Manhattes island.
</P>
<P>
   A MISSING CHAPTER. For years, children's literature has sat on
the backburner of publishing, the forgotten child in world of
``real literature,'' writes columnist Amy Wu. But thanks to J.K.
Rowling's creation of a child wizard in the ``Harry Potter''
series, children's literature is experiencing a renaissance. Wu
believes that the spotlight on Harry Potter does not make up for
the real void in children's literature _ the lack of true diversity
and, even more disturbing, the lack of debate about it. ``There is
a real need for stories that reflect America's changing face and
that dispel the myths about different people,'' Wu writes. ``And
there is room to tell these stories in a creative way.''
</P>
<P>
   AFRICAN-AMERICANS ARE KEY TO CAMPAIGN 2000. Regardless Of who
gets elected as our next president, Campaign 2000 will be notable
for two breakthroughs that have received very little attention: Two
African-Americans _ a Democrat and a Republican _ have scaled the
campaign hierarchy of white candidates and hold positions that
blacks have never held before. As national chairman of GOP
candidate Steve Forbes' campaign, Ken Blackwell is the first black
to oversee the presidential campaign of a prominent white
candidate. As Vice President Al Gore's campaign manager, Donna
Brazile is the first black woman to run the day-to-day operations
of a major presidential contender. A report by Kevin Merida.
Excerpted form Emerge magazine.
</P>
<P>
   KENNEWICK MAN'S PAINFUL JOURNEY CONTINUES. Clues to America's
past lie within the bones of a 9,200-year-old skeleton found in a
Pacific Northwest river more than three years ago. This prehistoric
man lived more than nine millennia ago. The significance of these
bones is that they may lend credence to a scientific theory that
people other than American Indians are the real First Americans. In
the three years since his resurgence, Kennewick Man, so called
because he was discovered in the Columbia River near Kennewick,
Wash., has been caught in a philosophical chasm between
evolutionists and Native-American creationists. ``I see and
understand both sides,'' writes columnist Karen Lincoln Michel.
``But my thoughts are with ... an ancient man who lost his life
along the Columbia River. As Kennewick Man is probed for more
clues, it seems his painful journey continues.''
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN, IN HIS OWN WORDS. Since 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez was
found clinging to an inner tube in the Florida straits, he has been
caught in a battle between Cuba and the United States, between his
father and his U.S. relatives. It seems as though everyone has
spoken for young Elian except the child himself. ``So far, we've
heard from his lawyers, a swarm of politicians and practically
every one of the boy's relatives. But what does Elian have to
say?'' asks columnist James Garcia. In this imaginary interview,
Garcia asks young Elian whether or not he would like to go home.
</P>
