<HEADER>
A9122 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-THEATER-JITNEY-REVIEW     02-07 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-JITNEY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUGUST WILSON'S `JITNEY' RUNS VERY WELL, INDEED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The velvety timbre of Marvin Gaye, soaring through the Mark
Taper Forum, is our first clue that August Wilson's ``Jitney'' is a
period drama pitched at the midpoint between hope and resignation,
dreams and disillusionment.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gaye, after all, whose keening pop-soul protest anthems
of the early `70s echoed the waning black power movement and helped
define the ambivalent state of black America in the post-Vietnam
years.
</P>
<P>
   In Wilson's native Pittsburgh and similar Rust Belt enclaves,
the growing gap between expectation and reality had by then become
painfully obvious to many African-Americans. Which, in response,
was the proper course of action: Run for your life, or stand and
fight the power?
</P>
<P>
   This is the setting, and the resounding ethical dilemma, that
shapes Wilson's coming-out play, which is receiving a first-tier
production at the Taper from director Marion McClinton and an
ensemble cast as virtuous and harmoniously emphatic as a
rock-steady r&AMP;b unit.
</P>
<P>
   Written and originally produced in 1978, before Wilson had
imprinted his rumbling, lyrical baritone on the American theater,
``Jitney'' is relatively compact by Wilsonian standards, just over
two hours. Though lacking the full-throttle poeticism of his later
works, it's as solidly assembled as a Buick, with high-octane
passion to burn. Wilson apparently has reworked the play
extensively in recent years, and its only obvious remaining flaw is
that it needs a conventional Oedipal key to jumpstart its fairly
simple plot.
</P>
<P>
   That key is the fractured relationship between Becker (Paul
Butler), the owner of a jitney, or taxi service, in Pittsburgh's
decaying Hill District, and his 39-year-old son, Booster (Carl
Lumbly).
</P>
<P>
   A church deacon and towering moral figure, Becker is a strict
but fair employer, who keeps order among a motley crew of four
jitney drivers and a hanger-on or two.
</P>
<P>
   All beautifully performed, they include Shealy (Willis Burks
II), a gap-toothed numbers runner; Youngblood (Russell Hornsby), a
Vietnam veteran constantly in dutch with his girlfriend (Michole
Briana White); and, best of all, the gossipy, mischief-making
Turnbo, played by Stephen McKinley Henderson as a kind of
inner-city Sir John Falstaff. Set to the staccato rhythm of the
jitney station's constantly ringing phone, the play makes ample
room for their funny, stirring personal stories.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Jitney'' begins, Butler is awaiting Booster's imminent
release from the local penitentiary, where he has spent 20 years
for murdering his rich, white college girlfriend after she falsely
accused him of raping her.
</P>
<P>
   We can sense the coming showdown between the upstanding,
play-by-the-rules father, who blames Booster for throwing away his
life, and the son who only wanted to stand tall in his father's
eyes by repaying a racist slap.
</P>
<P>
   While Wilson later revisited father-son conflict in ``Fences''
(1986), there's a raw, compelling edge to his treatment of it here,
abetted by the two dynamic actors' fiery chemistry. Lumbly makes
Booster's tortured integrity shine through his handsome features,
while Butler's imposingly righteous presence gives ``Jitney'' its
steel-frame backbone. We can easily see why his fellow drivers
would rally round Becker when he opts to resist the white
bureaucrats who want to tear down the block and build housing.
</P>
<P>
   In their different ways, all the play's characters are, as
Booster puts it, ``warriors'' combating a common enemy. Typically
of this urbane playwright's empathic vision, ``Jitney'' doesn't
crudely label that enemy. Rather, it invites us to see that
self-respect, like moral justice, is a two-way street, where a soul
must always prepare itself for the long haul. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
What: ``Jitney.'' &QL; 
Where: Mark Taper Forum, Performing Arts Center of Los Angeles
County, 135 N. Grand Ave., downtown L.A. &QL; 
When: Through March 19. Performances at 8 p.m. Tuesdays through
Fridays, 2:30 and 8 p.m. Saturdays, 2:30 and 7:30 p.m. Sundays. &QL; 
Tickets: $29 to $42. Call (213) 628-2772 or visit
www.TaperAhmanson.com on the Web. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
