u f BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS &LR;      02-07 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAREER PEAK: BOTTOM RUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; People think Steve Hoffman must have burned out, or messed up,
or just plain flipped. Why else would a 47-year-old guy with a
family walk out on a six-figure-plus income at a prestigious Boston
law firm to become an assistant district attorney at $28,000 a
year?
</P>
<P>
   It's a joke, right? It's like that old Bob Newhart routine where
Newhart does Abe Lincoln's press secretary, coaching the great man
on how to give the stump speech: ``No, Abe _ first a rail splitter,
then an attorney.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hoffman isn't kidding. Hoffman is rich, and not just in
terms of an investment portfolio that allows him financial
maneuvering space. He is rich in the best way a person can be rich:
He is doing the work he loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is here for the money,'' says Hoffman, sitting at a
shabby table in the drab Marlborough District Court cafeteria (his
office has no room for visitors). He's been an assistant DA for
Middlesex County since last September, when he left a
21-year-career at Sugarman &AMP; Sugarman, where he was a personal
injury and liability attorney _ as well as partner _ to drop back
down to what's considered the first rung of his profession.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because he wanted to do public service law, and wanted to
work for Middlesex District Attorney Martha Coakley, who took a
similar leap in her career, when she left Goodwin, Procter &AMP; Hoar
for the DA's office.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hoffman enjoyed the intellectual challenges of the law
firm, he says he was always drawn to the rough-and-tumble world of
``pure public service.'' When Coakley became DA, the idea ``went
from the back of my mind to the front.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his new job, he says: ``I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might ask: What's to love? For where he once enjoyed the
more contemplative pace of civil case work, he is now in the legal
equivalent of triage, ``learning to deal with a lot of stuff at
once and keep my wits about me.'' Roughly 50 to 75 criminal cases
come through the court in a day, so he and his colleagues must read
papers fast and make instant decisions: whether to ask for bail,
whether to ask that a batterer or substance abuser or a drunk
driver be held. They work 10- and 12-hour days. They make calls
through the dinner hour to line up witnesses. They sweat the
nerve-racking business of getting battering victims on board to
testify against their husbands and partners; they lose many of
those women back to their abusers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the ones you lose sleep over,'' he says, adding that
a good day is getting a ``guilty'' verdict and knowing that ``if I
take one drunk driver off the road I may save a life.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman focuses on the basics. He and his wife Sally, who is an
English and reading tutor at Massasoit Community College, never
bought into the conspicuous consumption that is a rite of passage
for so many people in this sizzling economy. While the roaring
stock market is helping them deal with a drastic cut in salary,
they and their two teenage daughters weren't living lavishly
before, so the shift doesn't hurt a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live a solid middle-class lifestyle,'' says Hoffman, a
Newton resident. He doesn't play golf, belong to a country club,
own a vacation home or a boat, and has never wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a nice home, live in a safe community, and have
enough money to put the kids through college, and that's it. What
else do you need?'' he asks. ``What's important to me is that my
kids see their parents do meaningful work.''
</P>
<P>
   Basics. Not exactly Thoreau on the pond, but there is a fresh
simplicity to this tale of one household budget in the suburbs that
makes a person want to sit down at the kitchen table, figures in
hand, and find the literal bottom line of happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Below all the buzz about money, money, money, and the pressure
to make the financial killing because everybody else is, some
people are discovering something more important: human worth, the
treasure trove that gives meaning to a person's days and peace of
mind through the night. Steve Hoffman found his gold in a room
without a view at the bottom of the ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Where's yours? The quest should be easier in this era of
mega-fortunes, and yet for many people, the perceived need to make
more and more becomes a trap that ties them to a grind rather than
setting them free. ``Sometimes,'' says Hoffman, ``the traps are all
up here in your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that he sees himself as a hero, for he knows that the fat
years enabled him to make his choice. Headed for hours of paperwork
and another late night, he says with a smile: ``I'm in a privileged
position.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Susan Trausch can be reached at s-trausch(at)globe.com_
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
