<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9144 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-TV-DAYTIME-KANSAS-KAN     02-07 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DAYTIME-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SYNDICATED FARE IS TYPIFIED BY BAWDIER, BOLDER CONTEST SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON BARNHART  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think today's crop of daytime TV shows is unfit for human
consumption? Wait until you see what's coming this fall. How about:
</P>
<P>
   - A show where a single woman interviews three single guys and
then chooses one _ as her husband?
</P>
<P>
   - A show where people who think their spouses are cheating can
have them followed by a private investigator?
</P>
<P>
   - A dating game in which hormone-addled teens talk about having
premarital sex while their parents listen in horror offstage?
</P>
<P>
   These were among the dozens of syndicated shows TV executives
were biting on at the recent gathering of the National Association
of Television Program Executives in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The syndication cycle basically plays out in four acts. First a
concept is pitched to a TV studio, which signs the producers to
shoot a pilot episode of the show. Next, the studio's sales force
shops the pilot to TV stations covering as much of the country as
possible. Depending on how many stations agree to carry it, the
show is either abandoned or gets the green light (or ``firm go'')
to begin production, with a launch usually timed to the new fall
season.
</P>
<P>
   By the time of the NATPE convention some shows had already
gotten the firm go. Some, like the new relationship program
starring radio shrink Dr. Laura Schlessinger, sold themselves, with
bidding wars between TV stations in some cities for the right to
carry the show. Others weren't quite there yet but were hoping to
do enough deals in New Orleans to put them over the top.
</P>
<P>
   Among the daytime hopefuls were eight more reality-based
courtroom shows, still more talk shows and a revival of the old
game show ``To Tell the Truth.''
</P>
<P>
   But the ones that created the most buzz at New Orleans were a
new breed that featured a little bit of everything: the intrigue of
a dating show, the spice of a soap opera, the high jinks of a game
show.
</P>
<P>
   And the one that took the cake _ the wedding cake, that is _ was
``Wed at First Sight,'' which audaciously proposes to hitch a bride
and groom before a studio audience, following a one-hour courtship.
</P>
<P>
   If this scenario sounds a little familiar, that's because it
happened two years ago in that weird dimension known as the real
world. A Minneapolis bachelor who had tired of the dating scene
asked his friends to help him find a wife. The nationwide
``Campaign to Elect a Mrs. David Weinlick'' attracted hundreds of
proposals, plenty of media coverage _ and a lucky winner, who
married Weinlick at the Mall of America before 3,000 onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked with Dave Weinlick and his wife, Elizabeth,'' said
Pat Finn, the executive producer of ``Wed at First Sight.''
``They're still together a year and half later and still happy. He
gave me some advice on how his friends made the recommendation.''
</P>
<P>
   Because daytime TV draws mainly female viewers, ``Wed at First
Sight'' will at first have only prospective brides choosing their
Mr. Right. Each contestant will be aided by the ``wedding party'' _
friends, parents and anyone else whose advice she trusts _ as well
as the Web site matchmaker.com, which bills itself as ``the leading
online community enabling secure connections between people with
similar interests and needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Before each taping, the show's producers will cull a list of
potential grooms who have filled out elaborate surveys at the Web
site. From a cut of 10 bachelors, the bride will reduce the field
to three. Then the wedding party interrogates the three finalists,
a process that's videotaped with portions played back during the
show.
</P>
<P>
   The taping itself is the final mating ritual between the woman
and the men _ not just the usual round of ``Dating Game''-styled
questions but also ``compatibility games,'' half-serious attempts
to see if she and he agree on sushi over steak, or boxers over
briefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it a relationship show? Or is it a game show? It's really a
blend of both,'' Finn said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the moment of reckoning arrives, and the bride chooses
bachelor number one, two or three. The fellow gets down on one knee
to propose and then ... the show goes to commercial.
</P>
<P>
   During the break _ Finn said taping will cease for about an hour
_ the two parties consult with family and friends and decide
whether to go through with it.
</P>
<P>
   And if they say yes?
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we do the ceremony!'' Finn said. ``There's an officiant
standing by.''
</P>
<P>
   (The couple in the pilot episode, in fact, said ``I do.'' They
were last spotted on the convention floor, smiling and posing for
snapshots with TV executives.)
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt ``Wed at First Sight'' was an easier show to
pitch to a TV studio because of the media coverage surrounding
Weinlick's real-life courtship. But it was also made possible by
the free-wheeling, almost-anything-goes attitude of today's daytime
TV environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experience of the last 10 years is that people will do
anything on the air,'' said Tim Brooks, senior vice president of
research for the Lifetime cable network.
</P>
<P>
   That trend actually started 20 years ago with Phil Donahue's
boundary-pushing talk show. As soap operas got steamier, talk shows
began to borrow elements of the soaps and incorporate them into
``relationship'' shows, starting with Ricki Lake and veering off
into Jerry Springer-land.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, the phenomenal success of Judy
Sheindlin's ``Judge Judy'' has touched off a wave of courtroom
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was only a matter of time before some inventive TV
producer figured out that court shows, talk shows, soap operas and
game shows had all progressed to the point that pieces of each
could be assembled in ever-daffier combinations.
</P>
<P>
   That's the thinking, for example, behind another daytime show
that was being shopped around at the convention. ``Cheaters'' pairs
the tawdriness of ``Jerry Springer'' with the authenticity of a TV
investigative team. In ``Cheaters,'' spouses who think their mates
are fooling around on the side can send a detective on their trail.
If the gumshoe confirms the adultery, the unlucky philanderer is
brought onto the show and confronted.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's ``First Date,'' a program clearly meant to get
teen-agers watching and parents squirming.
</P>
<P>
   The program works pretty much like ``The Dating Game,'' except
that Mom and Dad watch from backstage while their child interviews
prospective dates. In the five-minute preview tape shown to TV
executives, we see the adults' jaws literally drop when their
teen-age daughter dares three boys to tell her they're still
virgins at their advanced age.
</P>
<P>
   Steam practically comes out of the ears of two other parents
when they hear one boy named Edwin brag that the first thing he
looks for in a girl is ``a nice round butt.''
</P>
<P>
   In a later sequence, the parents emerge ... and they/) get to
interview the prospects. (Dad, in particular, has a few things to
say to Edwin.)
</P>
<P>
   When it comes time to choose a date, there's an incentive: If
the teen-ager's choice matches her parents' pick, she gets extra
spending money.
</P>
<P>
   Really, now. What would Dr. Laura say?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
