<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9145 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-VIDEO-COSTS-2TA     02-07 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-VIDEO-COSTS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY KILLED THE VIDEO STAR 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lost in the wake of the recent media mergers of AOL with Time
Warner, and Time Warner with the EMI Group, is a darker corporate
story about the decline of music videos _ once hailed two decades
ago in the way that downloadable music is hyped today. Videos are
under attack and their costs are spiraling ``out of control,'' say
many artists and record executives, who note that even an average
video now costs $200,000 to $300,000 to make, while many exceed
$1,000,000 for superstar acts.
</P>
<P>
   All this money is being spent in the hope of getting played on
fewer and fewer available slots on cable channels, though the
Internet may soon provide alternative sites and the promise of
lower-budget, less slick videos with the advent of faster broadband
cable access. But is it a case of too little, too late? Right now,
video is an overripe medium _ and strictly a rich person's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge millstone around a band's neck,'' Counting Crows
singer Adam Duritz says of the current situation, in which bands
and their labels try to outspend each other and compete for space
on MTV, VH1, BET, the Box, and the occasional local video show
(though there are far fewer of those these days).
</P>
<P>
   ``Videos are expensive and there's no guarantee that they're
going to get played _ or maybe MTV will just play them for a week
or two,'' adds Duritz. ``I made a movie once and it cost a third of
what videos cost today.''
</P>
<P>
   Videos were a populist touchstone when MTV began in 1981 with
the airing of the Buggles' ``Video Killed the Radio Star.'' The
video channel changed the way Americans perceived music and has
since boosted many careers, from Duran Duran (the British popsters
who rode impossibly
</P>
<P>
   VIDEOS, Page N6 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   corny videos to stardom) and Dire Straits (whose clarion call
was ``I want my MTV!''), to Michael Jackson (who made the first $1
million video, for ``Thriller''), up through Madonna, Mariah Carey,
Puff Daddy, Korn, and Kid Rock.
</P>
<P>
   But today, the thrill is waning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bloated world
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Videos are a pain, an extensive pain,'' says singer Gavin
Rossdale of the band Bush. ``Videos are the last bastion of the
'80s. There's nothing as bloated as the whole video world. . . .
Sometimes I feel sick and immoral doing them. I just don't think
money should be spent like that. I find it really hard to justify
when it's more expensive than the record you make.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, that happens frequently. The Boston band Godsmack
made its self-titled debut album for just $5,000, but the video for
its single, ``Voodoo,'' which featured an extensive cast, topped
$300,000. Says singer Sully Erna: ``I doubt we'll ever do that
again. That is a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Videos continue, in theory, to be promotions for bands _ or,
increasingly, for soundtracks, such as Hole's new clip for ``Be a
Man,'' featuring footage from Oliver Stone's ``Any Given Sunday''
woven in.
</P>
<P>
   But due to the escalating costs, fewer videos are being made _
and fewer rock acts, especially, are making them because MTV often
shuns rock bands and instead caters to the bubblegum pop of Britney
Spears and the Backstreet Boys, or the urban/hip-hop of Puff Daddy,
TLC, and Will Smith, who have all made $1 million-plus videos.
</P>
<P>
   Some musicians are declining to make them at all _ Pearl Jam,
with one exception, stopped making videos after its first album in
1991; and Tom Petty, once hailed as a video pioneer, said recently
that he may not make another, period.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, skepticism is replacing excitement in the video world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't watched MTV in a while,'' says singer Fiona Apple,
``but I was just astonished when I tuned in recently. Everybody was
in a computer-generated suit and using dancers in blocked-off city
streets. It's a little ridiculous. It's no longer about looking at
an artist singing a song, which is what it should be. It's now:
`Look at my new style, look at what we can do, and look at how much
money we have, because we're so successful that we can make this
kind of video.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Making fewer, spending more
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird arithmetic, isn't it?'' says John Beug, senior vice
president for film, video marketing, and programming for Warner
Bros. ``We're making fewer videos, but we're spending much more on
them. Will the cycle ever get back to making more videos? Probably,
when the Internet is up and running _ and you can stream something
in high quality and real time, which is not far away. But right
now, you can really take a bath when a video is not played.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros. tries to place ``between 60 and 70 percent'' of its
videos on the major cable outlets, Beug says, but can still pay a
heavy price by not getting the rest of them aired.
</P>
<P>
   In the industry, that's called a ``dead investment'' and it's
not uncommon at a time when the music cable stations, hurt by low
ratings for videos, add more nonmusic programming to their
schedules. That's especially the case at MTV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music is still the core of our channel, but we're packaging
videos differently,'' says Tom Calderone, MTV senior vice president
of music and talent. ``Now we have shows like the `Beat Suite,' the
`Hot Zone,' and `Total Request Live.' . . . That's where you'll see
videos by Korn, Dr. Dre, Fatboy Slim, and Britney Spears. It's an
inclusive program, versus the niche-specific programming of our
other shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Calderone defends the increased costs of videos, saying ``the
costs represent a need to compete with your contemporaries. . . .
These are not expenses based on excess. They're based on making
great TV.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar thought is expressed by VH1's Wayne Isaak, a vice
president at that channel. ``Are labels spending more money on
videos? I guess they are, compared to two or three years ago. But
the goals and aspirations for videos are higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the prices are going through the roof. Devo, a
popular new band in the '80s, pioneered video as an art form and
made its ``Whip It'' and ``Beautiful World'' videos for a
relatively meager $17,000 and $26,000, respectively. Band member
Jerry Casale has since directed videos for Soundgarden, Foo
Fighters, Mint Condition, and Silverchair.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paying the price
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Today, Casale says, a ``lot of people who don't know what
they're doing are creating an amazing amount of chaos'' in video
production. Bands are put at a disadvantage because they don't own
the copyrights to their videos, yet they're paying half the costs
out of their own record royalties, he says. The labels, which
typically choose the director and the concept for the video, pay
the other half, but are often confronted by angry bands that later
wonder where their royalties went.
</P>
<P>
   ``An act may owe $250,000 to $400,000 right out of the box for a
video,'' says Casale. ``They're going to have to sell another
200,000 records to make up for that. When you're a Top 20 artist,
that might be no problem. But for other artists, the economics are
ridiculous. You'll pay and pay for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   More specifics come from Kate Miller, the vice president of
video production for Capitol Records. A video director typically
gets 10 percent of the cost of the video, she notes _ a sizable sum
given that the average video is shot in one to three days, though
there's also pre- and postproduction.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise driving up costs are what she calls the ``glam squads''
_ the hair, makeup, and wardrobe designers who earn up to $5,000 a
day and all have assistants making $300 to $500 daily. ``The
fashion costs are especially high for urban-market videos, where
you have to have the latest clothes,'' says Miller.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 1336EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9146 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-VIDEO-COSTS-2ND     02-07 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-VIDEO-COSTS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... says Miller.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Unless you're in the business, this all sounds like a lot of
money, but it can be worth it,'' she says. ``Take the case of a
makeup artist who can make someone look so incredible that you
don't have to spend thousands of dollars covering up a pimple when
you do postproduction.''
</P>
<P>
   And that doesn't begin to cover the cost of special effects done
on postproduction computers called by such trade nicknames as ``The
Flame,'' ``The Smoke,'' and ``The Henry.'' Some of these cost $700
an hour _ and may be needed for hundreds of hours.
</P>
<P>
   Other costs include paying professional dancers (a must for
Ricky Martin and Madonna videos) and hiring fire chiefs for safety
purposes, and tutors for underage children on the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artists are often the ones who push the expenses,'' says
Miller, ``because they think, `Oh, I've only got one or two shots
to get on the air.' And some artists, if you don't spend enough,
will say, `It looks like you're not supporting us.' ''
</P>
<P>
   This leads to a ``disconcerting drama between artists and record
labels,'' says Ron Shapiro, executive vice president and general
manager of Atlantic Records. But it's hard to put brakes on the
process _ and Shapiro says it's also due to what today's young
video viewers expect.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In my room
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago, I could go into my room with two albums and play
them and read the liner notes all night and be content with that,''
Shapiro says. ``But kids are now raised in a 200-channel
remote-control environment where the visuals have to blow their
minds. They also go on line and play computer games and have
Nintendo and Sony Playstations.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the reason that video costs are so high _ you've got
kids with clickers who have seen everything and will click you off
if you don't impress them right away.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Shapiro differs from other executives because he has
set a ceiling for video spending at his label _ no more than
$500,000 for a single clip. ``I think for any video, as soon as you
hit $400,000, you're talking an obscene amount of money,'' he says.
``At Atlantic, we're still trying to carry the flag for the power
of the song.''
</P>
<P>
   Some popular video artists are on Atlantic _ such as Brandy and
Kid Rock _ but all their videos have been made for $500,000 or
less, Shapiro says.
</P>
<P>
   A major problem cited by the record labels is that MTV is now in
a ``passive'' mode and tends to play a video only after the song
has become a hit on the radio and has begun selling in the stores.
MTV is not taking many chances and not breaking many acts anymore,
label executives say.
</P>
<P>
   MTV's Calderone disputes that charge, noting that MTV broke Kid
Rock and hopes to do the same with pop singer Coco Lee. ``I
strongly disagree that we do not break new music,'' says Calderone.
``Can we take credit for Britney Spears, for example? We can't take
full credit, but we were definitely a part of her plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, tensions are mounting. And no one is exactly sure what to
expect in the future, particularly with the Internet's impact. The
labels are at least hoping to recoup some of their losses by
offering downloadable videos, just as they're now offering
downloadable music.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet will offer more outlets, which should ease reliance
on MTV, which is currently being investigated by the Justice
Department as a possible monopoly. (MTV's Greg Baldwin simply says
the network is cooperating with the investigation.)
</P>
<P>
   And the Internet should become a way of digging out all the
videos from the past and giving them another whirl in the
marketplace. That might be a scary thought, but then, ``classic
rock'' radio has done the same for rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, when you look at the AOL/Time Warner merger, you
can see what might happen in the future,'' says Capitol's Miller.
``Videos are a big content source and they've been requested on the
Internet by many people. . . . In the past, videos often just sat
on the shelves when their time ran out. Some labels thought, `Well,
we can sell them as home videos,' but that didn't work out. They
sold poorly. But on line, there may be requests for, say, the old
Madonna videos and the hair-band rock videos from the '80s. A lot
of videos that people no longer see may come back this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty soon, all these Web sites will become channels,''
Miller says, ``and if you're just showing pictures on your Web
site, you'll be a Model T.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, if labels can make some money off catalog video sales,
they might not be quite as desperate to spend so much on current
videos in hopes of scoring a lucky hit.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, stay tuned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
