<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9147 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-CLAS     02-07 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-CLASSES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF I HAD A HAMMER ... I'D NEED LESSONS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Note italics below) 
By EVEN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``This is not your house, and these are not your walls,'' my
instructor intoned as I sat on bleachers outside the Woodland Hills
Home Depot store on a recent Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to what you might think, this wasn't an invitation to
take up graffiti as a hobby. Instead, a few of us hardy souls were
braving the chilly night air (and munching store-provided
doughnuts) to learn how to install, well, bathroom fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   In front of us sat a prototype bathroom about twice the size of
(and much cleaner than) my own back home.
</P>
<P>
   Then the instructor added the words we all wanted to hear: ``So
make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about an invitation! Mistakes? Sure, I can do that. I'm
even good at them. That's the really comforting part about Home
Depot University, a series of hands-on, two-hour classes designed
to teach participants a given home-improvement or decorative skill.
You make the mistakes before going home and playing around for real
on your own walls or furniture.
</P>
<P>
   The classes are free and are taught by Depot employees. The
instructors are experts in their topic and patient enough to keep
the un-handy _ like myself _ from either hurting ourselves or from
flinging a tool into the parking lot in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday classes are part of a four-week series devoted to a
given area of the house such as the bathroom or the kitchen, but
since the classes vary from location to location, you can probably
always find a new way to damage/fix/decorate whatever part of your
home needs it.
</P>
<P>
   That night I learned to put in towel racks, toilet paper holders
and the rather challenging recessed medicine cabinet. How hard
could it be to put up a soap dish?
</P>
<P>
   OK, so I'm not Bob Vila, but for some of my other classmates it
(BEGIN ITAL)was(END ITAL) a snap.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Schaaf, a computer consultant from Woodland Hills, even told
me that the skills taught during the class were already so familiar
to him that, at a convenient interval, he pulled aside our
instructor, Scott Riding, and learned how to install a shower
safety bar.
</P>
<P>
   Extra credit! Why didn't I think of that?
</P>
<P>
   Schaaf was right, though. Many of the skills were pretty basic,
and the instructors don't let you do anything dangerous without
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   What they don't tell you is that things that should be easy
typically aren't. Take that nasty little wall-mounting bracket, the
sole purpose of which is to hold up all the bathroom fixtures.
Using an eyeglass repair-kit screwdriver to tighten the bracket's
set screw can be tricky when you have to maneuver said screwdriver
with your hand flush up against a wall (unless you possess the
dexterity of a watchmaker). Despite my best efforts, I couldn't get
the fixture to catch and hold securely over the bracket.
</P>
<P>
   My instructors were patient. They didn't take over until they
were absolutely certain my effort was futile. Then they gave me a
second chance. And a third.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I _ and the fixtures _ caught on, my classmates had
moved on to the evening's final and most difficult activity _
installing the recessed medicine cabinet. Which involved new tools:
a stud finder and a drywall saw.
</P>
<P>
   At HDU, the procedure is demonstrated on the floor, not on the
wall. If I actually intend to saw into my bathroom wall back home,
I would need to _ hello! _ shut off the power to avoid accidentally
tapping into an electrical wire. Careful measurements are another
must. Otherwise, I might have to shore up the cabinet with a couple
of pieces of board to make sure it fits into the recessed space.
Which, during the demonstration, is exactly what instructor Paul
Koch had to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you do something, the more confident you get,''
agreed my classmate Louis Duvand, a draftsman from Woodland Hills.
``And if I goof, I can come here and ask someone what to do next.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy for him to say. He got the bracket mounted on the first
try.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days later, I checked out a free how-to clinic at
North Hollywood's Home Depot. On Saturdays and Sundays at any Home
Depot location, visitors can learn about installing a thermostat or
the ins and outs of water filters. Unlike the HDU sessions, the
weekend demonstrations are always the same, regardless of which
location you visit.
</P>
<P>
   My selection, installing Pergo flooring, wasn't a popular
choice; in fact I was the only one there. Nevertheless, my
instructor, Jorge Mora, pulled out all the materials and set up the
display. He showed me the Pergo panels, the padding, glue, putty
and straps used to hold the newly glued Pergo in place. In an ideal
world, assembling Pergo would be just like connecting blocks. But I
figured improperly gluing your floor would be a pretty nasty faux
pas, and I wasn't about to risk it. For flooring needs, I
concluded, I'll go to the Yellow Pages.
</P>
<P>
   My final HDU class _ on decorative paint techniques _ encouraged
creativity. And even messiness. I was in Glendale this time, but
there again were the outdoor bleachers sitting next to a table
crammed with cans of paint, primer, buckets, rags and sponges.
Present also was the prototype room with walls prepared in advance
for decorative paint.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, mistakes were allowed, and I quickly learned why.
Goofs are relatively easy to erase when one works with a latex
(water-based) instead of an oil-based paint. A little soap and
water cleanrs it right up.
</P>
<P>
   In this class, we worked with paint-saturated rags, sponges _
and even the edge of a feather to create veining effects. Frank De
Jesus and Sindee Gomez, the evening's co-instructors, demonstrated
each technique. Then it was our turn to don Home Depot aprons
(which we got to keep) and latex gloves and start painting
decoratively.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good tune-up for my classmate Kimberly Gifaldi who,
back at her home in Burbank, had a hallway waiting for a decorative
paint job. She envisioned a mixture of goldenrod and green.
</P>
<P>
   Gifaldi had the right idea. You'll benefit greatly from HDU
classes if you're working on a specific project to which your newly
learned home skills can be applied. The more specific the questions
you have, the more you'll gain.
</P>
<P>
   Project-deficient interlopers like me can benefit, too (beside
the doughnuts, of course). I now plan to install Pergo floors in my
faux-finished, accessory-filled bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   All I need is for my landlord to give me the OK. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
