<HEADLINE>
WHEN IS RETIREMENT FEASIBLE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. I am 49 and my wife is 47. Combined we earn about $110,000
a year. I am currently unemployed and no longer contributing to my
401(k), and there is no guarantee that my next employer will have
one. My wife has been contributing $1,040 a year, or 3 percent of
her salary, to her 401(k). I estimate that we will need $50,000
annually upon retirement. At what age would our financial resources
be sufficient to retire? What changes should be made in our
investment strategy?
</P>
<P>
   K.B., East Greenwich, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; A. It's almost impossible to make a sensible projection, based
upon two factors.
</P>
<P>
   One, of course, is the uncertainty about what you will be able
to save in the remaining years before retirement. The other is the
great uncertainty involved in projecting growth for your very
aggressive port- folio.
</P>
<P>
   If I just plug in the numbers and assume the 10 percent
long-term growth rate I normally apply to a diversified stock
portfolio, including only your wife's relatively minimal
contributions, you would have $1,127,963 at age 60 and $1,821,959
at age 65.
</P>
<P>
   To maintain a standard of living equivalent to $50,000 in
today's dollars, you would need $72,993 in 11 years, and $86,699
after 16.
</P>
<P>
   If you retired at age 60, such a nest egg could be relied upon
to provide your income stream, but without much left over to build
a significant hedge against inflation. The figures at age 65 would
be much more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, everything will be much improved once you get a
new job and resume saving, whether in a 401(k) or in other
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   But overall I am very uncomfortable with any projection, based
upon your particular investments. Your Janus Aspen Aggressive
Growth fund takes a very aggressive stance, holding the same kind
of stocks you have in your IRA account. These have provided some
wonderful rewards, such as the 124.3 percent return last year for
Janus Aspen.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, I tally a bit more than 54.4 percent of your
retirement assets in such holdings. If you stick with this, you're
likely to end up either a big winner or a big loser; obviously,
some of these issues are going to end up as the big victors in the
new economy, and just as obviously others are going to lose the
technological wars and fade away, taking their stock prices with
them.
</P>
<P>
   I would be much more comfortable if you limited the
technology-dominated segment of your retirement portfolio to about
30 percent, or $116,400, replacing the rest with more standard
retirement fodder _ a diversified portfolio made up of index funds
focusing on various market sectors, equity income funds, balanced
funds, and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, I'm also betting you won't, or won't until a market
jolt convinces you that you are indeed assuming a lot of risk.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a retiree, 83 years old. My wife is 75. We are
reasonably healthy and live an active life, budgeting about $60,000
a year for expenses. With the market past 11,000 I am scared stiff
to put my nest egg in stocks, although I know I should. We live on
Social Security and the income from our investments. I would like
to invest these funds to produce an offset for our expenses, but
find it hard to approach with a three- to five-year time horizon.
Do you have any suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   F.J., Rio Verde, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   A. You don't make it clear how much of your income Social
Security is providing, but whatever the level, I can say fairly
confidently there is no prudent way you can invest this $600,000 of
assets so that it will reliably produce the entire budgeted income
stream. Attempting that would involve either stocks or low-grade
bonds, and I agree with you about the current market.
</P>
<P>
   The best course would be to make some fairly minor moves,
designed to take your portfolio average from its current level,
which I estimate at about a 5.5 percent portfolio average, to a
little better than 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, I'd move about three-quarters of the money market
funds to investments such as your GNMA certificates and unit
investment trusts, where you could expect income levels in the
range of 6.5 percent. Leaving $100,000 in the money market accounts
for emergencies, that would boost the income to about $37,500.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the shortfall is between that $37,500 plus your Social
Security benefits, I'd simply withdraw the money from your
principal and not worry about it. You're right: If the market was
scary at 9,000, which I thought it was, it's terrifying at current
levels.
</P>
<P>
   This also isn't a good time for the bond markets, since it
appears that more rate increases are in the pipeline. But following
your current practice of outright ownership of bonds and unit
investment trusts, you can focus on the yield and not worry about
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I own some stock in Vanguard Windsor II. Within
the past year it has dropped about 30 percent. We contribute $200
per month to this fund. Our ages are 72 and 64. Also, our children,
ages 41 and 31, have the same fund, and contribute $100 a month.
Should we sell or hang on to this fund?
</P>
<P>
   D.S., Port Arthur, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, 1999 _ and the beginning of 2000 for that matter _
hasn't been a good time for shareholders of Windsor II, or most
other value-oriented funds. But it hasn't been that bad. For 1999,
the fund lost 5.8 percent, and it is off 6.01 percent for 2000 as
this is written.
</P>
<P>
   Has it suddenly become out of date? No, it's just operating as
it always has, in a conservative segment of the market, which is
pretty thoroughly out of fashion. If you look at its market
concentrations _ very heavily invested in utilities, energy stocks,
and durable manufacturers; very light on health and technology
stocks _ you'll understand why.
</P>
<P>
   It's a disciplined fund, with a low annual turnover rate of 31
percent, so it basically is sticking with the kind of issues that
have brought it to its very solid long-term record. Over a decade,
the fund has average annual returns of 13.80 percent, and 17.90
percent for five years. Even over three years, despite the last 13
months of losses, it can claim average returns of 9.98 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The only solace investors in Windsor II can take at this point
is that market fashions change, and betting on stocks such as
telephone companies, money-center banks, and oil companies is
likely to pay in the long run. Whether the so-called dot-com mania
that's been propelling the recent market will hold up is anybody's
guess, but with Windsor II you won't have to worry about it.
</P>
<P>
   Since you have been continuing to add to your Windsor II
position, I am presuming that you view this as a long-term
accumulation, designed to help you deal with inflation in your
later years, provide for emergencies, and become a part of your
estate. If that is correct, I suggest you hang in there with
Windsor II, and of course the suggestion would be the same for your
children.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
