<SLUG> BC-MARKET-LEFTOUTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATCHING UP WITH THE BULLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stock market news of the second blares onto Franklin Street
in front of the Boston Stock Exchange as eager investors gather
around at lunchtime. It's just another day in the life of the
nation's longest-ever bull market and economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Lai Chan, 53, who works in accounting at a bank down the street,
peers through the exchange's big picture window at TV monitors
flashing the latest data.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a small investor,'' says Chan, bundled up against the
wintry weather while spending part of his lunch break in front of
the exchange's street-level data wall. ``I have to see whether my
stock is up or down'' _ even though he knows he's in for the long
haul.
</P>
<P>
   From Main Street to Wall Street to Franklin Street, folks such
as Chan are feeling fortunate to be part of a bull market that
seems to have no end in sight, despite a mixed reaction last week
to the Federal Reserve's raising of interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   According to a new Federal Reserve survey on consumer finance,
though, more than 50 percent of US families have been on the
sidelines, with no stock holdings whatsoever, not even through
mutual funds or retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Is it too late for them to get into the market? And would even
those already in the market who are accustomed to double-digit
annual returns be able to stomach a double-digit drop?
</P>
<P>
   No one should be denied the right to be particular about where
they put their money. Some people are penny pinchers, with every
cent in certificates of deposit; others are gung-ho day traders,
turning over stock positions with a click of a mouse. But financial
advisers say experience and statistics show that long-term
ownership of stock is a critical way of building net worth, for
everything from retirement to paying for college educations for
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are your choices? You only have stocks, bonds, and cash.
Cash _ there's a place for it, but not for your long-term money or
your retirement money,'' said Deborah Maloy, a certified financial
planner whose Neiman-Maloy Financial Group of Wakefield, Mass.
``You need some stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Long-term, through ups and downs, stocks have averaged more than
10 percent return a year, while bonds have averaged about 5
percent, and certificates of deposit barely keep pace with
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Some people worry about losing money in the stock market and
keep everything in CDs, but they often forget to consider the risk
of losing buying power by failing to keep ahead of inflation,
financial advisers say.
</P>
<P>
   Their advice for those who have shied away from the market and
kept everything in certificates of deposit, or think they have too
little to get started:
</P>
<P>
   Take a deep breath and tiptoe into the market by investing as
little as $25 to $100 a month. And don't worry about whether the
market is going to crash the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time's a good time to invest,'' said Jonathan Pond, a
Boston-based financial adviser and commentator on both public radio
and public television.
</P>
<P>
   The key, he said, is to have a long-term horizon, to diversify,
and to invest systematically by, for example, having money
automatically deducted from a bank account and put into mutual
funds. This strategy _ buying into funds regularly, at a variety of
high and low prices _ is known as dollar-cost averaging.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may think that the train has left the station and you're
standing on the platform,'' Pond said. But ``one could have said
that seven years ago, five years ago, or last year.''
</P>
<P>
   And for those who have been on board the gravy train and think
it will continue full steam ahead forever, personal finance
specialists caution that occasional declines in the market are
inevitable. Don't sell in a panic, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear people saying they were very disappointed with their
portfolio last year; it made only 20 percent. That's a horrendous
expectation to keep up. Part of my job is lowering expectations,
making people aware of what can happen,'' said Maloy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember bad markets. It wasn't that long ago.''
</P>
<P>
   This month marks the longest economic expansion ever in US
history _ 107 months _ with the trough of the last recession way
back in March 1991, according to the National Bureau of Economic
Research, a Cambridge, Mass. nonprofit that tracks business cycles.
The current bullish market dates back even further.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are those such as Harvard professor of economics N.
Gregory Mankiw who remind people that the stock market has dropped
by as much as a third, sending the country into recession, as in
the late 1960s and early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people ask the question, `Are we ever going to see a
recession again?' _ I'm sure. When, I don't know,'' said Mankiw.
</P>
<P>
   And when people seek his advice, Mankiw tells them to ``buy a
diversified portfolio of stocks and bonds, something they'll feel
comfortable with for the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   Mankiw defines long term as 20 years and longer, while Maloy
suggests at least five years. Pond says at least a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Mankiw paraphrases billionaire Warren Buffett: ``The optimal
holding period is forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Mankiw tries to apply that buy-and-hold-forever strategy to his
own portfolio of individual stocks. He also has mutual funds and
inflation-adjusted US Treasury securities in his tax-deferred
retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Chan, who watched his stake in America Online drop in value, in
response to fears about the interest rate hike, said his long-term
investment horizon is at least 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a small investor, it's hard to own short-term,'' he said.
Chan is keeping his eye on other stocks to buy if the price is
right. He also holds mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   For the beginner with no large sum of money to plop down, stock
mutual funds with low minimums and monthly automatic investment
programs are a good way to ease into the market.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to use dollar-cost averaging, you can arrange to
have your mutual fund or brokerage firm automatically deduct a
specified amount of money from your savings or checking account and
invest it regularly. You buy more shares when the price is low and
fewer shares when the price is high, thus leading to a lower
average purchase price than if you bought everything at the top of
the market.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ``Spread your money around and you'll do quite
fine,'' Pond said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
