u i BC-BRITAIN-DOCTOR-2TAKES     02-07 1537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-DOCTOR-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DIABOLICAL CASE OF THE DEADLY DOCTOR 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HYDE, England _ John Shaw ran a one-man taxi business out of his
small apartment, using his Volvo to ferry the ladies of Hyde into
the town center, often to the office of a kindly general
practitioner named Dr. Harold Shipman.
</P>
<P>
   One day in January 1994, after one of his customers, 82-year-old
Joan Harding, unexpectedly died in Shipman's office, Shaw made a
list of other customers who had suddenly died after seeing the
doctor. As he stared at the list, Shaw came to a chilling
conclusion: Shipman was killing them.
</P>
<P>
   But for more than four years, Shaw shared his suspicions only
with his wife, who begged him not to go to the authorities. Kathy
Shaw told her husband he would be made a laughingstock, and perhaps
thrown in jail, if he sullied the reputation of the town's beloved
family doctor on the flimsiest of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw reluctantly agreed, kept his mouth shut, and over the next
four years, his list of dead customers ballooned to 24. His
business in this Manchester suburb was slowly being killed off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just a taxi driver,'' said Shaw, 64, a big, gentle man
with thick eyeglasses. ``Doctors are like gods.''
</P>
<P>
   Others more prominent and learned than Shaw, even some doctors,
harbored similar suspicions, but they, too, were slow to point a
finger.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 31 Shipman was convicted of murdering 15 female patients,
most of them elderly, by injecting them with pure heroin,
apparently for the thrill of it. After his conviction, prosecutors
said that they plan to charge Shipman with at least 23 more
murders, and police said they believe he killed more than 100
others. Some investigators say he killed hundreds over a medical
career that spanned 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   If the police are right, the 54-year-old Shipman, a
mild-mannered father of four, is the world's worst serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   The police describe Shipman as a cold, calculating murderer, but
he was known here as a warm, dedicated doctor. His unsolicited
house calls, during which he killed most of his victims, made him a
pillar of this old mill town of 35,000 just south of Manchester. He
was a throwback to the days of the family doctor whom everyone
knew, who was always on call, who never said no to a patient in
need.
</P>
<P>
   One of 10 residents in Hyde was a patient of Shipman's. There is
hardly a family here that does not count one or more of his victims
as a relative or close friend. When he arrived at the aptly named
Strangeways prison Monday night to begin his life sentence, two
guards had to be put on indefinite leave because Shipman is
suspected of killing their mother.
</P>
<P>
   The realization that one of the community's most valued and
trusted members was actually murdering its most vulnerable
residents is still sinking in. And while the authorities debate why
Shipman killed so many, the more disturbing question is how he was
able to get away with it for so long.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to reassure the public, the British government has
launched an investigation and has vowed to tighten the regulation
of doctors. But the real answers lie in the narrow streets and the
humble row houses of this gray town. Shipman hid behind his status
in a place where doctors and other authority figures, especially
men, are deferred to and seldom questioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hyde is a place where people inherently trust professionals,''
said Dr. Raj Patel, one of the doctors in a clinic across the
street from Shipman's who eventually alerted the authorities.
``It's a poor, working-class town. The people are lovely and very
warm and genuine and proud, but they were brought up not to
challenge authority, to know their place. As a doctor here, you're
treated like a minicelebrity. People wave to you on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   If Shipman exploited his place in a patriarchal society, and
used that position to kill women almost exclusively, it was perhaps
fitting that a group of women who dared to think the unthinkable,
and to assail the unassailable, did the most to bring him to
justice.
</P>
<P>
   But even after they alerted police to Shipman, his standing in
the community, and the fact that he had altered his victims'
medical records, threw investigators off his trail. He was only
caught because he got sloppy by forging the will of a woman whose
daughter was a lawyer savvy enough not to buy his explanations. It
was the only death of more than 130 that the police have
investigated in which profit was an obvious motive.
</P>
<P>
   Known by his middle name, Fred, Shipman grew up in a place not
very different from Hyde, in a housing project in Nottingham. The
son of a truck driver, he was smart enough to win a place at an
exam school and go on to university, a rare departure from career
paths that were largely determined by class. As a teenager, Shipman
watched his mother die slowly from lung cancer, her pain eased by
diamorphine, the prescription form of the pure heroin he would
later use to kill his patients.
</P>
<P>
   At 20, while in medical school, Shipman was forced to get
married after his 17-year-old girlfriend, Primrose, got pregnant.
But he was disciplined enough to finish his studies and become a
doctor. Soon after he joined his first practice, however, his
partners discovered that he was forging prescriptions to feed his
addiction to pethidine, an opiate.
</P>
<P>
   The British medical profession was, and many say still is, a
fraternity that protects its own. Shipman was allowed to plead
guilty, keep his license, and quietly move to another practice.
There was no mechanism to let patients know about his past.
</P>
<P>
   The police believe Shipman killed patients throughout his
career, part of what they think was a ``God complex'' _ he was
stimulated by the feeling of power. Most of his victims, like 70
percent of Britons, were cremated before burial, destroying the
evidence needed to trap him. Investigators believe it was not until
1992, when Shipman set up a solo practice, that he felt insulated
enough to begin killing patients in droves.
</P>
<P>
   His victims seemed to be picked for their vulnerability. Most
were elderly women of limited education, living alone on fixed
incomes, who gravitated to him because he was the town's only sole
practitioner, and who trusted him inherently. While most appeared
robust and healthy just before they died, few of their families
challenged Shipman's diagnoses of natural causes. Those who dared
to request an autopsy were talked or bullied out of it by Shipman,
who gave them gruesome details of what a post-mortem examination
entails.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you really want to dissect your mother?'' Shipman asked two
brothers as their mother sat lifeless in a nearby chair.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 15 other doctors in town, who admired Shipman's
unquestioned clinical skills, routinely examined the bodies of his
victims and, seeing nothing obvious to arouse their suspicions,
signed off on the certificates legally required for cremation. He
did the same for them, a you-scratch-my-back-I'll-scratch-yours
arrangement known as ``ash cash,'' because doctors collect a $65
fee for each case. If the discrepancy between the mortality rates
of their patients and Shipman's sometimes nagged them, Shipman's
peers reasoned that he had more elderly patients.
</P>
<P>
   It was not that Shipman never aroused suspicion. He did,
especially in recent years, when more and more of his patients died
suddenly. But he was able to deflect any detailed examination that
could have ended his killing spree by manipulating the deference
traditionally shown to doctors by their patients and their peers.
</P>
<P>
   His reputation as a conscientious doctor was earned. He was
widely admired for nursing terminally ill patients to the bitter
end. There is no suggestion he killed to relieve his patients of
suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the room where he first drew up the death list, Shaw
remained haunted by the thought he could have saved many of his
customers. But he voiced a conviction that no one would have taken
him seriously had he made his suspicions known years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``From where I'm sitting now I can see the homes of six women he
killed,'' Shaw said as he and his wife stared out their window and
Dinky, the orphaned cat he took in when Harding died, lounged at
his feet. ``They weren't just my customers. They were our
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Bambroffe, an undertaker at her father's funeral parlor,
was the first to break the silence in 1997. She had noticed that
she was being called to the homes of Shipman's patients far more
often than to those of any other doctor. Even though Shipman was
her doctor, too, and had never displayed anything but
professionalism, something gnawed at her.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the numbers, she was bothered by the similarity of the
bodies. All were women. All were dressed, usually seated in a
chair. Her experience had been that when elderly women died at
home, they were usually in bed.
</P>
<P>
   But there was something else that ate at Bambroffe: All of the
dead women had been visited by Shipman on the day they died. In
fact, Shipman said most of the women were dead when he arrived.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 1343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9157 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-DOCTOR-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     02-07 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-DOCTOR-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 HYDE, England: ... he arrived.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `It just didn't add up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She told her father, Alan Massey, who was so disturbed that he
went to Shipman's office and gingerly confronted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I was concerned,'' Massey recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Shipman calmly replied that there was nothing to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody can inspect this book,'' he said, showing Massey the
records he kept of his patients who died.
</P>
<P>
   Massey wanted to believe him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I trusted this man with my family,'' the undertaker said.
</P>
<P>
   But the calls to collect the bodies kept coming, and Debbie
Bambroffe's suspicions only grew. In February 1998, Shipman asked
Dr. Susan Booth, who worked at a practice across the street, to
examine the body of one of his patients at Massey's funeral home
and sign off on a cremation.
</P>
<P>
   Bambroffe took Booth aside and shared her suspicions. Booth
hurried back to her offices, which she shares with four other
doctors. They pulled their records and compared the mortality rate
of their 9,800 patients and Shipman's 3,500 patients. Patel, one of
the partners, remembers feeling flushed when they realized that 41
of Shipman's patients had died suddenly at home in 1997, compared
to just 14 of theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``His patients were dying at a rate three times our patients,''
Patel said. Still, he said, such a small statistical pool meant
little. But while Patel and the others saw logical explanations,
their newest partner, Linda Reynolds, did not.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds also was less inclined to believe that doctors were
above reproach. Before coming to Hyde, she worked in a practice
where the most senior, respected physician had been convicted of
molesting patients.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors gathered at a pub outside town to decide what to do.
Reynolds gradually wore them down, convincing them they had to take
their suspicions to someone in authority. With their blessing, she
called the local coroner, John Pollard.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds risked her own career by essentially accusing a peer of
murder, but Pollard was alarmed by what she told him and alerted
police. The initial investigation was discreet, and many now
criticize it as only cursory. Neither Shipman nor the relatives of
the dead were questioned. After reviewing records that turned out
to be bogus, police dropped the inquiry, saying there was not
enough evidence to go further.
</P>
<P>
   Then, three months and three dead patients later, Angela
Woodruff walked into a police station and said, ``I think my
mother's doctor killed her.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodruff, a lawyer, had done her own investigation after
learning that her 81-year-old mother, Kathleen Grundy, had altered
her will just before she died in June 1998. The new will, which
left her mother's 300-year-old stone cottage and entire estate of
$600,000 to Shipman, had a signature that was clearly not her
mother's. Woodruff tracked down two people who had signed the will
as witnesses. They said their signatures had been forged.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a credible complainant, police got a court order to
exhume Grundy's body. After traces of diamorphine showed up in
Grundy's remains, more exhumations followed, and Shipman was
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   While many people in Hyde take some solace from Shipman's
conviction, there is a lingering bitterness, not least because
residents realize their town will always be associated with infamy.
For 20 years, the area has been stigmatized for being home to two
child killers known as the Moors Murderers. But Shipman has now
become England's, if not the world's, most diabolical killer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because of a law that is a legacy of the status afforded
doctors, Shipman kept drawing his paycheck until Friday. It will be
several weeks before he is struck off the rolls as a physician.
While awaiting trial, he collected more than $160,000 in
taxpayer-funded salary.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, the 49-year-old doctor who was instrumental in
exposing Shipman, was diagnosed with terminal cancer last year and
has little time to live.
</P>
<P>
   Across this town, dozens of other families are haunted by
uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Philomena Bardsley is convinced that Shipman murdered her
71-year-old mother, Alice Kitchen, and is determined that he stand
trial. She remembers how Shipman patronizingly dismissed her
insistence that her mother could not have died from a heart
condition for which she had never been diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Denis Maher, the 59-year-old pastor at St. Paul's
Church, is haunted, too. Five of his parishioners were among the 15
women Shipman was convicted of killing. He stood by their graves
during the exhumations, praying for both the dead and himself.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens more of his parishioners are among the suspected victims.
Shipman's conviction has triggered an outpouring. Every day last
week, someone called Maher or stopped him on the street. One woman
said Shipman had found her father dead four years ago, then
screamed at her when she insisted her father was healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at his desk, Maher wrote a homily he planned to deliver
at Mass. It was a sermon about forgiveness. But even Maher, a man
of great faith, was having trouble following his own advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord never forgives sin, but He forgives the sinner,''
Maher said in a soft brogue that betrays his native Tipperary. ``I
can't forgive Shipman until he accepts responsibility and shows
some remorse.''
</P>
<P>
   Maher says we will never know how many people Shipman murdered.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know something,'' the priest said, ``I don't think Shipman
even knows. He killed so many he would have lost count.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
