<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIANITY'S HOLY LAND CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ An educational campaign aimed at alerting Americans
that indigenous Christians are in danger of disappearing from the
land where Christianity began is under way at churches in
Washington and Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The effort is being mounted by the Holy Land Christian
Ecumenical Foundation, a Washington-based group that seeks to
highlight, as it puts it, ``the real possiblity that Christians are
becoming extinct in the Holy Land.''
</P>
<P>
   The group invited Palestinian Catholic priests to speak and
celebrate Mass in local parishes Sunday as it launched its ``Church
to Church'' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In the months ahead, the clerics will address other Catholic and
Protestant churches across the United States to draw attention to a
quiet exodus of Palestinian Christians in recent decades.
</P>
<P>
   The diminishing Christian presence is also expected to be
addressed by Pope John Paul II on a historic pilgrimage in March,
when he will retrace the path of Jesus's life through Jordan,
Jerusalem, Bethlehem, and Nazareth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many Americans who do not even realize that there
are Palestinians who are Christian,'' said the Rev. Emil Salayta,
director of educational services for the Jerusalem Latin
Patriarchate, who spoke at several Maryland churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we have to explain that our Christian community, which
traces its roots back to the time of Jesus 2,000 years ago, is now
in jeopardy,'' said Salayta in a telephone interview from Maryland.
``We hope American Christians will see how important it is to
maintain a Christian presence in the land where the faith began.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation is headed by American and Palestinian church
leaders, as well as Donald Kruse, a former political officer at the
US consulate in Jerusalem. According to Salayta and foundation
literature, data collected from local parishes by the Vatican
indicate that in the early 1900s Christians accounted for
approximately 20 percent of the population of what is today Israel,
the West Bank, and Gaza, although census data gathered by the
British in the first half of the century indicates the figure was
much lower.
</P>
<P>
   The group's literature asserts, and Israeli census data
confirms, that the Christian population in that area is now less
than 2 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the turmoil of 50 years of Arab-Israeli conflict,
Palestinian, or Arab, Christians have steadily emigrated, most
seeking better economic opportunity in the United States, South
America, and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Complex economic, political, and social forces have pushed many
educated and talented young Christians to leave, said Salayta.
There are just 10,000 Christians living today in the West Bank city
of Ramallah, he said, although there are 70,000 Ramallah Christians
in the American Ramallah Federation, a social organization for
Palestinian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Many academics, including Karen Armstrong in her 1996 book,
``Jerusalem: One City, Three Faiths,'' support the contention that
the Christian presence was roughly 20 percent in the early 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   However, that figure is disputed. A 1922 British census put the
Christian population at about 11 percent, notes a Boston-based
media watchdog, CAMERA, which focuses on issues involving Israel.
The census was taken during the British mandate that governed
Palestine following World War I.
</P>
<P>
   A number of church officials insist that the Christian
percentage of the population has declined dramatically since the
early 1900s, the result of emigration by Palestinian Christians,
waves of Jewish immigration to Israel since 1948, and the surging
birthrate of Palestinian Muslims, compounded by the relatively low
birthrate of Palestinian Christians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
