<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9163 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-RECORD-BOS &LR;      02-07 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-RECORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LIBERAL' TRAG FOR MCCAIN AT ODDS WITH HIS RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ As George W. Bush struggled to regain his campaign
footing this week, a message appeared to rise from the ashes of New
Hampshire: John S. McCain won the primary because of his liberal
views on taxes, his shared ideas with Al Gore, his tactic of
campaigning ``from the left.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor was careful not to question McCain's
Republican credentials outright. But by slipping ``liberal'' into
his remarks and in tying his opponent's name to the Clinton
administration, Bush took a tack that has prompted an
eyebrow-raising question on Capitol Hill: If McCain is liberal, who
would qualify as conservative?
</P>
<P>
   Thus far in his campaign, McCain has taken a far more modest
stance than the Texas governor on tax cuts, with a plan half the
size of Bush's proposal. The Arizona senator has shied away from
religious rhetoric. Most notably, he has stuck to his longstanding
demand for an overhaul of the way political campaigns are financed,
an idea anathema to the Republican fund-raisers and their
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   But with two glaring exceptions, campaign finance and his
outspoken opposition to tobacco interests, many familiar with
McCain's voting record view him as a mainstream conservative who
rarely wavers from the party line on issues ranging from tax cuts
to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, he voted with Republicans 93 percent of the time,
according to an independent voting study. Despite his reputation as
a maverick, McCain has managed, on some government spending issues,
to ``outconservative just about everybody,'' said Derrick Max,
political director of the libertarian Cato Institute.
</P>
<P>
   He voted to confirm two conservative Supreme Court justices,
Robert Bork and Clarence Thomas. He sponsored legislation banning
family-planning clinics from discussing abortion options. He voted
against Henry Foster for surgeon general in 1995, after disclosures
that Foster had performed abortions. When the 1996
telecommunications bill to deregulate the industry was on the
floor, McCain was the only Republican to vote against it, because,
he said, it was too weak. Last year, he voted for the $792 billion
Republican tax package. He also opposed last year's Democratic plan
to raise the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I served with John McCain for four years in the House of
Representatives, and the one thing he's never been accused of,
before this, is being a liberal,'' said Guy V. Molinari, Staten
Island Borough president and the head of McCain's campaign in New
York. ``This man is a conservative. Frankly, what I think we're
seeing is a laughable example of desperation on the part of the
Bush campaign. The Bush campaign is really coming apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Reed, a Republican strategist who ran the 1996 Dole
campaign and who is not affiliated with any candidate this year,
agreed. ``At the end of the day, you have to admit McCain is a
conservative Republican,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a group of old, fat, white conservatives saying
McCain's not a conservative. To the McCain campaign, that's a good
thing,'' Reed said. ``That's what they're trying to show: that
there will be change.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, McCain has positioned himself in a way that makes it
difficult for the Bush campaign to pigeonhole him. Even the tax-cut
issue is tricky. While McCain's $237 billion, five-year tax cut
proposal is far smaller than the $483 billion plan set forth by
Bush, the Arizona Republican has emphasized another fiscal priority
dear to many conservatives: paying down the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are several high-profile issues on which McCain has
been out of step with his party, and which support the message of
the Bush campaign. One example is McCain's vote against a 1997
Republican-sponsored proposal to ban research that uses fetal
tissue. He also voted in favor of legislation to increase the
tobacco sales taxes, a vote that has come under fire in South
Carolina in advertisements sponsored by the National Smokers
Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   And there is one McCain policy that nearly all Republicans
oppose: campaign finance reform, which his Senate colleagues have
fought him on for years. Bush has made the most of the issue,
mentioning McCain and Gore in the same breath during news
conferences. And his campaign is clearly poised to emphasize the
issue in South Carolina, where Bush advisers believe their
argument, that McCain's brand of campaign finance reform would harm
the Republican Party and give power to labor unions, will appeal to
traditional conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain has taken the Clinton-Gore position on campaign
finance reform,'' said former South Carolina governor David
Beasley, while campaiging with Bush. ``We've let him get away with
a lot. He's to the left. He speaks to the left.''
</P>
<P>
   Such talk, however, is offensive to many Democrats, who say
McCain has never been aligned even with the block of Senate
Republicans who sometimes vote with Democrats and are consistently
moderate on issues such as abortion rights and health care.
``There's nobody on our side of the fence who would characterize
him as a liberal,'' said Senator John F. Kerry. ``That's trash
talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides said they are not trying to cast McCain as a liberal,
but are simply noting that he espouses views identical to, if not
more liberal than, those of the Clinton administration. Especially
when it comes to taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no suggestion that John McCain is a liberal,'' said
Ari Fleischer, a Bush spokesman. ``On the contrary, John McCain is
a Republican who agrees with Al Gore and Bill Clinton too much. . .
. When you consider that President Clinton cuts taxes by more than
John McCain, that's not exactly the Republican way of getting
things done.''
</P>
<P>
   But even on taxes, McCain aides say his record adds credibility
to his claim as a conservative.
</P>
<P>
   The National Taxpayers Union, one of the most conservative
special-interest groups in Washington, gave McCain a 73 percent
approval rating for his Senate votes on taxes in 1998, 12 points
higher than the rating for Senate Republican leader Trent Lott, and
64 points higher than that of Senator Edward M. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights
Action League, an abortion-rights group, approved McCain's votes
just 10 percent of the time. NARAL also says McCain has voted 82
out of 86 times to restrict abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   As for the AFL-CIO, it gave McCain a rating of 8 in 1998. Two
years later, he scored a zero.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
