<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORING HIS WAY TO INFAMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a restaurant, I found myself seated next to a table occupied
by a world-class bore.
</P>
<P>
   Now I know bores, and I have met bores, and I have been
tormented by scores of bores in my time, but this guy won the
prize.
</P>
<P>
   His conversation was beyond boring. It was stupefying. And it
was loud. I didn't have to strain to overhear a word. Fully half
the people in the restaurant were subjected to his monologue. It
was like some kind of awful floor show. Strangers exchanged
sympathetic glances, smiled ruefully at one another.
</P>
<P>
   The bore's two female victims were seated across the table from
him. Occasionally, one or the other would attempt to say something,
but the bore would cut her off rudely after a word or two and
yammer on about himself, launching into another pompous soliloquy
with an opening line like, ``Another thing I'm very good at is . .
.'' or ``The first year I'll only make 40 percent of a million
dollars, but that's a down payment on a pretty nice house . . .''
or ``I could sit here and become very, very rich doing the same
thing, but I need a challenge and I think the synergy I feel at
General Mills . . .''
</P>
<P>
   From what I could gather, which was a lot more than I wanted to
gather, all the blathering came down to whether he should take a
job selling Cheerios. As one who tries to remember to eat her
oatmeal every morning, I would never underestimate the importance
of breakfast foods. But let's be honest, the fate of the universe
doesn't hinge on Cheerios sales, although, listening to this guy
talk, I might have thought otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   I sat there asking myself the same question I always ask in
these situations: Does this person have any idea how boring he is?
</P>
<P>
   Of course he doesn't. They never do. Even when people tell bores
straight out that they're boring, they refuse to believe it. How
many times have commentators pointed out that Al Gore is boring?
And yet he goes right on being boring. Why?
</P>
<P>
   There ought to be a Bores Anonymous. But since most bores are in
denial, who would attend the meetings? Although I bet if somebody
launched Bore-Anon, a self-help group for the friends and loved
ones of bores, the sessions would be jammed.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has the capacity to bore. At some point, each of us
bores somebody. If we're lucky enough to have even a shred of
self-awareness, we learn from our mistakes and try not to bore
again. The dyed-in-the-wool bore isn't able to see that he's
boring. He thinks he's fascinating. Why would he want to change?
</P>
<P>
   A psychotherapist I know tells of treating an extremely boring
patient, a man so boring that the therapist kept falling asleep
during their sessions. Eventually, there was a breakthrough. The
patient came to realize that he had developed a boring style as a
way of discouraging intimacy. The ploy had worked perfectly. He'd
never had any success with relationships, which was one of the
problems that had brought him to the therapist in the first place.
Once he understood why he was boring, he was able to change his
behavior and presumably went on to live a full life as that rarest
of creatures, a reformed bore.
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible that guy in the restaurant was trying to avoid
intimacy by boring on about himself? Or was he just an
old-fashioned bore?
</P>
<P>
   Thinking about him reminds me of that recently published study
about competence, in which researchers concluded that most
incompetent people have no idea they're incompetent and are, in
fact, more confident of their abilities than people who do things
well. There may be something similar at work when it comes to
bores. Perhaps scientists will apply themselves to the question, if
they can stand to do the research.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 1351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
