<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SUIT: DRESS-UP CAN STILL BE CASUAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Men's khakis pants, which revolutionized the dress code of
corporate America in the 1990s, are headed for retirement this fall
_ to be replaced by the most unlikely of garments: the business
suit.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of fashion industry shows this week and last in
New York and in Milan last month, the suit is reemerging as a hip
option for men.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at some of the top names _ Prada, Gucci, and
Dolce &AMP; Gabbana _ they all filled their runways with suits,'' says
Dan McCampbell, men's fashion director at Saks Fifth Avenue. ``You
could have counted the suits (shown) last spring on one hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Do these shows signal the end of ``business casual,'' just when
such venerable companies as Boston law firm Hale and Dorr are no
longer requiring their attorneys to wear suits?
</P>
<P>
   Relax. Most of the suits being presented aren't uptight. A new
category of suit _ dressy casual _ is making its move as the new
century unfolds. Created for work and play, these suits are
tailored but have modern design elements: no upper chest pockets,
flat-front slim trousers, hidden jacket buttons, no jacket linings,
smaller lapels.
</P>
<P>
   Fabrics are in colors such as olive green, and pinstripes are
made of subtle reflective materials or in colors such as berry.
Some fabrics have stretch material in their weaves for comfort. And
many of the suits are presented with no ties, just a shirt with an
open collar.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a brand-new kind of feeling'' in menswear, says Alan
Bilzerian, owner of self-named boutiques in Boston. ``It's a mood
change. Society is now transforming. Everybody looks way too
casual. The suit is the thing that men have always been able to
rely on for business, going out at night, traveling.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, fashion insiders say men are hungry for more elegance in
their wardrobes. While no one is advocating a return to the
buttoned-down stiffness of yesteryear, the dress-down casual look
is unacceptable to some.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are coming up on 10 years of casualization. Khakis and
cargoes are not happening,'' says Tom Julian, a fashion trend
analyst for New York ad agency Fallon McElligott. ``Designers are
reinterpreting the suit for a new audience and new lifestyles. What
is the modern suit? I think the idea is that individualism (instead
of uniformity) is now required.''
</P>
<P>
   Says designer Ron Chereskin, who unveiled his collection
Thursday, ``My whole show is definitely casual dressy. I think it's
a tremendous movement right now.'' Chereskin presented about 10
``non-matching suits'' _ essentially a group of sports coats paired
with pants of similar colors. ``The whole idea is to get much more
out of your wardrobe.''
</P>
<P>
   From a cultural perspective, fashion analysts contend that the
new look signals that men are freer to express their feelings in
society. ``When you wear a suit and tie, all your feelings are kept
inside. You have self-restraint,'' says Ruth P. Rubinstein,
associate professor of sociology at the Fashion Institute of
Technology in New York and author of ``Dress Codes: Meanings and
Messages in American Culture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These new fashions are saying, `No, men can express their
feelings,' . . . `I don't take life so seriously.' The suit is less
an image of authority and self-denial,'' she said. ``The use of
color (or hidden buttons or funky pinstripes) enriches you and
makes you feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Next fall, consumers can expect suits of every style. Designer
Joseph Abboud presented 40 suits on Saturday with such elements as
unlined jackets, small cargo pockets on the pants, and no shoulder
padding. Paul La Fontaine, design director for Claiborne Menswear,
sent 10 suits down the runway last Thursday with, among other
things, hidden buttons and pocket zippers, flat-front pants,
stretch fabrics, and fabrics in colors such as reddish brown and
olive green.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, these won't be acceptable in every workplace and may
not appeal to all ages. ``It's a little ahead of the curve right
now,'' says Debra Greenberg, president of retailer Louis Boston.
``The movement of men (in fashion) is very slow. It took them all
this time to get the casual idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she says, there is an entire generation of men under 35
intrigued by the idea of a suit. ``It's a novelty to them. They
truly have grown up without (formal) clothing as we know it. We're
selling suits to young computer guys who want to look like they've
made it. . . . It's going to be cheeky to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Lou Andre, president of wardrobe management company
Organization by Design, says the business-casual movement has
actually prepared men to be more open to the dressy-casual suit.
``Almost every single man has a business-casual day so they're in
the stores, they're looking, they're thinking,'' she says.
``They've been coached and educated through the media and their
employer that there is room for more than two looks (work and
non-work) in their closet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If designers can translate the fantasy looks of the runway
into a reality at the store level, they have a huge opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   But will everyday men, many of whom have become quite
comfortable in khakis, embrace these new suits?
</P>
<P>
   John McGee, the owner of Mamma Maria restaurant in Boston's
North End, thinks so. ``It's an easy way to get dressed,'' says
McGee, 40. ``The whole crisis of the dress-down day is that no one
knows what to do, other than throw on khaki pants. This is a
one-stop relaxed way to dress. You don't have to wear it with ties.
You can wear it with an open neck or a turtleneck.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Jeffry Pond, a Boston architect, ``I enjoy dressing up to
go to the theater or out to dinner. I was brought up that way. I
can't imagine meeting with lawyers and bankers without wearing a
suit. I know things are much more casual than they used to be but I
think society could use a little bit of that formality. We like to
believe we're all friends and chummy but we aren't really.
Politeness and courtesy are all about making our interactions work.
Formality in dress is a part of that as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Pond, 54, steers clear of traditional suits in navy and
charcoal. ``I don't want to have that much of a uniform on. I
prefer to feel that the suit I have on is a little bit out of the
ordinary.'' Currently, his wardrobe includes a green-brown suit and
a bright tomato-red number. ``It's not a usual color,'' he says.
``That's what gets me excited.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 1353EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
