<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9166 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIES-DICAPRIO-BOS &LR;      02-07 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-DICAPRIO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DICAPRIO TAKES THE PLUNGE INTO HIS FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``The Beach,'' Leonardo DiCaprio drinks snake blood, cusses
like Tony Soprano, smokes funny cigarettes, and is generally the
kind of guy who would sucker-punch that sissified Jack Dawson for
all his Dudley Do-Right chivalry and woo-woo ``King of the World''
nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   Toto, I don't think we're on ``Titanic'' anymore.
</P>
<P>
   It was, of course, that 1997 blockbuster that catapulted
DiCaprio from an Oscar-nominated up-and-comer into Hollywood's
hottest young actor. Playing an old-fashioned romantic hero, he was
a boyish, golden-haired Rhett Butler for a new generation of
teenage girls whose repeated viewings of the film propelled it to a
record-shattering $1.86 billion worldwide gross. Faster than you
could say ``My Heart Will Go On,'' DiCaprio became a tabloid fave
and paparazzi magnet, with his face as the wallpaper of choice in
girls' bedrooms from Boston to Bangkok. It was a tremendous boost
for DiCaprio, then 23, but it also sharply divided his career into
``before'' and ``after,'' with everything since ``Titanic''
receiving, perhaps unfairly, a harsh and relentless scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   The ``after'' portion of DiCaprio's professional life begins in
earnest this Friday, with ``The Beach.'' Although he has appeared
in two films since ``Titanic'' _ ``The Man in the Iron Mask'' and
Woody Allen's ``Celebrity'' were both released in 1998 _ ``The
Beach'' was the first project he signed on to during those feverish
months when it seemed every director and producer in Hollywood was
offering DiCaprio the world plus points.
</P>
<P>
   And ``The Beach'' is a far different film from ``Titanic,'' with
DiCaprio playing an often selfish, unsympathetic character _ which
has some already wondering if the actor hasn't strayed too far from
the kind of role that shot his career into the stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The superstar mentality is you're a superstar forever; the
reality is it ain't so,'' said Martin Grove, movie analyst for The
Hollywood Reporter. ``His superstardom is based on the success of a
single film which scored at the box office not completely because
of him, but because of the totality of what it was. He needs to
ensure his longstanding success by doing more films along the lines
of what his fans want to see.'' Whether ``The Beach'' falls into
that category remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Alex Garland's 1997 novel, ``The Beach'' stars DiCaprio
as Richard, a young and restless American looking for excitement
and danger in Bangkok. In his fleabag hotel, he meets Daffy (Robert
Carlyle), who gives him a hand-drawn map to an island paradise.
Richard shares the map with two French friends, and off they go in
search of freedom, adventure, and lots of marijuana, which
supposedly covers the island. Of course, once Richard and his pals
get there, they learn that paradise isn't everything it's cracked
up to be.
</P>
<P>
   It's like ``Lord of The Flies,'' with smatterings of
``Apocalypse Now'' _ hardly the sort of movie fare that makes
teenage hearts go pitty-pat, even though DiCaprio has love scenes.
But the $50 million film is far more reminiscent of the quirky
projects DiCaprio, 25, used to favor before he was lured to the
ocean by ``Titanic'' director James Cameron's siren song. (Or was
it Celine Dion's?)
</P>
<P>
   Before ``Titanic,'' DiCaprio was shaping up as one of
Hollywood's more interesting actors, or at least one willing to
take chances. He first caught critics' eyes with ``This Boy's
Life,'' a 1993 adaptation of the Tobias Wolff memoir. Only 19,
DiCaprio more than held his own with Robert DeNiro and Ellen Barkin
as a teenager adjusting to, among other things, his mother's
marriage to an abusive man. The movie wasn't a hit, but DiCaprio
emerged as someone to keep an eye on.
</P>
<P>
   What gifts ``This Boy's Life'' implied blossomed a year later in
``What's Eating Gilbert Grape.'' DiCaprio played Arnie, the
mentally retarded younger brother of the title character, played by
Johnny Depp. The film was a wonderful drama about small-town life,
but it was DiCaprio's performance that got people talking. Without
gimmickry or hamminess, DiCaprio completely disappeared into Arnie,
inhabiting the character from the inside out. The role earned
DiCaprio the best reviews of his career, as well as Academy Award
and Golden Globe nominations.
</P>
<P>
   He plunged into other unconventional roles. In ``Basketball
Diaries,'' he starred as Jim Carroll, a playground hoop hero-turned
smack-addled author. In ``Total Eclipse,'' he was gay French poet
Arthur Rimbaud. Both films were mediocre, and both flopped at the
box office (though ``Total Eclipse'' became something of a must-see
among Leophiles, since DiCaprio briefly appears nude). Yet they
showed DiCaprio as an actor willing to steer clear of vapid
romantic dramas and teen sex comedies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, returning to the dark and offbeat ``The Beach'' may not
be the best thing for DiCaprio's career momentum, Grove said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing the quirky, small films is nice, but that sort of thing
comes either early in your career or later in your career,'' Grove
said. ``In the middle of your career, you need to satisfy your core
base of fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that DiCaprio himself hasn't considered this. He just hopes
his fans will allow him to play characters other than Jack Dawson.
DiCaprio recently told MTV's Chris Connelly ``I think it would be
underestimating them as an audience and their intelligence to not
think that an actor's not going to take different types of roles. .
. . I think I'd be underestimating them if I were to go do the same
thing over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always known what I wanted to do as an actor, and I
wanted to take chances, and that's all. That's all I really wanted
to do,'' he said. `` `Titanic' was something that in its own right
was a chance. It was something that I'd never done before, and it
was trying to do something different, and it was experimenting in a
lot of ways. And it's not to say that I won't try something like
that again, I don't know. But that was much more different than
what I'm doing now.''
</P>
<P>
   While that may be fine and good for DiCaprio, the filmmakers
weren't taking any chances. They tweaked the romantic side of
DiCaprio's character, which was far less prevalent in Garland's
book. According to an article in Variety, that's not all bigwigs at
20th Century Fox, the film's distributor, have done to help the
film. Adopting a less-is-more strategy, the studio scaled back on
prerelease hype, perhaps in hopes of deflating expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But it may already be too late. Mention DiCaprio, and hype comes
whether anyone invites it or not. While no one expects ``The
Beach'' to hit the whopping numbers of ``Titanic,'' anything less
than a No. 1 debut next weekend will be considered a failure, no
matter how much the studio tries to spin it. For better or worse,
DiCaprio is the film's brand name, and for the first time in a
still-evolving career, he's expected to ``open'' a film on the
strength of that name. Now, after two years away from the screen,
DiCaprio may have his greatest career challenge yet in trying to
prove he's still king of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're really serious about long-term superstar status, you
must do what your fans want to see you do. That's been the story of
Hollywood since the very beginning of movies,'' Grove said. ``Give
the fans what they want, the fans will be back. Do something
different, and they may start watching somebody else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
