<HEADLINE>
RANKINGS SHOWN TO SWAY COLLEGE CHOICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's ranking season again, when colleges across the country plow
through foot-high piles of surveys seeking data _ from SAT scores
of incoming freshmen to donation rates of alumni _ to help
determine the popularly published pecking order of higher
education.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges that sink lower on the list will curse the rankings;
those that rise will boast. All along, though, most every college
will insist that rankings don't matter.
</P>
<P>
   But new evidence shows they do, hurting or helping a school's
ability to attract the best students and even determining the cost
of tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Even a small slip on the rungs of the US News &AMP; World Report
rankings of major colleges and universities may mean a school
becomes less selective and must offer more financial aid simply to
fill its freshman class. Fewer applicants tend to accept offers of
admission, and those who do will have lower SAT scores than the
previous class.
</P>
<P>
   And chances are, according to one study, that once a school
begins to slide, it continues to do so because the magazine then
weighs the school's ability to attract the best students and the
quality of those students in deciding the next year's rankings. A
ranking, in other words, doesn't just grade a school for quality,
it helps determine what ranking that school might get the following
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a vicious circle,'' said James Monks, an economist with
the Consortium on Financing Higher Education, who coauthored a
study on the effect of the US News &AMP; World Report rankings for 30
elite schools over 11 years. ``If it's not surprising that students
would be more likely to choose an institution that's doing better
in the rankings, why would they not respond the other way, and be
less likely to choose a school that's doing worse?''
</P>
<P>
   The study only confirms what colleges are loath to admit.
</P>
<P>
   Monks and Cornell University economist Ronald Ehrenberg looked
at the performance of some of the highest-ranked schools in the US
News rankings, the granddaddy of a series of rankings put out by
magazines and guidebooks. All the schools belong to the consortium,
which includes smaller liberal arts colleges such as Amherst and
Trinity as well as large research schools such as Yale and Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the shifts in rank are dramatic: Bryn Mawr, in the most
extreme case, slipped from fifth in 1990 to 23d in 1991; Cornell
bounced from 14th to sixth to 11th between 1987 and 1999; this
year, the California Institute of Technology jumped from ninth to
first place among national universities.
</P>
<P>
   It might seem obvious that a school that ranks higher will
attract more students. Cornell, for example, increased its yield _
college parlance for the percentage of applicants who accept
admissions offers _ from 46.6 to 49.2 as it rose from 14th to sixth
in the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   What surprised the researchers, though, was how a decline in
rankings could make it harder for a school to lure students.
</P>
<P>
   On average, for every five points a school slips, it admits 2
percent more applicants _ becoming less selective. But the drop in
rank also means a smaller percentage of applicants will accept
admission offers: Every six-point decline in ranking means a 1
percent drop in yield.
</P>
<P>
   A school that fell from sixth place to 10th sees its average SAT
scores drop 5.5 percent, the study found. And schools that drop
also have to offer more financial aid to attract students. For
every 10 points a school falls in the rankings, it ends up getting
4 percent less tuition after financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps understandably, the study also found that schools can
increase their yield with an increase in endowment. Every $100,000
increase in endowment means the school can offer 4 percent more in
grant aid.
</P>
<P>
   Richer schools essentially can buy their way to higher yields.
But poorer schools that slip in the rankings may not have the
option of offering more aid. And because higher-ranked schools have
to give less financial aid, Monks said, he suspects that they end
up getting more affluent students because they can afford to go
somewhere that doesn't give them as much money.
</P>
<P>
   However, US News, which is in its 17th year of compiling the
rankings, says the effects the study found are so small as to be
insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Changes of that sort are just as likely to be associated with
the success of their varsity football team,'' said Peter Cary,
special projects editor for the magazine. ``I wouldn't be surprised
if the schools see that movement year in and year out regardless of
how US News ranks them.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey also questions how US News determines rank.
</P>
<P>
   The methodology changes periodically. When the magazine started
``Best Colleges,'' rankings were based on reputation alone (the
University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign was number one ). Now US
News factors in a range of other data, including yield, how many
applicants are accepted, per-student spending, and the number of
full-time faculty.
</P>
<P>
   Given how much some schools bounce from year to year, Monks and
Ehrenberg say, the method is flawed; it's simply not possible that
one school becomes that much worse or better. Colleges chime in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is, it's the rankings that change more
than the institution,'' said Lorna Miles Whalen, dean of enrollment
and admissions at Johns Hopkins University, which rose in rank from
14th to seventh this year. ``It's not really anything we did.''
</P>
<P>
   That hardly means schools don't pay attention to the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are rankings aware,'' Miles Whalen added. ``We think about
the implication of actions on our rankings; we're as vulnerable to
moving forwards as backwards.''
</P>
<P>
   As colleges gather the data they will submit to US News and
other ranking surveys, they try to figure out how they can
calculate their numbers to best increase their status.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell used to count anyone who ever attended the school as
``alumni.'' Recently, though, it began excluding anyone who did not
graduate because that increased the percentage of alumni who donate
to the school.
</P>
<P>
   At Hopkins, administrators quibble over whether their
student-faculty ratio is 9 to 1, 8.7 to 1, or 9.2 to 1, as if the
smallest change would make that much difference in the ranking.
</P>
<P>
   And at Connecticut College, President Claire Gaudiani has said
that she sets targets for the school based on what will help in the
rankings. ``It's really unfortunate, because university resources
could be better used educating students, rather than being devoted
to working the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say the things the magazine weighs have little to do with
measuring how good a school is. In fact, college presidents
complain that the things they do to become better can hurt them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pride ourselves on doing more with less, but every time we
do something more efficiently, our rankings go down,'' said Stephen
Lewis, president of Carleton College in Minnesota, which generally
falls among the top 10 for best liberal arts colleges. ``What
bothers me is the appearance of being scientific and quantitative,
when they are not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
