<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9168 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-QUIZ-CULTURE-BOS &LR;      02-07 1737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUIZ-CULTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GAME SHOWS SAY SOMETHING ABOUT OUR INTELLIGENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Incudes sample questions text table; a and l coding)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the mid-1950s, at the height of Egghead Chic, a contestant on
a popular network quiz show won $32,000 by correctly answering a
two-part question about characters in the Sherlock Holmes stories.
The answer had 14 separate components. No multiple choice, no
audience ``lifelines.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' ABC's current prime-time
hit, a contestant recently won $32,000 by answering the question,
``Which of the following months has no federal holiday?'' There
were four choices listed, further reducible by a ``50-50 lifeline''
option or by polling the studio audience.
</P>
<P>
   The degree-of-difficulty gap between the two raises ticklish
questions about these shows themselves. Does the content of
programs like ``Millionaire'' and ``Twenty-One'' (the reincarnated
version) reflect a watering down of the intellectual product, a
dumbing down, so to speak, of their audience appeal? And if so,
what does the unexpected popularity of these shows say about
society today compared to the America that went nuts for quiz shows
in the '50s?
</P>
<P>
   On style points alone, the debate is a no-brainer. NBC's
``Twenty-One'' resurrects the show's original '50s-style isolation
booth _ but precious little of its intellectual muscle. Contestants
would have to have been locked inside such a booth since 1958 not
to answer such puffballs as, ``NASA's launch site is located in
Florida. True or false?'' Even allowing for drama building, some of
the early-round questions on ``Millionaire'' (What two colors do
you find on an Oreo cookie?) would not stump Bert or Ernie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched one guy win $1 million on a question I had in
seventh-grade science,'' scoffs Herbert Stempel, a real-life star
of the original ``Twenty-One'' show. ``They've dumbed it down to
such an extent, even `Jeopardy' isn't what it used to be. There's
no comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   Author Don Lessem, who competed on ``Jeopardy'' last month, also
appeared on a '70s-era quiz show called ``Who, What, Where.'' It's
a whole new ballgame today, Lessem says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not in tune with junk culture, you're at a real
disadvantage on these shows,'' he says. ``To earn money in the
'70s, I had to know who discovered the cure for syphilis. Now all
you need to know is which actor has syphilis.''
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, none of this is terribly surprising. This is the
golden age, after all, of Mortal Kombat, ``South Park,'' and the
World Wrestling Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Standardized tests are under attack in school systems
everywhere. Network shows are vying for an increasingly fragmented
audience, most of which is not attending Mensa meetings anyway.
Cultural literacy is a slippery concept at best, well beyond the
capacity of Regis Philbin to define in a few brief moments with
thousands of dollars _ and upward of 30 million viewers _ at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's taken for granted as information most educated people
should know changes over time,'' notes E. D. Hirsch, an authority
on cultural literacy. ``I'm all for the democratization of
knowledge that some of these shows represent, but there's a big
difference between good general information and useless general
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Also misleading information. On a recent installment of
``Millionaire,'' a contestant complained about being disqualified
for answering a question about who was the youngest US president at
the time of his inauguration. The contestant chose John F. Kennedy.
The supposedly correct answer, Theodore Roosevelt, hinged on the
definition of inauguration, some historians pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard education professor Howard Gardner, no fan of these
shows, says it's too bad that ``Millionaire'' and its spawn promote
the idea of knowledge as a way to win money.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the point of view of entertainment, it's no better or
worse than much of what's on television, I suppose,'' Gardner says.
``But as a social message about what we should know and why we
should learn, it is discouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   To properly frame the debate over declining quiz-show standards,
some say, it helps to recall the time in which these earlier shows
flourished, when brainiacs like Charles Van Doren and Joyce
Brothers became heroes by winning one tense prime-time duel after
another.
</P>
<P>
   Van Doren, a nerdy Columbia University professor, became a
national idol on par with James Dean before it was revealed that he
and others had been fed answers by the shows' producers.
</P>
<P>
   Egghead Chic was more than entertaining in its heyday. It was,
well, sexy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then,'' recalls Richard Goodwin, a key investigator in
the scandal that killed off prime-time quiz shows for four decades,
``the whole objective was to showcase people from one walk of life
who had an improbable knowledge of other areas, like Joyce Brothers
and boxing. Or to make heroes out of supergeniuses like Van Doren.
It would be impossible to do that today because you couldn't keep
contestants on that long without rigging the shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's shows don't demand the same breadth of knowledge, adds
Goodwin, because ``the whole idea now is, this could be you. You
could be winning all this money. It's more like advertising in that
sense, getting you to identify with the beer drinker or the sexy
girl. But at least it's honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Thompson, director of Syracuse University's Center for
the Study of Popular Television, points out the radical shift in
the cultural context, too. Knowing a lot of pop culture minutiae, a
staple of today's quiz shows, was not much on America's mind back
when television was in its infancy, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifties television really reflected the Cold War,'' Thompson
says. ``In 1957, our rockets were blowing up on the launch pad
while the Soviets had put Sputnik in space. There was this feeling
that intellectual prowess could boost us past the Soviets, so we
threw the educated elite into the arena and watched them play. We
watched Van Doren then the way we watched Michael Jordan play
basketball, to marvel at the brilliance of people more gifted than
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's shows, Thompson says, are about ``people with jobs like
ours answering questions we could answer. It's a much more American
model in many ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate has a generational aspect as well. A Harvard Law
School student, Rahim Oberholtzer, 27, won a record $1.12 million
on ``Twenty-One'' earlier this month. According to Oberholtzer, the
questions he got were nowhere near as easy as they may have seemed
to viewers at home _ even if none contained a single historical
reference to any period prior to the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a situation where a lot of education will necessarily
help,'' Oberholtzer observes. ``The most crucial thing is having a
good memory. You don't need a law degree, but you do need to stay
up on current events, whether it's movies or music or politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Fodera, 24, of Newton, Mass., became a minor celebrity
through his appearance on ``Millionaire'' last month. Fodera
guessed wrong on a $100 question about what Jack Horner pulled out
of his famous nursery-rhyme pie (Fodera picked ``blackbirds,'' not
``plum''). For Fodera, this proved to be both good news and bad
news.
</P>
<P>
   The good news was that he and another first-round loser were
invited on Rosie O'Donnell's syndicated talk show. Fodera won a new
car by acing a makeup test and has been invited back by O'Donnell.
The bad news? The New York Post published an editorial fingering
Fodera as the poster boy for all that is wrong with American youth,
from its obsession with video games to the fact that parents no
longer read enough books aloud to their toddlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe they wrote about the dumbing down of
America and based it on me,'' fumes Fodera. ``I'm a former doctoral
student, for one thing. My parents read books to me all the time. I
didn't play video games. It's a game show, that's all it is. It is
not indicative of the American educational system _ or anything
else.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing on which virtually all agree is that the bottom line
of all these shows, present and past, is money. Lots of money
earned in the white heat of competition.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin says it's no accident these shows are hot again.
``This,'' he says, ``is the most materialistic era America has seen
since the '50s. And these days it wouldn't be Van Doren on the
cover of Time, it would be Philbin.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SOME SAMPLE QUESTIONS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
From ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
(For $1 million) &QL;
