<HEADER>
A9184 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-DIANE-KEATON-IN-HANGI     02-07 1440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANE-KEATON-IN-HANGING-UP-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO HANG-UPS: DIANE KEATON'S CLEAR-EYED VIEW OF HOLLYWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Diane Keaton with Meg Ryan and Lisa
Kudrow in a scene from ``Hanging Up.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    As usual, the tabloids were full of catfight rumors.
 &HT;    Three top female stars _ veteran Diane Keaton, at-her-peak Meg
Ryan and up-and-coming Lisa Kudrow _ were co-starring in ``Hanging
Up.'' To add to the mix, Keaton was directing as well.
 &HT;    Did the fur fly?
 &HT;    ``Of course, when you put three strong women together,'' Keaton
says, ``everyone wants to know if there was trouble.''
 &HT;    On the contrary, the actress/director says _ the three actually
found a lot in common.
 &HT;    ``Meg would gather all of us in the makeup trailer and we'd talk
about our kids,'' she says. ``We would talk about the stresses of
being working moms. It was heavenly.''
 &HT;    Clad in a maroon-leather jacket, matching pants and a white
T-shirt for an interview at Los Angeles' Four Seasons Hotel, Keaton
shows no sign of any second thoughts about ``Hanging Up,'' her
loose adaptation of screenwriter/novelist Delia Ephron's family
memoir, which will open nationwide on Feb. 18.
 &HT;    Notoriously private, Keaton doesn't especially like doing
interviews, but she's professional enough to know when it's
necessary.
 &HT;    ``You know, I don't think I'm so shy,'' she insists. ``I've got
this self-effacing thing going on. And I think I'm protective and a
little paranoid. But I'm too old to be shy.''
 &HT;    Certainly, the 54-year-old Keaton wasn't so shy as to sit back
waiting for the chance to direct ``Hanging Up.''
 &HT;    ``I've saved an hour-long message on my phone machine from
Diane, insisting why she was the only one to direct this movie,''
says co-writer/co-producer Nora Ephron, who briefly considered
directing it herself. ``And Diane was right. I was too close to the
project. And Diane brought the right sensibilities.''
 &HT;    Keaton, Ryan and Kudrow play three sisters dealing with their
aging, alcoholic and often abusive father (Walter Matthau).
 &HT;    ``The minute I read the script, something clicked,'' Keaton
says. ``I am one of three sisters. I love the themes of death and
loss and redemption. And I identified, because this is also a movie
about the stresses facing modern women.''
 &HT;    From ``Annie Hall'' (1975) to ``Baby Boom'' (1987) to ``The
First Wives Club'' (1996), Keaton has spent her career embodying
victims of those stresses.
 &HT;    ``I'm like any mom out there,'' she admits. ``I feel scattered.
I'm always trying to do too much at one time. I feel like I'm being
pulled in all directions.''
 &HT;    Being simultaneously the director and a star of the film didn't
make things any less stressful for Keaton, Ryan says.
 &HT;    ``We're in a hospital room and I'm sobbing into the arms of my
sister, played by Diane,'' Ryan recalls in a separate interview.
``Her back is toward the camera. The actress in Diane is patting my
shoulder and looking at me with such concern and grief.
 &HT;    ``Then the director in Diane whispers in my ear, `OK, are you
done? We've got to move on.'''
 &HT;    Directing counts to Keaton, whose first feature, ``Unstrung
Heroes'' (1996), won strong reviews.
 &HT;    ``I'm at the age as a woman in Hollywood where I know I need
another craft if I want to keep making a living,'' she says
matter-of-factly. `The First Wives Club' saved my professional life
_ that was a big hit. But, let's face it, I'm not 22 anymore. Roles
are not pouring in.''
 &HT;    One recent role cast her opposite Warren Beatty, her former
co-star in ``Reds'' (1981) and former offscreen love interest. But
the long-delayed ``Town &AMP; Country,'' which co-stars Goldie Hawn,
was reportedly a mess from beginning to end.
 &HT;    ```Town &AMP; Country' was, um ... you would ask me about `Town &AMP;
Country,''' Keaton says hesitantly. ``What can I say? Except the
film has been delayed and it has to come out. They've spent too
much money.''
 &HT;    Working with Beatty wasn't a problem, says Keaton, who has also
co-starred with former lovers Al Pacino and Woody Allen years after
their breakups. Nowadays, she adds, she's happily single and
raising her adopted daughter, Dexter.
 &HT;    ``When you're famous it's harder to experience love,'' she says.
``People give you their fantasies about you, and that is something
you can't possibly live up to in real life.''
 &HT;    She isn't bitter, though.
 &HT;    ``The memories of the past are sweet to me now,'' Keaton says
thoughtfully. ``Sometimes I'll sit around and get out the old
photos of my family and my life. I like to document people and take
a look at the past _ it's a way to take a look at what you've lost
and the person who meant so much to you. It's like letting them be
there again for you.
 &HT;    ``Then you don't lose them completely.''
 &HT;    As a young girl growing up in Los Angeles, Keaton recalls being
fascinated by the silver screen.
 &HT;    ``As a kid,'' she says, ``I would watch movies and think, `I'm
so self-conscious and shy, but maybe if I was another person I
wouldn't feel that way.'''
 &HT;    She dropped out of college at 19 and headed for New York, where
she studied acting and got her first break in the original cast of
the rock musical ``Hair'' (1968).
 &HT;    ``I was the only one who didn't take off my clothes at the
end,'' she says, laughing. ``I negotiated to wear a body
stocking.''
 &HT;    That same year Keaton met Allen, who cast her in his play ``Play
It Again, Sam.'' He was 32 and she was 22, and the two fell into an
intense personal and professional relationship.
 &HT;    ``What Woody taught me was to laugh about sex,'' she famously
said of their relationship. ``Not all the time, but once in a
while.''
 &HT;    Keaton won an Oscar as Best Actress for the title role in
Allen's ``Annie Hall'' (1977). The film also triggered a fashion
trend, as women across America started dressing the way Keaton
always had, adopting the floppy hats, baggy pants, oversized vests
and sweaters that once led Larry McMurtry to dub Keaton ``the Queen
of Swap Meets.''
 &HT;    ``I like to express myself through fashion,'' says Keaton, who
still dresses that way, ``but I never thought people would follow
along.''
 &HT;    A string of hit films followed, including ``Looking for Mr.
Goodbar'' (1977), ``Reds,'' ``Crimes of the Heart'' (1986), ``Baby
Boom'' (1987) and ``Father of the Bride'' (1991), as well as a
gradual immersion in directing, starting with music videos,
episodes of television's ``Twin Peaks'' and ``China Beach'' and,
finally, a couple of documentaries.
 &HT;    ``I never think about big financial hits,'' she says. ``I just
try to tell a good story.''
 &HT;    When she wraps, Keaton heads home to a Frank Lloyd Wright house,
located off Sunset Boulevard in the Hollywood hills.
 &HT;    ``My Dad would work really hard all day, and then he'd come home
and turn into a zombie,'' she says. ``That's not me. When I'm home
with my daughter, I say, `OK, enough for today. I will not worry
about movies.'
 &HT;    ``Fourteen hours is enough to devote to my craft,'' she says.
``I'm not going to cut into my daughter's time by having a phone
conversation with my agent where I'm saying, `No, I don't think I'm
right to direct `Gandhi II.'''
 &HT;    But what if it were about Gandhi's three sisters?
 &HT;    Keaton wrinkles her brow.
 &HT;    ``Can I get back to you about that one?''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Hanging Up,'' consult the Sony
Pictures Website at www.spe.sony.com. And don't forget to visit The
New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
