<SLUG> BC-KATE-WINSLET-IN-HOLY-SMOKE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UN-JULIA: KATE WINSLET'S FIGHT TO TRIUMPH OVER STARDOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Kate Winslet in a scene from ``Holy
Smoke.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Kate Winslet thought she was going mad.
 &HT;    She was 18 or 19 years old, and deeply confused as to who she
was. Though she'd started acting and loved the craft, she still
groped for an identity, a sense of herself as a person.
 &HT;    ``That's very typical for young people _ not just women, but
young people _ to feel,'' the English actress says. ``I pushed
myself through that period, saying `I'll go through this lonely
bit, I'll go through this suicidal bit and I'll come out the other
side and feel OK.'
 &HT;    ``It took a long time,'' she admits, ``but I knew there were all
these other important things that I had to do. I suppose I was
lucky, because I had a really stable upbringing that gave me the
security to do that.
 &HT;    ``Some people don't have that, and it can be quite scary.''
 &HT;    Those hard days may have been worth it, however, because they
equipped Winslet to deal with the consequences of her own success.
They gave the now-24-year-old actress the courage not to be a movie
star.
 &HT;    After her meteoric rise in the wake of ``Titanic'' (1997),
Winslet might have seized the moment, starring in one blockbuster
after another as so many others have done. But instead of ``going
Hollywood,'' Winslet has reaffirmed her status as one of the most
talented actresses of her generation, seeking out challenging roles
in smaller, idiosyncratic films that allow her to test herself and
further develop her art.
 &HT;    First there was ``Hideous Kinky'' (1999) and now there is ``Holy
Smoke,'' opening nationwide throughout February. Directed by Jane
Campion and based on a screenplay by Campion and her sister Anna,
``Holy Smoke'' stars Winslet as Ruth, an Australian woman who,
during a visit to India, becomes caught up in the teachings of a
Hindu/Buddhist guru.
 &HT;    Disturbed by Ruth's new life, her family plots to save her from
herself, ultimately reaching out to P.J. Waters (Harvey Keitel), an
American deprogrammer. Waters whisks Ruth away to a halfway hut in
the middle of nowhere, and the agonizing deprogramming process
begins. It's thrown out of whack, however, when Ruth seduces P.J.
and turns the tables on him.
 &HT;    ``I loved the fact that Jane was asking me to play a woman who
was very real and very now and very ballsy,'' Winslet says, rolling
her first of several cigarettes during a conversation at
Manhattan's Essex House. She's in winning form, speaking earnestly,
laughing at herself often and looking chic in a blood-red blouse
and black jacket.
 &HT;    ``I was flattered to be asked,'' she says. ``It made me think,
`God, maybe I really could do this.' I loved the script.
 &HT;    ``Ruth is just trying to figure out who she is,'' Winslet says,
``and I think she does that through her relationship with P.J. He
opens up other sides of her she didn't even know she had, and she
does the same for him.
 &HT;    ``It was the script, Jane, the character and Harvey Keitel that
attracted me, as this one big, fabulous package.''
 &HT;    Winslet threw herself into the project, spending two weeks in
India researching her role, taking the advice of a friend to
actually get sloshed for a drunk scene and giving her all in
several sexually charged scenes opposite Keitel. For one particular
sequence, Winslet was called upon to stand buck naked, urinate on
herself and confront Keitel.
 &HT;    The actress felt liberated after filming her first nude scene,
in ``Jude'' (1996). Now, she says, it's just part of the job. Sort
of.
 &HT;    ``When I had to do it in `Jude' I was so petrified,'' she
recalls. ``I felt like I just couldn't do it. Emma Thompson said,
`You'll feel liberated. Just go for it.'
 &HT;    ``She was right,'' the actress adds, ``and I did. Ever since
then ... nude scenes are hard to do, but at the end of the day they
are no different from any other scene, because you have to forget
yourself and your physicality, and you have to concentrate on the
work involved. Otherwise all kinds of my own paranoia would come
into play, and I wouldn't be embodying the character.
 &HT;    ``They are difficult scenes to do, but there is a certain sense
of `Yes, I did that' when you get to the other side.''
 &HT;    Actually, she admits, not much scares her anymore.
 &HT;    ``I don't think so,'' she says, smiling slyly. ``When it comes
to being in a movie, there are all kinds of things and you think,
`I can't even act anymore _ I look like the back end of a horse.
How can I possibly do this?'
 &HT;    ``You panic like crazy,'' she says, ``but I don't know a single
actor who doesn't do that. Apart from a normal paranoia until you
get to day one, there really isn't anything that scares me.
 &HT;    ``If anything, `Holy Smoke' almost changed any fears I
subconsciously had,'' she adds, ``because I had to play that role.
I had to be really uninhibited. I had to be very free and not
afraid.
 &HT;    ``Jane dragged me there, kicking and screaming.''
 &HT;    Back home in London, Winslet reports, there's little kicking or
screaming. She and her husband, aspiring director Jim Threapleton,
are doing fine, thank you very much.
 &HT;    As for the age-old question that arises whenever half of a
couple is a major star ...
 &HT;    ``It's a question that is asked a lot to celebrities, if you
like,'' Winslet says, interrupting. ```Who wears the trousers in
your relationship?' I say we wear one leg each. It's incredibly
equal, and that just doesn't come into play.''
 &HT;    Winslet, who first made her mark in such period films as ``Sense
and Sensibility'' (1995) and ``Jude,'' is back in corsets for her
next film, ``Quills.'' The story of the Marquis de Sade, the film
co-stars Geoffrey Rush and Joaquin Phoenix, and is directed by the
always-unpredictable Philip Kaufman.
 &HT;    As its subject matter suggests, ``Quills'' is far more likely to
win critical plaudits than to score big at the box office. And
chances are that Winslet passed up far more commercial projects and
larger paydays in order to do it, the same way she reportedly
turned down ``Shakespeare in Love'' (1998), ``Anna and the King''
(1999) and the upcoming ``Autumn in New York'' in favor of
``Hideous Kinky'' and ``Holy Smoke.''
 &HT;    ``I hate to get down to specifics,'' Winslet says, shaking her
head at the mention of those other films. ``I don't have any
regrets, because I don't believe in having regrets in life. I think
you only have one life, and if you regret things then you're
stepping backward.
 &HT;    ``I'm a believer in going forward and going for it and having
fun, actually,'' she says with a smile. ``I have no regrets in my
life at all.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Holy Smoke,'' consult the
official Website at www.holysmokethemovie.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
