<SLUG> BC-SINGER-CARLOS-SANTANA-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUPERNATURAL' PHENOMENON: THE RESURRECTION OF CARLOS SANTANA 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of singer Carlos Santana.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    It's almost ... well, supernatural.
 &HT;    About the last thing anyone associated with the pop-music scene
looked for last year was a record-shattering comeback from Carlos
Santana.
 &HT;    But that's exactly what has happened in the wake of June's
release of ``Supernatural,'' a record that pairs Santana with such
contemporary luminaries as Dave Matthews, Lauryn Hill, Rob Thomas
of Matchbox 20, Everlast, Eagle-Eye Cherry and Wyclef Jean, as well
as fellow rock-guitar hero Eric Clapton.
 &HT;    Faster than you can say ``Oye Como Va,'' ``Supernatural'' became
a sensation, topping the Billboard album charts at the same time
``Smooth,'' co-written and sung by Thomas and Santana, hit the top
of the singles charts.
 &HT;    Besides reviving the star Santana kindled 30 years ago with his
defining performance at the original Woodstock festival, it also
earned the 52-year-old songwriter, musician and bandleader an
American Music Award for the year's favorite pop/rock album and a
whopping 10 Grammy Award nominations, the most of any artist this
year.
 &HT;    And, Santana says, this success isn't entirely accidental.
 &HT;    ``This CD is assigned and designed to reach junior-high school,
high school and universities,'' explains the Mexican-born musician,
whose previous two No. 1 albums, ``Abraxas'' and ``Santana III,''
were released in the early 1970s. ``With Lauryn Hill and Dave
Matthews, it was designed to assault the radio airwaves with the
Santana vibration.
 &HT;    ``If you play something from the heart,'' he adds, ``they'll
listen to it. Eubie Blake, the piano player, used to say `If you
listen, we get you.'
 &HT;    ``So it ain't about generations,'' Santana says. ``We're
connecting because, even though they're very young and some of them
may have never heard us, once we drop the music on them, they go
`Oh, what is this?'
 &HT;    ``It's going in, and it's making an impact.''
 &HT;    Santana's three-plus decades of recording include not only work
with his own band but also numerous collaborations and a leading
role in the blending of Latin and rock styles. He views music as
spiritual expression _ something that, when done correctly, can
``rearrange the molecular structure of the listener'' and inspire a
higher understanding of the self and the world around us.
 &HT;    At the turn of the century, Santana also feels compelled to
spread a ``positive vibration'' to counterbalance the aggressive,
violent images that saturate popular culture.
 &HT;    ``All you have to do is look at what's happening in schools,
with guns and stuff, and I felt that by creating this music we were
presenting the audience, the young listeners, a new menu,'' he
says. ``We don't want them to feel like us or think like us or
believe like us _ everybody's entitled to their own unique
viewpoint and to pursue their own destinies. But we did want to
present them with a new menu.
 &HT;    ``In other words,'' he explains, ``when the sound resonates and
the vibrations that come out of us through the songs rearrange the
molecules, then you and I are reminded that we are multidimensional
spirits, and we have enormous opportunities and possibilities to do
grand things for the highest good of life and people on the
planet.''
 &HT;    Of course, what's a message without an audience to hear it?
That's what brought Santana back to Arista Records chief Clive
Davis, the man who had signed him to Columbia Records in 1969, to
help put together ``Supernatural'' and its superstar
collaborations.
 &HT;    For his part, Santana says his main responsibility wasn't really
the music as such, but rather to make sure the project stayed true
to his mission.
 &HT;    ``This is not show business,'' he says. ``This is not
entertainment. None of the musicians I play with on this CD is an
entertainment guy or a show-business guy _ we're musicians, and we
believe that music has the power to bring unity and healing in a
new kind of dimension and thinking. And that's why we did it.
 &HT;    ``All of us came with our hearts forward, and it sounds like one
breath,'' Santana says. ``It doesn't sound like it was painted by
numbers or like I was dipped into somebody else's stuff. To me,
it's a masterpiece of joy.''
 &HT;    ``Smooth,'' the album's big hit, is also one of its most joyous
moments, a celebration of sensuality and romantic dynamics. Yet
beforehand many wondered if Thomas, best known for hooky-pop hits
with Matchbox 20, wasn't a bit too lightweight to be working with
someone like Santana.
 &HT;    ``He was just as deep as all the other people, no less,''
Santana insists. ``Don't let the word `popular' fool you _ there's
nothing more popular than Nat King Cole, still. (Thomas')
convictions are true for what he's doing _ he caught that spirit of
Spanish Harlem, `Mona Lisa.'
 &HT;    ``He has this beautiful lady, she looks Afro-Cuban or she might
be Puerto Rican, so he understands the concept of
multidimensional,'' the musician adds. ``He has a deep soul and
deep convictions. We sat down and talked about it before we started
recording the song. I'm just very, very grateful, man _ he's a
great writer.''
 &HT;    There are stories behind each of the album's pairings. Hill, for
instance, had Santana as a guest on her Grammy-winning ``The
Miseducation of Lauryn Hill,'' and was more than happy to return
the favor.
 &HT;    Santana had been introduced to Matthews' music by his 9-year-old
daughter. Intrigued, he presented Matthews with the beginnings of
``Love of My Life,'' a song inspired by Brahms' ``Concerto No. 2,''
and let the younger rocker finish it.
 &HT;    Clapton, meanwhile, had seen Santana perform with Hill at last
year's Grammys, and called after Davis approached him about the
project.
 &HT;    ``He said, `I definitely want to play on your album, but only if
you hear me and if there's room for me,''' Santana recalls. ``Can
you imagine Eric Clapton telling you such a thing?''
 &HT;    The two met one afternoon and came up with ``The Calling,'' a
lengthy opus which Santana likens to ``having two Apaches at the
Grand Canyon evoking the spirits, that kind of thing.''
 &HT;    Part of ``Supernatural's'' success is its opportune timing, many
observers believe. The success of Ricky Martin and others has
reawakened mass interest in Latin music, resulting in some
sales-inducing curiosity about Santana as one of its important
figures.
 &HT;    The guitarist himself dismisses the notion, however _ though
``Supernatural'' does include several songs with Spanish lyrics.
The way he sees it, he's been around far too long to be helped by
trends.
 &HT;    ``I take great delight in crystallizing the reality that Latin
or Spanish, whatever we call it, is really African music,'' Santana
says. ``Ricky Martin, yours truly, Gloria Estefan, Los Lobos _
everyone who calls themselves Latin or Spanish is really playing
African music, unless you mix it with polkas or waltzes.
 &HT;    ``But basically, everybody's playing rumba, cha cha cha, samba,
bolero, and all that stuff really comes from Africa,'' he says.
``Whatever we call ourselves these days, Latin or Spanish or
Chicano, it's OK _ but we have to remember that we really are
playing African music and so honor that.''
 c.2000 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Supernatural,'' consult the
official Santana Website at www.santana.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
