<HEADER>
A9189 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-JON-STEWART-IN-THE-DA     02-07 1418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JON-STEWART-IN-THE-DAILY-SHOW-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DAILY' WORKER: JON STEWART ON COMEDY, POLITICS AND `THE DAILY
SHOW' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Jon Stewart in a scene from ``The Daily
Show.'') 
 By KEVIN SNOW  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be published in Canada before Feb. 13. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's no wonder that most live television shows employ a warm-up
comedian before the host gets near the audience. You can't expect a
cheerful reception from a bunch of people fresh from 30 minutes
standing in line out in a frigid New York night or jammed into a
cramped anteroom that really is referred to as a ``holding tank.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the host is his own warm-up man. David Letterman meets
his audience prior to taping, for example, but his brief chat
almost gives the impression that an audience should feel privileged
to be in his presence.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Stewart is a different story. As soon as he steps onto ``The
Daily Show'' set, he makes everyone feel at home. For almost 10
minutes he lets the crowd know that he's as happy to see them as
they are to see him.
</P>
<P>
   And Stewart actually is happy to see his audience. After years
of guest-host status on dozens of shows, Stewart took over as host
</P>
<P>
   of Comedy Central's popular program in January 1999, and he
hasn't looked back since. A nightly news-parody program is a long
way from the network talk shows that he was reportedly in line for
on numerous occasions, but it suits the 37-year-old Stewart just
fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is perfect for me,'' Stewart says, leaning back into a
chair in his New York office. ``The opportunity to write jokes
about the news is a gift. I have a forum every day on television.
I'm really enjoying this.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in his career, Stewart admits, he found frustration at
every turn. There are those who love the forever-on-the-road life
of a stand-up comic, but he isn't one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comedy circuit is tough,'' Stewart says. ``You begin to
wonder how many times you can jump in the van and head to Rochester
to play the karaoke club. That was probably the toughest part for
me _ I was looking for a way to know where I was going.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, an MTV talk show seemed to offer that
direction. Paramount bought the show in 1995, but its attempts to
syndicate it came to nought.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman's Worldwide Pants production company then signed
Stewart to a contract, but the only results of that deal were
endless rumors that he would be replacing various current hosts.
The most prevalent one had him replacing Tom Snyder on ``The Late,
Late Show'' _ a position ultimately filled, ironically, by
Stewart's ``Daily Show'' predecessor, Craig Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   The rumors became so widespread that, when Stewart played
himself on Garry Shandling's ``The Larry Sanders Show,'' the
running gag for the final season focused on Larry's fears that his
bosses were grooming Stewart to take over the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like I was ever being interviewed for these jobs or
sending out resumes,'' the comedian says, laughing. ``I was just
going about my business, and every so often people would say, `Hey,
I hear you're taking over on that show.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It was funny, because the story of what was really going on
was so different.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Stewart says, he tried not to let the rumors get
to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what helped most is that my goals are never much
beyond what I'm doing now,'' he says in retrospect. ``This is the
kind of business that can disappoint you on a daily basis if your
needs are so great.''
</P>
<P>
   His unexpected down time allowed Stewart to experiment in film
acting, playing supporting roles in a few 1999 films, including
``The Faculty,'' ``Big Daddy'' and ``Playing By Heart,'' which
offered him his largest role to date.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Stewart has ambitions to become a movie star. In fact,
he says, he feels a bit uncomfortable even discussing it seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of fun to do,'' he says, ``but I recognize the
limitations of what that presents for me. I really have trouble
talking about acting to people, because it's something I don't
truly understand.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Playing By Heart,'' an ensemble film whose illustrious cast
included Sean Connery, Gena Rowlands, Dennis Quaid, Madeleine
Stowe, Angelina Jolie and Ryan Phillippe, Stewart played a
sensitive architect courting a neurotic, romantically scarred woman
played by Gillian Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest part for me in that film was the earnestness,''
the comedian says. ``Having to tell someone you love them, eight
times, in front of a bunch of guys standing around holding lights.
Those Teamsters aren't big huggers.''
</P>
<P>
   His film work was interesting and enjoyable, he adds, but it
only made it clearer to him that he wanted to get back into
television _ though not necessarily into the talk-show game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd already done the celebrity-driven thing,'' he says, ``so I
wasn't sure if I wanted to go that route again.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart can pinpoint the exact moment when he realized that he
had to get back on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching Mary Bono during the Clinton impeachment
proceedings,'' Stewart recalls. ``She had just written a book about
Sonny Bono, all of his drug issues, how he died. And she was on the
congressional subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk about a travesty,'' he says, rolling his eyes. ``When
they got to her, her comment was, `What do I tell my children?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sitting there thinking, you just wrote a tell-all book
about Hollywood ... What do you tell your children about the
president? How about this: The president was on painkillers and he
skiied into an intern.'''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This made me realize I had the itch,'' he says. ``The book and
movie roles didn't have the pop that I was looking for _ I wanted
to get back in the daily grind.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Stewart's role on ``The Daily Show'' is as an
anti-anchorman. He doesn't simply read the news _ he takes shots at
it and how it's presented. Sometimes his facial expressions and
body language are enough to make his opinion hilariously clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess there's a dual role of commentary and satire on the
way the news is disseminated nowadays,'' he says. ``It's a show
about the media to a certain extent, but not explicitly. It's sort
of an implicit tear on the media, but not just the news _ it's just
using the actual structure of a newscast.''
</P>
<P>
   The show benefits from its team of correspondents, with regular
contributors Vance Degeneres and Mo Rocca taking minor news events
and blowing them way out of proportion, almost as tribute to some
of the major networks' newsmagazines.
</P>
<P>
   Those programs are one topic that gets Stewart heated up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pomposity of `Dateline,' `20/20' and the new world of
scare tactics is unbelievable,'' he says, shaking his head. ``News
today functions like entertainment. There is no grander thesis, no
higher purpose anymore, and it's unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's passion for the news may be what makes him so happy
with his current post _ though he typically resists embracing it
wholly, happy or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I've got work, I always think that things are good,'' he
says. ``The way I look at, if I'm not bartending anymore, things
can't be too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Kevin Snow is a staff writer at TV Guide Canada, based in
North York, Ont.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Daily Show,'' consult the
official Website at www.thedailyshow.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
