   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-TROUBLE (Undated) _ Experts are predicting that the 2000
Census will have the worst participation rate ever. The latest data
indicate Americans are increasingly unlikely to get involved in
anything that isn't directly connected to their daily lives because
they don't have time. By SHERRY SYLVESTER.
</P>
<P>
   TB-RESEARCH (San Antonio) _ Texas tuberculosis researchers have
unraveled the secrets of a key protein that could aid in the search
for new treatments for drug-resistant strains of TB, as well as
vaccines to protect people. By CINDY TUMIEL.
</P>
<P>
   AIRFORCE-LOGO (San Antonio) _ The Air Force is poised to adopt
its first servicewide symbol, and the leading candidate features
stark blue diagonal bands resembling folded wings, lifted behind a
white star. The logo aims to boost the service's image and capture
its colorful history and traditions. By SIG CHRISTENSON.
</P>
<P>
   KORESH-DEVICE (Waco, Texas) _ Volunteers rebuilding David
Koresh's chapel say they have found a device that could solve the
mystery of the fiery end of the Branch Davidian cult: an incendiary
or fire-starting device, allegedly fired by government agents into
the complex during the 1993 siege. However, the people who found
the suspect device refuse to give it to investigators. By DICK J.
REAVIS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VOUCHERS (Dale City, Calif.) _ While the battle to
desegregate schools was fought against Southern segregationists,
the battle for school choice will be fought against liberal special
interest groups. While it isn't perfect, school choice is the only
certain solution that will break up the educational status quo and
ensure that greater educational opportunities are available for the
people who need them most. By LEE HUBBARD.
</P>
<P>
   CORPORATE-AMERICAN (Oakland, Calif.) _ It's Jan. 30, 2040, and
nobody complains anymore. And why would they? When advertising
finally prevailed, so did we. Just look around: Castro is long
dead. Elian grew up a proud American, with many possessions. The
average Beijing resident now tools around in a late-model
hydrogen-powered Buick. And we have all the things we'll ever need,
a
</P>
