<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9199 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BBN-GALARRAGA-COX     02-07 2451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GALARRAGA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beloved Big Cat is not alone in recovery
 &HT;    By Carlos Frias
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ With two armed guards at his side, it takes
Andres Galarraga 15 minutes to walk 15 feet, past the throng
stretching to touch his fingertips. Fans hang over the railing
behind home plate, and he is swept into a sea of arms. Those in
front don't hoard him; they pass forward an assortment of items to
be signed _ a new baseball, a torn sheet of notebook paper, an
old-style Braves cap, a scuffed baseball, a faded Yankees cap. He
pauses before signing the latter.
</P>
<P>
   These items won't end up at an auction. They might sit atop a
nightstand or coffee table, cherished by their owners and perhaps
passed down to grandchildren _ a memory of the day Abuela met The
Big Cat.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga signs every item, and as he hands it back, he looks
the owner in the eyes and flashes a wide grin.
</P>
<P>
   University Stadium begins to fill with more than 17,000 fans,
some who arrived more than three hours earlier to buy tickets. When
the announcer cries out ``Numero 41, Andreeeees Galarraaaaaaga!''
cheers cascade through the park and Galarraga's face barely
contains that famous smile.
</P>
<P>
   This is a day for celebration. More than 20 former and current
major-leaguers have come to Caracas to play in a charity softball
game to raise funds for Venezuela's mudslide victims.
</P>
<P>
   But more than that, it is a day to celebrate that Galarraga has
overcome an intruder that threatened their national treasure. That
the tiny scar on his back is all that remains of an illness that
kept him out of baseball for a season.
</P>
<P>
   That he has beaten cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Salsa music and the smell of home-cooked black beans filled the
cool night air as Galarraga, the youngest of five boys and a girl,
watched his sister, Haide, the oldest, dance with his brother,
Orlando, in the back yard of his mother's home.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago this week, Galarraga's aunts, uncles, cousins,
siblings and neighbors gathered in Los Dos Caminos, a suburb of
Caracas, to celebrate Haide's 50th birthday. With a half-empty
plate of shredded beef, black beans and fried plantains in front of
him, Andres swallowed and turned to his mother, Juana, seated next
to him at the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing in my back _ I'm not sure what it is, but it's
really starting to bother me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when are they doing the exam?'' Juana asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 17th. In Atlanta. They say they should know right away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ay, Dios, Andres. I hope it's nothing serious. Call me right
away and tell me what the doctor says.''
</P>
<P>
   The morning of Feb. 17, Juana awoke early and sat alone in her
upstairs den. As she prayed beside a statue of the Virgin of
Coromoto, Venezuela's patron saint, the baby of her family flew
from West Palm Beach to Piedmont Hospital in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Six p.m., no word from her son. Eight p.m. Midnight. Seven a.m.,
Feb. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Her nervous curiosity became concern when Haide called West Palm
Beach. Andres' oldest daughter, Andria, answered the phone and said
that Eneyda, Andres' wife, had taken the first flight to Atlanta
that morning.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, Juana started to cry. ``Something bad must have
happened if Eneyda went to him,'' she said. ``Ay, Nino Jesus!
What's happened?''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, at 4 p.m., Juana's phone rang.
</P>
<P>
   Eneyda's trembling voice broke the news _ it was cancer. Eneyda
passed the phone to Andres, who prepared his mother for the flurry
of phone calls and news reports that would fill the airways in the
coming hours.
</P>
<P>
   Juana could not speak. So mother and son sat together on the
phone and cried.
</P>
<P>
   Andres Galarraga knows what cancer can do. When he was 21, he
watched for five months as pancreatic cancer withered the body of
his 75-year-old father, Francisco, who fought in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Five days short of the 17th anniversary of Francisco Galarraga's
death, Andres had been diagnosed with non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, a
form of cancer, in a vertebra in his lower back.
</P>
<P>
   ``That word _ when I heard `cancer,' I thought I was going to
die the next day,'' he said. ``But you know what? I was actually
relieved to hear it was cancer. At least I knew what it was, and
that with medicine and treatments, I could be cured.''
</P>
<P>
   Five months of chemotherapy and one month of radiation treatment
awaited. Intolerable pain and discomfort that would threaten to
break his spirit. But the worst part would come first: telling his
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga decided to say it simply, using the tool he has used
to break down so many barriers: ``I said it smiling.''
</P>
<P>
   With his wife carrying their youngest daughter Andrianna, 1, in
her arms, Galarraga sat across from his oldest, Andria, now 14, and
Katherine, 8, and broke the news, hiding any tears underneath his
smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never mentioned cancer. We called it lymphoma,'' Galarraga
said. ``It's a word they didn't really know, so it didn't sound so
scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, this is going to make me cry. They answered, `You're going
to be OK, Papi. We're going to take care of you.' And they did.
They did, you know, little kid things _ get my slippers, get my
lunch ready _ taking care of me as well as they could.''
</P>
<P>
   With his family by his side, Galarraga began the first of five
chemotherapy treatments. Right away, everyone realized this would
not be easy on him, physically or mentally.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that first day, I was like, `Oh, my God, how much more
of this can I take?''' he said. Goose bumps covered his arms as he
remembered four days of vomiting and nausea that haunted him after
the treatment. Medication made him retain water, adding nearly 30
pounds to his playing weight of 235 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe what I saw when I looked in the mirror,''
he said. ``I couldn't run. I couldn't lift weights. I couldn't do
anything. Imagine. I gained so much weight.''
</P>
<P>
   His salt-and-pepper hair began falling out, a little at a time
at first, then in clumps. Juana watched as her son brought her
handfuls of his locks, looking for encouragement. In typical
Galarraga fashion, she hid the tears behind a smile and sent him to
get a haircut, where he had the barber shave it to the scalp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say, `That's nothing. Don't worry,''' Juana remembers.
``Then, when he left, I would go upstairs and cry. But we couldn't
let him see us cry. We always showed him a smile.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga was in the worst shape of his life, physically and
emotionally. For the first time in 20 years, he had gone an entire
season without playing baseball. Especially discomforting was being
away from the game, watching his teammates on satellite television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd watch one or two innings to see how things were going,
then I'd turn it off,'' he said. ``I felt _ I don't know _
uncomfortable not being able to be with them.''
</P>
<P>
   To keep his mind fresh, Galarraga would spend hours outside in
the shade painting, a talent he discovered when he was 8 years old.
The walls of his home in West Palm are filled with his artwork,
mostly of peaceful landscapes and seascapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Painting really helped distract me from everything that was
happening,'' he said. ``I'm no artist or anything, but I would
spend four and five hours a day painting, and it really helped me a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga knew he was making progress. The tumor was shrinking
and the chemotherapy became easier with each session. But the
outside world, especially his fans in Venezuela, clamored to know
more.
</P>
<P>
   To begin to understand the love affair between Venezuela and
Galarraga, picture a stout young boy from impoverished and tattered
Chapellin, about 15 minutes from the heart of Caracas, where too
many homes have only three cinder-block walls and a tin roof.
</P>
<P>
   Like most kids from his neighborhood, his first form of
organized baseball was chapitas, a kind of stickball with a bottle
cap for a ball. Galarraga loved playing so much that his mother
used his siblings and nephews as spies to find out whether Andres
was skipping class to play pickup baseball at nearby Miranda Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would say, `Mama, why do I need school? I'm going to be a
baseball player,''' Juana remembers. ``I said, `That's not how it
goes. First, study. Then, we'll see what you can become.'''
</P>
<P>
   When Andres was 11 and playing with a youth league team from
Chapellin, he hit a grand slam to rally his team from nine runs
behind to a 10-9 win. A photographer from the local paper caught up
with Galarraga as he and his family were heading home, and asked
for a picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `No, Mama. I already changed and I'm tired,''' Juana
remembered. ``I said, `Listen, Andresito, this is important. It'll
just take a minute. Put your jersey back on. Put your cap on, and
let's take that photo. And smile, boy, smile!'''
</P>
<P>
   He forced a grin barely big enough to show his teeth, and the
next morning in Las Ultimas Noticias, The Latest News, was the
first published photo of the smile that has become his trademark.
</P>
<P>
   ``From that day on, he never stopped showing up in the papers,''
said Juana, looking at a large, glossy reprint of the photo. ``And
he never wipes that smile off his face.''
</P>
<P>
   That proved an important lesson for Galarraga, who has
distinguished himself by being gracious and approachable. Fans see
him not as an idol, but as an equal _ a hometown boy made good, who
married a girl who grew up three blocks from him, and whose mother
lives in a humble home, by choice, just 10 minutes from where
Galarraga grew up.
</P>
<P>
   When the world caught wind of his illness, even his family was
stunned by the level of support.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Mama, she didn't know just how much people loved him until
he got sick,'' said Alfonso Galarraga, the second youngest. ``He
received letters and prayers from everywhere _ Africa, Italy, Spain
_ everywhere. Everybody has been with him every moment; his wife,
Eneyda, all his family, all of Venezuela.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The phone here never stopped ringing,'' said Haide, Andres'
sister. ``People called us. They stopped us in the streets.
Everyone asking, `Como esta El Gato?'''
</P>
<P>
   Local television aired a documentary of his life, from his
origins in the poor suburbs to his signing of a professional
contract with Montreal, where Expos manager Felipe Alou dubbed him
El Gran Gato for his cat-like reflexes, to becoming the Venezuelan
with the most home runs in the majors. When Venezuela chose its
team of the century, Galarraga received the most votes.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor of Juana's claimed that La Virgen de la Rosa Mystica,
an apparition of the Virgin Mary in Venezuela, had appeared to her
and said Andres would pull through his illness if they prayed for
the Virgin Mary to intercede on his behalf every day until March 8.
Today, Galarraga and his mother have statues of the Virgin Mary in
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Present and former players from around the majors, and from
other sports, called in support. That, Galarraga said, might have
made the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suffered because of this thing,'' said Dennis Martinez, a
teammate of Galarraga's in Montreal for six seasons, and with the
Braves in 1998. ``I've known him since he was young. I've seen him
go though his ups and down. I care for him so much. I was one of
the first to call him and give him courage, make him know he has
friends with him.''
</P>
<P>
   His country didn't fail him when he was ill, and Galarraga could
not stand by when his homeland was in peril.
</P>
<P>
   In the second week of December, torrential rains caused
mudslides throughout La Guaira, Caracas' mountainous region,
killing more than 30,000 and leaving tens of thousands injured and
homeless. That same week, doctors checked and the malignancy in
Galarraga's back had disappeared; they cleared him to return to
full workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Just over two months remained before spring training, but rather
than increase a workout regimen that has him within 5 pounds of his
playing weight, Galarraga boarded the first flight from his home in
West Palm Beach when flights to Caracas resumed. On Christmas Eve,
the major day of celebration for Latin American families, Galarraga
visited several hospitals in Caracas, distributing toys donated by
him and the Braves to children injured in the mudslides.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, again sacrificing precious workout time, Galarraga
participated in El Juego de la Fraternidad, The Game of
Brotherhood, where he was the main attraction. He received a
standing ovation from fans elated to see their Big Cat again on the
prowl and among them in their time of need.
</P>
<P>
   Watching this display of affection were three native Venezuelans
who might attract their own attention most other times. Cleveland
shortstop Omar Vizquel, who organized the event, former
major-leaguer David Concepcion and Hugo Chavez, the country's
president, were unable to keep from smiling as Venezuela greeted
its favorite son with total fixation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple people recognize me,'' said Braves catcher Eddie
Perez, also a native Venezuelan, ``but here in Caracas, it's Andres
they love.''
</P>
<P>
   University Stadium looked like old Atlanta-Fulton County
Stadium, dotted with the many Braves caps and jerseys in the crowd.
And the mere mention of Galarraga's name elevated the crowd into a
20-second burst of applause.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, when the country's rookie president was introduced,
boos broke out, and voices called for his ouster:``Fuera!'' Thump,
thump. ``Fuera!''
</P>
<P>
   During the game, which was aired on every local television
station, every player pulled Galarraga aside to share good tidings
and their amazement at his recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `I'll be ready to play,''' former major-leaguer
Dave Winfield said. ``I said good, because they need you _ with the
bat, with the glove, with the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I see him so strong. He looks so good,'' says Alfonso
Galarraga, who sits in the dugout alongside his brother. ``All the
prayers _ I think that really motivated him. He's done this all on
faith and desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Faith has done something else; Galarraga now refers to cancer in
past tense, health in the present and baseball in the imminent
future. Thus, a nuance appears in Galarraga's batting routine.
Before stepping into the box, he pauses and crosses himself.
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd's cheers of hope and respect ring in his ears
again, the Big Cat feels grateful to be alive and lucky to be
playing the sport an entire country believes he was born to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great physically and mentally, especially mentally,''
Galarraga says. ``I actually feel stronger than when I had the
problem with my back. Baseball's always been my passion, and I
think God has laid his hands so that I can be here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
