<P>
   PFIZER (New York) _ Folo on Pfizer's $90 billion acquisition of
Warner-Lambert to create the world's second-biggest drug company.
By Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BOOM (Washington) _ The economy's robust expansion has
largely overlapped with the Clinton era, and the president and his
team have not been shy about claiming their share of credit for the
boom. But by the reckoning of many Republicans, the expansion is
nothing more than an extension of a growth surge that began in the
Reagan administration. This current stretch of good times, however
framed, clearly has many factors behind it. There have been
dizzying advances in computing power. Investors have proven willing
to finance new ideas. Workers have become more productive. The
Federal Reserve has conducted monetary policy with skill and
flexibility. But this is an election year, making it hard to avoid
putting the economy and the longevity of this expansion in a
political context. And to a remarkable degree, voters are being
asked to judge whether they believe this is a Reagan boom or a
Clinton boom. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   GOLD-PRICES (New York) _ Looking at the recent surge in gold
prices. Other big gold producers are expected to announce on Monday
that they are abandoning hedging. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daly marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks were little changed in early trading.
At 10:55 a.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was down 0.75
percent, the S&AMP;P 500 was down 0.41 percent and the Nasdaq composite
index was up 0.74 percent. Treasury prices were slightly lower,
with the sharpest decline at the long end. The yield on the 30-year
bond stood at 6.31 percent. European markets were lower, with
London down 0.60 percent and Frankfurt down 2.26 percent. In Asia,
the Nikkei closed up 0.92 percent, while the Hong Kong market was
still closed for the Lunar New Year holiday. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA-ECON (Vienna) _ A look at the economic and business
implications of Austria's political isolation because of the
ascendance of the anti-immigrant Freedom Party. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH-AIRWAYS-EARNINGS (London) _ British Airways says
third-quarter losses widened because of fierce competition on North
Atlantic routes, but the results are better than expected, and BA
says its focus on business travelers is paying off. By Andrew Ross
Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   POLO-NBC (New York) _ Polo Ralph Lauren has agreed to form a
30-year venture to sell Polo Ralph Lauren American products with
NBC and two NBC affiliates. NBC will contribute $110 million of
television and online advertising on NBC and CNBC.com.
</P>
