A9219 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-AIRFORCE-LOGO-HNS &LR;      02-07 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRFORCE-LOGO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AIR FORCE, FACING RECRUITING SLUMP, WORKS ON A LOG 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The Cold War is over. The economy is booming. And
patriotic teen-agers aren't exactly circling Air Force recruiting
centers.
</P>
<P>
   What to do? Try a logo.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force is preparing to adopt its first servicewide symbol
to boost its image and capture its colorful history and traditions.
The leading candidate features stark blue diagonal bands resembling
folded wings, lifted behind a white star.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Michael E. Ryan, the Air Force chief of staff, said the
idea is to get those outside the service to know it better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know who we are and what we do, now and in the future. We
want others to know, associate with and support our Air Force,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The service spent $805,000, hired a consulting firm and listened
to 68 focus groups in a bid to put a face to its name.
</P>
<P>
   Though no decision has been made on the logo, Ryan said he was
``coming to appreciate'' the logo, which ``just has a lot of
meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   Branches of the Air Force, among them the Air Combat Command and
the U.S. Air Forces in Europe, have bright, colorful logos well
known to many service members worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   While the service has a seal, it never has had an official
symbol, the kind of identifiable logo such as the Marine Corps'
globe and anchor.
</P>
<P>
   The most identifiable Air Force symbol is the roundel, with a
star on a circular field with three bars on each side, that appears
on aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the roundel nor a similar symbol _ a red circle inside a
white star that was used before and in the early days of World War
II by legendary air commander Gen. H.H. ``Hap'' Arnold _ is
official.
</P>
<P>
   While it is ``very significant, very special to us,'' the Arnold
emblem never was made an official Air Force symbol, said Col. Ron
Rand, the service's public affairs director.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force research showed air personnel often felt more
allegiance to their units than the service itself. Keeping veteran
personnel in uniform and recruiting enough new ones is a crucial
issue for the Air Force, which fell short of its enlistment goal in
1999, the first time in 20 years that had happened.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force also is spending millions on its first paid
advertising campaign, has revamped an Internet site for recruiting
and is giving bonuses to new recruits in hopes of reversing a
recruiting tailspin that has affected every military branch except
the Marines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
