<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9228 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CENSUS-TROUBLE-HNS &LR;      02-07 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-TROUBLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CENSUS CHIEF FEARS POOR RESPONSE TO POPULATION COUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SHERRY SYLVESTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Census Director Kenneth Prewitt fears that Americans may be
too busy to participate in the all-important head count this year.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government plans to spend $7 billion on the
population count, including a multimillion-dollar advertising
campaign to encourage people to fill out forms.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt has stressed for months that census information is
confidential and will not be shared with other government agencies,
particularly the Immigration and Naturalization Service and the
Internal Revenue Service. But recently, Prewitt said
confidentiality worries are not the real problem facing the census.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the 35 million households which will not return their
census forms, only about 5 percent are hostile or afraid,'' Prewitt
said. ``The others simply can't be bothered.''
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt is calling for a ``great civic moment.'' Wherever he
goes, he urges Americans to fulfill their civic responsibilities by
participating in the census. But for increasingly busy Americans,
the timing of this census may be particularly bad.
</P>
<P>
   Figures released in December from the U.N. International Labor
Organization reveal Americans now are working more than citizens of
any other industrialized nation.
</P>
<P>
   The average American spends nearly 51 hours per week on the job.
That means that after sleeping and commuting time, there are fewer
than 20 hours remaining for what has been called ``leisure'' time,
even though many of those hours also must be earmarked for
housekeeping, laundry and maintenance activities.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a third of college-educated men and 20 percent of
educated women are working more than 50 hours per week.
</P>
<P>
   Data from the National Center for Health Statistics indicate
that 56 percent of Americans feel ``a lot or moderate'' stress, and
a Pennsylvania State University study found people feel so rushed
that almost 50 percent said they would be willing to give up a
day's pay to get a day off work.
</P>
<P>
   Similar research at the Family and Work Institute found 70
percent of all parents feel they do not spend enough time with
their children, and 85 percent of the public, including nonparents,
say they have family responsibilities that they don't have time to
fulfill.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt, who headed the National Opinion Research Center at the
University of Chicago before taking charge of the U.S. Census
Bureau, is aware of the data that show a constant decrease in
public participation because people feel they are too busy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The data are undeniable on voter participation and the
census,'' Prewitt spokesman David Hoffman said. ``So Dr. Prewitt is
saying to America: `We can do better.' The census is a unique
opportunity for civic responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Kalb, executive director of the Shorenstein Project at
the John F. Kennedy School of Government at Harvard University,
which is conducting the Vanishing Voter Project, said what the
Census Bureau is facing is similar to what his program is learning
about ``vanishing voters'' who display little interest in
campaigns, politics or government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans don't want to be rattled, disturbed or pressured
into thinking about serious global or national issues,'' Kalb said.
``The economy is fine; we're not at war; crime has gone down.''
</P>
<P>
   Kalb said it is not hard to imagine millions of Americans
collectively saying: ``Please Mr. Census Person, get off my back.
I'm not interested in talking with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Kalb also believes that in addition to being busy, Americans
also have become increasingly hostile to any kind of government
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people have a deep distrust of large
institutions, particularly government,'' Kalb said, noting the
Census Bureau's decision to hire a private advertising firm to
create census advertising is recognition of anti-government
hostility.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been an attempt to use extra (government) money to
make things seem as if they're not government programs, to package
ideas in ways that suggest they're a nongovernmental approach even
to governmental problems,'' Kalb said.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials are cautiously optimistic, saying they have
closed all the glaring gaps of the 1990 census, including updating
the national mailing list and targeting hard-to-count areas with
door-to-door enumerators.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt recently told the National Press Club that Census 2000
will be a benchmark on the status of civic responsibility, and a
lower response rate will indicate that the downward slide is
continuing. The census, conducted every 10 years, is used as the
basis for congressional districts and federal aid to cities and
states.
</P>
<P>
   But if the response to Census 2000 improves over the 1990 count,
Prewitt believes it will be a sign Americans are starting ``the
21st century by embracing our civic responsibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
