<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9230 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-TB-RESEARCH-HNS &LR;      02-07 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TB-RESEARCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DISCOVERY COULD LEAD TO NEW ASSAULT ON TUBERCULOSIS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CINDY TUMIEL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Forty years ago, doctors and scientists thought
antibiotics would make tuberculosis a disease of the past. Yet TB
remains a potent killer, responsible for an estimated 3 million
deaths worldwide each year.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, drug-resistant strains of the bacteria
remain serious public health threats in South Texas and other
border areas.
</P>
<P>
   But tuberculosis researchers in Texas have unraveled the secrets
of a key protein that helps the bacteria to thrive and to carry on
their destructive work in the lungs. Tuberculosis most often
attacks the lungs, leading to violent coughing and hemorrhage.
</P>
<P>
   The protein discovery could lead to new treatments, as well as
vaccines to protect people.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting in the scientific journal Nature Structural Biology,
James Sacchettini and his colleagues at Texas A&AMP;M University
defined the three-dimensional structure of the protein, called
antigen 85c.
</P>
<P>
   The protein is an enzyme that performs a major function in
building and maintaining the cell wall of the tuberculosis
bacteria, a protective coating that can prevent some antibiotics
from entering.
</P>
<P>
   It also plays a role in tricking healthy cells into letting the
bacteria invade them.
</P>
<P>
   Knowledge of the molecular structure of antigen 85 will help
scientists interfere with the bacterial life cycle, Sacchettini
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we know about its molecular structure, we can design
drugs that bind to this particular protein and inhibit its ability
to function to keep the bacteria alive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The protein helps the bacteria enter healthy cells called
macrophages, which normally kill invading bacteria, Sacchettini
said.
</P>
<P>
   The new knowledge about antigen 85c possibly could lead to
treatments interfering with that process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, now that we know the molecular structure, we can design
a really good antigen. This would allow us to vaccinate people so
their immune system would be ready for invasion by the bacteria,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Cox, director of clinical research at the Texas Center
for Infectious Diseases in San Antonio, said the A&AMP;M researchers
have made a ``potentially major breakthrough'' in the search for
much-needed new treatments.
</P>
<P>
   The overall number of tuberculosis cases is down _ the rate of
cases declined 10 percent in Texas, and 8 percent nationwide,
between 1997 and 1998. But the number of drug-resistant infections
is growing, Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly the San Antonio State Chest Hospital, the Center for
Infectious Diseases is one of the few remaining places in Texas
where tuberculosis patients can get long-term care beyond their
initial hospital stay.
</P>
<P>
   At any given time, the center houses 50 to 60 patients from
across the state, who generally stay 115 to 145 days, said James
Elkins, the facility's director.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disease takes a long time to be killed from the body,
regardless of antibiotic treatment,'' Elkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuberculosis remains a rampant killer in developing nations,
spurred on both by drug-resistant strains and the acquired immune
deficiency syndrome, or AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The World Health Organization estimates that one-third of the
world's population is infected with tuberculosis bacteria, and
about 200 million each year will develop an active infection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
