<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9255 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-ROBERTS-$ADV13-COX     02-07 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERTS-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STEVE AND COKIE ROBERTS, A COUPLE OF AUTHORS
 &HT;    Moving in (e) entertainment and (w) Washington categories for
release Sunday, Feb. 13.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. _ It's a winter morning and a foot of snow covers
the back yard where Cokie Boggs and Steve Roberts were married on a
warm September evening in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   President Lyndon Baines Johnson was among the 1,500 wedding
guests. A White House doctor used his tiny ear light to find
Steve's wedding band after the 4-year-old ring bearer dropped it in
the grass. The ceremony took place behind the sprawling suburban
home where Cokie grew up as the daughter of House Majority Leader
Hale Boggs, a Louisiana Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Cokie and Steve Roberts still live in that house. Their
daughter, Rebecca, was married in the same back yard. In the
springs and summers, Steve tends the vegetable garden first tilled
by his father-in-law nearly half a century ago. For years, Steve's
parents timed their drives from Florida to New Jersey to coincide
with the Seders that their Catholic daughter-in-law prepared for
Passover in this house.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the seasons of a marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, we've lived for better, not worse; richer, not poorer;
in health, not sickness,'' concludes Cokie. ``Still, after 33
years, we can't anticipate what will happen from this day
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From This Day Forward,'' a phrase from traditional wedding
vows, is the title of a new book by the journalist couple. She is a
news analyst and anchor for ABC-TV and National Public Radio. He
was a New York Times correspondent for 25 years and is now a
commentator on CNN and public television while also teaching about
the media and public affairs at George Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   The book chronicles their life together, from their meeting when
he was at Harvard and she was at Wellesley to their latest family
holiday welcoming the new millennium in Rome with her mother, Lindy
Boggs, the U.S. ambassador to the Vatican. It's a lively story of
the very mixed marriage of a Catholic woman from New Orleans to a
Jewish man from New Jersey. Fittingly, publisher William Morrow has
set a publication date of Valentine's Day for the 351-page volume.
</P>
<P>
   But the authors stress that they haven't composed a guide to
marital bliss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to set ourselves up as anything here. That is
truly asking for it,'' said Cokie, 56. ``That's why I feel very
strongly that we're just telling stories here, folks. We're not
saying 'how to,' because that is a recipe for disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not sermons. We're not preaching even the gospel of
marriage, although we say in the book we're very much partisans of
marriage for us and for most people,'' said Steve, 57. ``But we
also know that not every marriage is made in heaven. We also know
that marriage is not for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   This conversation is taking place in the Robertses' den over
cups of New Orleans-style coffee with chickory. Each half of the
couple has a lot to say. Sometimes they take turns talking.
Sometimes they interrupt each other. Sometimes they finish each
other's sentences. That's how much of the book goes, too. They told
their stories to Colleen Connors, a former student of Steve's, who
prodded them with questions when needed. The tales were transcribed
and edited.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't write about your experiences in the relationship in
each other's voice,'' said Cokie. ``We realized that the only way
you could do it is in dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   They worried that writing a book about their marriage might
jeopardize the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We very consciously said when we started this project that if
it became an issue between us, we'd drop the project,'' explained
Steve. ``The marriage is more important than the book.''
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   They dispute what she was wearing when they met. He recalls her
in charcoal-gray Bermuda shorts. She denies ever owning such
attire. They agree that he refused her request to stop for a snack
at Eddie Leonard's Sandwich Stop while driving to the Hay Adams
Hotel after their wedding reception.
</P>
<P>
   Steve was working for the Times and they were living in New York
a couple of years later when their son, Lee, was born. Shortly
thereafter, they moved to a mountaintop in Malibu and Steve covered
the West Coast for the Times. Their daughter, nicknamed Becca, was
born was born during their five years in California. Steve traveled
a lot. Cokie worked part-time as a TV producer but focused mostly
on motherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Then the New York Times sent Steve to Greece. The family lived
in a suburb of Athens. Again Steve was frequently on the road and
Cokie had the primary responsibility for daily child-rearing.
However, during a Turkish invasion of nearby Cyprus, she gained
notice in media circles for radio reports she filed for CBS News.
</P>
<P>
   At home, they schooled their children in the heritage of dual
faiths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living in that part of the world often reminded us of how
Jewish and Christian traditions are so intertwined,'' Steve writes
in the book. ``That made it easier to raise the kids in both
religions and celebrate everything!''
</P>
<P>
   In late 1977, they returned to Washington. Five years earlier,
Cokie's father had died in a plane crash in Alaska. Her mother,
Lindy, had been elected to represent his Louisiana district in
Congress. Now Steve and Cokie and their children moved back into
the house Cokie had first moved into at the age of 8. Not long
afterward, Mrs. Boggs moved into an apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Although they had eaten grits in California and Greece, the
Robertses' kids received a renewed dose of their Southern heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cokie's parents served in Congress for a combined total of 50
years,'' said Steve. ``It wasn't just that just they were from the
South. They represented the South.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Being from New Orleans is almost like an ethnicity,''
explained Cokie. ``It really is a particular thing. It's the people
and the food and our music and you do feel a sense of kinship
forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple also found that living in Washington was much more
expensive than living in Greece. They needed two incomes. So while
Steve wrote for the New York Times, Cokie reported for the National
Public Radio programs ``Morning Edition'' and ``All Things
Considered.''
</P>
<P>
   Their children grew up and left home and married. Their careers
took new paths. Steve left the Times, wrote a column for U.S. News
and World Report, then became a professor at George Washington
University. He still appears regularly on CNN's ``Late Edition''
and public television's ``Washington Week in Review.'' Meanwhile,
Cokie became co-anchor of the ABC Sunday program ``This Week With
Sam Donaldson and Cokie Roberts.''
</P>
<P>
   The transition caused some strains, the couple recalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I very quickly decided that the worst thing I could do was
let this become an issue between us, a competition,'' said Steve.
</P>
<P>
   It helped that he discovered a new deep satisfaction in
teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, the fact that Cokie was so successful made that
possible,'' he said. ``In some ways, it was liberating. If I was no
longer the main source of income, that freed me to spend time on an
enterprise'' where salary is not the chief reward.
</P>
<P>
   The new focus on career also helped Cokie adjust to her children
leaving home. ``My first definition of self had been as a mother
for 20 years,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, they agree, their story together has turned out pretty
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been incredibly blessed,'' Cokie writes.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
