Congress. Now Steve and Cokie and their children moved back into
the house Cokie had first moved into at the age of 8. Not long
afterward, Mrs. Boggs moved into an apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Although they had eaten grits in California and Greece, the
Robertses' kids received a renewed dose of their Southern heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cokie's parents served in Congress for a combined total of 50
years,'' said Steve. ``It wasn't just that just they were from the
South. They represented the South.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Being from New Orleans is almost like an ethnicity,''
explained Cokie. ``It really is a particular thing. It's the people
and the food and our music and you do feel a sense of kinship
forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple also found that living in Washington was much more
expensive than living in Greece. They needed two incomes. So while
Steve wrote for the New York Times, Cokie reported for the National
Public Radio programs ``Morning Edition'' and ``All Things
Considered.''
</P>
<P>
   Their children grew up and left home and married. Their careers
took new paths. Steve left the Times, wrote a column for U.S. News
and World Report, then became a professor at George Washington
University. He still appears regularly on CNN's ``Late Edition''
and public television's ``Washington Week in Review.'' Meanwhile,
Cokie became co-anchor of the ABC Sunday program ``This Week With
Sam Donaldson and Cokie Roberts.''
</P>
<P>
   The transition caused some strains, the couple recalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I very quickly decided that the worst thing I could do was
let this become an issue between us, a competition,'' said Steve.
</P>
<P>
   It helped that he discovered a new deep satisfaction in
teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, the fact that Cokie was so successful made that
possible,'' he said. ``In some ways, it was liberating. If I was no
longer the main source of income, that freed me to spend time on an
enterprise'' where salary is not the chief reward.
</P>
<P>
   The new focus on career also helped Cokie adjust to her children
leaving home. ``My first definition of self had been as a mother
for 20 years,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, they agree, their story together has turned out pretty
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been incredibly blessed,'' Cokie writes.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
