<HEADER>
A9298 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-07 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORK AHEAD FOR BUSH AFTER N.H. LOSS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ It was obvious last week _ and not just because
of the snow and single-digit temperatures _ that the governor
wasn't in Texas anymore.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't even in Iowa. There were too many mountains, too many
trees and too much John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's lopsided loss to the Arizona senator in New
Hampshire's first-in-the-nation primary doesn't end his
presidential bid. But it does tarnish the long-held perception that
Bush's ``coronation'' is inevitable, and he must rebound quickly in
upcoming contests in a friendlier South Carolina and other states.
</P>
<P>
   The race for the Republican presidential nod is still Bush's to
lose. The Texas governor scored an important victory in the Iowa
caucuses, continues to rake in millions of dollars in campaign
contributions and is backed by thousands of Republican leaders
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   And he doesn't have to campaign anymore in New Hampshire, where
all of the above advantages were of little help and may have even
been minuses.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a widespread misperception, it is not true that everyone
in New Hampshire has shared a cup of coffee with a presidential
candidate, has had a presidential candidate knock on his or her
door or even shaken hands with such a creature.
</P>
<P>
   But New Hampshire, like Iowa, is one of the few remaining places
in America where voters have numerous opportunities to see, hear
and question presidential contenders up close and personal in
countless town halls, school gymnasiums, diners and living rooms.
</P>
<P>
   This style of retail politics has been smothered in the
more-populous states like Texas, where well-funded candidates
usually win elections with paid television commercials,
endorsements, photo-ops and other events staged for a TV audience.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush was waging a national campaign, McCain skipped the
Iowa caucuses and bet his candidacy on New Hampshire, where he
spent much more time than Bush and outhustled the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   The senator was well-suited to New Hampshire campaigning. Vastly
outspent by Bush, McCain had nothing to lose by going one-on-one
with the voters, taking their questions at 114 town hall-style
meetings and being easily accessible to reporters. He was
constantly on the record with newspeople traveling on his campaign
bus.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush is as gregarious as McCain, the governor and his
handlers ran a more controlled, Texas-style campaign heavy on TV
commercials, big-name endorsements and photo-ops and had more
limited press contact.
</P>
<P>
   Bush drove a snowmobile, went bowling and flipped pancakes, all
of which produced some cutesy photos but didn't impress many
voters. He is, after all, running for president, not
chef-of-the-week.
</P>
<P>
   In one telling incident on the day before the election, Bush
abruptly canceled an appearance in Exeter when his political
handlers and taxpayer-paid, Texas security detail got spooked by a
small group of demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who traveled with no bodyguards, took demonstrators in
stride as part of New Hampshire's normal political process, made a
point of inviting them to ask questions at his town hall meetings
and often gave them answers they didn't want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's plain-spoken style _ laced with humor, sarcasm and
attacks on the ``big-money,'' special-interest Washington
establishment _ obviously appealed to New Hampshire voters, who
pride themselves on their independence and contrariness. They
apparently also were impressed with his military record and the
toughness that enabled him to survive five and one-half years as a
prisoner of war in North Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   They were turned off, not impressed, by Bush's support from
almost all of their state's Republican leaders. And, as history has
repeatedly demonstrated, they love voting against front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also benefited from New Hampshire laws that allowed
independent voters to cast ballots in the Republican primary. Those
independents were instrumental in his victory, although the senator
drew strong support from registered Republicans as well.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and McCain were editorially battered by The Union
Leader, the state's largest newspaper, which supported publisher
Steve Forbes' lost cause. But in the closing days of the campaign,
the ultra-conservative paper spat most of its venom at Bush, even
calling him ``Gov. Smirk'' in a Page One editorial.
</P>
<P>
   In conceding his loss, Bush called New Hampshire a ``bump in the
road for front-runners.'' The state often doesn't vote for the
eventual presidential winner, but it also has been known for
permanently derailing the White House hopes of some early
front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   Bush now has to work to keep that bump from becoming a sinkhole.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
