</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Sights and sounds, flavors and
feels of days gone by
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Alton T. Warner
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant memories of days gone by ...
</P>
<P>
   A clean yard with no grass. Mother raking the yard with a
dogwood brush broom.
</P>
<P>
   Riding to the grist mill on horseback to get corn ground into
meal.
</P>
<P>
   From under the house, the grunting of hogs trying to get warm on
a wintry night.
</P>
<P>
   The lowing of the milk cows as they make their way home.
</P>
<P>
   The old ones talking and the children listening. The old eating
first and the children last.
</P>
<P>
   The homeward journey of a family from town in a wagon, father
and mother on the spring seat eating cheese and crackers, the
children in the back licking stick candy, faithful dog trotting
under the wagon for protection from the hot sun.
</P>
<P>
   Hosts insisting on visitors staying for supper and spending the
night.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying hot flat irons or bricks to bed to warm your feet on a
cold night.
</P>
<P>
   Mother taking a broom and fluffing up your feather bed. (Mr.
Sealy never made a mattress that slept better.)
</P>
<P>
   A pitcher of water and a glass on the pulpit for the preacher
when he got thirsty.
</P>
<P>
   A lamp being held so the preacher could read the Scriptures.
</P>
<P>
   A preacher who had plowed all week and rode 10 miles horseback
to preach on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting until almost Christmastime before all the boys and many
of the girls were allowed to wear shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Axle grease used for everything from greasing the wagon to
greasing the kids for ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Flirting with serious illness if you did not wear a bag of
asafetida around your neck.
</P>
<P>
   Sassafras tea, considered a must for good health.
</P>
<P>
   The meat market coming to your door in a wagon, the meat covered
with sweet gum brush in 100-degree weather.
</P>
<P>
   When stove-fixing was a good profession.
</P>
<P>
   People saying ``Much obliged'' instead of ``Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Saddle and harness hanging on the porch.
</P>
<P>
   When cheese didn't spoil, and milk was kept cool in the well.
</P>
<P>
   Mother making hominy.
</P>
<P>
   Half-soling shoes for the family at night.
</P>
<P>
   Gathering hickory nuts.
</P>
<P>
   When apples and oranges hidden under the bed before Christmas
smelled sweeter than any perfume.
</P>
<P>
   Block and chain on a dog to keep him in the yard.
</P>
<P>
   Washing at the spring with homemade soap that took off dirt and
skin.
</P>
<P>
   Sound and smell of coffee being ground in the early morning.
</P>
<P>
   Man plowing and a colt following alongside.
</P>
<P>
   Gun rack made of limbs over the doorway.
</P>
<P>
   A farmer hog-hunting on horseback, his cur dogs muzzled.
</P>
<P>
   When mothers had no time for nervous breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Quilting parties, candy pulling, log rolling and chimney
daubing.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors digging neighbors' graves.
</P>
<P>
   Peddler selling his goods from a wagon and taking chickens for
pay.
</P>
<P>
   Burning old rags and cow chips to keep away mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer going down the trail in early morning, hollering and a
neighbor answering.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing you were afraid of for your children was a mad
dog or a fighting cow.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Alton T. Warner lives in Lufkin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
