<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
 Attn Sports Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sports stories from The New York Times News Service for
 &UR; TUESDAY &LR; , Feb. 8.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on
John Rocker, the combustible Atlanta Braves reliever whose
suspension for highly offensive language is now being appealed by
the Major League Players Association. That appeal is now scheduled
to be heard in New York on Wednesday. By Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-KNICKS-HORNETS (Charlotte, N.C.) _ N.Y. Knicks at Charlotte,
7:30 p.m. EST start. By Selena Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-STJOHNS-BARKLEY (New York) _ St. John's expects to hear from
the NCAA on Monday about the eligibility of its star point guard,
Erick Barkley, who was suspended over the weekend in what the
school says is nitpicking by the association. By Judy Battista.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-PEBBLE-BEACH (Pebble Beach, Calif.) _ Final round of the
AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach tournament. By Clifton Brown.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-DAVIS-CUP (Harare, Zimbabwe) _ Now that John McEnroe is 1-0
as Davis Cup captain, he gets to experience what Jeff van Gundy
does as coach. He has to dole out the minutes. Next up for the
United States team following its narrow 3-2 escape here against
Zimbabwe on Sunday is the Czech Republic, in April in Los Angeles.
McEnroe has a while before naming his starters, but he may have
issues that are longer term to deal with. First and foremost, what
to do, if anything, about Pete Sampras. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other sports
stories from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News Service,
Hearst News Service, The Arizona Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San Francisco
Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 1538EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9313 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      02-07 1496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of TUESDAY, Feb.
8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIFE-BEYOND-EARTH (Undated) _ Two prominent scientists say
the conventional wisdom the intelligent life is common beyond the
Earth is way off base. Drawing on new findings in astronomy,
geology and paleontology, the two argue that humans might be alone,
at least in the stellar neighborhood, and perhaps in the entire
cosmos. They say modern science is showing that Earth's composition
and stability are extraordinarily rare. Most everywhere else, the
radiation levels are too high, the right chemical elements too rare
in abundance, the hospitable planets too few in number and the rain
of killer rocks too intense for life ever to have evolved into
advanced communities. Alien microbes may survive in many places as
a kind of cosmic shower scum, they say, but not extraterrestrials
civilized enough to be awash in technology. By William J. Broad.
(2100 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIFE-HUNT (Undated) _ More than a million people and
computers are now involved in processing data that may involve
transmission of signals from alien life. By William J. Broad. (385
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MOTHERS (Undated) _ Dr. Sarah Blaffer Hrdy (cq) examines the
complexities of motherhood and concludes it is a barter, a supple,
ever-changing push-me pull-you negotiation between two individuals
who need each other and are closely related, but who are not clones
and so do not always see eye to eye, or breast to mouth for that
matter. Hrdy, in a new book, tells of motherhood from a distinctly
Darwinian perspective, an appraisal of how a welter of selective
forces have shaped maternal behaviors, impulses and strategies over
tens of thousands of years. By Natalie Angier.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-DRUGS (San Francisco) _ The Doctor's World: In less
than four years, the euphoria over the success of new drug
combinations to treat AIDS has yielded to the sobering challenge of
dealing with the drugs' complications and failures. By Lawrence K.
Altman. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CLIMATE-AFRICA () _ It has become increasingly clear to
scientists that in the 10,000 years since the last ice age ended,
the world's climate has often served up droughts far surpassing
anything seen in the last 150 years, resulting in some cases in the
collapse of entire ancient civilizations. Now a new study has found
that over the last millennium in equatorial East Africa,
decades-long droughts far longer and more severe than any in
recorded weather history have alternated with periods when rainfall
was heavier than today. By William K. Stevens. (1275 words)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CLIMATE-YELLOWSTONE (Big Sky, Mont.) _ There is mounting
concern among biologists and other researchers that global climate
change may be creating conditions in and around the Yellowstone
National Park that are inhospitable for a tree that produces a nut
crucial to wildlife. If climate warming is the real, long-term
phenomenon many experts think it is, it could set off a domino-like
series of changes that could kill 90 percent or more of the white
bark pine trees and possibly compromise the future of the
threatened grizzly bear. By Jim Robbins. (1550 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PREDICTING-DURATION (Undated) _ Two experts dispute the
theory that the likely future duration of anything, from the human
race to a musical playing on Broadway, can be predicted. All you
need to know is the time that has passed since the entity in
question came into being until the moment when you asked, ``How
long will this last?'' By James Glanz. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on the
mysteries of ball lightning, a tracking device for the honeybee and
the ways honeybees measure distance. By Henry Fountain. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-CANCER (Undated) _ New ways to analyze various risks
with various strategies taken after breast cancer is diagnosed. By
Denise Grady. (1330 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-THERAPY (Boston) _ A Boston medical center has
suspended its gene therapy tests because of safety concerns arising
from a student's death last year in a similar trial program in
Pennsylvania. By Philip J. Hilts.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COLORBLIND-AID (Undated) _ New glasses to help the
colorblind distinguish hues have been approved by the Food and Drug
Administration, becoming the first lenses specifically authorized
for color deficient vision. While some users are pleased, many
experts caution that such lenses do not make people see colors as
people with normal vision do. And while the lenses can help people
tell some colors apart, they can make it harder to distinguish
other colors. By Andrew Pollack. (1220 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BOULDERING (New York) _ The Novice: Bouldering in Central
Park, a form of rock climbing for those afraid of heights. It moves
more horizontally than vertically. By Liz Neporent. (825 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Personal Health: Nuts are back on
the menu, even for people on strict low-fat diets, because they
provide so many health benefits, including lowering cholesterol and
blood pressure. By Jane E. Brody. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and
nutrition:
</P>
<P>
   _ Boston researchers may have found a way to reduce the risk of
mother-child transmission of HIV by using a vaccination of
antibodies instead of the live virus. (270 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A new study makes a tentative link between a strong wind and
migraines, but primarily the researcher discovered that people had
trouble telling just what set off the migraines. (325 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ The American Heart Association is reminding people that
decongestants can be hazardous for people with high blood pressure.
(230 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A twice-a-week, monthlong program of physical therapy and
exercise training significantly reduced pain levels and surgery
rates among patients with arthritic knees, according to a study in
this month's issue of the Annals of Internal Medicine. (175 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A study of Pennsylvania winters has found that a combination
of just over an inch of snow and temperatures below 20 degrees
caused death rates from heart attacks to triple among men aged 35
to 49 years old. (240 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: I got a brace
when I was 7 to correct idiopathic scoliosis. Is this still the
standard practice? Is it true that this problem is
disproportionately common in girls? By C. Claiborne Ray. (350
words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SF-MODERN-ART (San Francisco) _ Arts in America: Blessed with
new sun-filled galleries, the San Francisco MOMA is on a $130
million buying spree. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   YELTSIN-MEMOIR (New York) _ Boris Yeltsin's memoirs to be
published here. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   TIR-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ ``Tir Na n'Og'' at the New
Victory theater. Reviewed by Lawrence Van Gelder.
</P>
<P>
   UPDIKE-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Gertrude and Claudius,'' by
John Updike (Knopf). Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   TV-NOVA-REVIEW (Undated) _ On PBS's Nova: ``Trillion Dollar
Bet.'' Reviewed by Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (``s'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on
John Rocker, the combustible Atlanta Braves reliever whose
suspension for highly offensive language is now being appealed by
the Major League Players Association. That appeal is now scheduled
to be heard in New York on Wednesday. By Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-KNICKS-HORNETS (Charlotte, N.C.) _ N.Y. Knicks at Charlotte,
7:30 p.m. EST start. By Selena Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-STJOHNS-BARKLEY (New York) _ St. John's expects to hear from
the NCAA on Monday about the eligibility of its star point guard,
Erick Barkley, who was suspended over the weekend in what the
school says is nitpicking by the association. By Judy Battista.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-PEBBLE-BEACH (Pebble Beach, Calif.) _ Final round of the
AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach tournament. By Clifton Brown.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-DAVIS-CUP (Harare, Zimbabwe) _ Now that John McEnroe is 1-0
as Davis Cup captain, he gets to experience what Jeff van Gundy
does as coach. He has to dole out the minutes. Next up for the
United States team following its narrow 3-2 escape here against
Zimbabwe on Sunday is the Czech Republic, in April in Los Angeles.
McEnroe has a while before naming his starters, but he may have
issues that are longer term to deal with. First and foremost, what
to do, if anything, about Pete Sampras. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories
from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst
Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona Republic, Kansas
City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San
Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
