<HEADLINE>
LACING UP VALENTINES: CORSETS AS FASHION  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for Valentine's Day, Feb. 14)   (This 300-word ``separate-buy'' article is from the International
Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
  
 By SUZY MENKES  
 c.2000 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It looks like an unusual St. Valentine's Day gift: a
heart-shaped vase of lacy, metallic lattice for your dozen red
roses. But it is your body you are supposed to squeeze into this
iron contraption from the 16th century.
</P>
<P>
   Corsets _ rigid, decorative, patterned with rosebuds, laced with
pretty ribbons or embroidered with bouquets of flowers _ are on
display like so many surreal sculptures at New York's Fashion
Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   And just in case you think this ancient way of reshaping the
female is history, ``The Corset: Fashioning the Body,'' which runs
until April 22, shows modern examples: from luscious bodices with
lashings of romance from Christian Lacroix haute couture, through
those saucy underwear-as-outerwear creations in which Jean Paul
Gaultier famously turned Madonna's bosoms into twin peaks.
</P>
<P>
   The show's curator, Valerie Steele, is not afraid to suggest the
corset's erotic or even fetishistic underbelly.
</P>
<P>
   That seems cute and saucy in a collection of vintage postcards
of Victorian belles swelling in their stays, but sinister when the
tortured rib cage of a current corset freak are shown in ``before
and after'' X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we've replaced the boned corset with the hard body,'' says
Steele, explaining how the corset has moved from a hidden _ if
decorative _ corrective to a fashion statement. But maybe it always
was.
</P>
<P>
   Steele contrasts the steamy Belle Epoque scarlet creations for
courtesans with the ``white for chastity'' wedding corsets with
hand-span waists.
</P>
<P>
   This naughty-versus-nice spirit runs through the show, from a
bodice full of artificial roses from Charles James in 1937 to
Thierry Mugler's dominatrix in shiny vinyl and Alexander McQueen
orthopedic laced leather.
</P>
<P>
   But even today corsets can be about hearts and flowers _ as in
Anna Sui's ribbon-laced floral bodice worn with blue jeans. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 300-word article from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is: weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
