<SLUG> BC-EASTEURO-HAIDER-REAX-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENTRAL EUROPEANS REACT HESITANTLY OVER HAIDER  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 725-word ``separate-buy'' article is from the International
Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``i'' international news and ``a'' general news files.)  
  
 By PETER S. GREEN  
 c.2000 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE _ Austria's Central European neighbors, some of which
hope to join the European Union one day, have reacted cautiously to
the inclusion of Jorg Haider's xenophobic Freedom Party in the
Austrian government.
</P>
<P>
   While echoing the condemnation of the Austrian developments
heard in the West, these countries also are hesitating to shout too
loudly at a country with which their historical ties are long and
deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Central European countries think they are playing it
safe: Don't get Haider mad and keep a low profile,'' said Jiri
Pehe, head of New York University's program in Prague and a former
adviser of President Vaclav Havel of the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Havel and President Milan Kucan of Slovenia both roundly
condemned the compromise that has brought rightist extremists to
power in a democratic Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But Hungary and Slovakia, both of which were allied with Hitler
during the War, have played down the importance of Haider's
newfound power. The Czech government broke with Havel and also took
a wait-and-see attitude.
</P>
<P>
   The EU move to isolate Austria has also fueled the significant
Euroskeptic movement in Central Europe. Populist politicians have
painted an intrusive and bureaucratic Union as a modern version of
the Soviet Union, which occupied the region for close to half a
century.
</P>
<P>
   ``It plays well into the hands of people who describe the EU as
an interventionist organization which does not respect the
sovereignty of its members,'' said Jiri Sedivy, director of the
Institute for International Relations in Prague. ``They say, `Look
what will happen to us in five years' time.'''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Czech Parliament, Vaclav Klaus, said last
week, ``It seems very strange to me that Austrian voters elected
someone, and somebody from outside wants to dictate to them who
will be in their government.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Viktor Orban of Hungary said he was ``surprised''
by the EU move. ``It must be considered whether anybody has the
right to intervene,'' he said, adding that the EU was ``laying out
paths which to some extent run against the will of the Austrian
people.''
</P>
<P>
   His foreign minister, Janos Martonyi, has said that Hungary does
not plan to join EU states in isolating Austria diplomatically.
</P>
<P>
   In Slovakia, the deputy foreign minister, Jan Figel, said his
country, which has just joined the EU expansion short list, had to
look after its own interests first. Austria is Slovakia's biggest
trading partner.
</P>
<P>
   Relations with Austria are fraught with historic overtones.
Austria sees itself as Nazi's Germany's first victim, but
historians generally agree that Austria was a willing ally of the
Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   And until World War I broke up the Austro-Hungarian Empire, most
of Austria's neighbors had been its imperial subjects for
centuries. During the Cold War, Austria's neutrality made it one of
the few openings the captive countries of Eastern Europe had to the
free world.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a certain amount of sympathy for Haider's agenda
in Central Europe. Still struggling with their transitions from
communism and central planning to democracy and free markets, many
of the Central European countries have suffered the same problems
that won Haider so many votes in Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Six Central European countries hope to join the EU this decade,
but Haider's party has openly called for the EU expansion eastward
to be halted and for tighter controls on immigration from what it
calls ``the East.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, Haider agreed with his coalition partners, the
conservative People's Party, to support the EU's planned expansion
eastward.
</P>
<P>
   Havel, who is hospitalized with the flu, said through a
spokesman that ``what Haider has said conflicts with the principles
on which a unified Europe was built after World War II, as well as
the fundamental principles of democracy and human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Kucan said Haider's success was ``not a good omen for the future
of Europe'' and ``a danger to Slovenia,'' which had been one of the
victims of Nazism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such a turning to the wrong pages of history is dangerous for
Europe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighboring countries are also worried by Haider's calls for
them to return confiscated property to Austrians who, as citizens
of Hitler's greater German Reich, were expelled at the end of World
War II from what is now Slovenia, the Czech Republic and Slovakia. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 725-word article from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is: weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
