<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9356 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-HEART-DISEASE-COX     02-07 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-DISEASE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An ounce of prevention goes far in reducing heart disease
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In our fascination with fancy technology and
shocking studies, media reports tend to miss the main points about
heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   First, heart disease is much easier and cheaper to prevent than
to repair. Second, the most valuable technologies are the ones that
identify people most likely to develop it before they need to
repair it.
</P>
<P>
   Heart surgeons can do miraculous things. But by the time a heart
patient meets a surgeon, he or she is probably assured of some
permanent damage and considerable expense, not to mention the risk
of Alzheimer's-type dementia from surgery. Doctors have to stop the
heart to perform these operations, so it's best to halt heart
disease well before needing the chain-link safety net of heart
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Computer imaging and genetic rearranging are becoming valuable
tools, but so are the somewhat older technologies of writing on
paper and growing edible vegetables. So while studies about
baldness and hormone-replacement therapy received much attention in
the past two weeks, it's too bad significant research about stress
in particular and demeanor in general was generally ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Papers like this actually divert attention from the primary
message,'' Dr. Philip Greenland, a Northwestern University
cardiologist, said of the baldness study. It correlated heart
disease with hair loss at the crown of the head but not a receding
hairline.
</P>
<P>
   Greenland dismissed the need for further research into which
lost hairs warn of heart disease, because ``about 80 to 90 percent
of what we need to prevent heart disease is already known. The
problem is that addressing those behaviors is something a lot of
Americans don't want to do, so they are looking for other
excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, let's not kid ourselves about the big roles of
high blood pressure and cholesterol, low physical activity,
smoking, obesity, diabetes, poverty and diet. In one of the
recently ignored studies, the Jan. 29 British Medical Journal
reported that what we do as adults had far more to do with who gets
heart and blood vessel disease than our birth weight, childhood
snacks and parents' social class.
</P>
<P>
   A problem with these same-old-thing studies is they are not
being supplemented with research into how to help people
realistically choose to walk more flights of stairs and eat fewer
french fries. They also aren't as eye-catching as the recent news
that postmenopausal women are 40 percent more likely to get breast
cancer if they are taking estrogen and progestin supplements.
</P>
<P>
   News reporters make their livings with words and tend not to be
very good with numbers, although the pages usually come out in the
right order. TV reporters are more candid about this flaw, actually
admitting that we are ``not going to believe'' what they're going
to tell us whenever they get around to interrupting their
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   So a few things were sadly omitted from most of these reports:
Estrogen supplements reduce the rate of heart disease; women after
menopause are more than 11 times as likely to die of heart disease
than of breast cancer, and the researchers' main point was that
choices about drugs should not be made independently of choices
about diet and exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Because we probably won't all adopt Mormon lifestyles tomorrow,
it's valuable to find ways of detecting the earliest stages of
heart disease. So it's too bad so little was made of the Jan. 18
report in Circulation: Journal of the American Heart Association,
that mental stress can intensify potentially fatal irregular heart
rhythms, and of the report in the January Journal of Health
Psychology that stress can provoke the poor blood flow that can
cause a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   The latter research showed that a five-minute mental stress test
can help reveal a person's risk for heart disease. Other research
last year recommended monitoring the progress of an older woman's
heart disease with simple question about how well she's handling
household chores. Other research has shown better ways of
interpreting the basic treadmill stress test and the heart rate
after it.
</P>
<P>
   Reports in the last year also have shown that impotence, a
spouse's heart attack and fatty deposits elsewhere in the
bloodstream are largely ignored warning signs of heart disease.
They're not as exciting as the genetic markers, newly discovered
proteins and computerized images that also signal dangers, but
they're also not as expensive. They deserve attention.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb is the Dayton (OH) Daily News health writer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
