<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9360 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-PREGNANT-SUPPLEMENTS0     02-07 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREGNANT-SUPPLEMENTS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    USE OF SUPPLEMENTS FOR MORNING SICKNESS IS DEREGULATED
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Food and Drug Administration (FDA) on Monday
gave manufacturers the right to sell herbal remedies and other
``natural'' products to treat morning sickness without first
proving that the preparations are safe for unborn children.
</P>
<P>
   The rule went into effect despite objections from health
advocates and experts on birth defects.
</P>
<P>
   The agency declared that the bouts of nausea which plague at
least one-third of all pregnant women are not actually a disease.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, when supplement makers say their preparations relieve
it, they will not be legally claiming to treat a disease.
</P>
<P>
   That means they will not have to prove in advance that the
products are effective, or even safe, as drug manufacturers must.
</P>
<P>
   The exemption also applies to leg edema, or bloating, associated
with pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battle has only begun,'' Dr. Sidney Wolfe, director of the
Public Citizen Health Research Group, said Monday. ``We are going
to keep pressing on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe and Dr. Godfrey Oakley Jr., a birth defects expert at
Emory University in Atlanta, wrote to FDA Commissioner Jane Henney
last week, objecting to the rule.
</P>
<P>
   They said the FDA ``seems to have thrown caution to the wind and
appears willing to endanger unborn babies by pretending that
medical condition such as morning sickness and edema of pregnancy
are not diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the products have never been tested in pregnant
women,'' Oakley said Monday. ``Something that might be viewed as
generally safe in an adult could be quite harmful to a fetus,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate letter to Henney, Dr. Philip J. Landrigan of Mt.
Sinai Medical Center in New York warned that the FDA was failing
``to recognize the unique vulnerability of the fetus and infants to
patent medications.''
</P>
<P>
   Landrigan, former chairman of a National Academy of Sciences
committee on the effect of pesticides on the diets of children and
infants, said the rule ``fails to recognize the unique
vulnerability of the fetus and infants to patent medications,'' or
supplements.
</P>
<P>
   The provision was included in new supplement labeling
requirements. The burgeoning food supplements industry had lobbied
against regulating pregnancy as a ``disease.''
</P>
<P>
   When the FDA published a preliminary draft of the labeling rule
in 1998, it did not include the language declaring that morning
sickness and edema are not diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The agency received more than 220,000 comments on the draft
rule, including many from supplement users who thought it would
restrict their access to the preparations.
</P>
<P>
   Annette Dickinson, vice president for scientific and regulatory
affairs of the Council for Responsible Nutrition, a supplements
industry trade group, said she hoped the industry could work with
concerned physicians such as Wolfe and Oakley to develop labeling
requirements to protect fetuses.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that some supplements, such as vitamins and folic
acid, are recommended for pregnant women.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
