<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9362 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-KORESH-DEVICE-HNS &LR;      02-07 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KORESH-DEVICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GROUP CLAIMS TO HAVE NEW EVIDENCE IN WACO SIEGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DICK J. REAVIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Volunteers rebuilding David Koresh's chapel at the
Branch Davidian compound near here say they found an incendiary
device, allegedly fired by government agents trying to end the
standoff with the cult leader in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But the volunteers, who announced the discovery on an Internet
page, have declined to turn the alleged evidence over to the
authorities. And it appears to be about the size of a D-cell
battery.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Branch Davidian church and residential complex
burned to the ground on April 19, 1993, there has been speculation
that government agents, not Koresh or his followers, ignited the
fire that killed some 80 people, including several children.
</P>
<P>
   Similar charges are being raised in a wrongful death lawsuit
brought by survivors of the assault.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, scheduled for trial in mid-May, alleges that
pyrotechnic rounds fired by federal agents, ``probably caused
and/or contributed to the spread and intensity of the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the search for a fire-starting device has produced at
least three promising objects, the plaintiffs' charges have yet to
be confirmed. Last summer, Colorado filmmaker Michael McNulty, one
of the figures behind the Emmy-award-winning documentary, ``Waco:
The Rules of Engagement,'' claimed to have found the mystery
devices.
</P>
<P>
   While searching through the contents of a vault of evidence kept
at the Texas Department of Public Safety headquarters in Austin,
McNulty found three objects, 40mm in diameter, labeled by the Texas
Rangers as rifle silencers.
</P>
<P>
   McNulty said they are flash-bang grenades, capable of igniting
fires. The documentary filmmaker explained his findings to the
Rangers, who in August promised to confirm, or deny, his charges _
but the Rangers have not yet said what their examination concluded.
</P>
<P>
   McNulty's claims led to confirmation by retired FBI agents that
pyrotechnic 40mm tear gas rounds had been used at the Branch
Davidian compound. But they said the rounds were not used against
wooden buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has appointed a special counsel, former
Sen. John C. Danforth of Missouri, to investigate the government's
handling of the assault at the Branch Davidian compound near Waco.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-January, while rebuilding the church, volunteers found a
burned artifact that they took to be the remains of an incendiary
device, an illumination round, or maybe, a flash-bang grenade. They
promptly posted a photo on the group's site,
``rebuildthechurch.com,'' identifying the object as a ``pyrotechnic
grenade recently unearthed during clean up.''
</P>
<P>
   The volunteers say they do not trust the government to
investigate the item and are hiding it.
</P>
<P>
   The item is about 2 inches tall, and in the pile of rubble where
they found it, there was a wad of crusty gray material, which the
volunteers suspect is the remnant of a propellant charge.
</P>
<P>
   But its base measures 32mm in diameter, not 40mm _ the size of
D-cell batteries, not military pyrotechnic rounds. On the inner
side of the object's base is a plastic ring, marked by its
manufacturer into five sections. One of the sections bears the
letters ``APC,'' and adjacent section, the notation ``JI.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a technical adviser for the Eveready Battery Co. said
that APC is a code on its products, denoting ``a contractor that we
used for subassembly.'' The wadding found with the alleged
incendiary includes a small strip of cloth, like the cloth strips
that are used to envelop the electrolytes in batteries today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
