<HEADER>
A9372 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-LIFE-HUNT-NYT &LR;      02-07 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LIFE-HUNT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1.6 MILLION CYBERLINGS GO A-HUNTING FOR ALIENS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Wis.)   (Science Times)  
(Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the 2nd graf instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems. Web site in last graf
is CQ.) 
 (af)  
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earthlings are so enamored of aliens that 1.6 million of them in
224 countries have recently joined an effort that harnesses home
and office computers to the job of sifting through a few zillion
radio bands to hunt for signs of intelligent life among the stars.
</P>
<P>
   The SETI(AT)home project of the University of California at
Berkeley uses idle computers linked to the Internet to plow through
signals collected by the huge dish at Arecibo, Puerto Rico,
searching for intelligently made radion signals amid the celestial
static. The biggest of all the world's radio telescopes, at 1,000
feet in diameter, it is also the best single antenna for gathering
faint signals.
</P>
<P>
   Through the Internet, the project distributes software that
enables home computer users to help scientists crunch Arecibo data
in what its creators call the world's largest ad hoc supercomputer.
The software works as a screen saver, analyzing data only when
computers are idle. Once the data have been analyzed, a process
that can take days, they are returned to Berkeley for another slice
of the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Since May, when the project started, volunteers have donated
165,000 years of computing time to analyzing radio emissions from
outer space.
</P>
<P>
   Among the top performers listed on the website: Sun Microsystems
(287 years of computer time), Intel Performance Labs (199 years),
the Computer Aided Engineering lab at the University of
Wisconsin-Madison (89 years), America Online (71 years), Microsoft
(41 years), Fermi National Laboratory (59 years), Pixar (29 years),
Compaq Telecom Engineering (26 years), A.W. Spence Middle School in
Dallas (25 years), Frank Terhaar in Yonkers, N.Y. (24 years) and
someone named Jean-Luc Picard (six years).
</P>
<P>
   ``So far we don't have any really exciting signals,'' said Dan
Werthimer, the project's chief scientist. ``But it's early in the
game. We've only just begun and Earthlings are pretty primitive in
this field. We're just scratching the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   Free hunt software can be downloaded from
www.setiathome.ssl.berkeley.edu, which has been done 1.6 million
times, Werthimer said. Among the effort's sponsors are the
Planetary Society, the University of California, Sun Microsystems,
Fuji Film, Paramount Pictures, Intel, the SETI Institute and
private donors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 1645EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9373 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-EDITORIAL-AUSTRIA-COX     02-07 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-AUSTRIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Austria's far right poses concerns
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have Western Europe and U.S. capitals gone overboard in reaction
to the new coalition government in Austria? Have they shunned it
diplomatically as if it were a pariah just because one of the
principals in its new regime has a history of soft-on-Nazi
utterances?
</P>
<P>
   No to both questions. While it is true that Joerg Haider, the
controversial leader of the new-to-power Freedom Party, won't hold
a position in the coalition, he is expected to have a profound
influence on policy-making in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   And that bodes no good. Here is a man whose parents were rabid
Nazis and who presides over an estate once owned by Jews who had to
flee. Here is a man who complimented Adolf Hitler's ``orderly''
employment policies, who saluted veterans of Waffen SS death squads
as ``decent people of good character'' and put a reverse spin on
places like Auschwitz and Dachau, calling them ``punishment
camps.''
</P>
<P>
   All those remarks, he says, were mistakes, and he's sorry about
them.
</P>
<P>
   But Haider's word isn't worth much. Last weekend, for instance,
no sooner had he signed a declaration forced on him by Austrian
President Thomas Klestil in which Haider had to denounce
xenophobia, anti-Semitism and racism than he repudiated the
declaration as ``an affront to the Austrian public.''
</P>
<P>
   He then went on to startle history-sensitive Europeans by
suggesting Sudeten Germans expelled from Czechoslovakia after World
War II were entitled to the same sympathy and compensation as Jews
rousted by the Nazis. No doubt he also caused a ripple of fear in
Vienna by hinting that Klestil should be investigated for treason.
</P>
<P>
   Why should the West be concerned over Austria? Partly because it
never came to grips with its Nazi past as Germany had to do after
World War II. Partly because the ultranationalist, anti-immigrant
sentiment that lured thousands of Austrians to Haider's party
resonates in more important countries like France, Italy, Germany
and Britain, threatening years of effort toward economic
integration and away from cross-border frictions.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that it's OK to bring elements into a government that
only pay lip service to democracy and the rule of law should have
no place in a civilized Europe. And the place to make that point is
Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
