<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9374 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HEALTH-WEB-COX     02-07 0263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-WEB-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinical tests offer alternatives
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There must be something more I can do.'' It's a common
reaction in health care, both from people just diagnosed with a
potentially life-threatening illness and from patients and family
members dealing with a long-lasting chronic problem.
</P>
<P>
   Often, the ``something else'' turns out to be enrolling in a
clinical trial: a test of a new medicine or treatment on a group of
volunteers that allows limited enrollment and is performed under
strict medical and ethical guidelines. Members of trials can have
access to drugs or dosages that are not yet on the market, though
they usually don't know what they're taking and are given no
assurance that it will work.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible, though time-consuming, to find clinical trials by
talking to specialists and calling medical centers. A new Web site,
drugMonitor (drugmonitor.com/default.htm), offers to make that
process easier by providing a free nationwide gateway to trials
that are recruiting patients. The site allows you to search for
trials by disease or by geographical location, and it offers
automatic e-mail notification of new trials as they are registered.
The site, launched in January, is well-designed but looks
low-traffic; at the moment, it lists only trials for allergies,
arthritis, asthma, back pain, heart disease, depression and
insomnia.
</P>
<P>
   M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constiution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
