<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9377 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-NEWSSTAND08-COX     02-07 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain stands tall on this week's covers
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judging from the covers of the newsweeklies, you'd think John
McCain was the Man of the Century. Instead, the war hero, Arizona
senator and presidential candidate is simply the man of the hour in
the wake of his surprise victory in the New Hampshire primary. Can
he sustain the momentum? That's the question all the pundits are
asking. One factor in his favor, says Time ($3.50), is that half
the state primaries through March 14 allow independents _ who seem
to be favoring McCain _ to vote Republican or Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   In Newsweek's ($3.50) analysis package, Jonathan Alter examines
the candidate's wild ride and wonders whether his refreshingly
straight-talking, spontaneous approach will lead to pitfalls or the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More Rocker reaction: Speaking of outspokenness and
spontaneity, U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($3.50) columnist John Leo
weighs in on the John Rocker controversy and major-league
baseball's punishment. Though not defending Rocker (he calls him
``a bigoted oaf''), Leo takes exception to Commissioner Bud Selig's
role as arbiter of politically correct behavior. Asks Leo: Why
punish speech when you don't punish actions?
</P>
<P>
   ``Selig didn't suspend the Colorado Rockies pitcher who recently
pleaded guilty to beating his wife or the Arizona Diamondbacks
reliever charged with smacking his wife around as their young child
watched. Surely these cases, too, had a negative effect on the
salability of baseball as a wholesome product.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Peanuts and pop-ups: The New Yorker ($3) has long been known
as much for its humor as its serious pieces. Two brilliant examples
in the current issue are ``Abstract Thought Is a Warm Puppy,'' Art
Spiegelman's illustrated elegy for Charles Schulz's ``Peanuts,''
and Georgia writer Frank Gannon's version of VH1's pop-up video as
it applies to English literature.
</P>
<P>
   In a three-page strip, Spiegelman brings together his Maus
creation with Schulz's Snoopy. Perched atop Snoopy's house, Maus
reflects on ``Peanuts'' and its influence: ```Peanuts' was `about
nothing' years before Jerry Seinfeld was even born.''
</P>
<P>
   Gannon, meanwhile, adds pop-up humor to three famous literary
passages: John Donne's ``Holy Sonnet 10,'' Andrew Marvell's ``To
His Coy Mistress'' and Dylan Thomas' ``Do Not Go Gentle Into That
Good Night.'' For example, Gannon's pop-up to Marvell's opening
lines, ``Had we but world enough and time, this coyness, Lady, were
no crime,'' is ``Sodomy is still a crime in Mississippi.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Ramsey business: In the year after JonBenet Ramsey's
death, Brill's Content ($3.95) reports, 804 children age 12 or
younger were murdered in the United States. Why, then, did the
Boulder, Colo., case become such a media sensation? Brill's
reporter Katherine Rosman attributes it to the media's hunger for
the ``Next Big Story'' after O.J. Simpson and Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been a cottage industry of books and TV shows. A
CBS TV movie based on Lawrence Schiller's book ``Perfect Murder,
Perfect Town'' is scheduled to air Feb. 17 and March 1. Seven books
about the case are already on the shelves, with two more on the way
this spring. Former Boulder police Detective Steve Thomas'
``JonBenet: Inside the Ramsey Murder Investigation'' is due in
April, and John and Patsy Ramsey's book, ``Death of Innocence,'' is
scheduled for March publication.
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean the Ramseys expect to profit from their child's
murder? The Ramseys' lawyer insists that any proceeds will be used
to pay off legal debts, with the remainder donated to the JonBenet
Ramsey Children's Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Slimmer singer: Look up the word ``diva'' in the dictionary,
and you're likely to find a picture of Mariah Carey. At least
that's the portrait Mim Udovitch paints in an entertaining Rolling
Stone ($3) interview. Carey, shot in several revealing poses, talks
about her music, her affair with New York Yankees star Derek Jeter
and her dieting obsession after Joan Rivers' catty remark about her
weight at last year's Academy Awards. Also of note is a guide to
the hottest spring-break destinations for college students. Yes,
Panama City Beach is still on the list, along with South Padre
Island, Texas, and Daytona Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Big news: Noting that more than 13 million Americans report
having vision problems, Time has introduced a large-print edition.
The easier-to-read version also is aimed at those who like to read
while working out on a stationary bike or StairMaster. Time Large
is available, by subscription only, for $79.97 annually.
Information: 800-881-2137.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail:dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
