 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, Feb. 8. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ The Palestinian Authority on Monday
froze peace talks with the Israelis and then released from prison a
charismatic Islamic fundamentalist leader who is a withering
opponent of the peace effort. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHAN-HIJACK (Stansted, England) _ Developing: Day and night
negotiations with gunmen who seized an Afghan jet on a domestic
flight and ordered it flown to London succeeded Monday in gaining
the release of eight passengers and providing supplies for those
still trapped on board. The identity of the hijackers and the
nature of their demands remained unclear, though reports from the
Middle East said their purpose might be to liberate an Afghan
fighter jailed by the Islamic fundamentalist Taliban movement that
now rules the country. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton sent Congress a
budget proposal Monday built on the idea that the burgeoning budget
surplus will allow the nation to have it all, from increased
spending on government programs to tax cuts and big reductions in
the national debt. The president's budget, his eighth and last,
calls for additional spending across the range of issues that have
long been central to his agenda, including health care, education
and the environment. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SC-VOICES (Columbia, S.C.) _ In interviews with voters across
South Carolina, it's not so much the numbers of McCain supporters
that you notice, but it's the passion. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
(1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   NY-GIULINAI-CONSERVATIVES (Colonie, N.Y.) _ The leader of the
Conservative Party all but closed the door Monday on his party's
supporting New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for the Senate,
saying he would like to see the mayor drop out of the race, and
that his party would readily nominate Rep. Rick Lazio. Staff.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIFE-BEYOND-EARTH (Undated) _ Two prominent scientists say
the conventional wisdom that intelligent life is common beyond the
Earth is way off base. Drawing on new findings in astronomy,
geology and paleontology, the two argue that humans might be alone,
at least in the stellar neighborhood, and perhaps in the entire
cosmos. They say modern science is showing that Earth's composition
and stability are extraordinarily rare. Most everywhere else, the
radiation levels are too high, the right chemical elements too rare
in abundance, the hospitable planets too few in number and the rain
of killer rocks too intense for life ever to have evolved into
advanced communities. Alien microbes may survive in many places as
a kind of cosmic shower scum, they say, but not extraterrestrials
civilized enough to be awash in technology. By William J. Broad.
(2100 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIALLO-PAUSE (Albany, N.Y.) _ As the prosecution this week
continues presenting its case against four New York City police
officers charged with murder in the death of Amadou Diallo, a pause
in the fusillade of 41 shots fired by the officers is becoming
almost as central as the gunfire itself. Two witnesses for the
prosecution have testified to a pause in the 41 shots fired, and
more are expected to do so. While defense lawyers say the pause is
meaningless, prosecutors maintain the pause could have given the
officers the opportunity to think about their actions before firing
again. By Amy Waldman.
</P>
</TEXT>
