<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     02-07 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATES CANNOT FORCE TEN COMMANDMENTS ON THEIR CITIZENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Colo., Fla., Ill., Ind., Ky., Miss., Okla., Mo., S.D. ATTN)  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are a number of things government should not do. Pushing
religion is one of them; telling people when and how to pray is
another. Some Colorado legislators, however, don't see a problem
with state government intruding on its citizens' private religious
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Legislature is set to vote on a measure that would
mandate the posting of the Ten Commandments in every public school
classroom and in the main entryway of every public school in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Eight other states are currently considering legislation to
authorize state governments to push the Ten Commandments on the
citizens of their states: Florida, Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky,
Mississippi, Missouri, Oklahoma and South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Whose Ten Commandments _ the Jewish, Catholic, Lutheran,
Protestant?
</P>
<P>
   The text of the Ten Commandments that must be posted, according
to the Colorado bill, ``is a compromise version.'' Neither this nor
that, neither Jewish nor Protestant. The Colorado legislature's
version of the Ten Commandments more closely conforms to the
Catholic version.
</P>
<P>
   That's what you get when government tells you what the Ten
Commandments are _ a mishmash that glosses over the deep
theological questions and controversies involved in the wording and
selection from the 16 laws set down in Exodus.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed Colorado legislation also mandates a brief period
of ``quiet reflection'' at the start of every school day, ``with
the participation of all the pupils therein assembled.'' The law
requires teachers to announce the period of reflection with these
words: ``The class will now observe a moment of silence for
reflection on our heritage as a free people in one nation under
God.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt that the period of quiet reflection is
meant as a moment of prayer. The legislative declaration makes it
clear by creating the context in which this bill's mandates exist.
The declaration mentions a ``Supreme Being and the authority of
transcendent standards for human conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the requirement to post the Ten Commandments in public
schools and the mandated brief period of quiet reflection for
public school students are in direct conflict with the state's
constitution.
</P>
<P>
   In Article II, Section 4, the Colorado Constitution states: ``No
person shall be required to attend or support any ministry or place
of worship, religious sect or denomination against his consent. Nor
shall any preference be given by law to any religious denomination
or mode of worship.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, the U.S. Supreme Court addressed the issue of a state
requiring a moment of silence at the beginning of the public school
day. An Alabama law required the moment of silence to be used for
``meditation or voluntary prayer.'' In Wallace vs. Jaffree, the
high court found the state law had a religious purpose and was
therefore unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Children can pray in public schools, on their own initiative, as
long as no student is coerced into joining or listening and the
activity does not interfere with the normal running of the school.
But the state cannot force anyone to pray or to join others in
prayer, even silent prayer. Religion is not within the state's
province.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's proposed legislation's mandated version of the Ten
Commandments seems, by default, to give preference to the Catholic
religion. It certainly doesn't conform to the Jewish version of the
Ten Commandments in which the first commandment states, ``I am the
Lord your God'' and the sixth commandment states, ``You shall not
murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does it conform to the Protestant version of the Ten
Commandments, which includes in the second commandment a
prohibition against graven images. The 10th commandment in the
Protestant version forbids coveting your neighbor's house and
coveting your neighbor's wife. The Colorado Legislature's version
separates those prohibitions into the ninth and the 10th
commandments, as does the Catholic version of the Ten Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature's mandated Ten Commandments definitely violates
the Colorado Constitution's requirement: ``Nor shall any preference
be given by law to any religious denomination or mode of worship.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if it didn't show preference to Catholicism, it would show
preference to Judeo-Christian religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Of the other eight states considering Ten Commandments
legislation, seven _ Florida, Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky,
Mississippi, Missouri, South Dakota _ have state constitutions
forbidding state government from intruding upon the religious
consciences of their citizens or giving preference to any religion.
Oklahoma is the only exception.
</P>
<P>
   However, the U.S. Supreme Court spoke to this issue in 1980 with
the case, Stone vs. Graham. A Kentucky statute had required the
posting of the Ten Commandments on the wall of every public school
classroom in the state. The high court struck down the Kentucky law
for violating the Establishment Clause of the U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The high court wrote: ``The Ten Commandments are undeniably a
sacred text in the Jewish and Christian faith, and no legislative
recitation of a supposed secular purpose can blind us to that fact.
The Commandments do not confine themselves to arguably secular
matters, such as honoring one's parents, killing or murder,
adultery, stealing, false witness, and covetousness. Rather, the
first part of the Commandments concerns the religious duties of
believers: worshiping the Lord God alone, avoiding idolatry, not
using the Lord's name in vain, and observing the Sabbath Day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ten Commandments is a religious document. However, there is
no agreement on exactly what constitutes the Ten Commandments.
There is no standard version. The Bible lists more than 10
commandments. And Jewish and Christian theologians have debated the
issues involved for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   States have no right to push any religion's version of the Ten
Commandments on their citizens. That's precisely what the
Establishment Clause means. States cannot favor any religion or set
of beliefs. This nation is home to nearly 2,000 different
religions, denominations and religious beliefs. Any preference
shown toward one or a group of religions discriminates against the
others.
</P>
<P>
   Public schools and public buildings must show neutrality toward
all religions so that none are favored or are seen to be favored.
Children and citizens of all religious faiths have a right to equal
treatment by all government agencies, including the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   It is understandable that state legislatures may be reacting to
the tragedies suffered as a result of a number of school shootings
around the nation. However, posting the Ten Commandments in public
schools is merely a symbolic gesture and not a solution to the
troubling social problems that cry to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than spending thousands of dollars to purchase tens of
thousands of copies of the Ten Commandments, it would be wiser to
use that money to pay for in-depth sociological and psychological
studies of the school-shooting incidents to see whether it is
possible to discern the reasons behind those disasters. That would
be a first step to finding a real solution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 1657EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
