r k BC-EDITORIAL-GUNS-COX     02-07 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-GUNS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strengthen enforcement of gun laws
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, the National Rifle Association and its allies have
insisted America needs no new gun restrictions, only stricter
enforcement of laws already on the books. At last, President
Clinton is challenging the movement's minions on Capitol Hill to
put a substantial sum of money where their mouth is. The
president's budget includes a request for more money to help
federal agents enforce current laws.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the president requests $280 million to
reinvigorate the drive against gun violence, which has been
weakened by years of budget reductions and staff shortages. Part of
the increased funding would go to hire 500 Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms agents and inspectors and more U.S. attorneys; part would
be made available to state and local jurisdictions so they could
hire additional prosecutors. Gun-lobby defenders who must face the
voters this year could find Clinton's offer one they dare not
refuse.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also would spend $30 million for a national ballistics
database for the FBI, the ATF and state and local authorities to
share. He also wants $10 million to accelerate development of
weapons designed so that only the owners can fire them. The idea
behind these ``smart-guns'' is to minimize accidental shootings and
gun thefts.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the ATF produced fresh evidence that a minority of gun
dealers are giving a black eye to law-abiding brethren in the
trade. Its study showed a mere 1.2 percent of firearms dealers and
pawnbrokers are to blame for marketing 57 percent of the guns used
in crimes. The Clinton crackdown would concentrate ATF scrutiny on
dealers who sold 10 or more weapons involved in crimes last year.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, the NRA's top Washington lobbyist dismissed the
change in emphasis as ``just the latest installment in the
Clinton-Gore plan to drive lawful and licensed gun dealers out of
business'' _ as if to say those targeted vendors are upstanding
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   True, Clinton still would like to see some more gun restrictions
enacted _ for instance, requiring gun-show vendors to run
background checks on buyers and prohibiting the importation of
large-capacity ammunition clips. Still, he could consider his last
year in office a success on this score if he can persuade Congress
to get serious about enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
