<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9393 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-DANISH-BOS &LR;      02-07 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DANISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMPASSIONATE STORY OF UNUSUAL LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE DANISH GIRL 
By David Ebershoff 
Viking, 270 pp., $24.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1930, Einar Wegener, a Danish artist, became the first known
recipient of gender reassignment, or what is more commonly called a
sex-change operation. For years, Wegener had teetered on the
increasingly fragile divide between his life as husband to fellow
painter Gerda Wegener, and as Lili Elbe, the woman within who would
come to overshadow Einar.
</P>
<P>
   Within this factual framework, David Ebershoff has fashioned
``The Danish Girl,'' an extraordinary work of fiction that imagines
the lives of the Wegeners as they come to terms with Lili, the
other woman in their marriage whose presence could no longer be
denied. Heartbreaking and unforgettable, it is a complete triumph,
and also a tribute to a wife's unconditional love for her husband.
</P>
<P>
   It is 1925, and Einar and Greta (as she is called here) are
painters living in Copenhagen. They are six years into their
marriage when Greta requests a favor from her husband. Her model
has canceled an afternoon session, so Greta asks Einar to slip into
the woman's stockings and shoes so that she may complete the legs
of the portrait. At first, Einar is reluctant, yet something stirs
within him as he imagines ``the wrinkled roll of the stocking
gliding over the white bone of his ankle. Over the small cushion of
his calf. Clicking into the hook of a garter.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he would agree to also try on the model's dress, its silk
caressing his hips, its lace bib resting gently on his chest. To
Greta it's all a bit of a laugh to see the near-hairless legs of
her husband, whom she has always considered ``a pretty man,'' clad
in a pair of her stockings. But Einar is transformed, even before
Greta says in jest, ``Why don't we call you Lili?''
</P>
<P>
   Einar, his childhood friend Hans Axgil would later recall, had
always been ``a little boy with secrets.'' As a child, he would
make his way into the pickled-ash wardrobe of his dead mother,
wrapping her beads around his small neck or draping his head with
one of her scarves. If his father discovered him among the felt
skirts and gabardine dresses, he would yell at Einar, ``You can't
do that! Little boys can't do that!''
</P>
<P>
   But with the realization of Lili, Einar indulged in what little
boys were forbidden to do. At times, Greta would come home
expecting her husband and instead would find Lili in a dress
accessorized with Greta's jewelry. And when Einar would return, he
would always seek Greta's permission for Lili to visit again.
</P>
<P>
   ``All she wanted to do was to allow him his desires, but at the
same time she had the irrepressible urge to hold him in her arms
and tell him what to do about Lili,'' Ebershoff writes of Greta's
reaction. ``Eventually, she said _ but only as it occurred to her _
`It's up to Lili. It's whatever she wants to do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In the lexicon of modern pop psychology, Greta would be called
an enabler, a coconspirator in Einar's masquerade. But as time goes
on and Lili becomes a regular part of their lives (Lili even
becomes Greta's muse), both husband and wife understand that this
is neither a masquerade nor a game. With each passing week, there
is more of Lili, less of Einar. Lili even falls in love with a
fellow artist, Henrik Sandahl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Einar sensed how he was turning the world on its head by
dressing as Lili,'' Ebershoff writes. ``He could eliminate himself
by pulling the camisole with the scallop-lace hem over his head.
Einar could duck out of society by lifting his elbows and clasping
the triple strand of Spanish pearls around his neck.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Einar and Greta finally seek medical advice to explain
Einar's condition. One doctor suggests Einar suffers from ``pelvic
tumors'' that have compromised his manhood. In Paris (where they
move to further Greta's career, after her portraits of Lili become
all the rage), there's another who recommends a procedure ``so full
of promise'' called a lobotomy. Then Greta finally meets Professor
Bolk of the Dresden Municipal Women's Clinic in Germany: This is
the man who would free ``the pretty girl with the stemlike throat
trying to break out of the dry, sick skin of old Einar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Danish Girl'' is a remarkably daring leap for a first-time
novelist, yet Ebershoff accomplishes it with grace, beauty, and
intelligence. What could have been freakish and exploitative in
less compassionate hands unfolds as a probing exploration of sexual
identity. Yet even more so, it is a sublime psalm to an unusual and
enduring love, as a woman must choose between holding on to the
husband she adores and honoring his innermost desires, which will
inevitably and forever unravel their life together.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
