<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Feb. 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dry and somewhat milder weather will be the rule Tuesday from
the central Rockies to the Atlantic Seaboard. In fact, only a
portion of New England, parts of the Southeast and California will
notice readings below seasonal levels. The rest of the country will
have above to much above normal temperatures. A split in the jet
stream will keep the supply of moisture separate from the potent
disturbances along the polar front. As a result, no significant
storms will affect the nation for the next several days.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure will stretch from the northern Appalachians to
central Texas and westward into Utah. Much of this region will
experience ample sunshine and light breezes. The morning will dawn
frigid in New England, but milder air will arrive on a freshening
breeze from the southwest Tuesday afternoon. Meanwhile, a push of
chilly air into the Southeast will combine with a weak jet stream
disturbance over the Gulf States to produce varying amounts of
clouds along with scattered showers or drizzle.
</P>
<P>
   Warmer air will be lifted over the cold snow-covered terrain of
the upper Middle West leading to thickening clouds and a few
patches of light snow or freezing drizzle. Temperatures may
approach record values in the western Plains as gusty winds from
the west descend the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   A stream of moisture from the eastern Pacific will cause dull
and damp conditions in south-central California and Nevada. Another
current of moisture will bring showers to the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Bitter Winter
</P>
<P>
   By Alaskan standards, the town of Cold Bay has a moderate
climate. Located near the beginning of the Aleutian archipelago,
arctic air masses are typically modified by surrounding waters
before reaching Cold Bay. However, this winter is setting records
for severity. Last year ended with the coldest December ever
measured there. In January, blizzard conditions occurred on a
record-setting 13 days. The snow depth reached 46 inches in
January, 26 inches more than the previous record. Finally, the
month came to a bitter end as the all-time record low temperature
of -13 was tied on January 30.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
