r l BC-OBESE-KIDS-HEALTH-ART     02-07 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBESE-KIDS-HEALTH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAIST MANAGEMENT: HELP KIDS KEEP FIT AND TRIM
</HEADLINE>
  (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature, contact New York
Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 (Includes a color photo of kids playing soccer. It is in JPEG
format and available by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By ELIZABETH SOMER 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our parents called it baby fat. In those days, chubby kids were
considered cute and cuddly, with pudgy cheeks meant for pinching
and round tummies ripe for a rub. Not anymore. Today it's called
childhood, or pediatric, obesity, and it's the No. 1 one
nutrition-related health problem troubling American kids. One in
four children in this country is overweight or obese, a statistic
that has grown more than 50 percent in the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Baby fat is also no longer something children grow out of. A
third of overweight preschoolers and half of overweight school-age
kids will be obese adults _ a fate heavy kids are twice as likely
to suffer as their lean counterparts are. What's more, ``There is
every reason to believe this trend will continue; in fact, it will
probably get worse unless we make serious changes in our
lifestyles,'' said Tom Baranowski, a professor of behavioral
nutrition at the Children's Nutrition Research Center at the Baylor
College of Medicine in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consequences of childhood obesity go far beyond
cosmetics,'' said Dr. William Dietz, the director of nutrition and
physical activity for the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention in Atlanta. The longer a child remains obese, the
greater the likelihood that he will stay that way, escalating his
risk of diabetes, gallbladder disease, hypertension, arthritis,
sleep problems and even cancer. And according to a study from the
New England Medical Center and Tufts University in Boston, excess
body fat in childhood also lays the groundwork for heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the health ramifications lie the social issues: Bullies
are more likely to ridicule larger kids, who tend to have fewer
friends than their peers do, and teachers often view heavy students
as lazy and not as smart. Thus obese kids face discrimination
throughout school, in sports, at college entrance _ and even into
adulthood, when they join the work force. All of this can take its
toll on a youngster's already fragile self-image.
</P>
<P>
   Obesity begets obesity. Children whose parents are both obese
have an 80 percent chance of piling on the pounds; that figure is
cut in half if only one parent is significantly overweight _ yet
the stats plummet to 7 percent if Mom and Dad are lean. However,
this weight epidemic is not genetic in origin; obesity rates are
rising far too quickly for that to be the case. ``It takes eons for
our genes to adapt to changes in our environment,'' Baranowski
said. ``Escalating obesity among children is a phenomenon of the
past few decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Many kids simply consume more calories than they burn. They are
eating more fat, sugar and processed foods, and are moving less
than ever. In a study of 125 youngsters between the ages of 3 and
7, Baranowski found that the overweight kids took in more fat and
calories. Other research concludes the same thing: Children who
follow high-fat diets are most likely to be fat, while those on
low-fat diets stay lean. Then there's the problem of anxiety-driven
eating: From school pressure to divorce, children face more stress
today than did previous generations.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of exercise also plays a role. Gone are the days when kids
walked to school and rode their bikes until sundown. Today children
sit. They watch three hours of television a day, and that's not
counting the time spent surfing the Net or playing Nintendo.
</P>
<P>
   But whether your child is a bit pudgy or downright too big for
his britches, use common sense. Don't fall for the restrictive
weight-loss diets that can escalate a weight problem into an eating
disorder later on. Here are a few suggestions for putting your best
food forward:
</P>
<P>
   _ Cultivate a child's taste for nutritious foods early on.
Emphasize smart choices rather than calories or fat grams: frozen
blueberries instead of ice cream, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Help kids get in touch with their bodies' hunger and satiety
signals. ``Part of our children's problem with obesity comes from
eating when they're not hungry,'' said Debra Waterhouse, a
registered dietitian and the author of ``Like Mother, Like
Daughter: Breaking Free From the Diet Trap.'' Don't force
youngsters to eat if they don't want to, and don't require that
they clean their plates.
</P>
<P>
   _ Switch from soda to water. Children consume 8 percent of their
calories from soft drinks. Substituting water for high-calorie soda
is an important step in controlling weight.
</P>
<P>
   _ Replace French fries with baby carrots. Only one in every five
children meets the minimum recommendation for vegetables (five or
more servings daily). Making the switch from ketchup and fries to
raw veggies with fat-free ranch dip cuts calories by 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Review your menus. According to researchers at the University
of Maryland, four of the five dinners most often served in the
United States _ fried chicken, pasta, hamburgers, hot dogs and
pizza _ are high-fat. Just switching from fried to baked chicken
would cut calories by almost half.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never use food as a reward or a punishment. If you tell your
son he can't have cake until he's finished his spinach, you teach
him that greens are punishments and sweets are rewards. This can
lead to overeating or using treats to fill emotional needs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nurture an appreciation for health. Don't focus on weight as
much as on how eating well gives your child energy, shiny hair and
a clear complexion while it boosts brain power and athletic
performance.
</P>
<P>
   According to the North American Society for Physical Education,
children need a minimum of one hour of daily robust physical
activity. An overweight child requires even more. That means making
exercising as automatic as brushing teeth.
</P>
<P>
   The most effective way to encourage kids to exercise is through
what James Sallis, a professor of psychology at San Diego State
University, calls the ``chauffeur function.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The children who are most active are the ones whose parents
take them someplace where they can play,'' Sallis said, ``whether
it's to the park, the YMCA, soccer practice or a tae kwon do or
dance class.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Elizabeth Somer writes for Country Living's Healthy Living, a
Hearst Communications magazine.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ''separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 1717EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
