<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9399 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-ITALY-PAINTING-ART-NY     02-07 1403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-PAINTING-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADING A CAREER IN FINANCE FOR PAINTING'S PLEASURES
</HEADLINE>
  (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature, contact New York
Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 (Includes a color photo of Maddine Insalaco in her New York studio.
It is in JPEG format and available by calling William Gonzalez at
212-499-3355.) 
 By LESLIE MARTIN 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a hillside in Tuscany, 12 art students work at their
canvases, shaded by brightly striped umbrellas. They have gathered
in Italy to study the intricacies of plein air, or open air,
landscape painting _ to capture in oils the fugitive light, the
contours of hills, the luminous greens of vineyards and olive
groves. Their teacher, Maddine Insalaco, wanders from easel to
easel and thoughtfully critiques her students' work, suggesting a
brush stroke here, a dab of color there.
</P>
<P>
   For Insalaco, a gifted painter and teacher, art is at the center
of her life. She divides her time between a home in Italy, where
she runs landscape-painting workshops six months a year, and a
studio in New York, where she concentrates on developing her own
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is very rich,'' said the 41-year-old. ``I've never felt
more satisfied.'' Her contentment has been hard-won, however: It
took years of inner conflict before she felt comfortable turning
her dream of living an artist's life into a reality.
</P>
<P>
   After completing a sound education with academic honors _ which
included internships in Luxembourg, with the European Parliament,
and in Brussels, the headquarters of the European Economic
Community; followed by a master's in international affairs from
Columbia University _ Insalaco landed a high-powered banking
position with a shipping company on New York's Park Avenue. ``I was
in my mid-20s and already on the treadmill,'' she recalled. ``Even
then I was anxious and sensed that the world of international
finance wasn't for me. But I had no idea what to do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since she was a child Insalaco had loved sketching and painting,
so, once settled in the job, she decided to provide a
counterbalance to her professional responsibilities by pursuing her
art, enrolling in evening classes at New York's Art Students
League. Upon receiving an offer in 1985 to work with the U.N. Food
and Agriculture Organization, she accepted the Rome-based position,
in part for the opportunity to develop her art abroad.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 years, Insalaco lived at the foot of the pine-shaded
Palatine Hill, drinking in the historical, cultural and visual
riches of the city. She strolled daily past the ruins of imperial
palaces and the Coliseum's travertine arcades, drank in the toasty
aromas of cappuccino and espresso wafting from corner cafes and
delighted in the Mediterranean light as it intensified the
ocher-and-mustard hues of buildings lining cobblestone streets. At
night, she studied art at the Scuola delle Arti Ornamentali, where
she had access to a painting space.
</P>
<P>
   The dry routine of her workdays _ authorizing payments, signing
checks, writing memos, analyzing accounts and supervising staff _
began to make her feel ill at ease, however. Despite a good title,
and the kind of financial security she had not known growing up in
a single-parent household, Insalaco could not ignore a hollowness
at her core.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep down, I knew that I'd never feel truly fulfilled if
creativity were not at the center of my life,'' she said. But
having devoted years to her professional training, she couldn't yet
fathom veering off in a new direction.
</P>
<P>
   But her dissatisfaction only grew. ``I started to envy people
who enjoyed what they were doing professionally,'' she said. ``Work
was sapping all my creative energies. I simply couldn't sustain the
division in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Confused and anxious, Insalaco took a leave of absence and
returned to Manhattan, where she studied intensely for an MFA at
the New York Academy of Art. ``I hadn't burned any bridges, so I
was still risk-free,'' she explained. ``The thought of giving up my
lovely 15th century Italian apartment, my Palatine Hill, and the
image of myself as a U.N. professional _ everything I had so
carefully protected _ was very threatening.''
</P>
<P>
   While continuing her coursework, Insalaco weighed the pros and
cons of her structured career against those of an artist's life.
``But all my list-making, all my efforts at reason, brought me no
clarity,'' she recalled. Her dilemma still unresolved, she returned
to Italy at the end of nine months to face yet more office
politics, plus the same workaday concerns and disgruntled faces.
</P>
<P>
   During one of her walks in the city she loved, she lit upon a
plan: ``I decided to paint my way through my crisis.'' On New
Year's Eve of 1994, she resolved to paint every weekend at the same
site _ the ruins of the Circus Maximus, ancient Rome's grandest
chariot racecourse. She did so religiously and in five months had
produced 20 paintings. But her consistency and faith in the process
held even greater rewards: ``By May, something in me had shifted,
and I knew what I had to do.'' She left her U.N. job three months
later, gave up her cherished Rome apartment and returned to New
York to complete her MFA.
</P>
<P>
   What actually occurred during her weekend ritual, a meditation
of sorts? ``In the process of painting consistently and honoring my
personal commitment, I identified with myself as an artist,''
Insalaco said. During her Circus Maximus sessions, Insalaco gained
a new perspective. ``Painting made me feel alive and happy. Picture
making became really meaningful. In those months, I realized that
life wouldn't work if I didn't recognize and respect my values. I
came to understand that I was protecting myself falsely.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that relinquishing the security of her life in Rome was
easy. ``It was agonizing. I tried on the idea of teaching landscape
painting, and it scared me. But I knew that's what I wanted to
do,'' she said. ``And the idea of teaching painting in Italy was
the only way that I could face the sacrifice of leaving my beloved
home abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to her financial training, Insalaco was able to develop a
business plan for Etruscan Places, her landscape-painting program
in Tuscany. Of the $12,000 she'd saved, she dedicated $5,000 to the
business itself. She organized and advertised workshops from New
York and set up a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Insalaco traveled to Tuscany for her first two
workshops, each attended by just two students. By the following
year, she was conducting six workshops, and, after a write-up in
The New York Times, her classes swiftly reached their maximum
enrollment of 12. She hired an assistant and, in time, purchased a
van and more painting equipment. Finally, Insalaco signed a
long-term rental on an apartment in San Gimignano, where she lives
when conducting her 10 annual Tuscan workshops.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Insalaco married artist Joe Vinson, with whom she now
runs Etruscan Places. ``It is significant, though, that I was
single at the time of my decisions and transition,'' she said.
``While being alone had the familiar drawbacks, I was in a position
of complete freedom to decide my fate myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the arduous process of allowing her passion for art to
guide her, Insalaco has come to recognize a truth she holds dear:
``To be creative, you must learn to be comfortable by yourself. I
learned the value of an interior world. It's so dynamic and has its
own vitality. It has given me strength and resources. Having made
this transition, I now feel that I can take on just about
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Does she miss her financial security and the luxuries of an
affluent lifestyle? ``I was not very materialistic to begin with,
so apart from exotic travel, which I miss, I don't think I
sacrificed a lot,'' she said. ``I live a simple life with much less
money. Freedom has a high value, and from that point of view I am
very wealthy. And just think, everything I love is a tax
write-off.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Leslie Martin writes for Country Living's Healthy Living, a
Hearst Communications magazine.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
