<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-MILITARY-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIAN PRESIDENT CHANGES COURSE WITH MILITARY LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Easing a strange long-distance
confrontation with his top general, President Abdurrahman Wahid has
suddenly taken a new tack, saying in newspaper reports Monday that
he trusts the general and is ready to forgive him.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks in Rome over the weekend, the president reportedly
asserted that several years ago when he was a dissident religious
leader, the general, Wiranto, saved his life by warning him of a
government plot to kill him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I trust Mr. Wiranto,'' the president said in Rome, in an
interesting twist on his recent warnings that military officers
were planning a coup against his government.
</P>
<P>
   Then, according to the local reports, he said, ``If Mr. Wiranto
is judged guilty by a court I will forgive him.'' But Wahid left it
unclear whether this was an expression of personal sentiment or
whether he had an official pardon in mind.
</P>
<P>
   The president first demanded that Wiranto step down one week
ago, when a government commission named the general as one of five
military leaders responsible for the violence and destruction in
East Timor last year.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's detailed report, which named 33 people, was
turned over to the attorney general for prosecution. By moving
aggressively, Indonesia is trying to avoid international
prosecution for crimes against humanity during the violence and
destruction that followed an independence vote in the former
Portuguese colony last August.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's report and the president's demand for Wiranto's
resignation brought fears of a military backlash here, with the
army commander saying he was trying to persuade his officers not to
stage a coup.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the new tone of his remarks, newspapers reported
that the president, who is halfway through a two-week foreign trip,
also seemed to repeat his demand for Wiranto to quit, saying: ``I
hope he resigns before I come back. But if not, we will implement
what we said before: those who face prosecution should be
`non-active' and be replaced temporarily.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's seemingly impulsive comments have shifted the
atmosphere in Jakarta from one of tension over fears of a military
backlash to bemusement over the garrulous leader.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the speaker of the house, Akbar Tandjung, said, ``We
are reminding the president not to make statements that could cause
confusion among the people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jakarta Post, in an editorial Monday, suggested that
Indonesians need to accept Wahid's unceremonious style and what it
called his ``talent for stepping on people's toes.'' It called the
president a refreshing change from the obscure and mumbling
imperial presidency of the country's former strongman leader,
Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   ``His penchant for making seemingly ambiguous statements about
all kinds of issues, from the most immaterial to the most serious,
has of late particularly come under fire,'' the newspaper said in
the editorial. ``We believe Indonesians would do best to get used
to this peculiar style of leadership which, after all, is and
always has been uniquely Abdurrahman Wahid's.''
</P>
<P>
   Strangely in this time of national crisis, with separatist
movements flaring in several areas and Muslim-Christian violence
surging, the president has spent a large portion of his first three
months in office abroad. But this has not stopped him from stirring
the political pot at home, for reasons that often seem unclear.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After his demand for Wiranto's resignation last week, the
president announced that he had reached a cease-fire agreement with
separatist rebels in the province of Aceh. A separatist leader
hotly denied this and the matter seems to have been dropped.
</P>
<P>
   On a previous trip, Wahid called ``three or four'' unnamed
members of his Cabinet corrupt and said that they must resign or
face termination when he returned. He then seemed to forget about
his threat.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, newspapers reported that he said Wiranto had telephoned
him several days ago to complain about his warnings of a possible
coup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you believe such rumors?'' Wahid quoted the general as
saying.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the president seems to have become one of the general's
defenders. ``I believe in Mr. Wiranto,'' he reportedly said. ``Why?
Because I know him. It is other people who know nothing about him
who make generalizations about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Using the common initials for the Indonesian military, the
president added: ``I am asking the people not to see all TNI
members as bad guys who always do wrong. There are two kinds of TNI
_ those who obey and those who are rogues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
