<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9437 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-ALL-ABOUT-LOVE-L     02-07 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ALL-ABOUT-LOVE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEP, THE MOVIES KNOW ALL ABOUT LOVE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: note italics) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most of us learn an awful lot about love by watching the movies.
(The operative word here being ``awful.'') This explains where we
pick up all our romanticized notions about dating and marriage. It
also explains why our divorce rate is so high, but let's not dwell
on that.
</P>
<P>
   What do movies teach us? Basically, the same things fairy tales
do. Only in the movies, sometimes Cinderella is a prostitute and
her Prince Charming is a soulless corporate raider.
</P>
<P>
   Ain't love grand?
</P>
<P>
   But Hollywood's love lessons aren't all that twisted. In fact,
some of them, remarkably, have a ring of truth to them. So read on
for further instruction about how movies enlighten us about
passion, devotion and the prevention of gum disease.
</P>
<P>
   SOMETIMES, LOVE JUST ISN'T ENOUGH. You know the drill. Men are
from Mars; women are from Venus. And try as we might, the planets
just don't always line up. Deep-rooted personality conflicts can
wreak havoc with even the most consuming of loves; look at
Streisand and Redford in ``The Way We Were.'' (Then again, maybe
Redford simply became weary of listening to Streisand talk all the
time.)
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, accidents can happen (``An Affair to Remember'') or
the Grim Reaper can make an untimely appearance. It's hard to
sustain even the best of relationships when one half is bobbing
like a Popsicle in the ocean (``Titanic'') or coming down with some
darned terminal illness (``Love Story'').
</P>
<P>
   By far, the most tragic example of this maxim comes in ``Old
Yeller,'' when the faithful frontier dog contracts rabies after
saving a boy's life, and the boy has to load up his gun and take
Old Yeller ... and ... well ... we can't even bring ourselves to
think about what happens next.
</P>
<P>
   But if love can't save a hero like Old Yeller, what chance do we
mere mortals have?
</P>
<P>
   MEN AND WOMEN CAN'T SIMPLY BE ``FRIENDS.'' By the way, a woman
(Nora Ephron) wrote this line, so don't blame the messenger. But if
``When Harry Met Sally ...'' taught us anything (besides the fact
that women can fake a great many things), it's that the ``sex part
always gets in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry and Sally are friends until they sleep together. Then
they're adversaries _ until Harry asks Sally to marry him. And then
they're married. Certainly, they can still be friends after the
nuptials. But not ``just friends.'' It's an important distinction.
Which brings us to ...
</P>
<P>
   MARRIAGE PROPOSALS NEED NOT BE ELABORATE TO WORK. Hollywood has
long fueled the idea that an invitation to marriage must be
accompanied by a little box from Tiffany's and a fireworks show.
But movies have also shown that a simple heartfelt speech can do
the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they aren't always as sweet as Harry's speech to
Sally at that New Year's Eve party. In Alfred Hitchcock's
``Rebecca,'' Maxim, a wealthy widower played by Laurence Olivier,
makes this kind offer to Joan Fontaine's wallflower:
</P>
<P>
   ``Either you go to America with Mrs. Van Hopper or you come home
to Manderly with me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean, you need a secretary or something,'' Fontaine
submissively replies.
</P>
<P>
   Olivier then utters the words every woman dreams of hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm asking you to marry me, you little fool!''
</P>
<P>
   Now, what woman could say no to that?
</P>
<P>
   A couple of generations later in ``Modern Romance,'' Albert
Brooks freaks out when he thinks his girlfriend (Kathryn Harrold)
is going to dump him. ``Marry me,'' he begs. That she ultimately
agrees to walk down the aisle instead of head for the hills speaks
more to the fact that Brooks wrote and directed the movie than it
does to any real-life plausibility.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a man can hope, can't he?
</P>
<P>
   Which leads us to the ever-popular ... MEN ARE PIGS. This
perennial favorite could be considered a bit of a surprise, given
that most movies are made by men. Maybe it's part of an
indoctrination program for women. Maybe they're telling women what
they want to hear. Or, heck, maybe it's true.
</P>
<P>
   Just listen to Daniel Stern share with Steve Guttenberg his
romantic view of marriage in Barry Levinson's ``Diner'':
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the big part of the problem? When we were dating, we
spent most of our time talking about sex. Everything was about
getting sex or planning our wedding. Then when you're married it's
crazy. You can have it whenever you want. You wake up. She's there.
You come home from work. She's there. So, all the sex-planning talk
is over. And the wedding-planning talk. (You and I) can sit up and
(talk) the night away, but I can't have a five-minute conversation
with Beth. But I'm not putting the blame on her. We've just got
nothing to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Crystal's aforementioned Harry offered this insight in
``When Harry Met Sally ...'' about what men think about after sex:
</P>
<P>
   ``You have sex, and the minute you're finished, you know what
goes through your mind? How long do I have to lie here and hold her
before I can get up and go home? Is 30 seconds long enough?''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder so many women in movies believe that A GOOD GIRLFRIEND
AND A PINT OF PREMIUM ICE CREAM CAN EASILY TAKE THE PLACE OF A MAN.
``Beaches'' is the mother of all female friendship movies, a film
so full of estrogen that the mere mention of it sends men running
for the nearest sports bar. (Don't even ask what happens when a man
(BEGIN ITAL)sees(END ITAL) a copy of it lying around the house.)
</P>
<P>
   The movie's philosophy was neatly encapsulated in the scene
where Hillary (Barbara Hershey) whines to her boyfriend about the
growing rift between her and her best friend, CC (Bette Midler). A
rift that was _ you guessed it _ caused by a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would I do without a best friend?'' Hillary laments.
</P>
<P>
   Boyfriend: ``You have me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillary: ``It's not the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's why some men like to dream that $3,000 UP FRONT
AND ANOTHER BILLION OR SO IN THE BANK WILL FIND YOU TRUE LOVE WITH
THE PROSTITUTE OF YOUR DREAMS.
</P>
<P>
   That was the inspirational message behind ``Pretty Woman,''
wasn't it? Or maybe it was: Always floss before going to bed.
Remember Julia Roberts telling Richard Gere that you shouldn't
neglect your gums, making her unique in the vast universe of
Hookers With Hearts of Gold. (BEGIN ITAL)She(END ITAL) was an
outspoken advocate of proper dental hygiene.
</P>
<P>
   LOVE IS ALL FOREPLAY. Think about it. With precious few
exceptions (``Two for the Road'' comes to mind), movies tell us
plenty about romance, but very little about what it takes to stay
together. If we do see a movie marriage, it usually involves the
couple from hell (``The War of the Roses,'' ``The Story of Us'')
whose ways are more destructive than instructive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sleepless in Seattle'' stands as the ultimate example of the
foreplay genre. The film's lovers (Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan) don't
meet until the very last scene, and yet were supposed to believe
that they'll live happily ever after. Who knows? Maybe they will.
But don't you think Hanks should at least find out if Meg watches
``Ally McBeal'' instead of Monday Night Football before he goes and
does anything crazy?
</P>
<P>
   LOVE MEANS NEVER HAVING TO SAY YOU'RE SORRY. Unless you made
``Love Story.'' Or ``Pretty Woman.'' Or, especially, ``Beaches.''
Then you have a lot to answer for, and a simple apology will not
suffice. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 1742EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
