<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9447 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-FEDBUD-MEDICARE08-COX     02-07 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEDBUD-MEDICARE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS COOL TO CLINTON MEDICARE, SOCIAL SECURITY PLANS
 &HT;    With FEDBUD.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - President Clinton's Medicare and Social Security
proposals received a cool reception from congressional leaders
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan would trim Medicare spending by $70 billion over
the next 10 years and use nearly $300 billion of the projected
federal surplus to extend the program's lifetime to about 2025.
</P>
<P>
   The president also proposed using the surplus to pay off more
than $3 trillion of federal debt owed to the public by 2013. Using
the interest saved by paying off the debt would extend the life of
the Social Security program until about 2050, he said. Clinton
proposed to invest a portion of that money in private equity
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., chairman of the House Ways and Means
subcommittee on health, which oversees the Medicare program, noted
that Congress had rejected proposals last year to trim $72 billion
from Medicare, ``which is why I can't understand why he would again
propose cuts in Medicare to the tune of nearly $70 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when seniors are struggling with the high costs of
prescription drugs and other treatments, we should be increasing
their access to benefits while lowering their out-of-pocket costs,
not the other way around as the president proposes,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   But Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala said
Clinton's budget ensure's the program's viability for an additional
10 years while providing much-needed reforms to make the program
operate more efficiently and providing a prescription drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of Medicare as a blank check are over,'' Shalala
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan would use nearly $300 billion of the projected
surplus over the next 10 years to bolster the Medicare hospital
trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton would spend $160 billion over 10 years for
a voluntary prescription drug benefit. In addition, Clinton
proposed a $35 billion ``catastrophic drug fund'' that would help
pay drug costs in excess of $2,500 a year by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Under the president's plan, the federal government would pay
half the cost of prescription drugs up to $2,000 in 2003 (the
federal share would be $1,000) and up to $5,000 (the federal share
would be $2,500) when fully phased in by 2009.
</P>
<P>
   Premiums for the drug benefit would begin at $26 a month in 2003
and increase to $51 a month by 2009.
</P>
<P>
   Low-income beneficiaries, those with income below 135 percent of
poverty level at that time, would not pay premiums. Those with
incomes between 135 and 150 percent of poverty level would pay
reduced premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, chairman of the Senate Special
Committee on Aging, said Clinton deserves credit for proposing a
Medicare prescription drug benefit, but his proposal ``needs
revision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Adding a prescription drug benefit without rebuilding
Medicare's foundation won't help older Americans in the long run,''
Grassley said. ``Medicare can't continue indefinitely in its
current form. We have to restructure Medicare to save it for future
generations. We should add a prescription drug benefit only in that
context.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's proposal to invest a portion of the surplus savings in
the equities market also drew complaints from GOP leaders. The
president had dropped the equities plan from a Social Security
reform proposal he offered last fall, but he restored it in the
budget offered Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any reasonable observer would have to wonder: why?'' said Rep.
E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., chairman of the House Social Security
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Chairman ``Alan Greenspan called government
investing 'very dangerous.' Which leads to another question: Is the
president serious about saving Social Security? His 'now you see
it, now you don't' approach on government investing suggests not,''
Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget also proposes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Expanded preventive care by eliminating co-insurance and
deductibles for colorectal cancer screening, bone mass measurement,
pelvic examinations, prostate cancer screening, diabetes
self-management and mammographies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Allowing persons aged 55 to 65 to ``buy into'' the Medicare
program.
</P>
<P>
   _ A demonstration project to make it easier for Medicare
patients to participate in cancer clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
