<HEADER>
A9463 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-FEDBUD-EDUCATION08-CO     02-07 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEDBUD-EDUCATION08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDUCATORS PRAISE CLINTON'S CALL FOR HIGHER SPENDING
 &HT;    With FEDBUD.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton pleased education groups Monday
by seeking a sharp jump in federal help for education.
</P>
<P>
   His budget for the 2001 fiscal year includes a $4.4 billion
increase in discretionary spending by the Education Department. It
offers an average of $3 billion a year in education-related tax
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   To top it off, Clinton also proposed a separate $1.6 billion
increase for Head Start and other early childhood programs
supervised by the Department of Health and Human Services, said
Joel Packer, chief lobbyist for the nation's largest teacher union,
the National Education Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly the biggest increase in education outlays we've
ever seen, and it goes into a lot of high-need areas,'' said Edward
Kealy, executive director of the Committee for Education Funding.
His coalition coordinates the lobbying efforts of 95 national
groups that favor higher spending on education from the pre-school
level to post-doctoral research.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's definitely going to challenge Congress to show
just how much they value investing in education during this
election year,'' Kealy said happily. ``I think (the
Republican-controlled) Congress will want to match (the Democratic
president's) suggestions in most areas and exceed them in some
others that are a higher priority for Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, Republicans have shown a greater interest
in funding grants for experiments in educational innovation and for
increasing the federal share of funding of special education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased by the attention the budget gives to student aid
and scientific research,'' said Paul Massey, federal relations
associate at the American Council on Education, which represents
most colleges and universities. ``It's a good blueprint.''
</P>
<P>
   Discretionary spending must be funded each year by Congress. In
the current fiscal year, the department's discretionary spending is
$35.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are requesting $40.1 billion, an increase of $4.5 billion
or 12.6 percent,'' Education Secretary Richard Riley told
reporters. ``This budget represents the biggest jump in
discretionary spending in the history of this department.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest boosts would be $1.3 billion for emergency
renovations at schools in high-poverty areas, $547 million for
after-school learning centers, $450 million to hire more teachers
in order to reduce class sizes in kindergarten through third grade,
and $416 million to help districts make major changes in their
worst-performing schools.
</P>
<P>
   On the tax side, Clinton proposed deductions and credits for
educational purposes that would cost the federal treasury $839
million in the next fiscal year and $15.5 billion over a five-year
period.
</P>
<P>
   About $11 billion of that $15.5 billion would help college
students and their families by expanding the Lifetime Learning tax
credit. The other education-related tax breaks include $2.4 billion
to subsidize bonds for school construction and modernization and
$1.2 billion to ``bridge the digital divide'' by giving tax breaks
to businesses that help poor people and minorities get computers
and acquire technology skills.
</P>
<P>
   None of the education lobbyists was concerned about Clinton's
proposal for $2.9 billion in cuts next year in mandatory spending,
the kind that continues automatically until Congress changes the
law. Congress, which rejected such proposals in the past, is widely
expected to once again reject the main cut requested by Clinton,
which would restrict subsidies to student-loan guaranty agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is andym(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
