<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9466 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-0208-     02-07 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-0208-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    MORE ALLEGATIONS OF ABUSE BY RUSSIAN SOLDIERS IN CHECHNYA
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia _ More allegations of killings, kidnappings and
looting by Russian soldiers against civilians have surfaced from
refugees who have fled the bombed-out husk of Grozny, the Chechen
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch, a New York-based watchdog group, has
documented eight incidents in the Staropromyslovsky neighborhood in
which it says a total of 22 civilians were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Still unconfirmed are reports of more than a dozen other murders
which allegedly took place during the months-long campaign by
Russian soldiers to take Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   ``A disturbing number of civilians have been murdered by Russian
troops in Grozny,'' said Peter Bouckaert, a researcher with Human
Rights Watch. ``They were willfully killed. This shows the need for
independent international observers and investigation of this
war.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian military officials did not respond to telephone calls
Monday asking for comment. Sergei Yastrzhembsky, the government
spokesman for Chechnya, said he was not aware of the cases cited by
Human Rights Watch. In the past, Russia has said that it is not
targeting civilians in its offensive aimed at eradicating
``terrorists and bandits'' in the breakaway region.
</P>
<P>
   Most reports of civilian suffering during the war have been the
result of Russian artillery and air strikes. However, there have
been reports of killings and other abuse similar to those described
by the Staropromyslovsky refugees.
</P>
<P>
   In the first week of December, at least 14 civilians were
murdered in the village of Alkhan Yurt by Russian soldiers after
the army took control of it, Human Rights Watch and refugees claim.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents from Staropromyslovsky, one of the first
neighborhoods in Grozny to come under Russian control, are the
first such reports of human rights abuses from the capital city,
Chechnya's largest. It is estimated that 15,000 to 30,000 civilians
remained trapped in Grozny during the two months it took Russian
forces to conquer the territory.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged attacks in Staropromyslovsky took place between Dec.
22 and Jan. 21, after soldiers announced they had liberated the
neighborhood from rebel fighters. Witnesses and relatives broke
into tears as they described their experiences to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Fatimat Dangaeva, 46, told how she had lived for months, trapped
with family members in Grozny under relentless Russian air strikes
and street battles between Russian soldiers and the Chechen forces.
She would leave her invalid parents, an uncle and a neighbor _ all
more 70 years old _ at the family's two-story brick house to sleep
at night, while she took shelter in a nearby bomb shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before Christmas, Russian soldiers announced they had
complete control of the district. ``They said it was all safe,''
she recalled, rubbing her brown eyes.
</P>
<P>
   She said the soldiers forced civilians living in the bomb
shelter with her to collect corpses of dead soldiers from the
streets. ``They said if we didn't come out they would throw a
grenade in,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers also harassed the family, arriving at night with
masks over their faces and demanding alcohol, she said. During one
visit, she continued, they stole a gold clock, Dangaeva's treasured
family heirloom.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 9, Dangaeva said her mother walked outside past a
soldier trying to cover his face. She confronted him, saying,
``Don't bother to cover yourself. I will remember you.''
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, Dangaeva walked from her shelter to her home
and found her father and a female neighbor shot to death in the
kitchen, the room where they slept.
</P>
<P>
   The basement, where her mother and uncle slept, was on fire. She
said she could not open the doors because the heat was too intense.
Her mother and uncle have been missing ever since, and she assumes
they died in the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the military police station just 200 meters (60
feet) away. They said they saw nothing and heard nothing,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided then to flee,'' Dangaeva said, sighing heavily while
sitting around a rectangular wooden dining room table at a
relative's house in Nazran, just across the border from Chechnya.
``I cannot understand why they would kill these old people.''
</P>
<P>
   She insisted that Chechen rebels could not have been responsible
for the deaths, because Russian troops were heavily concentrated in
her neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Saipudin Saadulayev, 39, a former oil worker with a salt and
pepper beard, said he saw Russian soldiers shoot an elderly man at
point-blank range. The old man, Said Tugoyev, was shot when he left
the cellar he was living in with Saadulayev and a group of other
men and walked across a yard to tell two Russian soldiers that only
civilians were in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They shot him with a machine-gun and then a soldier leaned
over and shot him in the head,'' Saadulayev told reporters during
an interview at a home north of Nazran, the capital of Ingushetia,
where he is living as a refugee.
</P>
<P>
   Saadulayev said the soldiers threw a grenade at him, but he
jumped back into the basement and escaped injury. Later, he said, a
second group of soldiers came to the basement and ordered everyone
out.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers took eight men prisoner and drove them across
Grozny and unloaded them into a pit where they were beaten. He said
the men made them strip and threw water over them in the sub-zero
temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, the soldiers reportedly took a group of 18
Chechen men to a camp outside Grozny. Saadulayev said he escaped
and that he doesn't know what happened to the rest of the men.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate account, Magomed Kheshiyev, 59, told reporters he
found his sister Lida and her teenage son shot dead on Jan. 25. His
brother and another nephew are missing.
</P>
<P>
   Guilt weighs heavily on the man, who left his home in Grozny in
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her, 'I beg you to leave,' but my sister did not want
to listen. She said 'I'm not afraid of anything,''' he recalled.
``I saw her body and I wept. And I don't (usually) cry.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
