<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9469 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-07 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPS TO SMOOTH PAYING FOR FUNERAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SHANNON BUGGS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The blur of tears and phone calls to family, friends
and funeral homes can make the first 48 hours after a loved one
dies seem surreal.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do people grieve for the deceased, they worry about the
mundane and the immense.
</P>
<P>
   Who will sing at the funeral?
</P>
<P>
   How will all the bills get paid?
</P>
<P>
   Will I be able to go on?
</P>
<P>
   An answer to the first question may be found in a farewell
letter with funeral instructions, while a resolution to the third
requires fortitude and fidelity.
</P>
<P>
   The second concern, however, can only be solved by advanced
planning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MAKE A WILL ACCESSIBLE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We all know we should prepare for the day we die by writing a
will and sharing what's in it with our families.
</P>
<P>
   But most people put off writing down their final wishes until
it's too late. If they do commit their desires to paper, very often
they don't want anyone to know how much will or won't be in the
estate. So they hide the will away in a bank safety deposit box
without a mention to family or friends.
</P>
<P>
   The result is the person places an unnecessary burden on the
people left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Families should be able to get a full accounting of your
finances within the first couple of days of your death to properly
wrap up your affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, they will need to know how much money you have
available to pay for the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially true for people who believe their life savings
and worldly assets are so insignificant that they don't merit a
will. By state law, counties must bury those whose families don't
have the money to buy a burial plot. Some counties, including
Harris, which includes most of Houston, require that officials be
notified within 48 hours of the death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best remedy is to look at these things prior to a death,
so you don't add stress to people at such a difficult time,'' says
Walter Johnson, president of Johnson Funeral Home in Houston. ``But
a lot of times that doesn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TRACKING DECEASED'S ASSETS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you find yourself struggling to plan a funeral and to piece
together the deceased's financial history, in addition to calling
your attorney, financial planner and funeral director, here are
steps you can take:
</P>
<P>
   1. Call family members and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond sharing the sad news, you can ask everyone if they have
any knowledge of where important documents may be.
</P>
<P>
   Also ask if the deceased ever shared any thoughts about what he
or she wanted done at the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it helps to ask the other mourners if they have
requests or preferences for the funeral and burial. By taking
others into consideration, you can avoid hurt feelings later.
</P>
<P>
   2. Search the home.
</P>
<P>
   Your first priority is to locate as many financial papers as
possible. These include a will, insurance policies, bills, bank
statements, safe deposit contracts and keys.
</P>
<P>
   You should also be on the lookout for funeral instructions that
can guide your planning.
</P>
<P>
   3. Visit the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure you take a death certificate, safety deposit box key
and personal identification with you. By state law, banks must
allow an immediate family member to remove wills, burial plot
contracts, insurance policies and funeral instructions from a
deceased customer's safety deposit box.
</P>
<P>
   The bank can only do this before a court probates the will and
appoints an executor to handle the estate. However, the bank can't
allow anything else to be removed from the box.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you know the person would have wanted to be buried with
the military medal or sorority pin that was kept in the box, and
you have power of attorney or have access to the box, it's best to
remove those items before you inform the bank of the death.
</P>
<P>
   That also means you should check the bank box before you run an
obituary in the newspaper. Most banks assign a staffer to read
obituaries every day and check them against a master list of
customers. When a match is found, the client's accounts are
immediately frozen.
</P>
<P>
   So, if the deceased spouse's name is the only one on all the
couple's bank accounts, the survivor may have to seek an immediate
probate of the will to get the money to pay for the funeral.
Probating a will in Texas is fairly simple, but it is still
troublesome to do it immediately after a death.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
