<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9479 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-CLIMATE-YELLOWSTO     02-07 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CLIMATE-YELLOWSTONE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT YELLOWSTONE, AN ECOSYSTEM TEETERING ON A NUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mont., Wyo., Idaho, Kansas)  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By JIM ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIG SKY, Mont. _ At the very top of a rocky, wind-whipped ridge
above this sprawling ski resort west of Yellowstone National Park
stands a towering grove of ancient whitebark pine trees. They are
one of the few living things that thrive in the harshness at such
altitudes, and they produce a large nut that is rich in fat and
critical to wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   There is mounting concern among biologists and other
researchers, however, that global climate change may be creating
conditions in and around the park that are inhospitable for the
tree. If climate warming is the real, long-term phenomenon that
many experts think it is, scientists believe it could set off a
series of changes that could kill 90 percent or more of the
whitebark pine trees and possibly compromise the future of the
threatened grizzly bear.
</P>
<P>
   The whitebark pine produces cones with pea-size nuts that bears
eat in the fall. ``Of all the vegetable foods in the ecosystem,
whitebark pine is probably the most important,'' said Chuck
Schwartz, leader of Interagency Grizzly Bear Study Team, a federal
agency responsible for protection of the bear. ``They are critical
to the fall fattening process to get the bears through the
winter.''
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances of the tree illustrate the breadth and
complexity of the problems a warming climate could create for
natural systems. And it underscores the challenges faced by
scientists and parks officials as they try to preserve intricate
ecosystems.
</P>
<P>
   The whitebark pine thrives at the top of the Yellowstone
ecosystem, the last tree before the timberline on most of the
mountain ranges in and around the park, in stands of a few acres to
thousands of acres. The cones blossom in the trees' upper reaches
and are fed on by many birds, including Clark's nutcracker, which
take the nuts and each year stash tens of thousands of them in
crevices in the craggy rocks or in the soil less than an inch deep.
Red squirrels, meanwhile, bury nut-laden cones in the duff on the
forest floor, heaps called middens, which concentrate the nuts in
piles large enough to be nutritional for grizzly bears.
</P>
<P>
   With the arrival of fall, when the bears are voraciously feeding
to build up a store of fat for winter, they travel to the high
country to dig up the squirrel caches. Some experts believe the
nuts are the source of as much as 40 percent of a bear's layer of
winter fat, and research shows they are important for fertility.
</P>
<P>
   Humans have become an integral part of this ecological
relationship between bear and tree. When the nut crop is poor, the
bears search out alternative sources to tide them through the
winter's sleep. Instead of climbing into the high country, they
often head into low-lying areas inhabited by humans, where they
find dog food, beehives full of honey, garbage _ and trouble.
</P>
<P>
   There is a direct correlation between poor nut production and
grizzly bear mortality, experts say. More bears die from ``human
induced'' causes _ for example, being shot _ when there are not
enough nuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pine nuts are more than a food,'' said Louisa Wilcox, project
coordinator for the Sierra Club Grizzly Bear Ecosystem Project in
Bozeman, Mont. ``They are a shield for bears against human-caused
mortalities.''
</P>
<P>
   Because nutrition affects reproduction rates, a drop in nut
production can also affect birthrates, lowering the number of new
cubs.
</P>
<P>
   The exact number of bears in Yellowstone is not known, but is
estimated at 200 to 400. So a modest increase in deaths could have
serious effects.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the global warming factor and a disease that affects
whitebark pines called European blister rust. The rust, a fungus
brought over from Europe, was discovered in North America in 1906.
Windborne spores spread through the miles of whitebark pine
forests, through Idaho and into Glacier National Park in
northwestern Montana, where the disease has killed 43 percent of
the whitebark pines, and will probably kill 90 percent of those
remaining. Fortunately for the grizzlies in Glacier, there are
other fall food sources, mainly huckleberries and thimbleberries.
Berries are rare in Yellowstone.
</P>
<P>
   Blister rust, first noted in the park in 1948, is now present
throughout Yellowstone. Until very recently, the disease was
present at low levels and did not kill trees. The spread of rust is
dependent on moisture. Fogbanks must envelop the trees for 48 hours
for the rust to spread.
</P>
<P>
   Those conditions are common west of the Continental Divide,
where warm, moist air flows inland from the Pacific Ocean. But
those conditions stop as they bump into the wall of the northern
Rockies. The east side of the divide, the Yellowstone side, is
cooler and much drier.
</P>
<P>
   As the earth's temperature rises, the atmosphere can hold more
moisture and becomes wetter as more water evaporates from the
surface. Some scientists say that in general this is happening now,
and research is under way in the park to determine whether it is
happening there.
</P>
<P>
   While that research is not conclusive, blister rust has been
spreading in the southern part of the region in the past few years.
``We've seen increasing heavy infections over the last five
years,'' said Roy Bergstrom, a forester on the Shoshone National
Forest in Wyoming. ``Maybe we have two to three decades before it
really spreads.''
</P>
<P>
   The orange fungus, which girdles the tree and kills branches,
could virtually wipe out the nut crop. Just one in 10,000 trees are
resistant. Because the whitebark pine is not commercially valuable,
the U.S. Forest Service is not spending money for research or
solutions to the rust problem. But some researchers are discussing
a number of possible strategies, all admittedly long shots.
</P>
<P>
   One choice is to do nothing. That is the present strategy of the
National Park Service, which has a natural regulation philosophy
that allows nature to take its course.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the disease spreads over hundreds of years, the tree will
adapt,'' says John Varley, chief scientist for the park. But if the
disease explodes in the next few years ``and it looks like 90
percent of the trees are going to die, it's conceivable we'll dial
up the Forest Service and ask them for disease-resistant trees and
plant them,'' he said. ``The trees are simply too important to this
ecosystem.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing is done and the trees die quickly, it could take 500
to 700 years for the groves to regenerate.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There is talk of ``genetic bottlenecking'' _ waiting for the
disease to run its course through some stands of whitebark pine in
the southern part of the ecosystem, and then taking pollen from
those that survive and using it to pollinate unaffected trees in
other places. Some scientists are talking about taking pollen from
resistant trees in Glacier or Idaho and doing the same thing.
Another possibility, Bergstrom said, is to burn away areas around
groves where trees have survived to create conditions favored by
Clark's nutcracker for stashing nuts, a kind of natural replanting.
</P>
<P>
   Officials agree they cannot simply let the tree die out and
plant the seeds of the survivors. ``If we wait till they're all
gone, it could take a long time to replace them,'' said Ward
McCaughey, a research forester with the Forest Service in Bozeman.
``It takes 30 years for a tree to produce a cone, and 50 to 80
years to produce a usable crop of nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Should even worst-case situations occur, biologists expect the
bear to survive. ``The bears would not curl up and die,'' Schwartz
said. ``They would find alternative food sources.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are not as sure. ``If it was just the nuts, they might be
OK,'' Wilcox said. ``But it's not. When you tie in the loss of
habitat from subdivisions, possible oil and gas leasing and other
things, then the long-term survival of the bear is far less
certain.''
</P>
<P>
   As scientists learn more about the complex ecology of species in
and beyond Yellowstone, they learn how much of the equation is well
beyond the control of the managers. For example, another important
grizzly bear food source is the army cutworm moth. The nondescript,
slate-gray moths flock in large numbers to the meadows above the
timberline in the park, where they feed on the nectar of alpine
flowers. They are another critical source of fat for perhaps as
many as a third of the park's grizzly bears, which overturn rocks
to lick up the insects, as many as 40,000 per bear in a single day.
It is possible that the moths could take up some of the slack
caused by a loss of pine nuts.
</P>
<P>
   In their larval stage, however, the cutworms live in wheat
fields on the plains of Montana and perhaps as far afield as
Kansas, where farmers consider them a pernicious pest. It is a
paradox not lost on Schwartz. ``We're monitoring the number of moth
sites and working diligently to understand this critical food
source,'' he said. ``And people are working just as diligently to
eliminate it as a pest.''
</P>
<P>
   A genetically modified seed that created a strain of wheat
resistant to cutworm moths, he said, could do as much damage or
more to the long-term viability of the grizzly as European blister
rust. ``It makes it clear how the bears are tied to everything,''
Wilcox said. ``The ecosystem really has no boundaries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
