<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9484 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-CENSUS-RACE-HNS &LR;      02-07 1766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-RACE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS REVISIONS BRING BOTH COMFORT, CONCERNS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Fla.) 
 
By KIM COBB 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Ryan Graham testified before Congress at age 12, a
committee member belittled him for declaring himself multiracial
instead of black.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have tried to pigeonhole me all of my life,'' Ryan
says, recalling the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, the teen and his family are celebrating a
personal victory: the 2000 Census expected on their Tallahassee,
Fla., doorstep next month will for the first time allow people to
identify themselves as a combination of races.
</P>
<P>
   The old method instructed those surveyed to choose one from a
handful of racial categories. Now, Americans can check off as many
boxes as they like _ providing the Census Bureau with data on 63
different possible racial combinations, plus a separate category
for Hispanic origin.
</P>
<P>
   The racial revisions to the census forms reflect the political
climate and, in part, the changing demographics of the United
States. The answers will reveal much about how Americans define
themselves, but raise other questions about the enforcement of
civil rights protections drawn for people who fit more narrow
racial definitions.
</P>
<P>
   The questions are serious enough that some black advocacy groups
are offering their constituencies subtle encouragement toward
identifying themselves as black, rather than multiracial, to avoid
diluting their political base.
</P>
<P>
   Some question whether the change in the racial options will add
to the confusion and reluctance people already associate with the
census, further dropping participation in this national head count.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `` &LR; We just don't know,'' admits Census Bureau race and
statistics chief Claudette Bennett. ``We explored those
possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States is expected to lose its white majority
sometime around 2050. For states with large immigrant populations
such as Texas and California, the change will come sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Census data show that the number of children born to parents of
different races grew from less than one-half million in 1970 to
about 2 million in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   But even those who lobbied for the right to identify with more
than one race are concerned about how government agencies will
tally these new combinations _ decisions that could affect
everything from the mapping of congressional boundaries drawn to
protect minority voting strength, to monitoring protections
guaranteed under civil rights laws.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of groups such as the National Urban League and the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People express
fear that people deserving the legal protections due black
Americans will be missed if counted as multiethnic rather than
black. And there's money at stake _ an estimated $182 billion will
be distributed annually based on formulas using Census 2000 data.
</P>
<P>
   Every U.S. Census has measured race, with each count reflecting
the laws, politics and immigration policy in place at the time. The
first census in 1790 reflected the nation's acceptance of slavery _
dividing people into Free White Males over 16, Free White Males
Under 16, Free White Females and Other Free Persons and Slaves.
</P>
<P>
   After slavery was abolished, race was still used by the
government to the detriment of ethnic and racial groups, says
Carnegie-Mellon University statistics professor Stephen E.
Fienberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, something surprising happened,'' said Fienberg. ``With
the Civil Rights Act, and the civil rights movement of the '60s,
suddenly there was a need to measure race in order to implement
government policy in support of minority groups, instead of to
control them.''
</P>
<P>
   The racial and ethnic categories appearing on the census forms
are determined by the Office of Management and Budget, which sets a
single standard for all federal statistics and administrative
reporting.
</P>
<P>
   This year's census offers slight variation in the racial
categories that were available in the last census: white, black,
American Indian and Alaska native, Asian, native Hawaiian and
Pacific Islander and ``some other race.'' But those surveyed in
2000 can check off as many race boxes as they like, and Hispanic
origin is a separate ethnic category.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a person could mark boxes declaring himself Asian,
black and white. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Every decade there is a big push by different groups to get
added to the list because there's a perception that if you're on
the list, you're a minority group, and you might get money that's
allocated and political power,'' Fienberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That process itself is, if not contentious, at least very
elaborate,'' Fienberg said. ``Every decade there's lots of public
hearings.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ryan Graham, the road to those public hearings started with
his mother's unsettling experience with the Census Bureau a decade
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I received my 1990 census form and I discovered no categories
for my children,'' Susan Graham recalled. ``I'm white, my husband
is black. My children are, at least, biracial.''
</P>
<P>
   She picked up the phone, called the Census Bureau, and asked
what box she was supposed to check for her children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children take the race of the mother,'' the clerk
responded, after checking with his supervisor. Why, Graham asked?
</P>
<P>
   ``In cases like this, we almost always know who the mother is
and we don't always know who the father is,'' the clerk responded,
dropping his voice nearly to a whisper.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have since apologized for that, but it took nearly four
years,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, when Graham was registering her son, Ryan, for
kindergarten, she was told it wasn't necessary to check the race
box on the registration forms, but later found that Ryan's teacher
was told to pick a category for him. She chose based on Ryan's
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the same child was white to the census, black at school,
and multiracial at home,'' Graham said. Choosing a racial category
labeled ``other'' was no solution, she said. It made Ryan feel like
a ``space alien.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming she couldn't be the only person struggling with this
problem, she founded an organization called ``Project Race'' to
lobby for multiracial classifications at all levels of government.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she and Ryan would testify before congressional
subcommittees considering the change in federal race categories.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing people to identify themselves as a combination of races
no longer offers a clear, statistical divide between black and
white, and it makes some civil rights groups nervous about
enforcing anti-discrimination law. Further complicating matters,
the Census Bureau has not finalized how those numbers will be
tabulated for redistricting purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, the Census Bureau's race and statistics chief, says
that, at a minimum, the bureau will present the six single racial
tabulation categories and a separate category called ``two or more
races.'' This would provide a baseline of information similar to
that collected in 1990, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The data is used in a voting rights perspective to see if
people who had their voting rights denied were still having their
voting rights denied and to see if people were still facing
employment discrimination,'' said William Spriggs, Urban League
Research and Policy Director.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not used in some biological sense, and it's not used in
some sort of touchy-feely sense of who are your parents, and who do
you want to recognize,'' Spriggs said. ``It's related to the
persistence of gaps born of legal segregation.''
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP is not opposed to allowing people to identify
themselves as more than one race, but fears that blacks will be
undercounted as a result. ``We're convinced a tabulation method has
to occur that's sensitive to our history and the support of civil
rights laws,'' said Hilary Shelton, director of the Washington
bureau of the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think about how the Census Bureau identified my
children in 1990 (it was) white,'' Graham said. The black community
lost numbers by that arbitrary determination, she said.
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, as many as 10 percent of Americans who would
have identified themselves as black in the last census will,
instead, identify themselves as members of several races. Melanie
Campbell, executive director of the National Coalition on Black
Voter Participation, said it's important for her organization
to &UR;  &LR; inform people about the potential consequences of that choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because people don't know this has anything to do with
redistricting or their potential for having a stronger voice for
electing candidates of choice, people need to be educated,''
Campbell said. ``With my conversations around the country, after
educating them, they'd rather check one box and not complicate the
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic origin is the only ethnic category specifically spelled
out in the census, which means tabulating their numbers will be a
straightforward head count. Officials for such groups as the
Mexican American Legal Defense and Education Fund are most
concerned that the census forms get to and are filled out in their
hardest-to-reach communities, such as migrant workers, immigrants
wary of the government and people living in nonstandard housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest hurdle is getting people to participate in the
census,'' said MALDEF census director Margaret Leal-Sotelo.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics will soon pass blacks as the largest minority group in
the United States, raising questions about the future of political
alliances between the two _ particularly in the face of the groups'
different measurements by the census.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coalitions that we currently have, especially at the
national level, are sustained because we still perceive
discrimination against our various groups,'' said the Urban
League's Spriggs. ``So they're not based on a box we check _
they're founded on a reality of discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be local areas, and Houston may be one, where there
are sufficient numbers of Hispanics, that a coalition between
blacks and Hispanics doesn't hold any longer,'' Spriggs said.
``Maybe Hispanics will feel they can have political power without a
coalition. But that, again, won't happen because of a box they
check.''
</P>
<P>
   Numbers, alone, will not change the balance of power, said Luis
Plascencia, associate director of the Texas office of the Thomas
Rivera Policy Institute. ``Simply being a majority doesn't get you
anything _ it's when you mobilize that you can translate it to
something.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
