<P>
   BUDGET-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton sent Congress a
budget proposal Monday built on the idea that the burgeoning budget
surplus will allow the nation to have it all, from increased
spending on government programs to tax cuts and big reductions in
the national debt. The president's budget, his eighth and last,
calls for additional spending across the range of issues that have
long been central to his agenda, including health care, education
and the environment. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ The Palestinian Authority on Monday
froze peace talks with the Israelis and then released from prison a
charismatic Islamic fundamentalist leader who is a withering
opponent of the peace effort. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-RANGEL (Washington) _ There's a jingle to Rep. Charles
Rangel's step now, a little like the ka-ching of a cash register
swallowing up dollar bills. ``They throw it at me,'' Rangel said,
only half-kidding, about the money he's collecting to win back
control of the House for the Democrats. The Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, which is in charge of raising
money and spending it strategically to win this year's crucial
House races, is awash in funds right now. In a remarkable
turnaround, the group has more than double the amount of cash in
the bank than its Republican counterpart in the House. And, in a
year of staggering warchests, it has managed to sock away more
money than any other party committee, Republican or Democrat. By
Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-ABORTION-PILL (Trappes, France) _ The students stopping
in at the high school infirmary on a recent morning were making
their usual requests: Some wanted aspirin. Others cold medicine.
One just wanted a place to cry because she had flunked a math test.
Soon, however _ as soon as the nurse here gets in her supply _
students will also be able to pick up morning after pills. In
January, France became the first country in the world to give its
school nurses the right to dispense emergency contraception pills.
The pills are to be available in both high schools and junior high
schools where students are as young as 12. And although the nurses
are advised to make efforts to inform the child's parents, they do
not have to. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   SC-VOICES (Columbia, S.C.) _ In interviews with voters across
South Carolina, it's not so much the numbers of McCain supporters
that you notice, but it's the passion. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
(1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DEL (Dover, Del.) _ Signaling a new, aggressive tone to his
campaign, a combative George W. Bush on Monday chipped away at the
reform mantle worn by his chief Republican rival, John McCain,
portraying the Arizona senator as someone who ``says one thing and
does another.'' With his once huge lead over McCain in the polls in
South Carolina now evaporated, Bush depicted himself as the genuine
reformer, citing his record as governor in Texas on issues such as
education, taxes and civil justice as one of ``a reformer with
results.'' He also conceded that he failed to define himself in
eyes of voters in New Hampshire and claimed that McCain distorted
his proposed tax cut plan. By Jim Yardley. (800 words)
</P>
