<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: CALIFORNIA, MCCAIN ON HIS WAY
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   John McCain has cut national front-runner George W. Bush's lead
among California Republicans in half, according to a poll released
today. Less than three weeks ago, Bush led McCain by 40 points in
the Field Poll. The same poll now shows Bush ahead 46-27 percent.
The poll (3.5 percentage point error margin) was conducted just
after New Hampshire. The poll also shows McCain in a statistical
tie with Al Gore in a potential general election matchup in
California, and comfortably ahead of Bill Bradley. McCain is in
Michigan today in advance of the Feb 22 primary there.
</P>
<P>
   Political reform message from Bush _ Unveiling his retooled
campaign message in Delaware today, George W. Bush called himself a
``reformer with results'' and accused John McCain of not living up
to his self-styled image as a political outsider. ``If you're tired
of no results and simple, empty rhetoric, if you're tired of people
saying one thing and doing another, come join my team,'' Bush said
as aides promised new emphasis on McCain's centerpiece issue:
political reform.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like desperation to McCain _ John McCain, campaigning in
Michigan, said today that George W. Bush's campaign is starting to
sound ``desperate,'' in the wake of the New Hampshire defeat.
McCain says Bush's new attacks on his campaign finance reform
message ``fly in the face of the facts.'' Bush has accused McCain
of engaging in ``Washington double talk'' for attacking special
interests while also courting their financial support.
</P>
<P>
   The battle of Delaware _ George W. Bush is trying to take some
of the sting out of his huge loss to John McCain in the New
Hampshire primary by bouncing back in Delaware. Bush campaigned in
The First State on Friday, and was back today. Forbes has spent
four days on a bus tour of the state, with two more town meetings
on tap today. Forbes won the state four years ago, gaining 33
percent of the vote to beat Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Spoiling for a fight _ The conventional wisdom in conservative
circles is that the longer Steve Forbes stays in the race, the more
votes he pulls away from George W. Bush. Bush adviser Ralph Reed:
By running negative attacks, he has only succeeded in hurting the
front-runner, and it is self-evident he has not helped himself.''
The University of Virginia's Larry Sabato: ``I wonder whether, at
this point, Forbes will stay in the race merely to help destroy
George W. Bush. ... There is no question Forbes dislikes Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Focus on traditional constituencies _ Aiming at the
coast-to-coast primaries of March 7, Al Gore and Bill Bradley
opened a national battle Monday for the minorities, women and union
members at the core of the Democratic Party. Bradley campaigned for
black support in Florida; Gore courted labor in New York. Bradley
is targeting minority voters for the moment, in Florida today and
then to South Carolina for a symbolic bash at the Confederate flag
flying over the Statehouse. But Gore has built strong ties
minorities over the past eight years, and analysts say it won't be
easy for Bradley to push past that.
</P>
<P>
   Impasse on debates _ Representatives of the two Democratic
campaigns failed to reach agreement on whether the candidates will
hold regular debates, according to Bill Bradley spokesman Eric
Hauser. Bradley has challenged Al Gore to debate once a week, while
Gore wants to debate twice a week _ but only if the two candidates
give up most TV ads as part of any deal. The two sides will discuss
the issue again Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to Sharpton for help
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton called on Al Gore to debate Bill Bradley on
race and urban issues, and he hinted that he would encourage black
voters in New York to support Bradley if Gore did not do so. With
Bradley at his side at the Allen AME Church in Queens on Sunday,
Sharpton said that he had found only what he characterized as
disturbing signals or indifference from the Gore campaign on racial
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Ready for prime time? _ Former Sen. Alan Simpson (R-Wyo.)
revived a charge that he and Bob Dole made in 1992: that Al Gore's
decision to vote for U.S. intervention in the Persian Gulf War was
based, at least in part, on which side would give him the better
prime time speaking slot during the televised Senate debate. Dole,
according to the Boston Globe, said Gore asked him how much time
the pro-intervention side would give him. Fifteen minutes was the
answer. Dole said Gore told him the other side had offered only
seven minutes. Gore's response to Dole, according to the Globe:
``Let me think about it.'' Says Mary Romash of the Gore campaign:
``It is wrong. It is irresponsible. The people who say it are
nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Time to get back to real life _ The New York Daily News reports
that Donald Trump _ who never was an official presidential
candidate anyway _ is ``pulling out of the race in about two
weeks,'' and, ``that may mean a public reconciliation with model
Melania Knauss.
</P>
<P>
   And that safari helmet looks great _ Ignoring a plea by the
Humane Society of the United States, George W. Bush accepted a
conservation award from an organization of trophy hunters that the
society says promotes the killing of rare species. But it was his
father, the former president, who went to Reno, Nev., as keynote
speaker to accept it. The Safari Club International was honoring
the younger Bush as ``governor of the Year.'' ``It's my
understanding they're recognizing him for his conservation efforts
in Texas,'' said Bush campaign spokesman Scott McClellan.
</P>
<P>
   Shuffle off to Buffalo _ A day after announcing officially,
Hillary Rodham Clinton kicked off her first swing through upstate
New York as an official candidate for Senate. She was greeted by
about three dozen supporters this morning at a charter airstrip
outside Buffalo, where she planned to address job growth and
economic issues. ``We have a lot of work to do, but it will be
fun,'' Clinton told one supporter as she autographed campaign
signs.
</P>
<P>
   Move that spotlight a little over this way _ Long before Hillary
Rodham Clinton took the stage Sunday, Rudolph Giuliani had spent
hours in interviews, hopping from one TV studio to another to
promote his Senate candidacy on five morning news programs, and
then tending to mayoral obligations including a hospital party for
children with heart problems. At each stop, he focused relentlessly
on promoting his record as mayor, and sought to underscore the
point that Clinton has never served in elective office.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
