<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9498 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-BUDGET-BOS &LR;      02-07 0353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINDING THE GAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although it was hard to discern amid the veritable hailstorm of
new proposals, President Clinton's final budget proposal, released
Monday, accentuated a goal he has been pursuing more vigorously of
late: narrowing the income gap.
</P>
<P>
   This is a worthy goal. Many studies have shown the growing
disparity between the economic circumstances of the nation's
richest 20 percent of the population and the poorest 20 or 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pointed to this gap in the 1992 campaign. ``While taxes
fall and incomes rise for those at the top of the totem pole,'' he
said simply, ``middle-class families pay more and earn less.''
</P>
<P>
   During his time in office, the wealthiest have generally
prospered _ many enormously _ while those at the bottom have
stagnated or actually slipped back. The major relief has been
expansion of the Earned Income Tax Credit, which provides
significant tax relief to low-wage workers. Still, the heavy burden
of Social Security and other payroll taxes leaves many at the low
end struggling.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton's health care proposals were defeated in 1994, he
mentioned the income gap less often. But in recent months this has
changed, as he has taken business leaders around the country to
emphasize populations and regions that need investment.
</P>
<P>
   The new budget unveiled Monday contains a number of proposals
that would open opportunities for those with modest incomes. It
would increase tax credits for child care, for persons who provide
relatives with long-term care, and for working families with three
or more children. It would soften the marriage penalty in the
existing tax code, and it would encourage savings for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   A tax break for college expenses would also be helpful, if there
is a way to make sure the schools don't gobble up the money by
raising fees.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, these budget proposals for low- and moderate-income
persons amount to a modest tax cut that would use the budget
surplus to help the nation grow together.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 1837EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
