<HEADLINE>
ANTIDOTE TO SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there is a primary reason for the resilience of liberal
democracies, it is that they are self-correcting. Witness the
successive revelations about corruption scandals tainting Germany's
erstwhile chancellor, Helmut Kohl, after 16 years in power.
</P>
<P>
   The first wave of scandal concerned hidden donations to his
Christian Democrat Party, money that Kohl controlled in secret
slush funds. Now come investigations of enormous payoffs to
well-connected middlemen in Germany and France who greased the
rails for a sale of German tanks to Saudi Arabia and the purchase
by a French oil company of a dilapidated oil refinery in the former
East Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most telling aspect of these cases is that the
corruption alleged was not confined by national borders and is now
being pursued by prosecutors in Germany, France, and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the East German oil refinery to Elf-Aquitaine,
citizens on both sides of the Rhine are now learning, was a shady
deal that produced not only $60 million in dubious commissions for
former intelligence officials but also a package of geopolitical
payoffs: to the French government of former president Francois
Mitterrand for its acceptance of German unification and to Kohl for
his support of a European single currency and the diluting of
Germany's influence in a unified Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The refinery affair as well as the complex transaction that
resulted in the transfer of 36 German Army tanks to Saudi Arabia a
decade ago suggest a systemic penchant for corruption that would
not seem out of place in contemporary Russia. The great difference
is that the polities of France and Germany show signs of being able
to expose, cleanse, and correct their corruption.
</P>
<P>
   It is healthy that Kohl's Christian Democrats are paying a
political price for the sins of yesteryear and that the complicity
of French authorities is being illuminated. A free press and an
independent judiciary are the stabilizers that keep liberal
democracies from being capsized by leaders like Mitterrand and
Kohl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
