<HEADLINE>
THE MESSAGE OF RISK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since the world became aware of the dimension of the AIDS
epidemic and the role that sex plays in its transmission, health
officials have tried to make the public aware of which sex
practices were most dangerous and which less so. This is no easy
matter; with an infected partner no unprotected sex is completely
safe. On the other hand, officials have been reluctant to portray
all acts as dangerous for fear that their counsel would simply be
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   This balancing of risk and realism was shaken last week with the
report from a carefully conducted study in San Francisco showing
that, in one group of 102 gay and bisexual men with AIDS, about 8
percent were infected through oral sex. This is a huge increase in
the risk factor that AIDS specialists initially had attributed to
oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   The study caught the attention of AIDS specialists in
Massachusetts and elsewhere. Jean Maguire of the state Department
of Public Health's AIDS bureau said her office will be notifying
AIDS-prevention groups it works with about the heightened concern
over oral sex. Carisa Cunningham of AIDS Action Committee of
Massachusetts sees the study as a corrective to those who, as she
puts it, ``hear `safe' '' when they are told that something like
oral sex is ``safer'' than unprotected anal sex.
</P>
<P>
   The message about the risk of oral sex should especially be
delivered by AIDS-prevention groups and sex-education instructors
working with adolescents. As Maguire notes, this is a population
that is difficult to reach with any information about health and
sex. Better ways simply have to be found to make clear the full
danger of an act that many indulge in casually.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ronald Valdiserri of the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention values the new study for its emphasis on preventing the
disease. ``America doesn't seem to be as engaged in prevention as
we are,'' he said. After last week's report, everyone in America _
but especially parents, teachers, doctors, and health officials _
have good reason to be more engaged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
