<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Feb. 13) 
(jt) 
 By SUZANNE MacNEILLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Day Trips From Heathrow &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a nine-hour layover at Heathrow, and would like some
tips on where to spend an afternoon without going into London
proper. I'd prefer an activity that involves some walking. And
please include information on public transportation. _ Sydney Lyle,
Rochester
</P>
<P>
   A. There are many lovely places near Heathrow where you can
stretch your legs. The following sites are about 30 to 45 minutes
from the airport and are easily accessible by public
transportation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Botanic Gardens, a few minutes' walk from the Kew
Gardens subway station on the westbound District Line, was
originally two royal estates, which George III merged in the late
18th century. The site is now a 300-acre center for science and
conservation with greenhouses, galleries, follies, a museum and a
collection of more than 30,000 plants. You'll find gardens devoted
to bluebells, roses, rhododendrons and azaleas; stands of sweet
chestnut, juniper and Japanese cedar, as well as greenhouse gardens
devoted to alpine, tropical, rain-forest and temperate species. The
gardens open at 9:30 a.m.; closing time varies from 3:30 to 6:30
p.m., depending on the season. Admission is $8, figured at a rate
of 62 pence to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond-upon-Thames, also on the District Line, is one subway
stop beyond Kew Gardens. The pretty, prosperous London suburb, with
its central Green surrounded by 17th- and 18th-century houses is
fun to explore, especially for architecture buffs. Among the
noteworthy buildings are the late 19th-century Richmond Theater (on
the Green); the 18th-century stone Asgill House at the end of Old
Palace Lane; the Museum of Richmond in Old Town Hall on Whittaker
Avenue (admission is free); and the early 18th-century Maids of
Honor Row, a collection of four three-story houses, built to house
the Maids of Honor who attended the Princess of Wales during the
time of George II. Nearby is the 2,358-acre Richmond Park, home to
herds of red and fallow deer. Information: (44-181) 940 9125.
</P>
<P>
   Another opion is Windsor Castle, one of Queen Elizabeth II's
three official residences. You can visit St. George's Chapel, the
State Apartments, Queen Mary's Dolls House, as well as the castle's
precincts. Hours are 9:45 a.m. to 4 p.m.; admission is $17.
</P>
<P>
   Signs for subway and bus stations at Heathrow are clearly
posted. If you travel after 9:30 a.m., the most economical option
for getting to Kew Gardens and Richmond-upon-Thames is to buy a
one-day unlimited London Travel Card _ good for buses and subways _
for $5.35.
</P>
<P>
   For transportation to Windsor take the No. 191 or 192 bus from
the station at Heathrow. A round-trip ticket costs $7.25.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Budget Lodgings in Belem &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can you give me the names of some inexpensive, atmospheric
accommodations in Belem? I'd like to keep the price to $50 or
under. _ Jonathan Levy, Brooklyn
</P>
<P>
   A. You won't have a hard time finding atmospheric lodgings in
Belem, capital of the northern Brazilian state of Para. In fact,
large portions of this 384-year-old port city at the mouth of the
Amazon River are loaded with a distinctive Brazilian-colonial
ambience _ from the narrow streets lined with blue-tiled,
Portuguese-style buildings to the bustling market selling
everything from Amazonian fish and manioc flour to medicinal herbs
and religious potions.
</P>
<P>
   The Parque dos Igarapes, about four miles from downtown, has 15
bungalows set on 40 acres of Amazon forest. The rustic bungalows,
built of wood and straw, are air-conditioned; a double room with
private bath is $50. The hotel is at the mouth of the Ariri River
and guests have access to canoes, as well as a swimming pool,
volleyball court and soccer fields. The hotel is at Kilometer 7 of
the Augusto Montenegro Road; telephone (5591) 248-1718, fax (5591)
248-6910.
</P>
<P>
   The Manaca Hotel, in the pleasant suburb of Nazare, is a
renovated old house with 16 rooms. It is decorated in a colonial
style, with tropical hardwood furniture. The rooms have
air-conditioning, private baths, telephones and television sets.
Doubles, including breakfast, are $35. The address is 1645 Travessa
Quintino Bocaiuva. Information: (5591) 222-6227.
</P>
<P>
   Guest rooms at the Hotel Central, at 290 Avenida Presidente
Vargas (Belem's main street), have gorgeous wooden transoms on the
windows, 14-foot ceilings and a bathroom with original 1930s tiles.
Doubles are $30. Information: (5591) 241-8177.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Left Bank Tours &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm going to Paris for the first time and want to take a
walking tour of the Left Bank. Can you help? _ Sandra Liever,
Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   A. Organizations offering guided tours of the Left Bank are
plentiful. Unless otherwise noted, the companies below offer tours
in English as well as in French.
</P>
<P>
   Decouvrir Paris has many tours of Parisian neighborhoods and
buildings. Traditional Left Bank tourist haunts like
St.-Germain-des-Pres are covered, but Decouvrir Paris also visits
less well-known neighborhoods like La Butte aux Cailles, an ethnic
neighborhood with Russian and Alsatian enclaves, in the 13th
Arrondissement. Tours last 90 minutes and cost $7.50 (figured at a
rate of 6.72 francs to the dollar), plus additional entrance fees,
when applicable. Information: (33-1) 47.89.41.68.
</P>
<P>
   Paris a Pied, which is based in Minneapolis, has a Left Bank
tour that lasts three hours and covers a lot of ground, passing
through the Mouffetard quarter, the Pantheon, the Luxembourg
Gardens, the Sorbonne and and Cluny. This tour costs $45 and
includes a coffee break. Reservations: (800) 594-9535. Information
is also available at www.parisapied.com.
</P>
<P>
   Claude Marti has been leading walking tours in Paris for six
years. He is certified by the Culture Ministry, which gives his
groups access to many courtyards and interesting interiors normally
closed to the public. Marti's tours range from the winding
Mouffetard quarter in the Fifth Arrondissement to the renovated
neighborhood around the new Francois Mitterrand Library, in the
13th Arrondissement. Tours are in French only; they last two hours
and cost $7.50. Information: (33-1) 40.31.56.06.
</P>
<P>
   You might also refer to the weekly publication Pariscope, sold
at newspaper kiosks. It gives a day-by-day listing of walking tours
under the heading ``Promenades.'' Recent examples included a tour
of the St. Sulpice Quarter and the Montparnasse Cemetery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
