<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't let the good times go to your head
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The economic expansion that started in March 1991 has raised
real gross domestic product by more than a third, put the federal
budget into a surprising surplus situation and given jobs to people
once outside the working world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best of all,'' says Business Week (Feb. 14) in a special cover
package, ``it has transformed the psyche of millions of Americans.
The pervasive gloom at the beginning of the 1990s is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Business investment in computer technology, which improved
productivity, gets credit for the boom, along with the
restructuring of corporations into lean and mean fighting machines
capable of taking on global competition.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, says Business Week, too many people have given in
to the temptation to conclude that this ``New Economy'' also means
the end of the business cycle. That is wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Many sober economic historians think the current situation is
too reminiscent of the economic boom of the 1920s, when inflation
was low, productivity was high and the stock market soared.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Eichengreen, an economist at the University of California
at Berkeley and leading expert on the Great Depression and the
international financial crises of the 1990s, put it this way: ``If
you believe history repeats itself, all the ingredients are there
for a stock market-led downturn.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting an early start
</P>
<P>
   About two stocks a week went on the market for the first time in
1999 and at least doubled quickly in price. Yet most individual
investors were unable to buy shares of those initial public
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   According to Worth (February), the lion's share of an IPO goes
to the 100 biggest money managers, and most of the rest goes to
institutions, leaving only a small amount for wealthy individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's package of articles on the ins and outs of IPOs
explains why the little guy has such a little chance of making a
killing in this market.
</P>
<P>
   Too much tech too fast
</P>
<P>
   The attempt by Flowers Industries to modernize production of its
Mrs. Smith's line of pies in less than 12 months backfired because
it was too much too fast, Forbes (Feb. 21) says in a profile of the
Thomasville-based snack foods company. Equipment that was supposed
to work didn't, and costs swelled as the company hired people to do
what the technology didn't, Forbes says.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive Officer Amos McMullian told Forbes the company
will have ``record earnings at Mrs. Smith's and Flowers this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning
</P>
<P>
   For all the pre-Christmas hype about online buying, shoppers
were dissatisfied, says The Economist (Feb. 11). In fighting for
market share, most online retailers neglected to fulfill customer
service. The magazine says eToys failed to deliver 4 percent of its
merchandise in time for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Working Woman (February) offers a Dick-and-Jane primer on what
it takes for women _ and presumably men _ to get on headhunters'
lists of good job candidates for a career change.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
