<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9509 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SF-MODERN-ART-2TAKES-     02-07 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-MODERN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECKS FLYING, SAN FRANCISCO BUILDS A MODERN ART COLLECTION
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Four years ago, when the San Francisco Museum of
Modern Art unveiled its new home, a $63 million brick-clad building
designed by the Swiss architect Mario Botta, the trustees quickly
saw their problem. The museum's painfully skimpy art collection was
dwarfed by the large, sun-filled galleries.
</P>
<P>
   Many visitors who flocked downtown to the 225,000-square-foot
structure, just across the street from the city's new arts complex,
left shaking their heads. Where, they asked, was the art?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was aware our paintings did not justify the building,''
recalled Phyllis Wattis, 94, the museum's biggest benefactor.
``After it opened, I was almost embarrassed by our collection.''
</P>
<P>
   While no other trustees dared to be as forthcoming about the
collection's deficiencies, they all agreed something had to be
done. And fast. So they dug into their deep pockets and turned
their museum into the biggest buyer in the contemporary art world.
</P>
<P>
   In less than two years the trustees have helped the museum
acquire more than $130 million worth of art by contemporary masters
like Jasper Johns, Robert Rauschenberg, Ellsworth Kelly and Mark
Rothko. Their shopping habits _ paying top dollar for the best
available _ are more aggressive than those of any museum in the
world right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trustees are in it to win,'' said Matthew Marks, A New
York City dealer who has worked with the museum, helping to
negotiate the sale of 22 early works by Kelly and to organize a
show of recent works by Johns. ``People love the new in San
Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   While the trustees say they cannot possibly compete with the
Museum of Modern Art in New York, whose core collection was formed
in the early part of the 20th century, they would like to.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way we could be better than MOMA,'' said Donald
Fisher, founder of the Gap clothing chain and a San Francisco
trustee. ``But we'll be delighted to be recognized as an
outstanding museum worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   The force driving the museum is a group of high-profile
executives and their wives who not only love contemporary art but
also collect it with a passion. Besides Fisher and Wattis, widow of
Paul Wattis, a construction and mining magnate, the trustees
include Charles Schwab, chairman and founder of the discount
brokerage firm; Mimi Haas, the wife of Peter Haas, a former
chairman of Levi Strauss; Leanne Roberts, wife of George Roberts, a
partner in the firm of Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co.; and Pamela
Kramlich, the wife of Richard Kramlich, the venture capitalist.
</P>
<P>
   In much the same way that the new rich of the last century _
Morgans and Rockefellers, Mellons and Palmers _ shaped great
museums by buying art or donating entire collections to the
Metropolitan Museum of Art and the Museum of Modern Art in New
York, the National Gallery of Art in Washington and the Art
Institute of Chicago, their West Coast counterparts are intent on
building a world-class museum in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a golden age here,'' said Gary Garrels, the museum's
chief curator for the last seven years, who resigned last month to
become a curator at the Modern in New York. ``San Francisco is in a
boom.''
</P>
<P>
   A gateway to the Pacific rim and barely half an hour from
Silicon Valley, San Francisco has consolidated its position as a
center of commerce and power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The locus of innovation has shifted westward in the United
States,'' Schwab, chairman of the museum's investment committee,
said in an interview in the museum's all-white boardroom, with
trial pages from the museum's updated Web site tacked on a wall.
``Entrepreneurship is a big thing in San Francisco, and the visual
arts are particularly amenable to it. The art world moves so much
more quickly than, say, music. It reflects our changing society.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, when David Ross resigned from the Whitney Museum
of American Art in New York City to become director of the museum
here, popularly known as SFMOMA (pronounced S.F. MO-ma), he said
his decision had to do with San Francisco's being the only city in
the world where the No. 1 museum featured modern art. ``The idea of
modernity is congruent with San Francisco, '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For its first 60 years the modern art museum was a poor cousin
to other local attractions, especially the 106-year-old
institutions that make up the Fine Arts Museums of San Francisco:
the M.H. de Young Memorial Museum, which specializes in American,
African, Oceanian and pre-Columbian art from the Americas; and the
Legion of Honor, devoted to ancient and European art.
</P>
<P>
   Housed in rented, cramped quarters upstairs in the
Depression-era War Memorial Veterans Building in the Civic Center,
the modern art museum organized some important exhibitions, but it
never had the space or the budget to do anything significant. So
its move to a new building was considered bold.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago this downtown neighborhood south of Market Street,
the major axis of downtown San Francisco, was the equivalent of
Hell's Kitchen in Manhattan, a seedy part of the city where the
museum's moneyed trustees dared not go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to do a lot of convincing that this was the right
move,'' said Wattis. ``Several key members of the board left
because of it. A lot of trustees had never crossed Market Street on
foot before. They thought I was the most adventurous person in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's Redevelopment Agency was trying to transform the
downtown area into an arts district and was looking for an
institution to become its anchor. To encourage the museum's move,
the agency offered to sell a parcel of land at Third and Mission
Streets for $1 if the money to build and operate the museum could
be raised privately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw the city changing, and this was a chance to become a
part of it,'' said Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Today the neighborhood is home to the Yerba Buena Center for the
Arts, right across the street. Around the corner, on Mission
Street, the Jewish Museum is gearing up to move into a building
designed by the Polish architect Daniel Liebeskind. The Italian
architect Gae Aulenti is designing a Mexican Museum next door to
the Jewish Museum. Restaurants, shops, art galleries and
photography studios have sprouted in the neighborhood, which also
has an existing Sony entertainment complex.
</P>
<P>
   The move downtown was led by John R. Lane, the former director
of the museum who is now director of the Dallas Museum of Art, and
John Caldwell, the San Francisco museum's first curator of painting
and sculpture, who died in 1993. Ross and the trustees credit these
two men with inspiring the museum's benefactors to collect
contemporary art for its galleries and for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Now Ross and some of the trustees are looking for creative ways
to lure gifts to the museum, especially from Silicon Valley's rich
young technology pioneers, who may collect cars and yachts but not
art. Some trustees have made partial or promised gifts of their
art, a common way of taking a tax deduction while enjoying their
collections during their lifetimes. Others, like the San Francisco
real estate investor Paul Sack and his wife, Prentice, who have a
collection of 1,000 photographs, have created trusts that yield tax
deductions equal to the full appraised value, a larger tax break
than if they had donated the collection as partial or promised
gifts.
</P>
<P>
   As a result the museum is offered everything that comes on the
market. ``The trustees around here do not bargain,'' said Ross.
``They recognize that one of the reasons great pictures are being
offered to us is because our trustees are willing to pay. They know
what a great picture is worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Even artists are getting into the act. Both Rauschenberg and
Kelly have recently sold the museum large bodies of work that they
had long held onto. In honor of Wattis, Rauschenberg also gave the
museum ``Hiccups,'' a monumental work from 1978 consisting of 97
drawings on sheets of handmade paper fastened together and
extending 63 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Johns was flattered when Garrels asked him to exhibit his latest
works at the museum last September. The largest of them, a painting
called ``Bridge,'' was bought anonymously by a trustee. It was the
first time Johns' work had been shown in San Francisco in more than
20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Last week an anonymous donor bought the museum a 1971 painting
by Cy Twombly. The 10-by-16-foot work came from the artist's
collection in a deal negotiated by Larry Gagosian, the Manhattan
dealer.
</P>
<P>
   The museum also keeps an eye on important gallery shows. It
recently bought ``Princess of the Posse,'' a major painting by the
Chris Ofili, part of the group known as the Young British Artists;
it was among five of his works displayed last fall at Gavin Brown
Enterprises in New York City. Ofili's ``Holy Virgin Mary,''
exhibited in the Brooklyn Museum of Art's ``Sensation'' show, was
the subject of great controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Arne Glimcher, chairman of PaceWildenstein, which has branches
in New York and Los Angeles, is responsible for the Rauschenberg
purchase. ``San Francisco moves very quickly,'' he said. ``It's
good for the artists to have museums of modern art on both
coasts.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the museums of modern art on both coasts are outwardly
collegial, it is hard not to notice the copycat acquisitions list.
In June the Modern in New York announced that it had acquired four
works by Rauschenberg; a year ago the San Francisco museum acquired
14. In May 22 works by Kelly came to San Francisco; New York's
Modern acquired 15 works on paper by him in 1997 and his `Sculpture
for a Large Wall, 1957'' in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're competitive people,'' said Fisher. ``We're in
competitive businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   There is even competition among the trustees, and Wattis has
helped egg them on. A philanthropist whose largess extends well
beyond this museum, she has led many of its most expensive art
purchases. She thinks nothing of phoning other trustees and asking
them to write big checks. And they do.
</P>
<P>
   In April the museum spent what is reported to be $60 million on
10 works by artists like Johns, Frank Stella and Roy Lichtenstein
from Fukuoka, the Japanese bank. It has also paid often
record-breaking prices at auction for artists like Rothko, Eva
Hesse and Magritte.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics think the museum is overpaying and not necessarily
buying the right things. ``They buy rich, but they don't buy
smart,'' said Francis Bowes, who along with her husband, John,
resigned from the museum's board when Ross became director.
``They're too cavalier with money, spending far more than a
collector would for things. They also don't support local
galleries.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the big spending has helped raise the institution's
profile. Attendance has grown nearly 50 percent in the last 18
months. Membership is at an all-time high, with nearly 40,000
people paying the minimum fee of $55 a year.
</P>
<P>
   On Ross' to-do list: First, stabilize the museum's $50 million
endowment with a capital campaign. Next, create a
14,000-square-foot open-air sculpture gallery on top of the new
garage; the old underground garage will become an expanded
education center. Then there are plans to build a collections and
research department to cope with the huge volume of acquisitions.
This would entail hiring scholars and researchers. And like all
museums, this one is thinking commercially, planning to expand its
store and open a satellite shop in the new San Francisco airport.
</P>
<P>
   There is also talk of expanding the gallery spaces by close to
100,000 square feet, by building wings on either side of the
building, an expansion Botta took into account as part of his
initial design.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a 10-year plan,'' said Ross. ``It all could occur
faster. But I don't want to move too fast. I inherited something
great here, and I want it to last.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
