<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISHOP SPONG WILL NOT GO QUIETLY INTO RETIREMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (Resending to fix summary line) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bishop John Shelby Spong, a gadfly liberal churchman from
Newark, N.J., officially retired as an active bishop last week,
much to the delight of many who see his theology as heretical.
</P>
<P>
   But the 68-year-old Spong, known as Jack by his supporters and
detractors, isn't going away. He will likely remain the nation's
most controversial Episcopalian.
</P>
<P>
   During his 23 years as a bishop, Spong has forcefully spoken out
for the right of homosexuals to be ordained. He has written
shocking books, such as ``Why Christianity Must Change or Die,''
which calls for revamping most of the doctrines of his own church.
</P>
<P>
   I spoke with him last week by phone just as he and his wife,
Chris, had moved into an apartment at Harvard University, where
Spong will lecture for the next several months. Spong will be
delivering the William Belden Noble Lectures, which will become the
basis of a new book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll also be teaching a course to young clergy on how to
preach,'' he said. ``We get about 2,000 seconds of people's time
for every sermon, more time than most people get to voice their
views. We need to make the most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Spong certainly makes the most of his time.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his Harvard lectures, he will be in Texas next
week to speak in Dallas, Houston, Austin and San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   He will discuss ``Overcoming the Barriers of Prejudice'' at 6
p.m. Feb. 12 at the Cathedral of Hope in Dallas, the nation's
largest predominantly gay congregation. He will also sign copies of
his new autobiography, ``Here I Stand: My Struggle for a
Christianity of Integrity, Love &AMP; Equality'' (Harper San Francisco,
$25).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel very retired, yet,'' Spong said.
</P>
<P>
   Spong's 464-page autobiography traces his evolution from a young
man growing up in the conservative South to his championship of
liberal causes.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Charlotte, N.C., and as a youth delivered
newspapers to Billy Graham's family, who lived about a mile away
from the Spongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also lived in Lynchburg, Va., in the same town with Jerry
Falwell,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised a biblical fundamentalist,'' he said. ``I would
have gone over well in East Texas during my early years. But I've
come a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Spong reveals that he had trouble dressing like a bishop at
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``For five years, I could not bring myself to wear the purple
shirt of the bishop's office,'' he writes. ``It reminded me of
someone trying to be Robin Redbreast.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after becoming a bishop in 1976, Spong began advocating
the right of gays and lesbians to be ordained. He believes that
eventually everyone will agree that gays should not be banned from
the priesthood because of their sexual orientation because of
growing evidence that people do not choose their sexual
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't choose to be a heterosexual,'' he said in the
interview. ``I just woke up when I was about 12 years old and
thought that girls were OK.''
</P>
<P>
   In his autobiography, he credits retired Fort Worth Episcopal
Bishop Clarence Pope, one of Spong's strongest critics, with
helping to create the international headlines surrounding Spong's
ordination of a noncelibate man.
</P>
<P>
   Pope was one of the first to issue a statement denouncing
Spong's action. His statements were reported locally and worldwide.
Spong then responded to Pope's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had known Clarence for more than 20 years. ... I genuinely
liked him,'' Spong writes. ``I had no intention, however, of
stopping this ordination to keep Clarence happy. What Clarence had
done ... was to turn the ordination into a media event. Our diocese
had hoped to avoid making this a spectacle.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the few formal denunciations, Pope and others led a
successful move in the House of Bishops to dissociate the group
from Spong's ordination of the openly gay man.
</P>
<P>
   Spong has antagonized traditional Christian thinkers at every
turn. In one of his books, ``Rescuing the Bible From
Fundamentalism,'' he speculated that the Apostle Paul might have
been gay. He suggested that Jesus might have been married to Mary
Magdalene.
</P>
<P>
   He has been called the Antichrist and the devil incarnate. But
he also has quite a following among those who are searching for a
more meaningful faith.
</P>
<P>
   Spong will be a bishop for life, and he has the right to vote
and discuss issues at this year's Episcopal General Convention. But
he has vowed not to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised, though, if Spong makes waves again. He has a
lifelong habit of shooting from the hip when it comes to discussing
volatile theological, moral and ethical issues. And it is a habit
not easily broken.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
