<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK WEIGHS IN ON HEALTH ISSUE FOR BLACK WOMEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It took two pregnancies to put meat on my bones.
</P>
<P>
   Until then my weight had fluctuated between 110 and 116 pounds.
I ate like two men. I looked anorexic. Great metabolism, I used to
boast.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not overweight, but I'm not bragging anymore. Nowadays, I
have to watch my weight like the rest of America. But I don't diet,
mind you. Never have. Never will.
</P>
<P>
   When I've abstained from food, it has been strictly for
spiritual reasons. I've fasted for as many as three days at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I was a little more than intrigued recently when Kathleen
Rodgers wrote me about this new book: ``Slim Down Sister: The
African-American Woman's Guide to Healthy, Permanent Weight Loss''
by Roniece Weaver, Angela Ebron and Fabiola Gaines (E.P. Dutton,
$23.95).
</P>
<P>
   I always thought _ based on my own personal experiences, of
course _ that the best way to keep weight off was simply to watch
your waistband. If it feels tight around the waist, pull back on
your appetite a bit.
</P>
<P>
   So I didn't know what to make of Slim Down Sister. This was not
my struggle. At least not in the personal sense.
</P>
<P>
   But then, talking the other day with Ebron about the statistics
made this issue feel too close for comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty-two percent of us are overweight, and it doesn't show
any signs of slowing down,'' said Ebron, referring to
African-American women. ``There is tons of research that will
convince even the most skeptical person that being overweight is
linked to life-threatening diseases like hypertension, diabetes,
heart disease and certain types of cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   I had to think only of my five sisters, all overweight, most of
them suffering from one of these ailments. My mother, though not
overweight, died of a heart attack at 43. I remembered a night
recently at choir rehearsal and the prayer requests from sisters
about to undergo surgery or tests to determine the source of their
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Look at them, talk to Ebron and you know why.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times it takes a health scare to convince someone to
try to lose,'' said Ebron, a senior editor and fitness writer for
``Family Circle'' magazine. ``That's the thing that snaps a lot of
people into reality. Hopefully, sisters will pick this book up
before they have the health problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebron knows what she's talking about. Losing weight has been a
lifelong battle for her. The emotional ups and downs are like best
friends. And that's the reason, she said, she joined with Weaver
and Gaines to write what is being billed as the first weight-loss
book written especially for African-American women.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to addressing the serious health concerns of black
women, Slim Down Sister offers tips for exercising and streamlining
your diet, real-life testimonials from women who have lost weight
and kept it off, a guide to organizing a weight-loss program at
your church and how to set up a support system.
</P>
<P>
   ``As someone who identifies with the reader,'' Ebron said,
``there wasn't anything out there that addressed our specific
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Where diet is concerned, Ebron found that the majority of books
offered dietary substitutes like tofu, a bland protein foreign to
most African-American palates.
</P>
<P>
   But with Slim Down Sister, you don't have to sacrifice
traditional family meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want food that we like, that our family like, that reflect
our heritage,'' Ebron said. ``You can have pretty much any food you
want. It's about moderation.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also about exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a chapter even I can use.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 1844EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
