<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9520 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r b BC-PRAYER-LANGUAGE-TEX     02-07 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRAYER-LANGUAGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME, SPEAKING TO GOD IN AN ANCIENT TONGUE PUTS FAITH ON A
HIGHER PLANE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By LIZ STEPHENS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some years back, a student approached religious-studies
Professor Kay Read with a complaint. The student attended a
Catholic church where the prayers, which she had memorized, had
always been recited in Latin. Then one day the church switched to
English.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she finally understood what was going on, she didn't like
it,'' recalls Read, an associate professor at DePaul University in
Chicago. The words were not what she had thought they were.
</P>
<P>
   Billions of people across the globe pray in languages different
from the ones they speak. These sacred tongues are usually ancient
languages, often written or spoken by the religions' founders and
frozen in time. They include Arabic for Muslims, Hebrew for Jews,
Sanskrit for Hindus, Latin for Catholics and Pali for Theravada
Buddhists. But outside of Arabic, and to a far lesser extent
Hebrew, most of the languages aren't readily spoken anymore _ a few
never were.
</P>
<P>
   For some modern worshippers, the language barrier can present an
obstacle to fully embracing a faith. For others, scriptural
language offers a direct link to the divine and a connection to a
worldwide community of other believers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public prayer addressed to God should always be in the
highest, noblest style and in the most expressive, most
historically continuous language possible,'' says James Patrick,
provost of the College of St. Thomas More in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was speaking specifically about Latin, Patrick's
statement is widely applied. Most of the religions mentioned above
consider their sacred language as one befitting their god(s), if
not the actual language the deities spoke.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Islam, Muslims believe Mohammed received the
revelations from God in Arabic. To Muslims, then, the word of the
Koran IS the word and sound of God, notes Barbara von Schlegell, an
assistant professor of religion at the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``The act of reciting the Koran is really the most important
thing a Muslim can do,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Though Arabic is the holy language of the world's 1.2 billion
Muslims, it is the mother tongue of just a fifth of that
population, von Schlegell notes. Yet the vast majority of Muslims
can at least recite passages from the Koran, and children from the
most devout families memorize the entire Scripture (about the
length of the New Testament), down to the length of time to hold
syllables.
</P>
<P>
   For Abdul Majeed of Euless, Texas, learning Arabic came fairly
easily, as his native languages, Urdu and Punjabi, share the Arabic
script. ``Even in government schools in Pakistan, Arabic is taught
to the extent that people can read the Koran,'' says Majeed, a
retired United Nations administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Hebrew, a sister language to Arabic, was the tongue of Moses and
King David, notes Michael Meyer, a professor of Jewish history at
Hebrew Union College in Cincinnati. And it is the written language
of the Hebrew Bible, or Torah, portions of which date back 3,000
years.
</P>
<P>
   In about 400 B.C., Aramaic, the language of Jesus, replaced
spoken Hebrew, and Hebrew was relegated to literary use until the
late 19th century when Zionism, the movement to establish a Jewish
state, once again embraced it.
</P>
<P>
   The three main Jewish branches all incorporate Hebrew to varying
degrees during religious services (Orthodox Jews use it almost
exclusively in the synagogue). And Jewish children who pass through
the traditional rite of the bar/bat mitzvah usually recite Hebrew
passages from the Torah in that ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The Hebrew renaissance continues today, partly due, Meyer
believes, to the influence of Israel and partly due to a desire on
the behalf of Jews in the Diaspora to recapture tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sense that the language connects you with the
people as a whole and the history of the people,'' says Meyer. ``If
you go into a synagogue anywhere in the world, you will hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the New Testament was originally written in Greek, an
``Old Latin'' translation dates back to the second century, notes
St. Thomas More's Patrick. Catholic rites were conducted
exclusively in Latin until the Second Vatican Council in the '60s,
when Rome gave its member churches the option of worshipping in the
language of their congregants.
</P>
<P>
   Certain prayers are primarily still recited or sung in Latin _
the ``Agnus Dei,'' for instance. But as a result of Vatican II,
Latin has lost some of its clout in the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future of Latin in the Catholic Church is that it will
persist, but it will be, for the average Catholic, a minor
engagement and a minor tradition,'' Patrick says.
</P>
<P>
   The sacred languages of eastern religions have played similar
roles in worship. Sanskrit and Pali, like Latin, were originally
elite languages, used by scholarly priests. The lay person wasn't,
and isn't, expected to be able to read and write them. (Unlike
Latin, however, Sanskrit and Pali are the original languages of
their sacred texts, like Arabic).
</P>
<P>
   ``Sanskrit was considered the language of the gods,'' says
Andrew Fort, a Texas Christian University professor specializing in
Asian religions. The word itself means ``pure or perfect,'' he
explains.
</P>
<P>
   And Pali, literally ``texts,'' is still chanted during some
Theravada Buddhist ceremonies, he notes.
</P>
<P>
   Does it matter that worshippers have only a vague idea of what
is being said?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that there are some messages of religious tradition
that lose something in the translation from the original
language,'' says Richard Turner, an associate professor of religion
at DePaul, ``so that you miss some of the flavor, some of the
intricacies of the revelation.''
</P>
<P>
   But total fluency in a religion's sacred language probably isn't
essential for most of the world's believers. Culling the essence of
a prayer or ritual _ even just hearing it _ can be spiritually
satisfying, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you always knew (during Latin prayers) was that the
priest was talking to God on your behalf,'' Patrick says. ``And it
didn't make so much difference if you didn't understand every word
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kay Read's student, in fact, understanding the Latin liturgy
temporarily distanced her from the religion.
</P>
<P>
   The student had developed her own interpretation of the sounds
she was uttering, and not knowing Latin had allowed her to
personalize her religious experience in a way. ``If you pray in a
language that you don't understand, you can understand it in your
own way,'' Read says.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of (religion) is ritualized, and ritual isn't
necessarily about belief,'' she adds. ``It's about doing, and the
prayer itself is an action and you link with the sacred through
action.''
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 1844EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9521 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-MOTHERS-900(2TAKE     02-07 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MOTHERS-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW VIEW OF MOTHERHOOD: MATERNAL STYLES MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By NATALIE ANGIER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody knows what a good mother is. She is a lot like apple
pie: reassuringly firm on the outside, but soft, sweet, warm and
bland within. A good mother gets pleasure from the comfort and
pleasure of others. A good mother gets pleasure from being sliced,
diced and eaten alive.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while everybody knows what a good mother is, and everybody
wants one, nobody seems to know where to find her _ and with
reason. That good mother, who gives infinitely and unstintingly,
is, in the phrase of the primatologist Sarah Blaffer Hrdy, the
woman that never evolved, nor could have.
</P>
<P>
   Hrdy, of the University of California at Davis, knows a lot
about mothers _ real mothers with their feet on the ground, rather
than earth mothers with their feet on pedestals. She knows about
human mothers across cultures and eras, and she knows about
nonhuman mothers across phyla. She knows about the complexity,
beauty and ferocity of the bond between a mother and her young. She
knows that the bond is not a given, nor is it fixed and clean and
sweet, but instead is a barter, a supple, ever-changing push-me
pull-you negotiation between two individuals who need each other
and are closely related, but who are not clones and so do not
always see eye to eye, or breast to mouth for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Now Hrdy has gathered her insight and research into a book,
``Mother Nature: A History of Mothers, Infants and Natural
Selection,'' published last fall by Pantheon Books. The book, which
took her more than 15 years to complete, is thick, complex,
scholarly and personal. Fastidiously documented and footnoted, yet
nonetheless beautifully and accessibly written, it is the product
of a woman who, before going into science, had considered becoming
a novelist. It is the story of the mother-infant bond told from a
nuanced but distinctly Darwinian perspective, an appraisal of how a
welter of selective forces has shaped maternal behaviors, impulses
and strategies over tens of thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
   Among its many narrative parries, the book challenges a bedrock
assumption of evolutionary biology, the premise that males of most
species, including humans, vary far more in reproductive success
than do their female counterparts. Some males manage to mate like
Lotharios while others are sexual duds, the theory goes, whereas
females are in such demand that they can mate as much as they need
to and thus end up with more or less the same number of offspring.
With this model of female monotony in mind, mothers have been
viewed as cookie-cutter characters, with scant variation in
maternal methods or maternal success from one female to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Calling this bit of theoretical orthodoxy into question, Hrdy
discusses the growing evidence that the variation in female
reproductive success _ in the ability of females to rear offspring
who themselves reproduce _is far greater than had been suspected.
Motherhood matters, she says, and maternal styles and decisions
matter, and why did it take people so long to see that simple,
profound truth?
</P>
<P>
   Hrdy talks about the extraordinary demands of human mothering.
Most primate mothers can rear their infants on their own, but human
mothers cannot. They need help, and throughout history and
prehistory they have gotten it however and from whomever they can _
from mothers, grandmothers, brothers, aunts, cousins; from one man,
or more than one man.
</P>
<P>
   New research, Hrdy says, has revealed the prevalence of a
practice called partible paternity _ the idea that a baby is a
patchwork quilt of the various men a woman sleeps with during
pregnancy. Found among the traditional peoples of lowland Amazonia,
eastern and southern Africa, New Guinea and elsewhere, partible
paternity and customs like it turn out to be of advantage to women
and their offspring. If a woman's primary husband dies or deserts
her, the other second-tier mates are expected to help protect and
provide for her children. As one young Zambian woman is quoted as
saying: ``Why put all your eggs in one basket?''
</P>
<P>
   Hrdy does not flinch from the brutal side of human motherhood.
As a communal breeder beholden to the assistance of others in
rearing her young, a woman must be a true political animal. She
must be calculating, sometimes ruthlessly so. Hrdy delves into the
subject of infanticide, revealing the practice to be a sorry staple
of humanity's efforts to plan and manage their families.
</P>
<P>
   If a baby is born feeble, or handicapped, or the wrong sex, or
too soon after the last child, the parents may choose to kill,
abandon or neglect it, rather than struggle to rear it against all
odds and thus put their other children's futures at risk. Sometimes
they dropped the child in the river. At other times, they committed
infanticide passively, by depositing the unwanted progeny at a
Dickensian-like orphanage, for example, or shipping it off to a
distant and overburdened wet nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Many cultures postpone until several days or weeks after an
infant's birth official rituals like baptism, circumcision and
naming ceremonies, Hrdy points out, perhaps in recognition that not
every newborn is destined to be reared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I consider this material to be part of what I do
for a living,'' said Dr. Lee Cronk, an evolutionary anthropologist
at Rutgers, ``Sarah presented a huge amount of information on the
history of child abandonment practices with which I wasn't
familiar. It's a terrific book.''
</P>
<P>
   A fifth-generation Texan who retains a trace of twang, Hrdy
(pronounced HUR- dee) is 53, almost six feet tall and strappingly
handsome, yet with limbs and neck just elongated enough to give her
an almost balletic air. She is the daughter of considerable wealth
and prominence _ Dallas banking on the maternal side, Texaco oil on
the patriline _ but she fled from her background as quickly as
possible. ``I wanted out of there,'' she said. ``When I went off to
college at 16, it was wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Married to Daniel Hrdy, a infectious disease doctor and farmer
(to whom she dedicates her latest book as ``the wisest choice this
female ever made''), she has three children: Katrinka, a varsity
rower who graduates from Harvard in the spring; another daughter,
Sasha, who will enter Harvard in the fall; and a 13-year-old son,
Niko, named after the great naturalist Niko Tinbergen and the only
one, Hrdy said, ``who shows signs of becoming a naturalist.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
