<SLUG> BC-FRAZZLED-PARENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESENTING MOM'S NEW DEAL 2000
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By CATHERINE NEWTON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A little bit of Monica in his life,
</P>
<P>
   a little bit of Beta Al by his side,
</P>
<P>
   a little bit of Hillary he did need,
</P>
<P>
   a little impeachment, he did see.''
</P>
<P>
   When a beleaguered Bill Clinton saw an instant rise in his
approval rating following last year's State of the Union address, I
had an idea. I called together my two small constituents _ Reps.
Jack and Hadley _ for our first State of the Family speech. I
figured my own approval rating could use a boost, too.
</P>
<P>
   I delivered an inspirational speech on health care, clutter
reform and sibling relations. While I failed to have either Sammy
Sosa or Rosa Parks in the audience, my children were nevertheless
clearly moved by my efforts, interrupting my impassioned prose just
twice to ask for milk.
</P>
<P>
   Based on this record of resounding success, I decided to follow
with a 2000 State of the Family address. Again, Clinton was my
inspiration. His speech this year marked a return to an activist
agenda, an ``era of big government'' that just four years ago he
said was over.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it seems like a time for some ``big parenting,'' as well.
</P>
<P>
   I downloaded his speech, and began cribbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Master Jack, Ms. Hadley, honored pets. We are fortunate to be
alive at this moment in history. Never before has our family
enjoyed, at once, so much prosperity and social progress with so
few external threats.''
</P>
<P>
   I paused. Maybe Clinton could get away with a sweeping statement
like that. But I'd have to break it down:
</P>
<P>
   Prosperity &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, I asked that we meet our responsibility to the
tax man by maintaining our fiscal discipline. Thanks largely to the
recent decline in Pokemon popularity, the complete removal of all
Beanie Babies from the market, and our public school's new
mandatory uniform policy, we are finally beginning to follow that
path.
</P>
<P>
   To enhance those positive financial efforts, I am asking you to
embrace my new Friday-night pizza policy. After much analysis, I
have discovered that adding both cheese sticks and bread sticks to
the weekly order to accommodate picky palates has meant a 34.3
percent increase in our bills, and also a 50 percent increase in
the leftovers that sit in the fridge for a week and never get
eaten. From this moment on, only one sort of ``stick'' will be
approved on a weekly basis.
</P>
<P>
   I also ask you to welcome our new ``Birthdays are for Giving''
campaign. In the past, as you know, trips to Noodle Kidoodle to buy
presents for other children's parties have resulted in small
purchases for each of you, too. Last year, a total of $200 was
spent on ``why can't I have something, too'' impulse buys. This
year, the money that would go toward those inane purchases will
instead go into something known as a ``savings account'' that will
one day help to ensure the American Dream for you both. If we stay
on this path, we can make our family debt-free for the first time
since Andrew Jackson was president in 1835. Please, hold your
applause.''
</P>
<P>
   Social progress &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the fact that Hadley did not get the
just-five-easy-payments phonics program advertised on Nickelodeon
that she insisted she needed to learn to read, she has indeed made
progress on that front within the traditional framework of her
overcrowded kindergarten class. I applaud her for recognition of
all initial consonants. Jack, too, is to be commended for his
educational efforts this year. Thanks to the Harry Potter books, he
completed his personal commitment toward the school's Million
Minutes of Reading program without any parental angst. In addition,
his memorization of the complete ``Hamlet'' soliloquy, which
neither parent was able to learn, was an unequivocal highlight of
the year. What does all that mean? That you children are capable of
success, when it is something that interests you. To this end, I
insist that we begin a ``Your Homework is YOUR Homework''
initiative. While some of you may see this as a last-minute effort
on my part to remove myself from this month's overwhelming
fourth-grade Texas history project, I assure you that my goals are
for the greater good. So draw the Alamo on your own and make your
own collage this time. You will be a better person, and our family
will be stronger. That's the spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   External threats &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``To realize the full possibilities of this family, we must
reach beyond our own borders. We have to be at the center of every
vital global network, as a good neighbor. To this end, and to
ensure that the lease on our duplex is not revoked by our landlords
who live next door, I ask you to support my ``Speak Quietly and
Don't Carry a Hula Hoop'' policy. Any child found screaming or
throwing hula hoops or, for that matter, basketballs against the
living room wall on Saturday mornings, shall be required to spend
the rest of the morning in his or her room, contemplating world
peace.
</P>
<P>
   While this passive good neighbor policy shall dictate our
behavior at home, in the face of demonstrated aggression at school
on the behalf of one adversary known as ``the school bully,'' I
shall endorse a new tattle-tale policy. I recognize that
tattle-taling is what prompted the bully to start his ``Make Jack
Eat Dirt'' afterschool program in the first place (Why did you have
to tell the principal about the kid's contraband Pokemon cards,
anyway, Jack?). Nevertheless, should the bully act again, I insist
that you tell me about this when it happens instead of waiting
three months and mentioning it in casual conversation. With this
new policy, I will be able to take immediate parental action.
</P>
<P>
   With a commitment to these goals, I feel sure we can make this
family more liberal _ I mean, livable.
</P>
<P>
   This is big business. This is a big issue. This is big
parenting.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, and now and only now, you may have your milk.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
