<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-SCENE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHappaqua's abuzz, or is it New Castle?
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. _ The high-powered flash of light emanating from
one of the official vehicles was mercifully brief, but the message
was abundantly clear: Move along.
</P>
<P>
   On a Saturday night in the suburbs seemingly designed for
dropping in on neighbors, a wooden sawhorse, several police cars
and a couple of imposing-looking unmarked vans guarded Old House
Lane.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the car slowing down for a look might have been a
tourist, or a distinguished, longtime resident of this upscale
community located some 35 minutes from Manhattan. No matter. In the
suddenly topsy-turvy world of Chappaqua, the newest residents are
by far the most important, and things are very, very different from
just a few short months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live two roads over from where he lives,'' said Jonas
Curchack, 14. ``And just getting to school when he's here is really
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'' is President Bill Clinton, who comes to this Westchester
County town complete with Secret Service agents, traveling staff
and press, and, of course, his wife. First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton formally announced her candidacy for the U.S. Senate from
New York on Sunday, a little over a month after she had begun
moving boxes and furniture into the newly-purchased,
residency-establishing, house at 15 Old House Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton left Chappaqua behind Monday as she launched her first
offical campaign swing in upstate New York, telling supporters in
Buffalo, ``We have a lot of work to do, but it will be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Some residents of her new hometown may disagree about the fun
part.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the president joined her for their first night
together there, news that the First Couple had purchased the $1.7
million Georgian-style home created such a media and tourist
frenzy, it sometimes threatend to paralyze the town of 17,000
residents and quaint four-way stop sign intersections.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you needed was three big press vans for it to get very
disruptive to people's lives,'' said Linda Peterson, town clerk and
tax receiver for the Town of New Castle. (Like virtually everything
involving the Clintons, even the matter of their new town's name is
complicated. New Castle is the government seat of a 24-square mile
area that also includes the ``hamlets'' of Chappaqua and Millwood.)
</P>
<P>
   In the period since what more than one resident terms the
``invasion'' really began, Chappaqua _ actually, New Castle _ has
reacted in a way that the longtime government servant Clintons
should understand: By enacting legislation. The town has passed one
law prohibiting non-residents of Old House Lane from parking there,
as well as an ordinance requiring police department permission to
conduct demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can demonstrate, but they will have to get a parade
permit,'' said Peterson, adding that the ordinance has already
affected one large gathering completely unrelated to politics or
world affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Historical Society has a holiday lighting every year, but
because they had too many people coming, they had to get a permit
from the police,'' Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a public hearing is set for Feb. 22 on yet another
proposed law to turn Old House Lane into a tow-away zone. And this
past Friday _ two days before Mrs. Clinton's splashy candidacy
announcement in nearby Purchase _ U.S. Rep. Sue Kelly, a Republican
whose district includes Chappaqua, introduced federal legislation
that would provide the area's police forces with up to $1 million
to deal with costs associated with the Clintons' move.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
