<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE'VE MADE OUR BED, AND WE'RE ABOUT TO FLY IN IT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was a lousy American and skipped the Super Bowl this year _
the prospect of strolling my empty stomach down empty aisles at the
grocery store was simply too tempting to pass up _ so I missed the
much-talked-about commercial featuring Christopher Reeve.
</P>
<P>
   The ad, set in the future, depicted the actor walking onto a
stage to present awards for research on spinal cord injuries. Some
viewers said the spot offered false hope. Others complained that
the computer-generated image was confusing; they initially thought
the actor, who was paralyzed in a horse-riding accident in 1995,
had somehow been healed.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at Nuveen Investments, the ad's sponsor, sounded a bit
flummoxed by the criticism. Nuveen spokesman Chris Allen said the
spot, which urged people to ``invest well,'' was meant ``to inspire
a dialogue on money, to have a new dialogue and get away from
buying bigger boats and bigger cars and think about the impact that
money can have on the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, well, well. Is it too late to give Allen the game ball? I
think it's high time we started a dialogue on money.
</P>
<P>
   My mother taught me when I was a little boy that it's impolite
to point at people, and I suppose there's a corollary somewhere
that says it's impolite to point at people spending their own
money. Lately, though, my finger's been itching.
</P>
<P>
   As we all know by now, we live in an era of unprecedented
economic growth _ 161 months and counting. It's hard not to cheer
that, particularly on the way to the bank. But we also live in an
era of wretched excess, a time when wealth and greed are
back-slapping common sense and decency a little too hard.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Trump and Steve Forbes are running for president. The TV
event that unites us these days, aside from a football game with
$2.2 million-per-30-second ads, is a game show with a prize of $1
million, hosted by a guy whose regular TV partner used to make
headlines as a sweat-shop entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   We're striking it rich on Internet companies that produce little
and lose wads of cash, yet somehow are deemed valuable. Meanwhile,
charities are scraping for donations at Christmas, and bankruptcy
and debt are hitting record levels.
</P>
<P>
   We're living in a sequel to the Gilded Age, and the gild is
being glopped on several coats at a time. Two recent examples of
gloppery pop to mind.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was a report by the St. Petersburg Times on a house
that basketball star Matt Geiger is building in Pinellas County.
Fla. It's 26,000 square feet, not counting a 4,158-square-foot
guest house. It will be the biggest abode in the county's history,
bigger even than Hulk Hogan's 16,000-square-foot home.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of Geiger's house is $5 million, which sounds rather
economical, considering what it will include _ among other things,
a 270,000-gallon swimming pool with a water slide, three diving
boards and a spa; a fireplace big enough to stand in; an outdoor
kitchen designed by Outback Steakhouse; and at least 12 bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   I know. It's none of my business. Last year, Geiger signed a
six-year contract worth $52 million with the Philadelphia 76ers,
and it's his money to spend as he pleases. For all I know, he's a
wonderful guy who gives to charity, signs autographs for kids, and
helps old ladies cross the street.
</P>
<P>
   But I can't help but wince at the image of an
$8.7-million-a-year, 7-foot-1 guy in basketball shorts building a
fireplace in Florida that's big enough for him to stand in. Could
it be our society's priorities are a little more whacked than
usual?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe ``a little'' is overly generous, judging from another
story I read last week. This one was about Virgin Atlantic's plans
to offer beds to passengers on trans-Atlantic flights. The
round-trip price: $9,000 per person, $18,000 per couple.
</P>
<P>
   Yup, $18,000. Enough to buy a car, send a kid to a state college
for at least a year, or _ I'm guessing _ buy quite a few cords of
firewood for a fireplace you can stand in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to put the romance back into flying,'' explained
Richard Branson, the head of the airline. (Great. Then maybe we can
put the leg room back in coach? Or safety back in the air?)
</P>
<P>
   A dialogue on money, indeed. Perhaps I'm harboring false hopes,
but I think that would be just super.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla.,
part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group. Contact him at
daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
