<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-LOBBY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS SAY `FLO' ADS PROVIDE COVER FOR DRUG COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CARL HULSE   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is a bit shocking to hear someone at an AARP
meeting wish harm upon a nice older lady.
</P>
<P>
   But at the just-concluded national legislative board meeting of
the senior group, council member Ben Cook suggested he and others
would not be unhappy if Flo, star of a television ad campaign on
Medicare drug coverage, ended one of the spots by ``falling into an
open manhole.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She is an individual that seniors will not buy,'' said the
AARP leader from Texas about the Golden Girl-style character who
last year warned ``big government'' to stay out of her medicine
cabinet but now wants lawmakers to ``join hands'' for a bipartisan
solution on Medicare prescription insurance.
</P>
<P>
   AARP and others in Washington are also not buying the idea that
Citizens for Better Medicare, the group financing the Flo ads, is
anything more than a way for drug companies and corporate America
to influence the evolving debate over Medicare prescription drug
coverage from behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   The name may be Citizens for Better Medicare, but among its
chief members are the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of
America, the National Association of Manufacturers and the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a phony coalition, there is no question about it,'' said
Martin Corry, chief lobbyist for AARP. ``Nobody has any illusions
about who is behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   The group illustrates an increasingly popular approach to
advocacy advertising. Special interests know their message will
pack more punch if it is seen as coming from an independent,
grass-roots source. The result is groups like Citizens for Better
Medicare. Another recent example is Americans for Responsible
Alcohol Access, a group funded by liquor wholesalers fighting
Internet wine sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very hard sometimes to determine who the people are and
who is funding them,'' said Peter Eisner, an official of the Center
for Public Integrity, a watchdog group that tracks advocacy
campaigns. He said audiences can be easily misled about the agendas
of such groups.
</P>
<P>
   Corry said some people even assume AARP is part of Citizens for
Better Medicare though it differs with the group on how to achieve
a drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the coalition dispute that there is anything
misleading about the multimillion-dollar ad campaign. They said
more than 100,000 people have joined Citizens for Better Medicare
since the advertising effort was first launched last year on
television and in print.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't purport to represent the number of seniors that AARP
does but we do represent a lot of seniors,'' said Tim Ryan,
executive director of the coalition. ``Tens of thousands have
signed up in the last couple of weeks after having seen our ads and
our materials.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Holmer, president of the pharmaceutical trade group,
questioned why anyone would quibble with the new spots, which
promote congressional consensus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think the bipartisan tone of the ads, the interest in
being able to have a solution to this issue, is what we all need to
be able to accomplish,'' he told the AARP audience after Cook's
barb about Flo's hoped-for demise.
</P>
<P>
   But the group wasn't always open to compromise. Last year, when
President Clinton first launched his drug coverage plan, Citizens
for Better Medicare went on the attack with its first Flo ads.
</P>
<P>
   They raised the specter of retirees losing their private drug
coverage and government bureaucrats making decisions about
prescriptions. The industry said it was motivated to start the
campaign by fears that government price controls could cut into
profits needed for research into drug advancements.
</P>
<P>
   Facing criticism for rising drug prices, the industry last month
changed its tone, signaling in public statements and the latest
round of Flo ads that it is willing to work with Washington to
shape drug coverage. It supports a mainly GOP-backed approach that
would extend full drug benefits only to poorer Medicare
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The group won't disclose how much it is spending on the ad
campaign, but it is reported to be as much as $30 million, with ads
running on national cable outlets such as CNN and regional stations
in California, Florida, Texas, Colorado and elsewhere around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is national in scope,'' said Ryan, who until the
coalition was formed was director of advertising at the
pharmaceutical trade group. He attributed AARP's criticism to its
unhappiness at having a competing voice in the drug debate.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the corporate interests, the coalition includes some
conservative senior advocacy groups as well as a few patient and
health care organizations such as the Alliance for Aging Research,
a respected member of Washington's senior advocacy network.
Executive director Dan Perry said the alliance's aim is to make
sure drug research continues apace.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site promoted in the Flo ads, www.bettermedicare.org,
lists the members of the coalition but does not divulge their
respective financial contributions. Holmer said drug companies are
the chief source of money.
</P>
<P>
   As for Flo, he said she draws a positive reaction from seniors
despite the sentiments expressed at the AARP session.
</P>
<P>
   Though the woman playing Flo is a paid professional, Ryan said
she suffers from a hip condition that required her to draw on the
private drug benefits of her husband's retiree health plan, giving
her an appreciation for the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is an actress,'' he said, ``but her story is real.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
