<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-BASS-ANGLERS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG, EDUCATED ANGLERS ARE HOOKED ON BASSMASTERS TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., N.C., Ala.)  (jw) 
 By DEL MILLIGAN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ Tim Horton has made a habit of outsmarting bass
when it counts and of finishing high in Bass Anglers Sportsman
Society tournaments. His competitors say he will stay there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's good looking, he's intelligent, he's well-spoken. I think
he's going to be one of the superstars of fishing,'' said Shaw
Grigsby of Gainesville, Fla., one of today's superstar bass pros at
age 43.
</P>
<P>
   Horton, a 27-year-old from Spruce Pine, Ala., is one of the new
breed in pro bass fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Horton and North Carolinian Dustin Wilks, 22, are pro bassing's
young guns _ in their 20s, clean-cut, college-educated and driven
to be the best at the sport of their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Increases in prize purses over the last five years provide much
to dream about.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma cattle rancher Darrel Robertson, 49, pocketed
consecutive winner's checks of $250,000 and $600,000 last year for
winning the Wal-Mart FLW Tour championship and then the Ranger
Millennium Tournament in Winter Haven, Fla. Five years ago,
$100,000 was the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   With the inflated prize money and increased sponsor interest,
pro anglers agree that leaders like Grigsby can take home at least
$250,000 per year. And that may be a conservative estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Grigsby won $100,000 in one tournament on Jan. 15 at the Bass
Anglers Sportsman Society's Top 150 circuit at Lake Toho in
Kissimmee. He is on two television shows, and he rakes in
endorsements for everything from baits to bass rigs.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate sponsors are eager to get behind the future of the
sport, making pros like Horton and Wilks hot properties who might
build a name as Grigsby and a select few others have done.
</P>
<P>
   There are a half dozen others among this new breed including
Chad Brauer, 27, who has won on the BASS trail; Michael Iaconelli,
27, a front-runner who graduated summa cum laude from Rowan
University with a degree in advertising and public relations; and
Chris Elliott, a friend of Wilks from North Carolina State
University, who qualified for the Classic at age 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking for young pros with marketing degrees,'' said
pro bass angler Art Ferguson, 35, who guides on Lake Okeechobee in
the offseason. ``I wish I'd got my degree.''
</P>
<P>
   The importance of a college diploma is emphasized by this new
breed. They may never have to rely on a sheepskin, but sponsors
want the guys who have one.
</P>
<P>
   Denny Brauer, the all-time leading money-winner on the BASS
trail, insisted that his son, Chad, go to college even though he
wanted to follow in dad's footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   ``He insisted on trying it, and I told him if he went ahead and
got his college education, I'd be his No. 1 sponsor and back him
until he got his feet on the ground,'' Brauer, 50, said.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for the younger Brauer to win a tournament,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a great future in front of him, as a lot of these
young anglers do,'' Denny Brauer said. ``The sport is growing so
fast it's just neat to see these kids having success.''
</P>
<P>
   Middle-aged men who worked long hours and sacrificed family life
to fish weekends and build their dream on the professional bass
trail are seeing these young guns rise to the pinnacle of the sport
faster than they can reel in a 10-inch bass.
</P>
<P>
   Horton was No. 1 on the elite BASS Top 150 trail going into the
tournament on the Kissimmee Chain Jan. 12-15, and placed 22nd. He
went to Okeechobee for another BASS event the next weekend and tied
for 12th.
</P>
<P>
   Wilks won the points championship on the Eastern Division trail
to qualify for the Bassmasters Classic as a rookie last year _ at
age 21.
</P>
<P>
   Horton and Wilks were certain this was what they wanted to do
before they even realized the value of money.
</P>
<P>
   Horton knew he wanted to be a bass pro when he was in the 10th
grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``After my second year of college, I started competing locally
and had some success,'' Horton said. ``And it grew to a statewide
deal and it kind of just kept going.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilks first had the dream when he was 12, and fished his first
tournament at 13. He gave up baseball in high school _ because he
didn't want to hurt his casting arm.
</P>
<P>
   Wilks even tailored his college education around a career in
bass fishing with a major in fisheries and wildlife science from
N.C. State.
</P>
<P>
   Horton said his goal at tournaments is to fish as much territory
as possible in the shortest amount of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to cover a lot of water and find big groups of fish,
instead of learning a pattern and plucking out one or two here and
there,'' Horton said.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have a favorite style. He doesn't concentrate on
sight fishing, like Grigsby, or flippin' like Denny Brauer, or
cranking, like David Fritts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of your younger fishermen learn to be
versatile,'' Horton said. ``I think a lot of the older generation
fishermen are specialists.''
</P>
<P>
   To search as much water as he can, Horton usually employs a
crankbait for starters. Bomber's Fat Free Shad is a favorite. He
prefers ``anything chartreuse'' and insists on an orange belly.
``If it doesn't have it on there, I always paint it on there,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Del Milligan writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
