<HEADER>
A9544 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a x BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     02-07 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPS FOR `FAST FOOD MANNERS MONTH' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Wednesday, Feb. 9)  
(nk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not a moment too soon, but quite possibly several decades too
late, February has been declared ``Fast Food Manners Month.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not often that you see the words ``fast food'' and
``manners'' used in the same sentence, but the etiquette experts at
At Ease Inc., in Cincinnati, seem to be of the opinion that the two
concepts are not mutually exclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us seem to view the fast-food experience in much the
same way we view our careers, namely as something we want to be
done with as quickly and painlessly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   This is the notion from which much bad fast-food etiquette
springs, according to the folks at At Ease.
</P>
<P>
   A common fast-food faux pas (literally: McRib Sandwich), is
ordering food with your eyes locked on the menu behind the cashier.
This is discourteous to the cashiers, even if they happen to be
staring out the window at the time or examining something stuck to
the sole of their shoes.
</P>
<P>
   I agree that making eye-contact with your personal fast-food
server is an important and courteous thing to do during the four or
five seconds that you are interacting, but it is not as easy as it
sounds. For one thing, the huge, illuminated menu is hard to
ignore, featuring as it does plump, colorful food items that bear
no resemblance whatsoever to the flat, gray wads of food-like
substance that your personal fast-food server will plop on your
tray.
</P>
<P>
   One might argue that it is best for all involved in this fraud
to avert our eyes out of sheer embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   I have less of a problem with the second etiquette suggestion,
which is that diners should avoid shoving more than two French
fries into their mouth at the same time or taking such big bites of
their hamburger that their cheeks resemble those of Marlon Brando's
in ``The Godfather.'' This unappetizing spectacle could be avoided
if American fast-food restaurants would adopt the French custom of
the ``baguette,'' a cloth feeding sack that covers the entire face
and clips behind the ears.
</P>
<P>
   These suggestions are fine, as far as they go, but I think the
problem of bad manners at fast-food restaurants goes beyond chewing
ice and inhaling french fries, even when done at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, I think the managers of drive-through restaurants
should invest a dollar and buy some speakers that do not make the
person talking sound like he is choking on a chicken bone. We have
digital televisions, cell phones that can hook up the Internet and
computers that can type what we dictate. Is it so difficult to
design an outdoor loudspeaker that doesn't make every spoken work
sound like it's coming from someone in need of the Heimlich
Maneuver?
</P>
<P>
   Also, while we're on the subject of drive-through sound systems,
would it be possible to turn the volume down a little bit? We can't
understand what you're saying anyway; all you're doing is scaring
us to death. Often this causes us to jump so high in our seats that
we bang our head on the roof, which is not a good way to start the
day, especially if we're holding a cup of hot coffee. Also, if
there were a real emergency, there would be no way for us to know
because the loud, garbled sound of ``Evacuate the area immediately!
The deep-fryer's about to explode!'' sounds very much like ``Good
morning! Would you like to try our Value Meal?''
</P>
<P>
   If the managers of America's many fine fast-food restaurants
agree to this modest and long-overdue investment in speaker
quality, I agree to look directly into the eyes of the person
taking my order, no matter how many tongue-studs or nose-rings he
may be sporting.
</P>
<P>
   I refuse to look at the other customers, though, especially
while they're eating. They're way too disgusting.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
