<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S DOMESTIC GOALS BOUNCE BACK IN NEW PROPOSALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BUDGET-CLINTON) 
(js) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The budget unveiled Monday by President Clinton
shows the extraordinary persistence of his domestic policy: In
health care and other social programs, he is pursuing many of the
same goals as in 1993, though often by different means.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is still trying to expand health coverage, still trying
to expand eligibility for food stamps and other nutrition programs,
still trying to increase the Earned-Income Tax Credit, one of the
nation's biggest anti-poverty programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't call him the comeback kid for nothing,'' said
Edward M. Cooney, a special assistant to the secretary of
agriculture, noting how Clinton had pressed on despite setbacks and
detours.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Clinton proposed a big expansion of the food stamp
program under the Agriculture Department, and Congress approved it.
The 1996 welfare law cut food stamp spending, especially benefits
for legal immigrants. Clinton won restoration of some of the cuts
for legal immigrants in 1998, and on Monday he asked Congress to
restore the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, on health policy.
</P>
<P>
   No longer does Clinton try to guarantee health insurance for all
by redesigning the health care system from top to bottom. Rather,
he is proposing more modest steps to insure a dozen different
groups including workers between jobs, people age 55 to 64,
uninsured parents of children eligible for Medicaid, legal
immigrants and low-income women with breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In his new budget request, Clinton proposed to expand plans that
failed in recent years, and he offered to spend more money on those
proposals in the hope that Congress would now accept them.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, for the third year in a row, Clinton proposed to let
people age 55 to 64 buy Medicare coverage. Stung by criticism that
the premiums would be too high, he is now proposing tax credits to
offset 25 percent of the cost.
</P>
<P>
   So too with his prescription drug proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Congress last year balked at Clinton's proposal to have Medicare
cover prescription drugs _ half the annual drug expenses, up to a
maximum federal payment of $2,500 a year. Monday Clinton enlarged
his original proposal, adding coverage for the costs of people with
Medicare coverage who have extraordinarily high prescription drug
expenses. He gave no details of how he would design or finance
coverage for such ``catastrophic'' expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The first bill Clinton signed in 1993 was the Family and Medical
Leave Act. Under that law, people who work for a company with 50 or
more employees are generally entitled to 12 weeks of unpaid leave
to care for newborn children or sick relatives or to tend to
medical problems of their own. But many have a problem: They cannot
afford to take unpaid leave. So Monday Clinton proposed a modest
new initiative to provide financial assistance to those who need
it.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Clinton last year proposed a $1,000 tax credit for
people providing long-term care to relatives with chronic
illnesses. The proposal was well received in Congress, but never
became law. Monday Clinton proposed to triple the amount of the
credit, in the hope of winning more support.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise on the Earned-Income Tax Credit, a refundable credit
available to poor working families. In 1993, Clinton proposed an
expansion of the credit costing $28 billion over five years;
Congress approved $20 billion, providing help to 15 million
low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Clinton proposed a further expansion of the
Earned-Income Tax Credit, providing tax relief to 6.8 million
families at a cost of $2 billion a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
