<HEADER>
A9569 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-SC-VOICES-ART-NYT     02-07 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-VOICES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORT FOR BUSH IN S.C. BROAD BUT SHALLOW, GIVING MCCAIN AN
OPENING
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BUSH-DEL) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ As he struggled to fix a tractor by the side of
the road, Donald Hall underscored why South Carolina is sometimes
called ``Bush country,'' but also why Gov. George W. Bush may be
vulnerable here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to choose one right now,'' said Hall, a telephone
repairman, ``then I reckon it'd be Bush, because he's the only one
I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet when he was pressed on why he favored Bush, Hall simply
paused, shrugged and said, ``I haven't thought about it much.''
Finally he added, ``I like Bush because I like his dad.'' But he
also said that he liked what little he knew about Bush's rival,
Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain's got a military background, and I like that about
him,'' he said. ``He ain't had a gravy train all his life, that's
for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Driving the back roads of South Carolina and talking to ordinary
voters, there were many people like Hall who said they were leaning
to Bush _ but whose support seemed just an inch deep. The weakness
of Bush's base, however broad it may be, could leave a major
opportunity for McCain here in the next key battleground in the
presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   In several days of interviews on a meandering trip across South
Carolina, from the gorgeous beaches of Hilton Head in the southeast
to the hills around Greenville in the northwest, backers of Bush
were often tentative and unexcited. In contrast, supporters of
McCain tended to be more passionate. Often, they loved their man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a TV documentary, and it said McCain was a prisoner of
war in Vietnam, and he could have gotten out because his father was
an admiral,'' said Barbara Culbertson, a grandmother working
part-time at Greenville Technical College. ``That speaks volumes to
me. I'd like to go out and campaign for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next time I talk to my mom, I'll ask her about the
election,'' Mrs. Culbertson said. ``I'll encourage her to vote for
McCain. You bet!''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Young, a co-worker in the next room, came out at the mention
of McCain and was even more passionate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't clean up our government, then I think it'll
destroy our nation,'' Young said, praising McCain's proposal to
change the campaign finance system. ``When Bush started, he had $54
million, and I know people didn't give him that money for no reason
at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The candidates other than McCain, they always dodge the
questions. Only McCain will answer straight,''
</P>
<P>
   Young said he had sent a $25 contribution to McCain's campaign a
few days ago. Then he and Mrs. Culbertson began to discuss who they
could call to volunteer to campaign for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that many people in South Carolina had not thought
much about the election and had not made up their minds, even among
those who insisted that they always vote and would vote again in
the Feb. 19 primary. Many, it seemed, were inclined toward Bush _
South Carolina generally supported his father, former President
George Bush _ but McCain's sweeping victory in New Hampshire had
made people begin to think of him as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``His name's going around the room more often now,'' said Bill
Greene, a Honda dealer in Hilton Head. ``His win in New Hampshire
opened up a lot of people's eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene said he would probably vote for McCain, and he cited many
of the same reasons as other McCain supporters. Rather than
McCain's stance on the issues, what appears to attract voters is an
aura of strength, character and leadership _ and above all his
past. One of the first things to come up in conversation after
conversation is McCain's experience as a prisoner of war in
Vietnam, resisting his captors despite torture and refusing to
return to America before others who had been captured earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've been through what he's been through,'' Greene
paused as he reached for words, ``well, that showed his
fortitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene also praised McCain for speaking honestly, instead of
telling people what they want to hear. Greene and others often came
close to hailing McCain for being ornery and not doing what voters
want.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is letting public opinion sway him, but McCain's not like
that,'' Greene said. ``He's his own man. And you want somebody
who's going to do what he says, who, when he says something, is
totally honest with the people.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has less backing from the South Carolina political
establishment than Bush, and he has less money and fewer resources.
This may make it difficult for him to exploit the softness in
Bush's support, and he does not have the time to repeat the
retail-style politicking that worked so well for him in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's reputation as an underfunded maverick seems to be
precisely part of his appeal for many Republicans, and few appeared
troubled by his lack of support among statewide party officials.
Indeed, some said that they had been turned off by Bush's huge war
chest and by the way his campaign seemed heavily scripted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got Bush surrounded by too many advisers,'' complained
E. Bryan McCollum, an insurance broker in Walterboro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally, I was all Bush, but now I'm thinking of McCain,''
McCollum added. ``If the election was today, I'd probably go with
Bush, but I'm starting to look at McCain and I like what I see.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw that he was a Vietnam veteran and what he went
through, I had respect for him,'' McCollum said. ``He went through
hell, and still came through with his senses. People say he has a
temper, but you know what? I think we need a guy with a temper in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Several supporters of Bush said that they liked his emphasis on
education and respected what he had accomplished in Texas. But some
voters seemed happy to go along with Bush because everybody else
was _ or so they thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my neighborhood, lots of folks support Bush,'' said Ed
Souls, a computer repairman in Walterboro. ``But I don't know
anybody who supports McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the risks for Bush is that in the next couple of weeks,
as McCain campaigns in South Carolina and gets more attention, he
will win over people like Mike Young, a truck repairman who was
fairly typical of those interviewed. Dressed in green coveralls,
Young stopped in Wolfton to pick up a hot dog for lunch, and he was
taken aback when he was asked about the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been following it a bit,'' he said. ``If it were
today, I'd go with Bush. He's the only one I know anything about.
But I haven't made up my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   What about McCain?
</P>
<P>
   Young shrugged and said, ``I don't know anything about McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   At a construction site near Greenville, dusk was settling over
the hills and a group of tired workers leaned against a truck and
talked about the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Whitt, a big 54-year-old with twinkling eyes, said he
would probably vote for Bush. ``If he's like his daddy, he'll be
better than what we've got now.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A co-worker, William Lee, 23, said he, too, was supporting Bush,
but he became puzzled by the talk about Bush's father. Further
conversation had his eyebrows knitted almost in knots, and then
finally he had an epiphany. ``Oh!'' he said. ``You mean it's George
Bush's son who is running this time? It's not President Bush again?
Is that right?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 1918EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
