<HEADER>
A9571 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      02-07 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; PREVENTION: Cutting the Risk of AIDS in Infants &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In a study of pregnant monkeys and their offspring, researchers
have given the offspring temporary immunity to a form of the AIDS
virus, using a procedure that could offer a more effective way of
blocking HIV transmission during delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Most children who become infected with HIV do not contract it
from the blood of their mothers, but from contact with mucous
membranes before and during delivery. While the drug AZT has been
shown to reduce the odds of such transmission, it is ineffective in
8 percent of cases.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute in Boston
turned to a form of vaccination called passive immunization, in
which already formed antibodies are injected instead of harmless
forms of the virus that teach the body to make its own antibodies.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, scientists have isolated and reproduced
antibodies from a tiny group of people who for some reason seem to
have a natural immunity to HIV. In experiments reported in the
February issue of Nature Medicine, Dr. Ruth Ruprecht and colleagues
at Dana-Farber gave four pregnant macaques a combination of three
of these human antibodies.
</P>
<P>
   After delivery, tests showed that the antibodies had made their
way into the fetal bloodstream. The newborns were given a second
dose, then were exposed to a hybrid form of HIV. Eight days later,
they received an antibodies booster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never found the virus in the four babies over six months of
testing,'' Ruprecht said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAUSE &AMP; EFFECT: A Warm Wind and a Bad Headache &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Cold winds cause headaches everywhere. Out in western Canada,
there's a warm winter wind called the Chinook that many blame for
migraines.
</P>
<P>
   A neurologist at the University of Calgary decided it could
present an opportunity to test a new method of figuring out what
mechanisms set off migraines in particular people. A growing body
of literature has identified a number of factors that create a
predisposition for migraines, but what actually sets them off has
been left more to patients' guesses.
</P>
<P>
   Patients at the university's Headache Research Clinic are often
asked to keep written records of their pains, so Dr. W.J. Becker,
the neurologist, compared 75 of these diaries with weather reports,
looking for correlations between a Chinook and severe headaches.
</P>
<P>
   In an article in January in the journal Neurology, he reported
first that the typical patient was a poor judge of trigger
mechanisms. Seventy-nine percent said they thought that Chinooks
caused migraines. But in only 20 percent of the cases did he find
evidence that the two actually coincided.
</P>
<P>
   In that group, the link proved not to be simple. And, they fell
into two distinct camps: those whose headaches began just before a
Chinook arrived and those whose pains rose and fell with the winds.
</P>
<P>
   In an accompanying editorial, Dr. Richard B. Lipton of the
Albert Einstein College of Medicine noted that the diary approach
could offer a more reliable way to help patients identify their
particular headache causes and in turn help them determine when to
take medicine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONSEQUENCES: When Cold Pills Don't Stop at the Nose &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The American Heart Association has issued a reminder that colds
can be bad for high blood pressure, or at least that many
decongestants can be.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, said Dr. Kathryn A. Taubert, director of the
association's cardiovascular science division, is that most
decongestants go to work by reducing the swelling of inflamed sinus
tissues, but ``don't know that they're just supposed to act on the
nose.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, they can constrict blood vessels throughout the
body, raising blood pressure. In other cases, they can interfere
with the working of blood pressure medicines.
</P>
<P>
   Many patients are only moderately aware of this danger, a recent
survey found. The survey showed that while 86 percent of patients
with high blood pressure said they checked the labels of
over-the-counter medicines, half of them reported taking cold or
flu drugs that are not recommended for people with hypertension.
The survey was conducted by Schering-Plough Health Care Products,
which makes a decongestant, CoricidinHBP, that does not constrict
blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Taubert said that peering at drugstore shelves through watery
eyes was not the best way to choose an appropriate cold medicine.
People with high blood pressure ``should talk to their physician
before they get sick,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSCLE GROUPS: A Therapist's Touch on Arthritic Knees &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A twice-a-week, monthlong program of physical therapy and
exercise training significantly reduced pain levels and surgery
rates among patients with arthritic knees, according to a study in
this month's issue of The Annals of Internal Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The study, from the Brooke Army Medical Center at Fort Sam
Houston, Texas, put 83 patients, most over 60, into randomized
trials. Half were given physical therapy and training in knee
exercises to be done in the clinic and at home; the other half
received a placebo treatment _ ultrasound too weak to have an
effect.
</P>
<P>
   After eight weeks, those receiving the real treatment had
increased the distance they could walk in six minutes by 6 percent.
Over the year that followed, only 5 percent of the treatment group
needed knee surgery compared with 20 percent of the placebo group.
Members of the treatment group also said the pain was reduced by as
much as 40 percent after only three sessions, wrote the study's
lead author, Col. Gail D. Deyle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AT RISK: Snow Shoveling Imperils Young Men, Too &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Heavy snow and heart attacks go together like sidewalks and ice,
health officials have long known. But how deep does the snow have
to be for the risk to go up? Not all that deep, a study of winter
deaths in Pennsylvania has found: A combination of just over an
inch of snow and temperatures below 20 degrees caused death rates
from heart attacks to triple among men 35 to 49 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The risks went up for men of all age groups. Even men younger
than 35 faced a significant increase under those conditions,
according to the study, a joint project of epidemiologists from the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention and the Pennsylvania
Department of Health. In the study, published late last year in the
American Journal of Epidemiology, mortality records and weather
records were compared to establish relationships between snow and
cold and deaths from heart attack, strokes and respiratory
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Women fared better, the study found. The only significant
increase in death rates from bad winter weather were for women
older than 65, who faced higher risks of fatal respiratory illness
or stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier research has established that prolonged exposure to cold
makes the blood more likely to clot and cause a heart attack or
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest hazard, the researchers said, is probably snow
shoveling, which the article labeled ``a traditional male
activity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
