<HEADLINE>
SPINAL CURVATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 (Eds: Questions may be italicized. Please note that the word AT
within parentheses has been used in the end note instead of the
symbol, which is non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.)  
 (af)  
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I got a brace when I was 7 to correct idiopathic scoliosis.
Is this still the standard practice? Is it true that this problem
is disproportionately common in girls? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Idiopathic scoliosis, a sideways curve of the spine of
unknown cause in adolescence, is now believed to require active
treatment in only about 10 percent of cases, according to ``The
Merck Manual of Diagnosis and Therapy.'' When treatment is called
for, a cast or a device called a Milwaukee brace is widely used.
</P>
<P>
   At least 60 percent to perhaps 80 percent of the cases are in
girls, and girls tend to have worse curves and greater progression.
</P>
<P>
   A review of studies on scoliosis and its treatment, by Dr.
Stuart L. Weinstein of the department of orthopedic surgery of the
University of Iowa Hospitals and Clinics, found that the Milwaukee
brace, which has been in wide use since the late 1940s, has been
the subject of few long-term studies to evaluate its results.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein also noted that most of the studies did not keep track
of the progression of the curvature, making it uncertain whether
patients with braces would have gotten worse without it.
</P>
<P>
   Bracing tends to stop the curve's progression in 85 percent to
90 percent of patients, but there is wide variation in response,
Weinstein said; most common is a moderate correction while the
brace is worn with slow, steady progression back to the original
curve after its use is tapered off. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by mail to Question,
Science Times, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd St., New York, N.Y.
10036-3959, or by e-mail to question(AT)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
