<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOTSWANA-CAMELS-ART-820&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TSABONG JOURNAL: AN EMBARRASSMENT OF CAMELS (IT'S IN POLICE
HANDS) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TSABONG, Botswana _ How can you possibly patrol this blazing hot
desert, wondered the British colonialists who once ruled this
sleepy patch of the Kalahari as their police horses dropped dead
from thirst and disease.
</P>
<P>
   The answer came in a letter dated Aug. 30, 1889.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Sir,'' wrote Cecil Rhodes, the British diamond magnate
and founder of Rhodesia, in his graceful script. ``I am willing to
defray the cost of the purchase of twenty camels and the cost of
the engagement of six camel drivers to be employed in the service
of the police.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, 32 years passed before the camels arrived at the police
station here, but when they did, the officers sang their praises.
Camels, they rhapsodized, live longer than horses. Camels carry
heavier loads than horses. Camels walk longer distances than
horses. And, the clincher, camels drink little water and cheerfully
eat nettles and prickly shrubs, the plants that seemed to grow here
in great abundance.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1959, the allure had begun to fade. And in neatly typed
reports to their commanders, the department's Committee on Police
Camel Corps started delicately suggesting that camels might be a
bit passe, what with the increasing popularity of the motor car and
all.
</P>
<P>
   Which just might explain Lemme Talampe's dour face.
</P>
<P>
   He is the man leading the Tsabong police station into the 2000s,
the station commander who in 1997 inherited a modern red-brick
building, five sport utility vehicles, 50 smartly dressed officers
and, yes, nearly 200 camels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing about camels?''
</P>
<P>
   Talampe fell silent as he glumly considered the animals, now
down to 20, that together consume more than $28,000 a year in food,
medicine and training, money that some police officers suspect
might be better put toward cell phones, radios or new Land Rovers.
</P>
<P>
   He pondered and pondered as his sweating junior officers saddled
the grunting, snorting, grimacing camels during a training exercise
in the burning sun. And then he gave up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer a vehicle,'' Talampe said finally. ``With a vehicle,
you can go on patrol and come back the very same day. With a camel,
you have to spend days on patrol. It's a very slow animal. You
don't rush it. Otherwise it gets tired and doesn't move.''
</P>
<P>
   In this tiny outpost of a town, where goats still prance along
the tar road and the only motel lacks a telephone, these living,
breathing relics of another century seem mostly unwanted and
unloved.
</P>
<P>
   The young officers, who occasionally ride camels on patrol, sit
comfortably in the saddle, but openly hanker for the flashier
rides, the sports utility vehicles, which have the added benefit of
air-conditioning _ no small matter in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not comfortable,'' Officer Ditshweu Ditshweu, 27, said
of the camels.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Letsosa Namane, 29, said, ``The first time, I was afraid
to see them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the longtime camel trainer, who seemed offended by all the
disparaging talk about his charges, confessed that camels could be
a bit ornery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some can be funny,'' said the trainer, Shabi Dikhakhe, who has
been working with police camels for 16 years. ``They can
deliberately walk into low tree branches to knock you off.''
</P>
<P>
   Talampe, who wears starched white shirts and neatly pressed
trousers, was offended, too, when asked whether he patrolled on a
camel himself. (``You think senior officers ride camels?`` he
asked, astonished.) But he was pleased to discuss a happier topic,
the camel auction that had been planned for last year.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the police department here had nearly 200 camels,
and someone decided that selling them might be a good idea,
especially since the animals are rarely used these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people were interested, so many people!'' Talampe
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some wanted them for commercial use,'' he said. ``Some just
wanted to ride them. They used to telephone from all over, from
even as far as Cape Town.''
</P>
<P>
   But leaders in the local community protested, insisting that the
camels stay here so they could be used to attract tourists for
desert safaris. In the end, most of the camels were transferred to
the Ministry of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
   But the police brass in the national capital, Gaborone, decided
that the department here should keep 20 camels. Talampe said they
are used mostly when the station runs short of vehicles or to
patrol far off cattle posts, where there are no paved roads, only
sand roads.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the department should have simply gotten rid of
the animals once and for all, the junior officers looked nervously
at Talampe and Talampe looked nervously at them. Finally, after
they all chuckled nervously, Talampe said such sensitive questions
should be referred to national headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The camels themselves, with their big brown eyes and long
eyelashes, seemed totally indifferent to whether they patrolled or
not.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The brands on their rumps _ ``BP'' for Botswana Police _ clearly
identify them as police property, which protects them from theft.
Not that there is any real risk of theft. The government, after
all, is the only big camel owner in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The animals have numbers, not names, which are also branded into
their hides. ``They all look the same to me,'' said Talampe,
although the trainer politely disagreed, noting differences in
their color, facial expressions and teeth.
</P>
<P>
   After the training session was over, Talampe cheerfully left
Camels 237, 239, 287 and 266 to their own devices, relieved to
settle back in his air-conditioned office, where he could dream
about what his police station might have been like if the animals
had all been sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have made a fortune,'' he said wistfully. ``We could
have bought more Land Rovers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
