<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9580 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      02-07 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERY OF BALL LIGHTNING  
 FOLLOW THAT HONEYBEE  
 A BEE'S EYE-VIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ball lightning is one of nature's odder, and rarer, phenomena.
Few people have seen it, but those who have do not quickly forget
it. It appears in a thunderstorm as a floating luminous sphere,
usually about the size of a honeydew melon, that shines like a
light bulb for 10 seconds or so and then either explodes or fades
from view. Scientists have been at a loss to explain it
satisfactorily.
</P>
<P>
   But two researchers at the University of Canterbury in New
Zealand have come up with a promising new model for the phenomenon.
Essentially, to paraphrase one of Elvis' greatest hits, ball
lightning is just a hunk _ a hunk of burning silicon.
</P>
<P>
   When ordinary lightning strikes the ground, it produces intense
heat. The researchers, writing in Nature, argue that if the soil
has the proper ratio of carbon to silicates, a lightning strike can
produce extremely small particles of silicon and silicon-containing
compounds in the air.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers propose that the particles could then link up
into chains and then into loose fluffy clusters that would float in
the air. Oxygen in the air would eventually cause the silicon
compounds to oxidize, or burn up, and the researchers calculated
that the brightness, duration and color of the glow would match
reported observations. The heat of the ball, they suggest, would
determine whether it fades or explodes.
</P>
<P>
   Although the scientists were able to create chains of tiny
particles by simulating lightning strikes in the laboratory, they
caution that they were unable to recreate the total ball lightning
effect. So their theory remains just that, for now. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOLLOW THAT HONEYBEE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The flight of a honeybee is notoriously difficult to track. Even
the most sharp-eyed researcher cannot follow a bee for more than
100 feet or so.
</P>
<P>
   But bee tracking is now a lot easier, thanks to a radar
technique in which the insect is outfitted with a tiny
antenna-transponder. A signal received by the antenna is sent back
as a harmonic, or multiple of the initial frequency, enabling
researchers to sort out the tiny bee from background echoes.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the University of Illinois have used the technique
to study the orientation flights young bees make to develop their
homing ability.
</P>
<P>
   The radar data, reported in Nature, produced some intriguing
results. Successive trips are of the same duration as earlier ones,
but the bees fly faster, so a larger area is covered. And the bees
rarely fly completely around the hive; they usually explore only
one or two quadrants at a time. All this suggests that the bees
learn the local landscape progressively viewing it from different
positions with each flight. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A BEE'S EYE-VIEW &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The honeybees at the Australian National University in Canberra
do not wear antennas. But they do have to fly into narrow, wooden
tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   That technique was used by researchers to determine how a bee
calculates how far it had to travel to a food source, which the bee
then communicates to others through a ``waggle dance.'' One theory
holds that distance is gauged by the amount of energy consumed;
another holds that it is the movement of ground images in the eyes
that provides the cues.
</P>
<P>
   By using the tunnels, the scientists were able to show that
distance calibration is visual. In the tunnel, which is less than
five inches wide, a bee is far closer to the ``ground'' (in this
case, tunnel walls) than it would be in open air. For a given
distance, the movement of the ground image across the eyes would be
far quicker in the tunnel than in open air (just as, from an
airplane, the ground appears to move faster the lower the plane is
flying).
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, writing in the journal Science, compared how
far the bees thought they had traveled (as measured by the duration
of the waggle dance) to how far they actually traveled, and found
that a flight of about 20 feet in a tunnel seemed, to the bees,
more like 600 feet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
