<SLUG> BC-MEAT08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOLD-KIST SAYS CHICKEN NUGGETS 'SAFE TO EAT'
 &HT;    By ELLIOT JASPIN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Claiming the public is being ``misled'' by
disgruntled government food safety inspectors, the president of
Gold Kist Inc. released a statement Monday defending the safety of
his company's chicken nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gold Kist poultry products are safe to eat,'' said John
Bekkers, president of the Atlanta-based processor.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Department inspectors at two of the company's plants
in Alabama have said that school lunch programs in 31 states were
using chicken nuggets made in part from diseased poultry processed
by Gold Kist.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no factual support for their claims and there have
been no incidents of chicken-related illness reported to us or the
USDA,'' Bekkers said. He did not specifically deny the allegations
that diseased poultry was made into chicken nuggets, but called
them ``gross exaggerations.''
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors themselves said the diseased poultry was unlikely
to make anyone sick. Instead, they said chicken nuggets made from
poultry that had pus, scabs and sores was not wholesome.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Newspapers has also obtained copies of U.S. government
inspection records for a single day last month at Gold Kist's
Guntersville, Ala., plant that appear to contradict Bekkers'
statement. The records show that on that day, inspectors repeatedly
found carcasses with sores, scabs and infections that had
apparently been missed by company employees.
</P>
<P>
   Gold Kist did not respond to repeated requests for an interview
before an article on the chicken nuggets was published last
weekend. In addition, no one at Gold Kist returned repeated
telephone calls Monday to discuss Bekkers' statement, the
allegations of the federal inspectors or the federal records
showing diseased poultry at the Guntersville plant.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Bekkers noted that there is constant sampling
during production and ``that samples are taken from each hour's
production and are eaten by quality assurance employees.'' However,
Bekkers did not disclose the results of either his or the
government's sampling program.
</P>
<P>
   Government logs from Jan. 15 show one sample taken at 4:55 p.m.
found that seven out of 10 birds sampled had serious defects. The
exact nature of the defects was not listed but can include sores
and scabs. Another 10-bird sample taken at 8:30 p.m. turned up six
carcasses with some kind of poultry disease.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors said that about 50 percent of the poultry being
delivered to the Guntersville plant has some kind of disease.
Bekkers' statement did not discuss if the company was having
problems with disease in the flocks being delivered to the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bekkers accused ``union-activist USDA poultry
inspectors'' of making false accusations about the ``quality of
Gold Kist poultry products.'' At the same time, Bekkers cited the
inspections by U.S. Agriculture department as proof there is
nothing wrong with his company's products.
</P>
<P>
   Elliot Jaspin's e-mail address is elliotj(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
