<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS-EVENTURES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPS Web subsidiary launched
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Can United Parcel Service Inc. move digital bits as
well as it moves boxes?
</P>
<P>
   That's the challenge the Sandy Springs-based shipper faces in
the launch, announced Monday, of a new Internet subsidiary called
UPS eVentures.
</P>
<P>
   The subsidiary's assignment is to make UPS as big a presence in
electronic commerce as it is now in package delivery.
</P>
<P>
   That means translating the company's expertise in tracking and
logistics into Web-based software that can help other companies
coordinate everything from the purchase of raw materials to the
ordering of paper clips.
</P>
<P>
   ``UPS is looking to help companies virtualize themselves,'' says
Mark Rhoney, president of UPS eVentures. ``We can do everything for
them from execution of delivery to customer care.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, eVentures announced its first new offering, UPS
e-Logistics. The company plans to offer Internet-based software to
electronic commerce companies that help them track inventory, order
supplies and manage every aspect of their business.
</P>
<P>
   But eVenture's initiatives will not be limited to electronic
commerce. ``We plan to offer our services to any company,'' says
Rhoney.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Internet-based services play part of a larger
strategy to leverage off the company's core competency of
delivering packages worldwide. It delivers 12.5 million packages
globally every day. More than 6 percent of the U.S. gross domestic
product is shipped via UPS.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic management of goods and services is a natural for
UPS, according to some company observers. ``UPS is an ideal spot,
given their expertise in managing the delivery of goods for small
and midsize businesses,'' says Peter Coleman, the analyst who
covers the company for Bank America Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Rhoney says that, in launching eVentures, UPS is taking
what it has already done for itself and selling that to others.
</P>
<P>
   The company first embraced the Internet in the management of its
business. ``Then we realized that the Internet wasn't just about
our business but enabled global commerce,'' says Rhoney. ``That's
when the Internet became part of a new global strategy for us.''
</P>
<P>
   With eVentures, UPS is entering a business that remains wide
open. That business is called logistics by analysts, and it
generates $1 billion annually in revenue for scores of companies.
</P>
<P>
   Basically these companies try to marshal the Internet to help
companies control costs and manage operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a zillion players out there, but no one has emerged to
provide an end-to-end solution through the Internet,'' says
Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   It is a market, Coleman believes, in which UPS could hold an
advantage. The biggest buyers of third-party logistics software are
small to midsized companies and home offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' says Coleman, ``is UPS' bread and butter.''
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) Please see UPS, D4
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) Continued from D1
</P>
<P>
   UPS: Net
</P>
<P>
   unit to offer
</P>
<P>
   logistics help
</P>
