r f BC-EARTHLINK-COX     02-07 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTHLINK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Earthlink Inc. says it nearly doubled its revenues
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Atlanta-based Internet service provider, Earthlink
Inc., said it nearly doubled its revenues in the fourth quarter,
but its loss nearly tripled as the company spent millions on
advertising and marketing and the merger between it and Mindspring.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies reported combined pro-forma earnings Monday.
Their merger was completed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At an analysts' meeting at the Palace Hotel in New York, Chief
Executive Garry Betty said that, for the quarter ending Dec, 31,
1999, the combined company reported a pro-forma loss of $60.8
million, or 55 cents a share, compared with a loss of $21.6
million, or 25 cents a share, a year earlier. Excluding merger
costs, the loss was 22 cents a share in the latest quarter.
Fourth-quarter revenue rose to $199.1 million from $97.8 million a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a good quarter and a very good year for EarthLink,''
Betty said. ``We are executing our vision to be the number one
ISP.'' He defended the expense of intense marketing as part of the
effort to catch up to America Online, which, with 22 million
subscribers, is far and away the nation's largest ISP, but
EarthLink has its sights on closing or at least narrowing that gap.
</P>
<P>
   The new company now has 3.1 million subscribers, including
322,000 new subscribers added during the last quarter. The company
expects to have 4.5 million subscribers by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Original projections called for 5 million subscribers in that
time, but EarthLink president Michael McQuary said the figure was
revised because of stiff competition from the ISP rebate offers
many computer makers are offering (''sign up for three years of ISP
service and get $400 discount on a new computer'') and increasing
consumer demand for high-speed broadband services.
</P>
<P>
   To combat those pressures, EarthLink's plans call for increased
marketing efforts to raise awareness of the compan, as well as to
enlarge its broadband service areas. EarthLink currently offers
high-speed DSL service in some parts of metro Atlanta, as well as
15 cities around the country.
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink said it had examined the idea of working with computer
makers to offer rebates in exchange for subscription commitments
but rejected it. McQuary has said that customers who come for a
rebate don't become longterm subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will try to find the best place to optimize our growth,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Betty also said the company's primary growth method would be to
gain new subscribers from what he called the ``switcher'' market _
current Internet users unhappy with their service provider. He said
figures indicate that users shopping for a new ISP are a larger
percent of the ISP market than are new users.
</P>
<P>
   McQuary said high speed Internet access provided by telephone
and cable companies accounted for 40 per cent of ``churn'' or
customers who leave EarthLink for another ISP. He said that only 6
or 7 percent of users who leave go to free ISPs, which don't charge
customers for access but generate revenue from advertising
delivered to users.
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink and MindSpring have so far rejected the idea of
offering free access to users. ``It's something we keep an eye
on,'' McQuary said. ``Free ISPs are getting a lot of press right
now. If it makes sense to offer it, we can and we will, but the
economics don't make much sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty added that free ISPs don't offer the customer service and
support that EarthLink is known for. ``We don't get five million
calls to our call centers because people like to call,'' he said.
``They have questions, and we will answer them.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty also outlined the company's four target areas for the
company in the coming year: adding traditional dial-up customers,
increasing its ability to provide high-speed broadband acccess,
adding to its Web hosting business and adding content, commerce and
advertising partners to the EarthLink Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Betty
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) Please see XXXXX, D4
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) Continued from D1
</P>
<P>
   Xxxx: Xxxxxyyy
