<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9597 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BOULDERING-ART-NY     02-07 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BOULDERING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING A GRIP ON A CLUMP OF MOLECULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By LIZ NEPORENT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I am plastered against the side of a large rock, 15
feet above a patch of trampled dirt in Central Park. My fingers are
wedged inside a fissure. My left toe is balanced on a protrusion
about the size of a golf ball and my right toe is balanced on . . .
I don't know what it's balanced on.
</P>
<P>
   Below me my friend, Ivan Greene, the director of climbing at
Chelsea Piers, shouts encouragement. ``Smear your right foot onto
the rock,'' he says helpfully, ``Twist your left hip in, stand up,
and grab that giant knob just above you.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm trying to ``boulder,'' a form of rock climbing that involves
more lateral than vertical movement. Unlike sports climbing, the
type of climbing in which you scale a wall, bouldering involves no
ropes, harnesses or carabiners (hooks that connect climber to
rope). All you need is a pair of climbing shoes with sticky rubber
soles, a bag of chalk to powder your hands for a better grip and a
willingness to fall.
</P>
<P>
   As Ivan explains, there's really nothing to fear. ``You're only
falling from a twist-your-ankle height, not a fall-to-your-death or
even a break-your-leg height,'' he assures me.
</P>
<P>
   The object of bouldering is to ``solve a problem.'' That is,
find a way to get from Point A on the rock to Point B. You do this
by contorting your body into heretofore unimaginable positions and
by perching atop seemingly unperchable chips and minute clusters of
rock crystal.
</P>
<P>
   It requires creative and inconceivable body contortions and, of
course, the smoother the rock, the harder the problem. The
difficulty of a route also depends on the position you start from.
A sitting start is the most difficult because it requires a great
deal of arm strength, balance and skill to pull yourself up and
along. A start that requires jumping up into the first move is a
little easier provided you're connecting with a decent grip and
secure footing. Standing is the easiest and most pleasant way to
begin.
</P>
<P>
   The problem I'm on has a standing start. It is a beginner's
route etched into ``Rat Rock,'' a grouping of boulders near the
southwest corner of the park. Stephen Harris, an instructor at
Chelsea Piers, describes it as a straightforward traverse across a
short expanse of friendly rock.
</P>
<P>
   When I'm on the ground, I believe him. I watch a few experienced
boulderers glide across it like spiders. But when I'm up on the
rock, everything seems to flatten out. One hand space that, from
below, looked big enough to hide a nest of squirrels, requires
holding on with just my fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan instructs me to ``smear'' my feet; he wants me to press the
rubber edges and soles of my shoes as hard as I can into the rock.
This, in theory, would help my feet better stick to the surface of
the stone.
</P>
<P>
   I'm on this problem for about 30 minutes. I make progress but
the spoiler is a move that requires squatting low and stretching my
right leg out until the tip of my toe settles on a group of
molecules that Ivan swears are big enough for me to balance on. I'm
ejected and fall at this point in the problem over and over again.
Stephen, my spotter, is always there to catch me.
</P>
<P>
   As a kid, playing on the neighborhood jungle gym was my favorite
pastime. Bouldering is like a grown up version of the jungle gym.
It combines all the fun of using your body to solve a puzzle with
the grown up benefits of building stamina, strength, balance and
coordination. All this and not a treadmill or a weight machine in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   I also like that boulderers call each other ``dude'' _ even the
women _ and that they wear baggy pants with drawstrings and rip
cords sprouting from the pockets and waistbands. After a 10-minute
burst of intense activity, they relax. It's a refreshing change
from the spandex and headphone culture of the gym I've exercised in
for years.
</P>
<P>
   Since my Rat Rock session, I've been sharpening my skills at
Chelsea Piers, a large sports and recreation center on West Side
Highway at 23rd Street. The Piers has a decent artificial
bouldering wall made of a hard gray plastic material fashioned to
simulate stone; it's dotted with colored holds that define the
various routes and problems.
</P>
<P>
   With about three months of bouldering under my belt, I'm seeing
definite changes in my body: My shoulders and arms are slightly
bigger and more defined. My back is broader; some of my blouses are
a bit tight. My legs are stronger and more flexible. I was feeling
pretty good about myself until the other day when my husband looked
at my calloused palms and ragged cuticles and told me that I now
have ``man hands.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
