<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9598 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-JOURNALIST-BOS     02-07 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-JOURNALIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS SEEK TO QUESTION MISSING JOURNALIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The mystery over the fate of Radio Liberty's missing
war correspondent, Andrei Babitsky, deepened Monday when Russian
prosecutors said he was wanted for questioning on suspicion of
joining separatist rebels in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Just days earlier the Kremlin had said that Russian military
officials, who had been holding Babitsky, had turned him over to
Chechen rebels in exchange for Russian prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Sergei Prokopov, a spokesman for the Russian
prosecutor, said Babitsky would be arrested if he did not show up
for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky, 35, a reporter for the US-funded Radio Liberty,
disappeared on Jan. 15 after leaving Chechnya's capital Grozny,
where he was covering Russia's war against separatist rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Widely respected by colleagues for his hard-hitting reporting
and unwillingness to yield to Kremlin pressure, Babitsky appears to
have gotten caught in a conflict between the truth about Russia's
war in Chechnya and what Moscow wants the public to know.
</P>
<P>
   His withering reports from the war zone have contradicted the
Kremlin's official statements and infuriated military officials.
Many in Moscow say that Babitsky has become the target of a Kremlin
campaign to control information, intimidate the media and whitewash
the war.
</P>
<P>
   Oleg Panfilov of the Glasnost Defense Fund, a Moscow-based
free-speech advocacy group, said the Kremlin was moving toward a
crackdown on the media and was making an example of Babitsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a long-standing battle between the security
services and journalists there. Only now has the game become
dangerous,'' the daily newspaper Izvestia wrote last week.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to understand why the Russian military might want to
silence Babitsky.
</P>
<P>
   When they claimed that Grozny was sealed, surrounded and
impenetrable, Babitsky filed reports about how he stealthily
slipped through Russian lines. When Moscow said Russian forces had
captured a strategic square in central Grozny with minimal
casualties, it was Babitsky who filed reports of massive troop
losses _ and provided video footage to a Russian television station
to support his reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Since Babitsky's disappearance, the Kremlin has issued a series
of confusing, contradictory and often strange statements.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, authorities in Moscow denied any knowledge of his
whereabouts. Then, after news reports came out of Chechnya that
Babitsky was being held by Russian troops, the Kremlin acknowledged
that the journalist had been arrested for lacking accreditation to
work in the war zone. Law-enforcement officials also said Babitsky
was suspected of aiding and abetting Chechnya's separatist rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last week, Sergei Yastrzhembsky, a spokesman for acting
President Vladimir V. Putin, said Babitsky had been handed over to
Chechen rebels in exchange for Russian prisoners of war. A video
released Friday showed Russian soldiers handing a clearly
distraught Babitsky over to unidentified armed and masked men.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky's wife, Lyudmila, said the video only added to her
concerns about her husband's fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have watched that video one hundred times. I have never seen
Andrei so distraught,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday, Yastrzhembsky said Putin was
informed of the move only ``after the exchange took place.''
Yastrzhembsky would not say who authorized the exchange and told
reporters not to ask any more questions about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen rebel President Aslan Maskhadov, meanwhile, said he was
unaware of the exchange or Babitsky's whereabouts. He suggested
that the military may have killed him and is now trying to put the
blame on the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babitsky was inconvenient. Many methods could have been used
to liquidate him,'' news agencies quoted Maskhadov as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Patrushev, director of the Federal Security Service _
successor to the Soviet KGB _ was quoted by news agencies as saying
that Babitsky was alive. Patrushev added, however, that he did not
know where the journalist was located.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see these officials saying that Andrei is alive and well,
well where is he?'' Babitsky's wife said. ``I see that they are
alive and well, but I want to see my husband here with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyudmila Babitsky said she hasn't left her modest two room
Moscow apartment since his disappearance. She sleeps with a
telephone by her pillow as she waits for news of her husband's
fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sit at home and wait Andrei to call, or somebody with news
about him,'' she said, holding the couple's two-year-old daughter
Revekka. ``I jump every time the phone rings. What else can I do?''
she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
