<HEADLINE>
FLU-STRICKEN KENNEDY FACES SEVERAL MORE DAYS IN HOSPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Apparently striken with a bad case of the flu,
Senator Edward M. Kennedy is expected to remain in the hospital for
a few more days to recover, his aides say.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, 67, is suffering from a fever, muscle aches, chills and
a cough. He was admitted to Sibley Memorial Hospital on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's physician, Dr. Mark Abbruzzese, released a statement
Monday saying Kennedy has a viral illness, and ``is responding
nicely to treatment. His symptoms are typical of such cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbruzzese said he wanted to keep Kennedy in the hospital for
several more days for observation and treatment _ a decision backed
by Kennedy's wife, Victoria Reggie Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted is well on his way to a speedy recovery,'' Mrs. Kennedy
said in a statement. ``He's feeling better today than yesterday,
and is itching to go home. But he is still running a temperature,
and his doctors and I have convinced him that another few days of
rest is the best treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was visited by his sons, Edward Jr. and Representative
Patrick Kennedy, Democrat of Rhode Island, and by his daughter,
Kara. The senator has been in contact with his office and requested
briefing books, spokesman Will Keyser said.
</P>
<P>
   Keyser said Kennedy had had a flu shot.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as a week ago, Kennedy was visibly energetic and
apparently healthy, revving up the crowd at a rally in new
Hampshire for Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Kennedy called a senior aide to say he didn't think
he would be able to make it to the office the next day. He ended up
checking into the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts' other senator, Democrat John F. Kerry, is also
ill with what he described as walking pneumonia. Kerry has been at
work, but said he spent the holiday season and congressional break
with a terrible cough.
</P>
</TEXT>
