<SLUG> BC-AKAMI-INTERVU-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AKAMI BUYING INTERVU FOR $2.89 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Akamai Technologies Inc. of Cambridge, Mass. is spending $2.8
billion to acquire San Diego-based Intervu Inc., in a bid to lock
in leadership of the booming Internet content delivery market.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai runs a network of 2,000 Internet servers that stores
copies of popular Web sites. When a Web user requests data from a
site, it's sent to him from the nearest Akamai server, rather than
from the site's own server. This results in faster access to the
information. Hundreds of major Web sites, such as Lycos, Yahoo, and
CNN use Akamai to speed data delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Intervu also speeds data delivery. But while Akamai specializes
in text- and graphics-based Web sites, Intervu's network of servers
are designed for streaming media _ audio and video programs on the
Net. A number of major Web sites, such as CNN and Microsoft
Network, use Intervu servers to deliver audio and video data.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike Akamai, Intervu has been exclusively focused on on-line
streaming, both audio and video,'' said Akamai president Paul
Sagan. Akamai also wanted to enter the business, and decided to
acquire Intervu rather than build a new network from scratch.
``This speeds Akamai's time to market, reduces risk, and saves
money,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Intervu chief executive Harry Gruber said the two companies are
a perfect fit. Each has a key capability the other lacks, while
both are committed to the same business of speeding the performance
of the Internet. ``We have the same religion,'' said Gruber, ``and
that's what makes the synergy so great between the two companies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a very strong deal from a strategic standpoint,''
said Mark Langner, senior broadband analyst at J.P. Morgan
Securities Inc. in San Francisco. ``It makes a lot of sense on a
lot of levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Langner noted that Intervu and Akamai serve many of the same Web
sites. By acquiring Intervu, Akamai eliminates a competitor and
insures that some other firm can't purchase Intervu and gain a
foothold in the market. ``This is really textbook Internet business
building 101,'' Langner said.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai agreed to swap 0.5957 shares of its stock for every
Intervu share. At Akamai's closing price Monday of 228 5/8, that
makes the deal worth almost $2.8 billion. Still, it's relatively
cheap, considering that Akamai went public just three months ago at
36 a share. The company has been one of the biggest beneficiaries
in the huge Internet stock run-up, and is using its high stock
valuation to make some strategic purchases. Just last month, Akamai
paid $200 million in stock to acquire Network24 Communications, a
company that makes software for managing interactive Internet
broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   Five-year-old Intervu went public in 1997 at a price of 9 1/2 a
share. As with most Internet start-ups, the company has never
posted a profit, losing $14.5 million in the first three quarters
of 1999 on revenue of $6.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also will give General Electric Co. a small stake in
Akamai, because GE's National Broadcasting Co. business unit
presently owns 5 percent of Intervu.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Akamai closed down 6 3/8 to 228 5/8 Monday, while
Intervu gained 12 3/8 to close at a record high of 129 3/8, both on
the Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 1933EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9612 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-LAWFIRM-SALARIES-BOS &LR;      02-07 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWFIRM-SALARIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEGINNING LAWYERS OFFERED $140,000 IN TALENT HUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Faced with increased competition for law school
graduates from the Internet firms it represents, Boston law firm
Testa, Hurwitz &AMP; Thibeault will offer its associates $140,000 per
year, making its first-year lawyers among the highest paid in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are right in the midst of the high-tech revolution and, the
truth is, we have collected within our walls an awful lot of
talent,'' said Timothy C. Maguire, a partner at the law firm.
``These are people who know the industry and they are attractive to
a lot of companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost, so far, four to five people in the past year to
some very high-quality dot-coms,'' Maguire said. ``So, we decided
to take salary off the table. We'd like people to focus on the
quality of our training and the collegiality of the firm and not
get lost in dollars and cents.''
</P>
<P>
   The law firm, which represents emerging companies and the
venture capitalists that fund them, hired 45 law school graduates
in September. All will receive a 40 percent pay hike, from $100,000
to $140,000, effective this month.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, pay raises were extended to associates with more
than a year's tenure. One associate who joined the firm several
years ago said his annual pay increased from $175,000 to $217,000.
</P>
<P>
   The push to hike first-year associates' pay actually began in
California about a month ago. There, companies had established a
base compensation of $125,000, along with calculations that
included bonuses based on the number of hours worked by each
associate. Under this plan, an associate could make up to $155,000
per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you are now seeing is a reaction to what has happened in
California,'' said Earle Yaffa, managing director of Skadden, Arps,
Slate, Meagher &AMP; Flom.
</P>
<P>
   Based in New York with an office in Boston, Skadden Arps also
notified its first-year associates last Thursday their pay would
increase from $107,000 to $140,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to come up with compensation that would pay the same
total compensation that the best associates at California firms
would likely be paid,'' said Yaffa. ``With a bonus, the total
compensation could be higher. The bonus is based on a number of
factors, including how well the firm has done . . . We have paid
bonuses, in addition to base salaries, for at least three to four
years.''
</P>
<P>
   News of the pay raise at Testa, Hurwitz, which was announced
late last week, spread quickly throughout the legal community and
caused some firms to begin re-evaluating pay and compensation
packages again, just weeks after leading firms started offering
first-year lawyers $100,000 per year, excluding bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now reviewing what everyone else is paying and
hopefully, within the week, we will know how to respond,'' said
Robin Carbone, director of recruiting for Choate, Hall &AMP; Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The firm currently pays associates $90,000 per year, and was
planning to raise first-year associates' salary to $100,000,
Carbone said. She did not know how the increase at Testa, Hurwitz
would affect associates at her firm.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia C. Brier of MCB Communications, which represents law
firms in Boston, said the higher salaries would have a ``tremendous
impact on work-family balance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, there will be much more pressure on associates to
perform and bill,'' she said. ``They will have to do serious
billing to justify these stratospheric salaries and that will
affect work-family balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the legal community is not alone. The world's top
consulting companies have hiked pay and are offering an array of
benefits to prevent its brightest employees from joining Internet
firms. McKinsey &AMP; Co., for example, now offers investment
opportunities in Internet start-ups. And Mercer Management helps
talented associates design business plans and will even put them in
touch with venture capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   Testa, Hurwitz employs 330 to 340 people. Its associates receive
comprehensive health care, dental, and a company match of up to 4
percent of total pay in their 401(k) accounts. The company has
instituted a number of perks, including an equity incentive program
that offers associates access to Internet investments and a
concierge service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concierge service will even walk your dog, if necessary,''
Maguire said. ``It allows our associates to stay calm and not get
stressed out because a client is going into merger negotiations and
(the associate) cannot be home to meet the cable guy.''
</P>
<P>
   David Hagen, marketing manager at Infirmation.com, a career
resource for lawyers founded by two lawyers, said: ``Associates are
finding that the hours at law firms are very long, and they are
struggling. But when they join a dot-com, they are automatically
considered top management. A lot of them are doing content
management, or business development. In many cases, they are not
even practicing law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
