<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON TO FACE ANALYSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After Daniel Burnham took over as chief executive of Raytheon
Co. in 1998, some outside investment specialists warned him they
were wary of the company's financial footing.
</P>
<P>
   The Lexington, Mass. defense contractor had a reputation for
consistently hitting its earnings projections, but also for
reporting relatively low cash-flow figures.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics wondered whether the company could sustain its
profitability, though they relaxed when a new chief financial
officer was installed last March and seemed ready to gain a firmer
handle on Raytheon's outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the alerts now look more apt than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Profits for the quarter ended Dec. 31 fell 79 percent. Following
a series of warnings about its earnings, Raytheon's stock now
trades at less than a third of the high it reached in July.
Raytheon's Class B shares closed Monday at 21 5/8, down 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, a credit-rating downgrade has forced Raytheon to
increase its borrowings from banks.
</P>
<P>
   All of this has investors anxious to hear more details of
Raytheon's recovery plans at a conference the nation's
third-largest defense contractor has scheduled in New York Tuesday
with Wall Street analysts. Sources say the company is expected to
continue trying to free up cash, such as demanding up-front
payments and improving collections from customers, and reducing the
inventory it keeps on hand.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether such steps and other moves it might
announce will help enough as Raytheon tries to pay down the bills
it took on through acquisitions. Total debt stood at $9.7 billion
at the end of December, up from $8.9 billion a year earlier, and
just servicing it cost Raytheon $713 million in net interest
expenses in 1999, a big drain on earnings.
</P>
<P>
   To some, doubts also remain whether Raytheon has done enough to
improve its financial controls. ``They need to develop consistency
and predictability'' in that area, said S.G. Cowen analyst Cai von
Rumohr.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Raytheon has blamed its problems on
tougher-than-expected competition and difficulties integrating
other missile and defense-electronics companies it bought amid
industry consolidation. (The company purchased Hughes Electronics
and Texas Instrument's defense and electronics businesses in 1997).
Raytheon has laid off thousands more employees since 1997 and late
last year launched another restructuring meant to aid the reviews
of new chief financial officer Frank Caine.
</P>
<P>
   It is also trying to combine payroll, ordering and billing
systems that at one point were kept on 50 different computer
systems.
</P>
<P>
   But the more Caine and his troops sift, the more accounting
problems they seem to find. Others debate to what extent Raytheon's
problems are the fault of current leaders or their retired
predecessors, former chief executive Dennis Picard and former chief
financial officer Peter D'Angelo.
</P>
<P>
   Some blame both sets. ``It's easier to hold the previous
management team responsible,'' said Lehman Bros. analyst Joe
Campbell. ``However, the current team has had enough time that they
should have their arms around this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman declined to respond. Meanwhile, the stock's
grim performance has some investors pressing for steps more
dramatic than improved bookkeeping, such as the sale of trouble
assets such as its Cambridge-based construction unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably need to get themselves some financial
flexibility,'' said John Hayes of shareholder Independence
Investment Associates in Boston. On the other hand, the unit might
not fetch much, given weaknesses in overseas construction markets.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon has begun to borrow against a bank line worth more than
$4 billion because a reduced credit rating has diminished its
ability to tap other sources of funds.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon spokesman David Polk declined to discuss the exact
amount it has drawn down, but called the borrowings ``not unusual''
given the rating change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
