<HEADLINE>
ATA TO OFFER LOW-COST CHICAGO-BOSTON FLIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The battle between low-cost carriers and established
airlines will have a new front _ the competitive Boston-Chicago
market, which has been dominated by United Airlines and American
Airlines, the nation's number one and number two airlines
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Low-cost American Trans Air, the nation's 11th-largest carrier,
announced Monday that it will begin service from Boston's Logan
International Airport to Chicago's Midway Airport on May 7.
</P>
<P>
   And US Airways's low-cost service, known as Metrojet, will begin
Boston-Midway service on March 5, with four flights a day.
</P>
<P>
   Metrojet will have a 21-day advance purchase fare of $198 round
trip and a walk-up round-trip fare of $548. US Airways officials
are confident that the US Airways brand name will help win
customers, especially in Boston where the airline has a big
presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the targeting of a market that has a heavy demand, if
fairly high prices, and is a great opportunity for an upstart to
come in and offer low prices that presently do not exist in that
market,'' said Thomas Kinton, director of aviation for the
Massachusetts Port Authority, which owns and operates Logan.
</P>
<P>
   In making the announcement Monday, ATA said it will offer
introductory fares to Chicago's Midway, where it has a hub, from
$79 to $89 for a one-way trip. Fares to West Coast cities such as
Los Angeles, San Francisco and Seattle will be $119 to $149 each
way. Tickets must be purchased by March 31 for travel from May 7
through June 30, and the fare does not include passenger fees
levied by airport authorities, which can add as much a $6 per trip
segment.
</P>
<P>
   The new service makes a competitive market even more crowded.
American and United both have hubs at Chicago's O'Hare
International Airport, and have seen other low-cost entrants enter
recently, including Pan Am, which flies from Portsmouth, N.H., to
Gary, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   The low-cost carriers do not offer more than one class of
service, nor do they come close to matching the varied schedule
from Boston to Chicago that the big two do, but ATA officials are
confident they will do well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are excited about expanding our scheduled service to
include Boston,'' said ATA's president and chief executive officer,
John Tague. ATA flies to 26 business and vacation destinations,
including Dallas, Denver, Honolulu, Las Vegas and several Florida
cities.
</P>
<P>
   The airline will begin service to Chicago with three nonstop
flights every day but Saturday. The flights will continue on to
Dallas-Fort Worth, Denver and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston fits our profile as a city that can perform like others
where we have had success, including Philadelphia and New York out
of LaGuardia and Kennedy,'' said Rick Larsen, vice president of
marketing. ``It is a large market with limited access into Midway
Airport, and it is a market that some lower-fare competition can
stimulate.''
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old airline is known primarily for its commercial
and military charters, but has grown rapidly in the past seven
years as a scheduled airline. Scheduled service now accounts for
nearly 65 percent of the company's revenues. Last year ATA broke
the $1 billion mark, with total revenues of $1.122 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The airline operates a fleet of 53 airplanes, including 24
Boeing 727s, 11 Boeing 757s and 18 Lockheed L-1011s. The company
has its own heavy maintenance and engineering facilities at Chicago
and Indianapolis. The airline will fly 727s from Boston. All of
ATA's planes have one class of service.
</P>
<P>
   ATA closed Monday at 11 11/16, up 7/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
