u f BC-AUSTRIA-ECON-NYT &LR;      02-07 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRIA BRACES FOR BACKLASH FROM INVESTORS AND TOURISTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ Austrian economists and policy-makers fear
that the protests and sanctions against the new government could
dampen investment in this country and raise capital costs for
companies already doing business here.
</P>
<P>
   But the greater concern seems to be Austria's exclusion from
European Union deliberations at a time when the 15-nation group is
discussing policies crucial to the nation's economic future,
including the admission of several formerly Communist East European
countries that are Austria's immediate neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus here seems to be that the downgrading of relations
by the European Union, and the recall of ambassadors by Israel and
the United States, because of the inclusion of ministers from the
anti-immigrant Freedom Party of Joerg Haider, will not have
immediate and serious economic consequences. But that could change
if Austria's isolation deepens.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Haider sought to play down the impact of his
party's inclusion in the government. ``We will have a stable
situation in a few weeks,'' he said in an interview for NBC's
``Today'' program.
</P>
<P>
   The most visible financial effects of Austria's political
isolation were felt last week, when the Vienna stock market index
dropped 10 percent. It dropped 1.3 percent further Monday to the
lowest level in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one loves a stock exchange in a country with political
problems like this,'' Ronald Kern, a fund manager in Vienna with
Constantia Privatbank AG, told Bloomberg News. ``The fears are that
the last international investors will leave the market and not
return for three to six months.''
</P>
<P>
   Only the Brussels, Belgium, stock exchange index has performed
more poorly this year, dropping 13 percent so far.
</P>
<P>
   Austria's financial climate was not helped any last Wednesday,
after the Dutch bank ABN-Amro announced it was suspending a deal to
underwrite asset-backed securities for the Austrian province of
Carinthia, where Haider is governor, because of reports that the
securities would be used to finance a child aid program that would
exclude immigrant families.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in companies dependent on tourism, like Austrian Airlines
AG and Flughafen Wien AG, the Vienna airport operator, have been
dragged down.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, school authorities in Belgium scrapped ski trips to
Austrian resorts and a Belgian tourism trade fair canceled an
invitation to the northern Austrian resort of Scharding. The
Belgian foreign minister, Louis Michel, said skiing in Austria this
winter would be ``immoral.'' How many people will heed such
admonitions is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Sabine Koppl, spokeswoman for the Austrian National Tourism
Board, acknowledged ``scattered cancellations'' by tour groups, but
said it was too early to judge the reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Austrian tourism has been booming. In 1999, tourism revenue
reached a record $14.2 billion, after $13.8 billion the year
before. ``We live from tourism as never before,'' Koppl said.
</P>
<P>
   It is premature to gauge foreign investor reaction to Austria's
political shift. But there have been some disquieting signs.
</P>
<P>
   Rene Siegl, managing director of the Austrian Business Agency, a
government office that seeks to lure foreign investment, said the
new government was ``no catastrophe,'' yet he admitted to ``quite
some demand for explanations'' from prospective investors in Japan,
Taiwan and the United States. In 1999, the agency helped land 118
foreign investment deals totaling $271 million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bernhard Felderer, the director of IHS, an economic research
institute, said further stock market weakness would penalize
Austrian companies by increasing the cost of capital, forcing them
to pay in effect a premium for investment. And the success of the
new government depends in part on attracting new capital in order
to privatize much of Austria's nationalized industry, including the
remaining 75 percent it holds in Austria Telekom AG.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for the moment, Austria is hardly in crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Helmut Kramer, the director of WIFO, another economic research
group, said growth this year could reach 3 percent, after 2.2
percent in 1999. But he cautioned that lingering exclusion of
Austria from European Union deliberations could damage Austrian
interests by preventing Vienna from influencing future policy,
notably toward European enlargement into Eastern Europe, in its own
favor. Austria borders on Hungary and the Czech Republic, which
with Poland are the first three candidates for enlargement.
</P>
<P>
   Yet labor costs in those countries are roughly one-tenth the
Austrian level, Kramer said, and Austria has been urging European
partners away from an immediate opening of Eastern European labor
markets to prevent a flood of cheap labor.
</P>
<P>
   This means the sanctions resulting from Haider's victory could
hamper Austria in obtaining measures to prevent the increased
immigration he opposes. ``In representing our interests to the
European Union,'' said Kramer, ``we are severely handicapped.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
