<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-BIDDERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EBAY FACES ANTITRUST CHALLENGE IN COUNTERSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet auction search service Bidder's Edge, facing a
lawsuit from the online auction house eBay Inc., has filed a
countersuit claiming that eBay is violating federal antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   The countersuit, filed Monday in US District Court in San Jose,
Calif., says that eBay holds a virtual monopoly of the Internet
auction market, and that the company is using its market power to
interfere with Bidder's Edge's relationships with other firms. For
example, the countersuit charges that Krause Publications Inc.,
publisher of a magazine devoted to eBay auctions, canceled an
advertising contract with Bidder's Edge after being pressured by
eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Pursglove, an eBay spokesman, called the filing ``not
unexpected,'' but declined further comment on the allegations until
his firm's attorneys had a chance to study the filing.
</P>
<P>
   The antitrust charges come less than a week after press reports
indicating that the Justice Department is investigating whether to
launch its own antitrust investigation of eBay. Bidder's Edge
president Jim Carney said the countersuit was not connected with
the Justice Department probe, but confirmed that he had been
interviewed by a team of Justice Department attorneys for two hours
on Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   The Bidder's Edge charges are a response to a lawsuit filed in
December, in which eBay accused Bidder's Edge of illegally
publishing information that belongs to eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Bidder's Edge runs an Internet search service from Burlington,
Mass. that allows people to check auctions at different Web sites.
A visitor looking for an item can see prices at several auction
sites at the same time, without having to visit each site
separately.
</P>
<P>
   Some Internet auction sites welcome the Bidder's Edge service,
seeing it as a way to attract more customers.
</P>
<P>
   But Pursglove calls it ``trespassing.'' EBay says that the
auction listings on its site are company property, even if they are
displayed on a publicly accessible Web page. In addition, Pursglove
said that the listings offered by Bidder's Edge are partial and
inaccurate, thereby harming eBay's business.
</P>
<P>
   EBay wants the auction search companies to pay a licensing fee
and follow rules that Pursglove said would ensure ``complete,
accurate and timely listings.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of other auction search services have made such an
arrangement, but Carney has refused. Carney says that Bidder's Edge
is no different from other Web page indexes, such as AltaVista or
Lycos. These services do not need the permission of each of the
millions of Web sites they index. Carney says that if eBay's suit
is successful, it would set a precedent that would undermine the
free exchange of data across the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue here is really the openness of the Internet
itself,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
