<HEADLINE>
DEMAND FOR TECHNOLOGY STOCKS PUSHES NASDAQ ABOVE 4,300  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Nasdaq composite index cruised to a record
Monday, as demand for technology and biotechnology stocks remained
strong.
</P>
<P>
   But the strength in technology masked another lackluster session
for most stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology and biotechnology are good and everything else is
blah,'' said William Meehan, chief market analyst at Cantor
Fitzgerald. ``The broader market is responding to interest rate
hikes by the Federal Reserve. There will be more of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by Cisco Systems and Intel, the Nasdaq closed at 4,321.77,
up 77.63, or 1.8 percent. It was the sixth straight advance for the
index and marked the first time it has closed above 4,300.
</P>
<P>
   However, weakness in blue-chip companies like General Electric
and Alcoa pulled down the Dow Jones industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow dropped 58.01, or 0.5 percent, to 10,905.79. Nine of its
30 components gained in price, while the remaining 21 fell. Strong
gains in Hewlett-Packard and Intel prevented the Dow from
sustaining what would have been a loss of well over 100 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index was little changed,
falling 0.13 point, to 1,424.24. But strength in technology and
biotechnology shares helped to bolster the Russell 2000 index of
small company stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell, which so far this year has done much better than
either the Dow or the S.&AMP; P. 500, gained 6.87, or 1.3 percent, to
532.39.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was brisk.
</P>
<P>
   More than 918 million shares changed hands on the New York Stock
Exchange. Volume on the Nasdaq stock market was 1.6 billion shares.
</P>
<P>
   The continued strength in demand for technology stocks is
surprising some analysts, who point to sky-high valuations
throughout the sector as well as a long _ and growing _ list of
stocks that are trading at bargain-basement levels.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, at least, it is not an argument that many
investors seem to want to hear, or heed.
</P>
<P>
   John Manley, an equity strategist at Salomon Smith Barney, just
returned from a trip to visit clients in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Italians want to be in this market, and they want to own
technology,'' he said. ``That is true throughout Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Much the same seems to be true in the American heartland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am having a hard time getting anyone to listen to anything
but technology,'' said Philip S. Dow, a managing director in equity
research at Dain Rauscher Wessels in Minneapolis. ``Our clients
want to be in the right stocks, and they want to be in the ones
that are moving.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, which is expected to issue its quarterly earnings
report after the market closes Tuesday, certainly qualifies as a
mover.
</P>
<P>
   The stock gained 4 1-16 Monday, closing at 125 3-16. From the
close of business on Jan. 28, the stock risen by more than 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among Dow stocks, General Electric shed 5 11-16, to 135~. Alcoa
fell 2 3-16, to 68 3-16. Boeing dropped 2 3-16, to 41 13-16.
</P>
<P>
   Those losses were mitigated by big gains in Hewlett-Packard,
which jumped 10], to 128], and in Intel, which gained 3 3-16, to
107 15-16.
</P>
<P>
   It was a very good day for biotechnology shares, which continued
their torrid rise.
</P>
<P>
   Among biotech companies, Amgen gained 4 9-16, to 69 3-16.
Genentech jumped 6{, to 150{. Human Genome rose 25 15-16, to 142
1-16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
