<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9636 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-AFGHAN-HIJACK-ART-950     02-07 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFGHAN-HIJACK-ART-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
8 MORE HOSTAGES RELEASED FROM AFGHAN PLANE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANSTED, England _ Day and night negotiations with gunmen who
seized an Afghan jet on a domestic flight and eventually ended up
in this suburban London airport succeeded Monday in gaining the
release of eight passengers and providing supplies for those still
trapped on board.
</P>
<P>
   The identity of the hijackers and the nature of their demands
remained unclear, though reports from the Middle East said their
purpose might be to liberate an Afghan fighter jailed by the
Islamic fundamentalist Taliban movement that now rules most of
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen hours into the negotiations here, the men had made no
political demands, said John Broughton, assistant chief constable
of the police in Essex County, where the airport is located.
</P>
<P>
   Three women, three men and two children left the plane by its
back steps, bringing the total of freed passengers to 27. The plane
had 186 people on board when it left the Afghan capital, Kabul,
early Sunday for an internal one-hour trip to the northern city of
Mazar-I-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
   Civil aviation authorities in Kabul told Reuters that all the
passengers were Afghans, including 35 members of one family.
</P>
<P>
   The British Foreign Office, however, said it was in touch with
the embassies of other unidentified nationalities, suggesting that
some non-Afghans might have been on the plane. Britain does not
have diplomatic relations with Afghanistan, and conducts relations
with the country through Britain's High Commission in Islamabad,
Pakistan, or through the United Nations in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban's supreme leader, Mullah Mohammad Omar, issued a
statement read by the movement's ambassador to Pakistan describing
the hijackers as terrorists and saying, ``We will not negotiate
with them. We will not accept their demands.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after takeoff at 12:30 a.m. Sunday, an estimated half
dozen armed men took control of the Afghan-state-owned Ariana
Airlines Boeing 727 and forced it to land in Tashkent, Uzbekistan,
where 10 passengers were let off. It flew on four hours later to
Aktyubinsk in Northern Kazakstan, where a fuel tank was repaired.
In Moscow, the commandeered airliner's next stop, for refueling,
nine riders were allowed off.
</P>
<P>
   On being advised shortly after midnight Monday morning that the
gunmen wanted to come to London, British authorities mobilized
specialized hijack crisis teams and directed the airliner to
Stansted Airport in Essex County, north of London, where it landed
and taxied to a secluded runway at 2 a.m. Prime Minister Tony Blair
had been awakened at 1 a.m. and told the aircraft was headed here,
and the Foreign Office had given its approval.
</P>
<P>
   Talks, aimed at calming nerves and described by airport
officials as ``fairly calm and businesslike,'' began immediately
upon the plane's arrival. John Broughton, the assistant chief
constable of the Essex police, coupled his midday announcement of
the passengers' release with a statement saying, ``We are at a very
critical stage in our negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Stansted, with a futuristic glass terminal designed by Britain's
leading architect, Sir Norman Foster, is the place designated by
security officials as the preferred location for dealing with
hijackings.
</P>
<P>
   It is less cluttered with traffic than London's two other
international airports, Gatwick and Heathrow; it offers a location
that is away from population centers, and police, military and
security personnel trained in terrorism diplomacy are close by.
</P>
<P>
   In the last such episode, in 1996, Stansted negotiators secured
the release of the crew and 197 passengers of a Sudanese Airbus
forcibly diverted here by six Iraqis on a flight from Khartoum,
Sudan's capital, to Amman, Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The Afghan plane's stop at Stansted was probably its last on
this journey, since British policy prohibits hijacked airliners
from taking to the air again. The Taliban government in Kabul urged
the British to storm the plane, but officials said that military
assault was not an option as long as lives were not in danger. They
said they would rely instead on the tactics of talking patiently,
establishing trust and exerting persuasion, approaches that have
earned Britain a reputation for ending hijacking episodes with no
bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban found themselves in the middle of a hijacking
episode when an Indian Airlines flight from Nepal to New Delhi was
commandeered by gunmen on Dec. 24 and eventually landed in
Afghanistan. After days of negotiations, in which the Taliban
declined to participate, India agreed to release three imprisoned
Kashmiri militants.
</P>
<P>
   The hijackers and freed militants were given 10 hours by the
Taliban to leave the country, but they have not been found and it
is not clear where they ultimately went.
</P>
<P>
   The hijackers in Britain on Monday allowed baby food, fresh
water, hot meals, medicines and unidentified medical equipment to
be sent to the blue-and-white plane, parked in an isolated area
next to a perimeter fence and a hangar at the edge of the airport,
nearly a mile from the terminal building. The area has been used
before for hostage episodes.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen asked for, and received, a generator for power and
air-conditioning and the delivery of food supplies to the jet.
``There have also been requests for tea bags, cans of soft drink
and other such things to make the passengers as comfortable as they
can be,'' said Charles Clark, deputy chief constable of the Essex
force.
</P>
<P>
   As night fell, Clark said, ``This clearly remains a very
sensitive and difficult situation. We are still working toward a
peaceful resolution, and that remains our primary aim. I understand
that the occupants of the plane are as comfortable as they possibly
can be.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Broughton, asked about the progress of the negotiations, said,
``It's positive, the fact that we are talking, that we are
continuing to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Rogers, a terrorism expert at the University of Bradford,
said the main goal of negotiators was to reduce tensions. The
hijackers, he said, are being told they have as much time as it
takes.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report from the Pakistan-based Afghan Islamic
Press that was not confirmed by British authorities, the hijackers
are demanding the release of Ismail Khan, 58, an Afghan opposition
figure who, though a war hero against the invading Russians a
decade ago, fell afoul of the Taliban, who now control 90 percent
of Afghanistan. He was jailed in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
