<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIR-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TIR NA N'OG': A SPAGHETTI WESTERN SET IN AN IRISH LEGEND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain, Ireland) (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.) (DW) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``That was so good,'' a little boy said the other day
after the end of ``Tir Na n'Og'' at the New Victory Theater here.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as if someone had told him, ``You could say that again,''
he repeated his assessment: ``That was so good.''
</P>
<P>
   He was so right.
</P>
<P>
   Playing only five more performances from Friday through Sunday,
this deeply sensitive and highly imaginative production combines
Irish legend with family drama in a feat of theater that puts to
shame many a more lavish show.
</P>
<P>
   The work of the Traveling Light Theater Co. from Britain, the
70-minute intermissionless ``Tir Na n'Og'' rides on the lofty
talents of three actors and two musicians as it translates to the
stage ``Into the West,'' the fine 1993 film directed by Mike Newell
(``Enchanted April'') and written by Jim Sheridan, the director of
``My Left Foot.''
</P>
<P>
   From a bit of pipe, this production conjures a great white
horse, the windows of a Dublin housing project, the screen of a
television. From thrusting arms and voices, it summons up the sea,
hurling itself against the cliffs of a rocky shore; a tree
reluctantly surrendering its berries; and the rush of traffic in
the streets of Dublin. From a pair of sunglasses and a hand
slapping against a thigh while an actor runs, it creates a
helicopter, searching the west of Ireland for two runaway children
and a horse born of legend and love.
</P>
<P>
   Here once again, with the three actors playing all the roles and
a fiddler and an accordionist accenting and underscoring the
exciting and emotional story, is the tale of the great white horse
of Irish lore that emerges from the sea and follows a grandfather
to Dublin. There it is taken in by Finn and Ally, his two poor,
motherless grandchildren living on the 14th floor in Dublin housing
project with their father, once the king of the Gypsy-like
Travelers, now an alcoholic, mourning the death in childbirth seven
years earlier of his beloved wife, Mary.
</P>
<P>
   When the police make off with the horse and rebuff the father's
efforts to buy it back, the children learn that it is about to be
entered in an international jumping championship. They steal it
back and set off for the west, pursued by the police and their
flawed but loving father. They are made notorious by television
news and newspaper headlines that say their capture is worthy of
reward, just as in one of the spaghetti westerns that ``Tir Na
n'Og'' recreates with its keen understanding and humorous eye for
engaging detail.
</P>
<P>
   Tir Na n'Og is not only the name of the horse but also, as
Grandpa explains as he relates the legend of the warrior king Oisin
and his love, the fairy princess Niamh, a land beneath the sea off
the western coast of Ireland, where summer is eternal, and no one
grows old.
</P>
<P>
   The gifted actors Craig Edwards as Finn, Cerianne Roberts as
Ally and David Annen as Pa and Grandpa also people the stage of the
New Victory with a gallery of vivid characters, like busybody
neighbors, tough police officers with their crackling radios and
dogs, and Dubliners assessing the children as they sing (``Danny
Boy'') and beg for money to feed their horse.
</P>
<P>
   The fine instrumentalists are the fiddler Fiona Barrow and the
accordionist Thomas Johnson, who composed with music. Greg Banks is
the director and adapter who seems not to have missed an
opportunity to invest every minute of ``Tir Na n'Og'' with
memorable life in bringing it to the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Even adults are likely to leave the New Victory Theater saying,
``That was so good.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TIR NA N'OG'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Traveling Light Theater Co. production. Directed by Greg
Banks; designer, Katie Sykes; composer and music director, Thomas
Johnson; lighting by Andy Shewan; production manager, Petrus
Bertschinger; company stage manager, Jo Woodcock; technical stage
manager, Martin Jady; producer, Jude Merrill. Presented by the New
42nd Street Inc. At the New Victory Theater in Manhattan.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Craig Edwards, David Annen, and Cerianne Roberts; Fiona
Barrow and Thomas Johnson, musicians.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 1953EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
