<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9643 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-BROWN-GEE-BOS &LR;      02-07 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-GEE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN UNIVERSITY PRESIDENT GOING TO VANDERBILT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   E. Gordon Gee, who has rattled Brown University in his two short
years as its president, shocked faculty and students on the Ivy
League campus Monday by announcing he was leaving to become
Chancellor of Vanderbilt University in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   A Mormon lawyer given to sporting bow-ties who had served as
head of three big public universities, Gee was considered the
breath of fresh air candidate when chosen in 1997. He scored points
in his interview by asking those who hired him the impertinent but
obvious question: why would an East Coast liberal bastion hire a
conservative Utah native as its president?
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, some suggested that Gee was too much fresh air,
especially in contrast to Vartan Gregorian, the academic's academic
who led Brown for a decade before.
</P>
<P>
   Gee took a more businesslike approach, announcing plans to
review all programs and eliminate ones that couldn't compete with
their peers on other top campuses. He angered faculty by announcing
programs like a $47 million initiative in brain science without
having it reviewed by key faculty committees. He sent alarms across
campus when three top administrators left within weeks of each
other last year.
</P>
<P>
   On campus in Providence, R.I. Monday, the reaction ranged from
anger and disappointment to relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was working on the fit issue, and everybody was working
with him,'' said Laura Freid, Executive Vice President for
University Relations. ``In the end, he felt he was going to be more
comfortable somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real strength of Brown is its empowered and opinionated
students, and empowered and opinionated faculty,'' Freid said. ``In
his other roles, he did much more external functions. He wasn't
used to the kind of intensity that can happen at a small
institution.''
</P>
<P>
   The average college presidency is a little more than seven
years, and usually longer at the nation's most elite schools. And
the 55-year old Gee gave no sign of leaving; less than a month ago,
his ``new'' role at Brown was featured as the cover story in the
Chronicle of Higher Education.
</P>
<P>
   A two-year presidency, said Judith McLaughlin, who runs the
seminar for new college presidents at the Harvard Graduate School
of Education, is ``unheard of,'' and often suggests the institution
and the individual were simply mismatched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would guess that was the case here,'' she said. ``I like
Gordron enormously, he's a very capable guy, but for him, Brown
represented a foreign culture, and for Brown he represented a
stranger. That kind of learning about each other that happens in
the first two years was taking place, it was a bit messier than one
would have hoped it might be. Given the chance to go somewhere that
was a better fit, I'm not surprised he would.''
</P>
<P>
   A college president at age 37, Gee was at Ohio State when he was
named to the Brown presidency in 1997, and had served as president
of the University of Colorado system and West Virginia University
before that. A lawyer, he did not have a PhD, and was part of
something of a trend in higher education to seek presidents with
non-academic backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Brown might have guessed his tenure would be short; Gee's
previous presidencies had been about 5 years each. As Freid said,
``He's not a marathon runner.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he arrived, Gee told reporters this was the last
university presidency he would take. And he appeared to have
success, raising $109 million during his first full year in office,
double what was raised in the previous two years. He adopted a
folksy style with students, often inviting them to dinner. And
arguing that a college president should be a public figure _ a role
neglected by many in recent years _ he chaired the committee to
choose the new superintendent for the Providence Public Schools.
</P>
<P>
   But he also made faculty suspicious with plans to revamp
graduate education and trim academic programs that weren't
successful. He argued that if the programs weren't the best in the
country, there was no use having them at Brown. But while this was
a move that might be expected under constraints of a state budget,
it was considered almost crass at a private school, and certainly
in the Ivy League.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Gee told reporters in Nashville that leaving Providence
was one of the most difficult decisions he has had to make, but
praised Vanderbilt as ``a special place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He simply met an opportunity and an excitement at Vanderbilt
that he couldn't resist,'' said Stanley Ikenberry, president of the
American Council on Education and a Gee friend.
</P>
<P>
   Gee plans to leave in April to take his new job in August,
replacing Joe Wyatt, who has been chancellor for 18 years. Brown
officials said an interim president will be named by April, and a
search committee by the end of February.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
