u e BC-TV-MITCHELL-BOS &LR;      02-07 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MITCHELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CNN'S MITCHELL TABBED TO TAKE HELM AT PBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pat Mitchell, a top executive at CNN who launched her television
career as an entertainment reporter in Boston, was named Monday the
first female president and chief executive officer of the Public
Broadcasting Service.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Mitchell, a highly respected producer whose
documentaries have won 41 Emmys and who most recently oversaw CNN's
24-hour ``Cold War'' series, was hailed as a step toward
revitalizing PBS's staid image in the face of increasing
competition from cable channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could not have done better,'' said a CNN political
analyst, Jeff Greenfield. ``PBS needs an infusion of energy and
drive and ability to get things from the conceptual stage to the
screen much faster. She's the type who can cut a lot of Gordian
knots.''
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Charren, a longtime TV activist and board member at
WGBH-TV (Channel 2), Boston's public television station, added:
``She has managed big systems, she has produced documentaries _
which is the product of PBS _ and she's produced news. And she's
always been a savvy dame.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday, Mitchell called the post the
``realization of a dream'' and vowed that PBS, under her
leadership, will ``find a stronger niche'' in the multichannel TV
universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``PBS has an opportunity to stand out even more,'' she said.
``We have a high mission here, and we're going to deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mitchell, 57, assumes the reins at a challenging time for
public broadcasting. The system has been whipsawed between charges
of commercialism on the one hand, and what PBS supporters see as
chronic underfunding by Congress on the other.
</P>
<P>
   A funding increase was thrown into temporary jeopardy last year
_ and longstanding charges of liberal bias at PBS were resurrected
on Capitol Hill _ when it was revealed that local stations,
including WGBH-TV (Channel 2), had shared donor lists with
political organizations, most of them Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell replaces Ervin S. Duggan, who resigned in September, on
the day that an inspector general released a 31-page report about
the list-swapping practice. PBS officials have maintained that
Duggan's resignation was not related to the flap.
</P>
<P>
   However, that controversy tarnished the PBS image, and it
occurred in the context of tensions between PBS and member stations
over programming control and the direction of public broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very serious problems between the stations and
PBS,'' said a former PBS president, Lawrence Grossman. ``It's a
daunting undertaking she's got to deal with, both internally and
externally.''
</P>
<P>
   When she takes over on March 1 as the fifth PBS president in the
system's 31-year history, Mitchell will be in overall charge of 346
public TV stations. The initial response from some of those PBS
stations was positive Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Abbott, general manager at Channel 2, said Mitchell is
well-equipped to lead PBS because of her documentary background and
because she comes to public broadcasting from ``the cable
universe'' _ the source of much PBS competition.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's resume is notable for the array of on- and off-screen
positions she has held. From 1972 to 1977, she was an arts and
entertainment reporter at WBZ-TV (Channel 4), where she also
coanchored the 5:30 p.m. news, produced a political program, and
hosted a daily talk show called ``Woman '75.''
</P>
<P>
   Channel 4 anchor Jack Williams, who was briefly teamed with
Mitchell on an early-evening newscast, recalled her as smart,
fun-loving, and ``one of these people you have to be careful not to
underestimate.''
</P>
<P>
   NECN anchor Tom Ellis, who anchored the news at Channel 4 when
Mitchell worked there, described her as ``a perpetual-motion
machine'' and said it was always ``pretty clear she had abilities
above and beyond doing features on the 6 and 11 o'clock
newscasts.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell left Boston in 1977 for an interview show at WTTG-TV in
Washington. Over the next several years, she hosted several local
and syndicated talk shows, including ``Hour Magazine,'' and also
was a correspondent and substitute anchor on NBC's ``Today'' show
as well as an arts reporter on CBS's ``Sunday Morning.'' In 1983,
she formed her own production company and began hosting ``Woman to
Woman,'' a syndicated talk show.
</P>
<P>
   But her attention was increasingly devoted to producing. After
several years of developing documentaries and specials, Mitchell
joined Turner Broadcasting Inc. in 1992, and soon was in charge of
producing nonfiction programs for TBS and TNT, including
prizewinning documentaries such as ``A Century of Women.'' In 1997,
Mitchell was named president of CNN Productions and Time Inc.
Television.
</P>
<P>
   It was CNN founder Ted Turner who asked Mitchell to serve as
co-executive producer of ``Cold War,'' a job that consumed her
energies for four years.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday, Mitchell said she told Turner last
Monday that she might soon be put in charge of PBS. Turner's
response, according to Mitchell, was: ``You mean the whole thing?''
</P>
<P>
   Though she left Boston professionally more than two decades ago,
Mitchell retains some local roots: She sits on the advisory board
of Radcliffe's Schlesinger Library on the History of Women, and is
a member of the Women's Leadership Advisory Council of the John F.
Kennedy School of Government at Harvard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
