<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KANA-SILKNET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE FIRMS IN $3.9 BILLION MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Silknet Software Inc. of Manchester, N.H., has
agreed to be acquired by Kana Communications Inc., a California
software company, for $3.9 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, the latest in a wave of mergers and acquisitions to
sweep through the world of Internet commerce, is notable because it
involves two tiny companies that have less than $90 million in
combined annual revenue but have nevertheless ignited the stock
market's fancy for companies that sell so-called e-commerce
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Silknet, founded in 1995, sells software that lets companies
manage communications with their customers regardless of whether an
exchange took place via e-mail, on a Web site, by telephone, or in
person. Silknet clients, for example, use the company's software to
let customers track orders over the Internet, receive support over
the phone, or get marketing materials in an e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Kana, based in Redwood City, Calif., is in the business of
helping companies such as eBay Inc. and Ford Motor Co. manage large
volumes of e-mail to and from customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds preposterous, but the vast majority of companies on
the Internet have no idea who their customers are, what they're
buying, and whether they would be likely to return and buy
something else,'' said George Godfrey, director of research at ING
Barings in New York City.``Silknet and Kana look to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Together, the two companies are gearing up for a battle with
market leader, Siebel Systems Inc. in San Mateo, Calif., whose
annual revenue of $791 million is nearly 10 times that of Silknet
and Kana combined, but whose market capitalization of $19.4 billion
is just twice that of the two upstarts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the case of the Internet mouse that roared,'' said Bob
Chatham, senior analyst at Forrester Research Inc. in Cambridge,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the mouse needs to get larger in order to survive
in the field of customer relations management, Chatham said.
Companies interact with customers via phone, Internet, mail, and in
person to market, sell, and provide support.Few firms have been
able to master all those fronts, he said. Monday's deal combines
Kana's expertise with Internet-based exchanges and Silknet's
strength in phone-based communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about getting big,'' said Dave Fowler, vice president of
marketing for Silknet. ``In this game, you have to get big or go
home. In order to double through normal growth, we would have had
to find 250 new people to hire into our organization. Instead,
we've instantly doubled our size without the pain of having to go
out and recruit those people.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger, which is expected to be completed by the end of
June, will produce a company with 600 employees and 450 customers,
including ETrade, William-Sonoma, and Microsoft. More than 175
employees, primarily Silknet workers, will be based in New England.
The companies have no plans for layoffs or for moving any of their
operations, said Mark Gainey, president and cofounder of Kana.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, the opposite is true. We plan to aggressively grow
our presence,'' Gainey said. ``We're very excited to be in New
England.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Silknet, which is 18 percent owned by venture capital
company CMGI Inc. of Andover, Mass., have surged more than 12-fold
since its debut on the Nasdaq May 4 at 15. Kana, which also went
public at 15 a share on Sept. 21, has swelled 16-fold.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Silknet shares rose 44 13/16 on the Nasdaq market to
close at 183 5/16; Kana's stock fell 18 3/8 on the Nasdaq to 240
1/2.
</P>
<P>
   These sky-high valuations help boost the dollar value of Kana's
$3.9 billion acquisition of Silknet. The transaction is based on a
stock swap, in which Kana is expected to issue 16.4 million shares
of its stock, valued at $4.2 billion, to acquire Silknet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors have been paying a premium price for Internet
companies, and this is just a reflection of that,'' Godfrey said.
``That's why only Internet companies are the only ones that can
afford to buy other Internet companies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
