<HEADER>
A9651 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-POLICE-SHOOTING-BOS &LR;      02-07 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-SHOOTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI LOOKING AT SLAYING OF PROVIDENCE POLICE SERGEANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ In moves that significantly widen the probe
into the slaying of police Sergeant Cornel Young Jr., the Federal
Bureau of Investigation entered the case Monday, and the Rhode
Island attorney general has asked for an independent panel to study
ways to prevent similar deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Barry W. Mawn, special agent in charge of the FBI's Boston
office, said his office has opened a ``preliminary inquiry'' into
possible civil rights violations in Young's death. The FBI, he
said, will ``follow and review'' the separate investigation by the
Rhode Island attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI will not interview witnesses at this time, Mawn said;
however, if the probe leads to prosecution, the FBI would turn the
case over to the US attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, Attorney General Sheldon Whitehouse announced that
he will appoint nine law officers as special agents to assist a
grand jury conducting an inquiry of the case here.
</P>
<P>
   Those agents, including six officers from the Providence Police
Department, will investigate Jan. 28 fracas which led two
Providence officers to open fire on Young after mistaking him for
an armed suspect.
</P>
<P>
   In the the first-ever use of such resources in Rhode Island, the
agents will compile, review, and present evidence for the grand
jury. Bound by secrecy, they will answer directly to Whitehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Young, the son of the highest-ranking black officer on the
Providence police force, was off-duty but drew his weapon and
rushed to aid two officers confronting an allegedly armed man
outside an all-night restaurant. Minority activists have questioned
whether the officers, Carlos A. Saraiva and Michael Solitro III,
instantly assumed Young was a suspect because he was black.
</P>
<P>
   Police have not identified the races of Saraiva or Solitro.
</P>
<P>
   In a shift, Whitehouse now says that he supports pending
legislation that would require State Police to compile statistics
on traffic stops that could show whether troopers
disproportionately target minority motorists.
</P>
<P>
   His concerns that such a study might create divisions,
Whitehouse said, have become secondary to a greater need to build
trust between minorities and police.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the attorney general had backed a voluntary plan
that would identify and decrease racial profiling as well as
encourage recruitment of more minority police officers throughout
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehouse, however, rejected calls to recuse himself from the
investigation; some black clergy and activists demanded that he
step down to guarantee investigative independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view, it is particularly important that the course and
administration of justice not be influenced by public ultimatums,
however well-intentioned,'' Whitehouse said.
</P>
<P>
   Aldrin Diaz of Providence, who police allege had brandished a
pistol at the scene, has been charged with felony murder in Young's
death for provoking the incident, even though he obeyed commands
and dropped his gun before Young was shot.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford R. Montiero, president of the Providence chapter of the
NAACP, said he will convene an emergency meeting of the group's
executive board to study the new investigative plan.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, the Rhode Island Minority Police
Association unveiled several demands it has presented to Police
Chief Urbano Prignano Jr. and the police union.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that the ``majority of police officers
respect and serve our communities with great pride,'' Providence
police Sergeant Tonya King, association president, said the
department must admit it has ``racist individual officers'' and
that racial profiling _ assigning greater criminal suspicion based
on race _ exists among its ranks.
</P>
<P>
   That demand, she said, is intended to create a mechanism to
purge Rhode Island police departments of racist officers, closely
screen recruits and educate officers on cultural diversity.
</P>
<P>
   King said that Prignano and the executive board of the Fraternal
Order of Police have agreed to address these demands, which were
endorsed by Young's parents, Providence Major Cornel Young Sr. and
Leisa Young. Providence Police spokesman Major Martin Hames, could
not be reached for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The officers who shot Young, Carlos A. Saraiva and Michael
Solitro III, have been placed on paid leave. Whitehouse urged that
the public not prejudge the men.
</P>
<P>
   ``The processes of law enforcement have been honed by history to
protect the rights of defendants, and should not be set aside
lightly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both King and Leisa Young urged activists to have patience with
the investigation. Last week, 300 demonstrators rocked City Hall,
heckled Mayor Vincent A. Cianci Jr. and demanded Saraiva and
Solitro turn in their badges.
</P>
<P>
   The protests, however, have prompted several threatening calls
against activists and minority organizations.
</P>
<P>
   King said a black officer at the police academy got an anonymous
call: ``You're next.'' When minority officers tried to file a
complaint, King said, they were greeted with ``hostility'' at the
Providence Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   King added that the complaint was withdrawn initially because
the association did not believe it would be handled properly.
Prignano has been made aware of the threat, she said, and a probe
is under way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2001EST &QL; 
