<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-NEWENGLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.E. FISHERMEN SLATED FOR $38M IN AID IN CLINTON BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New England fishermen would get a $38 million aid
package to ease the burden of federal restrictions on local
fisheries under President Clinton's 2001 budget proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The package includes $12 million for a ``cooperative
management'' program to hire fishermen for industry-related
research. The idea is to help struggling fishermen with jobs while
also giving them more of a say in fisheries management by involving
them in the research, according to aides to Senator Edward M.
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Another $7 million would go for job training and counseling for
those fishermen needing to find new work; $10 million would be
available for a vessel buy-back program and other emergency aid for
fishermen. There would be $2.5 million on hand to help fishing
communities make infrastructure repairs, and $6.6 million in
low-interest loans so fishermen could refit their boats.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the country has been buoyed by the nation's record
economic growth, New England fishermen have been hard hit by
federal rules restricting fishing in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1996 Sustainable Fisheries Act, New England fishermen
were drastically restricted in the number of hours they could fish.
The law was a response to record low levels of fish in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Some fishermen are finding it virtually impossible to make a
living under those restrictions, and entire communities have been
affected by the conservation law.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry said he was very pleased by the inclusion
of the aid in Clinton's budget _ an item members of the New England
congressional delegation had fought hard to get. But getting the
aid passed by the Republican-controlled Congress will be a fight,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts and the region generally did well under the
Clinton budget, members of the congressional delegation said. While
there may have been a few cases in which senators and
representatives had gotten less money than they asked for
particular programs, the White House generally accommodated New
England concerns, aides to members of Congress said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy had lobbied hard for catastrophic coverage of
prescription drugs and got the item included in the budget, aides
in his office said.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts defense companies may also get a chunk of defense
contracts; the budget calls for 42 Hornet fighter planes, at a cost
of $3 billion. The engines for those planes are made by General
Electric Co.'s Aircraft Engine Division, based in Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   Other regional projects included in the fiscal 2001 budget are:
</P>
<P>
   --$33 million to continue construction of the South Boston Piers
Transitway, an underground bus tunnel linking South Station and the
South Boston Piers area.
</P>
<P>
   --$75 million for the YouthBuild program to help disadvantaged
youth find jobs and affordable housing.
</P>
<P>
   --Nearly $10 million for rehabilitation and preservation of
various historic sites and national recreation areas, including $1
million to complete the rehabilitation of the St. Joseph's Polish
Club in Salem, Mass., and $3,253,000 for the Cape Cod National
Seashore.
</P>
<P>
   --$350,000 for the University of Massachusetts at Dartmouth to
improve weed and pest control of cranberry crops. Cranberries are
the state's number one agricultural crop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
