<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Monday, Feb. 07, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Editors &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the following for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BUDGET (Washington) _ President Clinton sends Congress a
$1.84 trillion spending plan for 2001, the opening salvo in an
election-year battle over cutting taxes, reducing debt and health
care. Congressional Republicans quickly denounce Clinton's proposal
as a ``fantasy budget.'' By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   NASA-BUDGET (Washington) _ President Clinton asks Congress to
set aside nearly $14 billion for the nation's space agency in the
2001 budget. While the proposal would increase NASA's annual
budget, it still would leave the agency short of the $14.4 billion
it received in 1997. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-SAN-FRANCISCO (Washington, D.C.) _ A look at what
President Clinton's $1.8 trillion budget contains for the San
Francisco Bay area. By JUDY HOLLAND and DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-McCAIN (Washington) _ Unveiling his retooled campaign
message, George W. Bush calls himself a ``reformer with results''
and accuses John McCain of not living up to his self-styled image
as a political outsider. ``If you're tired of no results and
simple, empty rhetoric, if you're tired of people saying one thing
and doing another, come join my team,'' Bush said as aides promised
a daily assault on McCain's centerpiece issue: political reform. By
JOHN GONZALEZ and GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-RACE (Undated) _ When Ryan Graham of Tallahassee, Fla.,
testified before a congressional subcommittee at age 12, one of the
committee members belittled him for declaring himself multiracial
instead of black. Three years later, the teen is celebrating as a
personal victory that the 2000 Census will allow people to identify
themselves as a combination of races. But many people worry how
government agencies will tally these new combinations, decisions
that could affect everything from the drawing of congressional
boundaries to funding programs earmarked for minorities. By KIM
COBB. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Houston) _ The blur of tears and phone calls to
family, friends and funeral homes can make the first 48 hours after
a loved one dies seem surreal. Not only do people grieve for the
deceased, they worry about the mundane and the immense. Who will
sing at the funeral? How will all the bills be paid? By preparing a
will, your family should be able to get a full accounting of your
finances within the first couple of days of your death to properly
wrap up your affairs. By SHANNON BUGGS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Republican Sen. John McCain's hero
is President Theodore Roosevelt, that ``damned cowboy'' who recast
the Republican Party in his own irrepressible image, challenged the
big monopolies, built the Panama Canal and used his ``bully
pulpit'' to great effect. Could McCain be the next TR? By MARIANNE
MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Nashua, N.H.) _ It was obvious last week _ and
not just because of the snow and single-digit temperatures _ that
George W. Bush wasn't in Texas anymore. He wasn't even in Iowa.
There were too many mountains, too many trees and too much of John
McCain. By CLAY ROBISON. (Already filed.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
