<SLUG> BC-FASHION-TUECARD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fall-Winter 2000 shows
 &HT;    Girl power runs amok on catwalk
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More and more it seems as if Fashion Week is governed
by females who are barely old enough to vote.
</P>
<P>
   They are the headset-wearing guardians at the gates to the
runway shows; the groupies whose gate-crashing techniques cause
every show to start 30 minutes later than scheduled; ``interns''
for the deputy assistant market editor at (take your pick) magazine
and the roommates of the headset-wearing gate guardians.
</P>
<P>
   Girls rule. Who cares if they can't vote as long as they can
spend. That's why _ for the sixth straight year _ Monday's ``Girls
Rule!'' presentation of five up-and-coming brands was one of the
hottest invitations in town. Among girls, at least.
</P>
<P>
   The event is sponsored by Teen magazine, if that tells you
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Roaste Chuck's was my favorite of the five short shows. At one
point, a model stripped (clumsily) down to her sheer, floral-print
pantyhose to prove the inside-out wearability of Roaste Chuck
jeans. The brand's design chief, Toshi Hosogai, has nearly
perfected the most consumer-conscious of concepts: two stylish
garments for the price of one. His designs made some of the other
brands look amateurish (T-shirt sleeves as bras) at worst, and
contrived (Velcro skateboarding skirts) at best.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
