<HEADER>
A9664 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FASHION-SHOW-COX     02-07 0328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-SHOW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A report on fall-winter clothes
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The decidely dressy fall/winter 2000 designs that
Carolina Herrera previewed Monday under the big tent at Bryant Park
drew mixed reviews. That's noteworthy because Herrera's shows
usually draw unanimous approval from Central Park socialites,
cynical fashion critics and sassy ``downtown'' girls alike.
</P>
<P>
   The glitz and glamour typical of Herrera's collections were all
there: Mink was shown prominently, as was drop-dead beading and
embroidery. Still, some in the standing-room-only crowd left
feeling something was missing.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Hart, the critic who appears rather regularly with Herrera
on E! Network programs such as ``Fashion Emergency'' raved.
Predictably. But Kaye Davis, fashion director for Atlanta's apparel
mart (AmericasMart) did not.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said she thought there wasn't enough color: 32 of the 49
outfits were either black, tan or gray. But Hart contended, ``I
promise you, they'll be available in more colors. (Herrera's)
Latin, like me. She loves color.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said Herrera's fur coats and jackets _ in vertical or
chevron stripes in contrasting shades of mink and sable _ looked
somewhat dated. Hart: ``Once again she's made beautiful clothes for
women who want to look and feel beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the looks shown reach the stores next fall, the jury will
remain out. Determining factors will be whether or not women like
tight, shiny blouses; slinky leather pantsuits in colors like
shocking pink and flaming orange; low-slung pants that hug the legs
all the way down to the front-slit ankles; tailored jackets cropped
just above the derriere; and backless halters and dresses with long
scarves trailing from the hips, neck or shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
