<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9665 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-CLINTON-BUDGET-BOS &LR;      02-07 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OFFERS FAR-REACHING $1.8 TRILLION FEDERAL BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Looking decades beyond his administration and to
the presidential campaign at hand, President Clinton Monday sent
Congress the final budget of his final term: a $1.84 trillion
spending plan that aims to give tax breaks to some families, help
seniors pay for prescription drugs and yet wipe out all publicly
held federal debt by 2013.
</P>
<P>
   The budget, for the year that starts Oct. 1, includes a variety
of proposals already rejected by Congress. Republicans denounced it
as a political document designed to boost Vice President Al Gore's
bid for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Clinton's plan is sure to help shape the budget
debate in a year when spending proposals and politics are tightly
entwined. Democrats are already promoting Clinton's tax breaks for
child care, ill seniors and the college-bound _ ideas they believe
will win favor with voters _ while Republicans say Clinton's
rejection of a larger tax cut is a key reason to elect GOP
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin optional trim) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The president's plan offers mixed news for New England. With
many local hospitals and nursing homes already losing money, he
would reduce payments to health providers to shore up the finances
of Medicare. The president would cut Medicare payments to the
providers by nearly the same amount Congress recently added to the
program to help them, industry groups said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would essentially undo a good portion of the hard work
that our congressional delegation fought for last fall,'' said Judy
Glasser of the Massachusetts Hospital Association.
</P>
<P>
   The budget proposal does include a one-year boost for children's
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton plan would significantly increase engineering and
medical research, a likely gain for New England university and
hospital labs. It would send money to troubled New England fishing
communities. It does not change the financial picture for the Big
Dig, which was funded in a six-year plan that Congress approved
1998.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end optional trim) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The budget and explanatory notes _ all 2,700 pages _ can be
viewed on the Internet at www.gpo.gov/usbudget.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a balanced budget with a balanced approach to our
national priorities,'' Clinton said Monday. ``It maintains our
fiscal discipline, pays down the debt, extends the life of Social
Security and Medicare and invests in our families and our future.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans said there was no way Clinton could do all that
while putting more money into his favorite spending programs.
Discretionary spending, or money spent outside of Social Security
and Medicare, would rise 3.9 percent over 2000 levels, or about 1
percentage point more than inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's budget is a paradox. How can we pay down the
debt with a budget that substantially expands the size and scope of
the federal government?'' asked House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert,
Republican of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also said many of Clinton's spending proposals were
aimed at traditional Democratic constituencies, and therefore at
Democratic hopes in the fall elections. The White House summary of
the budget, in fact, calls it a ``Clinton-Gore'' document.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to working with the president in putting
together a serious spending proposal,'' said Senate Budget
Committee Chairman Pete Domenici, Republican of New Mexico. ``But
this is a document designed to help Al Gore win election.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has all things for everyone they feel they'll need to get
Al Gore elected president,'' said Representative John Kasich, the
Ohio Republican who is chairman of the House Budget Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the budget proposal is remarkable as the opening salvo in
a fight that was wholly unanticipated only a few years ago _ a
battle over how to spend billions of dollars in federal budget
surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton anticipates that the government will raise $746 billion
in surplus revenues over 10 years from sources other than the
Social Security payroll tax, far less than projected by
congressional budget-writers. He would devote more than half of
that to shoring up Medicaid over the next decade and adding a new
prescription drug benefit to the program, which would be even more
generous than in previous White House proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the remainder of the surplus would go to a range of
social spending plans, such as improved access to health insurance
for low-income people. Clinton also proposes $350 billion over 10
years in tax breaks for certain people saving for retirement or
paying college tuition, long-term health care costs or child care
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cuts would be paid for in part by ending tax
``loopholes'' that Clinton says are worth $96 billion over 10
years. They include new rules for people who renounce US
citizenship in order to avoid federal taxes. The administration is
also counting on $66 billion from a 25-cents-per-pack increase in
cigarette taxes and new penalties on tobacco companies that do not
reduce youth smoking. That proposal faces uncertain prospects in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated $2 trillion in surpluses from the Social Security
program over the next decade would be used to pay down the national
debt, and all $3.7 trillion in debt held by the public would be
gone by 2013, Clinton said. The remaining $2 trillion in national
debt is money the government owes to its own programs, such as
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the gains from paying off the debt, such as lower
debt service costs, would be transfered to the Social Security
program to improve its financial position.
</P>
<P>
   While growing in total dollars, the federal budget has been
shrinking during Clinton's term as a percentage of the US economy _
from 22 percent when he took office to 18.3 percent today. It would
fall to 16.7 percent by 2010 under his new plan, said Robert
Reischauer, president of the Urban Institute, a Washington think
tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a level we haven't seen since the Eisenhower
administration, to periods before we had Medicare, Medicaid, food
stamps and the student loan program,'' Reischauer said. ``It shows
a strong economy can trump a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Concord Coalition, a budget watchdog group, criticized
Clinton for using federal surpluses that might not materialize to
fund his proposed tax cuts and prescription drug benefit. The group
says no permanent spending plan, including Republican tax cut
proposals, should be built on tentative projections of a surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's nice to be talking about surpluses, rather than
deficits,'' said Robert Bixby, executive director of the group.
``These are nice problems to have.''
</P>
<P>
   With less than a year left in office, Clinton budget officials
argued that they nonetheless can lay the groundwork for spending
priorities well into the future. Using surpluses to pay down the
federal debt is so popular, for example, ``that if you lock it in
now with legislation, it will be politically difficult in five
years or 10 years to change that,'' said Gene Sperling, a senior
economic adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The budget proposes the largest-ever dollar increase for the
National Science Foundation, which would boost engineering and
physical science research at a time when Congress has already given
record increases to medical research budgets. The NSF would get a
boost of $675 million, or 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton would also add $1 billion, or about 5.7 percent, to the
annual medical research budget at the National Institutes of
Health. That amount is well below what is needed to meet Congress's
general goal of doubling the NIH budget over five years, but
Clinton has traditionally offered a small increase to the NIH with
the expectation that lawmakers will approve more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2012EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9666 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MITCHELL-PROFILE08     02-07 1440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MITCHELL-PROFILE08 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Many challenges await Mitchell as PBS president
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Pat Mitchell told her boss, Ted Turner, that
she was on the verge of being named president of the Public
Broadcasting Service, his response was, ``You mean the whole
thing?''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Mitchell, a native of Statesboro and former president
of CNN Productions, was officially named the new president and
chief executive officer of PBS. The whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is going to be terrific. She `gets it,''' said Sharon
Percy Rockefeller, a member of the search committee that
recommended Mitchell to the PBS board of directors. The board
unanimously approved her on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``As PBS enters its third decade and I enter my third act, this
is simply going to be the biggest, best time ever for PBS,''
Mitchell said Monday at the National Press Club. She will be the
fifth president of PBS in 30 years and its first female CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, 57, comes to PBS after a varied career that has
included hosting her own syndicated talk show, substituting for
Jane Pauley on the ``Today'' show and making independent
documentaries. Since 1992 she has run CNN Productions (formerly
Turner Productions), and she served as co-producer of the
award-winning 24-hour series ``The Cold War.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mitchell's steady stream of accomplishments was somewhat
undercut last year when Turner announced that she would be
president of a new cable channel called the Women's Network, then
canceled the network after Mitchell had started hiring a staff. The
reason: Turner didn't think it could be profitable. Many at
Turner's networks feel that Mitchell was treated poorly in the very
public announcement and cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disappointed, (but) I didn't for one second take
any of this personally,'' Mitchell said Monday. ``I don't think it
was the right decision to make, but I understood why they made the
decision.'' She said the scuttling of the project had nothing to do
with her decision to go to PBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am genuinely disappointed to lose her from CNN, but I'm also
equally enthusiastic and proud. I think she will be an even
stronger leader of PBS because of her Turner years,'' said Tom
Johnson, chairman and CEO of the CNN NewsGroup, who first met
Mitchell at the University of Georgia when they were students there
in the early '60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many producers are brilliant but terrible to work with,''
Johnson said. ``In the case of Pat, she's caring, she's funny,
she's got a great spirit. No sharp elbows, no BS.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell will take over March 1 at PBS' headquarters in
Alexandria, Va. But she said she will commute to and from Atlanta,
where she has a home in Morningside and a steady companion,
businessman Scott Seydel, and where she will continue to serve on
the boards of the High Museum of Art and the Atlanta Metro YMCA.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell acknowledged she's taking a big pay cut moving from CNN
to PBS. ``I didn't even hesitate,'' she said. ``I just accepted
that as part of the package.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's a lot more to the package. The president of PBS
faces several challenges, some of them unique to the job. Among the
major situations Mitchell faces:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Declining viewership. PBS' national audience has been dropping
about 2 percent a year for the past few years. That's not as much
as networks like CBS and Fox have seen, but it's not a good sign.
And while the total amount of money pledged by viewers has held
constant, the number of people making pledges has dropped. Public
radio, meanwhile, which operates similarly to public television,
hasn't seen these dropoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to reverse these trend lines before they become
serious erosion,'' said Robert Coonrod, president and CEO of the
Corporation for Public Broadcasting, the funding arm of public
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we need to do is remind the audience of the genres
at which we excel,'' Mitchell said Monday. ``Perhaps we could do a
better job of getting that message out, making that known to our
viewers, bringing them back.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A difficult structure. The president of PBS is not nearly as
powerful as the president of, say, NBC. Mitchell has to share a lot
of her power with the 346 PBS stations around the country, and with
the CPB, which controls the purse strings. Public television at the
national level is known for its cumbersome bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's slow in its decision-making,'' said documentarian Ken
Burns (``The Civil War''), arguably the poster boy of PBS. ``You
have many constituencies, and some stations are more powerful than
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said she wants to streamline the process of approving
which shows will air at PBS, called green-lighting. ``It's to
everyone's advantage to make the green-lighting process more
efficient,'' she said. In his recent book ``The Vanishing Vision:
The Inside Story of Public Television,'' James Day, former
president of WNET in New York, called PBS ``an institution of
enormous promise mired in a self-created bureaucracy. Its human and
economic resources are thinly spread over a highly fragmented
system, its national leadership is divided and largely impotent.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's challenge will be to provide strong leadership and
unite the sometimes quarrelsome factions within public television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat is known for her skills of working with people,'' said
CNN's Johnson. ``She can work with just about anybody.'' Colin
Campbell, chairman of the PBS board of directors, said she was
hired in part for her ``major diplomatic and consensus-building
skills.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Conversion to digital. All PBS stations have to convert to a
digital signal within six years, as do all other TV stations.
``It's an awesome challenge,'' said the CPB's Coonrod. PBS
estimates it will cost $1.8 billion for all of its stations to
convert, which is more than the $1.5 billion in total revenue all
346 stations take in annually. Obviously, there will have to be
government funding of the conversion, at a combination of federal,
state and local levels. Just as obviously, getting that money will
be an enormous task. (President Clinton's 2001 budget is asking
Congress for $393 million for digital conversion.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Encroaching commercialism. Not only do the pledge drives
irritate viewers, but the underwriting announcements that begin
most programs are looking more and more like regular TV ads. ``I'm
concerned about the extent to which corporate underwriting becomes
so central to programming,'' said William Hoynes, who teaches mass
media and society at Vassar College. ``Increasingly, PBS has moved
down the path of a more commercially driven market model.
Ultimately, this will be a failed strategy that will backfire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know these messages are essential,'' Mitchell said.
``As a producer, it feels a lot better to have a message at the
beginning and end of a program than to have it interrupted six or
seven times for commercials.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Competition from cable. Critics of PBS frequently say that
various cable channels fill needs that were once met only by PBS:
Programming about nature on Discovery and Animal Planet,
documentaries on the History Channel, quality British imports on
A&AMP;E, fine arts on Bravo, information in general on CNN and C-SPAN.
</P>
<P>
   PBS counters that cable is available only in about 75 percent of
American homes, and its mission is to serve everyone. ``There's a
difference between history programming on the History Channel and
history programming on PBS,'' Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The X factor. Also called ``It's always something.'' In the
mid-'90s, Congressional Republicans tried to end all federal
funding of PBS. Shortly after that, there was a wave of questioning
the need for PBS. Every couple of years, PBS airs a program that
generates heated controversy; last year, the Rev. Jerry Falwell
charged that one of the Teletubbies was gay.
</P>
<P>
   Also last year, several PBS stations were heavily criticized for
sharing their donor lists with political parties.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows where Mitchell will need to practice damage control
next. But something will happen.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of difficulties facing Mitchell as she takes over
the reins of PBS. The institution is no longer as simple as the
definition that was offered in jest by Robert MacNeil, former
anchor of ``The MacNeil-Lehrer Newshour,'' who once called PBS:
``English people talking and animals mating, occasionally
interrupted by English people mating and animals talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2012EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9667 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-BUDGET-SAN-FRANCISCO-     02-07 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SAN-FRANCISCO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     S.F. AND CALIF. WOULD GAIN UNDER CLINTON BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN and JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ San Francisco would get significant boosts in
housing and community development funds from President Clinton's
$1.84 trillion budget for fiscal 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, anxious to please California, a must-win state for
Democrats in this election year, also laced his plan with large
spending jumps in education, housing and the environment for the
state. And he proposed a hefty 8.4 percent raise nationally in
funds to combat HIV and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is seeking $9.2 billion in HIV-AIDS funding, a $716
million increase from this year's' spending level.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $9.2 billion, the National Institutes of Health would get
$2.1 billion for AIDS research, an increase of 5.2 percent. In
addition, Clinton proposed $100 million for AIDS prevention, care
and education in Africa and Asia, parts of which have been
devastated by the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., called the budget's HIV-AIDS
spending hike a ``reasonable start.'' But she added, ``We must
fight for funding above the administration's request, especially in
the AIDS Drugs Assistance Program, which provides lifesaving drugs
to people with HIV who cannot afford to pay for the drugs on their
own.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's budget for the Department of Housing and Urban
Development budget nationally includes 120,000 new housing
vouchers, a $690 million rent subsidy aimed at helping the poor,
the homeless and those going from welfare to work find housing in
increasingly tight rental markets. California is earmarked for
17,730 of those vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   The budget directs 458 of the vouchers _ valued at $5.3 million
_ to San Francisco, according to HUD calculations.
</P>
<P>
   Also proposed for San Francisco is:
</P>
<P>
   _ $9.7 million for housing for people with AIDS, up from $8.7
million this year.
</P>
<P>
   _ $7.6 million for homeless assistance, up from $6.9 million
this year.
</P>
<P>
   _ $10.3 million for the local public housing authority, up
slightly from $10.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ $26.3 million in Community Development Block Grants, aimed at
spurring economic development through improvements in commercial
downtown areas, old industrial areas and residential neighborhoods.
Last year, San Francisco received $24.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Proposed for the greater Bay Area is:
</P>
<P>
   _ $80 million to expand the Bay Area Rapid Transit System to the
San Francisco International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   _ $60 million for the California Bay-Delta Watershed.
</P>
<P>
   _ $23.4 million for the Presidio as the former Army post
continues its conversion into a national park.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget, unveiled Monday, would boost California's Head
Start funding for disadvantaged pre-schoolers to $772.8 million, an
increase of $136.1 million over last year.
</P>
<P>
   The president's effort to hire 100,000 teachers around the
nation to reduce class size in the early grades _ a centerpiece of
his education legacy _ earmarks $206.5 million for California, a
$140 million increase.
</P>
<P>
   A new program to recruit, train and reward good teachers would
channel $81.2 million into the state.
</P>
<P>
   California child-care programs for low-income parents, including
those leaving welfare rolls for work, would receive $243.8 million
from Washington, a $100.1 million increase.
</P>
<P>
   The president also proposed spending $54.1 million _ an $8
million rise _ on care of the severely mentally ill in California.
</P>
<P>
   On environmental issues, the budget would give the state $38.7
million to buy natural and historic sites within its borders.
</P>
<P>
   The budget would also pump $84.6 million into a revolving fund
for California drinking water, an increase of $632,300 increase
from last year. The money enables the state to float low-interest
loans to local water systems for so-called ``infrastructural
improvements.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Clinton's proposed $825 million nationally for the
clean water fund, Rep. Ellen Tauscher, D-Calif., said she was
``thoroughly disappointed'' that he had slashed that fund by $550
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned that waste water treatment facilities in our
area may not have the money to properly clean water that they put
back into the delta,'' Tauscher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we fought to restore funding of the clean water
fund to $1.35 billion. This year, I will try to increase that
appropriation as well as push my own bill to finally reauthorize
the clean water fund for the next five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein hailed the president's overall plan as ``a
fiscally prudent, balanced budget.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It sets out a solid blueprint for tackling the major issues
facing our nation, including reforming public education, expanding
the access to affordable health care, improving public safety,
enhancing the national defense and other critical priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans lawmakers said the Clinton budget faces an
extremely cool reception on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., applauded the president's proposal
to increase federal spending nationally on after-school programs
from $495 million last year to $1 billion in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer said after-school programs prevent juvenile crime and
boost school performance, by giving children ``safe productive
places to go in the critical hours after the school bell rings.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman and Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
