<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9668 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-BUDGET-CLINTON-ART-76     02-07 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-CLINTON-ART-765(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROPOSES $1.84 TRILLION BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BUDGET-PROGRAMS, BUDGET-DEFENSE) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT14-15 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics are being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton sent Congress a budget proposal
Monday built on the idea that the budget surplus will allow the
nation to have it all, from increased government spending to tax
cuts and big reductions in the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   The president's budget, his eighth and last, calls for
additional spending across the range of issues that have long been
central to his agenda, including health care, education and the
environment, as well as increases for the military.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it stresses fiscal responsibility and maps out
a path to eliminate the portion of the national debt held by the
public over the next 13 years. And it tries to define the size of
the surplus in a way that builds Clinton's priorities into the
budget mix for the next decade and leaves Republicans relatively
little room to pursue the sweeping tax cuts they want.
</P>
<P>
   There is no argument between the parties that projected budget
surpluses, assuming they materialize, present the nation with
tremendous opportunities, including a chance to pay down the debt
and insure Social Security's long-term solvency.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday's exchanges vividly illustrated the continuing
deadlock over how to apportion the surplus. Republicans have
generally emphasized tax cuts, Democrats for the most part have
called for maintaining or increasing spending on critical needs,
and each has labeled the other's approach a threat to debt
repayment and the future of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget blueprint is unlikely to break that impasse,
and the debate this year is raging not just on Capitol Hill but on
the campaign trail, where there are stark divisions within and
between the parties over how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget calls for total spending in 2001 of nearly
$1.84 trillion, including an increase of 3.9 percent in spending on
the third of the budget accounted for by basic government
operations like the military, national parks, education and law
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   That increase, and proposed growth in this discretionary
spending of about 2.5 percent a year for the rest of the decade,
would, at least by the White House's accounting, cover the costs of
a wide range of initiatives laid out by Clinton over the past few
months. They range from an expansion of basic scientific research
to new training for pre-school teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a balanced budget with a balanced approach to our
national priorities,'' Clinton told reporters. ``It maintains our
fiscal discipline, pays down the debt, extends the life of Social
Security and Medicare, and invests in our families and our
future.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is also an election year platform, chock full of programs
that Vice President Al Gore, Hillary Rodham Clinton and other
Democratic candidates can use to defend themselves, attack their
opponents and illustrate their stands on issues.
</P>
<P>
   They include aid for hard-pressed farmers and manufacturers,
initiatives to enforce gun laws and fight wage discrimination
against women, calls for additional spending on AIDS and biomedical
research and sweeping expansions in efforts to reduce child poverty
and make health care more accessible and affordable.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have in this budget is an opportunity for politicians
to just go out and tell every single group who has any kind of an
interest at all, `Oh, we're taking care of you,''' said Rep. John
R. Kasich, R-Ohio, who is chairman of the House Budget Committee.
``That's not leadership. It's all things for all people.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the centerpieces of Clinton's proposal, including the
addition of prescription drug coverage to Medicare, are politically
popular and stand a good chance of being enacted in some form by
the Republican-led Congress this year. There is also general
bipartisan agreement on using the portion of the surplus generated
by Social Security, estimated by the administration at $2.2
trillion over the next decade, to reduce the debt.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans derided the administration's overall proposal as
a liberal tax-and-spend manifesto that they would discard as they
set about drafting their own tax and spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's budget is a paradox,'' said House Speaker
Dennis Hastert of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we pay down the debt with a budget that substantially
expands the size and scope of the federal government?'' Hastert
said. ``How can we address the issue of tax fairness, when his
budget does not substantially ease the marriage tax penalty? How
can the era of big government be over when his budget would create
close to $350 billion in new government programs?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first budget battle between Congress and the administration
this year will be over the size of the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Surplus projections vary tremendously based on assumptions about
spending, economic growth and other factors. The Congressional
Budget Office laid out three estimates last month of the non-Social
Security surplus, ranging from $838 billion to $1.9 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget said the surplus outside of Social Security
would be $746 billion over the next decade, with the vast majority
of it being generated after 2005.
</P>
<P>
   In calculating that number, the White House assumed that overall
discretionary spending would grow from its current level at
slightly less than the rate of inflation over the 10-year period.
To assume any less growth in spending over that period would be
unrealistic, given past spending patterns, and would risk a nasty
fiscal surprise down the road, White House officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we start this year has everything to do with where we
end up,'' said Jacob J. Lew, the director of the White House's
Office of Management and Budget. ``If you start with realistic,
honest numbers and make the tough decisions within that framework,
we can get to paying off the debt by 2013.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress have not yet settled on a surplus
estimate, but they made clear on Monday that whatever number they
do use will assume substantially less spending than Clinton's
budget and will therefore be considerably larger than the
administration's surplus projection.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   They said the surplus should not be committed in advance to
spending increases, that many programs can be trimmed back, and
that the surplus should be calculated in a way that maximizes the
amount of money available for tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Should Clinton's surplus figure be adopted, it would severely
limit the ability of Republicans in Congress to pursue their
tax-cutting agenda, and it would make the tax cut being offered by
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas in his run for the Republican
presidential nomination look excessive. Bush's plan is estimated to
cost at least $1.3 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans were largely silent Monday on one of the major
changes contained in the Clinton budget: its formal abandonment of
the strict spending limits set by the 1997 bipartisan balanced
budget act. The caps would have required deep spending cuts in each
of the next two years, and although the two parties have found ways
around them in the past several years, killing them completely
would once have been politically treacherous for Republicans and
Democrats alike.
</P>
<P>
   With deficits now but a memory and surpluses piling up, though,
neither party seems inclined to make an issue of the spending caps.
Administration officials said the new path they set out, keeping
spending growth just below the inflation rate and using all of the
Social Security surplus for debt reduction, should serve as the new
standard for fiscal discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget puts a heavy emphasis on shoring up and
expanding Medicare, the system of health insurance for the elderly.
It would designate $299 billion out of the 10-year surplus
projection of $746 billion to go to extending the system's solvency
from 2015 under current projections to 2025.
</P>
<P>
   It would also create a $168 billion program over a decade to
help retirees pay for prescription drugs, which have become
cripplingly expensive for many older people. Clinton also
designated another $35 billion over a decade to help beneficiaries
who face huge drug bills stemming from a catastrophic illness.
</P>
<P>
   Under intense pressure from Republicans on taxes, Clinton called
for $350 billion in tax cuts, mostly for low- and middle-income
people. But he would offset a portion of the reductions by closing
what administration officials said were $96 billion of egregious
corporate tax loopholes _ a step that Republicans and many industry
groups said was an unfair tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's tax proposals include $45 billion over 10 years to
reduce the marriage penalty paid by some two-income couples.
Republicans in Congress are pressing hard for marriage penalty
relief this year, but are pushing for a much bigger package than
what the president proposed. The House will take up a marriage
penalty bill later this week worth $182 billion in tax reductions
over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the initiatives in the budget have Gore's stamp on them.
They include a plan to provide more money to towns and cities that
lose manufacturing jobs to foreign competition, the proposal to
create catastrophic drug coverage within Medicare and a plan to
create a national licensing system for handgun owners.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Clinton's proposal ``makes my point that surpluses
will be spent if we don't have a leader who's willing to cut
taxes.'' Bush's main rival for the Republican presidential
nomination, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, who has criticized Bush's
tax plan as too big, said he welcomed Clinton's emphasis on debt
reduction and Social Security, but added that he was ``concerned
about all the new spending programs that he is proposing here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
