<HEADER>
A9670 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-PRIMARY-DELAWARE-BOS &LR;      02-07 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIMARY-DELAWARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH BRINGS `REFORMER' IMAGE TO DELAWARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT AND MICHAEL CROWLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, Delaware _ Under pressure to revamp and energize his
campaign, Governor George W. Bush arrived here Monday championing
his credentials as a reformer and the real political outsider in
the race.
</P>
<P>
   There was no missing the new message.
</P>
<P>
   A giant blue banner hung over Bush's head during two events,
reading, ``A Reformer With Results.'' At a Republican luncheon in
Dover, he used the word ``reform'' eleven times in a 15-minute
speech. And, unlike his pattern in recent weeks, he didn't use his
campaign stops to underscore his endorsement by one high-profile
party leader or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to remind people that in this race there's only one
person who can stand up and say, `I'm a reformer with results,' ''
he told the 265-person crowd ``Somebody who comes from outside the
system. Somebody who's got a record of reforming and a record of
results.''
</P>
<P>
   The intended comparison was clear: His leading opponent, Arizona
Senator John McCain, has championed campaign finance reform but
never convinced the Senate to vote for it.
</P>
<P>
   The new tactic, unveiled on the eve of the Delaware primary but
clearly aimed at the South Carolina contest Feb. 19, was part of a
carefully orchestrated shift by the Bush campaign, whose soft-edged
campaign style has been widely blamed for the wide margin of defeat
in the New Hampshire primary last week. It was matched by new
efforts to underscore Bush's willingness to hear out and respond to
individual voters' concerns. This move _ heralded as ``One on One
with Governor bush'' in another giant banner _ is designed to
address concerns that Bush's campaign has kept him at too great a
remove from actual voters.
</P>
<P>
   And, while the new strategy did not take Bush in new policy
directions or even seem to have a noticeably different tone, it
changed the dynamic of his dialogue with Senator John S. McCain. As
of Monday, the debate no longer centered around the issues favored
by Bush _ subjects like tax cuts. Instead, both McCain and Bush
wrestled for the titles of ``outsider'' and ``reformer.'' Both men
aired their views on campaign finance reform. Each attacked the
other in public remarks and new television ads.
</P>
<P>
   McCain laughed off the developments in his opponents' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand Governor Bush is now a reformer,'' McCain said
during a stop in economically depressed Flint. ``If so, it's his
first day on the job. I've been at it for 17 years. It seems to me
the Bush campaign can't figure out whether to imitate me or attack
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The accelerated attacks in the Republican primary came as
several candidates, including Bush and Steve Forbes, campaigned for
the Delaware GOP primary taking place Tuesday. And few campaign
aides seemed sure of what to expect. No reliable polling has been
done here recently, and campaign aides said a small state like
Delaware can yield unpredictable results. Just 28 polling places
will be open, with some turnout estimates as low as 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Only 12 delegates are up for grabs here, but the vote does have
symbolic stakes for all the campaigns. Bush in particular is badly
in need of positive headlines, McCain would like further proof of
his momentum, and the struggling Forbes campaign is hoping to do
respectably in a state he won four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, with his campaign coming off a weak showing in New
Hampshire, is badly in need of new momentum. Delaware, a state
whose primary he won in 1996 would seem like a natural choice. But
Forbes aides were not optimistic about the contest, saying it was
likely Forbes would finish third behind Bush and McCain _
potentially embarassing result given that McCain did not actively
compete here while Forbes spent several days travelling the state.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bush carried on a long-distance debate throughout the
day, and each prepared to release new ads in South Carolina. In
particular, Bush went after McCain's position on campaign finance,
accusing the Arizona Senator of keeping a double standard as
chairman of the US Senate Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in his harshest language yet, told reporters at a news
conference that McCain had ``raised more money than anybody in the
campaign from lobbyists.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm running for a reason. I want to be judged for results, not
rhetoric,'' Bush said. ``The campaigns are all the time full of
people saying one thing and doing another, people saying lobbyists
are bad and special interests dominate Washington, D.C. and on the
other hand pass the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush stopped just short of calling McCain a hypocrite. ``That's
your word,'' he told reporters. Asked his word for it, Bush said:
``Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared, however, that Bush's accusations were inaccurate.
According to the most recent figures compiled by the Center for
Responsive Politics, a nonpartisan think tank in Washington, Bush
far surpasses McCain in his talent for raising money from
lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   As of last September 30, Bush had raised nearly five times more
from lobbyists than McCain. His total was $480,464. McCain's was
$96,675. McCain, however, relied on lobbyists slightly more heavily
than Bush; they accounted for 10 percent of his total funds, versus
8.4 percent for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, McCain pounced on the accusation and responded with one
of his own: that Bush has received contributions from 20,000 people
with Washington zip codes, compared 1,000 similiar contributions to
the McCain campaign. Bush routinely boasts he is the only candidate
without a Washington D.C. zip code.
</P>
<P>
   McCain called Bush's charges against him ``an act that may be
viewed by some as desperation.'' He ridiculed Bush for spending
more than $1 million on the Arizona primary, which McCain said he
would win. And he feigned nervousness over Michigan Governor John
Engler's political organization, which is backing Bush here the way
Senator Judd Gregg backed Bush in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all hoping that the Engler machine is as efficient and
overwhelming as the Gregg machine was in New Hampshire,'' McCain
said.
</P>
<P>
   While McCain joked, his campaign launched a serious ad in South
Carolina accusing Bush of releasing a ``new negative ad attacking
John McCain and distorting his position.'' This week, Bush is
planning to release an ad accusing McCain of doing the same thing.
Both ads feature the no-negative-campaigning handshake they made
during a Jan. 10 Republican debate.
</P>
<P>
   And both candidates threatened to go after each other much more
aggressively in coming weeks. McCain, referring to his days as a
Navy pilot, said he would not hesitate return take Bush's fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't just respond, we will respond doubly, and have a lot
of fun doing it. We can play as rough as anybody,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Countered Bush: ``I'm ready. You haven't seen the Barbara Bush
in me yet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Jill Zuckman of the Globe Staff contributed to this report, from
Michigan.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
