<SLUG> BC-BRITISH-AIRWAYS-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH AIRWAYS SHARES FALL AS A LOSS IS REPORTED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ British Airways PLC reported better-than-expected
third-quarter financial results Monday but still showed a loss from
fare discounting and a surge in fuel prices, and its shares fell
more than 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The airline is one of the hardest hit by aircraft overcapacity _
too many seats for too few passengers. Hoping to fill the empty
seats, carriers have cut some ticket prices so steeply that the
cost of an economy-class seat in some cases hardly covers the
airline's expenses.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways said it took in 3.2 percent more revenue per
passenger in the third quarter, reversing a trend of the previous
seven fiscal quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The improvement appeared to reflect results from a radical plan
undertaken this past fall to increase profits by essentially
reducing the airline's market share. The airline said then that it
would focus its attention on first-class and business class
service, which have higher profit margins than in economy class.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, premium-class traffic grew 6.8 percent and
non-premium traffic fell by 2.8 percent in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are reading the market correctly and the trends are going
in the right direction,'' said Robert Ayling, chief executive of
British Airways. ``We have seen premium traffic grow for the past
seven months in succession.''
</P>
<P>
   While conditions in the international marketplace continue to be
highly competitive, Ayling said, he expected British Airways
results would continue to show improvement.
</P>
<P>
   The airline said its third-quarter pretax loss narrowed to 60
million pounds, or $95.5 million, from 75 million pounds a year
ago. On the basis of operations, the company lost 2 million pounds
or $3.2 million, in the three months ended Dec. 31, compared with
an operating profit of 92 million pounds during the same period a
year earlier. The company reported a loss per share of 6.6 pence,
the same as a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the latest results were better than they had
anticipated, and said the British Airways outlook looked
encouraging. But some questioned whether its recovery would be
sustainable. The company has taken a number of strategic actions
and short-term corrective measures to raise profitability, Andrew
Light, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in London said in a note
to clients. The main outstanding issue is the timing of an industry
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel prices also are an unpredictable element in the airline
industry. Many carriers have reported weaker results in the latest
quarter partly because the price of jet fuel has surged over the
past year.
</P>
<P>
   Share of British Airways dropped 13 pence to settle at 295 pence
or $4.72. The shares slumped 5.2 percent on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
