<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Fla, Vt., Ill., Texas, London)  (For release Sun., Feb. 13) 
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oregon's Winterfest Has a Russian Theme
</P>
<P>
   A glimpse of life in Imperial Russia, with all its trappings, is
coming to Portland, Ore., and the city is celebrating with a
festival of events.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of Winterfest is a sweeping exhibition at the
Portland Art Museum, ``Stroganoff: The Palace and Collections of a
Russian Noble Family,'' which opens on February 19. It showcases
more than 230 paintings, icons and furnishings that belonged to the
Stroganoffs before they were confiscated during the Russian
revolutions.
</P>
<P>
   The treasures, on loan from the State Russian Museum, the
Hermitage and other Russian museums, will be arrayed as they were
in the grand 18th-century Stroganoff Palace on Nevsky Prospekt. The
exhibition will remain on view through May 31. (It then travels to
the Kimbell Art Museum in Fort Worth, the Musee des Arts Decoratifs
in the Louvre and the Hermitage.)
</P>
<P>
   More than two dozen other cultural institutions in Portland have
their own Russian-themed offerings.
</P>
<P>
   On March 17 and 18, in ``Stars of St. Petersburg,'' dancers from
the Mariinsky Theater (formerly the Kirov Ballet) will perform
solos and duets from ``Giselle'' and from less-known Russian
ballets at Arlene Schnitzer Concert Hall. Tickets are $36 to $80
for each night, or $125 for a benefit on March 17 that includes a
reception and meeting with the dancers. Tickets can be bought from
Ticketmaster at (503) 790-2787.
</P>
<P>
   The Oregon Symphony has scheduled three performances that
include Tchaikovsky's Symphony No. 5 (May 6, 7 and 8) and three
performances of Shostakovich's Symphony No. 9 and Prokofiev's
``Alexander Nevsky'' (May 20, 21 and 22), all at Arlene Schnitzer
Concert Hall. Tickets, $14 to $67: (800) 228-7343 or on the Web at
www.orsymphony.org.
</P>
<P>
   The Northwest Film Center will screen Russian classics, and many
galleries are featuring Russian icons and artworks. On March 11,
St. Nicholas Orthodox Church will hold a celebration of icons and
liturgical arts that concludes with a service of the Great Vespers;
admission is free.
</P>
<P>
   Eight Portland hotels, including the Mark Spencer, the Heathman,
the Four Points Sheraton and the Westin Portland, are offering
packages that include tickets to the Stroganoff exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Timed tickets to the exhibition at the Portland Art Museum, 1219
S.W. Park Ave., cost $13 and are available at (503) 790-2787.
Information on all events: (503) 226-2811 or
www.portlandartmuseum.org.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines Old and New Cut New York Fares
</P>
<P>
   Less expensive air fares are coming to New York, with JetBlue, a
new airline based at Kennedy International Airport, starting
operations this month, and Southwest Airlines, the biggest discount
airline, starting service from Albany in May.
</P>
<P>
   JetBlue, with one class of service on new Airbus A-320 jets, was
scheduled to begin service to Fort Lauderdale, Fla., on February
18; it will be followed by flights from New York City to Buffalo,
N.Y., on Thursday and to Tampa, Fla., on March 16. Within 18 months
Jet-Blue plans to add flights from JFK to Rochester, N.Y., and
Syracuse, N.Y., as well as Burlington, Vt., among the 30 cities,
mostly east of the Mississippi, it plans to serve by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Seats to Fort Lauderdale, purchased 14 days in advance, are $99
each way on Friday and Sunday, peak fare days, and $79 on other
days. Seven-day advance purchase is $139 peak and $119 off peak.
The last-minute walk-up fare is $159, about 70 percent less than
the one-way walk-up fare of $524.50 that Delta quoted recently.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo tickets are $69 peak and $49 off peak when bought two
weeks in advance; $79 and $59, a week in advance. The walk-up fare
is $99, compared with a recent quote of $246 on USAirways, which
flies from La Guardia to Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   JetBlue planes come with a television monitor showing
satellite-TV broadcasts at each seat. And its seats are one inch
wider than those on most commercial jets.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest will offer nonstop flights from Albany, N.Y., to
Baltimore-Washington International Airport, Orlando, Fla., and Las
Vegas starting in May. The airline, which flies Boeing 737's, has
been rapidly expanding in the Northeast with service from Islip,
N.Y., Hartford and Providence, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Advance purchase fares to Baltimore-Washington will be as low as
$88 round trip, and the walk-up fare will be $65 one way; USAirways
recently quoted a walk-up fare of $322.50 on that route.
</P>
<P>
   More of London Linked to Underground
</P>
<P>
   The recent completion of the Jubilee Line on London's
Underground makes many tourist sites in South and East London more
accessible. The 9.93-mile extension runs from Green Park in Mayfair
to Stratford in East London. It crosses the Thames four times: from
Westminster to Waterloo; Canada Water to Canary Wharf; Canary Wharf
to North Greenwich, and North Greenwich to Canning Town.
</P>
<P>
   Ten of the 11 stations on the new section of the line connect
with either other Underground services, above-ground trains, bus
stations or the Docklands Light Railway, which serves other areas
of East London. All the stations have elevators as well as
escalators when necessary, and eight have glass safety screens
between the platform and track with doors that open when the train
arrives. Trains run every two and a half minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Some of London's most historic areas are along the line:
Southwark, with Shakespeare's Globe (the open-air replica of the
original Wooden O theater); and the Oxo Tower Wharf with its
restaurants, museum and designer galleries and studios. Near London
Bridge are the London Dungeon; the Clink Prison Museum, with
exhibits on the original 16th-century prison for heretics; the
weekend food and flower market at Borough; the Gothic style
Southwark Cathedral; and the Golden Hinde, a full-scale
reproduction of the ship in which Sir Francis Drake circumnavigated
the globe from 1577 to 1580. North Greenwich is the stop for the
Millennium Dome.
</P>
<P>
   A free leaflet, ``The Millennium Mile,'' with information on
South Bank attractions, is available from (44-171) 928 6193.
</P>
<P>
   A Busy Month for Black History
</P>
<P>
   Throughout February, cities across the United States are
acknowledging Black History Month with exhibitions, performances
and other events.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the Chicago Cultural Center, ``Passages: Contemporary Art in
Transition,'' an exhibition of painting, sculpture, photography and
other works by the painter and multimedia artist Kerry James
Marshall, the sculptor Alison Saar and 15 other African-American
artists, will be on view through April 9.
</P>
<P>
   There will also be a series of mini-festivals at the center
through Feb. 28, each highlighting the cultures of specific areas
of Africa _ on February 15, there will be a storyteller presenting
tales in the tradition of southern African peoples and a choral
performance by Thula Sizwe, an ensemble from Gauteng Province in
South Africa. Admission is free. The center, at 78 East Washington
St., is open daily. Information: (312) 744-6630. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, the California Academy of Sciences in Golden
Gate Park will be host to an African-American Step Show on February
20 at 1 p.m. Stepping combines elements of military drills with
jazz and hip-hop moves. Students from the University of California
at Berkeley will perform. The academy is open daily; admission,
$8.50. Information: (415) 750-7145.
</P>
<P>
   The Express Theater in Houston has two productions at the
Children's Museum of Houston. ``Young Mandela,'' a musical, will be
performed February 20 at 2 p.m. and Feb. 26 at 11 a.m. A
presentation of music and dance called ``African Talking Drum''
will be held at 2 p.m. on Feb. 26, March 4 and March 11. Tickets
are $5. There will also be a free performance Feb. 24 at 6:30.
Through the end of this month, the museum will display ``Two
Thousand Letters to Dr. King,'' written by children in the Houston
area aged 3 to 13 and discussing their dreams, ambitions and
thoughts about the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. The museum, at
1500 Binz St., (713) 522-1138, is open Tuesday to Sunday. Admission
is $5.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
