<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9677 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-560&AMP;ADD     02-07 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPENSION OF TALKS AND SURGE IN FIGHTING COMPLICATE MIDEAST PEACE
HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Palestinian Authority froze peace talks with the
Israelis on Monday and released from prison a charismatic Islamic
fundamentalist leader from Gaza who is an outspoken opponent of the
peace effort and of the authority.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and U.S. officials interpreted the release of Dr.
Abdel-Aziz Rantisi, a senior Hamas official, as a provocative and
intentional coincidence with the suspension of the peace
negotiations. But Palestinian officials disagreed with their
interpretation, saying that Rantisi, a 52-year-old pediatrician,
had been held for nearly two years without charges and was due to
be released.
</P>
<P>
   For Prime Minister Ehud Barak, whose agenda since he took office
last July has been almost entirely focused on peacemaking, it was
not a good day. Indeed, with Syria having broken off negotiations
last month, Barak now faces a freeze on two peace fronts at once.
And with the intensification of fighting in Lebanon, where Syria is
a powerbroker, February appears bound to be a difficult month.
</P>
<P>
   By early Tuesday, the outlook for peace was further complicated
when Israel launched air strikes in southern Lebanon, according to
wire reports.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who is also the defense minister, ordered the strikes
against the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, guerrillas.
According to the wire reports, warplanes made three strikes on a
power station in Baalbek city in Lebanon's eastern Bekaa valley.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen Lebanese civilians were injured, one of them seriously,
and 11 of them were taken to a hospital, according to Agence
France-Presse. All the injuries were caused by flying glass or
debris from about a dozen missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The escalation in the conflict in southern Lebanon may well
affect _ some say jeopardize, others say kick-start _ the
resumption of talks with Syria, which Israel holds responsible for
the recent escalation of fighting in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli-Palestinian relations began to cool last week when a
summit meeting between Yasir Arafat, the Palestinian leader, and
Barak ended in deadlock, despite the fact that they have held
regular and generally productive meetings. And although the
Israelis predicted late last week that the negotiations would
resume as scheduled on Sunday, the Palestinians did not show up.
Finally on Monday, they indefinitely suspended their participation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no desire to return to the table in order to go around
in empty circles,'' said Yasser Abed Rabbo, the chief negotiator.
``That gives a tricky impression that the peace process is still
going on and is only facing small problems. In truth, the crisis is
a deep one.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Palestinian negotiators said they were awaiting
answers from the Israelis on three key questions before they would
resume talks. The questions were tough ones, and it seemed unlikely
that answers from the Israelis would be imminent or to the
Palestinians' liking.
</P>
<P>
   The issue that drove a wedge between them concerned the next
transfer of West Bank land, which was supposed to take place this
week. The Palestinians wanted the Israelis to include villages near
Jerusalem, and the Israelis refused, maintaining that the fate of
Jerusalem needs to be negotiated separately.
</P>
<P>
   That land dispute made it clear that the larger issues of the
final status talks _ borders, settlements, Jerusalem and refugees,
among others _ would not be resolved, even in broad brush, by the
original target date of Feb. 13.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That was a written goal for a framework agreement; the full,
detailed treaty is supposed to be accomplished by mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   So the Palestinians, in a meeting with the Israelis on Saturday
night at the home of Martin Indyk, the new U.S. Ambassador to
Israel, posed the three questions.
</P>
<P>
   First, they asked, ``since the February 13 target date is as
good as over,'' if Barak wanted to eliminate the framework
agreement _ which had been his idea _ and go straight to the final
treaty. Or, they asked, did he want to extend the deadline?
</P>
<P>
   Second, they asked if Israel accepted _ which Israel never has
-_ that the maps for the next land transfer of 6.1 percent of the
West Bank should be decided jointly.
</P>
<P>
   Third, they asked when Israel intended to carry out the final
interim phase of withdrawal from the West Bank, after the 6.1
percent and before the final treaty. Israel has indicated that it
prefers to skip that stage of withdrawal because the territory will
be divided once and for all in a final agreement. But the
Palestinians, fearing that a final agreement may never be reached,
insist that it must happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fate of the negotiations depends on the answers to these
questions,'' said Nabil Aburdeineh, a senior adviser to Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   When Rantisi was released on Monday in Gaza City, he boasted
that Arafat had personally ordered that he be set free. But,
outspoken as ever, he disparaged the notion that his release would
be seen as a provocation by the Israelis, saying that ``the
Zionists are not paying that kind of attention, and if it was meant
that way, then our leaders are playing and not practicing
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor was greeted at the headquarters of Hamas, which
carried out a series of suicide bombings that killed dozens of
Israelis four years ago, by the spiritual leader of the movement,
Sheik Yassin.
</P>
<P>
   Many consider Rantisi to be the second most powerful person in
the movement after the sheik. He spent eight years in Israeli
prisons, one year in deportation to Lebanon, and 21 months in the
custody of the Palestinian Authority, which accused him of
incitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that the Palestinian Authority is sending a green
light to Hamas, just like Assad is sending a green light to the
Hezbollah to hit Israeli soldiers,'' a Palestinian political
analyst in Gaza said, referring to Hafez el-Assad, the Syrian
president.
</P>
<P>
   Assad had warned Israel not to undertake a military retaliation
against Lebanon. But, as Barak flew to northern Israel to meet with
residents of the border towns, it was clear that Israel was headed
in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will fight,'' Barak said earlier on Monday, ``and we will
make sure that anyone who struck at us will be hit, and that it is
impossible to continue in this this way, to act against the Israeli
army without the aggressors and their operators being punished.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak faced rising pressure to order a large reprisal attack
after Israelis grappled for what analysts said was the first time
with live images of their wounded soldiers on television. Hemi
Shalev, a columnist for the Maariv newspaper, said the ``Lebanese
killing valley invaded the living room of Joe Israeli after 18
years of repression.''
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Israeli politicians had urged Barak to continue his
policy of restraint. ``We are not in Lebanon in order to take
revenge but to defend ourselves,'' said Yossi Beilin, the Justice
Minister. But most said Israel could no longer put itself in the
role of a sitting target for the guerrilla forces as it waited for
Syria to return to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   And the repercussions were bound to be felt. ``As Lebanon heats
up,'' a senior U.S. official said, ``the chances of a break-through
on Syria goes down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
