<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9685 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-BUSH-STRATEGY-COX     02-07 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-STRATEGY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush trying to out-McCain McCain
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, Del. _ Gov. George W. Bush re-entered the presidential
fray Monday with a new speech, new signs and a new, more combative
attitude, all designed to win the spotlight back from U.S. Sen.
John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign, which has offered ``compassionate
conservatism'' and ``prosperity with a purpose,'' is now based on
stealing McCain's thunder and positioning the former front-runner
as a reformer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush debuted his new strategy in Delaware, which holds its
primary today. But it was South Carolina, scene of his next matchup
with McCain on Feb. 19, that was clearly on Bush's mind. Bush heads
to the Palmetto State this morning, hours before the Delaware
results will be tallied. Monday, standing before new, blue and
white signs touting him as ``A Reformer with Results,'' and ``One
on One with Governor Bush,'' Bush was clearly trying to out-McCain
McCain, barely naming his chief rival, but telling the audience at
a packed GOP luncheon in Dover that he, Bush, is the candidate best
able to clean up Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It's the message McCain rode to a landslide win over Bush in New
Hampshire last Tuesday. Bush, flush with cash and big-name
endorsements, is scrambling to avoid a repeat in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I'm not going to let happen this time is to
get defined by my opponent,'' he said. ``He is the person who is
Mr. Chairman. He's been in Washington for a long time. He's been
there so long that he's now a chairman of a very important
committee and chairmen of very important committees have got the
capacity to call people up and say, 'I'd like your help.' On the
one hand, he preaches campaign funding reform. On the other hand he
says, 'Pass the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, campaigning in Michigan, was unimpressed with the new
Bush approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand Governor Bush is now a reformer. If so, it's his
first day on the job. He should join me in going to the heart of
what's wrong with the system today and that's campaign finance
reform,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's new look also emphasizes more ``one-on-one'' contact with
voters. The goal is to create something like the town-hall meetings
that McCain held in New Hampshire (113 of them) in which the
Arizona senator combined stand-up comedy, direct answers to
questions and a personal aura that rocketed him to political
success.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Bush has been doing question-and-answer at the end of
many events. But, like his early debate performances, it often
wound up as Bush offering his stump speech in sound-bite-sized
chunks. On Monday, Bush delivered a rewritten, truncated version of
his stump speech, peppered with the word ``reform,'' and expanded
the Q&AMP;A with voters. At one stop, an American Legion hall in Dover,
he skipped the speech and spent about 45 minutes fielding
questions.
</P>
<P>
   The new Bush strategy began emerging shortly after the New
Hampshire defeat when top strategist Karl Rove and other Bush
handlers began casting McCain as a Clinton-Gore liberal because his
$283 billion tax cut proposal is about half the size of the one
Bush has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   But it was clear Monday that Bush's new strategy is to cast
McCain _ a 17-year Beltway veteran (the last 13 as a senator) _ as
a cynical insider happy to accept the contributions he derides on
the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Buchanan, a political scientist at the University of
Texas, said Bush's new tack would be a tough sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing people care about is evidence of authenticity and
stand-alone leadership ... `` Buchanan said. ``Bush is the very
embodiment of the hypercautious candidate. That's his problem, not
liberalism or conservatism. I'm amazed that a guy as smart as Rove
hasn't figured that out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not use the word hypocrite Monday to characterize
McCain but said he'd call attention to the differences between
``what people say and what they do.'' In his two gubernatorial
races, Bush proudly noted that he never attacked an opponent. In
the presidential race, he has said he would adhere to an ``honest,
optimistic and very positive campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his new strategy is all about defending his record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna take it to him,'' Bush said of McCain. ``I'm gonna
take it to him. I'm not gonna let this happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   During a televised debate last month, Bush and McCain shook
hands to seal their agreement not to go negative on each other.
Now, both will air a TV ad showing the handshake and accusing the
opposition of breaking the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we really want another politician in the White House
America can't trust?'' the McCain ad asks. The Bush campaign has
not released the text of its handshake ad that will begin airing
this week in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spent the day shadow-boxing with McCain, who skipped
today's Delaware race and headed straight to South Carolina, eager
to capitalize on his New Hampshire win. Polls indicate a tight race
in South Carolina and show McCain gaining on Bush in polls of
national GOP voters.
</P>
<P>
   Basil R. Battaglia, Delaware's Republican party chairman,
criticized McCain's ``cafeteria-style campaign.'' He said Bush's
New Hampshire loss won't mean a thing to Delaware's 164,000
registered voters. Even if it does, Delaware, with 12 GOP
delegates, is hardly a high-stakes stop on the long road to the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell that to Steve Forbes. The millionaire magazine
publisher won here in 1996 and has been traversing the state
spreading his anti-tax, anti-abortion message. That may help him in
a state that is half the size of Los Angeles County, has no sales
tax and laws that have enticed more than 170,000 Fortune 500
companies to incorporated here.
</P>
<P>
   But most eyes were on the McCain-Bush showdown in South
Carolina. Bush heads there today on a campaign jet he jokingly said
he's renamed from ``Great Expectations'' to ``Retooled One.''
</P>
<P>
   Not in the retooled strategy, however, is any attempt to
distance the candidate from his famous parents. Ex-President George
Bush and wife Barbara made their first public campaign appearance
for their son on the Saturday before the New Hampshire primary. At
the time, polls showed Bush within striking distance of McCain, and
gave no hint of the landslide to come.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-President Bush will step up his involvement today with
appearances in Michigan, site of a Feb. 22 primary. He also will
hold his first campaign-related news conference. Barbara Bush will
attend several Virginia campaign events on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jena Heath can be reached at jenah(at)coxnews.com
</P>
