<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEDBUD-CDC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CDC boost envisions new labs, research, services
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Count the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
among the winners in President Clinton's federal budget for 2001:
The Atlanta-based agency's annual budget gets a proposed raise of
5.5 percent or $195 million dollars more than this year,
potentially bringing its total appropriation to $3.53 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In any year, three-fourths of CDC's budget flows in the door and
out again, to state and local health departments, and university
and field research. But the remainder of the 2001 funds, if
approved, will go to improve buildings, laboratories and electronic
resources at the agency's Chamblee and Clifton Road campuses, and
to expand HIV prevention and programs aimed at improving the health
of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The funding boost comes at a time when the CDC is mounting a
multiyear, multimillion-dollar expansion of its Clifton Road
facilities and satellite operations in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``This budget, as a whole, addresses our need to reposition and
renovate public health in the next century,'' Dr. Jeffrey Koplan,
CDC's director, said in an interview. ``It strengthens us at the
federal level, and at state and local levels as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Highlights of the proposed CDC budget, released by Health and
Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala at an afternoon press
conference, include:
</P>
<P>
   -- $127 million (an increase of almost $70 million over the
previous year) to improve security and build three new
laboratories: the second half of a new infectious diseases research
lab, and a new high-biosafety lab for very dangerous pathogens,
both on Clifton Road, plus a new environmental-health laboratory in
Chamblee.
</P>
<P>
   -- $795 million (an increase of $66 million) for HIV/AIDS
prevention efforts, including a $40 million increase for prevention
programs within the United States, $10 million to support
community-based programs, and $61 million to combat AIDS abroad,
especially in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   -- $123 million (an increase of $25 million) for combatting
emerging infectious diseases, including $20 million to create a
national electronic disease-surveillance network that will provide
early warnings of new infections and bioterrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
   -- $151 million (an increase of $15 million) to prevent cases of
other sexually-transmitted diseases _ especially syphilis, which
CDC hopes shortly to eliminate in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   -- $39 million (an increase of almost $10 million from the
previous year) for food safety research, including an expansion of
the PulseNet system that allows labs across the country to compare
strains of bacteria electronically.
</P>
<P>
   -- Increases in funds for programs that target adolescent
smoking prevention, monitoring for environmental hazards and
screening for breast and cervical cancer.
</P>
<P>
   -- $999 million in funds that will be shared among CDC and other
federal agencies to guarantee that at least 90 percent of U.S.
children receive the full series of recommended childhood vaccines.
That appropriation includes money to buy vaccines for underinsured
children, to research vaccine safety, and to target polio
eradication around the world.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON'S BUDGET PLAN
</P>
