<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-DEFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF THEMES OF MILITARY BUDGET: MODERNIZING AND TROOP WELFARE
</HEADLINE>
   (With BUDGET-CLINTON) 
(jw) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The $291.1 billion Pentagon budget proposed by the
Clinton administration on Monday not only reflects peacetime
concerns about improving the lives of those who serve but also
looks ahead to the challenges of a national anti-missile defense
and quick-and-dirty regional combat.
</P>
<P>
   The budget, for the fiscal year that will begin on Oct. 1, calls
for a 3.7 percent increase in military pay on top of last year's
increase, which brought the troops their first raise after
inflation since the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   New in the budget proposal is an increase in the housing
allowances paid to all service members who live off base. The
Defense Department would increase those allowances by $3 billion
over the next five years; the effect would be that at the end of
that period, personnel living off base would no longer have any
out-of-pocket housing expenses. The Pentagon would also push ahead
programs to improve on-base housing.
</P>
<P>
   While the budget would add $369 million next year to the
Pentagon's medical care program, top officials of the department
have yet to agree on a plan providing health care coverage to
retirees. Gen. Henry H. Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, has failed to persuade Secretary of Defense William S. Cohen
to approve a new $3 billion-a-year program to cover retirees'
health care costs, even though both men consider such coverage an
obligation of the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the options we've looked at are quite expensive,''
Cohen said in presenting the budget Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The military's Kosovo campaign, which brought $2 billion in
emergency costs, revealed shortcomings in the services'
war-fighting abilities and helped shape the new budget, with its
accent on modern weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   In particular this budget finds the Army, which had serious
difficulties deploying its Apache helicopters to Albania, unveiling
important changes for the sake of modernization. To make its forces
more mobile, the Army has cut by half the financing for its
fledgling Crusader artillery system until officials are convinced
that it can be built light enough for quick deployment.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Army has scrapped plans to build two new
vehicles, the Wolverine and the Grizzley, which among other uses
would have cleared minefields and knocked down bridges. Instead,
the service will spend $14.5 billion to create new weaponry, in
particular a mobile, lightweight armored vehicle that can be used
for combat in small-scale conflicts as well as major wars.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy has also reordered its budget, to spend more than $3
billion on development of a new destroyer powered by electric
motor, a ship that Secretary of the Navy Richard Danzig has said
will become a model for the future fleet.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the amount sought to develop various new weapons systems
for the military as a whole is $60 billion. The budget also calls
for $1.9 billion to be spent on a national anti-missile defense
system should President Clinton decide to build one, to protect the
nation from limited nuclear attack.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Air Force, it had expected approval of all its plans
to build new fighter jets, given the successful air campaign in
Kosovo. Instead, Congress last year scaled back production of the
F-22 fighter for the current fiscal year, in protest of the plane's
escalating costs. Now the Air Force proposes to put the F-22 back
on schedule by spending $4 billion on the program next year, with
plans to buy as many as 36 planes a year by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   The two leading Republican presidential candidates, Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas and Sen. John McCain of Arizona, have both argued
that military spending is too low.
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen said Monday that since taking office in 1997, he had
``laid the foundation'' for a strengthened military through
increased spending. For the current fiscal year, spending rose by
$17 billion, a figure that amounted to the end of the so-called
peace dividend, which had brought nearly 10 years of shrinking
armed forces and military budgets. This proposed budget is $13.5
billion more than the current year's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes without saying that we have the finest military in the
world,'' Cohen said. ``We intend to keep it precisely that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2043EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
