<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Not many answers in Lewis murder case
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than a week after the celebrated post-Super Bowl slayings
in Buckhead, the public knows next to nothing about the case beyond
the fact that NFL star Ray Lewis is accused of stabbing two men to
death.
</P>
<P>
   Most can probably remember the brand of limousine involved more
easily than the names of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta police, rarely particularly forthcoming about an
investigation, have shown remarkable reticence in this, one of the
most sensational cases to confront them in years. Chief Beverly
Harvard has not uttered a word, which is her wont in a high-profile
case. Mayor Bill Campbell has confined his comments to generalities
about seeking justice.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewis case is a hot topic across the nation. Some people,
especially in Baltimore where Lewis is considered a team leader and
is active in social programs, are concerned he is being held on
thin evidence. Atlanta police are still getting dozens of calls
daily from reporters in other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Police have confirmed only that:
</P>
<P>
   _They believe the altercation that led to the deaths of Jacinth
Baker and Richard Lollar started in a nightclub called Cobalt.
</P>
<P>
   _They found a knife at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   _Lewis' Lincoln Navigator stretch limousine was struck by
bullets ``one or more times.''
</P>
<P>
   _They arrested Lewis and charged him with two murders.
</P>
<P>
   _They recovered a firearm from in front of a Buckhead florist's
shop.
</P>
<P>
   _They believe that two of Lewis' acquaintances, A.J. Johnson and
Kwame King, were also in the 40-foot limousine.
</P>
<P>
   _On Monday, they confirmed that detectives searched Lewis' home
in suburban Baltimore. (His attorney had already confirmed that.)
</P>
<P>
   Some of those points are hotly contested. No one has said
publicly they saw the victims inside the Cobalt club
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, it seems unlikely the victims could have
gotten into the club. They were dressed neatly but casually, and
there was no indication they could afford the $100-a-head cover
charge or $10 per drink.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson spoke up from Baltimore and claimed that not only was he
not in the limo, he wasn't even in Atlanta. He said he stayed in
Baltimore on
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl weekend and didn't know Lewis well enough to be
invited to go club-hopping with him.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta officers talked with Johnson in Baltimore on Friday.
They won't say if they've talked to King.
</P>
<P>
   They also won't say who else was in the limo; that matter, they
say, is ``still being investigated.''
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the limo, Duane Fassett, was put under police
guard. While detectives apparently based their arrest warrant for
Lewis on what Fassett told them, the driver has told others that
Lewis had nothing to do with the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Who shot the limo? Police probably know, but they are not
telling. There are unconfirmed reports that the shooter was an
armed citizen trying to stop the fleeing behemoth.
</P>
<P>
   Police also have searched the Gwinnett County home of attorney
Max Richardson, where Lewis was arrested. They will not say what
they found.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' Maryland attorney said police who entered the football
player's home there Monday morning carried away plastic containers
full of things he would not mention, plus Lewis's computer. What
any of this might have to do with an apparent heat-of-the-moment
crime in Atlanta is not explained.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' attorneys have not been particularly talkative, either,
other than to repeatedly insist he had nothing to do with the
crime. They have not offered to explain why Lewis, though it was
his $150-an-hour limousine, would let anyone in his party get out,
stab a couple of Decatur men three times apiece, then get back in
and speed away.
</P>
<P>
   Officer John Quigley, spokesman for the Atlanta police
department, would not agree that police are saying less about the
Lewis case than they might about one of lower profile. ``It's
inappropriate to discuss witnesses and evidence at this stage in
the investigation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
