<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9700 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LEWIS-PARTYTOWN-COX     02-07 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-PARTYTOWN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In Atlanta, Buckhead is partytown
 &HT;    By Paul Donsky
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many people around the country, night life in Atlanta means
one thing: Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities around the country have similar, high-profile night
spots _ the French Quarter in New Orleans, Georgetown in
Washington, D.C., Rush Street in Chicago, South Beach in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   All are relatively historic areas that, over the years, have
evolved from neighborhoods and even suburbs into Party Central. All
are places where, on any given evening, tourists, businessmen and
locals converge to eat fancy meals, grab a drink, shop and dance.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Buckhead has become an important tourist
attraction and revenue producer for the city. But some local
residents wonder if the party scene has gotten out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Three homicides in the last two weeks in Buckhead _ including a
double murder last week near the Cobalt club _ have put the upscale
community on edge. Some leaders are calling for earlier closing
times, parking restrictions and more police in efforts to make the
area safer.
</P>
<P>
   Homicides are rare in most entertainment districts around the
country. Georgetown has seen two murders over the last three years,
Washington police said. The Buckhead bar district has had three
murders during that same time period, though those in Buckhead were
committed over a much shorter time span.
</P>
<P>
   Murders also are extremely unusual in Chicago's Rush Street
neighborhood and Nashville's downtown District, though police in
those cities said they had no figures available on the exact number
of homicides
</P>
<P>
   The French Quarter has been a bit more violent, reporting 16
murders from January 1997 to June 1999, New Orleans police said.
</P>
<P>
   How other entertainment districts deal with the crowds and crime
may offer Atlanta leaders some guidance as they deal with growing
pains in Buckhead:
</P>
<P>
   _ A moratorium on liquor licenses in Georgetown has helped that
district remain vibrant by maintaining a healthy mix of
restaurants, shops and bars, local business leaders say.
</P>
<P>
   _ In New Orleans, sophisticated crime-fighting strategies and a
beefed-up police force are credited with cleaning up the French
Quarter.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Nashville's bustling downtown area, known as The District,
police say a crack-down on ``quality of life'' crimes like
vandalism and traffic offenses has helped transform what was once a
dangerous, crime-ridden spot.
</P>
<P>
   Business and community leaders say some problems are unavoidable
when you mix large numbers of people with alcohol. But, they add,
serious, violent crimes are rare occurrences that do not accurately
reflect the safety of entertainment districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buckhead and Georgetown are probably the safest places in
Atlanta and in Washington,'' said Paul Cohn, president of the
Georgetown Business and Professional Association.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn, vice president of a company that once owned J. Paul's
restaurant in Buckhead, said the recent killings there should not
be seen as a sign the area has turned a corner and is headed for
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't take an isolated incident and stake a case for it,''
Cohn said. ``I stayed at the Ritz three weeks ago and walked by
Cobalt. There were a lot of police presence in cars. I felt very
safe. Things like that can happen anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say preventative steps can't help cut crime,
police and community leaders say.
</P>
<P>
   The violent crime rate in New Orleans has been cut nearly in
half since 1996, when the city began increasing the size of the
police force and police began using computers to track crimes and
act more proactively.
</P>
<P>
   Few places in the world rival the French Quarter's party
atmosphere. With its narrow, French-named boulevards, street
artists, peep shows, open-all-night bars and restaurants, the
Quarter has become a top tourist attraction and one of the city's
leading industries.
</P>
<P>
   Local leaders say despite the rowdy atmosphere, violent crime is
not a given in the area.
</P>
<P>
   A once-neglected home to dive bars and run-down honky-tonks,
Nashville's downtown District has made a dramatic turnaround in
recent years to become the heart and soul of Nashville's night
life.
</P>
<P>
   Trendy bars and packed nightclubs now line Second Avenue and
Broadway, the area's main streets, which are packed with locals and
tourists most weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Tayler, general manager of Buffalo Billiards and Havana
Lounge, an upscale District bar and restaurant frequented by many
Tennessee Titans players, said she's had few problems other than
the occasional fight involving college kids.
</P>
<P>
   It's important for a city to have the type of vibrant night
scene the District provides Nashville, Tayler said. ``What the
District down here offers to people is an enormous variety of
things to do.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, city officials have learned the hard way that
special steps must be taken during some events. Celebrations after
the city won professional football and basketball championships got
out of hand, recalled Burton F. Natarus, a longtime Chicago
alderman whose district includes the Rush Street area and the
Michigan Avenue shopping district north of the downtown Loop.
</P>
<P>
   When large crowds are expected in Rush Street, police now block
off streets to keep people confined to certain areas that are
heavily patrolled, Natarus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is the fact that on these streets
where there are large numbers of people gathered for entertainment
is (to have) a large police presence,'' Natarus said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Buckhead leaders are worried that the area has become
overrun with bars and have suggested zoning changes to attract more
shops to the area.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn, of the Georgetown business association, agreed with that
concern, saying that a moratorium on liquor licenses has capped the
number of bars and clubs in Georgetown and allowed other businesses
to flourish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were finding there were too many bars opening up one right
after another,'' Cohn said. ``We wanted to keep a good mix of
retail. You can't have a bar on every corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want this to become another Bourbon Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Buckhead residents also have wondered if earlier closing
times would reduce the risk of violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   Bars in Buckhead now stop serving alcohol at 4 a.m. Clubs in
Washington have to stop selling alcohol at 2 a.m. Monday through
Thursday and at 3 a.m. on weekends. In Nashville, taps go dry at 3
a.m. In Chicago, most bars stop selling drinks at 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Monaghan, owner of Molly's on the Market, a fixture in the
French Quarter for three decades, said curfews or earlier closing
times will not do any good.
</P>
<P>
   Molly's is only closed for four hours a day _ between 6 a.m. and
10 a.m., Monaghan said.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing up the closing time ``won't help a thing. That will just
worsen the situation,'' Monaghan said. `` It's like taking away
liquor in Prohibition. Anything they take away, (people) will do
just the opposite. That's human nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
