<SLUG> BC-DEL-PRIMARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 WOULD-BE WASHINGTONS CROSS INTO DELAWARE; 1 DOESN'T 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BUSH-DEL, MCCAIN-MICH) 
(nk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ For Steve Forbes, the Republican primary in
Delaware on Tuesday is a chance to prove there is life left in his
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   For George Bush, on the other hand, the race here is mostly a
distraction from his main goal nowadays of stopping Sen. John
McCain in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is on the ballot here, but he has not campaigned at all.
</P>
<P>
   In most respects, the contest in Delaware, which has only
700,000 residents and 12 delegates to the Republican National
Convention, is but a minor twist on the road from New Hampshire
last week to South Carolina, where the primary is Feb. 19. The race
has hardly been mentioned on network television or in the national
press, and even this state's newspapers are treating it casually.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats choose their delegates in caucuses beginning month, so
neither Vice President Al Gore nor former Sen. Bill Bradley
campaigned for the Democratic primary last Saturday. Gore won with
57 percent of the vote and a turnout of about 5 percent of the
state's 200,000 registered Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican race is being taken somewhat more seriously.
Forbes has spent considerable resources here, hoping to replicate
his experience in 1996, when he was the only candidate who
campaigned in the state. He won the primary with 33 percent of the
vote to Bob Dole's 27 percent. About 33,000 Republicans voted in
that primary, a turnout of about 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bush had no choice but to compete here, given his
emphasis on conducting a 50-state campaign. In Wilmington on
Monday, taking a swipe at McCain, Bush said, ``Anybody campaigning
for president ought to run in every state.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been no reliable recent public polls. As is the case
in most other states, Bush has the support of the business and
political establishment here, including Rep. Michael N. Castle, the
popular former governor who is Delaware's only House member.
</P>
<P>
   And within these circles, the prevailing view is that Bush will
win handily. Over the weekend, The Baltimore Sun quoted Patrick
Murray, a retired banker who is chairman of the Bush campaign in
Kent County, as promising a ``68 to 70 percent'' victory for the
Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' strength is difficult to calculate. He has spent much
more time here than Bush. Monday, on the third leg of a four-day
bus tour, Forbes once again emphasized his opposition to abortion
and the tax system. He also expressed optimism about his prospects
and took swipes at Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The elites are not picking the nominee,'' Forbes, a wealthy
publisher, said in Dover, referring to Bush's loss in New Hampshire
to McCain and his less-than-overwhelming victory in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Because Delaware does not have its own network-affiliated
television stations _ coverage comes from Philadelphia in the north
and Baltimore in the south _ Forbes cannot blanket the state with
commercials. He and Bush are both running advertisements on cable
television stations and on radio, but it is nothing like the
commercial saturation that characterized the race in New Hampshire,
where Forbes finished a distant third.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' advisers are playing down his chances, clearly hoping
that if he does make a strong showing it will exceed expectations.
</P>
<P>
   When asked at a news conference whether he would stay in the
race until the Republican convention in order to throw his support
to either McCain or Bush, Forbes responded, ``I see it the other
way,'' adding, ``I may need the help of one of them to get over the
top.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Bush's allies question whether, with all eyes on South
Carolina and so few delegates at stake here, he should be competing
at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a no-win proposition for him in Delaware,'' said an
ardent Bush supporter in Congress. ``If he wins big, it will be
discounted because McCain is not in the race. And if he loses or if
he only barely beats Forbes, it will be seen as a further sign of
weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, on his third visit to the state, Bush criticized McCain
for taking contributions from lobbyists while calling for campaign
finance reform. Bush said his record as governor showed that he was
the true reformer in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Another unknown factor is whether McCain is at all competitive,
not having campaigned or spent any money in the state. There is a
large Air Force base in Dover and thousands of military retirees
who might back the Arizona senator live nearby. A small bank of
McCain volunteers was making calls Monday to drum up votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If McCain had tried here,'' said Basil Battaglia, the state
Republican chairman, ``he probably would have done pretty well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
