<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9703 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-DEMS-RANGEL-ART-2TAKE     02-07 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-RANGEL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITCHING DEMOCRATS' CAUSE, RANGEL ADVANCES HIS OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT16,17 _ are being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There is a jingle to Rep. Charles B. Rangel's step
now, a little like the ka-ching of a cash register swallowing up
dollar bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``They throw it at me,'' Rangel said, only half-kidding, about
the money he is collecting to win back control of the House for the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, which is in
charge of raising money and spending it strategically to win this
year's crucial House races, is awash in money right now. In a
remarkable turnaround, the group has more than doubled the amount
of cash in the bank _ $19.8 million as of Dec. 31 _than its
Republican counterpart in the House has. And, in a year of
staggering war chests, it has socked away more money than any other
party committee, Republican or Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Few Democratic members have helped raise more cash this year
than Rangel, the 15-term congressman from Harlem with the gravelly
voice, wry sense of humor and a bygone aversion to campaign
fund-raising. And few members stand to benefit as directly from a
Democratic victory as Rangel, who is now the senior member of the
New York congressional delegation and would become chairman of the
House Ways and Means Committee, which shapes tax, Social Security
and Medicare policy.
</P>
<P>
   In a field cluttered with money-raising schemes, Rangel, 69, has
tapped into a novel fund-raising combination. He has by turn
reached out to old money _from traditional Democratic sources in
the business world _ and new money, much of it from a burgeoning
group of wealthy African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's new money,'' Erik Smith, a spokesman for the Democratic
House Campaign Committee, said about the $2.5 million that Rangel
raised last year. ``There is a term called `hitting a new vein.'
And that's what he's been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangel's pitch is straightforward, more suave than blunt. And it
inevitably focuses on his possible ascendancy to the tax-writing
committee's chairmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Charlie is selling is one of the most powerful positions
in the Congress, if not the government,'' said Robert Johnson, the
chairman of Black Entertainment Television Holdings, who is a
contributor.
</P>
<P>
   In his pitches to African-American business leaders, who
historically have not focused their giving on House races, Rangel
asks them to picture a House where black lawmakers would hold
unprecedented sway: himself at the helm of the Ways and Means
Committee, Rep. John Conyers Jr. of Michigan as chairman of the
Judiciary Committee and 19 other black members in control of
various subcommittees.
</P>
<P>
   Chief executives, who relish a tax cut of any size and usually
donate more money to Republicans, are often reeled in when Rangel
asks a hypothetical question: What if? And it has been effective.
More Republicans are sending money the Democrats' way, and in the
last few months.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel said he had sat down with a few unnamed, rich corporate
heads in luxurious private clubs, simply because they wanted to get
to know him better.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the black community, he relies on a combination of pride
and power,'' Johnson said. ``And in the white community, he says,
`Don't you want to hedge your bet on who will be chairman?' People
are putting safe money in his hands and pride money in his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangel is so popular in his district _ New York's 15th, which
includes all of Harlem and some of Manhattan's Upper West Side _
that he has seldom had to raise money for his own elections and
none of the current $19.5 million he has raised is for himself. He
is also involved in a get-out-the-vote plan hatched by Bill Lynch,
vice chairman of the Democratic National Committee, that proved
successful in the 1998 elections. He travels to swing districts
where black voters can make a difference, and asks them to turn out
on Election Day, in much the same way the Christian right does with
its supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But his cross-country fund-raising trips have served another
purpose, too: to build a national reputation for a man who is
headed into his 30th year in Congress. While Rangel has been a
household name in New York, his name does not always ring a bell
elsewhere. He is a liberal and a partisan Democrat, and is rightly
perceived that way, but he also is letting people see a third side:
that of the pragmatist, with a rapier wit, who can juggle the
concerns of the poor with the interests of the rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people didn't know him in the business community,''
said Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, and a former campaign committee
chairman. ``They have certain preconceptions about a congressman
from Harlem, but when they meet him and talk to him, they are blown
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in the business world, however, are not as keen about
Rangel's becoming the Ways and Means chairman, and they are
actively working for Republicans to prevent it. They offer the same
pitch to their constituents as Rangel does to his: Imagine this
congressman as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be an unmitigated disaster,'' said Brian Reardon, who
handles federal public policy for the National Federation of
Independent Business. ``He doesn't support small business and he
never met a tax he didn't like.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangel says nobody ever complains to him. But why would they, he
adds. He shrugs it off by pointing to the political friends he has
among New York's banking, Wall Street and real estate moguls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my chairmanship would shatter the vestiges of racism
overnight,'' Rangel said. ``There are people that absolutely become
colorblind when they got a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have no idea how much I want to preserve the economy and
make it grow,'' Rangel added. ``What good is civil rights during a
depression? What good is a decent education if you have no jobs?
Why would you fight against drug addiction if you were not
providing hope on the other hand?''
</P>
<P>
   Sanford I. Weill, the chairman and co-chief executive of
Citigroup, says Rangel does not give business concerns short
shrift.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have an issue, he's somebody you can talk to,'' Weill
said. ``And if what you're saying makes sense, he's supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bernard Rangel was born on June 11, 1930, to a Harlem
factory seamstress and a father he barely knew. A high school
dropout, he eventually joined the Army and fought in the Korean
War, where he rescued 40 men from behind enemy lines. He was
decorated with the Purple Heart and the Bronze Star.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, when the Democrats lost control of the House, Rangel,
who was once considered the least ideological black member,
proclaimed a new era for himself as an ``oratorical bomb-thrower.''
He was angry at the Democratic leadership and angry at President
Clinton. And he bemoaned the turn the nation was taking on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel still says he is fiery, but much of that is simply his
role as an agent provocateur in the minority. He enjoys needling
the chairman of the Ways and Means Committee, Rep. Bill Archer of
Texas, whom he sometimes compares to Dreyfus, Inspector Clouseau's
sputtering, foiled-again superior. He also once likened Archer to
Hitler, something the chairman did not forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you would call it strong humor,'' said Rep. E. Clay
Shaw Jr., a conservative Florida Republican on the committee who is
friendly with Rangel. ``Some may call it ruthless humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangel staunchly defended Clinton in the impeachment proceedings
last year, saying Republicans were more guilty of high crimes and
misdemeanors than the president when they failed to support
Clinton's decision to bomb Iraqi military sites in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel's colleagues on the Ways and Means Committee say Archer
has made his mark in the last few years, helping to keep his party
unified in committee and reaching out to more conservative
Democrats. Despite his run-ins with Archer, Rangel sometimes works
closely with other Republicans, including Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent speech before the National Federation of Retailers
in New York City, Rangel struck a chord that is seldom heard on
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth of the matter is, if you're talking about Medicare
and you're talking about Social Security and a real large tax bill,
the Democrats cannot have this and neither can the Republicans
unless we work together,'' he said. ``This is not a spirit of
bipartisanship. This is a spirit of common sense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
