<HEADER>
A9705 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-THREES-TEX     02-07 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THREES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME SEQUELS, THIRD TIME'S THE CHARM. OTHER NO. 3'S ARE SERIAL
KILLERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For some reason, our society is fascinated by threes. They're
good: The third time's a charm. They're bad: Three on a match means
bad luck. They're ambiguous: Good things and bad things come in
threes; a three-ring circus can be fun, but it can also signify,
say, an incoherent staff meeting. In baseball, it's good to get a
three-base hit, bad to get three strikes. Beginning writers learn
about a ``rule of threes'': when illustrating a point, use three
examples. Whoops, messed that one up.
</P>
<P>
   We are also a society that doesn't know when to quit, which
could explain why a movie that merits a sequel merits two sequels _
and sometimes, more. This is the case with Scream 3, which opened
to generally positive reviews that still classed it as the weakest
entry in the Scream horror-comedy series. Scream 3 will make a
boatload of money, thanks to magazine-cover hype and little
box-office competition last weekend, but as far as quality goes, it
looks like a victim of the law of diminishing returns.
</P>
<P>
   You can only return to the same well so often before it runs
dry, and the strategy of the Batman and Lethal Weapon series _ add
new characters while keeping old ones _ only serves to make for
noisier, more incoherent movies. Scream 3 manages to avoid this.
Although stars Neve Campbell, David Arquette, Courteney Cox
Arquette and Liev Schrieber (a good actor who probably wants to
break this cycle) return, screenwriter Ehren Kruger doesn't
overcrowd his script with new characters and director Wes Craven
brings the movie in at a mere 90 minutes _ a half-hour less than
Scream 2.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't make Scream 3 necessary, but it was probably
inevitable. Francis Ford Coppola, who created 1970s masterpieces
with The Godfather and The Godfather Part II, couldn't leave well
enough alone and tried to bring the saga to completion with 1990's
The Godfather Part III. Edie Falco, as The Sopranos' Carmela
Soprano, summed up Godfather III best: ``What happened there?''
</P>
<P>
   Also in 1990, The Exorcist novelist/screenwriter William Peter
Blatty tried to undo the damage done by 1977's Exorcist II: The
Heretic by taking the reins on another installment, Exorcist III.
Although it wasn't considered an embarrassment, it didn't have the
hair-frying cultural impact of the 1973 original, which was so
frightening that it scared people who didn't even see it.
</P>
<P>
   Not all movie series have succumbed to this. After the
travesties of Grease 2 and Caddyshack II, the minds behind those
films had the good sense to call it quits. And Gremlins 2, the rare
sequel to surpass its original (and make fun of it), was content
with being the last word in that series. Some of the movies below
(we didn't include all series) should have learned from other
sequel bombs; others were better than we had any right to expect.
</P>
<P>
   Die Hard With a Vengeance: After the adrenaline punch of Die
Hard and the meanness of Die Hard 2, this series (with Bruce Willis
as the world's unluckiest cop) began to show signs of self-parody
with this third installment, despite strong support from Samuel L.
Jackson and Jeremy Irons.
</P>
<P>
   Godfather III: Not really as bad as its reputation indicates,
this is still an example of an ordinary movie standing in the
shadow of two classics.
</P>
<P>
   Return of the Jedi: Again, a movie that's only weak in
comparison with its predecessors (Star Wars and The Empire Strikes
Back), marred with a cuteness that would also infect Star Wars:
Episode I _ The Phantom Menace.
</P>
<P>
   Friday the 13th Part III: An exception to the rule, this is
arguably the best movie in this disreputable series, although it's
still pretty blah if you can't see it in 3-D.
</P>
<P>
   Halloween III: Season of the Witch: This renegade Halloween
movie has nothing to do with the series' villain, Michael Myers.
And nobody should have anything to do with the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade: Yet another movie that's not
that bad, this still suffered from a five-year gap between it and
its predecessor, Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom. Beautifully
cast, though, with Sean Connery as Indiana Jones' dad and River
Phoenix as a younger version of Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Lethal Weapon III: The beginning of the decline of this series,
this installment turned a once dark, angry police drama laced with
humor into a glorified Three Stooges comedy with more graphic
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Naked Gun 331/3: The formula for this police farce seemed ripe
for burnout, what with its goofy, joke-a-minute humor. That didn't
stop its makers, the Zucker-Abrahams-Zucker team, from milking the
formula in a bunch of other movies.
</P>
<P>
   National Lampoon's Christmas Vacation: Another exception, this
Chevy Chase vehicle is funnier than anyone had a right to expect,
largely thanks to a persistent, conniving squirrel.
</P>
<P>
   Police Academy III: Look, we're not even going to pretend to
have watched this. We'll cop to watching the original, which was a
funny guilty pleasure, and to No. 2, which wasn't. That should be
enough. And they made seven of these!
</P>
<P>
   Rocky III: The first Rocky was an underdog that proved cliches
aren't always bad, just as long as you put 'em together correctly.
Rocky 2 was a sentimental favorite. Rocky 3 was at least less
gloppy than the next two entries, but aside from introducing the
world to Mr. T, it's pretty ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Star Trek III: The Search for Spock: The common belief about
Star Trek movies is that the even-numbered ones are pretty good,
while the odd-numbered ones are weak. III is actually OK, it just
doesn't hold up to II and IV. Think of it as a good,
extended-length version of the TV show, and it holds up better.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2056EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9706 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-GARTH-LIMITS-TEX     02-07 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARTH-LIMITS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AUSTIN CITY LIMITS' MAKES GARTH'S LIMITS CLEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There has always been a time-capsule element to ``Austin City
Limits,'' the venerable music show that is kicking off its 25th
anniversary celebration this year on PBS (see local listings for
times and stations).
</P>
<P>
   ``ACL'' has become something of a public television legend _ for
its down-home feel and its survey of American music, from the
mountainside porches and big-city nightclubs and honky-tonks of
America.
</P>
<P>
   To see a Willie Nelson or a Joe Ely or a Los Lobos or a Stevie
Ray Vaughan or a Ruth Brown on ``ACL'' is as close as we will come
to viewing from our living rooms the master American musicians in a
fairly normal performing situation.
</P>
<P>
   The staging is simple, the crowd is small, and the performances
frequently excellent. It's no wonder that ``ACL'' execs are
planning to release various episodes on home video: I can think of
a fistful of shows I'd buy tomorrow if I had the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday evening's program, billed as ``An Hour With Garth
Brooks,'' though, is a whole 'nother deal _ a different kind of
history, a visual document of a man who has just made a massive
career blunder and is trying to put a good spin on it.
</P>
<P>
   We are catching Brooks just about two months after the release
of the CD ``Garth Brooks in... The Life of Chris Gaines,'' in which
he assumed the role of a fictional rock star who has returned to
the public eye after recovering from a horrible car wreck. Garth
gave us Chris with Trent Reznor-like hair and a pop/rock/R&AMP;B soul
sound that veered unsteadily from Babyface to John Mellencamp.
</P>
<P>
   By early November, ``Gaines'' was already slumping on the
charts. It was because the rock didn't rock hard enough, and the
transformation from Garth to Chris had come to appear both weird
AND lame. This Chris guy may have looked like an '80s lite-rocker,
but his music was an unfocused stew of mediocre songs that had no
personality, and certainly never really rocked.
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour-plus taping Garth did for the ``Austin City
Limits'' show was quite a bit better than that, but it's mainly
because most of it was tried-and-true Garth country. Dressed in his
standard country garb, and fronting his touring band, he first tore
through more than an hour of hits such as ``Rodeo'' and ``The
Thunder Rolls,'' all sincerity and enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Gaines material; mercifully, Brooks didn't change
outfits or shift into the Gaines character, but he did have a
separate, young, multiracial band come on to navigate through the
new material.
</P>
<P>
   But he only played four songs from the new CD. That's right _
all the buildup, all the promotion done on this new character and
sound, and he wimps out. The new band was onstage less than 25
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This was clearly an attempt to show the faithful (a few of whom
actually walked out during the Gaines set!) that he was coming back
to the fold.
</P>
<P>
   And the show you'll see underscores this: In the end, only ONE
song from the Gaines CD _ ``Right Now,'' Garth's cringe-inducing
stab at rap _ makes the final cut for television.
</P>
<P>
   ``ACL'' publicist Pat Consgrove said that the Brooks camp had
final selection of the songs, which also include ``We Shall Be
Free, Friends in Low Places, Callin' Baton Rouge'' and the
concluding ``The Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   What can we conclude here? That Brooks is trying to distance
himself from the whole Chris Gaines diversion, playing damage
control and reminding us of his status as country's biggest name,
all in one fell swoop.
</P>
<P>
   So would you if you'd seen a project die as quickly as this
Chris Gaines diversion did. There's been no mention of late about
``The Lamb,'' the movie starring Garth as Gaines that was supposed
to start filming this year. Brooks has been a bit testy with
reporters about the CD, and has strongly hinted that he'll be
retiring at the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Don't you believe it. Brooks is too competitive _ and maybe, at
this point, just too angry that this shift in sound didn't go over
well _ to bow out now. My money's on him releasing another country
CD by the end of the year, and following it with a long worldwide
tour.
</P>
<P>
   After all, once you've been on the mountaintop (and Brooks has
been there for 10 years now) it's hard to admit you've got to go
back down the other side. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman covers the pop music scene for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can reach him at (817) 390-7839 or by e-mail at
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
