u i BC-CROATIA-ELECT-500&AMP;ADD     02-07 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROATIA-ELECT-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROATIA ELECTS RELAXED MODERATE TO SUCCEED TUDJMAN
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAGREB, Croatia _ A jocular former leader of the old Yugoslavia
was elected Monday as president, succeeding Franjo Tudjman, who
died in December.
</P>
<P>
   The winner, Stipe Mesic, 65, last leader of the collective
presidency before Yugoslavia disintegrated in 1991, earned the
trust of Croatians for his easy manner, his apparent disregard for
pretension and his relaxed attitude about Croatian nationalism, in
sharp contrast to Tudjman.
</P>
<P>
   A happy Mesic told a cheering crowd at his campaign headquarters
that he would concentrate on bringing Croatia into the European
Union and NATO ``as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   His opponent, Drazen Budisa, a 51-year-old former dissident,
conceded defeat shortly after the polls closed and early results
showed Mesic with a large lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the moment has come for me to congratulate Mesic on
his victory and to wish him a lot of success in carrying out the
presidential duties,'' Budisa said.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 99 percent of the vote counted, Mesic had 56.2
percent to Budisa's 43.8 percent, the State Electoral Commission
announced early Tuesday. Turnout was 61.5 percent of Croatia's 4.2
million voters.
</P>
<P>
   In the first round of the election, on Jan. 24, Mesic received
41.6 percent of the vote in a nine-party field, while Budisa
received 28 percent, but final polls had shown the race narrowing.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates are pro-Western and relatively liberal, favoring
membership in the European Union and NATO, and both are part of the
six-party opposition coalition that won parliamentary elections a
month ago, defeating Tudjman's once-dominant Croatian Democratic
Union.
</P>
<P>
   American and European officials had said they would be pleased
if either man won, especially after the strained and contentious
relationship they had with Tudjman.
</P>
<P>
   The election both concludes and opens an extraordinary period of
political change here, which Washington hopes will be a model for
neighboring Serbia, run by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the lingering illness and death of Tudjman last
year, the Croatian Democratic Union that he founded and that led
the state since independence from Yugoslavia in 1991 has been swept
out of all the major institutions of government by democratic
means.
</P>
<P>
   With a serious democratic alternative presented by a largely
united, six-party opposition coalition, Croatians voted in big
numbers to turn their back on their fiercely nationalist past, its
tenor and repressions founded in the Yugoslav civil wars.
</P>
<P>
   With Tudjman revered but politically unpopular, his party
tainted with charges of corruption and the economy deeply troubled
by unemployment and unpaid wages and pensions, the opposition won a
large victory in parliamentary elections on Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ivica Racan took office on Jan. 27 and has
already moved to soften nationalist policies, free up the media,
support democratic and human rights, and promote economic
discipline and sacrifice.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the first round of presidential voting, even the relatively
moderate candidate of the Croatian Democratic Union, Mate Granic,
finished in a poor third place, failing to qualify for Monday's
runoff election.
</P>
<P>
   The party, known here by its initials, HDZ, is wounded and is
likely to split, and in an interview last week, Racan himself said
that he feared that the rapid collapse of Tudjman's party was
risky, because it weakened the opposition all governments need.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, the H.D.Z. is falling apart too soon for the
democratic life of the country,'' Racan said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wanted his main coalition partner, Budisa, to win,
and described Mesic's appeal as ``populism with a smiling face.''
But he said that both men were democrats and that he could work
well with either.
</P>
<P>
   The real turning point for Croatia came with the opposition
victory in the parliamentary vote. Both Mesic and Budisa promised
to work to cut back the powers of the imperial presidency Tudjman
built for himself and to make Croatia a parliamentary democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, both men want the president to retain the position of
commander in chief and to have an important, if still vague role in
foreign and security policy. Part of the campaign debate here
focused on whether Budisa or Mesic were harboring secret ambitions
or agendas, and which of the two might work more easily with Racan.
</P>
<P>
   Mesic is less nationalist than Budisa, and has explicitly warned
Bosnian Croats that they must learn to live inside Bosnia and not
look to Zagreb for financial and military support. By doing so,
Mesic ensured the opposition of HDZ voters, who are especially
strong in Bosnia, where ethnic Croatians are allowed to vote in
elections here. Mesic and Racan want to stop that practice, too.
</P>
<P>
   So Mesic aides were particularly concerned about the possibility
of widespread vote fraud in Bosnia organized by the HDZ and its
Bosnian political allies. But voting went smoothly there, officials
said, especially after the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe criticized fraud in the first round and asked
the Croatian state electoral commission to replace its observers.
</P>
<P>
   If he lost, Budisa said he would serve as an ordinary member of
parliament and lead his Social Liberal party. Racan said he would
like Budisa, in that case, to join the government, at least
eventually, but that he doubted that Budisa would change his mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
