r l BC-DRAGON-TEX     02-07 1342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTER THE DRAGON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Millennium-schlmennium. Saturday marked the beginning of Year
4698 _ the Year of the Dragon. Maybe it's because we've all been
reading a lot of Harry Potter lately, but the thought of a year
celebrating the mythological, magical beasts hit with a blast of
fresh, hot air. Who wouldn't want to tap into the dragon's
benevolent and powerful energy, or ``chi''?
</P>
<P>
   The roar of the dragon days begins with 15 days of traditional
Chinese New Year celebration. Rather than stocking up on the Veuve
Cliquot and finding the best all-night party, Chinese families
prepare for the new year by paying debts, cutting their hair,
sweeping out the dirt (and ill fortune) from their homes and
decorating with paper cut-outs with the themes of happiness, wealth
and longevity. Not coincidentally, when the new year dawned this
weekend, rather than spending the day with hot-water bottles,
hangovers and Bowl games, families visited relatives and neighbors,
wishing them good luck. Old grudges are dismissed. Gifts are
exchanged. Feasts are shared.
</P>
<P>
   A dragon year is a cause for special celebration, as the dragon
is the most powerful of the 12 Chinese zodiac signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dragon symbolizes power, fertility, harvest, nature,
everything that is powerful. Usually that means activity,
prosperity and good luck,'' says Mike Xu, an assistant professor of
Chinese studies at Texas Christian University in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   As Martha would say, the dragon is simply a good thing. In
celebration of the new year, we salute the winged beast with this
primer on things dragonian.
</P>
<P>
   Zodiacal beginnings &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The legend behind the 12 signs of Chinese astrology goes
something like this: Buddha invited all the animals to come before
him on Chinese New Year. Only 12 showed up, in this order: rat, ox,
tiger, rabbit, dragon, snake, horse, ram, monkey, rooster, dog and
boar. To thank them, Buddha named a year after each of the
creatures and proclaimed that people born during those specific
years would share some of the characteristics of the year's animal.
Eastern vs. Western dragons &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Know your dragon's family tree. The Eastern dragon is a much
different creature from the dragons of Medieval lore. Western
dragons are the fire-breathing, evil creatures we all know and love
_ and hate. In Eastern cultures, the dragon is revered.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to pinpoint the origins of the dragon, but in
ancient mythology, the scaled, winged beast is said to be akin to
the Great Mother, the water god and the warrior sun god, making it
one of the most powerful creatures. Dragons eventually took on the
roles of Osiris, god of the underworld, and his evil brother Set in
Egyptian mythology.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, the nature of the dragon evolved within
different cultures. In Eastern Asia, the dragon was a benevolent
force; but in Europe, Africa and most everywhere else, it assumed a
belligerent identity. Often it took the form of various creatures _
a dragon might have eagle's feet and wings, a lion's forelimbs and
head, fish scales, antelope horns and a serpentine trunk, tail and
neck. Slaying a dragon was the highest achievement in medieval
lore.
Dragon People &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The dragon, the only mythological animal among a collection of
comparatively ignominious creatures such as the rat and the ox, is
considered the most powerful of the Chinese astrological signs.
</P>
<P>
   People born under the dragon sign are natural leaders. They are
also considered to be lucky, successful and likely to bring wealth
and luck to their families (but beware their flames of aggression
and determination).
</P>
<P>
   Famous dragons? Bruce Lee, Martin Luther King Jr., Grace Kelly,
Christopher Reeve, Frank Sinatra, Mae West, John Lennon, Joan of
Arc, Salvador Dali, Betty Grable, Oliver Hardy, Ernesto ``Che''
Guevara, Florence Nightingale and Shirley Temple Black.
Dragons in Pop Culture &QC;
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to think of ``Beowulf'' as pop culture, but once this
staple of college curricula was indeed contemporary. In case you
don't remember the details from English Lit 101, the hero is slain
by a dragon after he kills the monster Grendel and Grendel's
mother. Since then, even the bad-karma Western dragon has enjoyed
some moments in the spotlight. For instance:
</P>
<P>
   Drago, the digitally animated dragon voiced by Sean Connery in
1996's ``Dragonheart.'' Drago saved a king's life and gave him half
a heart, but when the king turned evil, the knight (Dennis Quaid)
and Drago teamed up to vanquish the corrupt monarch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Puff, the Magic Dragon,'' who lived by the sea, frolicking in
the autumn mists. Children's song by those '60s rascals Peter, Paul
and Mary.
</P>
<P>
   Maleficent, the evil witch of the classic fairy tale ``The
Sleeping Beauty,'' who turns into a dragon (Disney's 1959 film
version makes Maleficent one of the most beautiful Americanized
dragons).
</P>
<P>
   Dungeons &AMP; Dragons, the quintessential role-playing game in
which players take on the identities of wizards and other creatures
in an effort to stay alive and collect treasures.
</P>
<P>
   Mushu, the pint-sized dragon voiced by Eddie Murphy in the 1997
movie ``Mulan,'' which makes its television premiere on the Disney
Channel on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Spyro, an energetic young dragon hero of the popular PlayStation
game ``Spyro the Dragon,'' created by Insomniac Games. His goal is
to rid the Dragon World of Gnorcs, restoring the dragon populace
and reclaiming the dragon treasure.
Eating Dragon? &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The pairing of the dragon and the phoenix goes back to Imperial
China. The dragon, showing the yin or feminine side of nature, was
often used to symbolize the Empress, while the phoenix, symbolizing
the yang or masculine side, was a symbol of the Emperor.
</P>
<P>
   This traditional dish featuring poultry (the phoenix) and ham
(the dragon) celebrates the yin-yang balance.
THE PHOENIX AND THE DRAGON &QC; 
Serves 4 4 thin slices ham 1 whole chicken breast, boned and cut
into two pieces 4 pieces fresh caul fat, see Note 1/4 cup water
chestnut powder OR flour OR cornstarch 4 cups peanut oil, for
deep-frying Vegetable sauce: 2 tablespoons peanut oil 2 whole
cloves garlic, crushed 2 slices fresh gingerroot 4 fresh water
chestnuts, peeled and sliced lengthwise 1/2 cup bamboo shoots,
sliced lengthwise 4 whole scallions, cut in 3-inch pieces 1
tablespoon soy sauce 1 tablespoon Chinese rice wine OR dry sherry
1/2 cup chicken broth 1 teaspoon cornstarch dissolved in 1
tablespoon cold chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   Note: Caul fat is the thin, fatty membrane that lines the
abdominal cavity of pigs or sheep. The pork is considered better.
It looks like a lacy net and is used to wrap dishes like pates. The
membrane melts during baking. Order caul fat through your butcher.
To keep it from tearing, it may be necessary to soak the membrane
in warm salted water to loosen the layers before using.
</P>
<P>
   Lay 2 slices of ham on 1 side of piece of the chicken breast.
Refold the breast, enclosing the ham. Lay breast on a sheet made of
2 pieces of caul fat. Roll up tight. The caul is sticky, so it
needs nothing to seal it. Dust surface with water chestnut powder,
flour or cornstarch. Shake off excess. Repeat with second breast
piece.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in a wok to 350 degrees. Slide the chicken breast
pieces into the oil, one by one. When they've browned (about 5
minutes), remove one from the oil and press it. If it feels mushy,
it needs more cooking. Remove and drain chicken. Slice chicken,
crosswise diagonally, into 1/2-inch pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable sauce: Heat oil in wok and flavor with garlic and
ginger. Remove garlic and ginger and add water chestnuts, bamboo
shoots and scallions to the wok. Stir-fry for 30 seconds, then add
soy sauce, wine or sherry and chicken broth. When liquid boils,
stir in dissolved cornstarch to thicken the sauce. Spread sauce on
platter as a bed for the sliced chicken breast.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Internet Chef (www.ichef.com)
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
