<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-MICH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COPYING REAGAN'S STRATEGY, MCCAIN COURTS DEMOCRATS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ Touching on themes more common in Democratic than
Republican primaries, Sen. John McCain campaigned Monday in auto
factory towns in Michigan, praised unions, called his rival's tax
plan too generous to the rich and said he welcomed the support of
independents and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   While McCain presented a friendly face to the non-Republicans
who could play a crucial role in the Feb. 22 Michigan primary, in
South Carolina he released a tough advertisement criticizing his
main rival for the Republican nomination, Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, and raising questions of trust.
</P>
<P>
   At a town meeting in the Detroit suburb of Warren, McCain said
the United Automobile Workers union and its members had helped
improve the quality of American cars and the competitiveness of the
industry, although he also said he opposed so-called closed shops,
in which all workers are required to join a union.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who also campaigned Monday in Saginaw, 100 miles
northwest of Detroit, praised unions here and in Warren. Asked in
this blue-collar city 70 miles northwest of Detroit about his
support for legislation that would require unions to obtain their
members' permission before making political contributions, the
Arizona Republican said he also wanted companies to obtain their
shareholders' approval before making such donations.
</P>
<P>
   McCain cited the success of former President Ronald Reagan in
attracting support from union workers who usually vote Democratic,
and said at the news conference that he would welcome the support
of such voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we're seeking the Republican vote first, we want the
independents and we would appreciate the Democrats,'' he said,
while stopping short of specifically asking independents and
Democrats to cross party lines. ``Part of the success of President
Reagan was the so-called Reagan Democrats. The essence of the
Republican Party should be to reach out and appeal to a broad cross
section of voters.That's the way you lead the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan primaries are open to voters of any political
affiliation, and a state law even bars residents from registering
by party. Because of a Democratic Party policy that limits the
allocation of delegates based on open primaries, Vice President Al
Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley have pulled out of the primary
here on Feb. 22, and will participate instead in a separate
Democratic caucus on March 11.
</P>
<P>
   Voters going to the polls here on Feb. 22 will receive a single
ballot including not only the Republican primary candidates but
also some local referendums and at least one race for county
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Stewart, a General Motors transmission worker and UAW
member who voted for Reagan in 1980 but usually supports Democrats,
said after attending the town hall meeting that he planned to vote
for McCain. Stewart said that he admired the senator's stance on
campaign finance and added that in November, ``I'll vote for McCain
if he wins the nomination; otherwise I'll vote Democratic.''
</P>
<P>
   He also accused Bush of steering too much of his proposed tax
cuts to the wealthiest families and not enough to working
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Bush's criticism Monday that it was inconsistent
to pursue campaign finance reform while seeking campaign
contributions, McCain told reporters at a campaign stop in Flint
that broad hostility to him from the Republican establishment
demonstrated his independence from special interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``This attack that special interests have any influence on me is
just foolishness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain took a more aggressive tack in the television
advertisement, suggesting that Bush had broken an agreement not to
run a negative campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we really want another politician in the White House
America can't trust?'' the advertisement concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Asked here whether he was calling his opponent untrustworthy,
McCain said the advertisement was meant to indicate that ``the
American people deserve a president they can trust.''
</P>
</TEXT>
