<SLUG> BC-THREES-TRIVIA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WHO'S WHO OF MOVIE SEQUELS
</HEADLINE>
 (Accompanies BC-THREES-TEX) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it weren't for ``Scream`` movies, we were joking the other
day, David Arquette wouldn't have a career (unless you consider a
series of irritating long-distance-company commercials a career).
In fact, if it weren't for the Scream series, he probably wouldn't
have a wife _ at least his current wife, Courteney Cox Arquette,
whom he met while doing ``Scream'' and ``Scream 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Which just goes to show _ there's a lot of trivia in them there
sequels! And talking about Arquette was what inspired us to round
up these tidbits of sequel trivia.
</P>
<P>
   By now, most Kevin Bacon followers know that he appeared in the
first ``Friday the 13th.'' Here are some other actors who appeared
in the series: Crispin Glover (Part IV, officially known as The
Final Chapter); Ghost villain Tony Goldwyn (Part VI); and Welcome
Back, Kotter's Ron Palillo (Part VI).
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Lee Curtis and Donald Pleasance are the names most closely
connected to the Halloween series. Among others who have cropped
up: Dana Carvey (''Halloween 2''); and ``The Cider House Rules' ''
Paul Rudd and Dharma &AMP; Greg's Mitchell Ryan (both in ``Halloween:
The Curse of Michael Myers,'' the series' sixth entry). The most
recent installment, 1998's ``Halloween H20,'' was Curtis' first
Halloween movie in 17 years and the first in which most cast
members had made a name for themselves before the movie was
released.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wes Craven gets most of the credit, other directors got
early breaks with the ``Nightmare on Elm Street'' series (the most
imaginative and underappreciated movies in the slasher genre).
Chuck Russell, who directed Nightmare 3, went on to direct Jim
Carrey in ``The Mask'' and Arnold Schwarzenegger in ``Eraser.''
Stephen Hopkins, who directed Nightmare 5, also directed 1998's
``Lost in Space.'' Most notable of all was Nightmare 4 director
Renny Harlin, who directed last year's ``Deep Blue Sea'' as well as
another significant sequel, ``Die Hard With a Vengeance.''
</P>
<P>
   Actors who got an early break from ``Nightmare on Elm Street''
movies include Johnny Depp and ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit?'' voice
Charles Fleischer (the original Nightmare), and Patricia Arquette
and Laurence Fishburne (Nightmare 3).
</P>
<P>
   Nightmare director Wes Craven pops up in his own ``Scream'' as a
janitor dressed like Nightmare's Freddy Krueger. ``Scream 2's''
alumni include Portia de Rossi, now a familiar face on Ally McBeal,
and Heather Graham, who was a Powers girl in ``Austin Powers: The
Spy Who Shagged Me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Godfather Part III'' contains a couple of the most glaring
continuity errors in movie history. A subplot concerns the Vatican
of Pope John Paul I _ even though he died in 1978, and the film
takes place in 1979. Not that you would know by a copy of The New
York Times seen in the film _ the paper's 1990 copyright date is
easily visible.
</P>
<P>
   Among the people who have survived notoriously bad sequels are
Michael Caine (''Beyond the Poseidon Adventure,'' ``Jaws the
Revenge''); Sally Field (''Beyond the Poseidon Adventure''); James
Earl Jones (''Exorcist II: The Heretic''); Harrison Ford (''Force
10 From Navarone''); Michelle Pfeiffer (''Grease 2''); and John
Travolta (''Staying Alive'').
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9713 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-BRADLEY-BOS &LR;      02-07 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRADLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY DECRIES REPEAL OF FLORIDA AFFIRMATIVE ACTION LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ Bill Bradley, convinced that blacks would back his
struggling campaign if they only knew him, accused Florida Governor
Jeb Bush Monday of committing ``a clear wrong'' and a lapse in
leadership by repealing the state's affirmative action program.
</P>
<P>
   Scrambling to chip into Vice President Al Gore's overwhelming
support among blacks, Bradley launched the attack on the Florida
governor immediately before heading for South Carolina to charge
Texas Governor George W. Bush with a similar act.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that he has demonstrated a lack of vision and
leadership by repealing affirmative action laws,'' Bradley said of
the Florida governor during a town meeting in the Ybor City section
of Tampa. ``He did this despite the fact that affirmative action is
about fairness. It's about social justice. It's about making sure
all Americans have a fair chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida's primary is not until March 14, a week after the big
15-state primary Tuesday that is expected to make or break
Bradley's candidacy. And South Carolina, where the Democratic
primary is scheduled later, is largely inconsequential in the
Democratic race.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley is banking on his appearances in the two states to
boost his appeal to black voters and liberals. By nearly all
accounts, Bradley will be unable to break Gore's momentum toward
the Democratic nomination unless he can woo such core Democratic
constituencies as blacks, Latinos and liberals.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bradley has made racial unity a central theme of his
20-year political career, he has watched with frustration as the
nation's black establishment has buoyed Gore's candidacy. Gore, in
addition to basking in the reflected glow of President Clinton's
strong bond with black voters, spent much of Clinton's
administration cultivating black leaders in anticipation of a
challenge for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, in chastising the Florida governor over affirmative
action, said, ``Giving people opportunity, investing them with
responsbility, holding them accountable is not a preference or a
quota. It is the standard by which the mark of progress is made in
this country.''
</P>
<P>
   To the crowd's applause, he said, ``I strongly oppose the action
taken by Governor Bush because I believe that justice is one of the
most enduring and abiding principles that make up the promise of
America. When opportunity is taken away or snuffed out, justice is
denied and progress is brought to a standstill.''
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, Bradley plans to renew his criticism of the
Texas governor for recently taking his campaign for the Republican
presidential nomination to Bob Jones University, a fundamentalist
Christian college in the state, which lost its tax exempt status in
the 1970s because the school engaged in racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The two-pronged offensive against the Bushes comes eight years
after Bradley attacked their father, then-President George Bush,
for allowing race to become an issue in the 1988 election by
failing to repudiate an ad criticizing former Massachusetts
Governor Michael S. Dukakis over the furlough of Willie Horton.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, in a speech on the Senate floor, also blasted Bush for
opposing the 1964 Civil Rights Act when Bush ran for senator in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley launched his stepped-up appeal to black voters at a
predominantly black church in Queens, N.Y., on Sunday, when he cast
himself as a leader whom blacks could trust and respect as
president.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday Bradley is scheduled to broaden his appeal to black
voters when he delivers a major education address in Ohio calling
for policies that would better serve disadvantaged students and
their families.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
