<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9715 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-WASHINGTON-DC-     02-07 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-WASHINGTON-DC-2TAKES-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRO AND MURRAY: WASHINGTON, D.C.'S LATEST ATTRACTIONS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BARBARA GAMAREKIAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Visitors to Washington frequently arrive with a mental itinerary
taking them from the lofty precincts of Capitol Hill and the White
House to the greensward of the Mall with its museums, monuments and
memorials. And visit them all one must, for they provide an
encyclopedic view of America's culture and historic legacy.
</P>
<P>
   But despite this city's reputation as a static place where
little changes from year to year beyond the election cycle, there
are always new delights to discover.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most beguiling additions is the National Gallery of
Art's Sculpture Garden, which opened in May. It has already
attracted more than a million visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The Sculpture Garden has been a long time coming. A garden was
first envisioned in 1791 by Pierre Charles L'Enfant who, upon
laying out the master plan for the capital city, stipulated that
this very site, what is now 6.1 acres on the north side of the
Mall, be a ``landscaped park'' with ``copious water.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 years later, a $10 million grant from the Morris
and Gwendolyn Cafritz Foundation helped realize L'Enfant's dream.
The fanciful garden, designed by Laurie D. Olin of Olin
Partnership, beckons the passer-by to ``come in, look, explore.''
Curvilinear marble benches and a double row of linden trees
surround a pool and central fountain that in summer plays an
ever-changing water dance and in winter is alive with ice skaters
gliding to music under strands of twinkling white lights. As
twilight deepens on winter evenings, the spotlit sculptures provide
a luminous backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen works by artists including Mark di Suvero, Isamu
Noguchi and Joan Miro are situated among the magnolias and redbud
and towering elm and cypress trees.
</P>
<P>
   Calder's ``Cheval Rouge'' (``Red Horse'') catches the eye from a
distance against the monumental Washington skyline. Other works
appear as you make your way along winding paths: among them
Ellsworth Kelly's abstract ``Stele II'' and Barry Flanagan's
``Thinker on a Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The geometry of the Washington skyline was taken into
consideration when we were siting the sculpture,'' said Earl A.
Powell III, director of the gallery. Many of the artists
collaborated on the installation of their works. A sculpture by
Frank Stella is expected to join the collection, Powell said, and
there will be other additions over time.
</P>
<P>
   The guards have been hard pressed to keep children from climbing
Sol LeWitt's terraced ``Four-Sided Pyramid'' and hoisting
themselves up on Louise Bourgeois' bronze ``Spider.'' New plantings
have been artfully added to isolate and protect some of the most
``enticing'' sculptures from ``the curious and overzealous,''
Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   On a visit in the fall several dozen people relaxed on the
terrace of the Pavilion cafe, an eye-catching Art Nouveau-style
structure, which will open as a glass-enclosed bistro in the summer
</P>
<P>
   A few feet away Dr. Luke Faber, a surgeon visiting from Dubuque,
Iowa, gazed at George Rickey's ``Cluster of Four Cubes,'' a kinetic
sculpture revolving in the breeze. ``It doesn't tell me which
direction the wind is coming from _ they seem to flow against each
other,'' he mused to his wife, Mary Elaine. ``I guess that's the
art part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the garden under a canopy of trees, the Dimitropoulous
family, from Atlanta, had plopped down on Scott Burton's polished
granite chairs, aptly named ``Six-Part Seating.'' Twelve-year-old
Alex said his favorite sculpture was Claes Oldenburg and Coosje van
Bruggen's giant orange ``Typewriter Eraser, Scale X,'' a Pop art
rendering of an eraser leaning precariously on edge, fiberglass
brush bristles waving skyward.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Alex didn't know what it was,'' his father noted, smiling.
``We had to explain it to him because he had never seen a
typewriter eraser _ or a typewriter, for that matter.'' For his
part, Dimitropoulous said he was intrigued by Roy Lichtenstein's
``House 1.'' ``It looks simple but it's very complicated,'' he said
of the sculpture whose dimensions appear to change as you approach.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, William O'Neil, 5, and his brother, Daniel, 3,
unmindful of the protective plantings, circumvented the cartoonish
red and yellow house, poking their heads through windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, kids, out of there,'' called their father, and the
children scampered off to their next target: the LeWitt pyramid.
``It's an igloo!'' Daniel declared of the 15-foot white sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   A different but equally engaging experience can be had with a
quick trip, by Metro, across the Potomac River to Arlington, Va.,
for a visit to the Newseum. Since opening in April 1997, it too has
proved a hit with children and adults _ recently reaching the 1.2
million mark in visitors.
</P>
<P>
   As its name suggests, the $50 million, 72,000-square-foot museum
is devoted to the history of communication and news gathering. It
is financed by the Freedom Forum, a nonpartisan foundation
dedicated to free press and free speech.
</P>
<P>
   With its vaulted spaces and slick design, the high-tech museum
is visually exciting, and cleverly combines education and
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The best spot to get a fix on the place is the 220-seat,
dome-covered theater. A continuously running 10-minute film,
``What's News?,'' narrated by Charles Osgood, helps orient
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the museum you'll find an interactive newsroom, a
News History Gallery, two minitheaters with continuous films, a
radio-TV state-of-the-art broadcast studio and control room, and a
series of exhibits and seminars featuring media personalities.
</P>
<P>
   The News History Gallery traces the evolution of communication
from talking drums to the printing press, radio, television and,
finally, the global village and satellite television. Among the
artifacts are a pen owned by Charles Dickens and pages from Bob
Woodward's handwritten Watergate notes.
</P>
<P>
   For the nostalgia buffs, front pages proclaim: ``Scopes Found
Guilty,'' ``Babe Ruth Smashes Own Record''; and with a wand you can
hear, once again, the voices of Edward R. Murrow, Walter Winchell
and H.V. Kaltenborn.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Gillette of Camano Island, Wash., stood transfixed before
television replays of the night Robert F. Kennedy was shot and the
October day in 1987 when Baby Jessica was rescued from the well in
Midland, Texas ``I thought this place would probably just be a pat
on the back for journalism,'' she said, ``but it gives you a better
insight into how it all works.''
</P>
<P>
   It is in the interactive newsroom that the senses are bombarded
from all sides. A 126-foot-long Video News Wall simultaneously
broadcasts breaking news from a half-dozen cities around the world
as a news zipper flashes the latest headlines. Below the video
display is a wall of the day's front pages from 70 newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   At touch-screen video monitors, people try their hand at being a
reporter covering a story, or an editor figuring out the day's news
budget. And teen-agers cluster around booths where they can
broadcast a radio sports event or photograph themselves for a
magazine cover.
</P>
<P>
   The adjacent Freedom Park is a more contemplative spot, an
outdoor exhibit area that pays tribute to the 1,029 journalists who
died while reporting the news. Installations including cobblestones
from the Warsaw Ghetto and a bronze casting of the Rev. Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr.'s jail-cell door in Birmingham can be found there.
A 32-foot-long section of the Berlin Wall and one of the 30-foot
guard towers have been added most recently.
</P>
<P>
   The capital cityscape has had some other changes. The new Ronald
Reagan Building and International Trade Center, the second largest
federal building (after the Pentagon), now looms on 1300
Pennsylvania Avenue. Its Atrium Gallery offers rotating exhibits
(on display through March 15 is the work of six artists from
Senegal) and there are guided tours, a food court and a Washington
Visitor Information Center. Across the Mall at Third and
Independence, a giant excavation foretells the coming of the
National Museum of the American Indian scheduled to open in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Washington Monument has been metamorphosing. Undergoing
a two-year restoration, it was ``wrapped'' in blue mesh by the
architect Michael Graves to hide the scaffolding.
</P>
<P>
   Now with the restoration winding down, the blue mesh is gone and
the scaffolding is being dismantled. But during the years it was
clad in its festive garb, it was symbolic, one would like to think,
of the nation's ability to surprise. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Sculpture Garden at the National Gallery of Art is at
Seventh Street, between Constitution Avenue and Madison Drive, on
the Mall. It is open 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Monday through Saturday and
11 a.m. to 6 p.m. Sunday. From mid-November to mid-March, the
skating rink is open until 10 p.m. Sunday through Thursday and 11
p.m. Friday and Saturday (opening times same as the sculpture
garden). The charge for skating is from $4 to $5.50 (there are
discounts for students and seniors); skates can be rented for
$2.50. Information: (202) 737-4215. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Newseum is at 1101 Wilson Boulevard, Arlington, Va.; (703)
284-3544. It is a short walk from the Rosslyn Metro stop on the
Blue or Orange lines. Closed Monday and Tuesday until March, when
the museum is open Tuesday as well. Open 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Free. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Ronald Reagan Building and International Trade Center at
1300 Pennsylvania Avenue NW, (202) 312-1300, is open 7 a.m. to 7
p.m. weekdays, 11 a.m. to 7 p.m. Saturday. Free guided tours are
available on Monday, Wednesday and Friday at 11 a.m. beginning at
the concierge desk at the 14th Street entrance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
