<HEADLINE>
AUTO INSURERS SEEK OEM OPTION IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Auto insurers Monday pushed for the right to sell
drivers a $37 optional rider that would require certain vehicle
repairs to be made with original manufacturer's parts, instead of
cheaper generics.
</P>
<P>
   Generic parts have come under fire over the last year in the
wake of a billion-dollar court decision in Illinois and a Consumer
Reports study that indicated some parts may be unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   Auto insurers kept a low profile at Monday's hearing before
Insurance Commissioner Linda Ruthard. But auto body shops slammed
the proposal as an attempt to escape liability associated with what
they called ``counterfeit parts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it mind-boggling as to what this two-tiered policy
represents,'' said Christopher Colo, president of the Massachusetts
Auto Body Association, which says generic parts should not be used
until their safety can be demonstrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the real world of insurance, a diamond would not be
replaced with a cubic zirconia,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthardt gave no hint Monday of how she will rule.
</P>
<P>
   But Daniel Johnson, head head of the Automobile Insurers Bureau,
an industry group, said Ruthardt's staff has urged the bureau to
back the rider.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthardt has defended the use of generic parts in the past.
</P>
<P>
   To keep insurance rates down, state regulations require the use
of cheaper generics (or rebuilt or used brand-name parts), unless a
new brand-name part is available at a lower price or the car has
less than 15,000 miles on it. Generic parts are supposed to be used
only if they are ``of like kind and quality'' to a manufacturer's
brand-name parts.
</P>
<P>
   That standard, which is used in many states, has come under fire
since a $1.1 billion court judgment in October against State Farm
Mutual Automobile Insurance Co. for using inferior generic parts in
repairs to customers' cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, Consumer Reports had published an article on the
issue, entitled ``Shoddy Auto Parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Many insurers, including several operating in the Bay State,
stopped using generic parts outside of Massachusetts after the
court decision. They continue to use them here, however, because of
the state mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies say the rider would merely give consumers an
option, without driving up rates for everyone. The rider would be
triggered if the damaged part could not be repaired, and it would
apply only to exterior or cosmetic parts, such as fenders and
hoods. On average, the rider would cost an extra $37.
</P>
<P>
   The rider would in effect put the burden on drivers to decide
whether it's worth the extra money to buy parts from manufacturers
such as Ford and Toyota. It's not an easy call, given the
conflicting data. Many consumers are not aware that insurers call
for generic parts when authorizing repairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
