A9726 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-OTHERS-TEX     02-07 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-OTHERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE OTHERS' SEEMS TO HAVE BARELY A GHOST OF A CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   College student Marian Kitt doesn't know what she wants to do
with her life, which is fine, since she has little say in the
matter anyhow. We see why in the opening moments of ``The Others,''
an ambitious but rather calculating and distant suspense drama that
premiered on NBC last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Jolted from bed, Marian staggers into the bathroom of her
dormitory room, sees a toy ducky floating in a tub full of water,
and pulls it out. Suddenly, a mummy-type figure rises from the
tub's depths, arms out, as if wanting to pull Marian in.
</P>
<P>
   Later, we learn that the thing is a woman, a dead one at that,
who chased down pills with alcohol a year earlier, in that
dormitory, in that room, in that bathtub.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does stuff like this happen to you a lot?'' a stranger wants
to know in the next scene, cornering Marian in a library that looks
as spooky as everything else in this series.
</P>
<P>
   Marian: ``What do you mean?''
</P>
<P>
   Stranger: ``Psychic phenomenon. 'Cause I know some people you
really should meet.''
</P>
<P>
   The people she eventually meets, for better or worse, are a
small, mysterious and awfully creepy group of men and women who
share the extrasensory ability to reach ``the other side,'' as they
refer to their communication with deceased souls.
</P>
<P>
   Like superheroes with different modes of besting their enemy,
each is represented by an extrasensory gift. There's John Aylward
(ER) as Albert, a vision-impaired grouch with a heightened sixth
sense, and Gabriel Macht as Mark Gabriel, the passionate and
way-too-cute medical intern blessed (or is that cursed?) with the
gift of feeling the pain of others. (What, and he's sensitive,
too?)
</P>
<P>
   The cast also includes Bill Cobbs as a famed medium, able to
enter the other side and return to tell about it; Melissa Crider as
a store-front ghost caller; Kevin J. O'Conner as a homeless
``seer,'' someone who sees things before they occur; and John
Billingsley as a folklore professor who brings the group together
and records these paranormal events as giddily as a kid with a
bunch of new trading cards.
</P>
<P>
   Though reluctant at first (she calls the Others ``freaks''),
Marian, played by Julianne Nicholson, finally concedes to her
special ability, which is to see into the past and the afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry,'' she's told by Billingsley's Miles Ballard.
``They're all gifted people ... you know. Freaks. Like you.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how ``The Others'' will serve as weekly entertainment will
be developed over the next two episodes. Since their ``gifts'' are
used to help those in need, they interact with those alive and
dead. Such as a deceased man destined to walk the earth as long as
his wife blames herself for letting him drive that morning with
their infant son.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for ``The Others'' comes from Steven Spielberg's shop.
Glen Morgan and James Wong, who have experience with the dark and
paranormal, having written scripts for ``The X-Files'' and
``Millennium,'' are executive producers. They appear to be rather
deft at making everyday, nonthreatening sights _ doorknobs and
staircases, that sort of thing _ exude unexplained menace.
</P>
<P>
   As with most supernatural dramas, though, ``The Others'' will
take a while to find a tone balanced enough to lure more than a
handful of viewers. It doesn't help that no character jumps out
right away; even Nicholson, a former model who had a breakout
performance as the headstrong feminist in ``The Love Letter,'' is
rather forgettable. Which is a shame, since she's well-cast as the
overwhelmed newcomer and does a nice job of conveying Marian's
emotional vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   Not helping matters is that the so-so special effects do nothing
to camouflage what is, for the time being anyway, nothing more than
trite drama with high intentions.
</P>
<P>
   They better get with it fast. NBC has ordered only 13 episodes.
Worst case scenario is that ``The Others'' will go the way of a
similar NBC series, ``Sleepwalkers.'' The producer of that show,
about a group of people using dreams to solve problems, had asked
for patience, promising clear, engaging story lines down the line.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, ``Sleepwalkers'' never made it that far.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
