<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-YORK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PLANS A GOOD YEAR FOR NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BUDGET-CLINTON) 
(sw) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Whether it was Hillary Rodham Clinton's run for the
Senate or just Democratic politics at work in a prosperous election
year, President Clinton's proposed budget lavishes New York City
with money for important programs.
</P>
<P>
   Schools, housing, health care and job training _ all issues
Democrats love to claim as their own on the campaign trail _ are
among the programs that stand to receive a windfall this year if
Congress gives Clinton what he wants. In fact, most cities, which
withstood a long fiscal dry spell for years, will do better in next
year's budget.
</P>
<P>
   Although the picture of how New York City stands to benefit from
next year's budget requests is sketchy, a few details did emerge
today.
</P>
<P>
   New York City would receive $14.3 billion for low-income housing
vouchers, a $3.7 billion increase from last year. Public hospitals
would get a temporary reprieve on reimbursing the federal
government for Medicare costs. And Clinton wants to add $1 billion
to the pot for Head Start in New York City, bringing the total to
$6.2 billion. Another $450 million would go toward reducing class
sizes, for a total of $1.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., calls it ``probably the best
budget for New York City in years.''
</P>
<P>
   But for New Yorkers, Clinton's largesse, at least on paper,
raises the question: Coincidence?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those instances where good substance and good
politics coincide,'' said Schumer. ``I think he would have
emphasized education and stopped the hospital cuts, whether Hillary
was running or not, but it will clearly benefit her, and nothing is
wrong with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget requests would also secure $3.3 billion for
transportation programs for New York City, about $250 million more
than last year, and steer $1.2 billion toward training the city's
young people for jobs, an increase of $240 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
