A9731 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-FRANCE-DISNEY-     02-07 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FRANCE-DISNEY-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTS, ACTION IN FRANCE FOR SECOND DISNEY PARK  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The early struggles of Disneyland Paris, which the Walt
Disney Co. opened at Marne-la-Vallee east of Paris in 1992, may
have led some to believe that Europeans don't like amusement parks.
But in fact, the eventual huge success of the park prompted Disney
to announce in September that it would build a second theme park
next door to the first.
</P>
<P>
   The leftist Paris daily Liberation recalled that some had
described the arrival of the first park as a ``cultural
Chernobyl.'' Yet that did not deter Disney, which owns 39 percent
of the company that runs Disneyland Paris, from announcing plans
for a new $615 million, 62-acre park that will focus on film
studios, animation and television.
</P>
<P>
   The official opening is planned for April 2002, 10 years from
the inauguration of the first park. Nor did it discourage the
French authorities, who are delighted with the prospect of 5,000
jobs that the new park is expected to generate.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever some Europeans may think about theme parks, the
majority seem to be voting with their feet. In the year that ended
Sept. 30, Disneyland Paris drew over 12.5 million visitors, more
than any other attraction in France. Only about 41 percent were
from France, with 17 percent from Belgium, Luxembourg and the
Netherlands, 15 percent from Britain and 10 percent from Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``In California, we needed 35 years to reach those results, even
though the park there is larger,'' said Gilles Pelisson, chief
executive of Euro Disney SA, the company that operates the French
Disney park.
</P>
<P>
   The planned studio park is not a first for Europe. A park called
Movie World near Bottrop, Germany was recently sold by Warner
Brothers, the film and entertainment unit of Time Warner, to an
American company called Premier Parks; Warner Brothers and Premier
are building another movie park outside Madrid, to open in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney project in France will have the familiar features:
Guided tours of television and movie studios, demonstrations of
special effects, a half-hour stunt show in which actors portraying
secret agents attempt to arrest a band of terrorists on a set that
recreates a Mediterranean village.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's entry into the world of European theme parks was not an
easy one. Disney spent roughly $5 billion, much of it borrowed, to
develop the original park, only to swing open its pink Victorian
gingerbread gatehouse in 1992 in the midst of a European recession.
</P>
<P>
   The park's hotels drew so few guests that some had to be
shuttered temporarily. To hold costs down, Disney kept salaries
low, which over the years has led to strikes by disgruntled
employees, mainly low-paid performers.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Disney's original marketing strategy for the park
proved a flop. Originally named Euro Disneyland, signaling the
parent company's intention to reach out beyond France to all of
Europe, the park was soon quietly rebaptized Disneyland Paris, in
recognition of the need to focus on national markets.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising for the park was also redesigned along national
lines, taking into account the fact that features of the park that
appealed, say, to Germans would not be the same ones that drew
Dutch or British visitors. Wine was added to Disney menus, an
omission that had irritated the French, and perhaps most important,
ticket prices were temporarily reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to these initiatives, annual attendance quickly took off.
By the mid-1990s, Disneyland Paris was attracting more than 9
million visitors a year. Still, as the interest burden on Euro
Disney's debt caused financial losses to mount, the company was
forced in 1995 to obtain a five-year debt rescheduling agreement
from banks and forfeiture of management fees from the parent Walt
Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   For the fiscal year 1998-99, which ended Sept. 30, Euro Disney
recently reported a $24 million net profit. Though that was 46
percent less than the year before, the drop was attributed mainly
to a resumption of Euro Disney's payment of management fees to the
Walt Disney Co. and to stagnant attendance, which was hurt by the
World Cup soccer tournament in France in the summer of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Disney was buoyed by the rise in occupancy rates at the
six big hotels at Disneyland Paris to 82.6 percent for the year
that ended in September, from 80.9 percent the year before.
</P>
<P>
   So successful has Disneyland Paris been at drawing crowds that
some local politicians in the Marne-la-Vallee area are growing
nervous. Euro Disney is pushing to increase the returns on land it
bought in the early phase of the project, and this spring a
megamall built by an outside developer and designed to be Europe's
largest is set to open at Serris, next door to the original park.
</P>
<P>
   On one weekend in late October, when crowds flooded into
Disneyland Paris, highways leading to the park were completely
blocked by traffic. The addition of the Serris mall, plus the new
park, some local leaders say, will lead to continuous gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the local Communist Party demanded an immediate
study of the possible impact the mall and park will have on local
roads; not to be outdone, the conservative Assembly for the
Republic appealed to the ministers in Paris responsible for
transportation and the environment for early action to double the
size of the A4 highway that links the French capital and the park.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0449 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9734 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-CHINA-BEIJING-     02-07 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CHINA-BEIJING-2TAKES-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK IN TIME IN OLD BEIJING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is still possible, just barely, to get a glimpse of what
daily life for Beijingers was like at the last turn of the century.
You can't do it by touring the Forbidden City or by competing for
dubious antiques in the ersatz Qing dynasty market of Liulichang.
But you can by taking a relaxed stroll through one of the city's
oldest residential quarters, near the string of willow-lined lakes
to the northwest of the Forbidden City above Beihai Park.
</P>
<P>
   In my first week in Beijing, I was introduced to a particular
walk that transformed my impression of what is generally a
frenzied, frazzling city, stripped of its history. I have retraced
the same path several times since, always finding something
different and always feeling rejuvenated by the slowed pace, the
human scale and just enough remnants of the old days to fire the
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   This is no museum; the courtyard houses that line the
neighborhood's lanes were desecrated during the Mao years and are
often falling apart, and you can't let yourself be chagrined when
two familiar yellow arches poke out above a vista of sloping tiled
roofs. But in the alleys, or hutongs, that surround the lakes, and
on one ancient lane in particular _ one not described in most
guidebooks _ you can discern both past and present.
</P>
<P>
   Like most good travel experiences, this one started with a lucky
break. Two years ago, on the plane to Beijing where my family was
about to take up residence, our 5-year-old daughter, Cara, started
playing with a girl named Lida in a nearby seat. The ice broken, my
wife, Libby, and I struck up a conversation with the parents, Wu
Hung, a Beijing-born professor of art history at the University of
Chicago, and his wife, Judith Zeitlin, also a professor at Chicago.
We made vague promises to get together during their brief visit to
his family home.
</P>
<P>
   I scarcely imagined what a spirit-saver this tenuous appointment
would turn out to be. Our first days in Beijing were forbidding:
the air was acrid; the chaotic roadways seemed too dangerous to
cross, and the city composed of dusty construction sites and
undistinguished high-rises. We wondered what we were getting into.
</P>
<P>
   Then our new friends called and asked if we'd like to visit the
neighborhood where Hung grew up and his parents still lived. It is
one of the few remaining hutong neighborhoods in the city _ most of
them, regarded by authorities as slums to be given over to
developers, have been bulldozed; it lies just south of the lake
called Houhai, the second and largest of the three so-called rear
lakes.
</P>
<P>
   On a languid fall afternoon, we walked along the south edge of
Houhai, where we saw men tending what must be the world's longest
fishing poles. We dipped into the adjacent maze of alleys and saw
Hung's childhood home, a rectangular structure of brick with a
courtyard in the middle that, like most such houses, has seen
better days.
</P>
<P>
   We continued walking along the lake toward the east, crossing
the famed Silver Ingot Bridge that divides Houhai from Qianhai, the
smaller lake to the south. Then Hung led us along Old Pipe Lane, an
ancient shopping street, to the Drum Tower, one of the city's major
landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Hung was back in Beijing and I asked him to
accompany me on the same route again while I took notes. While I
had the benefit of a native guide, any tourist with a map and ready
smiles could enjoy the same walk in two or three hours: if you get
lost in meandering alleys, just say ``Houhai?'' (pronounced HO-hi)
with a quizzical look and you'll be directed back to the lake's
edge, where orientation is easy.
</P>
<P>
   For those who prefer organized tours, some of this same
territory _ though not Old Pipe Lane, thankfully _ is visited by
the Hutong Tours on pedicabs that can be arranged through hotels.
These tours have become so popular that in the fall and spring you
have to dodge pedicab caravans as you walk the alleys _ with the
unfortunate effect that more residents are keeping their compound
gates shut.
</P>
<P>
   One can make this trek starting from the Drum Tower, just east
of Houhai, but I like to start on the west side of Houhai, where
you walk in from busy Deshengmennei Street and then almost
immediately, as you get to the lake's edge and stroll under the
willows next to grizzled fishermen, experience a palpable slowdown
in rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   The three man-made lakes have their own rich history: during the
Mongolian Yuan dynasty in the 13th and 14th centuries, including
the time when Marco Polo visited, they were connected up with the
Grand Canal and served as ports receiving boatloads of rice from
southern China.
</P>
<P>
   The surrounding neighborhoods are dotted with homes of the
formerly rich and powerful, including Manchu gentlemen of the Qing
dynasty, which ended early this century. Today, the lakes are plied
by the occasional pedal boat and gondolas that were recently
introduced and can be rented at Qianhai.
</P>
<P>
   Walking along the southern shore of Houhai you'll soon encounter
a little amusement park, where children jump on trampolines and
drive small electric cars in a rink. Walk on and a bigger park area
opens up along the side. On any day you are apt to see many older
men ``walking'' their pet birds, as the Chinese phrase puts it.
Mostly, they hang the cages from trees, where the birds sing in the
fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   Mornings and late afternoon, you'll see elderly men and women
from the adjacent alleys practicing tai qi, or perhaps a group of
20 doing mild exercises together. Other clusters of men are huddled
around games of mah-jongg or cards.
</P>
<P>
   About three-fourths of the way to the east end of Houhai, just
after a statue of a bearded man doing exercises, is where I turn
off to the south into the alleyways. There is no one thing to see,
just the remains of a classic Beijing neighborhood, some of it in
disrepair, other parts being renovated or rebuilt altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on weather and time, you may see children playing or
elders gossiping in the lanes, but most life goes on inside the
courtyard homes. These all have gray walls facing the alleys, with
big double doors for an entrance, sometimes surrounded by intricate
detail work in stone or wood. Hung pointed out some extra-wide
gates that signified homes of the rich.
</P>
<P>
   But the stone beasts that once guarded many entrances are mostly
gone _ destroyed by Red Guards rampaging against ``feudalism''
during Mao Zedong's Cultural Revolution from 1966 to 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Without being too intrusive you can peek through open doors. You
may see someone washing clothes or doing other household chores.
What you will seldom see is the original large gardens that gave
these courtyard houses their name: during the Mao era, several
families were often squeezed into one family's home, and the
central gardens were filled with crude brick structures that remain
today. Most of the compounds are still shared by two or three
families. Plumbing is primitive; heating is usually with coal
bricks. Low incomes as well as uncertainty about land rights and
city policy have meant residents have felt little incentive to fix
up their buildings. Yet there is a shared sense that this
neighborhood is one of the last, best examples of a special Beijing
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   You may come across what, for better or for worse, is a possible
harbinger of the area's future. Hong Kong developers have rebuilt a
few of the courtyard homes from scratch, complete with garages. One
can imagine this becoming a choice neighborhood for a new breed of
the rich and powerful.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Once you work your way back to lakeside you are nearly at the
Silver Ingot Bridge. The current marble structure was built only in
the 1980s. But the bridge has a special place in Beijing lore, long
described as one of the city's 16 most famous scenes _ in this
case, as the perfect spot from which to view the Western Hills.
These days smog usually obscures the hills, but this remains a
colorful spot, a low-rise mini-world with a distinctly Chinese
feel.
</P>
<P>
   Across from the bridge, built in a traditional style, is a
venerable restaurant specializing in roast lamb called Kaorouji.
Around to the left side of the restaurant, to the north, perhaps 60
feet from the bridge, is the entrance to Old Pipe Lane, a curving
little street that ends near the Drum Tower, built in 1420, with
drums that marked the time.
</P>
<P>
   The street's name refers to a long-renowned shop that sold
tobacco and those long pipes once favored by Chinese. (The lane is
not labeled in English signs and if you aren't sure you're on the
right one, ask and point: the name in Chinese is Yan Dai Xie Jie,
pronounced yen dye sheeay jeeay.)
</P>
<P>
   By this point I am always ready for a snack and, luckily, a few
yards along the lane are open stalls and a bakery with a street
window selling a delicious array of traditional Beijing breads and
dumplings. I prefer the bakery's da bing, large, chewy flat breads
that look like baked pizza dough and are served fresh and hot.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy a half of a wheel for a couple of yuan, or splurge
on the whole thing. You might also sample some little saucer-shaped
corn breads and tasty xiao bing, pancakes stuffed with scallions or
meats.
</P>
<P>
   I like this narrow lane precisely because it hasn't been
restored. Mixed among the older shops and telltale signs of a
bygone era are an abundance of hair cutters and tailors and wooden
pushcarts offering everything from potatoes to persimmons. A few
shops sell pirated video compact discs. A number of the storefronts
still sport century-old slabs of wood, including the characteristic
heavy eaves across the top.
</P>
<P>
   Steps beyond the bakery, at No. 57 on the lane, is a cluttered
little shop, only a few yards wide and deep, run by an ancient
couple selling pet accessories, a strange variety of old- and
new-style pipes, kites, fishing poles, beer and other odds and
ends.
</P>
<P>
   Here, pet accessories doesn't mean flea collars and catnip: they
sell cricket cages carved from gourds and wooden grass-hopper cages
and tiny porcelain bowls to put in your bird cage, all of which
make nifty souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   If you're feeling tired by now, a bit farther at No. 40 you can
get a head and neck massage, about $2 for 30 minutes. Just past
that on the opposite side at No. 37 are the decaying remains of a
Buddhist temple, its roof grown over with grass. A sign on the wall
declares this building a protected cultural relic, but as Hung
noted, ``After all this destruction, it's meaningless.'' The people
living inside now, though, do a fine job of mounting and framing
traditional paintings and calligraphy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Next, at No. 21, is a white building that once housed a large
bath house: a community social center where people bathed and
talked for hours on end. Operating here for more than a century, a
commercial bath house remains on a smaller scale, serving local
residents who have no showers in their crumbling former courtyards.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, at No. 5, near the mouth of the lane, is the structure
that once housed the famous pipe and tobacco store. The store
continued operating to the mid-1950s, when the Communists took over
private shops. Part of the building is boarded up, part is occupied
by a tailor, but much of the 19th-century wooden storefront
remains.
</P>
<P>
   You can make out traces of paint on some heavily grained former
signboards, and along the top are curved cast-iron racks from which
signs once dangled. It takes a bit of effort, but if you pause for
a minute you can call to mind the scene here a hundred years ago,
when bearded Manchus came in to sample the latest shipment of
Yunnan tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   That reverie complete, you spill out into a jangling modern
street, Di'anmenwai, and modern Beijing. Worth a look across the
street is a shop selling old-style copper and brass pots.
</P>
<P>
   At this point you can bail out and flag a cab, to attack the
steep steps of the 15th-century Drum Tower another day. Or you can
walk over to the tower that looms less than half a black away, buy
your $1.25 ticket and climb up for a great view of Beijing and the
cluttered hutongs you just traversed. In which case, after you
descend, you may want to finish your afternoon in the teahouse
inside the Bell Tower just to the north. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those who prefer to take the guided Hutong Tour, in a pedicab,
can book a morning or afternoon tour through most hotels. The price
is about $22 a person, at 8 yuan to the dollar. The tours visit the
Drum Tower, courtyard neighborhoods and Prince Gong's mansion, on
the southwest edge of the neighborhood, a royal residence with
gardens that was converted into a museum and teahouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Drum Tower, on Gulou Dajie, is normally open from 9 a.m. to
4:30 p.m. Admission to this historic site _ the climb to the top is
well worth it _ along with the Bell Tower just to the north is
$1.25.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the base of the Bell Tower is the Bell Tower Teahouse,
which offers 18 kinds of Chinese tea, for prices ranging from $2.50
to $25 a pot as well as snacks. If you ask, the staff will serve
the tea with ceremonial flourishes. Open from 8:30 a.m. to 9 p.m.
(5 p.m. in winter). If you don't have a ticket for the two towers,
admission to the Bell Tower grounds alone is 75 cents. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
