<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9736 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PFIZER-ART-NYT &LR;      02-07 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PFIZER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PFIZER WILL BUY WARNER-LAMBERT FOR $90.27 BILLION IN STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When many drug companies decided to cut their sales forces in
the early 1990s because of the push into managed health care,
William C. Steere Jr., the then new chairman of Pfizer Inc., hired
more sales people.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy has paid off. By pouring money into sales and
advertising, Steere has transformed Pfizer from a company that
could not make the industry's top 10 list when he took over in 1992
to a company that is on course to become the world's largest drug
company.
</P>
<P>
   Early Monday, as expected, Pfizer announced that it would buy
the Warner-Lambert Co. for $90.27 billion in stock. The combined
company, which will be called Pfizer, becomes the second largest
drug company in the world behind Glaxo Wellcome and SmithKline
Beecham. Because Pfizer also becomes the fastest-growing
pharmaceutical company, it is expected to swiftly overtake
Glaxo-SmithKline, the British giant created by Glaxo Wellcome and
SmithKline Beecham, which announced their merger plans last month.
</P>
<P>
   After trying for three months to ward off Pfizer's hostile
takeover bid, the board of Warner-Lambert approved the deal just
before 1 a.m. Monday morning. Immediately the two companies began
acting like longtime friends, with Warner-Lambert's chairman,
Lodewijk J.R. de Vink _ who has decided to step down from his job
as a result of the takeover _ joining Steere and other Pfizer
executives to tout the combination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pfizer and Warner-Lambert represent a new competitive standard
for our industry,'' Steere said. ``By combining two world-class
organizations to create the fastest-growing, major pharmaceutical
company in the world, we are positioned for global leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of Warner-Lambert, Pfizer will add 2,500 sales
people to its 5,000 workers now selling drugs in the United States.
The combined Pfizer and Warner-Lambert will also have a research
staff of 12,000 _ the largest in the world. The need to spend more
on research is one reason that many drug companies are now
searching for merger partners.
</P>
<P>
   The decoding of the human genome, which is expected to be
complete by the end of the year, promises to give drug companies
millions of new targets to look at when trying to find new drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, you only had a few targets to aim at,'' said
C. Louis Clemente, executive vice president at Pfizer. ``Now we
have many, many targets. It's getting a bit overwhelming to sort
out.''
</P>
<P>
   But the growing numbers of drug mergers is raising concerns in
Washington. , Two ranking senators on the subcommittee that reviews
antitrust matters sent a letter to the Federal Trade Commission,
urging regulators to scrutinize all three drug mergers that have
recently been announced. In December, Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn announced
in it planned to merge with Monsanto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maintaining strong competition in the pharmaceutical industry
is of crucial importance to controlling health care costs and to
ensuring that innovation continues to take place,'' Sens. Mike
DeWine, R-Ohio, and Herbert Kohl, D-Ohio, wrote to the FTC.
</P>
<P>
   An aide on the subcommittee said that hearings may be held on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Pfizer executives said that they were not concerned
about any antitrust issues.
</P>
<P>
   Steere will remain Pfizer's chairman and chief executive. The
63-year-old executive worked in marketing and sales at Pfizer
before becoming a top executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Steere sees drugs as a consumer product,'' said Sergio
Traversa, an analyst at Mehta Partners, a firm that invests in drug
stocks. ``He understands marketing and that you can sell drugs like
any other product.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides increasing Pfizer's sales force, Steere has also
invested heavily in advertising drugs directly to consumers. For
example, the company's commercials for Viagra, one of Pfizer's top
selling drugs and one of the most heavily advertised products in
the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Steere has also increased the revenue from each sales person by
having them sell drugs made by other companies under joint
agreements. Last year, the fastest-growing portion of Pfizer's
revenue came from sales of Lipitor, a cholesterol-lowering drug
made by Warner-Lambert and from Celebrex, an arthritis drug made by
Monsanto.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer's agreement with Warner on Lipitor is the reason Pfizer
made the hostile bid for Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Lipitor agreement, Pfizer gets about half of the
profits of the drug, which is expected to have revenues of $5
billion this year. But when Warner-Lambert announced on Nov. 4 that
it would buy American Home Products Corp., analysts say that Pfizer
began to fear that it might lose its agreement on Lipitor.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after de Vink shook hands with John R. Stafford, the
chairman of American Home, Pfizer began an $82.4 billion hostile
offer for Warner. After months of bickering and fighting each other
in court, the two companies agreed last week to a merger.
</P>
<P>
   Many Warner-Lambert executives, including de Vink, are expected
to leave their jobs _ a main reason why Warner-Lambert tried so
hard to fend off Pfizer's attack.
</P>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert also has a large consumer products division,
selling products ranging from Listerine to Bubblicious chewing gum,
that Pfizer is not keen on.
</P>
<P>
   But Pfizer executives said Monday they had no plans to try to
sell the consumer products division. While Pfizer's headquarters
will remain in New York City, the consumer products business will
be managed from Warner-Lambert's headquarters in Morris Plains,
N.J. But Pfizer has said that some jobs will likely be cut, mostly
in management and administrative positions. Pfizer says that it
plans to save $1.6 billion by 2001. Analysts said Monday that
Pfizer must cut thousands of jobs to reach that goal. The two
companies have a total of 87,000 workers with 12,000 employees in
the New York City metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   De Vink said Monday that he was not sure what he will do. Pfizer
has offered to pay him as a consultant for his advice after the
companies combine their operations, which is expected sometime this
summer. Shareholders of both companies must approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   De Vink, 54, said that he did not want to be an executive at
Pfizer because he feared his ideas would clash with those of
Steere. ``There must be clarity of command,'' he said, ``clarity of
vision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' he said, ``I have a golden opportunity to redefine my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger leaves American Home Products, the spurned suitor of
Warner-Lambert, alone again for the third time in two years. Two
other proposed marriages _ one with SmithKline Beecham, another
with Monsanto _ fell apart in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But this time American Home walks away with $1.8 billion _ the
largest fee that any company has received when a proposed merger
ended.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer has agreed to exchange 2.75 of its shares for each share
of Warner-Lambert. Based on Pfizer's closing share price of $35.75
on Friday, that puts the value of the deal for Warner-lambert's
918.2 million fully diluted shares at $90.27 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Warner-Lambert rose $2.75 Monday, to $97.3125, a new
52-week high, while shares of Pfizer climbed $1.25, to $37.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
