<SLUG> BC-CHIPS-CHIPS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 AMD's Speedy New Chip Upstages Intel's  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
PC microprocessors, which crossed the 500-megahertz mark less than
a year ago, are set to double that speed before this year is out.
<P>
   At yesterday's opening of the International Solid-State Circuits
Conference _ a major industry event held annually in San Francisco
_ industry leader Intel said it will ship a version of its Pentium
III processor with a clock speed of 1 gigahertz _ one billion
cycles per second _ this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, however, was upstaged by rival Advanced Micro Devices,
which demonstrated a 1.1-gigahertz version of its Athlon chip and
promised to begin shipping it to customers in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   AMD's share of the PC chip market is only about 15 percent,
compared with about 80 percent for Intel. But the successful Athlon
design has recently given AMD a beachhead at the lucrative high
end, which Intel previously had to itself.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid acceleration in processor clock speeds over the past
few years has exceeded most predictions. In a famous 1989 article,
Intel executives forecast that speeds would reach the
then-unheard-of level of 250 megahertz this year.
</P>
<P>
   There's no indication, either, that the rate of improvement will
slow any time soon, even though the industry will have to overcome
some formidable engineering challenges to maintain its recent pace.
Intel now predicts that clock speeds will reach at least 10
gigahertz by the end of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   IBM used this week's conference as the occasion to announce what
could turn out to be an important milestone along that path: an
experimental design that allows conventional silicon transistors _
the tiny switches packed by the millions into today's chips _ to
reach speeds of 3.5 to 4.5 gigahertz.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's innovation involves operating different parts of a chip at
different speeds. The parts most critical to performance would run
at the highest speeds, while other parts would operate on their
own, slower clocks.
</P>
<P>
   That approach, according to company officials, reduces by half
the power consumption and heat that would be required to achieve a
comparable performance with today's designs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to disclosing its plans for a 1-gigahertz Pentium
III, Intel disclosed new details about Itanium, a radically new
chip it also expects to ship in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Intended initially for high-powered server computers rather than
desktop systems, the Itanium will start out at a speed of 800
megahertz. To give performance an extra boost, it will be packaged
in a module that also includes 4 megabytes of ``Level 3'' cache
memory also operating at 800 megahertz. That unusual design will
give the chip extra-fast access to data and instructions it needs
to use repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another new Intel design, code-named Willamette, is expected
to displace the Pentium III as Intel's top-of-the-line processor
for desktop PCs before the end of the year. The company, however,
has yet to disclose details about that chip.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Compaq and IBM also presented papers describing
upcoming 1-gigahertz versions of their respective server chips, the
Alpha and the PowerPC.
</P>
<P>
   Users of Apple Macintosh computers, however, will apparently
have to wait longer to cross the gigahertz barrier. The PowerPC
running at the speed IBM described is a high-end version Apple
doesn't use. In a separate paper, engineers from Motorola, which
also makes PowerPC chips, discussed a new version of the G4, the
PowerPC variant Apple uses in its high-end systems, but that chip
will run at only 780 megahertz.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest current G4 runs at only 450 megahertz, since
Motorola has not yet been able to produce in volume a 500-megahertz
version it announced last August. The G4, however, includes special
multimedia features that enable it to match or beat the performance
of seemingly faster chips on many tasks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
