<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-POLO-NBC-AD-COLUMN-NY     02-07 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLO-NBC-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: NBC HELPS RALPH LAUREN FULFILL A MULTIMEDIA DREAM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.)   (jw) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ralph Lauren, the pre-eminent peddler of aspirational clothes
and other merchandise, has dreams too. He wants to have a
multimedia presence like Martha Stewart, the omnipresent home guru.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, NBC and its Internet affiliates signed on with his
dream. They joined with Polo Ralph Lauren in a new media company
that will promote the designer's products online and on the air.
The deal, while a coup for Lauren, will further blur the line
between content and commerce at traditional media companies.
</P>
<P>
   The first and foremost task of the joint venture will be to
develop Polo.com, which is being billed as an upscale lifestyle
destination site _ like Stewart's Web site, but for the ponied set.
The idea is that consumers will go to the site to experience
Lauren's luxurious romantic version of safari or the American West
through video clips, and that they will then buy the related Polo
products, as well as non-Polo-related services like airline or
hotel reservations. Eventually, the company, RL Media, might
develop magazines or even TV programming for NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous media companies have tried to leverage their
advertising power for stakes in the Internet field. CBS, a unit of
Viacom, has traded airtime for part-ownership in some 19 Internet
businesses, including a health site and a portal that gives away
cash. And USA Networks signed a deal last week that would enable it
to sell National Basketball Association products and services on
its electronic commerce units, which include the Home Shopping
Network and Ticketmaster Online-CitySearch.
</P>
<P>
   In the Ralph Lauren announcement, analysts saw further signs
that the networks were preparing to profit from a time when viewers
want not just to watch television programs, but to shop from them
as well. (Hey, who made that leather thong Jennifer Aniston is
wearing and how much does it cost, anyway?) ``This is an enormous
step toward turning what's currently known as a television set into
an interactive appliance,'' said David Verklin, chief executive of
Carat North America in New York, part of Aegis Group, a media
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the 30-year joint venture, NBC and associated
companies will foot much of the bill (most of it in advertising)
for start-up expenses, in return for 50 percent of the company. The
network is committed to providing $100 million in advertising time
over the next five years; NBCi, an online holding company 47
percent-owned by NBC, will offer $40 million in online promotions,
and CNBC has committed $10 million in advertising time.
</P>
<P>
   ValueVision, which is 40 percent owned by NBC, and operates Home
Shopping Network, No. 3 in TV shopping, will put up about $50
million in cash. It will handle customer service, merchandise
stocking and distribution for Polo.com, and is building a warehouse
in Kentucky for Polo.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren will build the multimedia empire he has long coveted for
a relatively small sum. He will attach the Polo.com tag to the
annual $100 million in magazine advertising he already does to
promote the Polo brand, he will provide merchandise at cost, and he
will handle excess inventory through his outlet stores.
</P>
<P>
   But in return, he will retain 50 percent ownership and total
creative control of the site _ in fact his son, David Lauren, will
be creative director. When and if sales from the site exceed $75
million, Polo Ralph Lauren will begin to receive a portion of
sales. From $75 million to $200 million, it will get 10 percent of
revenues, and it will get an undisclosed portion of sales above
that level. In addition, Lauren will maintain relationships with
department stores, which will sell Polo merchandise through
bloomingdales.com, macys.com and saks.com, among others.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Lauren was vague about the content but ecstatic
about the potential. ``We don't know all the things that are going
to happen,'' said the designer, who even ventured that he had a few
thoughts about situation comedies, ``but this is about integrating
into the world of technology and new media.''
</P>
<P>
   The partnership also gives a nice kick to Polo Ralph Lauren's
stock, mired like those of many apparel companies and trading at an
all-time low before the announcement. Shares of Polo rose $2.125
Monday to close at $16.25.
</P>
<P>
   It is less apparent what NBC and its associated companies hope
to get from the deal, beyond a stake in a company that could have a
hot public stock offering. NBC executives seem eager to develop a
future for the network where content and commerce commingle more
easily. ``Instead of merely aggregating a great audience and
letting other people sell to them,'' said James Schwab, a senior
vice president for interactive services at NBC, ``now we are going
to sell things ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Lauren was advised by Robert S. Wiesenthal, head of
digital media at Credit Suisse First Boston, who helped broker the
deal between the two companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
