<HEADER>
A9742 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-KANA-KANA_SFCHRON &LR;      02-07 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KANA-KANA </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Kana Acquires Silknet in Deal for $4.2 Billion  &HT;     By Todd Wallack 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Kana Communications, a Redwood City company that helps firms manage
their e-mail, unveiled plans yesterday to spend $4.2 billion for
Silknet Software, a New Hampshire firm that uses Web software to
help businesses field questions from customers.
<P>
   Although both companies are relatively small, the mammoth price
underscores the growing importance of doing business over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The deal makes sense for Kana because it hopes to sell Silknet's
software to its existing customers. Though many of Silknet's rivals
sell software to help customer service departments handle queries,
Silknet's business is booming because it uses the same program to
handle everything from questions on Web sites to phone calls. The
software also makes it easy for both customers and employees to
access accounts with a standard Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   Silknet, which has 75 customers, works with such dot-com
companies as E-Trade and Priceline, and also helps more traditional
businesses, like Sprint and Office Depot, that are increasingly
using the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are taking the plumbing and building these
e-businesses,'' said Mark Gainey, Kana's founder and president.
</P>
<P>
   To land Silknet, Kana paid 55 percent more than market value of
the New Hampshire firm, based on closing prices of the two
companies on Friday. In other words, the purchase price works out
to about $16.8 million per worker, or 150 times annual revenue. By
comparison, traditional software firms usually fetch closer to two
or three times sales.
</P>
<P>
   Gainey said Silknet's ``explosive growth'' justified the price,
noting that his own company's sales leaped 140 percent to nearly $8
million in the latest quarter. Silknet has 250 employees, including
a dozen in San Francisco. ``We are just at the tip of the iceberg
iceburg  &LR; of this particular market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kana investors reacted cooly to the deal. Kana shares closed
yesterday at $240.50, down $18.38. It has a market value now of
just under $7 billion. Meanwhile, Silknet shares soared 33 percent,
to $183.31, up $44.81.
</P>
<P>
   Silknet lost $7.3 million on $14 million in revenue for the
first six months of the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Kana actually recorded smaller revenues than Silknet and
squirted more red ink. It lost $119 million on $14 million in sales
largely because of several acquisitions. But Kana also reported
torrid growth as sales zoomed to $6.5 million in the latest
quarter, up 650 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In defending the deal, Gainey said the premium amounts to only
21 percent based on the stock price during  &LR; over  &LR; the last 30 days.
He said the price was inflated because Kana's stock has soared
recently.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst said the deal made sense strategically. ``This could
be one of the biggest e-business moves of at least the first half,
if not the year,'' Reginal King, an analyst with Chase H&AMP;Q, told
Bloomberg News. ``Everybody needs this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
