<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MEXICO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY I LOVE MEXICO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first time I went to Mexico, I really didn't go there at
all.
</P>
<P>
   We got a package deal to Cancun; the beach was pretty, the
weather perfect, and I almost slammed into the side of a high-rise
hotel during an ill-advised parasailing expedition. After four
days, we went home with sunburns and T-shirts and hangovers from
the tequila shots practically forced on us by an
English-slang-slinging waiter apparently hoping we'd get so drunk
we'd overtip. It was an OK trip, but I didn't think I wanted to go
again. And I wasn't sure I liked Mexico all that much.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, I still feel the same way about Cancun. But
I've fallen in love with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure exactly which part of which visit turned me around:
The forced march to the bottom of the northern Copper Canyon, where
we swam in an ice-cold, waterfall-fed pool and picnicked near the
crumbling remains of a mansion built by a copper-mining magnate.
The torch-lit dinner at the old Spanish fort in Acapulco, where we
ate corn-fungus enchiladas (better than they sound) as a lavishly
costumed ballet folklorico troupe performed. The three-hour tour
from Topolobampo, when our little skiff was surrounded by a school
of dolphins, acting as playful tour guides the whole way back,
jumping around as if they were auditioning for a show on the Animal
Planet channel. The day spent lounging on a perfect deserted beach
two hours south of Cancun, one that nobody else managed to stumble
onto that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong _ I loved Paris, I loved Rome, I can't wait
to get back to London. But when it comes down to it, the only place
I really HAVE to visit every year, the only place that I find
myself actually MISSING, is Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you're a Texan, it's easy to love Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   For a few hundred bucks and in a few hours, you can be there, or
at least in one of its airports. And if you live in Texas and you
pay any attention at all, the sights and smells and sounds of
Mexico will stir at least a bit of recognition in you. (For me,
another attraction is that no matter how many
``now-YOU-say-it-in-French'' tapes I listen to, Spanish remains the
only language other than English in which I can do more than buy a
bus ticket and order wine.)
</P>
<P>
   More than that, however, it's that whatever I want, I can find
it in Mexico. Lots of countries have beautiful art or fascinating
ruins or great food or idyllic beaches or scenic mountains or
bustling big cities or fantastic shopping. Not many have them all.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond sightseeing and spending, of course, travel is really
about getting outside your comfort zone, of seeing how other people
do things and learning to adapt to that. In some places, that means
going faster, being more harried; sometimes it's hard work.
</P>
<P>
   But Mexico is one of the few places where my life seems to slow
down, a feeling that bothers me at first but then seems completely
natural. A couple of years ago, I was sitting in the Huatulco
airport, trying to get a seat on a flight into Oaxaca after
realizing we didn't have time for the bus. I fumed at first when we
spotted computers sitting unused while clerks carefully wrote out
the tickets. In longhand. In triplicate.
</P>
<P>
   It took a few minutes _ and a few moments of inhaling the scent
of the tropical hibiscus that bloomed everywhere _ to remember the
point. They were still getting the job done, if not as fast as I
might have wanted. We'd still get there. Maybe we should go get
some snacks.
</P>
<P>
   And I was frustrated at first at the old-fashioned spa in
Ixtapan de la Sal, a smallish town outside Mexico City. What was up
with the '60s-era diet (Melba toast, cottage cheese, chicken
broth)? And the casual approach to exercise? (The morning walk was
often led by a genial but very round fellow whose main job was
waiting tables in the resort's restaurant; we didn't, obviously, do
much power-walking.) When I asked for a harder workout, they
cheerily suggested I go get another facial instead. Also maybe a
nap.
</P>
<P>
   I finally listened to them. They were right.
</P>
<P>
   Travel is also about small, isolated moments, the ones that help
you form a relationship with a country and a culture. And many of
my most memorable ones _ singing in my bad Spanish at a karaoke bar
in La Paz, watching a funeral procession in a flower market in
Acapulco, being the only tourists climbing the pyramids at Coba,
eating German-style sausage and cheese at a Mennonite colony that
is for some reason situated south of Chihuahua _ are from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that I couldn't have had similar experiences elsewhere.
The point is, I didn't. And the result is, I feel oddly attached to
Mexico, almost protective of it. When I hear people say they've
been there, but they didn't really like it, I often wonder aloud if
they've given it a chance _ or if they've only been to the Club
Med.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, I went back to Cancun last summer, not
exactly on purpose _ we wanted to go to some less-developed beaches
in the Yucatan _ but Cancun is where the flight landed. For
logistical reasons, we spent the first night in one of those Cancun
high-rises, with the multilevel landscaped swimming pool and the
$10 breakfast buffet.
</P>
<P>
   After a day on the beach _ still beautiful, despite the crowds _
we went looking for dinner, walking on a busy four-lane divided
road past countless Tony Romas and Hard Rock Cafes and trying to
stay out of the path of the packs of daiquiri-toting high school
seniors. We finally found a place that wasn't too crowded, ate
quickly, and rushed back to the hotel. The next morning, we were up
at the crack of dawn, headed for a quieter beach; we couldn't get
out of town fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to dismiss Cancun (or, OK, maybe it is) or the other
plush resorts; I guess they have their place, and their fans. But
right down the road, there's a Mexico that suits me much better.
</P>
<P>
   (Patricia Rodriguez is travel editor of the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
