u s BC-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-NYT &LR;      02-07 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT ONLY GETS MORE INTERESTING FOR U.S. DAVID CUP TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ Now that John McEnroe is 1-0 as Davis Cup
captain, he gets to experience what Jeff Van Gundy does as a
basketball coach. He has to dole out the minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Next up for the U.S. team following its narrow 3-2 escape here
against Zimbabwe on Sunday is the Czech Republic, come April in Los
Angeles. McEnroe has a while before naming his starters, but he may
have longer-term issues to deal with. First and foremost, what to
do, if anything, about Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Agassi has said he is on board for McEnroe's first-year
run, which takes care of one singles spot. Sampras, who pulled out
of the first round, citing a hip-muscle injury sustained during his
losing semifinal match with Agassi at the Australian Open, never
committed himself to playing this year with the certainty that
Agassi did.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras may be even less enthusiastic after hearing that
McEnroe, in a regular column written for a London newspaper,
offered that Sampras may have never really wanted to come here in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you get a phone call from Sampras over the weekend?''
McEnroe was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upset?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say upset, no,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans happily reported that Jim Courier e-mailed his
friend, Chris Woodruff, wishing him luck Saturday night before his
straight-set breakout victory over Wayne Black on Sunday. Todd
Martin, who also had to withdraw from the first round because of a
viral infection, faxed the team and telephoned Woodruff for a
15-minute pep talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two class people,'' Woodruff said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean you're not a classy guy if you don't do it,''
McEnroe said, navigating the minefield. ``It means that you are if
you do.''
</P>
<P>
   At this stage of Sampras' career, his body rebelling as he
single-mindedly pursues a record-setting 13th Grand Slam title,
Davis Cup does not appear to be his thing. Agassi, overcome here
Sunday by humidity and high elevation, would be the first to admit
he has not been as consistently devoted to his career as Sampras.
At 29, in the best shape he has ever been in, Agassi seems to want
to do it all right now, make up for lost time.
</P>
<P>
   The other issue becomes one of creating the strong team core,
which McEnroe and Agassi always say is the only reason to play
Davis Cup in the first place. Woodruff, at 27, is no budding
Sampras, but he was ranked as high as No. 29 in the world before
tearing up his knee three years ago while kicking a football. Once
he got over his nerves here Sunday, he showed an effective
hardcourt game, with deep, heavy ground strokes and a serve he
cranked up to a high of 120 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a nice question,'' McEnroe said when asked if
Woodruff has complicated his life by rising to a fifth-match
occasion under extreme conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Woodruff was sitting right next to him, so McEnroe did not want
to get into it. He did, of course, because what subject has he ever
been unwilling to discuss?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like, you know, you just played the biggest match of your
life, thank you very much, now get the hell out of here,'' he said.
``This is when the job, in a way, gets tougher because we had such
a great team spirit. I believe, with this team, we'd beat
Czechoslovakia. I'll just tell you that right now. This team would
beat Czechoslovakia.''
</P>
<P>
   Would he keep it together then? ``I'm tempted to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   First things first, like getting hold of an updated European
map. Beyond the Czech Republic could come another trip, to the clay
courts of Spain. Sampras would not necessarily be of great value
there, either. But should the United States go that far without
him, it may be unreasonable to expect him to ever play again.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Martin, who after Agassi and Sampras is the most
dependable American player on hard courts.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe is only getting started. He has time to figure this all
out, and if he does not, well, he will live. Someone will play for
him. As the preacher, Matthew Ashimolowo, told his South London,
South Africa, congregation Sunday morning on the Zimbabwe Broadcast
Co., ``No matter what happens to you, it's not over till it's
over.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
