<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9745 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-MEXICO-FAVORITES-TEX     02-07 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FAVORITES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE FAVORITES
</HEADLINE>
 (Accompanies TRAVEL-MEXICO) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   {Oaxaca:} The art produced in the surrounding countryside is, on
its own, worth the trip _ intricately painted wooden animals and
plaster angels, carved masks and wooden skeletons, hand-thrown
pottery in black or green glazes and silver crosses, and subtle
woven shawls and tablecloths. (Not to mention the first mescal,
flavored with orange or lime, that I actually kind of like.) But
the city's main plaza, filled with entrepreneurs selling everything
from cheap plastic toys to folk art to warm ears of roasted corn
(served, to my dismay, with mayonnaise), and ringed with open-air
restaurants, is one of the best places to while away an evening in
Mexico _ or anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   {Ixtapan de la Sal:} Mexico is relatively new to the spa
business, but this small town near Mexico City has hosted guests in
spa resorts and a neighboring ``balneario,'' or spring-fed
bathhouse, for 50 years. The ``balneario's'' spa was a trip _ one
of the weight-loss treatments consisted of being painted in blue
wax, wrapped in plastic and left to roast under wool blankets. And
apparently no visitor comes home without buying jars and jars of
rose-scented lotions and vitamin-laced beauty creams, handmade by a
local woman and sold in her tiny boutique downtown.
</P>
<P>
   {Playa del Carmen:} The first time I visited this simple seaside
town a 45- minute drive south of Cancun, it was so laid-back that a
tame pig was wandering about the beach undisturbed. A half-dozen
years later, some shiny new hotels and its popularity with cruise
ships have drawn a bunch more tourists _ and driven up prices. But
the water and sand are still gorgeous, and the beachside palapa
huts are a fine place to drink $1 Bohemias _ even if the pig is
long gone.
</P>
<P>
   {Copper Canyon:} The train, running from Chihuahua to Los
Mochis, gets all the attention because of its stunning views of the
ridges of the Copper Canyon ranges and its astonishingly engineered
switchbacks. (Oh, and perhaps because it took nearly a century to
build, finally being completed in 1961.) But stop a few days, in
Creel or Batopilas or one of the other tiny towns, and hire a guide
to lead you into the depths of the canyon, hiking the trails that
the local Tarahumara Indians have used for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   {Acapulco:} It's touristy. It sits on a bay that fights repeated
attempts at cleanup. It's filled with breathtakingly beautiful _
and heart-stoppingly expensive _ resorts. But the oldest of Mexican
beach resorts still has a great mountainous location, a lovely,
authentic soul _ and those famous cliff-divers. Whatever they're
paid, it can't be enough; watching them soar perilously off the
sharp cliffs, arcing effortlessly into the ebbing water below, was
one of the few times I thought a classic tourist attraction
deserved its reputation.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
