<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9746 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BOND-BOND_SFCHRON &LR;      02-07 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOND-BOND </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Treasuries Turmoil Creates Opportunities  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
With the U.S. government accelerating its plans to retire its
long-term debt, investors in Treasury issues have to start thinking
differently.
<P>
   The market for Treasuries has turned into an Alice-in-Wonderland
scene, with the yields on shorter-term Treasuries moving higher
than the yields on longer-term Treasuries _ a phenomenon known in
the bond trade as an inverted yield curve.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, long-term issues are priced to yield more than
short-term ones because investors demand a higher interest rate to
compensate for the longer wait until their bonds can be redeemed at
face value.
</P>
<P>
   If you invest in Treasuries, or are thinking about it, the
obvious _ and correct _ move right now would be to phase into
shorter-term issues, experts say. There is no rational reason to
tie up your money for the long term at a lower yield than you can
get in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why ask for additional risk?'' is the way Joe DuCote, senior
managing director of Sutter Securities in San Francisco, puts it.
</P>
<P>
   But some experts suggest that conservative investors ought to
let their thoughts wander beyond the Treasury market. That's
because the buying spree in Treasuries has caused their yields to
look unattractive relative to other fixed-income securities.
</P>
<P>
   The spread between long-term Treasury yields and other long-term
fixed-income issues has opened up considerably, notes Kirk Hartman,
chief investment officer for fixed income with Banc of America
Capital Management.
</P>
<P>
   There are tempting alternatives among quasi-governmental
agencies such as Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, the mortgage lenders,
as well as among investment-grade corporate bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a situation of turmoil in the market,'' Hartman
observes, ``and when there is turmoil, it can create buying
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   The turmoil in the Treasury market reached a climax late last
week, when Gary Gensler, a Treasury Department undersecretary,
offered details of the government's massive plan to drastically
scale back the issuance of securities with maturities ranging from
five 5  &LR; to 30 years, and to buy back much of the long-term debt
outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   All this has been made possible by the booming economy, which
has filled federal tax coffers to overflowing and ushered in a new
era of budget surpluses. Because the government pays higher
interest on longer-term issues than on shorter-term, the
longer-term issues have been targeted first for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a looming shortage of long-term Treasuries set
off a buying panic in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative institutional investors such as insurance
companies, which consider long-term Treasuries essential holdings,
gobbled them up last week faster than baseball fans buy Mickey
Mantle cards.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Schlossberg, an economist with San Francisco's Wells
Capital Management, points out that there also was a lot of buying
by other institutions, which had borrowed long-term Treasuries and
sold them short as part of a routine strategy to hedge against
increases in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   As the prices of these issues shot up last week, the
institutions were forced to buy them back to avoid losing a lot of
money.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy buying pushed Treasury prices up and pushed down
interest rates, which move in the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
   As of yesterday, you could buy a two-year 2-year  &LR; Treasury
yielding 6.67 percent to maturity, or a five-year 5-year &LR;   &LR; Treasury
with a 6.74 percent yield.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the 10-year bond was yielding just 6.64 percent,
and the 30-year Treasury, which normally has the highest yield of
all, was down to 6.34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   You can get significantly better yields these days in the
corporate bond market, observes Richard Lehmann, a newsletter
publisher with the Bond Investors Association in Miami Lakes, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   In his most recent survey, Lehmann found that triple-A corporate
bonds _ those with the least risk of default _ were yielding 0.84
percentage points more than Treasuries with the same maturities. If
you are willing to accept slightly less quality, you could get a
0.94 percent spread on double-A bonds or 1.12 percent on
single-A's.
</P>
<P>
   All those spreads are larger than they have been in recent
months, Lehmann observes. And yet, ``with the economy booming, the
risk of default is at a low level.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Lehmann advises individual investors not to try
singling out particular corporate bonds, because the risk of
picking a loser is too great. Instead, investors should buy mutual
funds specializing in bonds, ``where they can get diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
