<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEALTHSIDE-WEALTHSIDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COPING WITH WEALTH
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some tips for the newly rich from Stephen Goldbart and Joan
DiFuria at the Money, Meaning &AMP; Choices Institute:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Buy the things you've always wanted, but don't overdo it. A lot of
money can make for a lot of debt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Don't be surprised if you don't want to retire. Instead, give
yourself the opportunity to decide what kind of work you really
want to do.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Find avenues to express your altruism that are personally
meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Communicate with family members about your new wealth. Keep in
mind that the arrival of money will have an impact on everyone in
the household.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Expect to lose some friends and make some new ones. Be prepared
for the envy of others.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Don't be surprised if you wonder who you can really trust. Expect
invitations, solicitations and loan requests to exponentially
increase.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2130EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0463 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9748 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WEALTH-WEALTH_SFCHRON     02-07 1366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEALTH-WEALTH </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Overcoming the New-Money Blues  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Silicon Valley has created tens of thousands of millionaires _ 64
new ones each and every day, according to some estimates.
Frequently, however, these newly rich find that big bucks don't add
up to big fun.
<P>
   Just the opposite, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of Bay Area psychologists, Stephen Goldbart and Joan
DiFuria, have come up with a name for the affliction: ``Sudden
Wealth Syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about having your life change earlier in adulthood than
you imagined, in ways that are dramatically different from how you
grew up,'' Goldbart said during a lengthy chat at the office he and
DiFuria share in Kentfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an early identity crisis,'' DiFuria, sitting nearby on
the couch, clarified. ``There's a sense of denial. There's a sense
of shock. There's a sense of I-don't-deserve-it.''
</P>
<P>
   To assist in overcoming such conflicted feelings, the pair have
founded the Money, Meaning &AMP; Choices Institute as a beacon of light
for those wandering in the darkness of Sudden Wealth Syndrome. They
are also at work on a book.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, it will be pretty darn hard for most people to
sympathize with some Porsche-driving, sneakers-wearing
propeller-head who's having a hard time adjusting to life as a
megamillionaire.
</P>
<P>
   And that's actually part of the problem. The suddenly affluent
find that, along with potential feelings of anxiety and guilt over
their windfall, one of the hazards of new wealth is coming to terms
with how others perceive you.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, experts say, is that very few people are
psychologically and emotionally prepared for the life-altering
effects of large amounts of money.
</P>
<P>
   To deal with the challenge, a growing cadre of wealth
specialists has emerged to help the rich be rich, tackling
everything from inheritances and stock options to raising kids in
newly affluent households.
</P>
<P>
   So great is the demand for such services, financial powerhouses
like Charles Schwab and Merrill Lynch have even held seminars for
clients on the topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The swift-rich do not have the wisdom of time to have their
psychology catch up with their affluence,'' said Paul Schervish, a
sociology professor at Boston College specializing in
wealth-related issues. ``They have to acquaint themselves with a
new identity. It's the same dynamic as being newly retired.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, sort of. While the newly retired and the newly rich may
both find themselves with excess time on their hands, the former
have planned for years on a lifestyle change, while the latter are
almost overnight thrown into the deep end of the financial pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of challenges that people face when they come
into wealth they didn't expect,'' said Christopher Mogil, director
of More Than Money, a Massachusetts nonprofit group dedicated to
assisting people in handling new wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your relationships with friends change,'' he said. ``You ask
yourself whether people are interested in you or your money. You
need to decide whether to keep working, which for men especially is
a real source of self-esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   Exacerbating the situation is the fact that many people with
money and misgivings often have a difficult time sharing their
feelings with others. The fear, of course, is that they will be
ridiculed for being unable to cope with what should be a sweet
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the last taboos in society _ talking about money
and class issues,'' Mogil said.
</P>
<P>
   As a cautionary tale, Money, Meaning &AMP; Choice's Goldbart related
the story of a 44-year-old San Francisco software developer named
John, who woke up one morning about a month after his company went
public and realized he no longer had to go to work. He no longer
had to spend more than 60 hours a week toiling away in a cubicle.
</P>
<P>
   John was now a multimillionaire. But instead of reveling in his
good fortune, he found himself increasingly distracted by feelings
of isolation and worry.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he found his way to Goldbart's office, John was
genuinely troubled. He said that he was uncomfortable with the way
other people were now treating him and that he was having a hard
time keeping his priorities straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The underlying assumption is that if you have all the money in
the world, you'll be happy and fulfilled,'' Goldbart said. ``That's
simply not true.''
</P>
<P>
   He and DiFuria, both well regarded in their field, first spotted
the trend of woeful wealth several years ago _ not coincidentally,
right around the same time that info-tech companies were turning
into slot machines for options-laden employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept seeing clients come in with issues of wealth, and they
were getting younger and younger,'' DiFuria noted. ``I had very
successful men who'd say they'd stop when they reached $3 million,
and then it was $15 million, and then $50 million.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've bought the BMW and they have the $3 million Mill
Valley house,'' Goldbart chimed in. ``And they still wake up in the
morning and say, `I don't feel good about myself.'''
</P>
<P>
   The pair have broken down their recovery process into three
stages. In the first, clients come to terms with the shock,
excitement and confusion surrounding the arrival of money into
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, they attempt to regain a sense of control over
the changes they have experienced. In the third, clients seek to
come up with a revised set of priorities and goals accommodating
their improved circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money means power,'' Goldbart said. ``The question is how
you're going to wield that power.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you use or abuse it,'' DiFuria added.
</P>
<P>
   Like many wealth specialists, they advocate philanthropy as the
key to peace of mind _ using one's riches as a tool for positive
social change.
</P>
<P>
   Here, too, the suddenly wealthy often find themselves at sea.
How much should they give? Who should they give it to? How should
they do it?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a wariness about giving away a lot of money,'' noted
Claude Rosenberg, founder of a San Francisco entity called the
Newtithing Group, which promotes philanthropic activities. ``You
can never really overcome that wariness.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he believes that the well-to-do can, and should,
commit a healthy percentage of their net worth to charitable
organizations. This, Rosenberg said, will both increase a personal
sense of fulfillment while addressing some of the nation's most
pressing needs.
</P>
<P>
   John Levy, a Mill Valley wealth counselor, said those who
inherit their riches, as opposed to hitting a home run in the stock
market, tend to have an easier time adjusting to la dolce vita.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inheritors are prepared in advance,'' he said. ``On the other
hand, they have to deal with not having earned it. That can cause
insecurity.''
</P>
<P>
   As for IPO millionaires, Levy said they frequently go on
spending sprees and flaunt their newly affluent status. ``They
don't know how to be rich,'' he observed.
</P>
<P>
   Most wealth specialists advise clients to take it slow, to not
rush into any major decisions. They urge the newly prosperous to
adjust first to the idea of being rich before turning their lives
upside-down with wholesale changes.
</P>
<P>
   Schervish, the Boston sociologist, said the suddenly rich could
do worse than to follow the examples of prominent wealthy guys like
Bill Gates, Ted Turner and Donald Trump, each of whom appears to
have reached a level of comfort with their status.
</P>
<P>
   ``The swift-rich must remember that money is empowering in a
material sense,'' he said, adding that until one learns to make
good use of money, ``it can be disempowering.''
</P>
<P>
   Schervish also advised new arrivals to the highest tax bracket
to be cautious when seeking guidance from self-appointed wealth
experts. ``As with every fast-growing industry,'' he said,
``there's some snake oil and there's some high-quality
counseling.''
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, some less-than-prosperous people might
conclude that being rich is more hassle than it's worth.
</P>
<P>
   Schervish laughed. ``Well,'' he said, ``it's a problem most of
us wouldn't mind facing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
