<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: QUEBEC VOTE RULED OUT
</P>
<P>
   Premier Lucien Bouchard of Quebec gave a cold shoulder to
separatist hard-liners at a Parti Quebecois convention, declaring
that his party's main goal should be to win re-election before its
mandate expires in 2003 instead of holding a third referendum on
independence. Previously, he promised to hold a vote on separation.
But opinion polls indicate support for independence and his
separatist party have sagged into the 35 percent to 40 percent
range.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: 745 ARRESTED
</P>
<P>
   A total of 745 people, including 83 minors, were arrested when
the federal police took over the national university to end a
nine-month student strike, justice officials said. Several dozen
were released on bail but three strike leaders, Alejandro
Echavarria, Alberto Pacheco and Mario Benitez, were charged with
felony crimes and denied bail. More than 7,000 people joined a
spontaneous march in Mexico City to demand the prisoners' release,
a call echoed by many intellectuals and opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: ADAMS PROTESTS BLAST
</P>
<P>
   The Sinn Fein president, Gerry Adams, under pressure to avert
the shutdown this week of the new Northern Ireland government by
producing disarmament by the Irish Republican Army, condemned the
bombing of a country hotel by a dissident republican group opposed
to the peace accord. No one was injured in the blast. ``The people
involved are not acting in the interests of Irish republicans,''
Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PINOCHET CHALLENGE
</P>
<P>
   Six human rights groups and the government of Belgium renewed
legal challenges thrown out by the High Court last week to prevent
Britain from freeing Gen. Augusto Pinochet from house arrest and
letting him return to Chile. They asked a three-judge court to make
Britain disclose the confidential medical report on the former
Chilean dictator on which it based its decision that he was unfit
to be extradited to Spain to stand trial on torture charges. A
decision is expected this week.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA: SERBS RALLY
</P>
<P>
   Some 2,000 Serbs in Mitrovica rallied to protest violent attacks
against Serbs in Kosovo and to hear local leaders denounce
international peacekeepers and administrators for failing to
protect them. One local leader, Vuko Antonijevic, praised the Serbs
for ``defending their city against Islamic terrorism'' on Thursday
when hundreds of Serbs went on a rampage and attacked Albanian
families after an explosion in a Serb cafe.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: MAD COW REPORT
</P>
<P>
   France, which defied a European Union decision to lift a ban on
British beef, has come under fire for its own efforts to prevent
mad cow disease. A European Union report found France has failed to
properly impose controls on cattle feed agreed to in the wake of
the mad cow disease scare. The report also found that while the
incidence of the disease in France appeared to be moderate, a study
showed that underreporting of suspected cases could not be ruled
out.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   DJIBOUTI: A CEASE-FIRE
</P>
<P>
   Djibouti's last remaining rebels have signed an accord to end a
decade-old uprising by ethnic Afars in this tiny Horn of Africa
nation, a former French colony. The accord, signed in Paris, calls
for reforms to improve democracy and provides for the immediate
release of all prisoners on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: PAKISTAN DENOUNCED
</P>
<P>
   Amid increasing rancor between India and Pakistan, Prime
Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee denounced Islamabad's failure to
endorse a no first-use policy on nuclear weapons. ``Pakistan is
threatening a nuclear war, but do they even know what it means?''
he said. ``They think they will drop one bomb and they'll win and
we'll lose. This won't happen. We have said we won't be the first
to use nuclear weapons, but if anyone uses them against us, we will
not wait for our annihilation.''
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIANS: JUDGES STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian judges walked out on strike to protest police
failure to stop a mob attack on a Bethlehem courthouse after two
convicted murderers were sentenced to 15-year jail terms. Hundreds
of angry supporters and relatives of the convicted men smashed
court windows and blocked traffic in the West Bank town. A leading
Palestinian human rights group said some local police officers had
joined the rioters.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: TUNISIAN VISITS
</P>
<P>
   A senior diplomat from Tunisia, Secretary of State for Foreign
Affairs Tahar Sioud, met with Foreign Minister David Levy in the
first visit to Israel by a high-ranking Tunisian since the two
countries set up diplomatic relations six years ago. Sioud said he
and Levy, a native of Morocco who has stressed improving ties to
North Africa, ``discussed peace, and we are here for peace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
