<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9753 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-BUDGET-PROGRAMS-1STLD     02-07 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-PROGRAMS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S DOMESTIC GOALS BOUNCE BACK IN NEW PROPOSALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS lede to reword; 4th graf to add background in 1st sentence;
7th graf to add background; adds new grafs 8-11 to explain
Clinton's approach and add quotes (bgng `Clinton described...';
12th graf, adds sentence of explanation; rewrites 13th graf; 14th
graf, changes `catastrophic expenses' to `catastrophic coverage';
deletes graf bgng `The first bill....'; 16th graf, reworks 1st
sent.;adds 6 grafs to end of original text with new reporting on
Head Start programs and immunization for children.)  
(With BUDGET-CLINTON) 
(js) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The budget unveiled Monday by President Clinton
shows his extraordinary persistence as an architect of domestic
policy. In health care and other social programs, he is pursuing
many of the same goals as in 1993, though often by different means.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is still trying to expand health coverage, still trying
to expand eligibility for food stamps and other nutrition programs,
still trying to increase the Earned-Income Tax Credit, one of the
nation's biggest anti-poverty programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't call him the comeback kid for nothing,'' said
Edward M. Cooney, a special assistant to the secretary of
agriculture, noting how Clinton had pressed on despite setbacks and
detours.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, his first year in office, Clinton proposed a big
expansion of the food stamp program under the Agriculture
Department, and Congress approved it. The 1996 welfare law cut food
stamp spending, especially benefits for legal immigrants. Clinton
won restoration of some of the cuts for legal immigrants in 1998,
and on Monday he asked Congress to restore the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, on health policy.
</P>
<P>
   No longer does Clinton try to guarantee health insurance for all
by redesigning the health care system from top to bottom. Rather,
he is proposing more modest steps to insure a dozen different
groups including workers between jobs, people age 55 to 64,
uninsured parents of children eligible for Medicaid, legal
immigrants and low-income women with breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In his new budget request, Clinton proposed to expand plans that
failed in recent years, and he asks Congress to spend more money on
them in the hope that the proposals will prove more popular if they
are more generous. Clinton would use anticipated budget surpluses
to finance many of his ambitious plans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton described his approach in his State of the Union Message
last month. ``The lesson of our history, and the lesson of the last
seven years,'' he said, ``is that great goals are reached step by
step, always building on our progress, always gaining ground.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Clinton acknowledged that his original proposal for
universal health insurance coverage would not work. But he said:
``Maybe we can do it in another way. That's what we've tried to do,
a step at a time until eventually we finish this.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart M. Butler, a vice president of the conservative Heritage
Foundation, said Clinton had persuaded Congress to accept major
changes in health and domestic policy by pursuing an incremental
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say it's more palatable,'' Butler said, ``but it's
harder to resist. It's directed at very tangible aspects of
people's lives. The president can say he's just solving people's
problems, not expanding the role of government.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, for the third year in a row, Clinton proposed to let
people age 55 to 64 buy Medicare coverage. Stung by criticism that
the premiums would be too high, he is now proposing tax credits to
offset 25 percent of the cost. He would, in effect, offer a tax
break to encourage people to participate in a government program.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also sweetened his proposal to offer prescription drug
coverage to all Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Congress last year balked at Clinton's proposal to have Medicare
cover prescription drugs _ half the annual drug expenses, up to a
maximum federal payment of $2,500 a year. Monday Clinton enlarged
his original proposal, adding coverage for the costs of people with
Medicare coverage who have extraordinarily high prescription drug
expenses. He gave no details of how he would design or finance such
``catastrophic coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Clinton last year proposed a $1,000 tax credit for
people providing long-term care to relatives with chronic
illnesses. The proposal was well received in Congress, but never
became law. Monday Clinton proposed to triple the amount of the
credit, in the hope of winning more support.
</P>
<P>
   The president also returned to one of his favorite programs, the
Earned-Income Tax Credit, a refundable credit available to poor
working families. In 1993, Clinton proposed an expansion of the
credit costing $28 billion over five years; Congress approved $20
billion, providing help to 15 million low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Clinton proposed a further expansion of the
Earned-Income Tax Credit, providing tax relief to 6.8 million
families at a cost of $2 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   From his earliest days in office, Clinton has been trying to
expand Head Start, the development program for preschoolers, with a
goal of serving 1 million youngsters. When he took office in 1993,
Head Start was providing health, education and social services to
713,900 children at a cost of $2.8 billion a year. This year
877,000 children participate, and the program has a budget of $5.3
billion.
</P>
<P>
   In his budget request Monday, Clinton sought $6.3 billion, for a
total enrollment of 950,000 children.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been equally persistent in trying to immunize
children against measles, mumps, polio and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, he and Hillary Rodham Clinton said they wanted the
federal government to buy up all childhood vaccine and distribute
it at no charge to all children. They later settled for a program
guaranteeing free vaccine for millions of children who were poor or
uninsured. But the program went awry when the administration
insisted on storing large quantities of vaccine in a federal
warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the White House scrapped plans for the warehouse,
scaled back the government's role and sought more money to help
drug companies distribute vaccine to state health departments and
clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Isabelle Claxton, a spokeswoman for Merck &AMP; Company, which makes
several pediatric vaccines, said: ``The lesson is that the
marketplace can work. Once you got past the politics, it became
clear that the price of individual vaccines was not the main
barrier. The Clinton administration reached out to states and
worked with them to do a better job of educating physicians and
parents to immunize children on time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
