<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEARL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLANCE OF FORBIDDEN LOVE LASTS FOREVER ON VERMEER CANVAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
 RETRANSMITTING FOR THOSE WHO MISSED THIS 
 
 REVIEW  of ``GIRL WITH A PEARL EARRING'' 
 By Tracy Chevalier (Dutton, $21.95) 
 
 
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The girl looks back over her shoulder with wide eyes and parted
lips, as if someone has come up from behind and taken her by
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Her earring, a giant pearl, catches the light, and a blue turban
hides the unruly hair that she never lets anyone see. Her pose
seems natural, but we know she was coaxed into it by the artist who
painted her _ he even instructed her to lick her lips and not to
close them. As she gazes back at him, we also know her secret: She
loves the man, but she can never speak of it to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   She is 17. Her name is Griet, and she is a maid in the house of
Dutch painter Johannes Vermeer, who is known today as the ``master
of light'' but who in 1665 was merely a respected artist struggling
to support a wife and six children (11, by the time he died a
decade later) in 17th century Holland.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeer and his family are real, but Griet is the invention of
Tracy Chevalier in her novel, ``Girl With a Pearl Earring,'' which
was inspired by Vermeer's painting of the same name. Griet is only
16 when she is sent to work in Vermeer's house, a move made
necessary after her father, a Delft tilemaker, is blinded in a kiln
explosion and unable to work.
</P>
<P>
   It is not an easy time for Griet, who has never been away from
her parents. She is Protestant and the Vermeers are Catholic, and
their home is full of religious paintings (Vermeer is a collector
as well as an artist) that are foreign and frightening to her. Her
days are long and hard, and she must fend for herself in the
constant power struggle that simmers among the women of the house:
Vermeer's suspicious and mercurial wife, Catharina; his
mother-in-law, the sly and powerful Maria Thins; Maria's personal
maid, Tanneke; and Cornelia, Vermeer's malicious 7-year-old
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Griet holds her own well enough. She has an instinct for
flattery that disarms Tanneke at first, and she manages to
establish a minor alliance with Maria Thins. But her biggest weapon
is the master himself. From the moment he meets her, Vermeer
recognizes Griet's eye for color and detail. It is not long before
he secretly enlists her as his assistant, teaching her how to mix
paints and plan what will appear on a canvas. And Griet begins to
see him not just as employer but as an artist, and then as a man.
</P>
<P>
   Griet narrates her story with a certain plodding charm, the
voice of a working-class girl who knows her place in life but
cannot resist the allure of what is beyond her. She is
hard-working, cautious, uncomplaining and clever, a Jane Eyre in
the land of canals.
</P>
<P>
   That her story moves so quickly (I read it in two days) is a
reflection of how shallow it actually is _ we never really have a
sense of why any of the characters are the way they are. But that
is not a drawback. Griet does not have time to analyze the people
whose lives touch hers. She must support herself, contribute to her
parents' well-being and navigate the dicey emotional tides in the
house of Johannes Vermeer.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, she does not settle happily into her master's arms
like Jane Eyre, but perhaps does something better: She makes a life
for herself and sees it for what it is, growing into a pragmatic
woman who tells her story exactly as it should be told.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeer left only 35 paintings behind at the end of his life.
Several _ including ``Young Woman With a Water Pitcher'' and
``Woman With a Pearl Necklace'' _ make appearances in Chevalier's
book, as if she cannot resist making up stories to explain these
dazzling and enigmatic works of art. Any one of them would have
made a good premise for a novel, but Chevalier has chosen well. We
don't know who really posed for ``Girl With a Pearl Earring,'' but
her Griet is a character worthy of the honor. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2140EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
