<SLUG> BC-SIERRALEONE-PEACEKEEPERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. INCREASES PEACEKEEPERS IN SIERRA LEONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The Security Council increased a peacekeeping
force for Sierra Leone Monday to 11,000 from about 6,000 and told
the troops not to shrink from using weapons against some of the
most brutal rebel armies anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The expanded peacekeeping mission, approved unanimously, becomes
the organization's largest. The council hopes the extra troops will
be able to better protect themselves as well as aid workers and the
people of Sierra Leone. The rebel forces, particularly the
Revolutionary United Front, led by Foday Sankoh, have been
responsible for many killings and the amputation of limbs.
</P>
<P>
   A peace agreement signed in July in Lome, Togo, between the
rebels and the government of President Ahmed Tejjan Kabbah,
officially ended a nine-year civil war, but not the attacks on
civilians, U.N. peacekeepers already on duty and African troops
from a regional force known as Ecomog.
</P>
<P>
   Countries contributing troops to the U.N. force were told at a
meeting here on Friday that soldiers will have to be more forceful
in opposing rebels they are charged with disarming.
</P>
</TEXT>
