<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9758 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      02-07 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW&AMP;NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; RETRANSMITTING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED IT &QL; 
 &QL; 
eere are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``MY GENERATION'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Michael Gross (Cliff Street, $25) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gross looks at the cultural impact of the baby-boom generation
(his rather liberal standards include anyone born from the day the
Japanese bombed Pearl Harbor in 1941 to the day John F. Kennedy was
assassinated in 1963) by focusing on 19 ``quintessential boomers,''
including Donald Trump, Marianne Williamson, political cartoonist
Doug Marlette, software superstar Steve Capps, porn star Nina
Hartley, New York criminal court judge Leslie Crocker Snyder and
public-relations executive Cynthia Bowman (she once lived with Paul
Kantner of the Jefferson Airplane and was Grace Slick's maid of
honor when she married her lighting director). The story of this
generation and how it evolved, Gross writes, ``is best told not
through the lives of average members but through those who achieved
or failed or both, extravagantly.'' His book is sometimes
scattered, but thought-provoking, and haunted by the belief of
fellow boomer Maureen Dowd that ``we are going to die without
experiencing the nobility that illuminated the lives of our parents
and grandparents.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``GREENE ON CAPRI'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Shirley Hazzard (FSG, $22) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oh, to be young and well-off and living in Italy, where you
could sit in a piazza and read books or work crossword puzzles
until your friend Graham Greene showed up to share a bottle of wine
and some scintillating conversation. This slight memoir begins in
the 1960s and is set in a succession of villas and cafes on Capri,
where Hazzard and her husband, biographer Francis Steegmuller, got
to know Greene very well. She addresses Greene's religion, his
fiction, his culinary habits, his friends and acquaintances, his
appreciation of women, his feelings about America and his own
country, his alleged anti-Semitism. All of it carries an air of
otherworldliness brought on by the underlying suggestion of leisure
and privilege (there are some references to ``completing
manuscripts,'' but mostly these people just seem to eat and talk).
Most of all, the conversations were literary. After Greene's death
in 1991 and Steegmuller's in 1994, the woman who had been Greene's
companion wrote to Hazzard that ``maybe now they have found each
other, and go on discoursing on Flaubert.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``BECOMING AMERICAN'' &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Meri Nana-ama Danquah (Hyperion,
 &UR; $23.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Lilianet Brintrup came to the United States from Chile as a
graduate student in 1981, she was humbled by the cold. Winter had
set in, hard and implacable, but the chill was also in the faces of
the people around her. They did not smile. ``I supposed that they
were in a hurry,'' she writes. ``I didn't see any sign of welcome,
not even one small flag waving in the wind as a sign of welcome for
foreign people. This lack of courtesy in a country of immigrants .
. . really surprised me.'' This wonderful collection of essays by
first-generation immigrant women will help you see this country in
a different light, as an adventure and a place of great opportunity
but also as a source of confusion and a sense of displacement. Some
of these women now think of the United States as home, as when
Gabrielle Donnelly, formerly a London journalist, writes with
delightful assurance of her American husband, her American city _
Los Angeles _ and her increasingly American sensibilities. Others
never will. Among the contributors are women from Haiti, India,
Korea, Russia, Ireland, Japan, China and Egypt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``LETTERS FROM THE EDITOR'' &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Thomas Kunkel (Modern Library, $26.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Orson: I was astonished at your column in yesterday's
`Post,' in which you say `The New Yorker' sneers at you. You were
brimful of prunes when you wrote that.'' We don't know about you,
but we are brimful of prunes over the fact that ``New Yorker''
Editor Harold Ross never wrote to  &UR; us, &UR; when he managed to send such
droll missives to everyone else in the world. Included are notes to
the above-mentioned Orson Welles, Katharine and E.B. White, Ring
Lardner, Groucho Marx, F. Scott Fitzgerald, H.L. Mencken, Ernest
Hemingway, Dorothy Parker, James Thurber, Lillian Hellman, Joseph
Mitchell. In short, some of the most luminous people of the day
heard from Ross, and they were lucky for it. He was witty, he was
affectionate, he was irascible _ he once wrote to E.B. White to
denounce the use of the term ``toilet paper'' in his magazine,
which, he said, ``would ruin my meal if I read it while eating. It
might easily cause vomiting.'' Ross is great company _ if you don't
have a letter of your own, this book is the next best thing.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
