<SLUG> BC-BKC-VINNY-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS SHOULD FILL FIRESTONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Callf. _ This is the weekend laid-back Malibu needs to
be the nastiest place around. The coffee shops along Pacific Coast
Highway should be empty, the bookstores and restaurants all closed
down.
</P>
<P>
   No rollerblading at the beach or hiking in the Santa Monica
Mountains. They'll be there next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   For once, Firestone Fieldhouse at Pepperdine University, the
home of the best college basketball team in town, needs to be
rocking and rolling like those thundering waves crashing onto the
beach across the highway.
</P>
<P>
   The Pepperdine men's basketball team has done its part. First-
year coach Jan van Breda Kolff and his overachieving players have
positioned themselves to win the West Coast Conference
championship. With wins Friday against Portland and Saturday
against Gonzaga, the Waves will pull into a first-place tie with
Gonzaga with four games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's time for the Pepperdine student body and local fans to
do their part. When Gonzaga rolls into town, the only appropriate
greeting should be unadulterated noise. Pepperdine fans need to
transform cozy Firestone Fieldhouse into a thundering, madhouse gym
like Duke University's Cameron Indoor Arena.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Waves encountered last Thursday when they
traveled to Gonzaga. There, Pepperdine was met by a rollicking
crowd that danced the line between supportive and bellicose. In the
end, the charged-up atmosphere helped fuel a furious Gonzaga
comeback, enabling the Bulldogs to race back from a 13-point
halftime deficit to win 62-57.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was by far the most hostile environment we've played in
this year, to the point where sometimes it was more then hostile,''
van Breda Kolff said. ``Hopefully, our crowd can be just as intense
and help motivate the team to play as well as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be a nice gesture, if a bit overdue. Over the last
month, Pepperdine has played some of the best basketball in the
country, winning nine of 10 games to make the WCC race a two-team
sprint. The Waves play an exciting style, using a full-court press
to create turnovers and fastbreaks. Van Breda Kolff, who left
Vanderbilt University to replace Lorenzo Romar, is liberal with his
playing time, going nine-deep on the bench and encouraging players
to look for their shots.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine isn't built around one star player. It instead relies
on its depth and unselfishness. At the end of games, opponents
can't focus on stopping one player, since any one of six or seven
can make an important shot. At various times, Brandon Armstrong,
Tommie Prince, Kelvin Gibbs, Nick Sheppard and Tezale Archie have
made huge plays down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   It's a style of play fans generally go for, and with the type of
excitement the Waves are creating, you'd expect Firestone to be
sold out most nights. Unfortuntately, that hasn't been the case.
Pepperdine is averaging less then 2,000 per game.
</P>
<P>
   That needs to change this weekend. The fieldhouse, which seats
3,104, needs to be sold out, loud and rowdy.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the Waves are playing for more then the regular-season
conference title. Pepperdine will earn an automatic NCAA Tournament
bid by winning the WCC Tournament March 4-6, but failing to do that
puts the Waves' fate in the hands of the NCAA selection committee,
which relies on a ratings percentage index (RPI) to determine
tournament-worthy teams. The RPI breaks down every team's strength
of schedule, then ranks them. Right now Pepperdine has a solid 29
RPI, falling between North Carolina and Utah. But much can change
between now and selection day, which means games like Saturday are
critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in good company right now, but it doesn't really mean
much until March,'' van Breda Kolff said.
</P>
<P>
   Make it seem like March this weekend in Malibu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
