<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2TAKES-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WINTER, PARKS OFFER QUIET FUN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some national parks are strictly warm-weather friends. By early
September, the Going to the Sun Road across Glacier National Park
is dicey: You can get a certain distance and find the road shut
because at those altitudes, it's already snowing on a perilous
route. And on the Blue Ridge Parkway in the Great Smokies, drives
in early spring in search of an ideal hike can also be frustrating
because runoff congeals into sheets of ice, and barriers are up at
tunnel entrances and along cliffs.
</P>
<P>
   But many national park areas in the chill belt remain
accessible, and disclose secrets to those who venture in. ``You can
see all of the animal tracks,'' says Malcolm Wilbur, chief
administrator of the Cape Cod National Seashore, ``if there is a
little frost or snow.''
</P>
<P>
   At Acadia National Park in Maine, a foot and a half of snow
invites cross-country skiers and snowshoers to explore vistas of
ocean and wilderness that are often blocked behind traffic in high
season. The crowding is down every place, and many parks and
recreation areas offer extensive activities to all comers.
</P>
<P>
   David Barna, chief spokesman for the National Park Service, said
he believed that there had been a rise in winter visits, related to
the younger age of retired people and their wish for vigorous
activity. ``Once we had winter activities only at the holidays,''
Barna said, ``but now this broader, younger retired audience has
more flexibility, in addition to college students who are out of
school in January and February.''
</P>
<P>
   Winter tent camping may suit only the hardiest, but for them, no
reservations are needed and space is plentiful. Others can ski,
snowshoe or hike. Most parks charge no admission fee in the
off-season.
</P>
<P>
   There are usually a few nearby bed-and-breakfasts open all
winter, and they are often easy to find through chambers of
commerce or visitor bureaus. Two major parks, Yellowstone in
Wyoming and Montana and Yosemite in California, have their own
lodges or cabins that take guests all winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out here on the ocean, we get rain when others get snow,''
said Ranger Wanda Moran at Acadia National Park on Mount Desert
Island in Maine. But when the park gets snow, as it did toward the
end of January, skiers can travel on the prized carriage roads,
where no vehicles are permitted in any season.
</P>
<P>
   All the parking lots in the park are plowed out, Moran said, and
these are accessible from a road called the park loop. For skiers,
a carriage road makes a six-mile circuit around Eagle Lake that is
easy to get to from Route 233. There is ice skating on the ponds
during a deep freeze (but check the ice, there are no warning
signs). Snowmobiles are permitted on most of the loop road.
</P>
<P>
   Blackwoods Campground, which has a hand pump for water, chemical
toilets and collection bins for refuse, is open all winter (free
till the ground thaws). There are no hookups, but there is a fire
ring at each site. The park's headquarters on Route 233 west of Bar
Harbor is open all winter, 8 a.m. to 4:30 p.m., and provides
information on snow conditions: (207) 288-3338. The Web site is
www.nps.gov/acad.
</P>
<P>
   In Southwest Harbor, outside the park but on Mount Desert, the
Captain Bennett House, (207) 244-9627, a five-room
bed-and-breakfast, is busy ``far beyond what we expected,''
according to its new owners, Jim and Jackie Michaud. They have had
painters, rock-climbers, hikers and sightseers come to an area
filled with crowds in summer. The Web site is
www.captainbennett.com.
</P>
<P>
   As at Acadia, snow is a sometime thing at the Cape Cod National
Seashore. At the end of January, after three good falls, Michael E.
Whatley, a supervisory park ranger at the Salt Pond Visitor Center
in Eastham, said: ``It is spectacular on the beaches. You can hear
the breakers and see the bands of white snow on the dunes.'' But it
disappears fast, he said, noting that rangers often tell callers
they should get their skis on right away because the snow will be
gone in two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Bird-watching, hiking, star-gazing and nature walks are major
activities in the park, Whatley said. ``It is a time to see the
place in its historic perspective,'' he said. ``We are closer to
the life style of the original settlers at this time of year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Pond center, (508) 255-3421, www.nps.gov/caco, is open
9 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. all year, and can provide maps and guidance for
hikes, cross-country skiing or exploration of the swamps in the
preserve. The park itself is open till midnight, but the outdoor
water faucets are turned off in winter and toilets are not easy to
find.
</P>
<P>
   A valuable complement to the national seashore is the
state-maintained Cape Cod Rail Trail, a 25-mile former railroad
right-of-way running from Dennis to Wellfleet, with a spur going
south to Chatham. Almost perfectly flat, suitable for both
cross-country skiing and snowshoeing, this trail passes through
pines and oaks and along ponds.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel O'Brien of the State Department of Environmental
Management in Boston says that the trail is not used much in
winter, and since nothing motorized is permitted on it, it provides
quiet and solitude. There are a number of parking lots along the
trail but O'Brien says only the one at Nickerson State Park in
Brewster, about halfway along the trail, is plowed. From there, you
can ski, hike, skate, ride a horse, bike or use your wheelchair in
either direction.
</P>
<P>
   Information on snow conditions on the rail trail may be obtained
from Nickerson Park headquarters, (508) 896-3491.
</P>
<P>
   Francis Matrango, a ranger at Nickerson, said that his park
stocked its pond with landlocked salmon in December and January, as
well as trout, and that many visitors came to fish for these,
either from the shore or from motorboats.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuyahoga Valley National Recreation Area, between Cleveland
and Akron, was created only 25 years ago, and its winter programs,
mainly on the weekends, have been steadily increasing over the last
five to eight years, according to Karen Kopchak, the chief
interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell people that if they can walk, they can snowshoe,''
Kopchak said. And the last weekend in January, she said, 100 people
came out for a winter festival. The park owns 100 pair of snowshoes
and rents them at $3 a pair a day. Rangers lead animal tracking
programs, tree identification walks and other expeditions.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The area's main feature is the Ohio &AMP; Erie Canal, with a 20-mile
reconstructed towpath. Cross-country skiers can enjoy the canal,
the locks and the Cuyahoga River.
</P>
<P>
   This coming weekend will include a family winter weekend, with
participants staying in two heated 60-bed dormitories in the park.
Meals are included, and there will be snowshoeing, a night hike and
a campfire. The cost is $55 or $35 for a child, with a maximum
family cost of $190.
</P>
<P>
   The dormitories, normally used for residential student programs,
are five miles north of Akron and 15 miles from Cleveland.
Information or registration: (330) 657-2796.
</P>
<P>
   A regular attraction in the park is ``Sherlock Bones,'' a ranger
disguised as a ``nature detective'' in a trenchcoat, pipe and
deerstalker hat. He is called in to solve mysteries for 3- to
5-year-olds, such as why did the leaves fall off the trees? Or, why
do salamanders move in groups?
</P>
<P>
   The park's winter activities are all listed on its Web site,
www.nps.gov/cuva. Cuyahoga Valley National Recreation Area,
Brecksville, Ohio 44141; (216) 650-4636.
</P>
<P>
   Yellowstone is ``another place'' in winter, Rick Hoeninghausen,
a spokesman for the park lodges, said. If you go to visit the
geysers, he said, you see wildlife, snow, ice and steam. Winter
also banishes the automobile blight from the park: except for one
road that dips into the northwest corner of the park, passing
Mammoth Hot Springs, Yellowstone's roads are traversable in winter
only by snowmobile or 10- or 15-passenger commercially operated
``snow coaches,'' closed, heated vehicles on tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, the park and Amfac, the company that manages the
lodges, opened the second half of the 100-room Old Faithful Snow
Lodge. This lodge and the 95-room Mammoth Hot Springs Hotel are the
only wintertime lodging places in the park. The snow coaches will
pick up guests for the snow lodge at park entrances, or at Mammoth.
Or one can enter by snowmobile, which may mean towing a sled if
your suitcase is bigger than a breadbox.
</P>
<P>
   The snow lodge was built on the lines of a classic lodge, with a
two-story lobby, using timbers salvaged from buildings that were
being demolished. Two gas fireplaces are in the lobby, along with a
dining room and a fast-food place.
</P>
<P>
   The big activities at Yellowstone are cross-country skiing,
snowshoeing, hiking and snowmobiling. Snowmobiles are available for
rent at both hotels, along with clothing for the ride. Both lodges
have ski shops, which rent all kinds of snow and ski equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The basic room rates range from $51 a night for a room without
bath at Mammoth to $121 a night for a room at the snow lodge.
Two-night packages include things like an hour in a hot tub at
Mammoth, a snowmobile rental at either place, or a snow coach tour.
A snow coach round-trip from the West Yellowstone entrance costs
$79, so a package is worth looking at.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that the park continues its entrance fees
through the winter: $20 for a car, which can go only to Mammoth;
$15 for a snowmobile and $10 a person in a snow coach. The fees
cover a week's visit.
</P>
<P>
   Yellowstone reservations are available at (307) 344-7311 and
www.travelyellowstone.com. Information on the park itself is at
(307)344-7381 and www.nps.gov/yell.
</P>
<P>
   Yosemite is a four-season park, with four-season lodgings.
Although winter is the slowest time, the great and high-priced 1927
Ahwahnee Lodge stays pretty much booked all winter, according to
Sherry Ward of the Yosemite Concession Corp., which operates the
park hotels.
</P>
<P>
   In winter, Scott Gediman, a park spokesman said, there is a
sharp drop in foreign tourists and most park visitors are from
California. It is a situation that means space for visitors, and
seeing the sequoia hung with snow is better than not seeing it at
all.
</P>
<P>
   The park's Badger Pass ski area offers Alpine skiing and
snowboarding, with four lifts, and there are three areas for Nordic
skiing and showshoeing: Badger Pass, Crane Flat and Mariposa Grove.
Gediman said that Badger Pass was always described as a family
area, not one in competition with Tahoe or similar high-style
resorts.
</P>
<P>
   Lodging is available at Curry Village, which has both wooden and
wood-floored canvas cabins, most of which are heated, for about $40
to $60 a night. There is a skating rink that rents skates. Above
are views of Half Dome, the granite monolith that is one of the
park's great hallmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers lead daily two-hour hikes for many levels; snowshoes are
rented for $3 a pair. The park publishes a 16-page quarterly guide.
For a copy, leave information on the park phone number, (209)
372-0200.
</P>
<P>
   Yosemite Lodge in the valley and the Wawona Hotel at the
southern part of the park offer winter packages that include ski
lift tickets. In midweek, a family of four pays $89 a night Sunday
to Thursday, not including holidays. Lodging only is $33.75 to $69
a night.
</P>
<P>
   Yosemite still has an admission charge in winter: $20 a vehicle
for seven days, or $10 a person. For lodging reservations: (559)
252-4848. Park information is also available at www.nps.gov/yose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
