<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9765 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LEWIS-RAID-COX     02-07 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-RAID-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Police make search of Lewis' residence
 &HT;    By Joshua B. Good
 &HT;    and Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The Maryland home of Baltimore Ravens linebacker and
Buckhead double-murder suspect Ray Lewis was searched early today
by police, who confiscated several items.
</P>
<P>
   The officers from Atlanta and Baltimore County arrived at the
home around midnight and spent about three hours there, said Ronald
M. Cherry, Lewis' personal attorney. They could be seen carrying
large plastic containers and loading a computer into a van.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry said he could not comment on what police were looking for
or what was confiscated from the home in Owings Mills, in suburban
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The search came one week after two Decatur men were stabbed to
death in a Buckhead brawl after a night of Super Bowl partying.
Police charged Lewis, who had rented a Lincoln Navigator stretch
limousine that fled the stabbing scene, with murder.
</P>
<P>
   Thelimo driver may not have stopped to help the victims, but he
did drive to a nearby hotel to call police and tell them what he
had seen.
</P>
<P>
   What driver Duane Fassett said led Atlanta police to arrest
Lewis and charge him with two counts of murder.
</P>
<P>
   In a one-paragraph affidavit supporting their arrest warrant,
investigators said Lewis ``along with others did unlawfully and
with malice aforethought cause the death of Jacinth Baker and
Richard Lollar by punching, beating, and stabbing them with a sharp
object. This according to a witness who saw the entire incident.
The witness knows Mr. Lewis by name and sight and has known him for
over a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Atlanta homicide investigators remained in Baltimore Sunday
evening with no plans to leave ``until they get all the information
they need,'' said another investigator from the Criminal
Investigations Division.
</P>
<P>
   The detectives spoke to A.J. Johnson at his Laurel, Md.,
apartment late Friday, and Johnson, who was wanted for questioning
in connection with the killings, has hired an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   A second man wanted for questioning, Kwame King _ who played
high school football with Lewis in their hometown of Lakeland, Fla.
_ is still believed to be in Atlanta and may already have spoken to
homicide investigators, King's relatives said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said last week they believed both men were inside Lewis'
limousine the morning of the stabbings.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has, through his lawyers, denied any involvement in the
slayings. Johnson has said that he was in Baltimore at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis should have been playing in his third Pro Bowl in Hawaii
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he gazed at his mother, grandmother and fiancee through
the thick glass during visiting day at the Atlanta City Jail.
</P>
<P>
   Elease McKinney, the football star's grandmother, vowed Sunday
to remain in the city until Lewis is released from jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only get to see him 20 minutes,'' McKinney said Sunday.
``He's in great spirits. He's happy to see us.''
</P>
<P>
   The three women see Lewis twice a week _ Wednesdays and Sundays.
They can't touch him. They can't hug him. They talk through a
telephone attached to the wall. The middle linebacker's children
have not been taken to the jail to see their father, McKinney said.
</P>
<P>
   While Fassett has not spoken publically his friends said he had
no choice but to speed away from the corner where Baker and Lollar
were killed. Bullets were flying and Fassett, 51, could not stop to
help. Instead, he drove a 40-foot long Lincoln Navigator stretch
limousine as fast as he could to the Holiday Inn on Peachtree Road.
</P>
<P>
   Shots had been fired into the driver's side, at least five slugs
from a large caliber weapon, either a .44 or .45 gun, police have
said, and Fassett wasn't about to stick around.
</P>
<P>
   And he wasn't alone.
</P>
<P>
   In the back seats of the black limousine _ which includes four
TV's, VCRs, bars and a mirrored ceiling _ police said were NFL
football player Ray Lewis and at least seven of his friends. There
were also blood and knives, Atlanta police have said.
</P>
<P>
   Fassett's boss, Tony Toskov, defended his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sit down in that car. You see if you throw it into park or
drive when somebody starts shooting at ya','' Toskov said. As owner
of All Stretched Out Limo the Baltimore-based limousine rental
Toskov said he frequently did business with Lewis, a middle
linebacker with the Baltimore Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday Fassett's attorney David Irwin said his client has
given Atlanta police a lengthy statement. Erwin said he doubts
Fassett's account is the sole reason Lewis has been jailed on
murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be a false assumption to make that he's a
star witness against Ray Lewis,'' Irwin said. ``He's told police
what he saw. And he's told police what he didn't see.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin would not divulge Fassett's description of the deadly
fight at the intersection of East Paces Ferry Road and Grandview
Avenue. The attorney, who also represented Linda Tripp, has been in
contact with Atlanta investigators and the Fulton County District
Attorney's Office. He said his client has not been asked to testify
before a grand jury about the fatal stabbings.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Fassett is not working as a result of the incident.
``(Fassett's) not making any money now. He's laying low,'' said
Toscov's brother Larry Toscov.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Lewis remains the only suspect to be arrested in the
deaths of 21-year-old Baker and 24-year-old Lollar.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McKinney, Lewis' grandmother, did not know whether he
would watch the Pro Bowl on TV Sunday evening. That's where her
grandson should have been instead of sitting in a small cell at the
city jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't even talk about that,'' said McKinney referring to
the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
