<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-INTELLECTUALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTIVATING SCHOLARS, EVEN IN THE SUN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., N.H., Mass.)  (jw) 
 By PATRICIA COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ ``I don't know where this prejudice comes
from,'' that people cannot think unless there is snow on the
ground, Teresa Brennan says.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan teaches at Florida Atlantic University here, where the
average temperature this month dances in the 70s, the sun shines
most every day, and the beach is a mere three miles away. An
enthusiastic woman who looks a bit like Diane Keaton with red hair,
Brennan helped create the university's new doctoral program for
public intellectuals. The program is the first of its kind in the
country and has elicited a late-night monologue's worth of jokes
since it began last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot more palm trees on Florida Atlantic's campus
than public intellectuals,'' said an article in the Chronicle of
Higher Education, which included digs from a number of professors,
all of whom live north of the Mason-Dixon line. ``Can you imagine
`the Boca Raton intellectuals' exercising clout in the national
media?'' another article asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's intellectual snobbism,'' said one of the students,
Rose-Marie Donovan, 44, in Brennan's office on this state
university campus, a series of low-slung, beige blocks surrounded
by parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan left her job as an editor at a local weekly newspaper to
study the effect of fiction on society. She is one of 19 students
in the program working to become the nation's first licensed public
intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
   Just what that means, however, is a subject of debate even among
the participants.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of the writer or scholar without a vested interest,
speaking out in the public interest, is associated in the United
States with people like Lionel Trilling and Irving Howe, who helped
shape cultural life and political conversation in the '50s.
</P>
<P>
   Today, public intellectuals tend to be academic celebrities,
professors who regularly write for magazines like The New Yorker or
television pundits who churn out opinions on topics from campaign
finance to ``The Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   To many of the doctoral students here, however, the razor-thin
specialization of the scholar and the inch-deep expertise of the
journalist are a public intellectual's Scylla and Charybdis.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Dottin, 31, who is something of an aspiring Charlie Rose
with hopes of having his own public-interest talk show, said he
wanted to ``speak effectively on a range of issues'' but also
``avoid what we see a lot of pundits do,'' abusing expertise by
knowing a single subject but speaking out on a dozen.
</P>
<P>
   Another student, Frances Chelland, said: ``This is not training
talking heads. That's exactly the thing I'm here to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Chelland, 50, took a two-year leave from her job as an assistant
professor of philosophy and gender studies at a college in New
Hampshire to enroll. She would like to organize training retreats
for teachers to discuss how to bridge what she called ``a deep
divide between ideas and action.''
</P>
<P>
   But can students maintain scholarly rigor at the same time they
speak on any number of topics? And is talking to a small group of
students and teachers sufficient to make the leap from plain old
intellectual to public intellectual?
</P>
<P>
   Dottin said having both breadth and depth was not easy, but, he
said: ``It's a character issue. We should only claim to know what
we know.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the size of the public, Chelland said: ``So what if it's
just my students? I'm contributing to an informed public.''
</P>
<P>
   Brennan said Chelland's teacher training program was a model of
what a public intellectual should do. A professor of social theory
who has taught at Harvard and worked on Capitol Hill, she readily
admits that ``you can't train someone to be a public
intellectual.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she continued, ``you can make sure that what's in them that
wants to be isn't killed off'' by the demands of a single academic
discipline.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the program offers a wide mix of courses, on issues
from globalization to gender.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan argues that now there are many different kinds of
publics, and environmentalists, union organizers and museum
curators could all be considered public intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
   K. Anthony Appiah agrees that the traditional definition has
been too narrow. One of the old-fashioned kind of public
intellectuals, Appiah teaches philosophy at Harvard, writes for The
New York Review of Books, and writes and edits books. He was in
Boca Raton to give a lecture on race and identity to the graduate
students. He forgot a tie, so he bought one, with pictures of
swimming blue swordfish, at the Radisson Hotel gift shop.
</P>
<P>
   To Appiah, new technology is transforming the idea of the
public, not to mention who is considered an intellectual. ``When
you create a certain conversation on the Web, you create a
community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A public intellectual should be what one does, not what one
is,'' he continued. ``It would be wonderful if in a democracy,
everyone could do it for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Where the students do fit the more traditional definition of an
intellectual, however, is in their passion, a do-gooder sensibility
and willingness to pay _ nearly $13,000 a year for an out-of-state
student, $3,500 for a Florida resident _ for the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan says there is one promise she makes prospective
students: ``This is one program which will not get you a job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
