<SLUG> BC-AILING-HMO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD UNIVERSITY SAYS IT'S WILLING TO HELP RESCUE HMO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX AND LIZ KOWALCZYK  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Harvard University _ which lent its brand name 30 years
ago to the health plan that became Harvard Pilgrim Health Care _
has told the Massachusetts attorney general it's interested in
helping rescue its brainchild by loaning the HMO millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard officials and other sources confirmed Monday the
university's interest in a proposal to keep ``the Harvard plan''
nonprofit through a money-raising deal involving major Boston
teaching hospitals, the data processing company Perot Systems, and
other investors.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard University has a near $15 billion endowment, but it
wasn't clear if its investment would come from the college's
endowment, from borrowings, or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, further details about the plan began to emerge as
potential investors received packets of financial data from the
attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   During a press briefing Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly said
his office has decided that investors will not be allowed a seat on
Harvard Pilgrim's board of directors or have any voting rights _
conditions he previously declined to outline. Investors are being
asked to lend money in exchange for IOUs called ``surplus notes,''
or surplus bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surplus bonds don't carry with them the right to manage
Harvard Pilgrim,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said that he would place additional conditions on the
deal that would prohibit investing hospitals from receiving special
treatment from the HMO. Some smaller hospitals fear that major
contributors to Harvard Pilgrim's rehabilitation would get perks
ranging from seats on the board to more favorable hospital payment
rates to referral relationships that would funnel more Harvard
Pilgrim patients to certain hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as HMO contracts go, this is one that will get quite a
bit of scrutiny,'' said Insurance Commissioner Linda Ruthardt, the
court-appointed receiver of Harvard Pilgrim.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from both Harvard University and Perot Systems
attended a meeting at a downtown law firm on Saturday, where
investment bankers hired by the state pitched a rescue plan to
potential investors, people familiar with the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, Dr. Robert Ebert, then dean of Harvard Medical School,
persuaded the university to lend its imprimatur to the fledgling
Harvard Community Health Plan, New England's first prepaid health
plan, or health maintenance organization. At the time it was a
controversial experiment, much criticized by physicians in the
traditional fee-for-service system. But eventually the Harvard plan
grew by a succession of mergers and aggressive marketing into the
region's largest HMO.
</P>
<P>
   Its growth ultimately was its undoing. On January 3, Harvard
Pilgrim discovered unexpected 1999 losses, forcing state officials
to put the giant HMO into receivership and launch a search for ways
to prevent its liquidation.
</P>
<P>
   Perot Systems, another potential investor in the Harvard Pilgrim
rescue proposal, signed a $700 million, 10-year contract with the
HMO last year to overhaul its disorganized computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   In an indication of the fragility of the deal and the
uncertainty about who will sign on, Reilly said two other options
are still on the table: the sale of Harvard Pilgrim to a for-profit
insurance company, and liquidation. Proposals are due by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   One hospital executive who attended last Saturday's three-hour
meeting said it was unclear whether there will be enough takers to
make the proposed deal viable. ``I honestly don't know,'' he said.
``I think everybody is back at the ranch trying to figure out
whether it makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The core of the proposed plan to keep Harvard Pilgrim nonprofit
is an infusion of cash from investors in exchange for ``surplus
notes.'' It was not clear how much the attorney general is asking
investors to contribute.
</P>
<P>
   These loans would need to be supplemented by a sale of some or
all of the 14 health center buildings that Harvard Pilgrim owns and
leases to Harvard Vanguard, a medical group. A bond issue to effect
this sale, which was cancelled last month when the HMO went into
receivership, was scheduled to raise $120 million.
</P>
<P>
   As explained by state regulators, the tax-exempt, long-term
surplus notes would bear high interest rates to compensate
investors for the high degree of risk involved, and for the fact
that such notes cannot be sold to others, unlike conventional
bonds. Also, bond holders would get repaid only if Harvard Pilgrim
has a surplus, which the HMO would build into its revenues _ that
is, the money it takes from subscribers in premiums.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is advantageous to Harvard Pilgrim because the money it
raised would be counted ``as part of the company's surplus,'' said
Ruthardt, rather than as part of the HMO's debt.
</P>
<P>
   However, the state insurance commissioner would have to monitor
Harvard Pilgrim's finances on an ongoing basis and approve any
interest payments on the surplus notes, based on her assessment of
the health plan's fiscal health.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the conclusion of the weekend we should know where we stand
_ whether there is a viable non-profit option or not, and what the
sales options are,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that beginning next week Harvard Pilgrim will
consolidate its employees in two locations, Wellesley and Quincy,
for an annual savings of $8 million. They now work out of six
offices.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly and Ruthardt said they approved Harvard Pilgrim's plan to
finish construction on the Quincy building in the Crown Colony II
office park. The moves will be completed in August.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, the Ad Hoc Committee to Defend Health
Care, a Cambridge-based group opposed to stockholder-owned health
care companies, accused Cigna Healthcare, one of the potential
buyers of Harvard Pilgrim, of censoring newsletters that the
for-profit HMO sends to its subscribers employed by the Phillip
Morris Co., which makes cigarettes among other products.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Ad Hoc Committee said they learned from company
emails produced as part of lawsuits against tobacco firms that
Cigna consulted Phillip Morris about references to smoking in
articles about asthma, heart disease, pregnancy, and other health
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Cigna representatives could not be reached for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
