<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0481 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9770 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-ATT-PROAM-BOS &LR;      02-07 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ATT-PROAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO STOPPING THIS TIGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ Under the ceiling of gray air that
covered the Monterey Peninsula Monday, he stood in the final
fairway, 2-iron in hand, 231 yards of golf's most historic real
estate to cover, and cast a casual eye at the numbers on the
leaderboard behind the 18th green. Tiger Woods had not an ounce of
doubt in his mind that he would make a birdie on the last hole and
prove once again that with him, all things are possible on a golf
course.
</P>
<P>
   With that birdie on the 72d hole, Woods capped another
miraculous finish: He played the last four holes in 4 under par,
shot a 31 on Pebble Beach's demanding last nine holes, in the
process erasing a seven-shot deficit in the last seven holes to
capture the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am tournament.
</P>
<P>
   His final-round 8-under-par 64 gave him his sixth straight win
on the PGA Tour, a streak that has commanded the sports spotlight,
though Woods has paid little heed to the commotion. He did,
however, smile and shake his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is more intriguing, no doubt about it,'' said Woods,
whose bogey-free final round put him at 15 under, two shots clear
of PGA Tour rookie Matt Gogel and Vijay Singh. With six straight
wins, Woods ties the second-longest streak in PGA history, that of
legendary Ben Hogan in 1948. Byron Nelson's feat of 11 wins in a
row in 1945, generally considered unbeatable, suddenly seems within
range. Woods plays at the Buick Invitational in San Diego this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Woods had started the day five shots off the lead and walked to
the first tee with one thing in mind: ``I thought I needed to shoot
64 to give myself a chance.'' Woods wanted to make early birdies to
put some fear into those golfers ahead of him, Gogel and Mark
Brooks, both at 12 under. Instead, it was the unheralded Gogel,
playing just his fourth event as a member of the PGA Tour, who
bolted from the starting blocks, making birdies at the first three
holes. When Gogel birdied the par-5 sixth and par-3 seventh, he was
17 under, making the turn in 31.
</P>
<P>
   Woods made three birdies going out, but a cool putter again
frustrated him as he lost ground to Gogel. ``But I know how
difficult it is to win out here,'' said Woods, who at that point
was 10 under and facing the teeth of Pebble Beach, holes 8-10. So
even when he went par-par-par, he knew there was still time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never over till it's over,'' said Woods. ``I just had to
be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   When he birdied the par-3 12th, he had it to 11 under, ``and I
figured if I could somehow get to 14 or 15, I might get myself a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   But even though he possesses unmatched talents, Woods needed
help. He got it in the form of a young golfer who was feeling PGA
Tour pressure for the first time. Gogel got through Pebble's
toughest stretch at 17 under, but then went bogey-bogey at the 11th
and 12th. As he was doing this, Woods was doing what he routinely
does: electrifying the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   On a simple 97-yard second shot to the par-4 15th _ perhaps
Pebble Beach's most routine hole _ Woods choked down on a pitching
wedge and took dead aim. The man who can swing a club more
ferociously than most mortals feathered the shot, landing the ball
less than a foot right of the hole. It checked nicely, then made a
left-hand turn into the cup.
</P>
<P>
   The eagle had landed, and the roar of the crowd let Gogel, three
holes away, know that the Tiger had finally jump-started his round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very surprised that went in,'' said Woods. ``It was one
of those things where you are trying to get it close and leave
yourself a putt at birdie.''
</P>
<P>
   The eagle made him 13 under, and for the first time all day, his
name was the closest to Gogel's.
</P>
<P>
   The game was on. Unfortunately for Gogel, it is a game that no
one is capable of playing quite like the 24-year-old Woods, who
marched to the 16th tee and unleashed another of his massive
drives. He was left with just 114 yards in, the wedge was again in
his hand, and only one thing was in his focus: the pin.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you,'' said Woods, ``I actually hit a better
shot on 16. The shot I wanted, the shape I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   It hit a foot in front of the pin, nearly rolled in, and settled
in tap-in range. He was 14 under and just one shot behind.
</P>
<P>
   The deficit disappeared quietly as Woods walked to the 18th tee.
Gogel had made a bogey at the 15th to fall to 14 under, a score
that got posted on the leaderboard as Woods walked to his drive
some 312 yards down the left side of the final fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Woods said he never considered the score, never thought of
anything other than attacking the 18th green. Most of the world's
greatest golfers play Pebble's 18th as a three-shot hole, but most
of the world's greatest golfers lack Woods's tenacity. He rifled
his shot into the cool air but didn't hit it pure. It came to rest
on the slope that fronts the green.
</P>
<P>
   His chip to 4 feet set up his sixth birdie of the day, put the
finishing touches on the 64, and put the pressure squarely on
Gogel, who for the first time all day did not see his name atop the
leaderboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what I had to do,'' said Gogel. ``I was swinging the
golf club so well.''
</P>
<P>
   But not well enough. He came off the bogey at 15 and made par at
16. Then, at the par-3 17th, Gogel's birdie attempt came up one
roll short. At the 18th, with Woods standing greenside, Gogel had
an uphill birdie putt from about 12 feet that could have forced a
playoff. It never had a chance. ``I misread it,'' said Gogel, who
then carelessly missed the comebacker to make a bogey 6, completing
an incoming 40.
</P>
<P>
   A stunning turn of events, to be sure, but nothing out of the
ordinary for Woods, who got a paycheck of $720,000. In his brief
but spectacular pro career, his earnings are up to $12,557,128, but
that figure does not make him blink. History is what he is after,
and next week he takes his quest to San Diego.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2203EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
