<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9773 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-SHOOTING-1     02-07 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-SHOOTING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV DEFENSE MINISTER, A CLOSE ALLY OF MILOSEVIC, IS SLAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to add background info on Bulatovic: 2nd graf to CORRECT
years as defense minister; adds new 10th graf, bgng `Bulatovic was
a fierce....'; penultimate graf to CORRECT relationship to
Asanin.) 
 (js) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAGREB, Croatia _ Yugoslavia's defense minister was shot and
killed Monday night when unidentified gunmen fired automatic
weapons through the windows of a Belgrade soccer club where he was
eating, the Belgrade police said.
</P>
<P>
   The minister, Pavle Bulatovic, 51, was from Montenegro and was a
close ally of Yugoslavia's president, Slobodan Milosevic. Bulatovic
had been defense minister since 1998 and previously from 1993-1996
and had served earlier as interior minister.
</P>
<P>
   Bulatovic was an important member of Milosevic's allied party in
Montenegro, the Socialist People's Party.
</P>
<P>
   The party is now in opposition in Montenegro, Serbia's sister
republic, which is led by Western-leaning president Milo
Djukanovic. Djukanovic has become an outspoken opponent of
Milosevic and has supported an eventual referendum on Montenegro's
independence from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But it was unclear why Bulatovic, a relatively colorless figure
with a low profile in Belgrade, might have been assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   His killing bore the hallmarks of a gangland-style murder, like
many of the political killings in Belgrade that have never been
solved. It came just one month after the Serbian paramilitary and
criminal leader, Zeljko Raznatovic, also known as Arkan, was shot
dead after eating dinner in a Belgrade hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The police say that they have captured most of those responsible
for that killing but that the organizers of the deed remain at
large. More than a dozen prominent people, some close to Milosevic,
have been killed in Belgrade in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Montenegro noted that Bulatovic was considered an
important player in the tense relationship between Serbia and
Montenegro. During the NATO bombing war against Yugoslavia last
year, he pushed for a more robust Yugoslav military intervention in
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   They also suggested Monday evening that Bulatovic had been
active in organizing military police that could be used in any
clash between Milosevic's Yugoslavia, which has up to 12,000 troops
in Montenegro, and Serbia's sister republic, where Djukanovic has
built up an equal number of well-armed police, a quasi-military of
his own.
</P>
<P>
   Bulatovic was a fierce critic of Djukanovic and was active in
organizing pro-Milosevic local assemblies in northern Montenegro,
an area that Belgrade has hinted could secede if Montenegro
declared independence.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav government, which met in a special session Monday
night after the killing, sent condolences to Bulatovic's family and
said in a statement that he ``was the victim of a classic terrorist
act'' and urged the launching of a fight against such terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government gives full support to the relevant
state organs in their uncompromising struggle against terrorism,''
the statement said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bulatovic often ate at the restaurant of the soccer club Rad,
near the military clinic where he was pronounced dead. His two
companions _ banker Vuk Obradovic and restaurant owner Mirko
Knezevic _ were wounded. They were sitting at a corner table when
the gunmen, apparently standing on the soccer field outside, fired
through the windows just before 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ljubisa Mitrovic, the editor-in-chief of the independent
Montenegrin newspaper Vjesti, said Monday night that Bulatovic
``was another victim from Milosevic's inner circle, another in a
series of murders whose motives are not clear but were obviously
well-planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Bulatovic is no direct relation to Momir Bulatovic, the Yugoslav
prime minister and leader of the Socialist People's Party. But the
two men became friendly while working together at a newspaper in
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Bulatovic was also a close relative of an important member of
the Belgrade criminal world, Darko Asanin, who was killed two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bulatovic was born in the Montenegrin village of Gornji Rovci in
the northern part of the coastal republic. He was trained as an
economist, was married and had three children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
