<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL NEWS IN BRIEF
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   KEYES RULES OUT McCAIN: Alan Keyes said Monday that if Sen. John
McCain won the Republican presidential nomination he would not
support him because, in his view, McCain was not unequivocally
opposed to abortion. ``Anyone who votes for John McCain betrays the
pro-life call,'' Keyes said in a speech at the National Press Club
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   THE HOUSE:
</P>
<P>
   FORMER U.S. ATTORNEY IN RACE: A month after he resigned as U.S.
attorney for New Mexico, where he won an indictment of the nuclear
scientist Wen Ho Lee on security charges, John J. Kelly announced
on Sunday that he intended to seek the Democratic nomination for
the 1st congressional District, which is largely the Albuquerque
metropolitan area. Kelly, who is 52 and a native of Albany, N.Y.,
joins a field that includes three other announced primary
candidates. The winner is expected to oppose Heather Wilson, the
latest in a succession of Republicans who have held the seat for
more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Michael Janofsky
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY'S SCHEDULES  &QL; 
BILL BRADLEY: Columbia, S.C., and Cleveland. &QL; 
GEORGE W. BUSH: Wilmington and Hockessin, Del., and Tigerville and
Columbia, S.C. &QL; 
STEVE FORBES: Wilmington, Del. &QL; 
AL GORE: Pembroke Pines and Tampa, Fla. &QL; 
JOHN McCAIN: North Augusta, Columbia and Goose Creek, S.C. &QL;
</P>
