</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0485 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9775 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-DEL-1STLD-WRITET     02-07 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DEL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH INSISTS HE IS THE REAL REFORMER, QUESTIONS MCCAIN'S
`RESULTS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS 7th graf, However, the ... to CORRECT that records are
from 1999, sted '95.)  
(See also DEL-PRIMARY, MCCAIN-MICH) 
(nk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY with FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, Del. _ Signaling a new, aggressive tone to his campaign
Monday, Gov. George W. Bush proclaimed that he was the true
reformer in the Republican field and portrayed his chief opponent,
Sen. John McCain, as someone who ``says one thing and does
another.''
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain has been wearing the reform mantle throughout
his campaign, Bush on Monday called himself ``a reformer with
results'' and pointed to his record as the governor of Texas on
issues like education, taxes and civil justice to justify the
claim.
</P>
<P>
   And in the wake of his 18-point loss to McCain in the New
Hampshire primary, he conceded that he had failed to define himself
in the eyes of voters there and asserted that McCain distorted his
proposed tax cut plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got defined,'' Bush said at a news conference. ``Those days
are over with. You can cut it any way you want, but I'm going to
take it to him, I'm going to take it to him. I'm not going to let
this happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   In a swing through Delaware the day before the state's
Republican primary, Bush used the news conference to raise
questions about McCain's credentials as an agent of reform, and
criticized him for accepting campaign contributions from lobbyists
for companies that have business before the Senate Commerce
Committee, which McCain heads.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, citing a news report but not giving its source, claimed
that the Arizona senator had received ``more money than anybody''
from Washington lobbyists. ``On the one hand he preaches campaign
finance reform. On the other hand he passes the plate,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Center for Responsive Politics in Washington said
campaign finance records through the first three quarters of 1999
indicated that Bush received almost five times as much money from
lobbyists and their immediate families as McCain. His aides later
explained that Bush was referring to a report in The Wall Street
Journal that said that among the candidates, McCain had the highest
percentage of total campaign contributions from lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's escalating fight with McCain has also been reflected over
the airwaves in South Carolina, the site of the next major
Republican primary, on Feb. 19. On Friday, Bush began running a
commercial that accused McCain of distorting elements of the
governor's tax cut plan.
</P>
<P>
   And Monday, McCain, using the harshest language of any political
ad so far this political season, began running an ad accusing Bush
of negative campaigning. The spot ends with the line: ``Do we
really want another politician in the White House America can't
trust?''
</P>
<P>
   That prompted a response from Bush's spokesman Ari Fleischer,
who said: ``Suggesting that Gov. Bush is as dishonest as Bill
Clinton is a disservice to our party and our principles. Our nation
has been through enough and John McCain's ad has gone too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Following Bush's stinging loss in New Hampshire and his sagging
poll numbers in South Carolina, Bush spent the weekend in Texas,
where he and his aides plotted a response to McCain's rising
popularity. The new theme became quickly evident as Bush arrived at
a luncheon sponsored by local Republican officials in Dover _ and
it was strikingly similar to McCain's campaign hallmarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Reformer with Results,'' announced a large blue and white
sign. Bush also shortened and revised his stump speech, leaving
more time for questions and answers, which the campaign dubbed
``One on One'' sessions. Again and again, Bush described himself as
a reformer, always careful to add the phrase ``with results.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as Bush and his campaign struck out in a slightly new
direction, they kept one wheel on the old track.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign announced Monday that the Texas governor's parents
would be back out on the campaign trail this week. Former President
Bush has one event scheduled in Michigan on Tuesday and and three
on Wednesday; Barbara Bush has three appearances scheduled in
Virginia on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Their appearance with the governor at a rally three days before
the New Hampshire primary was widely criticized by political
strategists and even a few people affiliated with the Bush campaign
as an ill-conceived publicity stunt that fed notions that Bush was
trying to inherit, not earn, the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   It did not help that Bush spoke for just a few minutes, making
no case for himself other than his bloodline. Additionally, his
father's reference to him as his ``boy'' arguably diminished the
governor's stature.
</P>
<P>
   Bush advisers said there had been top-level discussions about
the wisdom of using the former president and first lady as
surrogate campaigners, and that the consensus was that the couple
should no longer appear with the governor, but remained useful
campaigners on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a net plus,'' said one adviser, alluding to the
couple's popularity in many key states. ``It also helps up
establish ourselves as the alternative to Clinton by reminding
people: This is what you had.''
</P>
<P>
   But a few Republican strategists said that the Bush campaign was
playing a dangerous game with its use of surrogates and its parade
of endorsements, essentially urging voters to support Bush simply
because so many other people do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten to the point where the issue of Bush's gravitas
and abilities as a candidate are the driving issues of the
campaign,'' said one strategist. ``Having his parents work for him
doesn't address those.''
</P>
<P>
   In his appearance here Monday, Bush, while not using the word
hypocrite to describe his opponent, criticized the senator for
making campaign finance the centerpiece of his campaign while
taking contributions from lobbyists with business before his
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're tired of no results and simple, empty rhetoric,''
Bush told the lunch crowd, ``If you're tired of people who say one
thing and do another, come join our team.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain chose not to campaign in Delaware, focusing his resources
on South Carolina. Bush is the favorite in Delaware, where his main
challenger is Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   At Monday's luncheon, the governor sought to highlight McCain's
absence, saying: ``I look forward to going to every primary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
