</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEN-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHELE SAVOIA'S TIME HAS COME 
</HEADLINE>
   UNIFORMS BY DE LA RENTA(jw) 
THE LINK TO GLAMOUR   
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For 16 years Michele Savoia has been sewing
custom-made suits for men in the manner of those worn during the
1940s. For just as many years, most of his adult life in fact, he
has longed for a return to midcentury civility.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see people out at night in T-shirts that say things on
them,'' he lamented from his East Village studio and shop. ``They
were out all day in those T-shirts, and that's what you're sitting
next to in a restaurant. It's unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   There is not a huge following for the kind of anachronistic
wide-bodied clothes Savoia makes. Still, the tailor, who was
trained by his Sicilian grandfather and at the Fashion Institute of
Technology, has made a living assembling suits for men who compete
in dance competitions.
</P>
<P>
   He has outfitted the cast of the Broadway musical ``Swing,'' as
well as the occasional soul who wants very little to do with
anything one might find in a Banana Republic.
</P>
<P>
   After years of working quietly removed from fashion's circle,
Savoia had his moment on Thursday morning when he presented the
first show of his career, under the tents in Bryant Park. The
audience raved as dancers and a Frank Sinatra impersonator and even
Dominic Chianese (Uncle Junior from ``The Sopranos'') paraded down
the runway in Savoia's masterly cut trousers and jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Savoia emerged from backstage with tears in his eyes. ``I think
fashion is finally cathing up with me,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNIFORMS BY DE LA RENTA
</P>
<P>
   It is fairly certain that when an appointed commission met to
examine police corruption in New York, no one suggested creating
new uniforms for officers to ensure their superior behavior. Things
are apparently different in the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Not too long ago, Oscar de la Renta, who shows his fall 2000
women's wear collection on Tuesday, was asked by the country's
chief of police to design a new look for the law enforcers of the
Dominican Republic. The police force in that country, where de la
Renta keeps an oft-visited home, is being revamped in the wake of
corruption scandals that led to the firing of thousands of
officers.
</P>
<P>
   De la Renta, who is not being paid for his designs, says that
Dominicans are seeking a police force that is more civic-minded
than it has been in the past. The old uniforms were gray.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dark gray was a threatening color,'' de la Renta
explained. His uniforms will be less elaborate and more functional,
he said, adding that he is paring down on gold medals and ``things
one associates with a Latin American police.''
</P>
<P>
   His uniforms will be navy blue and white, ``more pleasing to the
eye,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, it is hoped, less intimidating to Dominican citizens.
</P>
<P>
   THE LINK TO GLAMOUR
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of what is done today on the Web is done by kids in
their teens and 20s who have no sense of aesthetic offline.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the words of Terron Schaefer, long out of his 20s, who
worked for 10 years as an advertising executive before moving into
marketing and helping to revamp Bloomingdale's, Macy's and Harrods.
(``They were selling Tampax and toilet paper on the first floor
when I arrived,'' he said of Harrods.)
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, at a party at the Four Seasons, he unleashed his
latest venture, Style365.com, a Web site that sells nothing but
links users to prescreened sites selling what, in Schaefer's view,
is the best of everything.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer is a man of impressive connections. His site has been
designed by the legendary graphic designer Massimo Vignelli. Its
board of advisers includes Frank Gehry; Joyce Ma, a Hong Kong
retailer; and Lady Victoria Waymouth, a British interior designer.
</P>
<P>
   If one clicks on the fashion category on Style365, one is
connected to the Web sites of houses like Yves Saint Laurent,
rather than houses like the Club Monaco. A food search links to a
Parisian bakery, Boulangerie Poilane, that for $37 will send its
famed sourdough bread.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer refers to the site as ``a finishing school.'' Rather
than flashing banner ads, he offers glamorous advertising images
shot by people like Bruce Weber, which, he hopes, will keep eyes
lingering longer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
