<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0487 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-WOMEN-FASHION-2TAKES-     02-07 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-FASHION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NOW, EVEN REBELS ARE LOOKING LADYLIKE  (ART ADV: Photo NYT20 is
being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Until now, the difference between being a lady and
dressing like a lady was usually a drag queen. The whole notion of
dressing up had degenerated into such a parody, a freak show of
Upper-East-Side-luncheon-suit gaiety, that only a few designers
would try it. But after last season's tony Prada show, and with a
new generation of women dressing like their mothers, even their
grandmothers, it's apparently safe again to be a lady.
</P>
<P>
   What's remarkable about this flowering of chic understatement
and such formerly stodgy details as piping and covered buttons is
that it isn't confined to the predictable designers, like Carolina
Herrera and Victor Alfaro, although they are firmly in the groove.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday afternoon, in the opening round of the women's fall
2000 collections, Susan Cianciola abandoned her art-house
wanderings into the meaning of seams and put on a real show, with
models and clothes that were as much about technique as the
innately feminine world of dressing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that I had to take everything I had done before and
throw it into the garbage,'' Cianciola said.
</P>
<P>
   And that night, in a community theater on the Lower East Side,
Miguel Adrover, whose collection last season made him the new
designer to watch this week, put on a brilliant show. It, too,
presented a more polished view of clothes, although Adrover, being
still young and ornery and poor, is too much of a rebel to fall
into conventional traps.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway into his show he sent out an elegantly cut coat made of
mattress ticking. It was stained with water marks and patched in
places with squares of the same fabric, and was buttoned over a
skirt of cotton shirting stripes, so that it looked like a simple
but respectable Sunday-going-to-church outfit out of a Willa Cather
story.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, afterward, when Adrover sweetly explained that the source
for the ticking had been a mattress that had belonged to his
neighbor, the recently deceased writer Quentin Crisp, the coat
suddenly acquired a macabre dimension. Having once absorbed the
shocks of life as a mattress, what future delights would it hold as
a chic town coat?
</P>
<P>
   Adrover put a lot of himself into this collection. One could see
that. For instance, he took an ordinary navy sweatshirt and a
couple of Yankee baseball caps and ingeniously worked the hats into
the shoulders of the sweatshirt, so that the model had these
built-up looking shoulders, except that they had NY's on them.
Wonderful. He made a similar play with a Burberry raincoat, turning
it inside out and around, so that the label was in front. But the
upshot was not a backward-looking Burberry or another avant-garde
instance of deconstructing a luxury label. It was, rather, a
beautifully finished dress.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Adrover's clothes _ the high-neck Princess Leia
blouses and pencil-thin plaid coats, the dresses in tea-stained
decorator fabric and a poncho made of reversed pieces of the
Burberry tartan loosely connected by scarf fringe _ demonstrate
that he wants to be taken seriously as a designer. ``I don't want
to end up with samples hanging in my closet,'' he said. ``I want to
sell clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cianciola's collection was a bit harder to follow, although it
may be a matter of looking more closely at the details _ the
delicate, almost invisible fraying on a turned-back cuff, or the
hand-stitching on a coat-and-skirt ensemble _ and getting beyond
the overall impression of 1950s, tearoom dowdiness. The results of
Cianciola's desire to change direction, to explore construction,
may be a case of the emperor's new clothes. But she is right to
move on.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the kind of people who sought out her influential
arts-and-crafts ideas, fellow artists and downtown style seekers,
will likely only be satisfied with sophistication on their own
offbeat terms. And that could be something as coyly wholesome as a
belted olive jumper over a black jersey top etched with beads.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any irony in the new ``new dressing,'' it is how
someone like Miuccia Prada or, for that matter, Adrover, can take a
formerly frumpy style like an A-line skirt or a classic town coat
and make it look cool and young, while designers known for ladylike
clothes haven't completely broken out of the old formulas.
</P>
<P>
   There was a lot to admire in Richard Tyler's collection Monday,
shown in his town house overlooking Gramercy Park: the boned
jackets and sharply cut trousers in faded chalk-striped navy; the
elegant, portrait-collared wool tops that fit the body like a tight
T-shirt; a sturdy brown herringbone coat playfully embroidered with
wisps of feathers; and a tunic made of tiles of pieced-together
brown leather.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, what has become of the light, frisky hand of Richard
Tyler? As sexy as his tailoring was _ and Tyler knows better than
most how to cut a suit or a pair of pants _ the clothes, often in
matchy-matchy combinations, lacked that loose, offhand edge that
separates modern ladylike dressing from the old uptight variety.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Herrera could have loosened things up a little, too,
but just a little. Her show Monday opened with slim belted coats in
black wool and leather, and dark pants suits with ultratight,
three-quarter-sleeved tops. There was a conspicuous richness in the
materials _ gray flannel, boucle mixed with georgette, broadtail
with chiffon _ and a familiar sense of Herrera's relaxed chic,
notably in a black merino sweater with wide mink cuffs and a cowl,
shown with sleek black wool pants.
</P>
<P>
   But there was also a self-consciousness about the clothes, as if
they had been studied too long _ a correctness that might have been
softened with humor and attitude that says, ``Let's not take any of
this chic business too seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bill Blass was one designer who knew how to do that _ and no
self-consciously hip red-leather A-line skirts with dipping
waistlines for him. Make it light, babe.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Alfaro put on a good, cool show on Sunday. His slinky
velour trousers in abstract checks and snug leather jackets evoke a
skinny socialite of the 1970s era, Lee Radziwill twirling the food
around on her plate and eating nothing; thin women who liked
chain-link belts and poor-boy sweaters and who could see the charm
in a black corduroy coat piped in kelly green, with a chain belt
looping in and out, as they went skipping through the bright, neon
stimulation of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Catherine Malandrino sent out cute pieces like gauzy,
bead-embroidery shirts, argyle sweaters in vivid shades of magenta
and violet, and fuzzy mohair tops with leather hot pants. But as
outfits they added up to a shuddering mess.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Cooper, an Australian designer making his first appearance
on the New York catwalks, showed halter-style jumpsuits, fuzzy
vests over slinky turtlenecks and buff suede trousers with a
chocolate, kimono jacket. The cuts evoked some of Alexander
McQueen's flair without his gothic overtones.
</P>
<P>
   Fause Haten, who apparently has a following in his native
Brazil, also showed Monday, with a jolting soundtrack that sounded
like ripping sheet metal at the Riverhead Raceway. There were black
coats and jackets that looked as if they had been slashed, and lots
of gold. Gold distressed leather. Gold flecked boots. Gold-Lurex.
Gold floral brocade. It was like being smothered by a Godiva
chocolate box. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
