u a BC-NY-DIALLO-PAUSE-600&AMP;A     02-07 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-PAUSE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIEF ABSENCE OF GUNFIRE EMERGES AS A KEY ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also DIALLO-TRIAL) 
(js) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ As the prosecution continues presenting its case
against four officers charged with murder in the death of Amadou
Diallo this week, a pause in the fusillade of 41 shots that the
officers fired is becoming almost as central as the gunfire itself.
</P>
<P>
   Three witnesses for the prosecution have testified to a pause in
the 41 shots fired _ one witness said it was as long as five
seconds _ and more may do so.
</P>
<P>
   While defense lawyers say the pause was so brief as to be
insignificant, prosecutors may use it to show that the encounter
with Diallo on Feb. 4, 1999, did not unfold as quickly as the
defense has maintained and that the officers had time to realize
that Diallo did not pose a threat to them.
</P>
<P>
   The brief absence of gunfire could prove troubling for defense
lawyers. In past police shootings in which there was a pause in
gunfire, state courts have ruled that the pause was a legitimate
issue for the jury to consider.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the 1984 shooting of Eleanor Bumpurs, a mentally
disturbed woman killed by the police in her Bronx apartment, the
State Court of Appeals cited an interval between the two shots that
killed her in upholding the indictment against Officer Stephen
Sullivan, who was ultimately acquitted of manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   In the other case, a decade later, an appellate court upheld the
conviction of Officer Peter Del-Debbio for assault in the shooting
of a fellow officer who was undercover. The court ruled that the
judge had correctly instructed the jury to analyze each shot fired
by Del-Debbio separately in determining whether the shooting was
justified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if a defendant is justified in using deadly physical
force at the beginning of a single, ongoing encounter with an
assailant,'' the court said, ``his right to use that force
terminates at the point he can no longer reasonably believe the
assailant still poses a threat to him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Diallo case, the question is whether any pause in the
gunfire was long enough for officers to realize that Diallo, who
did not have a weapon, did not pose a threat. He was later found to
be carrying only a wallet and a beeper when he was shot outside his
Bronx apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution has argued that Diallo had fallen or was falling
to the ground after some shots were fired, a point that is to be
supported by the city medical examiner in testimony on Tuesday. The
prosecution is likely to argue that the pause should have allowed
the officers to see that Diallo was incapacitated and that he did
not have a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers have objected to the very word ``pause,'' and
say the ``break'' _ their term of choice _ was not long enough for
the officers to have made such a determination.
</P>
<P>
   They have attributed any interruption in the shots to Officer
Edward McMellon, who was one of the two officers who opened fire
first, falling backward off the stoop in front of the vestibule of
Diallo's apartment building on Wheeler Avenue, leading the other
officers to believe that McMellon had been shot and to redouble
their fire.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Litman, a criminal defense lawyer, said the issue could
rest on the length of time between the shots. ``The less time that
goes by between shot one and shot last, the more a person can argue
that he or she was in the same state of mind at shot one and shot
end,'' he said. ``The more time that goes by, the more time for
reflection.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was a pause in the sequence of shots, Litman added,
``the more the prosecution's going to argue that restarting wasn't
justified.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In testimony last week, the first witness to describe a pause,
Debbie Rivera, tapped out a pause of a second or less. The second
witness who was on Wheeler Avenue that night, Ida Vincent, had
agreed in front of the grand jury that the pause was ``about a
second''; Monday, she described it as ``a few seconds,'' but the
sounds she tapped out suggested a briefer break.
</P>
<P>
   On the witness stand Monday, Thomas Bell, who lives around the
corner from the scene of the shooting, described hearing four or
five shots, followed by a pause of three to five seconds or four to
five seconds. As he tapped out the sounds of the shooting, the
pause was about four seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers honed in on Bell's distance from the scene of
the shooting, and his previous description to investigators of a
``slight pause.''
</P>
<P>
   Prof. Vivian Berger of Columbia Law School said a pause could
bear on the charge of intentional murder the officers face. ``It is
much harder to infer intent at the beginning _ the officers were
reacting in fright,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if they had even a few seconds to stop and think it over
and realize their mistake,'' Berger said, it could support a murder
charge.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution could urge Justice Joseph C. Teresi of state
Supreme Court, who is hearing the case, to consider the cases of
Sullivan and Del-Debbio as precedent or simply persuasive
precursors as he charges the jury.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
