u w BC-CLINTON-BUDGET-HNS &LR;      02-07 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PUTS FORTH $1.84 TRILLION BUDGET PROPOSAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trims) 
 
By JOHN C. HENRY 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton sent Congress a $1.84 trillion
spending plan for the federal government Monday, the opening salvo
in an election-year battle over cutting taxes, reducing debt and
financing health care.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who wants spending to increase by 2.5 percent in
2001, urged lawmakers to approve billions more for new programs, a
direction that would assure Clinton a policy legacy well beyond his
January departure from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``This budget, in short, makes really strong and significant
steps toward achieving the great goals that I believe America
should pursue in this new century,'' the president said at a
ceremony unveiling the 10 1/2-pound document for the fiscal year
that begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans quickly voiced their opposition,
characterizing Clinton's proposal ``a fantasy'' and ``a mockery.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has outmaneuvered Republicans in past budget
fights, loaded his 2001 spending plan with politically potent
proposals, providing Democrats with a checklist to carry into the
fall elections.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with his fourth consecutive budget surplus, Clinton urged
Congress to approve $351 billion in tax cuts for low- and
middle-income Americans to help pay for college, care for sick
relatives and save for retirement. He also wants to spend more on
schools, environmental protection, gun-law enforcement, and erase
the publicly held portion of the national debt by 2013.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who came into office in 1993 promising to expand health
care, included in his budget the initial funding for a 10-year,
$110 billion program to help provide health insurance for almost
one-fourth of the 44 million uninsured Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Again looking a decade ahead, the president asked Congress for a
$160 billion program to provide prescription drugs for the elderly.
He also called for setting aside another $35 billion under Medicare
as a reserve fund to cover ``catastrophic'' drug costs.
</P>
<P>
   The president also proposed saving $70 billion in Medicare funds
over the next decade by allowing the program to employ cost-cutting
methods used by private health plans, like creating networks of
care providers who agree to charge less for services.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also wants the Republican-led Congress to eliminate
corporate tax breaks totaling $96 billion, increase cigarette taxes
by 25 cents a pack and impose a $3,000 fine on tobacco companies
for each smoker under 18.
</P>
<P>
   The president's budget would increase funding for the Department
of Education to $4.5 billion, up 13 percent from the current level.
The increase _ the largest since the agency was founded in 1979 _
would be earmarked for reducing class size, increasing teacher pay,
and rebuilding and modernizing school buildings, including wiring
classrooms for access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also wants $1 billion more for Head Start, a boost that
would pay for an additional 70,000 children to participate. About
880,000 preschoolers currently are enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   The president's budget also seeks more money to restore coastal
areas damaged by offshore oil drilling and to protect historic
places and natural treasures, proposals that are gaining support
from both parties in Congress. He also proposes spending more to
help restore the Everglades, fight pollution in the Great Lakes and
assist the salmon recovery in the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   On law enforcement, Clinton proposes spending $150 million to
hire investigators and prosecutors to step up enforcement of the
nation's gun laws. He also wants $2.4 billion for a three-year
prison building program, the largest expansion of federal lockups
since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Although he proposes no increase in the defense budget, the
president wants to refocus spending to procure $60 billion worth of
new weapons, to increase military pay by 3.7 percent, and upgrade
health and housing benefits for the nation's armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans dismissed Clinton's budget as a campaign
document for Vice President Al Gore's bid for the White House and
the Democratic Party's effort to take control of Congress in the
November elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has all things for everyone they feel they'll need to get
Al Gore elected president,'' said House Budget Committee Chairman
John Kasich, R-Ohio. ``This budget is nothing more than a fantasy.
It's going nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in both the House and Senate, which begin budget
hearings in the coming weeks, said they plan to provide a bigger
tax cut and hold the line on spending. Clinton's suggested tax
increases, GOP lawmakers said, will be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me be very clear,'' said House Majority Leader Dick Armey,
R-Texas. ``This Congress will not raise taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Rep. Bill Archer's count, the president's proposed tax
increases would amount to $181 billion over the next decade. ``This
is the Regis Philbin approach to budgeting, except the government
gets all the checks,'' the Texas Republican and House Ways and
Means Committee chairman said, referring to the host of
television's popular game show ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, said Clinton appears to
be conspiring with House Democratic leaders ``to obstruct any
progress this year on any issue'' before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's budget is a mockery,'' DeLay said. ``He makes
no credible attempt to address tax relief, fiscal responsibility or
preserving Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Dallas, said she welcomes some of
Clinton's initiatives because they resemble what Republicans have
tried to pass in recent years. She cautioned that the difficulty
will come in negotiating details of the budget with the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be up to the (Republicans) in Congress to protect the
Social Security Trust Fund, strengthen our national defense and
return to hard-working Americans their due share of the income-tax
surplus,'' the senator said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For 2001, Clinton envisions a $184 billion surplus. Of that
amount, $160 billion will come from the Social Security retirement
system. He proposed using the Social Security surplus to help pay
off the federal debt by 2013, then dedicating the interest savings
on the debt to extend the solvency of Social Security to 2050.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget forecasts a $746 billion surplus over the next
decade in the federal budget outside Social Security. The
Congressional Budget Office estimates a $1.9 trillion surplus, a
figure Republicans prefer when arguing for a larger tax cut than
the president has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   The president is pushing to use almost $300 billion of that
surplus to bolster the Medicare system, extending it through 2025.
Democrats already are honing their rhetoric to attack tax-cutting
Republicans as willing to sacrifice the long-term viability of the
medical program for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans' mantra is massive tax cuts first and not a
penny for Social Security and Medicare,'' said House Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo. ``They have no budget _ only a reckless
plan to spend the surplus on an irresponsible tax cut for their
special-interest allies with no investment in Social Security and
Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   At an issues conference in Hot Springs, Va., Clinton urged House
Democrats to help him press congressional Republicans to approve
his spending plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the better of the budget battle the last couple of
years because we stuck together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
