<SLUG> BC-NASA-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROPOSES $435 MILLION BOOST TO NASA BUDGET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Monday requested a $435
million increase for the space program, including money to begin
planning for a successor to the space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   NASA chief Dan Goldin said that after years of cutbacks in
spending, the president's budget proposal for the fiscal year 2001
would finally allow the agency to grow again.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in seven years the NASA budget is really
going up,'' he said. In the current fiscal year the agency's budget
is $13.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin said the space agency is proposing to spend $6 billion by
2005, including a half billion dollars in the next fiscal year to
jump start stalled efforts begun in 1996 to develop a successor to
the space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   The $1 billion pledged by the space agency four years ago for a
reusable prototype called the X-33 has encountered a series of
setbacks. The obstacles forced plans to select a shuttle successor
this year to be postponed until 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The new money will be used for research and development to
further determine the safest, most efficient way of launching
humans into space. NASA's goal is a spacecraft that is 100 times
safer than the 19-year-old shuttle and 10 percent of the cost to
operate.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed budget, which is virtually certain to be changed by
Congress, would also provide money to hire 500 new employees and
replace 1,500 current workers who are expected to retire or leave
the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Not all areas of NASA are projected to grow under the
president's budget.
</P>
<P>
   The operational funding for the Johnson Space Center in Houston
would rise slightly from the current $4.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Overall funding for the international space station would
decrease from $2.3 billion to $2.1 billion as private firms
complete hardware for the station.
</P>
<P>
   However, the budget would allocate $300 million, $100 million
more than last year, to build back-up equipment to Russian pieces
of the station.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian-made crew module is more than two years behind
schedule and station planners question whether the Russians can
successfully carry out plans to restaff their aging Mir next month
and keep their commitments to the new international outpost.
</P>
<P>
   The president's budget also calls for an increase in research
funds for the space station from $394 million to $455 million.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed budget for shuttle operations would rise from $2.9
billion to $3.1 billion, enabling managers to more than double
annual investments in shuttle safety upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   Under the upgrade strategy, NASA would spend $2.1 billion
through 2005 to improve sensors that monitor the safety of powerful
rocket engines; replace a volatile hydraulic system with safer
electrical components and install electronic cockpit displays.
</P>
<P>
   The president also proposed an increase in NASA funding for
academic programs from $7.3 million to $10.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Texas, said that the NASA budget proposal
was better than those submitted in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to previous budgets this appears to be more
realistic,'' he said. ``And I would hope majority in Congress would
follow this and we do not have to fight like we did last year to
restore $1 billion to the NASA budget.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
