<SLUG> BC-TV-PBS-PRESIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNER BROADCASTING EXECUTIVE IS NEW PRESIDENT OF PBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Public Broadcasting Service announced the appointment Monday
of Pat Mitchell, a longtime news producer and executive for Turner
Broadcasting, as its president.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, the 57-year-old president of CNN Productions, the
documentary arm of CNN, will be responsible for navigating PBS
through an increasingly difficult landscape, marked by intensified
competition from cable channels like Discovery, A&AMP;E and the History
Channel, and by continued pressure to raise money from both the
federal government and corporations.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Mitchell acknowledged several
challenges, perhaps chief among them trying to lead an organization
that has a longstanding conflict between its central programming
arm and its member stations, almost 350 of them, many of which
believe they should control their own program schedules. The
situation has been described as a quagmire by numerous producers
and former PBS executives.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said she hoped to turn that situation into an advantage
by finding ways to make use of attractive local programming on a
national level _ which PBS' cable competitors cannot do _
especially in news and public affairs programs. In general, she
said, ``we need to maximize the promise of PBS.''
</P>
<P>
   Colin G. Campbell, the chairman of the PBS board, acknowledged
that differences in philosophy between the central PBS organization
and its station members had bedeviled the service in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``With any organization which is a membership organization,
there is going to be some tension at the center,'' Campbell said.
``We believe Pat will be able to operate with that and keep it to a
minimum.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Campbell and Mitchell cited the coming digitalization of
television, which will open up a whole new range of channels, as a
means to help PBS in several ways, including making it easier for
the organization to fulfill its educational mission, while also
supplying national programs of quality. But Campbell said that PBS
stations would need help to raise the money needed to convert their
signals to a digital format.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell also emphasized that PBS, which has fought several
battles in Congress over federal financing, would continue to seek
government money as well as contributions from corporations and
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nonprofit, noncommercial operation,'' Mitchell said.
``I'm going to meet with congressmen and discuss our goals. My
message will be, How can we be a country without an organization
like this?''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell replaces Ervin Duggan, who served for five and a half
years and left in October. The organization has been without a
chief program executive since last May.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell conceded that PBS also needed to affirm its status as a
leading television outlet for certain kinds of programming like
science, nature, children's, cultural and public affairs programs,
all of which have been usurped to some degree by channels that
cater to specific audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, she said she planned to use her own
extensive background as a news producer to upgrade programming in
those areas. Indeed, besides being the first woman to lead PBS, she
said it was far more important that she was the first former
full-time television producer to head the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how the process works,'' she said. ``I think I can help
in making the process of getting shows on the air work even
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell is scheduled to start at PBS on March 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2227EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0496 </DOCNO>
