<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9792 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GM-APPOINT-NYT &LR;      02-07 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CADILLAC CHIEF MOVES TO GM SERVICE UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Call him Mr. Goodwrench. John F. Smith, charged three
years ago with fixing the General Motors Cadillac division, was
named Monday as general manager of the company's service and parts
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The unit, which sells GM and ACDelco parts and accessories
worldwide and markets the Goodwrench service brand name, has 12,000
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cadillac is very important, but this clearly is a promotion
for him,'' said Christopher W. Cedergren, managing director of
Nextrend Inc., a Thousand Oaks, Calif., consulting firm. ``He was
instrumental in putting together a new portfolio of products that
focus on a central theme and unfortunately aren't out yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 49, presided over a redesign of the Cadillac line, but
most of the new cars and trucks will not appear in showrooms for
another two years. Until then, Cadillac sales are likely to
languish, or to improve only slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of tinkering with Cadillac, Smith will replace William
J. Lovejoy in the service unit. Last month, Lovejoy was put in
charge of G.M.'s sales, service and marketing in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was unavailable for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Under Smith's watch, Cadillac sales stalled while the division
planned a unified theme for the cars and trucks of the future. That
design is embodied in the Evoq, a roadster with a closer
resemblance to the Batmobile than traditional slab-sided Cadillacs.
</P>
<P>
   The first Cadillac to sport that futuristic design is the 2001
Escalade sport utility vehicle, which is scheduled to appear in
dealerships this fall. A year later, a racy new Catera sedan will
appear; about the same time a cross between a sport-utility vehicle
and a pickup truck will go on sale, according to industry
executives. In the autumn of 2002, the Evoq will finally go on
sale, along with a car-based sport utility vehicle, the executives
said.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Cadillac is fated to struggle, analysts and industry
experts said. For 57 years, Cadillac was the nation's best-selling
luxury car brand, a title it finally lost to Lincoln in 1998. Last
year, both Lincoln and Cadillac were passed by Mercedes-Benz and
Lexus. Cadillac sales fell 2.2 percent in 1999, to 178,507 cars.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's replacement has been chosen and is expected to be named
later this month, said Steven J. Harris, a GM spokesman. Until
then, Martin Walsh, Cadillac's general marketing director, is
running the division.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is not related to John F. Smith Jr., GM's chairman and
chief executive. G. Richard Wagoner Jr. is scheduled to take over
as chief executive in June. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
