<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9796 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-GIULIANI-CONSERVAT     02-07 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-CONSERVATIVES-ART-770(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE PARTY LEADER SAYS GOP CAN DO BETTER THAN GIULIANI
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLONIE, N.Y. _ All but ruling out his party's support for Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's Senate run, the Conservative Party leader said
Monday that he would prefer that the mayor drop out of the race,
and said his party would readily nominate Rep. Rick A. Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I would rather that he didn't run,'' the party
chairman, Michael Long, said at a news conference at the party's
annual conference here, near Albany.
</P>
<P>
   He also pointed out that Public Advocate Mark Green, a liberal
Democrat, would become mayor if Giuliani was elected to the Senate
with a year left in the mayoral term. ``He'd be doing the voters
and the taxpayers a favor if he stayed as mayor,'' Long said.
</P>
<P>
   He argued that any number of other Republicans, like Lazio, who
are more conservative but less polarizing than the mayor, would
fare better against the Democratic candidate, Hillary Rodham
Clinton. ``I submit to you if Rudy got out of the race and someone
like, for instance, Congressman Lazio, got into the race, she
loses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who also attended the Conservative conference, had
considered entering the Senate race earlier, and said Monday that
he had not ruled out doing so, but added that if he did, he would
want to be on the Republican line as well as the Conservative line.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor deflected questions about Long's comments, and
declined to say whether he would seek the Conservative Party
nomination. ``Generally, what I am interested in is not what a
political party thinks,'' he said. ``It is what the people in the
state think.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Conservative Party is small _ its 170,000 registered
voters are 1.6 percent of the state total _ it wields a
disproportionate influence in state politics. In statewide
elections, Republicans who also have the Conservative nomination
can count on getting about 300,000 votes on that line, or 4 percent
to 8 percent of the total vote, often enough to decide a close
race.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute between Long and Giuliani has been simmering for
months, as Long repeatedly complained that the mayor had not called
him or met with him to discuss a possible endorsement. But their
rift was deepened by many of the mayor's comments on television
news programs on Sunday morning, the day of Clinton's official
announcement of her candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said on television that he would not change his
position and support a ban on the abortion procedure that opponents
call partial-birth abortion, although the Conservative Party has
called such a change in position as a minimum condition for
considering endorsing him. If he is elected to the Senate, Giuliani
said Sunday on ``Meet the Press'' on NBC, ``I would vote to
preserve the option for women.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing the same day on ABC's ``This Week,'' the mayor said:
``I'd like to run on all the lines. I'd like to run on the Liberal
line, the Conservative line. I'd like to run on the Democratic
line, if I could figure out how to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Long said Monday that if the mayor stood fast on the abortion
issue, ``he doesn't get a ticket to the dance.'' But he also
suggested that Giuliani would never make a long-awaited pitch for
Conservative support, the closest Long has come to saying outright
that his party would not nominate the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Long and Giuliani talked briefly in March last year,
Conservative Party leaders have been increasingly frustrated with
Giuliani's refusal even to discuss the possibility of a pact. And
several people close to Long said the mayor's comments on the
Sunday talk shows might have been the final insult. Aside from
Giuliani's unwillingness to compromise on abortion, his suggestion
that party identity and party ideology are meaningless sounded to
Conservatives like an attack on their reason for being.
</P>
<P>
   Long repeatedly used the word ``liberal'' to describe Giuliani,
who has taken positions, like supporting abortion rights and
endorsing gay rights, that the Conservative Party opposes. And
several times, Long questioned whether the mayor really planned to
run, noting that Giuliani had not definitively stated his
intentions.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Giuliani said: ``I have not given up anyone's
endorsement. But the reality is I don't think that endorsements
really matter, particularly in my case. I am well known. I have a
record that people can look at and they can judge whether they like
that record and they would like to see that kind of dedication,
that kind of conscientiousness, that kind of hard work that I put
out on behalf of people in the city done for the people of the
state.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While Giuliani narrowly leads Clinton in public opinion polls,
those surveys have reflected a two-way race, without a third,
Conservative candidate. In any case, it is expected to be a close
contest, and no Republican has won statewide office in New York
without the Conservative nomination since Sen. Jacob Javits and
Attorney General Louis J. Lefkowitz were re-elected in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   New York is the only state that allows a candidate to be
nominated by more than one party and to compile the votes received
on the ballot lines of separate parties.
</P>
<P>
   The Conservatives have shown that by running their own
candidates, they can play havoc with the Republicans. In 1990, when
Gov. Mario Cuomo, a Democrat, would have been vulnerable to a
strong Republican challenge, the Conservatives nominated their own
candidate, Herbert London, drawing more than 800,000 votes and
helping assure Cuomo an easy victory.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Long has said that he was talking with a handful of
people who may run on the Conservative line, though he has refused
to name any of them.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, he went out of his way to talk up the prospects of
Lazio as a more acceptable, more conservative Republican _
intentionally provocative talk meant in part to tweak the
Republican establishment. Lazio, from Suffolk County, had wanted to
run for the Senate, and Gov. George Pataki was at first seen as
promoting his candidacy. But in August, Pataki and others pressured
him into stepping aside to clear the primary field for Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and other party leaders have had rocky relations
with Giuliani, but most consider him their party's best hope to
capture a seat now held by a Democrat, Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, who is retiring. While many would prefer Lazio, they see
him as a weaker candidate against Clinton, and they desperately
want to avoid a primary fight and a party split in November.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's appearance here Sunday night, playing host at a dessert
reception for Conservative leaders, ``certainly raises
speculation'' that the congressman still might run, Long said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if he made a phone call, we're ready to move,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said Monday, as he has before, that he still had not ruled
out a run. ``I am thinking it through, and I have not closed the
door,'' he said. But, he added, ``I would not pursue the
Conservative nomination without pursuing the Republican nomination
at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Conservative Party gathering, ``There was what I would
characterize as overwhelming support for me to get into the Senate
race,'' he said. ``It is very clear to me that if it is not me,
there will be some other Conservative candidate,'' running to the
mayor's right in November.
</P>
<P>
   Long revealed Monday that his party, which opposes abortion in
all forms, had been conferring with the Right to Life Party about
the possibility of both parties' nominating the same candidate for
Senate. ``Hopefully, we're going to do that,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
