<HEADLINE>
MAYOR ASSAILS SONG AT HILLARY CLINTON EVENT  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton's campaign says it was
intended to serve just as an innocuous bit of background music. But
a 27-year-old Billy Joel song played before she announced her
candidacy for the U.S. Senate on Sunday inspired an attack Monday
from her opponent, Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   A Billy Joel greatest hits album played for the audience at the
campaign event in Purchase, N.Y., included Joel's 1973 song
``Captain Jack,'' which tells the tale of a frustrated young man
who spends a Saturday night listening to music, smoking marijuana
and masturbating. ``Captain Jack will get you high tonight and take
you to your special island,'' Joel sings.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, a spokesman for Clinton's campaign, said the
first lady and her campaign staff did not pick the song, which he
agreed should not have been played. He said a sound technician
chose the song.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
