<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-EXP-BUDGET-CLINTON-NY     02-07 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXP-BUDGET-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROPOSES $1.84 TRILLION BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton sent Congress a budget proposal
Monday built on the idea that the budget surplus will allow the
nation to have it all, from increased government spending to tax
cuts and big reductions in the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   The president's budget, his eighth and last, calls for
additional spending across the range of issues that have long been
central to his agenda, including health care, education and the
environment, as well as increases for the military.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it stresses fiscal responsibility and maps out
a path to eliminate the portion of the national debt held by the
public over the next 13 years. And it tries to define the size of
the surplus in a way that builds Clinton's priorities into the
budget mix for the next decade and leaves Republicans relatively
little room to pursue the sweeping tax cuts they want.
</P>
<P>
   There is no argument between the parties that projected budget
surpluses, assuming they materialize, present the nation with
tremendous opportunities, including a chance to pay down the debt
and insure Social Security's long-term solvency.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday's exchanges vividly illustrated the continuing
deadlock over how to apportion the surplus. Republicans have
generally emphasized tax cuts, Democrats for the most part have
called for maintaining or increasing spending on critical needs,
and each has labeled the other's approach a threat to debt
repayment and the future of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget blueprint is unlikely to break that impasse,
and the debate this year is raging not just on Capitol Hill but on
the campaign trail, where there are stark divisions within and
between the parties over how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget calls for total spending in 2001 of nearly
$1.84 trillion, including an increase of 3.9 percent in spending on
the third of the budget accounted for by basic government
operations like the military, national parks, education and law
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   That increase, and proposed growth in this discretionary
spending of about 2.5 percent a year for the rest of the decade,
would, at least by the White House's accounting, cover the costs of
a wide range of initiatives laid out by Clinton over the past few
months. They range from an expansion of basic scientific research
to new training for preschool teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a balanced budget with a balanced approach to our
national priorities,'' Clinton told reporters. ``It maintains our
fiscal discipline, pays down the debt, extends the life of Social
Security and Medicare, and invests in our families and our
future.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is also an election-year platform, chock-full of programs
that Vice President Al Gore, Hillary Rodham Clinton and other
Democratic candidates can use to defend themselves, attack their
opponents and illustrate their stands on issues.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans derided the administration's overall proposal as a
liberal tax-and-spend manifesto that they would discard as they set
about drafting their own tax and spending bills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
