<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TURNS FOCUS TO EASING UPSTATE ECONOMIC TROUBLES
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEEKTOWAGA, N.Y. _ With her official declaration for the U.S.
Senate behind her, Hillary Rodham Clinton flew into a region of New
York on Monday that is likely to be a prime battleground in the
race this fall, turning her attention to what has long been a
dominant concern among voters here: the region's long-suffering
economy.
</P>
<P>
   With President Clinton back in Washington, the first lady moved
to settle into life as just another candidate running for public
office. She gave the first of what aides said would be five
speeches this week, this one offering measures to spur economic
growth here, including about $550 million worth of tax incentives
and grants to encourage Internet development. She granted three
one-on-one interviews with reporters, a notable break from her more
cloistered ``listening'' tour of the state last year. She visited a
part of New York where Democratic candidates for office always
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But she was also trailed by a presidential-size press corps and
Secret Service brigade that served as a reminder of just how
complicated it is going to be for Clinton to be just another
candidate running for public office. The most routine of political
rituals _ the official airport greeting by local politicians _
turned into a shoulder-to-shoulder commotion as local Democratic
officeholders competed for space with television crews from
Washington and Secret Service agents trying to maintain security as
they waited for Clinton's Air Force jet to emerge from the low
clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton walked into the terminal and climbed onto a marble
ledge, where she declared her affinity for this part of New York.
``I did grow up on the Great Lakes,'' she said, referring to
Chicago. ``I have spent time in western New York. I listened in
western New York.''
</P>
<P>
   In her policy speech, delivered at a job training center here,
Clinton laid out what will be one of the major themes of her
campaign against Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, noting the economic
decline of upstate New York and advocating _ in sometimes dry
fashion _ a package of programs intended to help the nation, in
general, and the region in particular. Her aides said her total
program would cost $550 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, she called for creation of tax-exempt bonds
to be issued by the federal government to finance the creation of
lines for high-speed Internet access. She also endorsed grants to
pay for the creation of broad-band networks in urban and poor rural
areas, again to provide the high-speed Internet access that she
asserted was key to the upstate economic revival.
</P>
<P>
   ``If upstate New York State were an independent state, it would
consistently rank in the bottom-fifth of job growth,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's emphasis on measures to, in effect, transform the
economy here _ from its traditional if now faltering manufacturing
base to one geared to the Internet _ came with a more typical
prescription for the region's problems. Like other candidates for
statewide office, notably Charles Schumer, who was elected to the
Senate in 1998, Clinton said she would support efforts under way in
Washington to deregulate utilities as a way to try to reduce
electric costs.
</P>
<P>
   And like other candidates running for Senate, Clinton complained
that New York taxpayers were sending more money to Washington than
they were getting back. She said the historical justification for
this, that New York was more prosperous than the rest of he nation,
was no longer so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, New York has the largest gap between the rich and the
poor of any state in the United States,'' she said. ``Therefore, it
is time for our friends in the rest of the country to return the
favor, to change the way business is done in Washington, to give
New York its fair share.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the Democrat Clinton and Giuliani
are running to replace, has issued an annual report keeping track
of that disparity. To date, though, no New York senator has had
much luck in changing that formula.
</P>
<P>
   On another hot-button issue, Clinton, in an interview with The
Associated Press, one of the three she did Monday, said she would
all but set a litmus test for how she would vote on judges for
federal courts. ``I can't imagine that I would vote to confirm''
someone who opposes abortion rights, she said
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
