u s BC-SPORTS-TEAMS-TAX-NYT &LR;      02-07 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-TEAMS-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED TAX LAW MAY CUT CLUB'S VALUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Clinton administration wants to curb the high cost of
buying a sports team, it may have found a way.
</P>
<P>
   In its proposed $1.8 trillion budget for the 2001 fiscal year,
which was unveiled Monday, the White House took aim at a 1976 tax
law that lets a buyer assign half the purchase price of a team to
player contracts and then amortize that valuable deduction over
five years.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sweet deal that has made the rich richer. Let's say
you're Robert Wood Johnson IV. You've just bought the Jets for $635
million. Under current Internal Revenue Service law, you can _ with
the requisite proof _ write off $317.5 million from your operating
income over five years. By reducing income, you reduce your taxes.
</P>
<P>
   And if you don't have enough income from the Jets, you can use
the yearly $63.5 million deduction to offset income from your other
businesses. It's good to be a king.
</P>
<P>
   This tax treatment survived a congressional change to the law in
1993 _ which required a few years to enact _ that codified a
hodgepodge of rules governing the amortization of intangible assets
in other businesses at 15 years. In amortization, a business writes
off, as a loss, the cost of buying assets against profits. By
reducing profits, you reduce taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But the IRS kept sports exempt from the 15-year rule,
maintaining an anomaly; it was a tradeoff for letting teams write
off short-term assets like player contracts, but disallowing
amortization of long-term ones like the values of the franchise and
its television contract.
</P>
<P>
   But disputes kept arising. Most notably, Pat Bowlen, the Denver
Broncos' owner, won a case in United States Tax Court two years ago
that allowed him to assign more than 50 percent of the value of the
team to the contracts he acquired in 1984 from the partnership that
formerly owned the team.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the Treasury Department has determined that ``there
exists no apparent justification for treating acquisitions of
franchises to conduct sports enterprises differently than the
acquisitions of other trades or businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   A Treasury Department official said Monday that the White House
had proposed changing the tax law so that ``all intangible assets
for sports franchises would be amortized over 15 years,'' including
such things as the franchise value and television contracts. The
official added, ``We could have raised more money by just extending
amortization of player contracts for 15 years, but we thought this
was fairer.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House's Office of Management and Budget figures that,
if enacted, the regulation would raise $509 million from 2001 to
2006. (The figure would probably rise if team price tags keep
soaring.) Still, half a billion dollars is a pittance in a $1.8
trillion budget. Just enough to build two nice arenas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will raise that much assuming that franchises will change
hands at the same rate they have been,'' said Robert Willens, a
managing director of Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the Clinton administration's desire to change the
taxation of sports teams is a different philosophy from the one
that guided a failed campaign last year to provide a tax break to
help Abe Pollin, a major contributor to the Democratic Party,
refinance his debt at the MCI Center in Washington at a lower cost.
</P>
<P>
   The White House chose a propitious time to seek greater benefits
from team purchases. The Washington Redskins (and FedEx Field) sold
for $805 million last year. The Cleveland Indians went for $320
million last year, and the Los Angeles Dodgers were bought by Fox
for $311 million in. The Yankees were valued at $600 million when
they merged recently with the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   According to Willens, the proposed 15-year amortization for
sports teams will increase the burden of buying a franchise. He
calculated that the present value of the proposed new rule would
have added a present value of $33 million to Johnson's costs and
might have led to a lower bid for the team, if he were subject to
it. But the rule would not be retroactive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would affect the price a buyer is willing to pay for the
team, but not the interest in buying it,'' said Marc Ganis, the
president of Sportscorp, a consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Art Modell, who recently agreed to sell 49 percent of his
Baltimore Ravens, said: ``I think this will have a deterring effect
on people buying.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sam Grossman, who tried to buy the Jets, said it wouldn't
matter to him. ``So they want to change the tax law. So what?'' he
said. ``There are so many intangibles, so many values, I don't
think it will matter.''
</P>
<P>
   As sweet a tax break as the five-year amortization schedule has
been, the IRS wasn't a pushover. The agency dared owners to prove
they were worthy, establishing a sports examiners team to determine
who was overstepping the bounds of appropriate valuation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to defend the value,'' said Steve Matt, the partner
in charge of the sports valuation practice at the Dallas office of
the accounting firm Arthur Andersen. ``The salary you pay a player
is not just the value of the contract, just one component.
Ultimately, it's an evaluation of the market demand of the player
and how much they would be paid on open market.''
</P>
<P>
   As team prices have soared, proving that the value of the
contracts equaled 50 percent of the purchase price has grown grew
more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went face to face with them on the Dolphins,'' Matt said,
``and they sat there with a spreadsheet of all the NFL teams sold
and what their allocations of player contracts were. They looked
for inconsistencies.''
</P>
<P>
   By seeking to eliminate inconsistencies, the IRS hopes to raise
more money. The rich get richer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
