<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9806 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-STUDENT-SHOT-2NDTAKE-     02-07 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-SHOT-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 VALHALLA, N.Y.: them commuters. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite a facade of normalcy _ classes were not canceled and
pedestrians walked the snowy grounds as on any other afternoon _
yellow police tape flapping from trees and squad cars parked here
and there piqued the interest of passers-by. As word of the
shootings spread, in part because of a mass of reporters and
photographers that quickly converged on campus, students gathered
in knots to express their shock and concern.
</P>
<P>
   Yovanny Otalvaro, 20, a sophomore from Ossining, said he heard a
shot near the student center, and when he and other students went
to see where it came from, they found the man lying on the ground
in the fetal position.
</P>
<P>
   Don Gregory, an assistant professor of journalism, said he was
walking out of the student center and saw the commotion moments
after the man shot himself in the head near a stand of evergreens
that is a popular gathering spot for smokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just so happens that there was blood on the snow,'' Gregory
said, who saw about six students standing near the man. ``I thought
he had fallen and hurt his leg. But one held up her hand and said:
`I can't believe he did that. Call 911.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ford said that to avoid disrupting student life, there were no
plans to cancel classes Monday or Tuesday, though counselors would
be made available. Some students were considering taking up the
offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear stories about people spraying bullets at school, but
you never realize you could be a part of it,'' said Regina Benchs,
21, from Putnam Valley. ``You just don't feel safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhea Williams, another student, said: ``I'm trembling. Why don't
they close the school?''
</P>
<P>
   Ford said unarmed guards patrolled each of the 10 or so
buildings on campus. A guard responded to the shooting, Ford said,
but he did not know what action the guard took. The university will
review its security, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Amir Sharif, 19, from Hartsdale, said students at the college
tended to keep themselves. Some, he said, ``carry baggage'' from
rough neighborhoods, but violent disputes are rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, it's Westchester Community College,'' he said,
standing in front of the Academic Arts Building, where the first
floor was closed off but classes were under way on other floors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
