<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-INFERTILITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP WANTS INFERTILITY TREATMENTS INSURED 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Republican leaders of the state Senate said
Monday that they intended to pass a bill on Tuesday that for the
first time would require health insurance companies to pay for some
infertility treatments, edging the Legislature closer to action on
the highly contentious issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats who control the state Assembly passed a similar
bill early last year, only to see it blocked in the Senate amid
fierce opposition by some of the Capitol's most influential
lobbying groups, including chambers of commerce around the state
and the insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   The move in the Senate is somewhat unexpected, because the
Republican majority leader in that house, Joseph L. Bruno, has
expressed serious reservations about mandating insurance coverage
for costly treatments like in vitro fertilization and artificial
insemination.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republicans' turnaround can at least partly be
attributed to election-year politics.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, Republican leaders, including Gov. George E.
Pataki, promised Orthodox Jewish leaders that they would give
serious consideration to such a bill as they sought their support
for a Republican candidate in a highly contested state Senate race
in Rockland County.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Orthodox Jewish leaders in the county threw
their support behind the Republican candidate, Thomas P. Morahan.
Morahan, who won, is up for re-election this year, along with every
other member of the Legislature, and he will need the help of the
Orthodox community once again. Both the Democrats in the Assembly
and the Republicans in the Senate are eager to protect their
majorities in the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   The issue represents the latest front in a long-running battle
that has pit consumer advocates, who want the coverage of certain
treatments and services mandated, against insurers and employers,
who complain that such requirements raise health care costs and
therefore premiums.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Pataki and the Legislature have enacted laws
requiring insurers to pay for procedures and services that they had
refused to cover _ from chiropractic care and diabetes treatment to
reconstructive surgery for women who have undergone mastectomies.
</P>
<P>
   Although a few health insurers in New York already pay for some
infertility treatment, the industry as a whole objects to
legislation that would force the companies to do so. If the measure
is enacted, New York will become the 14th state _ including
California, Texas, Connecticut and Massachusetts _ to require
insurers to pay for infertility treatments, according to the
National Conference of State Legislatures, which monitors state
policies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Leslie Moran, the spokeswoman for the Health Plan Association, a
trade group representing the state's health maintenance
organizations, said the bill would drive up health care costs _
ultimately increasing premiums and leading large corporations to
drop commercial coverage in favor of self-insurance plans. That,
she noted, would increase rates even more for smaller businesses
that cannot afford self-insurance. ``There's no free lunch,'' Moran
said. ``Higher benefits equal higher premiums.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill proposed by the Senate, health insurance
companies and health maintenance organizations would be required to
pay for the diagnosis and treatment of infertility. The treatments
covered under the bill include hormone drug therapy, artificial
insemination, in vitro fertilization and gamete and embryo
donation.
</P>
<P>
   But the fate of the Senate proposal is unclear, largely because
it differs from the version that the Assembly passed last year, and
intends to pass again, in several important ways. A key difference
is that the Senate bill does not apply to employees of the Roman
Catholic Church or any other organization with religious objections
to infertility treatments. By contrast, some Orthodox Jewish groups
welcome the procedures and have lobbied Albany to require insurance
companies to pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   Another difference is that the Senate bill would limit to
$60,000 the amount that insurers would be required to pay to cover
infertility procedures. In addition, the Senate bill applies only
to people between the ages of 25 and 44, while the Assembly bill
has no age restrictions. The Senate bill also says that insurance
coverage must be provided for infertility treatment only if there
is a ``reasonable expectation that treatment will result in a
healthy child.'' The Assembly bill has no such language.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between the two bills could lead to
confrontations between the two houses. Sheldon Silver, a Democrat
who is the speaker of the Assembly, objected to the Senate plan,
saying that it had loopholes. He said the Assembly would pass its
own bill again Tuesday, and urged the Senate to pass the same bill.
``It's time for the Senate to come on board and provide that
coverage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate proposal also received a cool response from groups
that have supported mandating insurance coverage for infertility
treatments. Lisa Angerame, the public policy director for the
American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists, said the
organization welcomed the Senate's interest in the issue. But she
added that the bill did not go far enough toward ensuring that
people who need coverage would get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is problematic and needs fine-tuning,'' Angerame said.
``But we wholeheartedly embrace the concept of insurance coverage
for infertility treatments. We hope this will be a springboard for
further fruitful discussions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
