<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER SEATTLE, TRADE GROUP SCALES BACK ITS AGENDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The World Trade Organization, seeking to move beyond
its highly publicized failure in Seattle to start a new round of
global trade negotiations, has agreed instead to begin negotiations
limited to opening markets in agriculture and services.
</P>
<P>
   In the two months since the collapse of the Seattle meeting, the
organization's 135 member countries have been groping for ways to
resurrect the effort to convene negotiations aimed at dismantling
barriers to global commerce. But the members had been unable to
agree on a broad agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to these realities, at least for now, the trade
organization formally set out a blueprint for how to proceed with a
narrower agenda Monday that would attempt to revamp trade rules for
farm goods and services. Countries agreed during the 1993-94 trade
negotiations in Uruguay that efforts to widen trade in at least
these two areas would begin this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WTO is back in business,'' said Mike Moore, the
organization's director general, expressing relief that it had
broken an impasse. Members had been meeting steadily since early
January to lay the groundwork for the meeting Monday, the first
formal session of the organization's governing body, called the
General Council. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Delegates have set a framework for negotiations, which will be
handled within existing WTO committees. This means negotiations on
trade in farm goods will likely start in late March, and services,
which include insurance and banking, in late February. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Figures compiled by the trade organization show that agriculture
and services account for 65 percent of global output and 80 percent
of the world's jobs. Agriculture alone employs half the world's
work force, according to recent World Bank statistics. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, no deadlines were set to conclude the talks, which
means they could drag on for months or even years. Agriculture, in
particular, is a difficult issue because countries like France and
Japan are firmly opposed to the Australian and U.S. view that farm
goods should receive no special treatment that protects domestic
producers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also still under negotiation is a request by developing nations
for extensions of deadlines to honor agreements made in the Uruguay
round of talks, particularly in the area of intellectual property
rights. This request has become a major source of contention
between industrialized and developing countries, and contributed to
the collapse of the Seattle meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Developing countries are seeking solutions to help meet their
obligations to respect intellectual property rights and upgrade
customs valuations methods and investment policies.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the biggest trading powers indicated willingness to
extend the Dec. 31, 1999, deadline on an individual country basis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2252EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0509 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9812 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-SEDONA-AZR &LR;      02-07 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEDONA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIKERS FACE NEW FEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY MARK SHAFFER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(SEDONA, Ariz.) _ If you plan on hitting the trails along the
famous red rocks, best bring some cash along with the hiking shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Come May, Coconino National Forest officials say, treks up such
scenic trails as Bell Rock, West Fork and Vultee Arch will likely
cost $5 for each carload for a day pass or $20 for a yearlong pass.
</P>
<P>
   It's the latest installment of the federal government's
Recreation Fee Demonstration Program, started four years ago to
give the local forest officials the ability to raise more money for
wildlife and watershed protection and for tourist services.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the fees are a long time in coming. The Sedona
area attracts more than 4 million people a year, almost as many as
Grand Canyon National Park. And although visitation to the area has
increased about 250 percent over the past 20 years, the forest's
recreation budget has dropped - by nearly a third in the past
decade alone, Forest Service officials said.
</P>
<P>
   About 95 cents of every dollar from the new fees will stay in
the Beaver Creek-Sedona Ranger District of the Coconino forest, an
agency spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Sedona Mayor Alan Everett, who backs the fees plan, ``The
fees they have mentioned aren't bad for what you get. The state
parks around here like Tuzigoot (ruins), Red Rock State Park and
Slide Rock all charge and I haven't heard anyone complaining about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett, however, said he is concerned that Arizona may end up
like California, where administrative costs eat up about a third of
the money taken in.
</P>
<P>
   Federal public lands officials first embraced the pay-as-you-go
concept in late 1996 when a $4 fee was charged to vehicles entering
Saguaro and Canyon lakes east of Phoenix. Soon, the other four
lakes in the Phoenix area had the same fee for entry, as did the
two most popular trails in the Superstition Mountains, Peralta and
First Water _ other outdoor destinations followed.
</P>
<P>
   Raquel Poturalski, a Coconino National Forest spokeswoman, said
the fees will apply to 160,000 acres extending from near the
Village of Oak Creek in the south to the scenic area of Oak Creek
Canyon on U.S. 89A to the north.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the annual and daily fees can be applied to enter
Crescent Moon Ranch near Red Rock Crossing and archaeological sites
on the Coconino forest which already require an entrance fee.
</P>
<P>
   Poturalski acknowledged that at the second of two public
meetings late last month, a number of the 125 people in attendance
spoke out against the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Sedona Councilwoman Sheri Graham isn't surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is bureaucracy at its best, charging for access to public
lands which we are already being taxed to maintain,'' she said.
``The Forest Service just looks at this like its their own private
property to do what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   But her colleague, Councilman George Tice, can see both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to see fees on the use of forest land but at least they
can use the money locally and may be able to hire some more
people,'' Tice said. ``But they need to be careful about this. If
you push tourists too much they may decide to stay at home.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Mark.Shaffer(at)Arizona Republic.com or (602)
444-8057. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2257EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
