<HEADER>
A9958 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG     02-07 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING STRONG FINISH _ DUCKS MIDSEASON REPORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Anaheim Mighty Ducks have reached a
critical point in the National Hockey League season, but they are
hardly in ideal position. As the All-Star break ends, the Ducks sit
10th in the Western Conference, three points out of a playoff
berth.
</P>
<P>
   Despite playing some wildly inconsistent hockey in the first
2months of the season, Anaheim looked good the day after Christmas.
They were four games over .500 (18-14-4-1), sixth in the conference
and optimistic they could climb higher.
</P>
<P>
   But then center Steve Rucchin went down with a staph infection
in his left ankle. When he returned 11 games later, the Ducks were
two games under .500 (20-22-6-1) and out of a playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   They still are. The team suffered through a 3-11-2 stretch Dec.
22 to Jan. 26, including an embarrassing loss to the lowly New York
Islanders at The Pond.
</P>
<P>
   They remain in the playoff hunt, however, because of the
brilliant play of team captain Paul Kariya, Teemu Selanne, Oleg
Tverdovsky and Guy Hebert on a make-or-break East Coast road trip
last week. The 2-0-2 trip was just what the Ducks needed as they
prepare for the last 28 games of the season. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
OFFENSE &QL; 
Scoring is up ever so slightly this year in the NHL, but the Ducks'
offense has stood still despite improved five-on-five production.
Anaheim is averaging only 2.52 goals per game, compared to 2.6 last
season. But there have been positive signs in the last few weeks.
Paul Kariya (30 goals, 58 points, plus-20 rating) has taken his
game to a new level (15 goals, 24 points in the last 17 games), and
Teemu Selanne (23-2750) has broken out of a season-long funk.
</P>
<P>
   The Finnish winger has seven goals and 13 points in the last
seven games after scoring only two goals and four points in the
previous 14. Three of his goals have come on the power play _ he
had only two in his first 47 games.
</P>
<P>
   Oleg Tverdovsky, who went 35 games without a goal, also is hot.
The defenseman has put together a career-high seven-game
point-scoring streak (2-1113). Steve Rucchin, so vital in the
defensive end and on faceoffs, has six points (2-46) in five games
since returning.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya and Selanne are the obvious keys (scoring 51 of the
team's 136 goals), but the Ducks will need some timely
contributions from the likes of Marty McInnis, Matt Cullen, Fredrik
Olausson, Rucchin and Tverdovsky to keep defenses honest. &QL; 
C-  &QL; 
DEFENSE &QL; 
Heading into the Dec. 22 game versus Phoenix, the Ducks were
nearing the top of the NHL defensive class, allowing only 2.15
goals a game. But they were embarrassed by the Coyotes 8-2, the
start of a 16-game stretch that saw them allow 3.55 goals a game.
After giving up four or more goals only four times in the first 34
games, the Ducks gave up four or more 10 times in that 16-game
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   But the Ducks are fourth in the Western Conference in goals
allowed (2.59), 10th in the NHL and have improved depth on the blue
line thanks to the additions of Tverdovsky and Niclas Havelid, the
emergence of Pavel Trnka (plus-15 rating) and the recent call-up of
hard-hitting, 19-year-old Vitaly Vishnevski.
</P>
<P>
   Havelid, who was becoming an mainstay, is sidelined with a
broken finger, but veteran Kevin Haller, bothered by knee injuries
earlier in the season, has picked up his game considerably. So has
Ruslan Salei, who has struggled with a turf-toe-type injury all
year. On the recent road trip, Anaheim allowed only eight goals in
four games. &QL; 
C+  &QL; 
GOALTENDING &QL; 
Hebert was a legitimate all-star candidate for the North American
team the first 34 games. He was among the NHL leaders in wins,
goals against average, save percentage and shutouts. But Hebert
suffered a strained neck versus Phoenix and, like the rest of the
team, went into a slump, giving up soft goals when the Ducks could
least afford them and not coming up with big saves when they were
needed most. Coach Craig Hartsburg challenged Hebert and Dominic
Russell to pick up their games, and Hebert has responded. Instead
of sulking, he was brilliant on the East Coast swing, especially in
ties against Buffalo and Philadelphia. He seems primed for another
late-season run. &QL; 
B  &QL; 
SPECIAL TEAMS &QL; 
The Ducks would be sitting in a much more comfortable position if
their special teams, especially the power play, hadn't needed
nearly 50 games to get on track.
</P>
<P>
   The power-play and penalty-killing units have been ranked near
the bottom of the league all season. But after going 5 for 82 in
the first 23 road games, the Ducks' power play is 7 for 20 in the
last four road outings. Moving Kariya to the point kick-started the
power play last season. This year, the key might turn out to be the
move of Kariya to the half boards.
</P>
<P>
   The 24th-ranked penalty-killing unit has been either very good
or very bad. Ten times the Ducks have allowed two or more
power-play goals in a game, but recently they have been very good,
killing off 18 of the last 19 penalties. &QL; 
D &QL; 
COACHING &QL; 
Hartsburg has taken a lot of flak for supposedly stifling Kariya
and Selanne with a defense-first system. Nobody complained when the
Ducks were four games over .500. Hartsburg has done a admirable of
maintaining his cool and keeping his team together during the long
slump. Now is the time to show he can keep the team rolling. &QL; 
C &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0513 </DOCNO>
