<SLUG> BC-BKC-SETONHALL-SYRACUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETON HALL HALTS SYRACUSE'S STREAK  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ Surviving a desperate run and the deafening
roar of the Carrier Dome crowd, unranked Seton Hall handed
Syracuse, the nation's last unbeaten team, a 69-67 loss Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   In snapping Syracuse's winning streak at 19 games, the Pirates
left the Orangemen tied with Connecticut for the longest streak to
start the season in Big East Conference history. In an unlikely
twist, it was the third straight time that Seton Hall (16-4, 8-2 in
the Big East) triumphed at the Carrier Dome after losing all 16
games here before that.
</P>
<P>
   The fans were spread out throughout the spacious arena, but as
Seton Hall's Shaheen Holloway rose in the corner for a 3-point
attempt with 11 minutes 46 seconds to play, the sound reached high
school pitch, as if walls surrounded the court. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The screams came with good reason as fourth-ranked Syracuse,
19-0 entering the game and 9-0 in the conference, had just taken
its first lead since the opening basket of the game. Now the
screams were as much of desperation as exuberance, and they grew
louder as Holloway calmly ignored the sound and serenely dropped in
the shot to give Seton Hall the lead back. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To win Monday night, it took the calm that Holloway displayed in
the corner, as well as the fire he showed in the final minutes,
when he nearly came to blows with Syracuse's Jason Hart. But it
took more than just Holloway's play.
</P>
<P>
   While the Pirates' lead went from 35-24 with 1:33 left in the
first half down to 35-32 in the opening minutes of the second half,
Seton Hall went 4:43 without a point. But with 16:50 left in the
game, Darius Lane calmly unleashed a 3-pointer that slipped through
the net. Then, on the next trip, Holloway buried a shot from beyond
the arc. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In all, Seton Hall made 12 3-point field goals. After Syracuse
battled back, taking the lead, 67-66, with 1:07 to play, Lane
drained his sixth 3-pointer of the game, giving Seton Hall the lead
for good with just 40 seconds remaining. Seton Hall then survived
five shots by the Orangemen to hold on for the victory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Seton Hall leading by 60-55, Al Harris was holding the ball
in the lane, pumping and trying to think of some sort of way out of
the jam he found himself in. With two defenders between him and the
basket and Hart clawing at the ball from behind, Harris, a freshman
averaging just 1.9 points a game, lost the ball. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Harris came up with an unlikely play, picking the ball back
up and hoisting a hook shot over the Syracuse defenders that
rattled around the rim and dropped through. Then, the next time
upcourt, Harris drove the lane and his shot was blocked, but a
goaltending call gave him the basket and Seton Hall a 9-point
lead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, the outcome went down to the buzzer as Syracuse freshman
DeShaun Williams scored 5 straight points to cut the lead to 64-63.
Lane, who provided the game-winner, also provided a scare by
missing the front end of two free throw opportunities, the second
one coming with 16.8 seconds to play. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2315EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
