<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAHOO-HACKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YAHOO BLAMES A HACKER ATTACK FOR A LENGTHY SERVICE FAILURE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Yahoo Inc. blamed a ``planned attack'' by
computer hackers for a service failure that lasted nearly three
hours Monday, in a rare interruption of one of the most popular and
best performing sites on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   The company said one or more hackers flooded a network with a
steady stream of data, causing the network to become clogged.
</P>
<P>
   The assault, which is known in the industry as a distributed
denial of service attack, directed a flood of data from at least 50
computers, making it impossible for the company to exchange
information with its regular customers.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak, said Jeff Mallett, Yahoo's president and chief
operating officer, the attack directed one gigabyte of traffic a
second at Yahoo _ the amount of traffic some sites get in an entire
year. ``It clogged our routers, to say the least,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that the attackers did not break into the Yahoo
network, and did not gain access to any internal files or data.
</P>
<P>
   He said Yahoo did not yet know who perpetrated the attack but
was ``starting to get clues.''
</P>
<P>
   It is usually difficult to trace this type of attack because the
instigators normally use dozens of computers they have hijacked.
</P>
<P>
   Elias Levy, chief technology officer for SecurityFocus.com,
which researches computer security issues, called the attack
remarkable because of how heavily reinforced the Yahoo site is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Yahoo was taken down means nobody is really
safe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo's Web site was down starting about 10:20 a.m. Pacific
Standard Time and was out ``intermittently'' for 2 hours and 45
minutes, said the company, which is based in Santa Clara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   This is the broadest attack ever on the Yahoo network, a company
spokeswoman said. The site is usually among the Internet's best
performers; its main page, yahoo.com, is accessible 99.3 percent of
the time, according to Keynote Systems, which monitors Web site
reliability and performance.
</P>
<P>
   The failure caused a great deal of inconvenience to Yahoo's
millions of users, but analysts said the revenue impact would be
insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the disturbance did not seem to affect the company's
stock. Yahoo shares closed at $354, up 50 cents, in Nasdaq trading
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Yahoo said it was serving up to 465 million Web
pages each day, meaning it may have lost as many as 100 million
page views during the failure, said Jordan E. Rohan of the Wit
Capital Group in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But he and other analysts said the cost to Yahoo in lost
advertising and e-commerce revenue would be slight, perhaps in the
range of $500,000. ``That's really a rounding error for the
company,'' Rohan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0515 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9963 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     02-07 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE GOALIE NEEDS TO WIN THIS RACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There are two candidates of decidedly different
personalities vying for their party's nod. Their stumping will take
them on the road later this month, to Chicago and Buffalo and on
into Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Goaltenders Stephane Fiset and Jamie Storr are the John McCain
and George W. Bush of the Los Angeles Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset is emotional, with frayed rope for nerve endings. He is a
brooder. Storr is hard to read. His self-possession can come across
as ambivalence.
</P>
<P>
   With the stretch half of the NHL regular season having now
officially arrived, it's time for either Fiset or Storr to step to
the fore. Platoon? It's not per chance that it rhymes with swoon.
</P>
<P>
   It says here the Kings have to have a clear-cut No.1 to rally
behind (or in front of, as it were) if they are to rise above
Western Conference foes such as Edmonton, San Jose and Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   There's much at stake in the last 31 games, starting with
tonight's Super Tuesday showdown against the Mighty Ducks at the
Staples Center. Home ice in the playoffs is there for the taking
but only if one of their goaltenders asserts himself the same way
Guy Hebert did with the Ducks three years ago, or Olaf Kolzig did
with the Washington Capitals in 1998, or former King Byron Dafoe
did with Boston last year.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, we don't blame the Kings' brass for inquiring as to the
availability of a third candidate, in this case the league's
reigning, two-time MVP, Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset and Storr, while marvelous in stretches, have suffered
enough setbacks to make one question their staying, starring power.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings employ Don Edwards as a goaltending consultant, but
maybe what Fiset and Storr really need is Naomi Wolf. The author
and informal advisor to the Clinton White House could help the
goaltenders become alpha males.
</P>
<P>
   For the 29-year-old Fiset, it all comes down to reveling in the
competition that Storr provides rather than resisting it. He is an
incredibly hard worker who is incredibly hard on himself. Some of
the worst shots he absorbs are self-inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' Edwards said, ``you almost have to tell Stephane
to take a deep breath and relax.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to see the ice like Paul Kariya to notice that
the Kings skaters seem to summon more energy in front of Fiset.
Without question, his teammates respect his work ethic and
appreciate how much he cares.
</P>
<P>
   Like Republican presidential hopeful Bush, Storr's future has
long been preordained, since the Kings selected him with the
seventh overall pick in the 1994 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Again, like Bush, it's not always clear how consumed Storr is by
ambition. He doesn't match Fiset's practice intensity and he can be
quiet to the point of inscrutability.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Jamie,'' Edwards said, ``you maybe have to get in his
face a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Storr should have spoken up in December, when he was
sent out against the New Jersey Devils and New York Rangers just
days after hitting his head on the crossbar in a collision with
Montreal's Martin Rucinsky. Storr was experiencing headaches,
dizziness and a stiff neck and thought his symptoms were, as he
recalled last week, ``very noticeable.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctors kept clearing him to play, though, and so he did.
The Kings lost his next two starts by a combined score of 15-4,
after which Storr was placed on the injured list with
post-concussion syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Storr; he tried to tough it out for the benefit of his
teammates and ended up taking it on the chin. He'll be the first to
tell you, this alpha-male stuff is tough.
</P>
<P>
   Storr is 24, which the Kings will tell you is young. However, he
is older than Buffalo's Martin Biron (22), the league leader in
shutouts, and Philadelphia's Brian Boucher (22), owner of the
league's second best goals-against average (2.02).
</P>
<P>
   His time isn't tomorrow. It has arrived, slipping in quietly
behind injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Storr has sat out a total of 11 games with post-concussion
syndrome and a right groin strain.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset missed 14 games in November with a right-hand contusion.
They're both healthy now, ``for the first time since the fourth
game of the season,'' first-year coach Andy Murray hastened to add.
</P>
<P>
   All that means is the Kings finally are free to find out whether
their netminding problems of December and January were purely
physical or somewhat psychological. With another expansion draft on
the horizon, they really need to know: Do Fiset and/or Storr have
the mindset to carry the Kings to the next level?
</P>
<P>
   The Kings must have some doubts or they wouldn't be calling
Buffalo about Hasek, who missed the first three months of what was
supposed to be his final season. The problem was a torn groin.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek is the league's headmost goaltender. He's also a bit of a
head case and 35 years old, with one foot back in the Czech
Republic (the way he's straddling continents, no wonder he keeps
straining his groin).
</P>
<P>
   Even if Hasek doesn't follow through on his announced intentions
to retire after this season so he and his wife can raise their
children in their homeland, we'd pursue Phoenix holdout Nikolai
Khabibulin before dealing for Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   Khabibulin is 27 and playing in Long Beach after appearing in 63
games for the Coyotes last year and posting the sixth-best
goals-against average in the league (2.13).
</P>
<P>
   The best-case scenario has Storr playing the rest of the way as
he did in November and Fiset's confidence not getting dislodged,
and in their spirited skirmish a greater battle being won.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
