<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9964 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-NY-1STLD-WRITETH     02-07 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RESTED GORE GOES AFTER HARD-HAT AND HIGH-HAT VOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: SUBS second-to-last graf, Gore took ..., to update with Gore
having narrated concert.) 
 (nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a two-day respite from the campaign trail, Vice
President Al Gore stepped up his New York campaign in earnest
Monday, paying homage to the labor unions he is counting on to
mobilize for him in the March 7 primary and spending the evening
courting arts patrons at Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   And in recognition of Bill Bradley's popularity here from his
days as a star basketball player and a senator from New Jersey,
Gore opened a new attack against his rival for the Democratic
nomination, saying Bradley's proposals, particularly on health
care, education and the budget surplus, would be bad for New York.
</P>
<P>
   New York is seen as Bradley's best hope for a breakthrough after
his losses to the vice president in Iowa and New Hampshire, and
Gore made it clear Monday that he was not going to give Bradley an
inch of breathing room here. His line of attack was tailor-made for
hard-core Democrats in New York, playing on party loyalty and the
economic success of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to describe to you one of the big differences between
myself and my opponent in the Democratic primary,'' Gore told about
1,000 people in Lower Manhattan at the headquarters of District
Council 37 of the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that you can run for the Democratic nomination
by running down the progress and achievements of the Democratic
Party over the past seven years,'' he said, ``because in fact our
policies have been good for this country.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Asked later if he would campaign in New York with President
Clinton, Gore said, ``I've got to win this race on my own, and I'm
campaigning on my own vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would campaign with Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is
running for Senate in New York, Gore said: ``It's a matter of
scheduling, not just me, but also her. I hope so. But that's yet to
be worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While Gore was courting New York Democrats, Bradley appeared in
Tampa, Fla., and took aim at the Republican governor, Jeb Bush, who
signed an executive order last year, ending affirmation action in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has long been a staunch defender of affirmative action,
as has been his opponent, Vice President Al Gore. But by choosing
to attack Bush, the brother of the Republican presidential
candidate, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, Bradley delivered notice
that he was prepared to take on any elected official or
presidential candidate or relative of a presidential candidate, in
his uphill fight for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that he has demonstrated a lack of vision and
leadership by repealing affirmative action in the state of
Florida,'' said Bradley about JEb Bush at a raucously supportive
town hall meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's brief appearance in Florida, whose primary is March
14, was his second in two days focusing on race relations. On
Sunday, he visited a church with a large black congregation in the
New York City borough of Queens, and on Tuesday, he will appear in
South Carolina, which has no Democratic primary, to criticize the
Confederate flag's presence over the State Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   In his appearance Monday before the labor group, Gore assailed
Bradley for having retired from the Senate in 1996 instead of
fighting against what Gore called the Gingrich Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he retired from the Senate during President Clinton's
first term, Sen. Bradley spoke about what he called a budget
stalemate and a process that was, in his words, paralyzed, a
continual deadlock,'' Gore said. ``And so he decided to leave. But
he was wrong. We broke that deadlock.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``If Sen. Bradley could not foresee the progress that
we made when we decided to stay and fight against the Gingrich
Republicans, what else does he not see now? How can he be counted
on to see what is right for working families today?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's remarks seemed to turn the tables on Bradley, who
recently has been accusing Gore of waging a campaign of distortions
and falsehoods.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore cannot tell the truth as a candidate, Bradley has been
asking audiences, how can the nation expect him to tell the truth
as president? And now Gore is asking about Bradley: If he did not
fight the good fight a few years ago, how can the nation expect him
to fight as president?
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Gore also said that Bradley's health-care proposal would
``eliminate Medicaid for more than 3 million New Yorkers who depend
on it, people with disabilities, people with AIDS, the elderly, in
nursing homes,'' substituting vouchers or subsidies of $150 a
month. ``See if you can find a health-care plan in New York for
$150 a month that pays your prescription drug benefits as Medicaid
does, that pays the kind of benefits that Medicaid pays,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Union members account for 30 percent to 40 percent of the
Democratic primary vote in New York, much higher than they figured
in Iowa and New Hampshire, and they drew most of Gore's attention
Monday. He began with an appearance via satellite at the United
Food and Commercial Workers meeting in Naples, Fla., then met at
his hotel with about 65 labor leaders from across New York state.
</P>
<P>
   He later went to a construction site on Manhattan's West Side,
at 63rd Street and West End Avenue. As he walked through the muddy
site in his heavy topcoat, business suit and cowboy boots, he shook
hands with carpenters and masons.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   To help Gore, the state AFL-CIO distributed 1 million pieces of
Gore literature Monday at 10,000 work sites across the state. The
fliers exclaim, ``No presidential candidate has ever been more
supportive of working families than Al Gore!''
</P>
<P>
   Denis M. Hughes, president of the New York State AFL-CIO, said,
``I don't know of any organized support for Bradley in the
trade-union movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore took about an hour and a half out of his labor
supplications to rehearse at Avery Fisher Hall for his nighttime
performance, in which he narrated Aaron Copland's 1942 classic,
``Lincoln Portrait,'' accompanied by the American Symphony
Orchestra, under the direction of Leon Botstein.
</P>
<P>
   The concert was a benefit for seven charities in New York. Tapes
of it are to benefit the Phillips Brooks House, a student-run
public-service organization at Harvard, Gore's alma mater.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
