<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SCOTT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACK SCOTT, A PROMINENT CRITIC OF SPORT'S EXCESSES, DIES AT 57
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICHARD GOLDSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jack Scott, a prominent critic of organized athletics during the
1960s and early '70s who later gained national attention when he
was suspected of helping Patricia Hearst elude capture in the
Symbionese Liberation Army case, died Sunday night in Eugene, Ore.
He was 57.
</P>
<P>
   He had throat cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Scott was the captain of his city championship high school
football team in Scranton, Pa., in the late 1950s and a sprinter at
Stanford University. But he became disenchanted with the sports
world, voicing his views in books, as an athletic administrator and
through a sports institute. He spoke out against authoritarian
coaches, excessive commercialization in sports and the use of
performance-enhancing drugs, and he called for greater inclusion of
women and members of minorities in sports programs and for giving
both college and professional athletes a voice in team management.
</P>
<P>
   Sports, he said, should be a joyful experience oriented to
participants rather than spectators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty is in the classic struggle of man against man, man
against nature and man against himself,'' he said. ``If you don't
struggle well, you should feel badly. But you shouldn't feel badly
just because you lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott, who graduated from Syracuse University in 1966 and held a
doctorate in sociology from the University of California, took aim
at authoritarian coaches in his first book, the privately published
``Athletics for Athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lombardi and other over-authoritarian coaches have proved that
heavy discipline can produce winners,'' he once said. ``But it is
also possible to learn and develop in a more free and creative
atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, Scott launched his Institute for the Study of Sport and
Society, which he ran out of an office above his apartment in
Oakland, Calif., its newsletter giving a voice to disaffected
athletes and coaches. He served as an adviser to Dave Meggyesy, the
pro football player who was critical of the game in ``Out of Their
League.''
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``The Athletic Revolution'' (The Free Press, 1971),
Scott wrote that intercollegiate athletics are essentially
worthwhile but need to be put under the same controls and
guidelines as university academic departments.
</P>
<P>
   After expressing criticism of Bear Bryant, the Alabama football
coach, Scott drew enmity from Vice President Spiro T. Agnew, who in
a speech before the Birmingham Touchdown Club in 1972 called Scott
an enemy of sport, a ``permacritic'' and a ``guru from Berkeley.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott put his views into action when he served as athletic
director at Oberlin College in Ohio from 1972 to 1974. He appointed
three black coaches, including Tommie Smith, the sprinter who
gained notoriety for his raised, gloved fist on the victory stand
at the 1968 Mexico City Olympics, and he provided an enhanced role
for women in Oberlin athletics.
</P>
<P>
   While at Oberlin, Scott became fascinated with the persona of
Bill Walton, the UCLA basketball star, an outstanding athlete who
also had social and political concerns, having demonstrated against
the Vietnam War. When Walton was breaking into the National
Basketball Association with the Portland Trail Blazers, he lived
with Scott and Scott served as his business adviser.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1975, Scott was in the public eye on a far larger
stage.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst, the granddaughter of the publisher William Randolph
Hearst, had been kidnapped by the revolutionary Symbionese
Liberation Army in February 1974, when she was a 19-year-old
college student. She later joined her captors in various crimes,
and in the summer of 1975 was the object of a nationwide search. A
federal grand jury in Harrisburg, Pa., was seeking to determine
whether Scott had a role in harboring Hearst, but he declined to
testify, alleging governmental misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst was arrested in San Francisco in September 1975 and was
convicted of armed bank robbery in March 1976. At her trial, she
testified that she met Scott at an apartment in Berkeley or Oakland
after a gunfight with the police in Los Angeles in May 1974 had
killed six SLA members. Hearst said Scott and several other family
members drove her east in the summer of 1974. She said that Scott
and she then drove alone to Las Vegas, where he left her.
</P>
<P>
   Scott later admitted to having sheltered Hearst, but no criminal
charges were filed. In 1984, Scott received $30,000 in settlement
of a libel suit against Hearst in which he contended that in her
book ``Every Secret Thing'' she falsely linked him to terrorist
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Scott's death came while his videotaped testimony was being
sought by defense lawyers for Sara Jane Olson, who is to go on
trial in Los Angeles on charges that she planted pipe bombs under
two police cars in that city in 1975 in retaliation for the deaths
of the SLA members in the 1974 shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Scott later worked with world-class track athletes as a
physiotherapist, specializing in the use of electric stimulation to
heal injuries. He helped Joan Benoit Samuelson recover from
injuries and win the first Olympic women's marathon in 1984 and
treated the track stars Carl Lewis and Jackie Joyner-Kersee.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Micki; his son, Jonah; and his
daughters, Lydia and Emma.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2318EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
