<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0518 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9968 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RUN-KENYANS-2TAKES-NY     02-07 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-KENYANS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENYANS MAY MISS RICH SUMMER TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PAUL GAINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kenya's famed distance runners will not be able to participate
in the International Amateur Athletic Federation's prestigious
Golden League series this summer unless agents and the IAAF can
persuade Kenyan authorities to reverse their decision.
</P>
<P>
   The country's national Olympic committee president, Kipchoge
Keino, blames his country's poor showing at the 1999 world
championships in Seville, Spain, on burnout after the athletes ran
in meets all over Europe for large cash prizes. At the world
championships, the usually dominant Kenyans won six medals to five
each for the Moroccans and the Ethiopians. Now Keino wants the team
to prepare for this year's Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia, by
training for six weeks at a high-altitude camp, instead of
competing in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting on Feb. 19 in Nairobi, Kenya, will bring together
about a dozen athlete representatives, the Kenyan Amateur Athletic
Association and the IAAF competitions director, Sandro Giovannelli,
who will try to avoid a conflict that could seriously damage the
IAAF program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it's a serious matter, but we have to discuss and find a
solution between us,'' Giovannelli said. ``It is difficult to say
if we will succeed. In the end the athletes must respect the wishes
of the federation and the national Olympic committee, and of course
if the federation says, `No you are not allowed to run the Golden
League meets,' then they don't run the Golden League meets. They
need the agreement of the federation. They are not free to do
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Olympic track and field program scheduled for Sept. 22
to Oct. 1, the IAAF Golden League meets in Europe have been pushed
back into August and September. Those meets have become the
showcase for world class track and field and offer a $1 million
jackpot to be shared by athletes who win their events at all Golden
League meets.
</P>
<P>
   If the Olympic training camp takes place in Kenya, some of the
best athletes will not compete in meets in Zurich, Switzerland;
Monaco; Cologne and Berlin in Germany, and Brussels, Belgium, nor
in many of the IAAF Grand Prix meets.
</P>
<P>
   Keino said: ``You blame Kenyans when they are not performing
well, but on the other hand they are the best athletes. So when the
team is selected they should train themselves up for the Games.
Which is more important? The Golden League or the Olympics?
Somebody has to make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The athletes and their representatives stand to lose hundreds of
thousands of dollars if Keino and the Kenyan amateur association
cannot be swayed from their position. Kenya is no longer the
world's dominant distance-running nation, and the Kenyan
authorities are in a bitter mood.
</P>
<P>
   Just recently, Isaiah Kiplagat, president of the Kenyan
association, lashed out at one of the country's leading coaches,
accusing him of allowing foreign news media into the country to
illegally film Kenyan runners. The coach, an Irish missionary named
Brother Colm O'Connell, has developed most of the Kenyan runners at
St. Patrick's Boys' School in Iten. Kiplagat's public outburst has
disturbed many of O'Connell's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Athlete representatives have also come under fire. They are
blamed for everything from racing the athletes too much to luring
young athletes to Europe. Their reception in Nairobi is expected to
be cool. Some of the agents, meanwhile, are tired of the posturing
by Kenyan authorities, whom they perceive as trying to gain control
of the athletes and their money.
</P>
<P>
   Gianni De Madonna, an Italian agent who represents a number of
top Kenyans, said: ``I am very happy for Keino's decision, because
finally we can demonstrate if the Kenyans train at home for the
Olympic Games, nothing will change. They will see the number of
medals will not increase, it will stay the same. The situation in
distance running has changed with the Ethiopians and the Moroccans
and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In an Olympic year, athletes usually choose their racing
programs more carefully, and they earn less prize and appearance
money. And, unlike the world championships where a gold medal is
rewarded with a $60,000 bonus, there are no bonuses for Olympic
medals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand their concern because some of those people
got burned out before they went to the world championships last
year,'' said Jos Hermens, manager of the Ethiopian superstar Haile
Gebrselassie and many Kenyans. ``But the athletes must also make
some money. I mean, what are the federations going to pay them back
for, not running? So there has to be a balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, two of Hermens' athletes, the Kenyan steeplechaser
Bernard Barmasai and Gabriela Szabo of Romania, won the overall
men's and women's Grand Prix events, earning $200,000 each. In
addition, Szabo won $500,000 for winning the 3,000-meter run in all
her Golden League meets. Hermens earned a 10 percent commission on
that prize money.
</P>
<P>
   Szabo has already decided to concentrate on the Olympics at the
expense of the Golden League.
</P>
<P>
   Hermens also represents about 20 Ethiopian runners, and he has
already had a confrontation with their federation. In December he
met with Ethiopian federation officials who told him that they
intend to keep their Olympic athletes in a training camp for up to
three months before the Games. He has argued against this but
ultimately he must abide by the federation's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the athletes, individual meet directors who rely on
the well-known Africans to promote the meets are expected to be
hurt financially. The Kenyans, Ethiopians and Moroccans have proved
invaluable because of their record-breaking performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they start to do this, then they should realize that the
Kenyan athletes will no longer be welcome at the Grand Prix meets
where they make their earnings,'' said Andreas Bruegger, meet
director of the Zurich Weltklasse meet and spokesman for the Golden
League Series. ``We will fill up with others and if they perform
well, then there is no need to invite the Kenyans next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruegger can afford to make such threats. The Zurich Weltklasse
meet is sold out six months in advance and he does not spend a
dollar on advertising. With a budget of $2.5 million, the big names
are usually easily persuaded. But the same is not true for the
other meets, which have recently experienced a decline in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the athletes also have a lot to consider.
</P>
<P>
   Most of their money comes from the European circuit _ but at the
same time, running for their country means a lot to them.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Tergat, the Kenyan who won a silver medal in the 10,000
meters in Atlanta and took the world half-marathon championship
last October, said, ``I know everybody back in this country has the
best welfare of our national team, maybe for more medals.
</P>
<P>
   ``So maybe what Kip Keino meant is that he needs to be sure that
by the time the team is leaving for Sydney they should be well
prepared as a team, not as individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially you have to run the Golden League competition to
see exactly where you are, what kind of shape and what kind of form
you are. I don't think they are going to stop us completely.''
</P>
<P>
   That remains to be seen. Under IAAF rules, the various national
federations control travel permits and have the power to keep
athletes from competing overseas. In Ethiopia, the athletes also
need exit visas and are much more tightly controlled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
