u a BC-STAMPS-RECOVERED-NYT &LR;      02-07 0342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAMPS-RECOVERED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VALUABLE STAMP COLLECTION IS FOUND WITH NO SUSPECTS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BARTH HEALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A million-dollar collection of stamps and envelopes
from 1869 that was snatched on a New York City street in November
1998 has been recovered by the FBI and returned, the owner said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, there are no suspects in the case, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The hobbyist who built the collection, Jeffrey Forster, a lawyer
in San Jose, Calif., said in an interview Monday that the
individual items were intact and accounted for but that they had
been removed from the pages on which they had been mounted for
exhibit at stamp shows.
</P>
<P>
   Neither he nor his insurance company, the Hugh Wood Agency, paid
a ransom for the collection, Forster said. Hugh Wood, which
specializes in insuring collectibles and had a $1 million policy on
the envelopes, had offered a $25,000 reward for return of the
stamps and envelopes.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the world of top-flight philatelic exhibits, Forster's
collection is exceptional. He has concentrated on the 1869 U.S.
issue, the first in this country whose designs come in two colors,
because they depicted scenes from history, rather than the usual
dead statesmen. The stamps are popular with collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Forster's collection focuses on postal history _ how the stamps
were used on envelopes _ and includes mail sent to exotic
locations. Some individual items were valued as high as $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   After exhibiting his collection at the Javits Convention Center
in November 1998, Forster put it in a briefcase and left the center
to go to the airport. When his back was turned to signal the car
service driver, someone grabbed the briefcase.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, which entered the case because it involved interstate
commerce, recovered the collection last spring, Forster said. They
told him then but asked for his silence while the investigation
continued.
</P>
<P>
   He kept his silence but pestered the FBI to return the
collection, and on Jan. 18, the bureau handed it over to him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
