<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9974 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-PEBBLEBEACH-HNS &LR;      02-07 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PEBBLEBEACH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ Someday, maybe, Tiger Woods will suffer a
bee sting, twist his ankle getting out of a bunker, break an arm
hitting from the rough and say a naughty word to make the golf gods
turn against him.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That'll be the day he loses by a stroke. Otherwise, there's no
end in sight for the young master.
</P>
<P>
   After Monday's Hail Mary comeback at the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach
National Pro-Am, fans and pros alike are wondering if there is
nothing Woods cannot overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the 12th tee at Pebble Beach Golf Links, he was
seven strokes behind leader Matt Gogel. Two hours later, Woods had
joined Ben Hogan in golfing history with an amazing rally that
featured a 97-yard wedge shot that was every bit as spectacular as
any 97-yard touchdown pass, finding its mark perfectly for an eagle
2 at the 15th hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about destiny,'' said the latest of Woods'
victims, Gogel. ``He's just damn good.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, 24, finished the weather-delayed AT&AMP;T with a dazzling
8-under-par 64 and wound up with a 15-under-par 273 total and a
two-shot victory after Gogel three-putted the 18th hole from eight
feet.
</P>
<P>
   If you're counting _ and the whole world is counting Woods'
victory streak now _ that's six consecutive starts on the PGA Tour
that Woods has won. Not since Hogan in 1948 had anybody won six in
a row.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one player ahead of Woods on that list now. Byron
Nelson owns the record with 11 consecutive wins in 1945. Once
thought to be an unbreakable record, it's conceivably in Woods'
sights.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who has 17 career victories, still doesn't think of his
run as a streak, because it has spanned two calendar years and two
PGA Tour seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But as the string of wins grows, ``it's definitely more
intriguing,'' he admitted. ``I'm more proud of the fact that I've
won eight out of nine, if you include the other tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods went two-for-three in post-PGA Tour events outside the
United States in November.
</P>
<P>
   Once every half-century or so, a unique kind of greatness
presents itself in sports. The world is seeing it now in Woods, who
won this time with the biggest comeback of his professional career.
And, he said, it was one of his most enjoyable wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``This definitely ranks right up there,'' Woods said. ``Coming
from behind is definitely a pretty nice taste in your mouth. I
don't know why. Maybe because it generally happens when you shoot a
great round of golf. Rarely do you see guys shooting 72 or 70 to
come from behind. They have to go mid- to low 60s in order to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods played his final four holes in 4 under par. In his first
start of 2000, the Mercedes Championships at Kapalua, Hawaii, Woods
played his final three holes in 4-under and edged Ernie Els in a
playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had some pretty good tournaments down the stretch where
I've been able to pull it off, and also some times when I didn't do
it,'' Woods said. ``Last year, I think I realistically could have
won two more majors if I would have just putted a little better at
the right times. So I have messed up a couple of times.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I also have the confidence to know I have done it before
in the past, coming from behind or edging someone out. That
definitely gives you a little shot in the arm, because you know the
feeling; you know how to handle it and deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really interesting when you're coming down the stretch in
a tournament and everything is on the line at that moment. You
forget everything else you've done. What really counts is the
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   And nobody is better right now at capturing a moment than Woods.
</P>
<P>
   He's doing the stuff Jack Nicklaus did in his prime. That Tom
Watson did. That Arnold Palmer and Sam Snead did.
</P>
<P>
   He's already part of that select company.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's performance will be remembered forever. Woods started
the day five strokes behind Gogel and Mark Brooks, who took a quick
dive down the leader board.
</P>
<P>
   But Gogel was sensational early and threatened to run away and
hide.
</P>
<P>
   Things looked gloomy for Woods after he failed to birdie the
par-5 14th hole. At that point, he still was five shots behind
Gogel, who was beginning to wobble. The leader bogeyed the 11th and
12th after shooting a sizzling 31 on the front nine.
</P>
<P>
   Woods had fired a respectable 3-under 33 on the front yet had
seen the deficit he was facing grow from five to seven shots.
</P>
<P>
   When he couldn't convert on the 14th, it appeared his rally had
stalled, although he refused to give up the chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over until it's over,'' he said. ``I know how
difficult it is to win your first tournament. I've been there. I
blew one at Quad Cities, and I know how difficult it is to go
through all the emotions and to have a lead like that. It's not
easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``So on the 12th tee, I figured if I could somehow get to 14 or
15 (under par), I might give myself a chance. Lo and behold, I got
to 15.''
</P>
<P>
   His comeback started with an incredible lightning bolt. From 97
yards, Woods nudged a wedge that landed a few feet to the right of
the 15th hole and spun straight to the left and into the cup.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, he was 13 under par, just two shots behind
Gogel. Woods said he figured he needed to birdie the final four
holes to have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do that,'' he said. ``But I still played them in
4-under.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods had struggled with his putter throughout the week on the
spongy, bumpy greens on the Monterey Peninsula. So he made sure he
didn't have to make any putts of significance down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   He birdied the 16th when he hit a wedge from 115 yards to two
feet. After a solid par on the par-3 17th, Woods hit a driver and a
2-iron that came up 10 yards short of the green on the par-5 18th
along the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   He chipped up to three feet and made the birdie putt to finish
at 273.
</P>
<P>
   Gogel, meanwhile, was feeling his collar tighten. He fumbled
away another stroke on the 15th when he couldn't get up and down
after missing the green.
</P>
<P>
   That left him at 14 under par. He needed a birdie on the 18th to
force a playoff. He laid up on his second shot, then hit a 9-iron
to eight feet. His putt, however, never had a chance, and he missed
the comebacker as well to make it a two-shot win for Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to somehow post my number early, and I figured they'd
be on No. 16 and have three holes left,'' Woods said. ``If I didn't
win, I definitely wanted to make it difficult for him to win. I
wanted to at least make it interesting and not just hand it to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was Gogel doing the handing. But in Woods' case
these days, he simply takes whatever he wants, regardless of who's
in the way.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
