<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LAST-LAP BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Tuesday, Feb. 8: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The $1.8 trillion budget proposed by President Clinton Monday
was for the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1, when he will have only
a few months left at the White House. But Clinton's fiscal
priorities could long outlive his tenure. The president called once
again for using projected surpluses to shore up Social Security and
Medicare, rather than to grant big tax cuts. He would also spend
additional money for education and other domestic needs.
Republicans in Congress may rewrite the numbers but are unlikely to
reorder his priorities in this election year. In part that is
because Sen. John McCain's challenge to party orthodoxy in his
presidential campaign has thrown Republicans on Capitol Hill into
disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Coming after his triumphalist State of the Union Message,
Clinton's valedictory Budget Message spent as much time looking
backward as forward. The president credited the longest recorded
economic boom in American history to the tough decisions he made in
1993 to restrain spending and increase taxes, and in 1997 to accept
budget cuts, especially in Medicare, demanded by Congressional
Republicans. His Budget Message was a kind of victory lap for
policies reviled by many Republicans and in truth not always
welcomed by his fellow Democrats. Indeed, Sen. Bill Bradley's
presidential campaign appeals to those Democrats tired of Clinton's
embrace of spending restraint.
</P>
<P>
   The budget was also significant for injecting a dose of reality
into budget calculations. Clinton wisely called for scrapping the
unrealistic spending caps enacted by Congress two and a half years
ago, which would destroy domestic spending programs if they were
ever adhered to. Congress has all but ignored these caps in the
last two years, sometimes by employing gimmicks like labeling
regular programs as ``emergencies'' and therefore outside the caps.
The much-quoted projection that there will be more than $2 trillion
in budget surpluses in the next decade is predicated on these cuts
taking place, which is extremely unlikely. It makes more sense to
assume that domestic spending will stay pretty much at current
levels, growing at something like the rate of inflation, as Clinton
has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Only last month the nonpartisan Congressional Budget Office
projected that, if spending remains at these more realistic levels,
the 10-year surplus outside the Social Security system will be only
$838 billion. Monday the president projected a surplus of $746
billion, roughly in the same ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, that is not enough money to pay for the large tax
cut proposed by Gov. George W. Bush in his presidential campaign.
The budget numbers suggest instead that McCain is on sounder ground
in favoring more limited tax cuts. Congressional Republicans should
not be reluctant to go along with these realistic numbers, even if
they undercut the presidential candidate most of them seem to
favor.
</P>
<P>
   With the presidential race heating up, Democrats and Republicans
in Congress are once again divided over whether it is more
advantageous to try for budget compromises or to draw lines in the
sand and hope to reap the benefits of confrontation. If they choose
to compromise, they could make some progress in bolstering Medicare
with money for prescription drugs for the elderly, and they could
increase spending for education and children, as the White House
wants. A small tax cut acceptable to all sides could become part of
this mix.
</P>
<P>
   In their hearts, many voters would prefer results rather than
confrontation to provide more fodder for campaign commercials.
Clinton's budget does ratchet domestic spending up, but in a modest
way that should be acceptable in Congress. Republicans in Congress
should be rethinking their demand for big tax cuts, especially now
that the issue is not working even in the Republican presidential
race. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
