<HEADER>
A9977 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-HSIA-TRIAL-1STLD-WRIT     02-07 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HSIA-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL FOR CLINTON-GORE FUND-RAISER BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Subs to delete California from hed) 
(DW) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A longtime fund-raiser for Vice President Al Gore
went on trial here Monday on charges that she helped disguise
illegal campaign donations to the 1996 Clinton-Gore campaign,
including at least $55,000 connected to a controversial appearance
by the vice president at a Buddhist temple in California.
</P>
<P>
   In opening statements before a federal jury, a Justice
Department prosecutor asserted that the fund-raiser, Maria Hsia,
employed a scheme to violate the law and deceive the Federal
Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Yaffe, the prosecutor, said Hsia arranged for people to
write checks to make it appear they were making political
donations. In reality, Yaffe said, these straw donors were
illegally reimbursed by other wealthy donors, including the Hsi Lai
Temple in Hacienda Heights, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The real donors were ineligible to give the money either because
the amount of their donations exceeded legal limits or they were
foreign nationals who were prohibited from giving campaign
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Among the people used as straw donors, the government has
charged, were dozens of nuns and monks at the Buddhist temple where
Gore attended an April 1996 event.
</P>
<P>
   The trial will doubtlessly serve as a reminder of what became a
deeply embarrassing incident for Gore, and has provided material
for his political opponents. At first, Gore asserted that his
attendance was merely something that he called ``community
outreach,'' but he later acknowledged that he knew it had something
to do with fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond serving as an untimely reminder of the 1996 Democratic
fund-raising practices, the trial may not produce any fresh
damaging information against Gore. In his opening statement, Yaffe
asserted that Hsia engaged in the deception by herself along with a
few close associates. Among those who were deceived, he said, were
people at the Clinton-Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Hsia, a California immigration consultant, has denied any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   In describing how Hsia allegedly arranged for the nuns and monks
to pretend they were actual Democratic donors, Yaffe said, ``She
didn't tell the Clinton-Gore committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Yaffe is part of a special task force named by Attorney General
Janet Reno to investigate possible fund-raising abuses in the 1996
campaign. Reno formed the task force in place of seeking the
appointment of an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   In Yaffe's telling, among those who were duped by Hsia were the
finance chairmen and treasurers of the Clinton-Gore campaign, the
Democratic National Committee and the finance committee for the
re-election bid of Rep. Patrick J. Kennedy, a Rhode Island
Democrat, who also received contributions in the name of nuns and
monks from the California temple.
</P>
<P>
   Yaffe said Hsia even concealed her actions from John Huang, a
former fund-raiser for the Democratic National Committee who has
been depicted by Republicans in Congress as a major figure in
fund-raising irregularities involving Asians.
</P>
<P>
   Hsia, a naturalized American citizen born in Taiwan, has had a
long association with Gore, and is equally unlikely to suggest in
her defense that either Gore or President Clinton were part of some
scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawyer, Nancy Luque, said in her opening statement that no
scheme existed because Hsia was unaware that those people who wrote
checks were not using their own money.
</P>
<P>
   Luque sought in her remarks to narrow the scope of the case for
the jury. She argued that Hsia is not charged with undermining the
political system or engaging in illegal schemes to conceal
donations as the prosecution had just told the jury. The actual
charges, five felony counts, are that Hsia ``caused someone else to
make false statements'' to the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case about five lies, and they claim she caused
these five lies,'' Luque said. If any lies were made, she said,
they were by the officials of the Clinton-Gore campaign, the
Democratic National Committee and Kennedy's finance aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Maria never spoke to any of those people,'' Luque said,
adding that even if Hsia knew there were falsely listed donors _
something she denies _ that would not be a crime because she was
not obligated to inform the campaign officials.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment charges in two counts that for a 1995
fund-raising dinner at the Century Plaza Hotel in Los Angeles, Hsia
found straw donors to help buy two tables.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, Hsia is said to have arranged for a wealthy
businessman to donate $10,000, but since federal law limits a
single donor to $1,000 per election, she had him distribute $5,000
among five family members. She had five others write checks for
$1,000 each and they were reimbursed in cash, the prosecution says.
</P>
<P>
   For the second table, she found straw donors because the real
donor was a foreign national, the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   Three other counts concern the Hsi Lai Temple. One of those
involves donations to the Patrick Kennedy campaign and two involve
the Clinton-Gore campaign, which the government said received as
much as $100,000 from the temple, funneled through nuns, monks and
others.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the April 29 luncheon with Gore, the government
charges that Hsia ``arranged for Gore to be invited'' and that
``she and John Huang were the driving force behind this event.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2321EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
