<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0524 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9979 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-SCOTUS-CAMPAIGN-     02-07 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SCOTUS-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE FLAW IN BUCKLEY VS. VALEO 
 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Feb. 8:
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is property; it is not speech.'' So wrote Justice John
Paul Stevens late last month, using his concurring opinion in a
campaign finance case from Missouri to attack the basic equation of
money-equals-speech that was the analytical basis for the Supreme
Court's 1976 Buckley vs. Valeo decision.
</P>
<P>
   In the helpful part of the Buckley decision, the court upheld
the constitutionality of campaign contribution caps, a position
wisely reaffirmed in the Missouri case. But it prohibited spending
limits on spurious free-speech grounds. Any effective campaign
finance law must address both contributions  &UR; and  &LR; spending.
Stevens' observation signals that the court may be getting ready to
take another look at the question of spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the court sidestepped that task in deciding the
Missouri case. The majority opinion reaffirmed the principle that
contribution limits help combat corruption, giving a boost to
ongoing efforts in Congress to bar unregulated soft-money donations
to the political parties by interest groups and wealthy
individuals. But it studiously avoided confronting Buckley's core
error of holding that mandatory limits on campaign spending would
unconstitutionally limit free speech.
</P>
<P>
   That part of the 1976 decision continues to inflict great harm
on the political process. It gives rich candidates like Steve
Forbes an unwarranted advantage over candidates without personal
fortunes. It also guarantees a ceaseless chase for special-interest
money by nonwealthy candidates. Reviewing this landscape in his
dissenting opinion in the Missouri case, Justice Anthony Kennedy
declared that ``Buckley has not worked,'' having created a
``misshapen system.'' He was correct, but his response _ a vote to
overturn the sound portion of Buckley that preserved contribution
limits _ was not. Even Kennedy, though, left open the possibility
that in a future case he might uphold limits on both expenditures
and contributions.
</P>
<P>
   When that case comes _ and it should not be long _ the court
should take to heart Stevens' admonition that money is not speech.
It must also take a realistic look at what has occurred in the 24
years since Buckley. If experience has taught anything, it is that
the corruption rationale the court used in Buckley, and has now
reiterated in upholding contribution limits, applies no less on the
spending side. The absence of mandatory spending limits pressures
candidates to amass ever-larger war chests and produces a political
finance system based on influence-peddling.
</P>
<P>
   In another thoughtful concurring opinion, Justice Stephen Breyer
began to provide a framework for the court's future review of
campaign regulations, including spending limits. The opinion cited
the valid role of restrictions in protecting ``the integrity of the
electoral process'' and in enabling ``a fairer election debate.''
Breyer also suggested that the compelling free-speech issue here
was not the right of individual candidates to raise and spend
unlimited amounts of money. It is the right of all Americans to a
campaign financing system that respects the democratic process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-07-00 2321EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000207.0525 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9981 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-STJOHNS-BARKLEY-N     02-07 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-STJOHNS-BARKLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NCAA FAILS TO RULE ON BARKLEY'S ELIGIBILITY
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the National Collegiate Athletic Association not yet ruling
on an appeal over his eligibility, St. John's point guard Erick
Barkley was left behind in Queens on Monday when his teammates
boarded a bus for Providence, R.I., where they will play the Friars
on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's had expected a decision on Barkley's appeal seeking
reinstatement on Monday. The university hopes to get a decision
from the NCAA on Tuesday, in time to get Barkley to the game if the
NCAA rules in his favor. Wally Renfro, a NCAA spokesman, did not
return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley was declared ineligible by the university on Saturday,
after the NCAA told the school that he had violated one of its
regulations. The alleged infraction involved a vehicle Barkley is
driving and the NCAA's edict against preferential treatment and
special benefits, according to a university official and an
associate of another university official.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley usually drives a Jeep Cherokee that is owned by his
brother. But he recently traded the Jeep for a Ford Explorer owned
by a longtime family friend who is a coach in the Rucker League and
who coached Barkley about eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, St. John's said the NCAA had asked Ed Manetta,
the athletic director, for ``further clarification from St. John's
as it relates to Erick Barkley's case.'' Manetta declined to
comment and the university did not make clear what information was
sought, but it was likely to include information on ownership,
title and insurance for the car. Barkley is not permitted to travel
with the team while he is ineligible, but he was allowed to
practice with the team Monday before it left for Providence.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Monday if St. John's first appeal had been turned
down and they had tried a second appeal, or if the NCAA had not yet
ruled on the first appeal. If an appeal is granted, Barkley would
be reinstated and allowed to rejoin his team. If the appeal is
denied, Barkley could seek a court injunction against St. John's
that would allow him to play while the case is sorted out. Barkley
would have to go to court against St. John's because it was the
university that suspended him, not the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley could have gone to court Saturday to try to become
eligible for the game against Boston College, but St. John's was
undoubtedly reluctant to have a player go to court against his own
school. That last-ditch option remains open Tuesday, though. But it
would have been more viable if the NCAA had ruled Monday, giving
Barkley time to go to court Tuesday and then, if the injunction
were granted, get to Providence for the game, which starts at 7
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope and pray Erick will play,'' Coach Mike Jarvis said. ``I
think his reputation has been damaged more than enough. I was
disappointed the right thing wasn't done today. There are many,
many things that could happen. I'm going to end up doing what I
think is right and what is in the best interests of Erick and of
this team. I'm not going to do anything to hurt Erick.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis lashed out Saturday in the wake of the NCAA's decision _
he compared college athletics' governing body to the Gestapo _ but
he apologized on Sunday for comparing the NCAA's handling of the
case to a rape. He said that if Barkley's appeal is not upheld
Tuesday, he would give Barkley ``all the necessary information to
make an educated decision,'' presumably about whether to seek an
injunction. Jarvis said he was unconcerned about the narrowing
window of opportunity if the NCAA rules against Barkley to get
Barkley declared eligible for the game Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just makes it more difficult, but there's always time,''
Jarvis said. ``There's planes, trains, buses and automobiles. When
he is declared eligible, we will get him to Providence.''
</P>
<P>
   With Barkley, who is averaging 16.9 points and 4 assists a game,
in the lineup, St. John's (14-6 over all, 6-3 in the Big East)
should have little trouble handling Providence (8-14, 1-8), the
worst team in the Big East this season. But on Saturday, with
Barkley suspended, the Red Storm looked disjointed and nearly lost
to the second worst team in the league, Boston College (9-13, 1-8).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
