<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PEBBLE-BEACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS FASHIONS AN UNFORGETTABLE COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ The streak is alive, and so is the magic
of Tiger Woods. In a comeback of epic proportions, on one of the
world's great golf courses, Woods overcame a seven-stroke deficit
with seven holes to play to win the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National
Pro-Am by two strokes over Matt Gogel and Vijay Singh.
</P>
<P>
   By winning his sixth consecutive start on the PGA Tour, Woods
tied Ben Hogan, who won six consecutive starts in 1948, for the
second-longest streak in professional golf history.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Nelson holds the longest winning streak with 11
consecutive victories in 1945, a record that has long been
considered untouchable. But the genius of Woods, who has already
won 17 tournaments in three and a half years as a professional, has
allowed him to achieve remarkable feats, such as Monday's comeback,
when he seemed hopelessly behind on Pebble Beach's picturesque back
nine only to storm back for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dramatic achievement, and fantastic even by Woods' high
standards. Shooting a final-round eight-under-par 64, the best
final round ever for a champion at Pebble Beach, Woods changed the
momentum of the tournament with one brilliant shot _ holing a wedge
shot from 97 yards for an eagle at No. 15. When the ball landed
about four-feet right of the cup, then spun into the hole for
eagle, Woods gave his signature fist pump, and it was almost like a
knockout punch to everyone else on the leader board.
</P>
<P>
   While Woods made three birdies and an eagle on the back nine,
Gogel, 28, a tour rookie looking for his first victory, collapsed
with four bogeys on his final nine holes, squandering a commanding
lead and becoming another of Woods' many victims.
</P>
<P>
   Woods finished at 15 under par for the tournament (273 _
68-73-68-64), two strokes ahead of Gogel, who shot a final-round
71, and Singh, who shot a 70. By succeeding the late Payne Stewart
as the champion at Pebble Beach, and by winning on a course that he
first played at age 12, Woods continued a steak of superb golf that
has lasted almost six months. Since last August, Woods has won
eight of his last nine starts on tour, including the PGA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The more Woods continues to win, the more confident he seems to
become. Though Woods was beaten in November in Taiwan, and at the
Williams World Challenge in January, he has not lost an official
PGA Tour event since the Sprint International last August. And
Monday, when almost any chance to win seemed lost, Woods never lost
faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the confidence to know I have done it before in the
past, coming from behind, or edging someone out,'' said Woods, who
won $720,000 to push his career earnings above $12.5 million, only
about $31,000 behind Davis Love 3rd, the career Tour money leader.
``I've had a pretty good run throughout my career of comebacks.''
</P>
<P>
   This comeback was one of the best. Starting the day five strokes
behind Gogel and Mark Brooks, who shot a 74 and finished tied for
seventh, Woods shot three-under par on the front nine. Yet he still
lost ground to Gogel, who had a blistering start. Playing like a
veteran instead of a tour rookie, Gogel birdied five of his first
seven holes to reach 17 under par, and at that point, it appeared
he might run away.
</P>
<P>
   When Woods reached the 12th tee, he was 10 under par, still
seven strokes behind Gogel, who was at 17 under par playing the
ninth hole. But from then on, Woods went into a different zone. On
the par 3, 202-yard 12th, Woods hit a 5-iron tee shot to five feet,
then made the putt for birdie. Then Gogel suffered his first
setback at No. 11, hitting a poor second shot over the green, then
failing to get up and down, leading to his first bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Gogel was a six-time winner on the Nike Tour, but this wasn't
the Nike Tour. This was Pebble Beach, Tiger Woods in pursuit, and a
tour rookie trying to deal with it all. Eventually, it was too
much. Gogel's first bogey was the first crack in his armor, and he
was never the same thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the first pro that has struggled on the back nine at
Pebble, and won't be the last,'' said Gogel, who has two top-10
finishes in four starts this year. ``Trying to win a golf
tournament for the first time, battling the emotions, it was quite
a test.''
</P>
<P>
   Gogel kept making mistakes, while Woods kept making terrific
shots. After a second consecutive bogey by Gogel at No. 12 dropped
him to 15 under par, Woods was four strokes behind.
</P>
<P>
   Then Woods made his dramatic eagle at No. 15, another example of
Woods' ability to make things happen when the stakes are raised, to
almost will himself to victory. Even Woods was surprised when the
ball sailed high into the air, landed softly on the green, then
took a hard left and disappeared into the cup. But players who are
good are often lucky. Monday, Woods was both.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those things where you are trying to get it
close and leave yourself a putt for birdie,'' Woods said. ``It just
happened to go in.''
</P>
<P>
   That pulled Woods to within two shots of Gogel. Then Woods made
another birdie at No. 16, and now he was one back, with Singh,
Gogel, and Notah Begay III all struggling on the back nine. Another
bogey by Gogel at No. 15, when he missed a five-foot putt, dropped
him into a tie with Woods. After a par for Woods at No. 17, when he
almost chipped in for birdie from 20 feet, Woods made a crucial
birdie at Pebble Beach's famous par 5, 543-yard finishing hole.
</P>
<P>
   There, he hit a solid drive down the left side of the fairway,
then hit a 2-iron that landed about 10 yards short of the green,
about 40 feet from the pin. After a delicate chip shot that Woods
hit four feet from the pin, he made the putt for birdie and a
one-stroke lead.
</P>
<P>
   Woods signed his scorecard, then waited and watched television
in the press room.
</P>
<P>
   Needing a birdie on one of the last two holes to at least force
a playoff with Woods, Gogel failed. He barely missed a birdie at
No. 17, when his 30-foot putt stopped one turn short of falling in
the cup. Then after a 3-wood and a lay-up at No 18, Gogel hit a
nice approach shot that stopped 10 feet from the pin. But Gogel
misread the putt and it slid past the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who had gone to the driving range to warm up for a
possible playoff, hugged his coach, Butch Harmon, knowing his
improbable victory had been secured. Obviously shaken, Gogel missed
his three-footer for par, and fell into a tie with Singh for second
place, and they settled for second-place checks of $352,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
