u l BC-FASHION-STAMINA-NYT &LR;      02-07 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-STAMINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM SINGULAR VISIONS TO THE GENTLY USED 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To sit through a succession of fashion shows requires
a certain kind of stamina. It isn't the sort a trek through
Patagonia demands _ though the women who have been making their way
to the fall 2000 collections wearing bare sandals through the icy
slush make one wonder why Outward Bound hasn't raided the ranks of
fashion magazines to find its expedition leaders.
</P>
<P>
   No, the strength sometimes needed for runway shows is like the
strength one presumes television executives deploy during pilot
season, as they watch dozens of new sitcoms, many trying to ape
whatever might be the existing hit of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Angie Harmon possesses enviable fashion stamina. She
goes to the collections for fun, she says, and she's even content
to sit in the back row, as she elected to do at the Oswald Boateng
show on Thursday evening, before a publicist shepherded her to the
front row. Harmon, who plays a prosecutor on the NBC drama ``Law
and Order,'' says she has to get up at 5:30 and doesn't have much
free time; still, she spent her weekend with a digital camera going
from Tommy Hilfiger to DKNY to Victor Alfaro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see that red outfit on Maggie?'' she said on Sunday,
referring to the Hilfiger jeans and cashmere turtleneck worn by the
model Maggie Rizer. ``I wanted to jump up on the runway, rip it off
her and put it on right there.''
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to share much of her passion for what Hilfiger sent
down the runway in a joint presentation of his men's and women's
lines at Roseland ballroom. Just a few weeks ago, Hilfiger signed
up Daryl K to consult on future collections, perhaps to broaden his
appeal beyond 14-year-olds who listen to Jay Zee and attract
28-year-olds who listen to Aimee Mann and do yoga.
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger's collection seemed more grown up than in the past, but
grown up in an imitative Ralph Lauren sense more than in a TriBeCa
sense. He showed full-length tartan skirts and Donegal A-line
tweeds. There was pony skin and leather mixed with mink. When he
wasn't alluding to the British Isles, he was aiming for
Continentalism. Yet, there was something off-putting about seeing
Hilfiger, who came to the world's attention by emblazoning his name
and flag across sweatshirts, shrink down his logo to a tepid ``TH''
embossed on slim trousers that mimicked the trend begun on European
runways for spring.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Donna Karan seemed to have Prada and Gucci on her
mind with her DKNY collection. The press material stated,
``Polished is the message!'' It's also the buzzword that magazines
have attached to the well-photographed Prada collection now in
stores. Karan showed lightweight, low-slung pleated skirts
reminiscent of the ones editors witnessed in Milan just a few
months ago. And she showed bright-colored hose with strappy shoes
in the manner that Tom Ford did for his equally praised spring show
for Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Melillo, a former fashion editor and stylist, managed to
stay true to his own very American vision for his Nova USA line.
Shortly after moving into his studio on West 26th Street, he
befriended a neighbor, painter Hunt Slonem, who lent Melillo his
10,000-square-foot loft for his show of men's and women's wear on
Sunday evening. ``I've never been to a show in an aviary,'' said
Kal Ruttenstein of Bloomingdale's, alluding to Slonem's enormous
bird paintings around the runway.
</P>
<P>
   Some might find Melillo's clothes mundane. He showed corduroy
warm-up suits for men, clean-lined moleskin coats and simple,
fitted herringbone dresses for women. One and all were shod in
black track shoes. But you have to appreciate the impish attitude
Melillo brings to fashion, a subject so many take so deadly
seriously. ``A lot of people want to look good without looking
crazy,'' he said before his show. ``This is what people wear. This
is pretty accessible to me and to Barry Diller and Leonardo
DiCaprio and Cameron Diaz.''
</P>
<P>
   Diller might find himself a bit on in years for some of the
lean-cut, popsicle-colored suits Oswald Boateng showed. But
DiCaprio surely could get away with wearing them. Boateng, based in
London, has shown in Paris for a number of years, but presented in
New York for the first time this season. He's brought hipness to
Savile Row tailoring and has developed a devoted following. He has
yet to perfect his women's wear, though. The suits with
ankle-length jackets and slit skirts lacked the thought and verve
of his men's suits. Still, they bore his own imprint. He's not in
the spinoff business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
