<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-TRIAL-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITNESS SAYS SHE HEARD TALK AFTER POLICE FIRED FATAL SHOTS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JANE FRITSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A woman who heard the gunshots that killed Amadou
Diallo testified Monday that moments after the shooting stopped,
someone outside her bedroom window said, ``OK, OK, we just want to
say this.''
</P>
<P>
   The testimony of the woman, Ida Vincent, 25, whose first-floor
apartment in the Bronx was near Diallo's apartment, was a
particular disappointment to lawyers for the four officers charged
with his murder.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Justice Joseph C. Teresi had granted their
motion to bar the testimony. But later, the judge said the defense
itself had ``opened the door'' to the testimony during
cross-examination of Vincent, and allowed her to say what she had
heard.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent was the third witness to testify that there was a pause
between two volleys of gunshots. She said the pause was several
seconds, but as she tapped out her recollection of the shots, she
paused for only a second or less between volleys. She also said she
heard no shouted warnings before the gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo, a West African immigrant, was standing, unarmed, in the
vestibule of his apartment building about 12:40 a.m. on Feb. 4,
1999, when he was hit by 19 of 41 shots fired at him by the police
officers. They have said that they thought he had a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent was one of two witnesses who testified Monday that there
was a pause between the two volleys of shots. Thomas Bell, who
lived around the corner from Diallo, said that he heard a pause of
three to five seconds. His tapped rendition of the sounds included
a break of that length.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bell, who is to graduate from the New York Police Academy this
month, had apparently taken the same subway home from Manhattan
that night as Diallo and had seen him walk into his building around
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Whether there was a pause in the shooting, and how long it
lasted, is significant because it could suggest that the officers
had time to assess the situation but kept firing anyway. This would
undermine their contention that the shooting was justifiable.
</P>
<P>
   Outside court, defense attorneys played down the damage that may
have been done by Vincent's testimony that someone said, ``OK, OK,
we just want to say this.'' They said that she was confused about
the sequence of events after the shooting and that she had no idea
who might have made that statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hearsay and can't be attributed to anyone,'' said James
Culleton, who represents one of the officers, Richard Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, who has been attending the trial and
organizing demonstrations in support of Diallo, said the statement
``certainly suggests that they began to put together some story.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Before Vincent took the stand, the lawyers had made a motion to
bar testimony about the statement on the grounds that it was
hearsay and prejudicial and that she did not know who had been
speaking. The judge agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Later, during cross examination, Stephen Worth, who represents
Officer Edward McMellon, asked Vincent whether police officers
investigating the shooting had questioned her about things she had
said regarding the minutes immediately after the shooting. After
that, Teresi allowed prosecutors to ask her about what she heard.
Without explaining, he said the defense had ``opened the door.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution is expected to rest its case on Tuesday after
calling Dr. Joseph Cohen, the medical examiner who performed the
autopsy on Diallo.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Vincent, who has four children, said she had had trouble going
to sleep that night and was coloring in a coloring book because she
found it soothing. A window in the bedroom was open about 2 inches,
she said, adding that she always kept it open because she has
asthma. Her building was separated from Diallo's by an alley.
</P>
<P>
   She said she knew Diallo only casually and did not know any of
his roommates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
