A9997 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-HORNETS-NY     02-07 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HORNETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS ARE NO MATCH FOR HORNETS, INSIDE AND OUT
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ The Knicks stitched the remains of their team
together Monday night and displayed the kind of character it took
to challenge the Charlotte Hornets, but they could not find an
answer for Eddie Jones and Derrick Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter what worn bodies Jeff Van Gundy sent out to
greet Jones and Coleman. Jones scored 34 points and Coleman added
29 as the Hornets left the depleted Knicks behind, 95-85, at the
Charlotte Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston scored 26 points and Patrick Ewing added 15, but
the Hornets, who shot 47 percent, leaned on their main twosome. The
Knicks came with just nine men because of injuries to Marcus Camby,
Larry Johnson and Chris Childs.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of Childs and Johnson is only temporary, but Camby
will miss at least six to eight weeks. Camby, who will undergo
diagnostic arthroscopic surgery on Tuesday to determine how badly
he tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his right knee on a bad
fall against Miami on Sunday, usually provides the energy the
Knicks need on nights when their bodies are worn and spirits are
flat.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks did not lack effort, pride or will. They lost the
rebounding edge by just 42-39 and played hard to keep the Hornets
from gaining the momentum for a blowout.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the Knicks tried to inch close, Jones came up with an
array of trick shots as he pulled up off the dribble and banked in
jumpers off the glass. As effective as Jones was, Coleman was just
as dominating as he left the Knicks' big men lunging in vain with
his jumpers from the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   It was too much for the Knicks to handle though they were able
to cut the Hornets' lead to 88-83 with 3 minutes 41 seconds left as
Ewing, of all players, raced in for a reverse layup. Once again,
Jones and Coleman came right back and pried open the Hornets' lead.
</P>
<P>
   This was a test of the Knicks' resiliency. Not only was their
roster threadbare from injuries, but the Knicks were also playing
their second game in two days. This was to have been an off day,
but the schedule was changed when the Jan. 14 game was postponed
because of the death of guard Bobby Phills, who lost control of his
Porsche less than a mile from the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were faced with keeping up the intense energy level
they had against the Heat on Sunday afternoon. Against Miami, Ewing
played a season-high 44 minutes and dominated with a 25-point,
14-rebound effort.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt the Knicks need him to make up for the loss of
Camby, but at 37, Ewing does not have the same elasticity he used
to have. The Knicks have not bounced back well as a whole in
back-to-back games this season _ with a 2-7 record on the second
night of two games in a row _ and showed signs of fading at the end
of the third quarter after sticking close in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Although their defense wasn't crisp and Ewing was the picture of
fatigue, the Knicks trailed by 51-47 at the half. They allowed the
Hornets to shoot 50 percent, but the Knicks stayed close in
rebounding with 20 to the Hornets' 22 and turned the ball over just
five times.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there were signs of trouble. The Hornets seemed to be
biding their time, almost waiting for the Knicks to wilt. In the
third quarter, they made a move. With Ewing staggering in the
paint, the Hornets' big men bulled their way inside while Jones and
Coleman continued to pop outside shots during a 15-5 run to end the
third quarter with a 77-63 lead.
</P>
<P>
   As the Hornets began to pick up steam, the Knicks were hit with
another major blow. With 3:42 left in the third quarter, Houston,
who had 20 points at the time, rolled his left ankle after having a
jumper blocked by Elden Campbell. After the Hornets built a 68-58
lead with 3 minutes left in the third, the Knicks exhaled a sigh of
relief when trainers told Van Gundy that Houston could return. But
Van Gundy didn't go to him right away, perhaps worried that his
ankle was too stiff.
</P>
<P>
   Houston was crucial to the Knicks' ability to stay in the game.
Latrell Sprewell was getting worn down by guarding Jones. Through
three quarters, he was 4 of 12 from the field while Jones had 27
points. Beyond Sprewell, Kurt Thomas had cooled down from his
10-point first quarter and Ewing was struggling to get 8 points
through three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was starting to slip away as the Knicks began to
fade. They were not getting back in transition and losing their
battle to rebound. Normally, this is where Camby provides a boost.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were running on fumes. Early on, Ewing looked tired
and ragged when he began the night 1 for 5 from the floor. In a
way, it was almost a reprieve for him when early foul trouble _ he
had three fouls before the six-minute of the first half _ left him
on the bench.
</P>
</TEXT>
