<HEADER>
A0001 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS &LR;      02-07 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
BUSH, McCAIN TRADE JABS AS RACE HEATS UP 
 
By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
and GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, Del. _ The race for the Republican presidential
nomination became even more overheated Monday as John McCain
responded to George W. Bush's negative attacks with an ad that
suggests Bush cannot be trusted in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has been attacking McCain since the Texas governor's
stinging defeat in New Hampshire last week, emerged from a weekend
of rest and ``retooling'' with a new, even more aggressive posture
and a new mantle _ that he, not McCain, is the reform candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in Delaware on the eve of Tuesday's Republican
primary, Bush brandished a new slogan, a slightly different style
but the same basic message as he plowed into crowds of supporters
at a Kent County GOP luncheon and an American Legion post
gathering.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who is skipping Delaware to concentrate on more crucial
states in the delegate race, took a day away from his South
Carolina campaign to search for independent-minded voters in Macomb
County, Mich., home of the so-called Reagan Democrats, who deserted
the party in 1980 to help deliver the White House to Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in Saginaw, Mich., McCain hoped to resurrect those same
kind of voters, but this time, they would be ``McCain Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has the overwhelming support of the state's GOP
establishment, including popular Gov. John Engler.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by nationwide criticisms that he was too aloof, Bush kept
a hectic pace, made more time for supporters' questions and fielded
more reporters' questions than usual, using every opportunity to
question McCain's commitment to campaign finance reform and
outsider persona, the centerpieces of his surging campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of smiling and sitting back and letting Senator
McCain define me are over,'' Bush told reporters, even though
McCain had restricted the rhetoric to the differences over their
tax cuts. ``I am going to defend my record ... with all my vigor.
And that's exactly where this campaign is headed. I welcome the
battle and I welcome the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The fight took another dimension Monday when McCain's South
Carolina campaign complained that Bush had launched a ``push
polling'' campaign in which callers, ostensibly taking a
public-opinion survey, badmouth a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few people do this any more,'' said Richard Quinn,
majority leader of the South Carolina House and a key McCain
supporter. ``When they do use it, they're usually desperate.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign held a news conference in Columbia at which
Suzette Latsko, a student at the College of Charleston, said she
received a telephone call Sunday from a woman who identified
herself as working for Voter/Consumer Research and calling from
Houston. Voter/Consumer Research of Washington is listed as a
polling contractor on the Bush campaign's filings with the Federal
Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Latsko said the caller misrepresented several of McCain's
positions and asked if she knew that McCain was reprimanded for
intervening with federal regulators in the savings and loan
scandal. A Senate ethics committee said McCain had shown ``poor
judgment'' in accepting free holidays from scandal figure Charles
Keating but had not broken Senate rules.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer denied it was a push poll, but
noted the importance of the Republican Party remembering McCain's
role in the S&AMP;L crisis.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had dismissed Bush's increasingly strident attacks until
Monday. But he returned fire with a new ad chastizing Bush for
breaking a promise made over a handshake at a Republican debate not
to run negative campaigns against each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we really want another politician in the White House ...
America can't trust,'' an announcer says at the end of the
30-second television spot that shows a clip from a Bush ad that
accuses McCain of lying, a clip of a Bush speech in which he
promised to run a positive campaign and a clip of the two men
shaking hands on their promise.
</P>
<P>
   McCain later insisted he thought the governor could be trusted,
but he added: ``We shook hands and now he's attacking me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been called a liar, a hypocrite ... and I've been accused
of abandoning veterans,'' McCain said. ``We're going to fire back
and every time he does it, we're going to fire back doubly.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain acknowledged a risk that voters would be turned off by
the negative tone, but said he weighed that risk against the risk
of ``letting it go.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of trust is an important one for McCain, who tells
people at every stop that he will ``always tell you the truth.''
His aides believe it is one of the reasons his message of reform is
attracting increased support across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Bush somberly assailed McCain's new ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the senator is referring to me, I'm going to defend my
record,'' Bush said. ``I did in office what I said I would do. The
people in my state ... know they can trust me to bring honor and
dignity to the office.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in months, Bush abandoned his standard stump
speech to focus on his new message that he, the son of the former
president, is the outsider reform candidate and one who can connect
with voters.
</P>
<P>
   Those two elements are precisely the ones that have propelled
14-year Senate veteran McCain to a lead in polls South Carolina and
a surge in such key states as Michigan and California.
</P>
<P>
   McCain insisted that the main focus of his Michigan campaign
will be to recruit more Republican voters. But he said he hopes his
message will attract voters across party lines.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, McCain said labor unions _ usually a Democratic
domain _ played a ``vital role'' the nation's history. ``I don't
think it's appropriate for any president to be anti-union,'' McCain
told the predominantly blue collar crowd in Macomb County. He added
that he does support right-to-work laws.
</P>
<P>
   In Delaware, Bush began his drumbeat that McCain is a Washington
insider without naming him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to remind people who sits on the inside, who resides
in the halls of power in Washington,'' Bush said. ``I'm going to
remind people that I'm a reformer with a record, a reformer with
results.'' The new ``reformer'' theme was repeated throughout the
day and was spelled out in huge new banners draped behind him at
his campaign stops.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush opposes most of McCain's campaign finance reform
proposal and is enthusiastically backed by the nation's Republican
establishment, he is trying to wrest the reformer mantle from
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponent said that he is the only person who can stand up
with Al Gore'' to debate campaign finance reform, Bush said. ``As
it turns out there's new evidence that may not be the case,
including the fact that he has received more money from lobbyists
than anyone in the campaign,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's response has been that he must compete within the
current system and that he wants to ban so-called soft money, or
unlimited contributions to the political parties.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
